<HEADLINE>
YOUR SUPER SEMIS ANSWER MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER 
Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everything you wanted to know about the NFL's
Final Four and didn't have the time or interest to ask:
</P>
<P>
   So, will a team that plays in a dome win a Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   It's too cloudy to tell right now. But a dome team will finally
play in one. The Vikings and Falcons both play indoors. Frankly,
this might be a bogus stat. After all, seven teams that normally
play on grass have won the seven indoor Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   How much of an advantage is there for teams hosting NFC and AFC
title games?
</P>
<P>
   It's money, with an asterisk. Since 1970, the home team has won
39 of 56 title games. But last year, both home teams lost, Denver
upsetting Pittsburgh and Green Bay winning in San Francisco. Over
the same period, teams favored in title games have won 39 of 55
games, and Minnesota and Denver are favored.
</P>
<P>
   Will the games be competitive?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope _ more so than Denver-Miami and Minnesota-Arizona. If
history repeats itself, the NFC game will be a rout and the AFC
game will be a war. The winning margin in the last seven NFC title
games, and 13 of the last 14, has been 10 points or more. The only
exception since 1984 was the Giants' 15-13 upset of the 49ers in
1990. Three of the last four AFC games were decided by four points
or less.
</P>
<P>
   How much of a shock is it to see the Vikings and Falcons in the
NFC title game?
</P>
<P>
   It's like the sun rising in the West. Dating back to the 1981
season, 29 of the 34 available berths in the NFC title game went to
just six teams _ San Francisco (10), Dallas (6), Washington (5),
Green Bay (3), Chicago (3) and the New York Giants (2). Those six
teams also accounted for all but two of the last 17 Super Bowl
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Teams earning the other five berths all lost, too _ Carolina,
Detroit, Minnesota and the Rams (twice).
</P>
<P>
   What's the most shocking stat about these four teams?
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Rich Kotite, the Jets went 1-15 in 1996.
Two years later, with 17 players remaining from that team, they're
13-4, AFC East champs, and playing Denver in the AFC title game.
This, of course, has nothing to do with the coaching of Kotite and
Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   How do Cinderfellas perform in January?
</P>
<P>
   Few teams go from pumpkins to princes. Three of the four teams
remaining didn't make the playoffs last year, but only one was
under .500.
</P>
<P>
   Three teams went from sub-.500 seasons in 1995 to the 1996
season's Final Four: New England (6-10), Jacksonville (4-12) and
Carolina (7-9). In 1991, Denver (5-11) and Detroit (6-10) both made
the title games (and lost) after poor 1990 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Only one team has gone from sub-.500 to Super Bowl champ _ the
1981 49ers. They went from 6-10 in 1980 to 13-3. The Bengals, the
team the 49ers beat in the Super Bowl, also was 6-10 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Which coach has the postseason mojo?
</P>
<P>
   That would be Mr. Tuna. Parcells' 11-5 record in postseason play
is fourth best among all coaches with 10 or more postseason
appearances, trailing Vince Lombardi (9-1), Joe Gibbs (16-5) and
Bill Walsh (10-4). Parcells is the only coach in Jets history over
.500. Parcells has 22 wins in two seasons. In the previous seven
seasons (1990-96) before his arrival, the Jets were 36-77.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a crowded field. Mike Shanahan won a Super Bowl last
year and is making his ninth appearance in an NFC or AFC title
game. Since becoming the Broncos' coach, he is 52-18, which has to
make Al Davis wonder how life might have changed if he hadn't
gassed Shanahan after 20 games (he was 8-12 as the Raiders head
coach).
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves won 117 games as the Broncos coach and got the mules
to three Super Bowls during his 12 years (losing all three). He's
taking his third team to the postseason, and the Falcons are a
stunning 20-3 in their last 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have perhaps the most audaciously bad coaching
history in the league. Their former leaders include Norb Hecker
(four wins in 31 games), Norm Van Brocklin (seven years, 37 wins,
no playoff games), Marion Campbell (17-51 in two separate stints),
Pat Peppler (3-6), Leeman Bennett (47-44 and one of the Falcons'
three franchise playoff wins), Dan Henning (22-41), Jim Hanifan
(0-4), Jerry Glanville (28-38, 1-1 in the postseason) and June
Jones (19-30).
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Green is the short straw here. He's 2-5 in the playoffs,
and those wins came against the Giants last season and Cardinals
this.
</P>
<P>
   What position did these coaches play in college?
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was a quarterback at South Carolina, Green a running back
at Iowa, Parcells a linebacker at Wichita State, and Shanahan a
wishbone quarterback/defensibe back at Eastern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any particular trend to look for?
</P>
<P>
   It's more likely that a trend will be broken. Since they began
playing Super Bowls, there's never been a suspicious quarterback
winner. The closest you could find would be Mark Rypien and Jeff
Hostetler.
</P>
<P>
   This year's quarterbacks include Chris Chandler, who was 35-49
as a starter coming into 1998; Vinny Testaverde, 48-83-1 prior to
'98; and Randall Cunningham, 64-45-1 as a starter but the owner of
a 1-4 playoff record before Sunday. If you're betting this trend,
then you unload on Denver and John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Super Bowl be decided by a kicker?
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely. Only two have come down to a field goal. Jim
O'Brien's field goal in overtime won Super Bowl V for Baltimore,
and Scott Norwood's miss cost Buffalo in Super Bowl XXV. The
Vikings and Broncos have the best kicking units. This area is the
Jets' biggest deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Which Super Bowl record is most likely to fall?
</P>
<P>
   If the Vikings and Broncos meet, it could be the record of 75
points in a game by both teams, set by the 49ers and Chargers. Or
so we hope. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
