<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST SAYS NBA PLAN IS A MODEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The way Lakers vice president Jerry West sees it,
the NBA's new labor agreement could serve as a framework for any
future pact between owners and players in other professional
leagues, especially baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's Board of Governors Thursday voted 29-0 in favor of an
agreement that essentially sets a cap on what individual players
can earn annually. The agreement is a first among professional
leagues in that it limits player earnings, not team spending.
</P>
<P>
   West believes the agreement will bolster competition in the NBA
because teams in New York and Los Angeles can't simply use higher
salaries to lure quality players from cities in less glamorous
locations like Washington, D.C., and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   A similar agreement may be needed to increase competition in
Major League Baseball, where players like the Dodgers' Kevin Brown
earn more in one season than the entire roster of teams in smaller
markets like Montreal and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the NBA has done better than any of the other
leagues,'' West said. ``If I were (a baseball fan) I would really
be concerned about how some of these other teams are going to
compete with some of the huge market teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be concerned about the quality of the product when you
have one player on one team making more than the whole roster on
another team,'' he continued. ``I think basketball has addressed
that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, which survived an ugly strike in 1994 that forced the
cancellation of the World Series, will have to enter labor
negotiations earlier than the other major sports. The current
contract between owners and players expires in 2000. The players'
union has an option to extend the contract through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball isn't likely to impose NBA-like salary caps -- in
spite of the disparity that exists among teams in the league today,
officials on both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry West didn't become one of the greatest basketball
players in the history of the sport by spending time studying the
inner workings of the baseball industry,'' said Gene Orza, an
official with the Major League Baseball Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that there might be one or two baseball owners
that might like to have this deal, that places a limit on what a
player can earn irrespective of their worth,'' Orza said. ``But I
wouldn't hold my breath on it happening in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, officials with Major League Baseball will scrutinize
the NBA deal once it is finalized, said MLB spokesman Richard
Levin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every league keeps an eye on the other leagues,'' Levin said.
``But what applies to one league doesn't necessarily apply to
another. I just wouldn't want to discuss possibilities for
baseball's future right now.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with the National Hockey League expressed similar
sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the NBA agreement isn't even on paper, it's
entirely too premature to make any expressions regarding its
impact,'' NHL vice president Frank Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the National Football League's labor agreement,
originally ratified in 1993, is a lot like the one the NBA is about
to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   The pact, which extends past the spring 2004 college draft,
includes among its provisions a hard salary cap that is strictly
enforced. Also helping the league is the fact that all 30 teams
share network television revenues. In baseball, each team is free
to negotiate its own television package.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a system that has supported competitive balance and
allowed all the teams to have an equal opportunity,'' NFL spokesman
Greg Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   As for West's comments:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's talking about the NFL,'' Aiello said.
``(The NBA) did some things just like we have already done: They
increased minimum salaries; they strengthened their drug program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to have this kind of structure. It's not
perfect, but probably better off than some other professional
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the impact of the recently agreed upon NBA settlement,
baseball is going to have to consider the impact of the widening
gap between its rich teams and its poor ones. There's no doubt that
disparity will be an issue when the bargaining begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any secret to anybody in professional
athletics that there's certain disparities that have to be
considered,'' said Angels spokesman Tim Mead. ``I think everybody
is acutely aware of the problem, I just don't know how many
individuals have the correct solution for baseball. That remains to
be seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
