<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECON (Havana) _ How people are managing in an embargoed
economy. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photos [NYT6,7) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-BIKO (Johannesburg) _ A former police officer who said
he helped tackle the anti-apartheid activist Steve Biko and smash
his head into a wall when he was in custody in 1977 has been denied
amnesty by the South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission.
By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-VILLAGE (San Vicente Del Caguan) _ In the streets, the
campesinos of San Vicente del Caguan dared a quiet pride and even
hope, seeing luminaries from the nation's capital and around Latin
America descend on their town for a giant party to begin talks with
leftist rebels this week. ``Laboratory for peace,'' said banners
strung across the airport and around the square, where the
government and leftist rebels have opened talks toward peace. The
signs did not refer so much to the national feelers to end the
fighting that has claimed 35,000 lives over the last decade, as to
this town's novel attempts to find a peace of its won with the
rebels in recent months. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-POLITICS (Hong Kong) _ Eight months after it scored a
resounding victory in legislative elections here, Hong Kong's
pro-democracy movement is divided over whether the Democratic Party
should abandon elective politics and take its cause to the streets.
By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-VATICAN (Ottawa) _ The second-ranking Vatican diplomat in
Canada is accused of stalking a former employee. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS (Mexico City) _ If he could take control of the
millions of dollars Mexico spends each year to combat drug
trafficking, Miguel Gonzalez Espinosa would spend a little less of
it on high-tech, heavily armed operations at airports and along the
border, aimed at stopping the flow of drugs from Colombia on their
way to the United States. Gonzalez, who proudly calls himself a
recovering alcoholic, directs a small drug rehabilitation center in
the downtrodden neighborhood that surrounds the city's Basilica de
Guadalupe. He sees firsthand the toll taken by a less-talked-about,
but increasingly damaging problem: the rise in drug abuse _
especially cocaine and crack _ among Mexican youth. By Ginger
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-REPS (Undated) _ Since an overhaul of the health care
system fizzled four years ago, the pharmaceutical sales force has
exploded, from about 35,000 full-time sales representatives and
supervisors in the top 40 pharmaceutical companies in 1994 to more
than 56,000 this year, according to the Scott-Levin consulting firm
in Pennsylvania. Pharmaceutical companies spent $5.3 billion in the
first 11 months of last year sending representatives into doctors'
offices and hospitals. But the relationship between the
pharmaceutical sales force and the doctors they ply with
information has been fraught with tension for many years, and many
physicians feel that it is only getting worse. By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY-DEATH (New York) _ A reconstruct of the troubled life of
Andrew Goldstein, the man who pushed a woman to her death in the
subway. By N.R. Kleinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-STUDY (Undated) _ The recent wave of get-tough-on-crime
sentencing laws has succeeded in making criminals serve longer
prison sentences and slowed the release of prison inmates; but it
has also helped increase the nation's record prison population even
as crime has dropped in the 1990s, according to the first
comprehensive study of the new laws released by the Justice
Department. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Undated) _ The vice president prepares for a big
week on the road, as the impeachment trial begins in earnest in
Washington. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-MARINELAND (Marineland, Fla.) _ Florida's most popular
tourist attraction in the 1950s and '60s, Marineland says it was
the world's first oceanarium and the first to teach wild dolphins
to perform. Now the park is mired in bond defaults, years of
neglect and blame-trading, and a Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing. By
Jim Carrier.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SECURITY (Washington) _ How good is airport security?
Good enough, the Federal Aviation Administration has said
repeatedly. Even so, efforts by outsiders to assess security at
America's airports are all but fruitless, because the FAA says it
cannot provide details without giving away information that could
help terrorists. But FAA reports of violations by one airline show
that agents masquerading as passengers were able to smuggle guns,
hand grenades and bombs past security guards and their scanners, or
send the weapons in through exits. By Mathew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLITICS _ The question now is whether Congress and the
Clinton administration can work together to deal with the full
plate of issues facing the country. Both parties have powerful
motivations to prove that they have not been consumed by
impeachment. But the challenge of getting on with the people's
business will be complicated not just by impeachment-induced
bitterness and distrust, but by the host of differing agendas in
play, from Gephardt and Gore to the conservative right. By Richard
W. Stevenson and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE _ In setting a detailed schedule to resume the
Clinton impeachment trial but putting off the vexing issue of
whether witnesses will be heard, the Senate demonstrated to many
lawyers and others just how different an impeachment trial is from
any other legal proceeding. By Neil Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HISTORY _ With a contemporary constitutional drama going
on just a few miles away, historians flocked to the nation's
capital last week to discuss topics like the dilemma of the South
Asian intellectual and acoustics in early America. And maybe
something else, too. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-RECORD _ On Monday, Janet Reno becomes the longest serving
attorney general of this century, breaking a record held by Homer
Cummings, an attorney general in the Roosevelt administration who
held the post from March 4, 1933, to Jan. 2, 1939. Reno, who took
over in 1993, is highly unlikely to break the all-time service
record held by William Wirt, who served for 11 years from November
1817 to March 1829. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
