   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-PRICING (Undated) _ It took communications experts time
to realize that when AT&AMP;T did away with long-distance charges for
wireless calls, as well as additional ``roaming'' fees, it changed
the ground rules of the wireless business in the United States. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-STOCK (Undated) _ For Amazon.com, the bestseller that
really mattered last week was not a book title, but the company's
stock, which had a remarkable run. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WB-TIME-WARNER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Along with much of the
audience and most of the profits, the confidence bordering on
arrogance that once characterized the network television business
has faded away this season. But it is alive and well in at least
one place, television's youngest, hippest and increasingly its only
upwardly mobile address: the upstart would-be network known as WB.
By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-JORDAN-RETIRE (Undated) _ If Michael Jordan retires from
basketball sometime before the lockout-shortened season begins,
book publishers will roll up their tweedy sleeves and shout with
joy. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   KINKOS-ADCOL (Undated) _ Kinko's is beginning an ad campaign on
Monday that uses humor to help persuade consumers that presentation
materials, color copies and video conferences should be considered
ways to communicate along with telephone calls and greeting cards.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPECTUS-COLUMN (New York) _ Bruce Bernstein, proprietor of
Main Street Partners, a data base application developer based in
New York, is frustrated that New York's software industry is almost
entirely overlooked except when it is related to new media, the
industry that has grown up around the Internet. By Janet Stites.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-GRAPHICS (Undated) _ After three years of declining
fortunes, Silicon Graphics Inc. is placing a big bet Monday as it
introduces a line of work stations built around Intel chips and
Microsoft software. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-PRICES (Las Vegas) _ Just two months after the transition
to digital broadcasting began, one company exhibiting new products
here at the annual Consumer Electronics Show is offering a
high-definition television for $2,999 _ less than half the cost of
the cheapest set the industry was selling in the fall. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT11) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NOMA-PROFILE-MEDIA (Tokyo) _ Sawako Noma, 55, looks like the
prototypical Japanese housewife: demure, gracious, unprepossessing.
Which is exactly what she was until 1987, when her husband died and
she took over the reins of Kodansha Ltd., Japan's largest
publishing company. By Suzanne Charle.
</P>
