<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7289 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      01-11 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW'S NEW COACH HITS TOWN WITH HEFTY TO-DO LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Like a sudden winter storm over the Rockies he had
just left behind, Rick Neuheisel blew into Seattle on Sunday. He
said he was exhausted, but managed not to look like it.
</P>
<P>
   If he's tired now, his fatigue likely will spike in the next
couple of days. Hired Saturday to be the next football coach at the
University of Washington, Neuheisel has a plate that's overflowing,
including a news conference this morning to introduce him.
</P>
<P>
   In an impromptu media gathering at Hec Edmundson Pavilion on his
way to sell himself to Husky players, Neuheisel made it clear he
has a full plate. It includes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Staff selection. Neuheisel said, ``There are certainly guys
in Colorado I'm interested in,'' referring to his last employer.
``I anticipate a lot of them joining us.''
</P>
<P>
   One apparently on the way is special teams and secondary coach
Bob Hauck, who told Bob Bourgette, the coach for hotly recruited
Kennedy High running back Paul Arnold, that he will be courting him
for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Colorado assistants _ A.J. Christoff, Karl Dorrell
and Jon Embree _ are seeking the job Neuheisel vacated but are
considered outside shots. Another aide, offensive-line coach Tom
Cable of Snohomish, is a likely addition here.
</P>
<P>
   -- Recruiting. A so-called ``dead period,'' per NCAA rules, is
in effect through Wednesday, and effectively freezes recruiting.
But Neuheisel and his staff will have three weekends to hurry
recruits in for campus visits before the national letter-of-intent
day Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Unclear is how Neuheisel will handle the roughly 10 UW recruits
who have made verbal commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would honor those commitments, Neuheisel said,
``There's a lot going on right now. Recruiting is certainly a major
issue. We're going to get busy immediately with recruiting. I'll
look at all the commits that are currently here; some I'll be
familiar with, some I won't be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get in a phone call to John Mackovic, who heads
the ethics committee (of the American Football Coaches
Association), of which I'm a member. I need to just make sure I'm
doing the right thing with respect to recruiting when you leave
from one school to another.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Deflection of public concentration on his salary. Neuheisel
and UW officials refused Sunday to discuss his contract terms,
expected to be outlined Monday. But he is reported to have been
attracted for $1 million to $1.5 million per year for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   If his contract calls for much above $1 million annually, he
would be second to Florida coach Steve Spurrier's roughly $2
million package. Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer, fresh from a national
title, had his contract redone for slightly more than $1 million,
while Florida State coach Bobby Bowden is at about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Barbara (Hedges, UW athletic director) I'm flattered
with the commitment she's made to me and my family,'' Neuheisel
said, calling his decision ``gut-wrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not talking money. It's not about money. It's a
decision based on a platform here at the University of Washington,
which I think can be a beacon university in the West and the entire
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salary is just not an issue with me. Obviously, security for
my family and seven years is a wonderful thing, but I'm about going
to work and seeing if we can't win 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, some academicians at Washington are upset at the
reported terms of the contract, which will be significantly more
than the $566,000 package earned by ex-coach Jim Lambright or any
other coach in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the reactions I've heard have been positive,'' UW
president Richard McCormick said Sunday, lauding Hedges' 10-day
search as ``stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed as to what values the contract represents, Neuheisel
said, ``I don't pretend to make any judgments on what market value
is. I think that's determined by the market. I'm just interested in
achieving the goals anybody in my profession wants to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Neuheisel was off to meet for the first time with his
players, whom he delighted with the news he was reinstituting their
favored gold helmets, part of the UW uniform before Lambright made
a switch in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 0047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7299 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     01-11 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TAKE ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ ``Upon review, the play stands'' _ a magical phrase
from the replay era of the NFL. Sunday night, words to that effect
were magical for the Mighty Ducks in a 6-4 victory over Edmonton
before 17,174.
</P>
<P>
   It was a victory doused with a generous amount of pixie dust.
The Ducks scored three times with a two-man advantage, had a goal
deflect in off a Oilers defenseman, and most importantly benefited
from a ruling that denied Edmonton from taking a two-goal lead
early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say we got a break or whatever, but as the year goes
along I'm sure things will even up,'' said Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg, referring to Ryan Smyth's shot that was ruled no goal by
referee Rob Shick and the video goal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth had a wide open net to shoot at in the first minute of the
second period and he appeared to have given the Oilers a 4-2 lead
when the red light went on behind Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hebert somehow got the knob of his stick on the
shot, the Oilers were convinced that the shot bounced just inside
the post, and the netting did appear to move on the replays. But
Shick quickly waved the goal off before consulting with the video
goal judge.
</P>
<P>
   The news would not be good for Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Director of officials Jim Gregory said none of the replay angles
showed the puck crossing the goal line and that it didn't matter if
the net moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guess,'' said Gregory. ``We've got to see it go over
and we did not see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who stopped 33 of 34 shots in relief of Dominic Roussel,
joked ``that I have to agree with the video judge and ``if it did
go in it didn't go in very far.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a more serious note, the Anaheim goalie said the ruling
was the turning point in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time those things go against you,'' said Hebert,
who explained that his stick may have caused the netting to move.
``As soon as that happened I knew we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Ducks, who had already benefited from a shot by Paul
Kariya that Edmonton defenseman Tom Poti accidentally poked into
his own net with 23.3 seconds left in the first period, tied the
game 3-3 on Travis Green's goal just over a minute after the ruling
on Smyth's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers then went into self-destruct mode _ giving up two
five-on-three goals to Teemu Selanne in less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Too many penalties, said disgusted Edmonton coach Ron Lowe, who
watched his Oilers give the Ducks their second and third two-man
advantages of the game when Poti pulled down Steve Rucchin from
behind on a Edmonton two-on-one at 7:15 and when goalie Mikhail
Shtalenkov shot the puck over the net, drawing a delay-of
game-penalty at 8:35.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne quickly scored goals 20 and 21 from the his new position
in the slot and the Ducks had taken a 5-3 lead with 11:25 left in
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play was great,'' said Hartsburg. ``It won us the
game, that and Guy stoning them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things you have to do well if you want to win,''
said Selanne of the three five-on-three goals, which included
Fredrik Olausson's goal in the first period. ``But it's not that
easy to score five-on-three, no goals are easy in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks put a stranglehold on the game when Matt Cullen scored
a shorthanded goal at 15:26 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton outshot Anaheim 23-6 in the third period and the Ducks
allowed a season-high 49 shots, but nobody was willing to give the
two points back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many situations where luck was on our side,''
admitted Rucchin. ``It was ugly, but we will definitely take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
