<SLUG> BC-CHOICE-AWARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSBY, JOHN, FORD TOP PEOPLE'S CHOICE AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; Bill Cosby, Elton John and Harrison Ford
were named all-time favorite television, music and movie
performers, ``Titanic'' had one last hurrah and the stars of
several shows nearing their end were given warm send-offs in the
25th annual People's Choice Awards held Sunday night at the
Pasadena Civic Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees and winners were selected through telephone surveys
conducted by the Gallup Organization. The winners of the all-time
favorites category were chosen through Internet balloting from
nominees identified in those polls.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the performers said they were glad to receive
People's Choice Awards because they were given by fans, rather than
colleagues or members of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting. Whatever we do, we do for the fans so it's
very touching,'' said singer Celine Dion, who won for favorite
female musical performer. ``This is really wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dion's win made for a sort of a third award for ``Titanic,'' the
movie blockbuster that steamed through last year's Academy Awards.
Dion sang the movie's theme song, ``My Heart Will Go On.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' was honored as both the favorite dramatic motion
picture and favorite motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just saying that we hope this is closure, and (star)
Gloria (Stewart) said, No, we want the party to go on,'' said
director and co-producer James Cameron. ``The film was chosen by
people globally in such a resounding fashion last year, it would be
silly to call it a surprise that we won.''
</P>
<P>
   It even led to jokes from other winners such as Tom Hanks, who
was honored for favorite motion picture actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's never too late in the year to give a trophy to
`Titanic,' that's my philosophy,'' Hanks quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse,'' starring Christina Applegate, tied with ``Will and
Grace'' for favorite new television comedy series. Applegate was
tabbed as the favorite female performer in a new TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nerve-racking, scary,'' Applegate said about being
nominated. ``It's been amazing to work with these people on the
show. For the hard work we do this (award) is an added bonus. It
feels really, really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three all-time performers -- comedian Cosby, actor
Ford or singer John -- was present to receive his reward, though
John taped a duet for the show with country singer LeAnn Rimes, and
the others appeared by videotape as well.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks, who also performed in the show, picked up his
seventh straight award as favorite male musical performer. The
voters honored several shows that are off the air or about to shoot
their last episode, leading host Ray Romano to joke that ``
`Seinfeld' finally went off the air and we thought, great, we'll
finally get nominated for a People's Choice Award. Then look what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seinfeld'' tied with ``Frasier'' for favorite television
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Hunt won for favorite female television performer, beating
out Calista Flockhart of ``Ally McBeal'' and Oprah Winfrey among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thrilling after seven years, and competing this year with
people like Calista Flockhart, who's shown up and created a
compelling character, and Oprah Winfrey, to be recognized,'' Hunt
said. ``It's really incredible. Some people are drawn to this
simple story of this marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said she probably won't do another TV series after ``Mad
About You'' ends this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine finding anybody I work with quite the way I
work with Paul (Reiser),'' Hunt said. ``The only topic that remains
interesting for seven years is a relationship and how it changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen, whose equally durable ``Home Improvement'' is also in
its last season as he prepares to spend more time making movies,
won for favorite male television performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do both of these anymore,'' Allen said. ``Perform, to
do TV the way I want to do it, and executive produce -- I can't do
both. I've let the movies slip. But I really like doing this TV
show and I really like being in this industry. It's a bunch of
really good friends coming up on single digits (in the number of
shows remaining to shoot) and it's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Lane won for favorite male performer in a new TV series
--``Encore! Encore!'' -- but it was bittersweet given the NBC
show's cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked up irony in the dictionary it would be a picture
of me holding up this award,'' Lane said. ``It's been sort of an
odd experience, but I wouldn't trade it for anything. Every decade
I do 13 episodes for NBC. I'm sure in 2005 I'll be playing a wacky
proctologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ``ER,'' which shows no signs of slowing or going as it
picked up the award for favorite television drama, is marking the
imminent departure of George Clooney who is shooting his last
episode on the show this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some fine actors will come on the show, but I don't
think George will ever be replaced,'' said co-star Noah Wyle. ``We
should just retire his number.''
</P>
<P>
   The yuppies hung in with ``LA Doctors,'' beating out teen faves
``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Felicity'' for favorite new dramatic
television series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally in the past six weeks we figured out the best way to
tell our stories,'' said star and co-producer Ken Olin.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bullock was honored as favorite motion picture actress
and ``Something About Mary'' was named favorite movie comedy.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
