r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-NEUHEISEL     01-11 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-NEUHEISEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC NEUHEISEL HAS COME LONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For Rick Neuheisel, big-time college football wasn't
always about a supposed $1 million-plus salary, mortgage buyout and
red carpet rolled from Husky Stadium to the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, he showed up at UCLA without a scholarship or
reputation. He was a walk-on quarterback and was treated that way,
forced to wear No. 24 _ the same as record-breaking Bruin tailback
Freeman McNeil _ and dress without a locker.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Neuheisel ran the scout team, played special
teams and held for extra points. Mostly, he sat.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when it came time for a breakthrough, his first start
on national television against Georgia, he was referred to as
``Rickheisel'' by ABC's folksy Frank Broyles for much of the
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   None of this seemed to point to him becoming the next Washington
football coach, apparently Division I's second-highest-paid leader
or a familiar face on SportsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd be a lawyer,'' said Neuheisel's mother, Jane.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the boyish-looking one chose to argue his case on the
playing field, doing so successfully as a player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel capped his playing career in a big way, leading UCLA
to a Rose Bowl victory and accepting the game's Most Valuable
Player award. He had a spotty pro football experience. As a coach,
he has won 70 percent of his games, including all three of his bowl
outings.
</P>
<P>
   Cocky. Pass happy. Great golfer. Big wallet. All of it easily
could describe another college football heavyweight down in
Gatorville.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done some remarkable things to be just 37 years old,''
said David Norrie, Fox-TV college football analyst and former Bruin
quarterback and Neuheisel teammate. ``I'd call him a young Steve
Spurrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The Florida coach and Neuheisel, if all accounts are
accurate, now rank 1-2 in earnings among the nation's college
football coaches.
</P>
<P>
   An astronomical payday for the new Husky coach has been a source
of consternation for some in the community. But for the Huskies to
clone Spurrier, it apparently became a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told them, `I've got a good job and if you want to be
Florida or Florida State of the West, you're not only going to have
to pay me a big-time salary but also my assistants and make a total
commitment to be the best,''' said Neuheisel's father, Dick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the difference between Washington and what (athletic
director) Barbara Hedges was doing, and Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel would seem a natural for making persuasive closing
statements. Law runs in the family. His father is an attorney, as
are two of his three sisters. He has a law degree and passed two
bar exams himself.
</P>
<P>
   When torts and briefs weren't being tossed around the family
home in Tempe, Ariz., Neuheisel was playing football, basketball
and baseball with equal aplomb at McClintock High. The fall sport
became his passion when, as a junior, Neuheisel led McClintock to a
4A state title and 14-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   On the frail side, he wouldn't become a Division I recruit. But
he was bright and funny. He could talk his way into any situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dated my daughter, and I played golf with him,'' said Karl
Kiefer, his high school football coach. ``I'm not amazed at
anything he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel considered attending Princeton or accepting an
appointment from the Naval Academy. Hometown Arizona State offered
him an academic scholarship. He got hung up on UCLA while watching
the Pac-10 team prepare for the 1979 Fiesta Bowl against Arkansas.
Then-coach Terry Donahue took an instant liking to the kid, told
him he was once a Bruin walk-on himself.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Neuheisel showed up dragging a guitar behind
him. He was a born entertainer. He didn't play much football at
first, but school officials used to take him to a booster breakfast
club to sing and mesmerize the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved him down there,'' said Jerry Long, former Bruin
assistant football coach and director of athletic promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to get out his guitar for dates,'' said Norrie, also a
frat brother. ``He doesn't have a shy bone in his body.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun-loving side of Neuheisel comes from his mother. While
others in the family spend their days in court or a coach's office,
she manages 42 employees on a nine-hole Tempe golf course that she
and her husband have owned since 1984. They live on the third hole.
</P>
<P>
   Originally from Wisconsin, the Neuheisels moved to Tempe's
warmer climate when their only son was 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I talk like this,'' Jane Neuheisel said, doing her
best ``Fargo'' impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel lost and regained his starting job as a UCLA senior.
He set an NCAA record that stood until this year by completing 25
of 27 passes, including 18 in a row, in a 27-24 victory over the
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   He played briefly in the NFL for San Diego and Tampa Bay, a
little longer in the USFL with the San Antonio Gunslingers. He's
still waiting on paychecks from the latter.
</P>
<P>
   He would return to UCLA as a graduate assistant under Donahue
solely to tutor Troy Aikman, then a redshirt. Promoted to a
fulltime job, he showed his creativity, making another walk-on,
John Barnes, into a productive quarterback. He left when Bob Toledo
became head coach and chose someone else as offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   After one year as as an assistant at Colorado, Neuheisel
succeeded Bill McCartney as head coach, even though he still hadn't
been an offensive coordinator. He blew away all other applicants
with a charismatic interview.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel hasn't been perfect. His third Colorado team finished
5-6, and the five wins that season were forfeited because of an
ineligible player. He has been criticized for his running game, for
not beating Nebraska, for his glibness.
</P>
<P>
   But he brought fun to the Buffaloes, taking players skiing,
rafting and partying. Before the recent Aloha Bowl, he rented a
Denver sports bar and threw a Hawaiian luau for his team, complete
with singers and hula dancers. Hours earlier at the same place, he
entertained about 30 recruits.
</P>
<P>
   People have wondered why some of this state's top prospects
would shun the Huskies in recent years. Ty Gregorak, a linebacker
from Spokane, has good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Neuheisel showed up at Gregorak's home carrying
the Butkus Award, given days earlier to Colorado linebacker Matt
Russell for being the nation's best at that position. The coach sat
the trophy on a kitchen table and dared Gregorak to win one
himself. Where do I sign?
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak had been a diehard Husky fan. His parents were alums.
Now Neuheisel is a Husky and Gregorak is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't lie to you,'' the linebacker said. ``I've thought,
`What would have happened if (the hiring) had happened a few years
ago?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
