<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-BOOSTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOSTER PRAISES HIRING OF `BIG-TIME' COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ University of Washington boosters who supported former
coach Jim Lambright and those who were glad he was fired agreed on
one thing Sunday: that hiring Colorado's Rick Neuheisel was a good
move.
</P>
<P>
   They believe he will salvage Washington's recruiting efforts
before the Feb. 3 letter of intent signing date and energize a
program that failed to record its first winning season in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime booster Doug Glant, a staunch Lambright supporter,
praised athletic director Barbara Hedges for netting Neuheisel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a worse record than Jim the last two years (13-10
compared to Lambright's 14-10), and that's without sanctions and
with an easier schedule, but the fact of the matter is I think
Barbara Hedges went out and hired a big-time guy,'' Glant said.
``She did that brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Glant has been openly critical of fellow boosters who pressured
Hedges to fire Lambright. But he also credited them with working
behind the scenes to make it possible to hire Neuheisel at such a
high salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys stake their careers and their reputations on what
they did last week to Jim,'' Glant said. ``Now, given that, they
did exactly what they should have done, and that's hire the best
guy you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those who wasn't surprised at Neuheisel's hiring was Ron
Crockett, a member of the Tyee Club's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably as good a recruiter as we could ever find, and
he's got a very proven track record on that,'' Crockett said.
``He's offensive minded and comes from the offensive side of the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Crockett believes that the best football programs often are run
by coaches whose speciality is crafting innovative offenses, and he
credited Hedges with finding one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she did a great job,'' Crockett said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the role boosters might have played in brokering the
deal for Neuheisel _ reported to be in excess of $1 million a year
_ Crockett said he knew of no direct involvement. One newspaper
account had boosters helping to buy out Neuheisel's mortgage for
his university-paid $850,000 home in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what boosters are doing that,'' he said. ``I know
I have never been approached on anything like that. There are
implications that (Hedges) had sat down with boosters and tried to
put together money from outside sources, and that really has not
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Glant said the salary paid to Neuheisel and the $4 million a
year paid to the Seahawks' new coach, Mike Holmgren, proves that
Seattle is willing to be a major player in the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from being a small town in the Pacific Northwest that
tries to get guys like Jim Owens early and cheap ... to going out
and paying the second-most in the country for a coach,'' Glant
said. ``It's just a different world than I'm used to. I'm from a
different era.''
</P>
<P>
   Another booster from that era, Herb Mead, believes the UW
program now has a secure future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess on the wish list of all boosters is to get somebody
like him. The more credibility, the better,'' Mead said.
``Everybody I've heard from or been associated with thinks it's a
very positive move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
