r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-FACULTY-S     01-11 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-FACULTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW FACULTY LEADERS DECRY NEUHEISEL'S SALARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Not everyone at Montlake was rejoicing Sunday about
the hiring of Rick Neuheisel as the University of Washington
football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty members say Neuheisel's salary package, reported to
be worth about $1 million a year, is a slap in the face for the
university's teachers, who are paid an average salary of about
$60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty leaders called Neuheisel's salary ``obscene'' and
``insane,'' particularly because it comes at a time when the
Legislature and regents are considering tuition increases to boost
faculty pay, which is ranked 16th in comparison to 24 other similar
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the faculty is underpaid and we're so much behind
our peers, but this is the football coach. ... It is sort of
obscene,'' said Galya Diment, president of the UW chapter of the
American Association of University Professors.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Kaltsounis, chairman of the UW Faculty Senate, said the
salary sends the wrong message to the public as well as faculty and
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``In principle, it's going the wrong way,'' Kaltsounis said.
``We're moving in the direction of professional sports, it looks
like, which I think is an insane direction. As a university, we
should be leading away from insane direction.''
</P>
<P>
   UW president Richard McCormick noted that the athletic
department operates on a budget independent from the university's
general fund and that the football program pays for more than two
dozen athletic programs that don't make money.
</P>
<P>
   No tax or general fund money will be used to pay Neuheisel,
McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the dollars are generated by the football program.
There's not one penny of state funds or tax appropriations or any
other university money in the (salary) program,'' McCormick said.
``It comes from filling Husky Stadium six times a year, going on
the radio and television with those games, and the commercial
endorsements that accompany it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the athletic department supports itself still
doesn't make Neuheisel's salary any easier for faculty members to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a separate department and you can argue that they have to
do what they have to do,'' said Kaltsounis. ``But it is unfortunate
that the public is willing to support a football coach at that
salary and the athletic department to the extent that they do. When
it comes to supporting the quality of the university, we seem to
have difficulty getting through to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaltsounis said he hopes that the same boosters who support the
football program will show their support for faculty pay increases
when the Legislature considers them in the coming session.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years we have been saying that we are hurting the quality
of education because we are losing faculty (because of low pay),
but unfortunately we don't get the same kind of excited support for
that aspect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diment, a professor of Slavic languages and literature, sees no
justification for paying the football coach so much money. She
noted that some associate professors in the humanities department
make less than $40,000 a year with 20 years of teaching experience.
</P>
<P>
   Kaltsounis would like to see some of the money generated by
football be returned to the entire university. But McCormick said
there was a ``thick wall'' keeping academic programs and the
athletic department apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, that's a good thing,'' McCormick said, adding his
endorsement to how athletic director Barbara Hedges conducted the
hiring process. ``The argument that we make on behalf of faculty
salaries is the same one that Barbara makes on behalf of the
coach's salary: If you want to recruit and retain the best _
whether you're talking about an English department program or a
football program _ you've got to pay for the best,'' McCormick
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
