r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-RECRUITIN     01-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-RECRUITING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKY RECRUITS REACT POSITIVELY TO HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Forgive Kevin Ware if he's feeling he just can't get
it right. The 6-foot-4, 252-pound tight end from Houston has
experienced a weird slice of college-football recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Ware, from Klein Oak Spring, Texas, a Houston suburb, was the
first recruit to give University of Washington coaches a verbal
commitment in September.
</P>
<P>
   But then startling events began to happen around the Huskies.
They fired Jim Lambright Dec. 30, leading Ware to scrub his campus
visit that was supposed to start Jan. 8 in favor of his second
choice, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Then it got crazy in Boulder Saturday night at a dinner that
included players and recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all sitting down, watching little highlight films,''
he said. ``And then here comes Coach (Rick) Neuheisel.''
</P>
<P>
   Here came coach Neuheisel telling the group, Ware says, that he
had turned down overtures twice from Washington, but the third one
was too good to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were crying, his staff was crying,'' Ware said last
night upon his return to Texas. ``We were kind of shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Ware was grinning. He says he's certain to attend
Washington now that Neuheisel has changed addresses to Seattle, to
the place he wanted at the start.
</P>
<P>
   With a slight kicker, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a couple of more trips,'' he said, referring to
Oklahoma and Miami. ``I gave my word, and I'm a man of my word.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, reaction to Neuheisel's hire was generally positive
among UW recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Arnold, the All-America running back from Kennedy High,
returned last night from a visit to UCLA and, said coach Bob
Bourgette, might yet visit the Huskies as his fifth trip. Notre
Dame will be No. 4 in two weeks, and Arnold has already been to
Michigan and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the University of Washington as well as anybody,''
Bourgette said.
</P>
<P>
   John Anderson, the All-America kicker from Boca Raton, Calif.,
who had committed earlier to the UW, said, ``I'm just going to stay
with Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted, however, ``I'm confused. Everyone for a whole week
and a half told me there was a guy from Toledo (head coach Gary
Pinkel) and then a guy from Iowa _ or Idaho (Chris Tormey). It's
more of a shock than anything, but I guess it's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Although stability has returned to the UW in the eyes of most
recruits, it remains to be seen whether Neuheisel and his staff
will honor all the verbal commitments made by Husky recruits. They
are non-binding and it isn't uncommon for new coaches not to follow
through.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last night at an impromptu news conference about them,
Neuheisel was vague.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to pre-Neuheisel conversations with UW officials,
Tyler Krambrink, a linebacker from Eatonville, said, ``They (UW
officials) pretty much told me my scholarship was going to be
honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Krambrink said that after the firing of Lambright, he was called
by UW senior associate director Ralph Bayard and UW athletic
director Barbara Hedges, attempting to smooth the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope something happens soon,'' said committed
quarterback Cody Pickett of Caldwell (Idaho), referring to interest
by Neuheisel and a new staff. ``I've got the Arizona State coaches
on hold, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington was my favorite, but if something happens, I'll go
in a different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Adis Davtyan, a 6-foot-3, 295-pound offensive lineman from
Glendale (Calif.) Community College, said Neuheisel's hiring
``doesn't matter. I'm still going there.'' He was also recruited by
Kansas State, Texas A&AMP;M, Alabama and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Irony is stalking Denver recruit Terrell Bailey, a 6-8,
285-pound lineman who committed last month to Washington. But his
father, Irvin Bailey, said Sunday Bailey will stay with the Huskies
provided the interest remains mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell never considered Colorado,'' said Irvin Bailey. ``They
don't recruit very much in Denver. They seemed to cater to the
California athlete and the Texas athlete. They're somewhat
estranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that CU hasn't tried. My son was partial to
Washington. The football program would send out information about
the Seattle area, the business school, life after football. The
University of Washington seemed to be interested in our son as a
human being rather than a piece of meat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
