<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGES PUTS CAREER ON LINE TO GET NEUHEISEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If I were casting the next Hollywood movie about a
hijacking, I know who would play the female-villain lead: Barbara
Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't look the part. But jeez, does she have a feel for
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Stealthy, clever, bold, reckless, borderline suicidal and
unfazed by ethical consequences, the University of Washington
athletic director lacks only a black ski mask and a rappelling
rope.
</P>
<P>
   Her purloining of Rick Neuheisel from the University of Colorado
was 007-ish in its amusing craftiness. She didn't need a gun. Money
and guts are always much more effective weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom of the deed remains to be seen. She has hired a good
coach who also brings baggage. And she spent as if she had a
limitless Nordstrom credit card at a 3-for-1 sale.
</P>
<P>
   As Neuheisel said, it was a blockbuster deal. If it doesn't
work, Hedges' block is busted.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know she was this desperate.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the choices of either Gary Pinkel or Chris
Tormey, former UW assistants who were the safe, familiar
candidates, Neuheisel is high-risk, high-reward. Hedges interviewed
Pinkel and Tormey early, and figuratively tucked the eager Don
James clones in her back pocket. If her gamble with big names
didn't work, they were the undynamic choices that at least wouldn't
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   But to appease boosters and keep up with the Seahawk miracle of
Mike Holmgren, Hedges felt she needed more _ a well-known name with
Division I success who also was skilled in sucking up, which is as
much a part of college football as scripting two-deep zone
coverages.
</P>
<P>
   She found that in Neuheisel, as well as a back-door exit for him
to Seattle _ Colorado's state law that prevents employees from
having contracts longer than one year. Although colleges usually
find a way around such rules to offer security to coaches,
apparently the only cash that Hedges has to pay to extricate
Neuheisel is the balance of a mortgage on his $850,000 home in
Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   But then she had to pay dearly to persuade Neuheisel that moving
from one school of similar rank and prestige to another wasn't a
trade unworthy of the grief. She bought him off with the kind of
contract that is normally reserved for Florida's Steve Spurrier and
Florida State's Bobby Bowden _ seven figures annually to stay in
the top 10 and win the occasional national title.
</P>
<P>
   The contract not only is astonishing for Washington and the
Pac-10 _ even though it isn't tax money, we're still talking about
a major research university that is supposed to be a symbol of
judgment, rectitude and sobriety _ it is flabbergasting for a coach
who, at 37, is only four years into a head coaching career. That
career has not included so much as a conference championship, and
is being outstripped by former Big 12 doormats Kansas State and
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   His 33-14 record at Colorado is impressive, as were his three
wins in as many bowls. But like Jim Lambright's 44-25-1 mark in his
six seasons at Washington, numbers are deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having big-game shortcomings, Neuheisel created an
impression of insincerity among many in Boulder. His youth and
ambition led many to believe, accurately as it turned out, that his
oft-repeated desire for a lifelong career in Colorado was
dishonest. As recently as Colorado's Aloha Bowl victory over
Oregon, Neuheisel reconfirmed to reporters in Honolulu that he was
staying in Boulder ``for the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, for someone who has a law degree as well as a father
who is a politician, Neuheisel is well trained in the forked-tongue
arts. All we need to find out next is that he once was a
journalist, and he will have the three most unsavory professional
pedigrees in American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the Husky job, too, is a way station for Neuheisel.
Which is OK, this being America and all. The problem is that the
athletic department will spend $267,000 next year so that Lambright
won't coach, and perhaps as much as $700,000 for Neuheisel to get
out from under his Colorado mortgage. So that's around a million
bucks, separate from salary, just to make the coaching switch.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the money comes from athletic department revenues
and not the state, it will be hard to amortize that expense in the
mind of a part-time prof on upper campus making $18,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Husky athletic department is supposedly awash in
its own cash surpluses, when the extensive facilities campaign now
under way is added to the two buyouts and Neuheisel's whopper
contract, Hedges is about one pair of pumps away from an Imelda
Marcos shoe binge.
</P>
<P>
   To undertake this controversial spree, Hedges had to feel that
the football program, and by extension the entire athletic
department, was near a cliff and needed an abrupt turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Her evidence is slowly coming out. In the two weeks since
Lambright's firing, it's clear that most current players are not
only not upset, most are happy. Even though few are willing to go
on the record for obvious reasons, player contempt for Lambright's
approach and techniques was high.
</P>
<P>
   Said one former athletic department employee: ``When he got the
head coaching job, he changed, and it wasn't for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that relatively few players were willing to
recommend the program to potential recruits. That is devastating.
So the change had to come, even if many in the public and the
legions of Lambright backers were confused, angry or both.
</P>
<P>
   But the program's appearance of disarray mitigated against
getting an established, high-profile replacement. Pinkel and
Tormey, from smaller schools, were there, but only until Hedges
threw big money at a candidate increasingly vulnerable in his own
job did a deal for a more glamorous figure come together.
</P>
<P>
   She and Neuheisel have created some serious resentment in
Boulder, where the athletic department is furious, the players feel
betrayed and the recruits are bewildered. Neuheisel, who never
quite won over many Colorado boosters and media, is being blasted
from Pike's Peak on down.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, the money will create resentment, too. Hedges paid a
huge premium to resolve what amounted to an athletic department
emergency, and will have to account for how matters became so dire
on her watch.
</P>
<P>
   If Neuheisel bolts again in the next few years, if he fails to
reverse the program's decay, well, it will be a return to
jock-factory crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges won't get a second chance to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
