<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7312 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDIN     01-11 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK CARDINALS WILL HAVE THEIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When prizefighter Stanley Ketchel died, a friend said in
tribute, ``Start counting _ he'll get up at nine.''
</P>
<P>
   These were the 1998 Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Comebacks were routine. Late heroics defined them. Time after
time they picked themselves up and fought back and won games in the
darnedest ways when it appeared they no longer had a prayer, or a
pulse.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cards the clock didn't matter. You never could count
them out.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This joy ride of a season ended against the Minnesota Vikings, a
team as explosive and relentless as the Metrodome's ear-splitting
noise. The Wild Cards ran three offensive plays in the first
quarter. ``Three.'' They fell 17 points behind before a nervous
Jake Plummer completed his first pass to the right-colored jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer called it ``a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards felt as if they had fallen through an ink-black circle
cut in a frozen lake by a fisherman or tumbled headlong into a hole
from which there seemed no escape.
</P>
<P>
   How do you come back, on the road, against the Vikings, who
scored more points this year than any team in NFL history?
</P>
<P>
   You don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we threw a shovel of dirt out,`` Lomas Brown said
after the 41-21 loss, ``two more came back on top of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals couldn't contain Randall Cunningham and Cris
Carter and Randy Moss _ although Pro Bowl cornerback Aeneas
Williams did his best. Shaky all season against the run, the
defensive line couldn't stop Vikings running back Robert Smith, a
human snowplow.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings should come with a warning label, like a box of
dynamite. They kept running and passing and scoring. They showed
off their superior talent. They flashed their superior smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McGinnis, the Cards' defensive coordinator, felt like a
fire chief battling a four-alarm blaze. He didn't have nearly
enough help. The Cards couldn't make a third-down stop. When it
finally was over, it wasn't what McGinnis said that told the story.
It was his expression. As he walked off the field, McGinnis _ a
leading candidate to become the Chicago Bears' next head coach _
rolled his eyes and heaved a weary sigh.
</P>
<P>
   This was Minnesota's game, its place, its fans. The home field
proved to be a big advantage. The cheering crowd, in symphony with
music cranked to full volume, was so loud Plummer covered the ear
holes of his helmet with his hands. He couldn't hear radio
instructions from the sideline. His offensive linemen couldn't hear
Jake when he called signals. The Cardinals tried using a ``silent
count,'' but one snafu led to a fumbled snap, and a killer
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, the Cardinals sat in companionable silence.
The players expressed mixed feelings. So did the owner. Asked
whether this wildly exciting season made him feel younger or older
than his 67 years, Bill Bidwill thought a moment then said,
quietly, ``I guess a little bit of both.''
</P>
<P>
   The close games (the Cards won seven by three points or less)
turned Bidwill's beard a little grayer. The strides this team made
also heartened everyone who cares about the Cardinals, the most
overdue team in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards went 9-7 during the regular season, their first
winning record since 1984. They beat the Cowboys in the playoffs.
They won over doubting fans, skeptics who said the Cardinals can't
win. Cynics who said this franchise never will do anything under
the Bidwill family ownership.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been fashionable being a Cardinal, or a fan. Veteran
players who suffered through one losing season after another can
appreciate the old line by former big league catcher Bob Uecker:
``The cops once picked me up on the street at 3 a.m. and fined me
$500 for being drunk, and $100 for being with the Phillies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards are no longer a joke. The players who dressed in
silence were upset. ``Ridiculous,'' Ronald McKinnon said of the
defense's inability to stop the run. But the Cardinals, who had won
four in a row coming into this game, know they have something here.
They look at the Vikings as a measuring stick. They see Sunday as
not an ending but a step in a new beginning. Growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards have two first-round draft choices. Rob Moore and
Jamir Miller must be re-signed. But the building blocks are in
place, and the most important one is the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jake Plummer went to New York as a Heisman Trophy
finalist. The morning of the big announcement the ASU senior, who
didn't win, was in the souvenir shop of the Downtown Athletic Club.
He bought several items, some for himself, others as gifts for
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever be back here again,'' Jake said at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   He could have said the same thing about the playoffs. But he
didn't. This kid knows he has a future, and so does his football
team. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 0140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7314 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDIN     01-11 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK CARDINALS WILL HAVE THEIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
