instructions from the sideline. His offensive linemen couldn't hear
Jake when he called signals. The Cardinals tried using a ``silent
count,'' but one snafu led to a fumbled snap, and a killer
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, the Cardinals sat in companionable silence.
The players expressed mixed feelings. So did the owner. Asked
whether this wildly exciting season made him feel younger or older
than his 67 years, Bill Bidwill thought a moment then said,
quietly, ``I guess a little bit of both.''
</P>
<P>
   The close games (the Cards won seven by three points or less)
turned Bidwill's beard a little grayer. The strides this team made
also heartened everyone who cares about the Cardinals, the most
overdue team in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards went 9-7 during the regular season, their first
winning record since 1984. They beat the Cowboys in the playoffs.
They won over doubting fans, skeptics who said the Cardinals can't
win. Cynics who said this franchise never will do anything under
the Bidwill family ownership.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been fashionable being a Cardinal, or a fan. Veteran
players who suffered through one losing season after another can
appreciate the old line by former big league catcher Bob Uecker:
``The cops once picked me up on the street at 3 a.m. and fined me
$500 for being drunk, and $100 for being with the Phillies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards are no longer a joke. The players who dressed in
silence were upset. ``Ridiculous,'' Ronald McKinnon said of the
defense's inability to stop the run. But the Cardinals, who had won
four in a row coming into this game, know they have something here.
They look at the Vikings as a measuring stick. They see Sunday as
not an ending but a step in a new beginning. Growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards have two first-round draft choices. Rob Moore and
Jamir Miller must be re-signed. But the building blocks are in
place, and the most important one is the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jake Plummer went to New York as a Heisman Trophy
finalist. The morning of the big announcement the ASU senior, who
didn't win, was in the souvenir shop of the Downtown Athletic Club.
He bought several items, some for himself, others as gifts for
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever be back here again,'' Jake said at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   He could have said the same thing about the playoffs. But he
didn't. This kid knows he has a future, and so does his football
team. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
