<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BICKLEY_CARDINALS     01-11 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY_CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS MUST FEEL THIS PAIN AT CAMP TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ You can be happy. They can not.
</P>
<P>
   They must remember what it felt like to trip over their own awe.
How embarrassing it felt to hold the ball for 54 seconds in the
first quarter. How awful it is to lose a winnable game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Cardinals have a wonderful future. But it can't sprout
from assumptions, that a 41-21 loss to the Vikings proves a Super
Bowl is just around the corner. They must remember that consolation
is for losers, and somehow the humiliation must linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll take from this game a few weeks from now is a lot
different than what we feel now,'' tight end Chris Gedney said.
`This was a big loss. And right now, it stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult after a breakthrough season. There will be
pats on the back, fuzzy memories of a playoff win in Dallas, tales
of resiliency about a team that defied the odds and its ugly past.
But the odor from Sunday still must be in the air when they arrive
in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, there will be a whirlwind of optimism swirling
around this football team,'' Larry Centers said. ``Next time we get
to camp, we're preparing to go to the NFC Championship Game, and
ultimately, the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a learning curve for every team. Nine days
ago, they whipped Dallas, the hint of future glory. This was
supposed to be the game that illustrated the rest of the journey,
except the expected 20-point loss was not a blow-out, but a gift.
</P>
<P>
   When Jake the Snake-bit calmed down, it was too late. His first
two completed passes were to the Vikings, and the nightmare was on.
The temperature was below zero, and after 15 minutes, so was the
total yardage. And then came frustrating moments when the game was
really lost, the windows that kept opening and closing before the
Cardinals could climb into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, the secondary did fine against a lethal
trio of receivers, particularly Aeneas Williams. But it should be
disturbing that the defense couldn't stop the run, an overall
performance that might cost Dave McGinnis a job in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the opportunity to finish them off and get the ball
back to our offense in the fourth quarter,'' Williams said. ``And
we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they weren't ready. Certainly not for the noise,
which borders on ridiculous in Minnesota. Somehow, the NFL allows
speakers to be placed behind the visitors' bench. Allows music to
be played at dangerous decibel levels while the guests try to
huddle. For all the good maneuvers near the end of the season,
Vince Tobin was wrong in not piping in simulated noise during
practice.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, they simply weren't ready to win this game.
Which is OK. As long as they don't take the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to realize that we could've won that football
game,'' Centers said. ``And that we match up pretty well with that
team.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, Cardinal-mania reached a new level. An
overflow crowd in a hotel bar chanted Cardinal chants. Michael
Bidwill walked in and was stopped for autographs. One man even
wanted his picture taken with the owner's son, except when his wife
pushed the button, oops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of film, honey,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect metaphor for the old Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, an unknowing media attendant handed a Vikings' towel
to owner Bill Bidwill. He shot back with a message: ``Tell them
thanks for the shoeshine cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect metaphor for tomorrow, and all its promise.
</P>
<P>
   Except the new Cardinals must remember that in many ways, they
gave a game away on Sunday, and it must hurt. All the way to
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   There is danger in being satisfied with what you didn't
accomplish. In feeling good because you could've done better,
could've stunned the world. There is danger in realizing you're
closer than you thought.
</P>
<P>
   They exceeded expectations. They won a playoff game. They turned
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   But the season ended with a nauseating loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, we lost by 20,'' Corey Chavous said. ``Who can be
happy about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
