<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7316 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-VIKINGS     01-11 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-VIKINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURPLE REIGNS: JITTERS, TURNOVERS DIG HOLE FOR CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Bobby McFerrin was on the Metrodome field for 2
minutes and 1 second on Sunday, hitting some incredibly high notes
while belting out our national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1 minute and 7 seconds longer than the Cardinals
offense was out there in the first quarter. With quarterback Jake
Plummer hitting mostly low notes, the Cardinals quickly were in the
position they knew they couldn't afford to be in _ 17 points behind
the NFL's most explosive team, the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jake rattled and rolled, throwing wildly and serving up
two early interceptions that helped dig the hole, and then fumbling
away a snap in the third quarter when the Cardinals had a chance to
cut the margin to six points.
</P>
<P>
   When the turnovers were combined with a defense that couldn't
stop the Vikings, the Cardinals' dream ride ended in the second
round of the playoffs. The NFC Central champion Vikings thumped the
Cards, 41-21, to move on to the NFC Championship game against
Atlanta here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Worry, Be Happy'' was a McFerrin classic, and it could
have been the mantra of a young team that exceeded all projections.
But the Cardinals were singing a different tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're mad,'' said Plummer, who completed 23 of 41
passes for 242 yards, no touchdowns and the two interceptions. ``We
should be mad for a while and let this sting. We had a great
opportunity, and we did not take advantage of it. Maybe a month
from now when I'm teeing off, I'll look back and think we did have
a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Vikings, with a league-leading 15-1 regular-season
record, are having an even greater one, showing why they were
unsurpassed as a scoring threat.
</P>
<P>
   With three All-Pros leading the way on their line, an explosive
running back, the league's best trio of wide receivers and a
veteran quarterback, who at age 35 still has plenty of mobility,
the Vikings scored on seven of their 10 possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're awfully good,'' said Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin.
``I'm not sure I know what a juggernaut is, but they looked pretty
good to me. They have great skill people.''
</P>
<P>
   That started with Vikings running back Robert Smith rushing for
124 yards, 6.5 a carry. Leroy Hoard added 44 hard-fought yards up
the middle, 4.0 a carry, and scored three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed they were able to run the ball like that,''
Tobin said. ``That's where defense has to start, no matter the
skill of the receivers. We tried everything in our defensive
arsenal, and nothing was particularly effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by a rushing game, Vikings quarterback Randall
Cunningham was free to pass for 236 yards and three touchdowns.
Cris Carter caught five of them for 82 yards. Randy Moss grabbed
four for 73.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of trying to force the ball, I've got Robert Smith to
hand off to,'' said Cunningham, who was coaxed out of retirement
last year to sign with the Vikings. ``When you know you've got
second-and-three, that makes a difference in my game preparation. I
don't have to scramble around anymore and try to make things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With 416 total yards, the Vikings had 100 more than the
Cardinals. The Vikings punted only once. Five of their kickoffs
were touchbacks, leaving the Cardinals a long field when playing
catchup. The Cardinals had 13 penalties, many caused by the crowd
noise. But the crusher was the three turnovers that gave Minnesota
17 easy points.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals defense, which had surrendered only five
touchdowns in its previous four games, yielded five touchdowns to a
team that set an NFL scoring record this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up short today, but we've laid the foundation for good
teams in the future,'' Tobin said. ``This is still a very young
team, and Minnesota is a very veteran team in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play this game to win the Super Bowl. You have to go in
increments to get there, and we made giant strides.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, around whom the future of the franchise revolves,
acknowledged that on this afternoon he played more like a wide-eyed
24-year-old neophyte than a $29.7 million superstar that the team
believes he will be one day. After his first five throws, he had no
completions and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was loud, a different situation,'' Plummer said of the
crowd of 63,760 in the Metrodome. ``We hadn't been any place like
this. The first interception was just me being hyped up wanting to
make a big play. The next one, I just didn't get my feet set and I
threw the ball high.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer settled down and positioned the Cardinals to get back
into the game in the third quarter. Then, he made the killer play.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cardinals trailing, 27-13, and in possession of the
ball at their 32, Plummer, fumbled a snap from center Aaron Graham.
Minnesota's Antonio Banks recovered at the Cardinals 19, and the
Vikings scored in three plays to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just shifted to a defensive front where we had to
audible into a better protection,'' Plummer said. ``We were going
on a silent count because of the crowd noise, and that process
takes about 4 seconds. There were 3 seconds on the play clock.
That's something you can't have happen in a critical situation.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
