<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-NOISE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THAT CLAMOR IN THE COSMOS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had to name a complaint about life that's high on the
list of most people over, say, age 40, it would be (no, not that;
clean up your mind) noise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our world, quite simply, is overdecibeled, overshrill, overover.
From TVs and CD players to stadia full of half-drunken football
fans to airplanes and cars and trucks and motorcycles and live rock
bands practicing in your basement (well, maybe not your basement,
but certainly mine), noise is the all-too-jarring atmosphere of our
lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not talking about high-crime neighborhoods full of
crackling gunfire or war zones exploding with deadly mortar fire
but, rather, ordinary American life. Now, compare all that noise
with the impression you have of outer space. Ah, silence. Deep,
wonderful, amazing quiet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, we're about to find out if your impression is right. The
National Aeronautics and Space Administration has launched an
experiment that I'm pretty sure we'll all regret some day. We're
sending a microphone to Mars to help us hear whatever noise is
going on there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently NASA isn't content to add to the national noise level
by blasting rockets into space now and then. It wants to find more
noise out in the cosmos and bring it back to Earth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As I say, this strikes me as a bozo notion, but I'm nearly
always willing for science to work its way through the rubble of
bad ideas on the chance it will serendipitously find something
wonderful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Polar Lander took off recently from Cape Canaveral,
which I think used to be Cape Kennedy, which used to be Cape
Canaveral, unless I've got it all mixed up with Hyannisport, which
used to be Hyannisport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander will take the entire upcoming baseball season
and most of the next football season to get where it's going. It is
expected to land on Mars on Dec. 3, by which time we'll be sick of
1999, no doubt, and eager for the chaos, turmoil and higher taxes
promised by 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I haven't figured out why NASA's wizards picked the 181st
anniversary of Illinois (my native state) joining the union for the
Mars landing. Maybe they wished to avoid conflicting with former
Saint Barbara's Day, the next day, Dec. 4. I don't know what _
besides ``former'' _ you call someone who, in 1970, was dropped
from the Roman Catholic Calendar of Saints, though when something
similar happened to St. Christopher all those dashboard statues
became known as Mr. Christopher medals. Whatever the thinking, the
Mars Microphone is to listen for the sounds of, well, no one knows
what. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mike was provided to NASA at no cost by the Planetary
Society of the University of California's Berkeley Space Sciences
Lab, an outfit known to its friends as OSUCBSSL, or oh-suck-bustle.
Or, anyway, known as that to me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OSUCBSSL says the mike is ``the first scientific instrument
funded by a public-interest organization to fly aboard a planetary
mission.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That makes it different from the scientific instrument funded by
a public-interest organization that flew aboard the space shuttle
last year, John Glenn, though there are those who would argue that
the U.S. Senate may not actually be a public-interest group. But
let it go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Planetary Society, in an officially launched press release,
quotes Louis Friedman, its executive director, as saying, ``Placing
a microphone to listen in on another world is a real opportunity
for discovery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. But I bet we discover one more thing at which to
shout: ``Please turn that darn thing down!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
