<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Communism seeks out religion
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Jan. 13, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The visit of Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema, a communist and
atheist, to Pope John Paul II last Friday was just another example
of the socialist world recognizing the fact that, despite its
personal dislike for religion _ a competitor _ it is impossible to
rule without it.
</P>
<P>
   And that's because the people the communists rule will not
abandon their religions. This has little to do with whether the
fundamentalist tenets of religion are true and more to do with the
fact that the people believe them to be.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro finally recognized that when he invited the pope to
Cuba, then followed up by reinstating Christmas as a holiday. To
say he used the pope's visit to strengthen his grip on a decaying
Cuba would be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   He found the formula: Give the people back their religion and
they'll become acquiescent about most other problems.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the case in Italy, where the communists have made
strong inroads since the end of World War II but at the expense of
provoking the papacy, inasmuch as atheism is a stated canon of
communist belief. By amending relationships with the Vatican _ by
going to the pope _ D'Alema has recognized the strongest emotional
link held by the Italian people: religion. He, like Castro, seems
to be saying that communism and religion can co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   While this pope's lifetime experiences, often heroic, ordinarily
would generate another opinion, the Polish-born and -raised pontiff
accepts these gestures and sees them as inroads to strengthen the
church within communist nations.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Mao Tse-Tung, China's founding communist ruler,
spoke often of God and of heaven. The newly released transcripts of
former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger's visits with Mao contain
many references to God, including this one in 1973 when Kissinger
was visiting the physically declining Mao and the conversation
turned to a possible attack by the U.S.S.R. on China: ``I'm not
afraid of anything. Anyway, God has sent me an invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything has succeeded in post-communist Russia, it has been
religion. It's been a constant, thousands of years older than
atheistic communism. Russians didn't just become Christians,
Muslims or Jews when the U.S.S.R. collapsed in 1991. Most of the
proletariat had remained faithful to a god through the 74 years of
Bolshevism, that faith passed down from generation to generation.
What happened in 1991 simply was an outing; it had been there all
along.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an essay that claims the beliefs of all religions
are valid or even rational; to each his own. What I am saying is
that most of the people of the world, from the U.S. to China and
everywhere in between, cling to some sort of faith. Call it
religion, call it mumbo-jumbo, call it superstition, call it
whatever you want, but to those people it is a faith.
</P>
<P>
   By instituting a form of government that maintains faith is
merely a delusion and, thus, cannot be practiced is to run against
the grain of human nature. You can force them to work longer on
behalf of the state, deny them foods and medicines, and most of
their rights, but you cannot separate people from their faith. It
is a battle the communists never could win. Only now are they
recognizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Italy never was in danger of losing its deep faith to communism.
The Vatican always has maintained a strong hand there, including
excommunicating communists in the immediate post-World War II years
when communism was growing rapidly in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, few, if any, of its premiers were anything but Roman
Catholic. But D'Alema is not. He is a pronounced atheist who sees
in Pope John Paul II a man he needs to create political stability
in an unstable but heavily Roman Catholic Italy.
</P>
<P>
   How the pope uses that to a religious advantage is anyone's
guess, but the Castro visit would indicate he knows what he's
doing.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
