<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gun industry has made itself a target
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With megabuck settlements won from the tobacco mongers as
inspiration, a growing number of individuals and cities are filing
lawsuits against gun makers in hopes of similar manna _ and, for
the well-intentioned among the plaintiffs, in hopes of forcing a
little sanity on the nation's lunatic gun trade.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco-equals-guns formula is rickety at best. In its
intended use, tobacco sickens and kills. Firearms maim and kill
mainly in their misuse. Tobacco, as a product, is pure liability.
Guns serve hunting, sport shooting, collecting and, although poorly
and with outsized risks, personal protection.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits dodge that awkward comparison by arguing,
variously, that the industry has been negligent in failing to adopt
easy safety features, winks at sales practices that all but openly
serve criminal buyers and produces far more weapons than legitimate
trade needs, knowing the excess must go to the under-age and the
underworld.
</P>
<P>
   Fair arguments, worth court time, but the industry feels it is
just a target of opportunity, and opportunists. Perhaps that's so
in some cases, but the industry has got it coming anyway. Its own
fierce opposition to a comprehensive national firearms policy has
forced the issues out of the political arena, where they really
belong, and into the courts as a backup venue.
</P>
<P>
   Polls since the 1930s have tracked steady public support for gun
control at 65 percent, give or take a bit. But the inert support
has been no match for its passionate opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby _ manufacturers, sellers and companion interest
groups like the National Rifle Association _ has used scare tactics
and lavish campaign contributions to run off or buy out Congress
and state legislatures. The result is a hopeless hodgepodge of laws
that are easily evaded and a mish-mash of muddled accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Other industrial countries have national firearms policies,
ranging from fairly accommodating to dauntingly prohibitive but in
any event with clear payoffs in public safety. It is not hard to
imagine a policy for us that would both respect private ownership
and serve public interests _ something like the familiar
car-and-driver model of registration and periodic licensing, with
the cheap handguns that are made for the thug and kid clienteles
banned.
</P>
<P>
   If there was ever a poster child for gun violence, we're it.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 200 million guns floating around this
country, 65 million of them handguns. Gun deaths, not counting
justifiable homicides, were running at about 33,500 annually at
last count. The huge jump in juvenile and young-adult murders in
the late '80s and early '90s was entirely the nasty work of gun
violence, as the firearms glut reached new hands.
</P>
<P>
   The public has a manifest interest in setting out reasonable
rules for firearms manufacture, sales and ownership. By
successfully closing off political deliberation and compromise, the
industry and the lobby have left public policy to be improvised by
the vagaries of litigation. They may come to regret their success.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
