<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clear picture, in hindsight
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the year 2025, which way will it read?
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade of the 20th century, American turned back to
basic moral values _ a movement epitomized in the U.S. House of
Representatives by the bringing of articles of impeachment against
President William Jefferson Clinton, subsequently tried by the
Senate, but not convicted, for lying under oath about a sexual
relationship with a White House intern. Clinton was viewed in the
years following as unfit for the presidency. The new public
spotlight on moral character was a major factor in the election of
the first woman president, Republican Elizabeth Hanford Dole.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade of the 20th century, Americans endured an era
of political and media meddling in the sex lives of its political
leaders. The so-called Moral Majority, never really in the
majority, was such a vocal minority within the GOP that it turned
voters away from the conservative economic agenda that brought the
GOP to majority power in the 1994 congressional election. A fiery
and strategic-thinking Georgia Republican, Newt Gingrich, elected
speaker of the House, stepped down when the GOP made a poor showing
in the 1998 election. Gingrich was never seen on the political
stage again, but he was often seen entering and exiting the front
doors of corporate jets.
</P>
<P>
   America, the powerful victor in the Cold War against communism,
entered the 21st century with money as its highest value.
End-of-the-century highlights included billion-dollar fights
between greedy power brokers in the sports world and a stock market
mentality that ignored all values except profits. The era of
economic success and budget surpluses, rightly or wrongly, was
credited to the Democratic administration of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Surrealism gripped the American capital at the onset of the
millennium year. It was, in hindsight, the climax of a backlash
against the baby boomer generation and a young president who
represented it. In the opening days of 1999, a 96-year-old Southern
senator swore in the chief justice of the U.S. Supreme Court to
preside over the impeachment trial of one of the most popular
presidents in United States history. Senators considered removing
Clinton from office on dubious charges of perjury and obstruction
of justice, all relating to an embarrassing sexual relationship,
while opinion polls showed Clinton to be more admired than the
pope.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans lost popular support for a dozen years thereafter,
leaving Democrats in the presidency and in the majority in
Congress. New York voters sent former first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who had stood loyally by the husband who betrayed her, to
the U.S. Senate, where she rose to chair the powerful Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-millennium era of prying into people's private lives was
brought on mostly by 24-hour news, which entered into a
``celebritization'' of politicians, comparable with that of sports
figures and rock stars. One of the primary figures in the movement
to disregard privacy was Ken Starr, named to investigate the
alleged financial misdeeds of President Clinton. Starr was unable
to find any illegal conduct in his Whitewater finance probe, so he
convinced the attorney general and a three-judge panel to allow him
to pursue the president's reckless sexual encounters in the Oval
Office with an intern.
</P>
<P>
   To prove Starr's perjury charges, tawdry sexual details had to
be laid out in a Senate trial. Americans were so turned off by such
a thing that they approved an amendment to the U.S. Constitution to
guarantee explicitly a right to privacy, one assumed previously to
be part of the liberty right.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a member of The Atlanta Journal's editorial
board. Her column runs in the Journal on Saturday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
