<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The most successful businesses get old by staying
new
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mean to tell me, Katie Scarlett O'Hara, that Tara _
that land doesn't mean anything to you? Why ... it's the only thing
that lasts.'' _ ``Gone With the Wind''
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett's daddy may have believed that only the land would last
in the South, but humidity and thirst are awfully enduring
features, too. That may help explain why two old Atlanta companies,
one big and one small, have a shot at celebrating the dawn of 2100.
</P>
<P>
   The Coca-Coca Co., incorporated in 1892, is secure among that
elite group of U.S. companies that have weathered a century of
fantastic social and technological change. Though Americans have
dramatically altered many of their tastes in the past century, they
still reach for a cold Coke when they're thirsty.
</P>
<P>
   And when Atlantans want to adjust their indoor climate, they
still hire Moncrief Heating and Air Conditioning Inc. In 1898, when
The Moncrief Furnace Co. was founded, Southerners controlled their
comfort by throwing another log on the fire or opening the door to
catch a breeze. So few furnaces existed in the 1890s that Moncrief
had to build the devices before they could install and repair them.
When air conditioning began to transform the South after 1950,
Moncrief starting building and installing those contraptions, too.
Today, with about 50 employees in Atlanta, the company is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   But how do these companies do it? Can they last another hundred
years?
</P>
<P>
   At least in the case of Coca-Cola, most Americans believe the
future looks promising. A recent national poll sponsored by the
Shell Oil Co. found that 89 percent of adults think the beverage
company will be around to toast 2100.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such optimism, the chances of pulling through a century
are fairly remote. ``In any industry, there are always far, far
more firms that enter and exit quickly than survive over a long
period,'' said David Hounshell, professor of technology and social
change at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh. ``The companies
that do survive are very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hounshell said survivors typically have two things in common:
No. 1, they entered their industry on the ground floor, and No. 2,
they hired smart people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helps to be an early entrant in your industry,'' he
said. So it's no surprise that pioneers such as Ford, Western
Union, General Electric and AT&AMP;T are survivors. And, ``It's very
important to have people who work harder and have better analytical
skills'' than competitors, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But being a trailblazer is no guarantee of success. Just ask
investors in the Hayes Corp. Once one of metro Atlanta's
highest-flying start-ups, Hayes collapsed into a heap of bills and
burnout last week. On its 21st birthday, the modem maker moved to
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a small company survive? By being aggressive in
adopting new technologies, says Moncrief chairman Frank Mutz. Even
a business as mundane as installing air conditioners requires heavy
doses of technology. ``The changes we are facing are
mind-boggling,'' Mutz said. ``It's unbelievable what we're doing
with computers.'' The company has just started using the Internet
to expand its heating and cooling business.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet for air conditioning? Yes, by using networked
computers, Moncrief is branching into distant cities, hiring
repairmen in Lexington, Ky., St. Louis, Indianapolis and elsewhere
while keeping the accounting, paging, billing, monitoring,
scheduling and so forth in the home office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   So can even a small business survive a second century? ``I see
no reason not to,'' Mutz said. ``We're actually excited about the
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not the humidity, it's the heat of
competition that keeps companies sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   This is a weekly report by Atlanta Constitution editorial writer
Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by the coming of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
