<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Swallowing a dog, choking on a flea
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fl.a _ Much has been made of the almost
unanimous support among blacks for President Clinton. The most
pious critics suggest that such support is an acceptance of lower
moral standards and a disregard for the level of decency and
integrity set forth in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that such critics consider another possibility:
government-sanctioned social conditioning. The history of black
people in this country has taught most of us that, in governing,
Americans condone selective morality, the kind that can swallow a
dog but choke on a flea to preserve power.
</P>
<P>
   Even when discriminatory practices by our government are
confirmed beyond any doubt, the public demands no official
admission of guilt to declare that past actions will not be
tolerated in the future. Nor in such cases of abuse of power is
there public outrage that a moral message must be sent to America's
children. We have only to look at recent events to confirm this
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Department of Agriculture settled a
discrimination suit brought by black farmers. This case was filed
in 1997 after many years of futile protests and public
demonstrations. Farmers argued that since 1983, the department
systematically had denied them loans and subsidies routinely given
to white farmers. Many black farmers lost part or all of their land
as they sank deeper and deeper into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Even after discrimination had been documented, records show that
department officials lied and used every legal maneuver to obstruct
justice. That caused little public concern, then or now, with this
suit being expediently settled by consent decree to avoid giving
wider exposure to blatant discriminatory practices. The $375
million settlement cannot compensate fully what the farmers lost,
nor can it make up for the loss to America's farm culture of
countless black people who wanted just to earn a living through
sweat and toil on their own land.
</P>
<P>
   Probably, many black youths who have taken up careers in the
drug trade or otherwise abandoned efforts to remain within the
system are amused that the government is offering the black farmers
chump change by today's standards: a minimum of $50,000 tax free
and forgiveness of their debts to the Agriculture Department. Money
as a moral salve is not a remedy that can heal the debilitating
wounds of official bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   The cynicism of those who have lost all respect for law,
however, warrants less concern than the settlement's provision that
the department does not admit it discriminated against the farmers.
The department agrees only that its procedures in handling bias
cases were ``flawed,'' says civil rights director Rosalind Gray.
And, may I add, tolerance of little flaws to serve the ends of
power is the American way.
</P>
<P>
   Such tolerance of ethical compromise emboldens other officials,
without regard to the Constitution, to routinely apply selective
morality as it suits their purpose. Evidence can be found
throughout this country's history _ from treatment of Native
Americans to discrimination against peoples of color. Indeed,
tolerance of immorality to perpetuate power among those
traditionally in power has become so pervasive that our intrinsic
perceptions of right and wrong are skewed by our politics more than
by any other principles.
</P>
<P>
   Lying under oath, sworn or implied by the responsibilities of
office, and obstruction of legal justice are grievous offenses.
Unfortunately, our government never has declared them punishable
behavior worthy of expulsion from office. Our children know that.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of Mr. Clinton's impeachment trial
resulting from his reprehensible sexual behavior, children will
ultimately conclude, as most blacks have already concluded, that
our government demands adherence to a strict moral code _ but only
when that standard serves the purposes of those in power. National
integrity should be made of sterner stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
