<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Cherish the moments
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Every so often, our senses awaken to the absolute
splendor of a given moment in time.
</P>
<P>
   I experienced such a moment recently. The scent of banana bread
baking filled the house. The boys and I were playing a board game
at the living room table. Music hummed softly in the background.
The dogs curled in slumber at our feet. Candles glowed warmly. It
was a moment awash in the goodness of life.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, most of our days are flooded with such moments.
The sweet, clean smell of your child's hair as he nuzzles in your
arms. The adoring brown eyes of your dog as she sits at your feet
showering your hand with dog kisses. Grandma's crocheted afghan
lovingly tucked around you by your husband as you drowse on the
couch. The heady aroma of hot, buttered popcorn. The page-turning
thrill of a well-written book.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeting moments all, often taken wholly for granted. Very few
are appreciated, especially in this day of gross sensationalism and
overstimulation.
</P>
<P>
   The news that bombards us daily is outrageous and confusing and
numbing. Special effects litter the media at every turn. It's a
deluge of sensory titillation that overwhelms. If it's not
exploding or morphing, or it doesn't come in the form of a
confession or an apology, it hardly registers on our awareness
scale. We live in a time when we can honestly say, ``I've seen it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that we get to a point where we don't see
anything. Too much is too much. For self-preservation, we have to
filter out a great deal of what assaults our senses.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, I swore off any movie that consisted
primarily of special effects. The other night, at the urging of our
sons, I relented and watched ``Amageddon'' with them. Halfway
through it, I was overloaded. Explosions and hurling meteors had
made a full frontal assault. Too much. Too much.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true with what passes for media coverage these days.
Do I really need to know about a growing list of politicians'
infidelities? It isn't new, but these days it is the news. Do I
really want to know about the cigar or the blue dress? Too much.
Too much.
</P>
<P>
   We have lost the art of subtlety, of clever nuance, of a finely
turned phrase or a delicate bon mot. Why are the movies based on
Jane Austen's books such a breath of fresh air? Because they allow
us to breathe. These carefully crafted movies return us to the
understated, where the most sensuous sexual expression is the touch
of hands and a fervent glance across the spinet piano.
</P>
<P>
   We now have seen and heard visions we could not have imagined.
So, of what use is our imagination? We have stripped it of its
possibility. What is left to dream?
</P>
<P>
   A telling moment for me occurred a few years ago. I was driving
our younger sons to the medical center for a doctor's appointment
when we saw a medivac helicopter landing on the medical center
roof. It hovered directly over us, the noise of its engine and
blades reverberating in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderstruck, one son, who was 5 at the time, whispered
reverently: ``Awesome graphics!''
</P>
<P>
   Reality had been reduced to a video game.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, those fragile moments of beauty and fulfillment are all
around us. We have to learn to readjust our antenna, to put a
V-chip block on the outrageous and the overdone. Life is more than
a never-ending assault on the senses.
</P>
<P>
   When we've reached our limit, we need to limit ourselves . . .
to the tiny, the inconspicuous, the delicate, the exquisite
ordinariness of the moments of our lives. It is where great meaning
is found.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
