<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Stammer at the sound of the tone
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Nobody sounds good on an answering
machine. No, not even Barry White.
</P>
<P>
   But become too aware of this fact, and you risk the heartbreak
of voice-mail freeze. And because every day increases the chances
that any telephone call you make will hook up to a machine,
voice-mail freeze can mess up your life. It can earn you the
contempt of superiors and the ridicule of subordinates. It can make
your romantic interest think twice and three times.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-mail freeze is a lot like stage fright. It happens when a
recording takes your message over the phone and you suddenly
realize you don't know what to say or what you said already didn't
come out right.
</P>
<P>
   Some people recover right away. Maybe most do. But many of us
get caught in a paralyzing spiral of embarrassment. If you back up
and explain yourself again, you will sound stupid. If you hang up,
you will be rude and mysterious. Perhaps a stalker and a candidate
for call-blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the seconds tick away and you don't know how much
time is left for more explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Your mind reels. You freeze. But wait, the lengthening silence
will sound even dumber on the phone than anything you'd say. Too
late. You can't do another take. You can't take it back. The tape
is still moving. The chip is still memorizing this pitiful
performance.
</P>
<P>
   This makes you freeze more. Remember: Two-minute message limits
are the norm. With time running out, you might try spitting out a
time you called and add a lame request to call back _ as though
someone would return a call from a voice-mail freezer _ or you
might wait out the clock and listen to the recording stop midway
through your last, pathetic ``uh.''
</P>
<P>
   You hang up the phone, sweating and trying to hide your
embarrassment. But to no avail. It's all on tape. It's all on the
memory chip. Recorded for the ages. A completed performance. The
person receiving the message might save it, might play it back a
few times, might let friends listen to it, might post it on a Web
site, or might add it to a CD compilation entitled the ``The 100
Dumbest Taped Messages of Western Man.'' (Call now, this CD is not
available in stores anywhere!) You don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Out of such uncertainty, voice-mail freeze spreads.
</P>
<P>
   The worst instances of voice-mail freeze aren't pitiable efforts
to recover from mistakes. They kick in when a recorded greeting
ends abruptly and you can't remember your lines. Maybe you wing it
by stammering out your name and number, but the words are hardly
off your lips before you need to figure out something else to say.
</P>
<P>
   These are the freeziest and most baffling of nonmessages for the
recipient. And they often take the entire time allotted in
unaccountable silences and stammering of monosyllables: ``uhm,
muhmf, uh, blheh, eh ...''
</P>
<P>
   One desperate way around voice mail freeze is to wonder aloud if
the person you're calling can hear the incoming call and is only
using the machine to screen messages. This comes from the vain hope
that maybe, just maybe, a live person is lurking somewhere close
by. It is a cry for help. It leaves you sounding like a desperate
member of a search-and-rescue team. ``Are you there? Can anyone
hear me? Shout if you can hear my voice ...''
</P>
<P>
   There is no graceful recovery if you're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For the very frustrated who are willing to brazen it out,
there's always the old switcheroo. You can pretend you are the
voice on the answering machine and demand the answering machine
leave you a message. ``I can't make it to the phone right now ...''
you state officiously.
</P>
<P>
   It's just confusing enough to your listener to cover a hasty
retreat, but it depends on you being able to make a convincing beep
at the end. Trying this more than once per answering machine is not
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   But these are mere palliatives. There ain't no cure for
voice-mail freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Until our technology can filter ``uhs'' from our phone voices,
listeners should discretely skip past the verbal thrashing about of
the voice-mail challenged. They should be understanding toward
those who just aren't meant for the recording business.
</P>
<P>
   And that's ... well, ... uh, ... really all I called to say.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
