<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Students speak out on school discipline
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A group of juniors at Campbell County High
School in northern Kentucky have responded to a column I wrote last
fall expressing my
</P>
<P>
   irritation with the parents of eight teens in Chelsea, Mich.,
who complained the school had no business suspending their kids
from school sports for 30 days for breaking into a local club. I
suggested the parents (and kids) quit whining and thank the school
for picking up the slack on a job the parents should have done
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the students had to say: Kevin Seiter, fearing
pessimism is taking over the world, chastises me for not mentioning
good students' parents and the great job they've done. ``I myself
am an A student with a clean record,'' he writes, ``and it's all
because of my parents. I thank GOD every day that I have two
wonderful, caring parents to be there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Alesha Caracecilia Chinn wonders if I'm not being too critical.
She reminds me that kids will be kids and even though their parents
might watch their children very closely they still might ``learn
things they shouldn't at school or from peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Harmon says things have changed since I was in school
in the '40s and '50s and asks me to `` ... just try to put yourself
in the shoes of a teen in today's world. Everyone is already
judging you and trying to find something to accuse you of. We don't
need it from the school too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Hale agrees about the importance of parents caring but
suggests that
</P>
<P>
   schools keep their noses out of their students' business.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Scott believes that the way students act in school
depends on their home life. ``I strongly believe discipline must
come from home before kids begin
</P>
<P>
   to have self-discipline.'' She also raises the possibility that
parents don't want to admit that their child's behavior is based on
how the child was raised. ``I know that my parents' strict behavior
will one day benefit me,'' she writes, ``and I hope others realize
that too.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela (AJ) Klette says I am WRONG! WRONG! and WRONG! and that
every day of
</P>
<P>
   her life her mom has ``installed (sic) a deep sense of values'
into her head and heart. ``It hurts me,'' she adds, ``to think that
most people think the way you've
</P>
<P>
   written.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Wells says her parents have strict rules. ``If I broke a
rule at school, I would be punished at school and at home. You do
the crime, you do the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Lynn Childers agrees that parents should take
responsibility for their children. ``If as high school students
they are breaking into clubs, I would hate to see what they are
doing as adults in the real world. For what the parents don't take
care of now, they are going to be extremely sorry on down the road.
If I were to do what these kids have done, I would be feeling the
generations of discipline in both parents' history behind that
whack!''
</P>
<P>
   Hoepe Bowen does not believe that students should be disciplined
by schools for things they do out of school. ``Most kids do get
discipline from their parents but teenagers do not always listen.
It is not the parents' fault when kids screw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua McKenzie agrees. Schools, he writes are there to teach,
not to punish.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Penrod suggests schools should butt out and wants to know
where I got the ``guts to go out on a limb and write a piece like
that.'' He's asked me to explain where I got the courage. That's an
easy one, Kyle. The courage came from 64 years of living, 31 years
of being a parent, and 10 years of being a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Terena Ziegler took a tough position. ``The parents need to
realize that maybe if they lived up to their responsibilities ...
then the school wouldn't have been
</P>
<P>
   involved. I'm a teenager myself and when I get into trouble my
parents punish
</P>
<P>
   me. I learn my lesson and know better than to do it again. I
know how the life
</P>
<P>
   of a teenager is and I can definitely say that being bad is not
the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Those parents are to blame along with their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Terena poses a few questions of her own: ``How do you discipline
your
</P>
<P>
   students? Do you ever have to pick up the slack for parents? How
would you
</P>
<P>
   like to see the discipline code among schools in the United
States?''
</P>
<P>
   I'll answer the questions in order, Terena:
</P>
<P>
   1. Fairly but consistently. 2. Every day. 3. Unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   And a big THANK YOU to the juniors at Campbell County High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg 43431 or eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
