<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Not much of a change in weather, airlines, or makeup
of Congress
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ When someone asked what I got for Christmas, I
ticked off a list of things that came in boxes and sat under the
tree. However, other ``gifts'' which I received may be more
noteworthy and certainly shared by many others: weather and airline
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Texans adapt to most kinds of weather well. We have no choice.
At most, weather has caused me temporary inconvenience, some worry
and maybe a several hour stretch without water or power.
</P>
<P>
   So a late-night wait for a flight three days before Christmas
wondering if my firstborn made it out of a frozen New Orleans
airport was a frightening and frustrating experience. After an
airline delay caused her to miss her original connection, the same
idiots, uh, airline did not show her on a later flight to
Shreveport, La., the last to get out that night after many delays
caused by icy weather. Neither did she answer a 20-minute page at
the New Orleans terminal.
</P>
<P>
   All her father, brother and I could do was sit, wait, pray and
stare into the darkness to see if she got off that last flight. She
did.
</P>
<P>
   Putting her back on a plane brought me another sort of Christmas
package, a rather disheveled one. In our third year of transporting
her back and forth from college in Massachusetts, we apparently
have gotten a little slack.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at the terminal, we discovered she did not have
her overcoat. Not good when she would be greeted by wind chills of
10 degrees below zero. A quick call to her sister resulted in the
coat and a pair of tennis shoes she didn't remember she had
forgotten being quickly transported to the airport. Meanwhile, the
very courteous clerk informed us LeighAna's bag was six pounds over
the weight limit. That means it weighed 76 pounds. Yes, it's a big
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Ever had to unpack in the middle of an airport?
</P>
<P>
   After unloading a Scrabble game, a couple of sweatshirts, a
bottle of cocoa mix, some sheets and the world's largest crossword
puzzle, the bag was five pounds under the limit. She asked for the
bag back and put the Scrabble game back in. ``Oops, 73 pounds,''
said the clerk, laughing when he saw our stricken faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   I waved goodbye to her, clutching her discarded articles and
hoping like heck her sister picks a college within easy driving
distance.
</P>
<P>
   On another topic: As I watched the ceremonial beginnings of
President Clinton's impeachment trial, the march of the 13
congressman-managers from the House to the Senate chambers, I was
struck by how little has changed in the 200-plus years since those
bodies were established.
</P>
<P>
   Our government is still run by folks who look a lot alike:
graying, balding, white men.
</P>
<P>
   It is still a strong government and it will survive this ordeal
and future
</P>
<P>
   ones as well.
</P>
<P>
   But when will it truly represent all the people?
</P>
<P>
   Only when we the people decide it will.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O.
</P>
<P>
   Box 1792, Longview TX 75606. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
