<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     01-11 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Internet without a net
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Internet is: (a) the ultimate encylopedia; (b)
Pandora's box via modem.
</P>
<P>
   People across the country, and in Waco this week, are arguing
whether the answer is (a) or (b).
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is: (c) all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   And the question of the moment is what to do when you have this
wondrous, mischievous resource in a public library.
</P>
<P>
   What you do, a federal court in Virginia has ruled, is that you
let the people open the encyclopedia/box, without choosing for them
what they can or cannot view.
</P>
<P>
   If you avail the Internet at a public library, ruled a judge in
a case involving the Loudoun County public library, installing
pornography-blocking software without patrons' consent violates the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court likely will rule on this in due time. But
people who want libraries to porn-block the Internet in these
public venues should know that the court already has sided against
government's prior restraint of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Congress tried prior restraint with the Communications Decency
Act of 1996. A unanimous Supreme Court then ruled that government
had to meet the highest standard of public necessity, the ``strict
scrutiny'' standard, to block anything from the Internet.
Underlying the court decision were the vague criteria the
Communications Decency Act could use to block material from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden words
</P>
<P>
   In the Virginia case, plaintiffs pointed out that
library-installed software blocked some Web sites that had nothing
patently offensive or vulgar, such as the Zero Population Growth
Web site and one offered by the Quakers. The blocking is based on
seeking out key words, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Judge Leonie Brinkema ruled that a public library can
choose to offer Internet services, but cannot choose to offer that
service and then excise parts of it, comparable to tearing pages
out an encyclopedia it offers.
</P>
<P>
   The case set up ironic adversaries. The defendants in the case
were the library and its board. Among those who supported the
plaintiffs' case against the library was the American Library
Association.
</P>
<P>
   One might point out that it's not censorship for libraries to
use discretion as to what material they carry, since they do and
always will.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Matthews with the American Library Association said the
discretion amounts to one choice alone: whether to offer the
Internet or not. If you offer it, you offer all of it.
</P>
<P>
   In response to an appeal that she install blocking software,
Waco-McLennan County chief librarian Pamela Bonnell said she won't.
Indeed, she even plans to have an Internet-access terminal in the
children's section when additional terminals are available. She
said the only provision the library might take in the children's
section is to have it in plain sight of a supervisor. Currently,
the library's sole Internet-access terminal has a screen to prevent
eavesdroppers or inadvertent eye-fulls.
</P>
<P>
   Loudoun County's new policy is to make blocking software, still
loaded but in an ``off'' mode, an option to click ``on'' for those
signing up to use the Internet. Children must have the signature of
a parent or guardian, who can choose to have the blocking software
activated.
</P>
<P>
   The American Library Association's Matthews said only about 15
percent of public libraries install blocking software. Based on the
federal court ruling, adults who demand to unblock the 'Net would
be within their rights.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain librarians' virtual solidarity in defiance of
blocking materials?
</P>
<P>
   Their profession is one of which the ``core values'' are
``protecting and advancing intellectual freedom supported by the
First Amendment,'' said Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that First Amendment. It's a Pandora's box, modem not
included.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
