<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Novice PC buyers should stick to familiar names
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My grandfather had some ironclad rules for buying a
car. It needed a high clearance so that _ when he crossed at the
fording spot on the Caddo River near Arkadelphia _ it wouldn't
scrape on the rocks. The spark advance control needed to be
accessible from the outside so that, when he cranked the engine
himself, he could adjust the spark.
</P>
<P>
   They were excellent rules and served him well. But I doubt
they'll help you much when you buy your next family car. It's much
the same with advice on buying PCs. I write about it often, and
that's because the advice has to change with the times. So let's
spend today assembling a list of what you should look for if that
hoped-for PC didn't arrive as a holiday gift and now you're in the
mood to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an up-to-date list for what to look for when buying a PC.
This advice is aimed at the novice, by the way. My suggestions on
where to buy and what to buy would be different for an advanced
user. I'm figuring advanced PC users don't need this help and could
probably give me advice.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you're going to notice when you go shopping is
prices vary wildly nowadays. You can still pay $2,000 and more for
top-of-the-line, name-brand computers and $400 or less for a PC
from one of the many storefront operations you'll find. The
frustrating fact is some of these storefront PC shops do an
excellent job, putting together a PC with quality components. Some
are as good as the high-priced models. But if you don't know a
motherboard from a surfboard, it's next to impossible to weed out
the bad.
</P>
<P>
   So, until you learn more about computers, search one out with a
brand name you've heard of and buy the PC from a store that has
been around for two or three years. Since some small shops come and
go more frequently than the postman, you'll want to buy from a
place that has a track record. That way, odds are the store will
still be in business if you have problems later on.
</P>
<P>
   Think of buying a PC in the same way my one rich friend selects
a wine in a restaurant. He avoids the highest-priced bottles
because they're often put on the list just for flash, to make an
impression. He also stays away from the cheapest wines because,
often, their total virtue is the fact they are cheap. So think
twice before buying that $325 PC, complete with monitor. Use the
same shopping skills that would come into play if you found a
Toyota that sold for $800. You need to at least wonder why it's
selling for so little money.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you'll notice is Intel isn't the only brand
anymore when it comes to processor chips. The processor is the chip
that does the actual computing work. In the old days, Intel was the
only sensible choice. But now _ based on which reviews you read _
some of the competing chips test out impressively. Power users
eventually develop their own prejudices as to which chip to buy.
But, in your case, I recommend you stick with the Intel chip. It's
still the target for the other chips, which attempt to emulate its
inner workings. Later, you may change your mind, but I promise you
won't feel foolish for buying Intel right now.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, make sure you get enough RAM memory when you buy your
computer. Since you're new at this, you'll feel uncomfortable _ in
the first few months _ even with the simple job of installing RAM.
And if you discover you didn't buy enough, you may end up paying
someone to install it for you. Get at least 64 megabytes of RAM
and, if you can afford it, double that amount. That's another thing
that has changed over the past couple of years. Windows now does a
much better job of turning added memory into faster performance. So
that added RAM can help supercharge your machine.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, since this topic deserves more discussion, we'll talk
about some some specific questions to ask at the computer store.
Some of these questions are very low tech and could end up saving
you a lot of grief and money.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
