<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe sites a tool for every cook
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Food and computers have always made a strange mix. The
earliest programmers and Net wizards seemed to live on Coca-Cola
and cold pizza. But your computer and the Internet can help you
with meals a touch more elaborate than that.
</P>
<P>
   Today we'll look at some Web sites that do the expected (provide
terrific recipes) and the unexpected (offer little touches that
make good use of the unique advantages offered by a computer and an
Internet connection).
</P>
<P>
   Our first food site will furnish good examples of what we mean
on both counts. Let's go to Epicurious: Food, Drink, Cooking and
Recipes at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .epicurious.com/ahome
</P>
<P>
   /a00home/home.html to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   This is a lavish and well-designed site. It offers a treasure
trove of recipes. Click on the recipe link at the bottom of the
page and you'll be able to ferret out even the most obscure recipe
using keywords. But there are times when you don't know what you'd
like to prepare for dessert, or, if you do know, you can't remember
the name of the dish.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the second method of searching the recipe file will
come in handy. It's divided into what seems to be nearly 100 topic
areas such as appetizers, breads, salads and so on. You can select
one of the topic areas and browse through the recipe file.
</P>
<P>
   That's the example of the expected. Any food site worth its salt
(and red pepper) offers recipes. And that's probably the most
helpful feature. But let's also use this site to see how the best
pages take an extra step toward making cooking easier and more fun.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like some beginning cooks, you may have heard someone
praise a specific ingredient or cooking utensil but need more
information. That's what you'll get at the Epicurious site, an
online dictionary that uses the computer's ability to search and
organize and the Web's knack for transmitting databases full of
information. If you want to know more about balsamic vinegar, for
instance, or even how to pronounce it, just click on the ``b'' in
the dictionary and you'll soon know the pronunciation. If you want
to know more, just use the hot link in the pronunciation guide to
visit an area where you'll learn more about vinegar than you ever
expected to know.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know what to look for in a cooking site, you'll
appreciate the virtues of our next stop: The Culinary Connection at
http://www.culinary
</P>
<P>
   .com/index.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   This site does a fine job with the expected recipe file (more
than 13,000 of them) and has added features that give it a unique
touch. If you're in the mood for live chat about food, you'll find
chat groups here. Or if you want to browse the thousands of Web
sites that feature food, then take a look at the links page. This
isn't the usual collection of names and links. Instead, the links
are rated by other users, so you'll be able to browse sites that
others have found useful.
</P>
<P>
   Those are two terrific general purpose sites. And, with the
collection of links on the second site, you have a way to find even
more. With all that done, let's take a look at a more exotic site
based at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   It's called The Global Gastronomer _ Cuisines of the World at
http://www.cs.yale.edu/homes
</P>
<P>
   /hupfer/global/gastronomer
</P>
<P>
   .html. If you have a special dinner party coming up and want to
prepare something out of the ordinary, you'll get some help in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the page is made up of links that take you to sites
dedicated to cuisine in specific countries. If the notion of
preparing that sort of a menu tickles your interest in a particular
part of the world, you can click on the country on an interactive
map and be taken to databases of information that cover more than
food.
</P>
<P>
   So when you serve the dish, you can also serve up some
information about its country of origin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
