<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-EMAIL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-mail gone wrong: Think before you send your electronic note
 &HT;    By Paige Braddock
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ E-mail has become a mainstay of both business and
personal communication.
</P>
<P>
   People think of it as something that appears and disappears in
an on-screen mailbox at the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   But e-mail leaves a trail that is very traceable, printable and
anything but private. Real-life e-mail disasters can happen to
anyone who doesn't pay close attention to the possible technical
and emotional glitches only e-mail can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example of how easily an e-mail exchange can go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy sent an e-mail to her friend Jennifer detailing plans to
break up with her boyfriend, Jeff, and why. She was sure she wanted
the breakup but had decided to get through the holidays and do the
deed after New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy and Jennifer sent several responses via that original
e-mail, eventually moving on to other, less-personal topics, one of
which was a bike race. As the plans to participate in the bike race
shaped up, Cindy sent a copy of the exchange to Jeff, so he would
know what the plans were for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff got the e-mail just as he was rushing off to a meeting, so
he printed the whole message out to read later. All previous
discussion between Cindy and Jennifer about the impending breakup
printed, along with the recent details of the bike race.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy got to spend the holidays alone.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Cindy accomplished her goal to break up with Jeff,
just not in the way she had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good situation to work from as an example of what not
to do when corresponding via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   One rule of thumb that will help keep you out of trouble is
never simply hit ``reply.'' Start a new message each time, so only
the most recent portion of the conversation will remain attached to
the original message, especially if you plan to forward a private
exchange to a public audience.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before you hit ``send,'' ask yourself how you'd feel if
this message were printed or forwarded to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you are sending a message to someone you trust, the
technological nature of e-mail is that once it's out there, it's
out there,'' said Abbie Lundberg, editor in chief of CIO Magazine,
a publication for business and information technology executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also good to ask yourself if e-mail is the best medium
for this message,'' said Lundberg.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lundberg, people who are new to e-mail sometimes
don't see the consequences that communicating electronically can
have on the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail does not convey emotion well,'' said Lundberg.
</P>
<P>
   A message not intended to convey anger, for example, may trigger
an emotional response that was not intended.
</P>
<P>
   Since you aren't present when the message is received, you have
no control over how it will be interpreted, added Lundberg.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how careful you are, there is no guarantee a good
e-mail won't go bad. An e-mail addressed incorrectly will bounce
back to you, but at the same time, a carbon copy of that e-mail is
sent to the mail administrator of your service provider.
</P>
<P>
   All incoming mail, misaddressed or otherwise, sits in a folder
waiting to be retrieved by the appropriate user.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and the person getting the e-mail are only two of about
four or five other individuals who could see that e-mail,'' said
Jason Schafer, a Web developer and Internet consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Before venturing on his own, Schafer was a Web server
administrator for an Internet service provider on the East Coast.
He got to see the good and bad of e-mail delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to read people's mail, but as the administrator,
misdirected mail bounced to me, and sometimes you can't help but
notice certain words. Like if a message has your name in it, for
example,'' said Schafer. ``Or if someone is sending threatening
e-mails to someone on your server.''
</P>
<P>
   Another word of caution is that if you send personal messages
through your company's e-mail system, you might consider getting a
free Internet account.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schafer, most companies have a policy that any
e-mail passing through their system is company property.
</P>
<P>
   The nuances of digital communication not only complicate the way
we communicate, e-mail has increased the pace with which we
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Pace is always increased by technological advances in
communication, and the ability to send e-mail from home and remote
locations has increased the speed of decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that when people were out of town, especially in
a business situation, certain decisions would wait until they got
back to the office,'' said Lundgren, whose online magazine features
resources to help users deal with the challenges of communication
via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quick decision-making is both positive and negative. It can be
negative, because we lose the time for a second thought. We lose
the opportunity to reconsider,'' said Lundgren.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to e-mail, it's always safer to think before you
``send.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the only way to be absolutely sure your
sweet nothings, friendly ramblings or business decisions remain
private is by sending them the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   Mail them at the post office.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE STORIES
</P>
<P>
   E-mail can bridge distances, emotional and geographical, to keep
people together. It can also be a powerful tool for tearing them
apart. Take these real-life scenarios, for example, in which the
names have been changed to protect the innocent (and the guilty).
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Margaret had been married for 10 years. Before they tied
the knot, Bob worked with the Peace Corps for two years in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bob spent Christmas in Romania. Before he left, he
sent a love letter, via e-mail, to a woman he'd seen while working
in the Peace Corps. Unbeknownst to Bob, the e-mail bounced back to
his home address after his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret logged on to check e-mail and found the love letter,
written by Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret called her attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Sam is a graduate student at a university in Georgia. He sent an
e-mail, of a playful romantic nature, to Kate in Illinois ... or so
he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Using a campus computer, and in a rush to get to class, Sam
accidentally selected his adviser's e-mail address, located just
above Kate's in his address book. Sam nearly got kicked out of
school for sexual harassment before the mishap got straightened
out.
</P>
<P>
   Jim, a postmaster of an e-mail server, receives all messages
that are misaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   Chris sent erotic notes to Susan, addressed to her at both work
and cc'd to her home address, which was typed incorrectly. Jim
thought that after the first couple of auto-replies from his server
about misdirected mail Chris would get the hint and check the
errant address.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of cyber love letters, Jim sent a note to them
both asking them to verify their addresses, ``so that their sweet
nothings could remain between the two of them.'' Chris and Susan
both wrote e-mails back to Jim blasting him for ``hacking'' into
their e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Jim had tried to do them the courtesy of pointing out their
error. But after receiving the angry e-mails, Jim printed out all
their correspondence and faxed it to the network guru of their
companies.
</P>
<P>
   George hated his boss.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, the tension between them had gotten so bad
that George found himself using e-mail to vent to friends about
work.
</P>
<P>
   One day after losing an argument with his boss, George sat down
to e-mail his buddy Frank. He dashed off an angry message, calling
his boss every name in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, because his boss was in the forefront of his
mind, he sent the message to his boss, instead of Frank.
</P>
<P>
   George now has a new boss.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Paige Braddock
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
