<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Civilization' moves to the next level
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Microprose has released its latest version of
``Civilization,'' one of the most popular games on CD. This
version, ``Civilization II,'' lets you play against up to seven
other people on the Internet or through a modem. The new edition
includes several add-on scenarios, such as the American Revolution
and Mars colonization. You can also build your own scenario with
this edition. Available only for Windows PCs, ``Civilization II''
retails for about $30.
</P>
<P>
   If the cold has put your tennis game on ice, check out ``Extreme
Tennis,'' a computer CD from Head Games Publishing. It's a 3-D
simulation of tennis for Windows PCs. You can play against the
computer or others through a modem or the Internet. There are five
different match options, including singles, doubles and tournament.
The game lets you watch play from multiple angles. There's also
instant replay. ``Extreme Tennis'' retails for about $25.
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   OK, now you've got that Nintendo 64 you wanted for the holidays.
But how do you decide which game to buy for it? You'll find some
clues in the January issue of Nintendo Power, a magazine devoted to
Nintendo 64, Gameboy and the games played on them. The January
issue includes tips on ``Or Die Trying'' and ``Link's Awakening
DX.'' You'll find reviews of new games such as ``South Park,''
``Castlevania,'' ``BattleTanx'' and ``NBA Jam '99.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those into PC games, check out the January issue of
PCAccelerator. It offers tips on ``Starcraft, Half-Life'' and
``Shogo.'' The issue also has reviews of ``Grim Fandango,'' ``Grand
Prix Legends,'' ``Trespasser'' and ``Global Domination,'' among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   If you've always liked oriental rugs, you'll want to check out
the Metropolitan Museum of Art's virtual exhibit of them online.
You'll not only find sharp pictures of rugs but a history of the
art form. You'll find this site at http://www.metmuseum.org
</P>
<P>
   /htmlfile/education/flowers
</P>
<P>
   /htm/indfs.htm.
</P>
