<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cold weather batters battery's health
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One victim of cold weather car killers is the battery.
</P>
<P>
   Has this ever happened to you? You go out to start your car in
the morning, after a subfreezing night, and hear either a sluggish
``grrrrr,'' a ``click click'' or nothing at all. What in the world
happened? Yesterday morning (a warmer day), the car started fine.
Now, without warning, the engine won't even attempt to turn over.
</P>
<P>
   Car batteries don't like cold weather. Batteries want to live in
temperatures around 80 degrees (don't we all?). At 80 degrees, a
fully charged battery will deliver 100 percent of its energy to
whatever electrical devices the car uses, including the starter. As
the temperature drops, so does the efficiency of the battery. In
fact, at 32 degrees, the battery is only about 80 percent
efficient. At zero degrees, available energy nose dives to around
50 percent. While even a partially charged battery may have enough
energy to start a car at 80 degrees, that same battery will fall
flat on its face when the temperature drops below freezing.
</P>
<P>
   The same cold conditions that cause the battery to become weaker
increase the engine's initial need for more electrical power. After
sitting overnight, the engine oil has a tendency to thicken. This
makes the engine harder for the starter to ``turn over.'' The
starter will try its hardest to accomplish the task, which means
using more electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have a vicious circle.
</P>
<P>
   The starter demands more electricity from a battery incapable of
delivering it. Consequently, ``click click.'' When you stop and
think about it, many of us drive around with partially charged
batteries, especially during the winter. If we drive short
distances with the accessories on (lights, wipers, defroster,
radio, etc.), we never give the battery a chance to fully recharge.
It actually takes about 20 minutes of continuous driving at around
2000 engine rpms to feed back to the battery the electricity used
for cranking.
</P>
<P>
   Because much of our commute time is spent idling at low engine
rpm, complete recharge is often never achieved. Of course, short
trips consisting of repeatedly starting the engine, driving a few
miles and shutting it off several times dig the fastest grave for
our little 12-volt friend.
</P>
<P>
   Short of overhauling your lifestyle, what can you do about it?
Make sure your battery is clean and the battery cables are clean
and tight (no green stuff growing on them). This ensures a clear
path for the electricity's travel. Take a long trip occasionally,
or at least make sure the engine is allowed to run continuously
about once a week for 20 minutes or so. (If you do this in the
driveway, don't turn on any accessories.)
</P>
<P>
   You might want to invest in a small, inexpensive battery charger
(2 to 5 amps). Hook it up to the battery overnight about once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   On nights it is going to be really cold, put your car to bed
with an old blanket thrown over the hood. Do this shortly after
you've shut the engine off. This will help keep some of the engine
heat under the hood and some of the cold out, which may help the
starting process in the morning. Most importantly, have your
battery checked and serviced as part of your annual winter
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems and marginal batteries can be caught and
attended to before they leave you stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/ L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
