<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A12-COX     01-11 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to find out what is legal in how a 401(k) plan is
administered. My employer has a 401(k) plan and started taking
money out of my paycheck on Sept. 25. Well, now it's three months
later _ a total of more than $1,400, not including any gains or
interest accrual, has been taken _ and the funds are still not in
the account. I have contacted Human Resources about this
repeatedly. My account is still inactive. Is it legal for this
company to be messing around with my 401(k) funds? I find its
lackadaisical attitude highly irresponsible and disturbing. What
sort of recourse do I have? Personnel and Payroll have so far been
no help whatsoever. I am beginning to worry that something is
rotten in the state of Denmark! _B.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know where the money is, but the U.S. Department of
Labor will help locate it! The Labor Department's Pension and
Welfare Benefits Administration field office in Dallas looks into
this sort of thing. As of Feb. 3, 1997, an employer is allowed a
maximum of 15 business days after the month in which money is taken
out of your wages for your 401(k) to deposit it. The department
computes the amount owed starting at the earliest date the money
could begin working for you. You stand to gain the 401(k)
contributions as well as what the plan would have earned on late
contributions or the prime interest rate plus 2 percent _ whichever
is higher. The employer may also be subject to the 502(l) penalty,
which goes to the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for four-tine fork lapel pins. _J.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: None ready made. Have these trinkets custom made by Flojac at
(800) 430-8368. Q: I have been wanting to ask you if you know of a
company that sells fireworks by mail. I happened to order some
before but that was many years ago. See what you can do. If not,
thanks anyway. _Jose B.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Fireworks have no place in the mail,'' says Postmaster
Dennis Walsh. ``It is clearly a safety issue.'' All fireworks are
Class 1 explosives and, as such, are prohibited from mailing. You
cannot even mail matches. Fina Morales, U.S. Postal Service
spokeswoman, says hazardous materials (flammable, corrosive,
reactive or toxic) cannot be mailed either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been looking for punch tin that is in reproduction.
You see it in restaurants on ceilings. Someone told me there is a
place in Houston. Can you help me find the number where I can
purchase this? _Jan C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact the Chelsea Decorative Metal Co. for a free catalog.
Rumor has it these sheets are easy to install. The company sells
2-by-4-foot sheets of several styles of this pressed tin used on
ceilings and walls _ Victorian to art deco. The number: (713)
721-9200.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find a ``Phases of the Moon'' calendar for
1999. I heard that planetariums offered them for free. Is that
true? Where would the closest planetarium be? _L.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: The posters, alas, are not free but are well-priced ($11 to
$15 plus shipping) from the McDonald Observatory, P.O. Box 1337,
Fort Davis, TX 79734. Interested in the full moons coming up?
January and March each boast two (as in once in a blue moon);
February is skipped altogether. By the way, it is atmospheric
conditions that make the moon appear blue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My granddaughter is visiting and had head lice. We purchased
an over-the-counter product and treated her head; however, I can
still see what appears to be eggs stuck to some of her hair
follicles. I read somewhere recently that if you coat the hair with
olive oil overnight, the eggs suffocate and can be removed easily.
Fact or fiction? I'm really in a quandary as I do not want to send
her home with lice and definitely don't want lice myself.
Suggestions? _C.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yikes! Children are the main carriers of head lice, passing
the critters along when sharing combs, coat racks and hats. Some
chemical treatments have not been effective in recent years.
Bedding and clothes should be washed in hot water and dried at high
heat as part of the treatment. The National Pediculosis Association
does not endorse treatments like olive oil, mayo or Vaseline to
smother the critters. The removal of the treatment is often
difficult and risky. Getting the lice out may be successful, but
then getting the Vaseline or olive oil out may pose other problems.
Call your doctor for a recommendation. The association does state
``mechanical removal is the common denominator for success.'' So
buy a nit comb to remove eggs _ a tedious process. (The association
happens to sell one, aptly called the LiceMeister.) For more
information, contact the association at (781) 449-6487.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am 9 years old and would like to know why we say ``Merry''
Christmas instead of ``Happy'' Christmas like we do for all the
other holidays (like Happy New Year, Happy Thanksgiving, Happy
Birthday, etc.)? Thank you. _Laura Mahany
</P>
<P>
   A: You have stumped me _ and all the other wordsmiths I
consulted. Maybe the ``merry'' was used to avoid repetition in
Happy Christmas and Happy New Year. The Brits sometimes say ``Happy
Christmas,'' and it is to English literature that I turned for
etymology. ``A Christmas Carol'' contains the line, ``They wished
each other Merry Christmas in their can of grog.'' (That grog thing
is a whole other issue.) Victorian times hatched many holiday
traditions _ maybe this phrase is one. Shakespeare penned ``Welcome
Merry Shrovetide'' in ``Henry IV.'' Shrovetide is th three days
preceding Lent. It's the only other place I found the adjective as
part of a salutation. The best part of a job like mine is there are
lots of folks to improve my answers.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Several readers answered my call for why the traditional box
exchanged at a Mexican wedding contains 13 pieces of silver. One
reader suggests the 13 pieces represent Jesus and the 12 disciples;
another, the 13 original colonies. All agree the exchange of these
coins represents a financial commitment between the bride and groom
to the new family.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many readers ask about the process for requesting greetings
from the White House. In addition to the address (White House
Greetings Office, Room 39, Washington, D.C. 20502), you may send a
request electronically: president(at)whitehouse.gov. Give the
office six weeks' advance notice for greetings regarding those
celebrating birthdays of 80 years or more, anniversaries of 50
years or more, weddings and births. Include the name and address of
honoree(s), exact date of the occasion, and age or number of years
of marriage. This is the work of volunteers, so be patient and
appreciative!
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Park System _ which covers more than 83 million
acres in every state (except Delaware), the District of Columbia,
American Samoa, Guam, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands _ is a
popular and economical summer destination. In general, reservations
for June are taken in January; for July, in February; and for
August, in March. Clip these numbers for easy reference: Campground
reservations in Yosemite National Park: (800) 436-PARK. Campground
reservations in other parks including Grand Canyon National Park,
Zion National Park and Great Smoky Mountains National Park: (800)
365-CAMP (2267). Tour reservations for Carlsbad Caverns National
Park, Mammoth Cave National Park or Frederick Douglass National
Historic Site: (800) 967-CAVE (2283).
</P>
<P>
   _ Put away those reading glasses next time you have to figure
the tip on that restaurant bill. Mr. Cool, Jack Nicholson, has
saved us all with a suggestion to Chase Visa: the LensCard. This
credit card comes with a built-in magnifying glass, allowing
patrons to read the bill sans glasses, at 3.5 times the print size.
Now if someone will only put a flashlight on the tray with the
bill. Get the Chase exclusive by calling (800) 203-1851 or, for
those looking to trade in old cards, (800) 323-6296.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
