<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORD-BLOOD-BANKS12-CO     01-11 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORD-BLOOD-BANKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Atlanta poised to be key player in cord blood
technology
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS; PLACENTA
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Frozen in Cincinnati is a Kentucky grandfather's gift
for his grandchildren, Ian and Clare Henderson of Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes they never open it.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is umbilical cord blood, collected on the day each
child was born as a type of biological insurance should the
siblings or other family members need it for a bone marrow
transplant to cure leukemia or other life-threatening illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason not to do it,'' Stephanie Henderson, 32,
said of her decision to have her physician collect the specimen
from both babies, born two years apart at Piedmont Hospital,
``especially since my father-in-law offered to pay for it. Who
wants to be kicking themselves down the road in 10 years when it
could potentially help someone in our family or perhaps save one of
our children's lives?''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more and more parents are plunking down $1,200 to
$1,500 for private cord blood collection, followed by an annual
storage fee of $100. As evidence of the disease-curing potential of
cord blood grows, some families do it because there's a family
history of cancer. Others, because they are concerned their baby's
ethnicity narrows the possibility of a bone marrow match.
</P>
<P>
   While private cord blood banking is a growing industry with
slick Web sites _ and brochures and videos scattered in doctors'
offices and birthing centers, banking for public use isn't as well
developed. Public blood banks are available in only a handful of
states _ not yet in Georgia _ mostly because cord blood
transplantation is still considered experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barbara Marston found that out recently when she was
pregnant with her first child. Marston's family medical history did
not warrant paying for private cord blood collection, but she
wanted to collect the blood and give it to a national registry that
matches donations to potential bone marrow transplant patients. No
hospital in the Atlanta area does that, though Northside Hospital
and Emory University are looking into collection programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fantastic resource,'' said Marston, an infectious
disease specialist at Emory University. ``I believe most
well-informed people would be willing to donate cord blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Marston and her husband, Dr. Larry Slutsker, watched
the potential lifesaving blood get tossed when Emma Caroline came
into the world two days before Christmas at Crawford Long Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad about it, but there was nothing I could do,'' said
Marston, who lives in Candler Park. ``Hopefully, we can have
another child, and, hopefully, by that time, the ability to donate
cord blood will have become routine.''
</P>
<P>
   She may get her wish.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta may yet emerge as one of the nation's leading public
cord blood donation sites, a Northside Hospital doctor predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is well-positioned to be one of the dominant cord
blood centers in the country,'' said Dr. Kent Holland, medical
director of Northside's stem cell processing lab. He was referring
to two key ingredients of cord blood collection that are already
here _ booming birthing centers and top-notch medical researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Northside Hospital is looking to partner with one of the
national programs already collecting cord blood and is seeking
grants to get a donor program up by spring, Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Northside is the nation's leading community hospital when it
comes to stork visits _ just over 13,000 babies were born there in
1998. Also, it's a leader in adult bone marrow transplants, with
100 procedures last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a facility already supporting the bone marrow
transplants. So storing cord blood would not be a problem,''
Holland said. ``But when developing a donor cord blood program,
it's very important to properly educate the people you are
approaching and there's all kinds of ethical questions that have to
be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Emory is also considering starting a public cord blood donation
program, estimating it would cost a couple of million dollars in
seed money. Last month, cord blood from an anonymous New York donor
was infused into sickle cell patient Keone Penn, 12, of Centerville
at Egleston Children's Hospital. It is believed to be the world's
first such unrelated cord blood transplant for sickle cell.
</P>
<P>
   White blood cells are just starting to appear in Keone's blood,
the first indication the transplant may be taking hold. Keone's
cord blood came from the Placental Blood Program at the New York
Blood Center, the nation's first and largest public cord blood
program, which is supported by federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   Placenta blood collected by such public programs, and some
participating hospitals, are made available on a national registry.
The nearest facility to Georgia with a public cord blood donation
program is the Carolinas Cord Blood Bank, which collects from
volunteer mothers at Duke University Medical Center and Durham
Regional Hospital in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply not ready to bank everyone's cord blood,'' said
LeeAnn Jensen, immunologist at the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute in Bethesda, Md., the federal center now expanding the
national public cord blood bank. ``It costs about $2,000 to collect
each unit of it. It's very expensive and labor-intensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Other facilities now contributing under a National Institutes of
Health grant to a public cord blood bank are Georgetown University
and the University of California at Los Angeles; six other centers
will be collecting donated cord blood and adding to the national
stockpile under a five-year, $30 million federal grant. Several
other smaller public cord blood collection sites exist at
university hospitals around the country.
</P>
<P>
   While public cord banking grows, some scientists worry about the
competition from private cord blood enterprises, which they claim
play on the worst fears of parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like taking insurance against getting hit by a meteor,''
said Dr. Lewis Hsu, pediatric hematologist at Grady Health System.
``The chances of someone getting leukemia is so so small. ... The
companies are just going to make tons of money off this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Angela Ogden, who oversees many bone marrow transplants at
Egleston Children's Hospital, said she's seen some private cord
blood brochures that exaggerate the potential of cord blood and
overstate the chances of possibly needing it .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they coerce some mothers into banking their children's
blood based on false data,'' Ogden said. ``The chance your child
will use it is about one in a million.''
</P>
<P>
   (There are about 3,100 U.S. cases annually of the most severe
type of childhood leukemia, called ALL for acute lymphocytic
leukemia; the risk is less than 1 in 100,000 your child will
develop it.)
</P>
<P>
   And, even if your child does develop leukemia, it would be
better to give that child someone else's cord blood, a Duke
University expert says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that cord blood may contain the leukemic cells.
Also, when you give them back their own cord blood, you're giving
them back their own immune system, which was not able to fight off
cancer the first time around,'' said Dr. Joanne Kurtzberg, who has
performed the most cord blood transplants in the world, 185, and
has a 50 percent success rate. She's also director of the Carolinas
Cord Blood Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ViaCord Inc., the private cord blood bank that's storing the
Henderson children's blood, says that so far, three families have
used the cord blood from their newborn for a sibling. All three
clients knew when they collected the sample that a brother or
sister needed it; one patient died and the other two are healthy
and featured in ViaCord brochures.
</P>
<P>
   Since cord blood banking is not regulated (the FDA is now
drafting standards for quality and safety), there is no way to know
how many families have opted for this new type of biological
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, ViaCord says its main competitors are CordBlood
Registry and CorCell; the three are considered the nation's largest
private cord blood companies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,000 families that ViaCord has collected from in the
past several years, 25 were from Georgia, said Mary Beth Mohan,
ViaCord marketing communications manager. Atlanta hospitals it's
worked with include Piedmont, Northside and Crawford Long.
</P>
<P>
   ViaCord customers also have the option of donating their blood
to the national registry, but they would still have to pay the
$1,500 down payment and the transportation fee. Local ViaCord
families interviewed for this article, however, said they never
read or heard of that option. Insurance companies are beginning to
pay for cord blood collection if there's proof a sibling needs the
blood for a medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of reasons people chose to collect the cord
blood, '' Mohan said, reading from a survey of ViaCord's customers
nationwide. ``The most common is a family history of cancer and
other diseases. But one mother did it because her baby was from
donated sperm and she didn't know the father's history. Lesbian
couples have chosen to do so. And parents who've gone through
infertility treatment and are pretty sure they are not going to
have another child.''
</P>
<P>
   None of these situations fits the Hendersons, whose son's blood
was collected in September 1996, followed by their daughter's this
past September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no particular reason we did other than precaution,''
said Ian Henderson Jr., father to Ian Henderson III and son to Ian
Henderson Sr., a lawyer in Louisville. ``I had never heard of this
until my father brought it up. He fancies himself as a doctor even
though he's a lawyer. We hope we'll never need to use it, but at
least we know it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen and Eric Schwartz of Northlake also admitted they are not
in a high-risk category for ever needing baby Ariel's cord blood.
But they preserved it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably doesn't statistically make sense for us, but you
never know in a few years from now what they may discover can be
done with it,'' Ellen Schwartz said over the cries of her
6-week-old daughter. ``You buy insurance for things you can't
afford to replace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
