<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7603 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLSTUFF12-COX     01-11 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLSTUFF12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K? Y2K worry? Bring it on
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's such a small problem. A few computer geeks
forgot to put a couple of extra numbers on a date. A tiny glitch.
Now what?
</P>
<P>
   (Say in a dramatic echo) Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Bank accounts will be erased; the stock market will crash. Some
warn that we will be left penniless, groveling for food. People
will starve. Planes will fall out of the air. There will be panic
in the streets. Gunfire. Bloodshed. Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   To all that I say: So what? Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, we're sweating the big stuff. Not seeing the trees for
the forest. It's the small stuff that's going to get us. What I
want to know is if my Walkman will work and if I will be able to
get a beer or play a videogame. Bank accounts? Who cares? Erase
them. More important, will the Y2K bug keep me from getting a scoop
of ice cream or microwaving a burrito?
</P>
<P>
   I set out recently to see what the true impact of Y2K would be,
to look at what life could be like for the common man, namely me.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping in mind that the fall of civilization as we know it will
occur after New Year's Eve, my first priority of the new century
will be to rid myself of my hangover (hair of the dog, it's a
Louisiana thing). For this, I visited Steve Anderson, brewmaster at
Waterloo Brewing Co., and addressed him with my concern. He gruffly
assured me there will be no problem, and if all hell broke loose,
the brewpub could store up to 168 barrels of nature's organic
hangover cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in Y2K,'' said Anderson. ``It's a hoax. Just
another way for the software companies to make money. Besides,
brewing beer hasn't changed much in hundreds of years. My main
instrument isn't a computer; it's a paddle. Believe me, we will
have beer on New Year's Day 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   While enjoying my beer, I'll surely want some live music. In the
coming dark times, we'll all need music to keep the human spirit
alive. The failure of computer-driven synthesizers could decimate
Austin's global reputation as ``Live Music Capital of the World.''
The horror.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Koym, guitarist and band leader of the cover band the Be
Wires, assured me that his band wouldn't be affected by the bug. He
said he has numerous backup synthesizers, but things would really
have to go haywire for them not to be able to play or, worse, have
to play acoustic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lost our keyboard, we couldn't play 50 percent of our
tunes,'' Koym said. ``You know, like we couldn't play our '80s
crowd-pleasers like `Bizarre Love Triangle' by New Order or
`Tainted Love' by Soft Cell. In that case, we would just play a lot
of guitar-based tunes like the Romantics' `What I Like About You'
or 'Matchbox 20'. We'd just cut out the dance material.''
</P>
<P>
   Music is safe, it seems, but how and what will I eat in the New
World Order? Most survivalist and Y2K alarmist groups speak of
storing grain, beans and canned goods. They claim the only way to
eat will be to live off the fat of the land. I question this plan
and fully expect to be gorging myself on queso fries and Dixie Red
Hot sandwiches at Texicalli Grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we'll be open in 2000,'' said the hyper-optimistic Danny
Young, owner of the restaurant. ``And I bet my 1954 station wagon
starts, too. Let me tell you something: I don't have a single
computer, answering machine or a touch-tone phone. As long as the
gas comes on, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if things turn ugly, and Danny is forced to take up
arms against a group of queso-starved survivalists who are sick of
beans and grain? That's when I go to the vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines are a veritable Y2K food and beverage stockpile
unto themselves: Ham and cheese sandwiches, burritos, Cokes and
Milky Way candy bars. Here in the American-Statesman building, we
have a hallway full of them. Recently, I asked a mustached service
associate replenishing a machine with tuna nicoise and french toast
and sausage sandwiches if they were Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck is that? Y2K?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the moment when 1999 becomes 2000, and all the computers
supposedly shut down. It is rumored the world could possibly end,''
I answered.
</P>
<P>
   I called his boss at Accent Food Services to ask my question
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a problem if those vending machines stopped
working,'' said Tom Hawkins, president of Accent.
</P>
<P>
   I concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we've contacted all of our suppliers and have
been told it won't be a problem,'' he said. ``We expect our Y2K
compliance letters from them in 30 to 60 days.''
</P>
<P>
   What a relief. With the food question out of the way, I turned
again toward entertainment. With the world on fire, it might be
safer to stay at home and play Playstation. At Babbage's in
Highland Mall I spoke with sales associate Frank. Frank is short
and robotic in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because your Playstation has no built-in calendar system or
battery backup system, there will be no problem with it,'' he said
in a tone that made me fear for his personal Y2K compliance. ``You
have nothing to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   But what fun would holing up with my Playstation be without a
big tub of Amy's ice cream? I couldn't imagine playing videogames
in a Y2K-worn world without a large serving of Mexican vanilla with
a Reese's Peanut Butter Cup mix-in. While Phil Clay, the self
proclaimed ``No. 1 Ice Cream Guy for Amy's,'' admitted there might
be a small problem with the company's computer network, he said
Amy's expects to be ready for business in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company doesn't hinge on the Y2K problem,'' he said.
``Assuming society doesn't collapse, we will definitely be serving
ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is that aforementioned Walkman thing. If there is
going to be a global collapse, I want it to happen to the tune of
whatever I'm playing. To check that there wouldn't be a problem, I
dialed up the Sony customer service line at(800) 222-SONY.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony Electronics, this is Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Gregory Kallenberg, and I want to make sure my
Walkman is Y2K compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will my Walkman still work after New Year's Eve 1999? After
all the computers shut down and the Earth is in chaos, will I still
be able to listen to my Pearl Jam album?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what you mean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you hold on a moment? Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Three and a half minutes later, Pat returned and read this
prepared statement: ``Sony products will not malfunction by virtue
of the transition of 1999 to 2000. Any such products which keep the
date will accurately do so, and no Sony products will fail because
of the date change. Thank you. Have a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   So while bank accounts might disappear and planes fall out of
the sky, we, the common people, will be fine. We will eat our queso
fries, play our videogames and drink our beers, all to the tune of
whatever is playing on our fully functioning Walkmans.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K. Bring it on. 354 days and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
