<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 10, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STATEOFUNION-REVIEW (Washington) _ In State of the Union
speeches before members of Congress and the Supreme Court,
presidents have made an implicit argument that the three branches
of government may be equal, but some are more equal than others.
This year, as President Clinton assesses the union's state before
an audience that is considering ejecting him from office, he will
be testing that proposition. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CAPITAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Never in the history of
modern business has there been a class of companies that has
spiraled so high, so fast and with so little regard for convention
as the Internet companies whose market values continue to astonish
Wall Street. What is particularly surprising is that most of them
have few if any physical assets. By David Barboza. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-LIDDY-REVIEW (Washington) _ It may be the ultimate slap
at the boys in suits who have long dominated U.S. politics: the
hottest electoral commodities, as of last week at least, are best
known for whom they married and have never run for public office:
Hillary Clinton and Elizabeth Dole. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   PET-PSYCH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Given the money to be made catering
to Americans' twin obsessions with psychological advice and pets,
it's only a matter of time before a flood of books, TV shows, radio
programs and newspaper columns feature pop psychiatrists whose
specialty is putting Rover on the couch or on Prozac. BY Joe
Sharkey. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-DATABASE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Linguists say that digital
libraries like JSTOR will reduce dependence on searching through
libraries to study the history of the language. Already, the word
`hopefully,' long considered a grammatical corruption that
originated in the 1960s, has been found in texts as far back as the
1930s. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANCHORS-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Perhaps to enhance their
legitimacy, America's TV news anchors are increasingly drawn across
the boundary from electronic media to the solid ground of books on
paper. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-REVIEW (Washington) _ Some liberals are beginning to
think that vouchers _ something they have largely shunned for use
in education _ might be a good for Medicare. By Michael Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in `i' category
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MAFIA-REVIEW (Moscow) _ Comparing the Russian and Italian
mafias. In Italy, the word `mafia' signifies discreet criminal
organizations with strict hierarchical structures, but in Russia it
has come to mean much more. In Russia it embraces the noxious blend
of crime, politics and business that has engulfed the nation in the
post-Soviet era. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-PROFESSIONS-REVIEW (Phnom Penh) _ In exterminating
Cambodia's lawyers but doctors, teachers, engineers, accountants,
clerks, businessmen, monks, artists and other professionals in the
1970s, the Khmer Rouge not only destroyed Cambodia's culture,
commerce and civil society. It eliminated the people who might have
been available to rebuild them. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-DEATHSQAUDS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Iran's official admission
that a death squad within the intelligence service killed some of
the regime's critics was made only after the murders had already
unleashed a remarkably open public debate, in which people who
suddenly felt more vulnerable complained of the specter of official
terror. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   KISSINGER-TRANSCRIPTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Documents released from
the archives of former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger include
transcripts of conversations that he and President Richard Nixon
had with Communist leaders like Mao Tse-tung and Leonid Brezhnev,
offering new insights on the thaw in the Cold War of the early and
mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Photo-Graphics editor is Deborah Marchand
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marchand(at)nytimes.com
</P>
