<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 17.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending Jan. 2 at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. A MAN IN FULL, by Tom Wolfe. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
</P>
<P>
   $28.95.) Life in Atlanta on the cusp of the millennium, as
</P>
<P>
   Old South values collide with a new world.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Flamingo, $26.) Five female characters,
</P>
<P>
   a missionary's family, narrate this novel set in
</P>
<P>
   the Belgian Congo during that country's fight for
</P>
<P>
   independence.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE SIMPLE TRUTH, by David Baldacci. (Warner, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   The appeal by a man serving a life sentence for murder
</P>
<P>
   creates chaos in Washington's legal community.
</P>
<P>
   4. WHEN THE WIND BLOWS, by James Patterson. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $25.) A young girl helps a widow and an FBI
</P>
<P>
   agent uncover a deadly plot.
</P>
<P>
   5. (x) SEIZE THE NIGHT, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A man who can live only at night tracks children who
</P>
<P>
   have mysteriously disappeared in a California town.
</P>
<P>
   6. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Knopf, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   7. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A Scottish
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   8. (x) BILLY STRAIGHT, by Jonathan Kellerman. (Random,
</P>
<P>
   House, $25.95.) A 12-year-old boy, trying to survive
</P>
<P>
   on Los Angeles' mean streets, witnesses a brutal murder.
</P>
<P>
   9. BAG OF BONES, by Stephen King. (Scribner, $28.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of terrifying events besets a best-selling novelist
</P>
<P>
   four years after his wife's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   10. (X) CHARMING BILLY, by Alice McDermott. (Farrar,
</P>
<P>
   Straus &AMP; Giroux, $22.) At a party to celebrate
</P>
<P>
   a man's memory, many secrets of the past come to life.
</P>
<P>
   11. RAINBOW SIX, by Tom Clancy. (Putnam, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   John Clark, heading an international task force,
</P>
<P>
   investigates terrorist incidents in Switzerland,
</P>
<P>
   Germany and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   12. ANGELS FLIGHT, by Michael Connelly. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $25.) Harry Bosch, a detective with the
</P>
<P>
   LAPD, investigates the murder of a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   13. MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE, by Nicholas Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $20.) After finding a seaborne bottle
</P>
<P>
   containing an enigmatic love letter, a divorced
</P>
<P>
   woman encounters love.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE LOCKET, by Richard Paul Evans. (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
</P>
<P>
   $15.95.) A young man learns much about life, love and compassion
</P>
<P>
   while working in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE VAMPIRE ARMAND, by Anne Rice. (Knopf, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The progress of an eternally young man from ancient
</P>
<P>
   Constantinople to contemporary New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1.THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   2. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death's door.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $22.) How a murderer helped compile the
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   5. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (Public Affairs, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   American submarine espionage from the early Cold War
</P>
<P>
   years to the present.
</P>
<P>
   6. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking
</P>
<P>
   the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 3, by Neale Donald
</P>
<P>
   Walsch. (Hampton Roads, $22.95.) More discussions of
</P>
<P>
   moral questions.
</P>
<P>
   8. CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 1, by Neale Donald
</P>
<P>
   Walsch. (Putnam, $19.95.) The author addresses questions
</P>
<P>
   of good and evil, guilt and sin.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE AMERICAN CENTURY, by Harold Evans with Gail
</P>
<P>
   Buckland and Kevin Baker. (Knopf, $50.) A copiously
</P>
<P>
   illustrated political history of the 20th century that
</P>
<P>
   emphasizes America's role.
</P>
<P>
   10. WE INTERRUPT THIS BROADCAST, by Joe Garner. (Sourcebooks,
</P>
<P>
   $45.) How radio and television reported historic events
</P>
<P>
   over the past 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE DEATH OF OUTRAGE, by William J. Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   (Free Press, $20.) The former secretary of education
</P>
<P>
   takes a critical view of the Clinton presidency. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12. LINDBERGH, by A. Scott Berg. (Putnam, $30.)
</P>
<P>
   The checkered life of Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   13. (x) SHAKESPEARE: THE INVENTION OF THE HUMAN, by
</P>
<P>
   Harold Bloom. (Riverhead, $35.) The literary
</P>
<P>
   scholar argues that Shakespearean characters
</P>
<P>
   like Hamlet and Falstaff helped create new
</P>
<P>
   kinds of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   14. (x) THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlessinger
</P>
<P>
   and Stewart Vogel. (Cliff Street/HarperCollins, $24.)
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the Ten Commandments today.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE ENDURANCE, by Caroline Alexander. (Knopf, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Shackleton's 1914 Antarctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. SIMPLE ABUNDANCE, by Sarah Ban Breathnach.
</P>
<P>
   (Warner, $21.) Advice for women seeking to improve
</P>
<P>
   the way they look at themselves. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. ONE DAY MY SOUL JUST OPENED UP, by Iyanla Vanzant.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $13.) How to raise one's morale and
</P>
<P>
   realize one's ambitions. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE 9 STEPS TO FINANCIAL FREEDOM, by Suze Orman.
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $23.) Practical and spiritual steps for
</P>
<P>
   managing your money. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. SOMETHING MORE, by Sarah Ban Breathnach.
</P>
<P>
   (Warner, $20.) Advice for women about finding their
</P>
<P>
   ``authentic self'' and making the most of it. (b)
</P>
