<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-PET-PSYCH-REVIEW-AR     01-11 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PET-PSYCH-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR DR. PETSHRINK: HELP! MY CAT IS DRIVING ME CRAZY. 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychotherapy or pills? For years, mental health professionals
have differed over how best to treat people with disorders listed
in the current edition of the American Psychiatric Association's
Diagnostic and Statistical Manual.
</P>
<P>
   In the pet world, some veterinarians have found a niche treating
behavioral problems that can drive pet-owners, well, crazy. But
except for the occasional tranquilizer, animal mental-health
specialists have mostly employed a kind of psychotherapy _ behavior
modification _ to help pets deal with anxiety, rage, depression and
other problems that some veterinarians say affect animals as well
as humans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the Food and Drug Administration approved
two drugs commonly prescribed for human depressive and
nervous-system disorders as medications for dog mental-health
problems like separation anxiety (which causes some pooches to tear
up the furniture when their owners go out) and old dog syndrome
(which leads dogs to forget important things, like having been
housebroken).
</P>
<P>
   Given the money to be made on Americans' twin obsessions with
psychological advice and pets, it's only a matter of time before a
flood of books, television shows, radio programs and newspaper
columns feature pop psychiatrists whose specialty is putting Rover
on the couch or on Prozac. Here's how one column might look:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Petshrink:
</P>
<P>
   My once playful, affectionate cat, Miss Whispers, has suddenly
stopped responding to me. She won't come to eat when I call her,
and refuses to play with her little toys or demonstrate affection.
All she does is lie on the couch. Please, would psychotherapy or
drugs help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Heartbroken in Hackensack
</P>
<P>
   Dear Heartbroken:
</P>
<P>
   Mental-healthwise, cats are tough nuts to crack. Perhaps Miss
Whispers is suffering from Oppositional Defiant Disorder, one
symptom of which the DSM lists thusly: ``Often actively defies or
refuses to comply with adult's requests or rules.'' You might
consider counseling, psychotropic medication and involuntary
commitment in a secure but cheerful facility.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Petshrink:
</P>
<P>
   I recently went horseback riding for the first _ and last _
time. Obviously hoping to encourage other riders to ridicule me
behind my back, the stable manager put me on a bloated mare that
stopped abruptly every 30 feet or so, jerking its head down to
gorge itself on huge mouthfuls of grass, leaves and other debris.
The horse also chewed the tip of my sneaker. What's ailing her?
</P>
<P>
   _ Recovering in Rochester
</P>
<P>
   Dear Recovering:
</P>
<P>
   What I'm hearing here is a classic case of Binge Eating
Disorder, which the DSM says is characterized by ``eating, in a
discrete period of time, an amount of food that is definitely
larger than most people would eat in a similar period.''
</P>
<P>
   This disorder responds well to group therapy, but horses are
notoriously judgmental, and it may be that she just hated you.
</P>
<P>
   Hey Petshrink:
</P>
<P>
   I got 40 acres here in God's country, and a couple of months ago
I caught my Rotweiler, Lt. Colonel Himmler, whimpering out by the
gun shed, where it had been chased by a chicken. This is the very
same dog I once seen chew the hind leg off a billy goat.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dog cries all the time, don't eat, and won't even growl
at the mailman, a uniformed federal employee. What should I do?
This is important. I'm going to be needing a combat-ready canine
come Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   _ Igor from Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Igor,
</P>
<P>
   Your dog may have a a combination of Dysthymic Disorder, (``low
self-esteem'' and ``feelings of hopelessness'') and Dissociative
Fugue (``confusion about personal identity'' and ``inability to
recall one's past''). Please do not contact me again.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Petshrink:
</P>
<P>
   My once well-behaved pet monkey, Moonshine, has begun to scream
hysterically 24 hours a day. He demands constant attention and
praise and is always showing off. When I have people over he makes
a disgusting spectacle of himself with lewd behavior, if you know
what I mean. Is psychiatric intervention called for?
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael from Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Michael:
</P>
<P>
   Well, as the man on the radio used to say, Monkeys is the
cwaaaziest people. We're probably talking Hypomanic Episode
(``inflated self-esteem or grandiosity'' and an increase in
``psychomotor agitation''). There also may be a concurrent onset of
Exhibitionism, ``behaviors involving the exposure of one's genitals
to an unsuspecting stranger.'' Group therapy sometimes works, but
seldom with monkeys, as you can't get them to pay attention.
Electroshock is an option, though he won't be as frisky afterward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
