<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN12-CO     01-11 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Optimizing a computer can elevate gaming to the surreal
 &HT;    EDs: This is the first in a regular series of columns for
advanced computer users.
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'll never forget the time I saw the light _ literally _ inside
a dungeon.
</P>
<P>
   I had discovered a keyboard command on a Dungeon Keeper chat
board; so I executed it, while possessing an imp. Suddenly, my
on-screen vision (through the imp's eyes, of course) sharpened, and
everything became crystal clear and very detailed, from the flames
in the fire to the shadowy creatures scurrying through darkened
passages.
</P>
<P>
   The command had kicked Dungeon Keeper into high-resolution mode,
and even with my little 2-megabyte video card it was one of those,
ahem, eye-opening moments that make you sit up straight in your
chair.
</P>
<P>
   The lush 3-D graphics, sound effects, music and speedy game
engines today yield incredible results on several levels. They're a
blast on an older machine, like my Pentium 166 with 2Mb of video
memory. But they can also take advantage of current high-speed CPUs
and a new graphics bus to blow you right out of your chair.
</P>
<P>
   From dad's flight simulator to junior's death match in ``Quake
II,'' it's a simple matter to optimize the family PC to provide a
surreal gaming experience.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the basics, and we encourage further exploration on the
Web and in the newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   There are minor modifications you can make regarding sound, like
adding a subwoofer system or using Creative Labs' Sound Blaster
live or a few more speakers for surround sound. And, of course,
there's a slew of joysticks and steering wheels and USB hubs for
dual play.
</P>
<P>
   But the real meat and potatoes of gaming (and a primary source
of confusion) are good 3-D accelerated graphics.
</P>
<P>
   If you're about to buy a new PC, get one with an AGP bus
(accelerated graphics port) and at least 8Mb of video memory. AGP
is the new graphics bus standard _ which can be 4X as fast as PCI _
and there are a wide range of accelerator cards from which to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   If you just got a new PC that doesn't have AGP, or if you're
upgrading an older Pentium machine, like a 166, it's only a problem
if you're one of those benchmark types who help keep the industry
honest. There are also plenty of good 3-D accelerators on PCI bus
cards you can use.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, if you want to upgrade to AGP, you'll have to get
a new motherboard with an AGP slot on it.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also have to take into consideration the RAM on your
video card. One important thing to know is it deals with the number
of colors you can use at high resolution. For example, an 8Mb card
will allow 24-bit 3-D color at resolutions up to 1,200x1,600, but
you'd want at least a 19-inch monitor to get good results.
</P>
<P>
   A brief note about monitors: You'll want at least a 75-MHz
refresh rate.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of types of video memory available for the
various cards. SGRAM is the fastest right now, but the PCI bus
speed doesn't take full advantage of it. MDRAM, WRAM and VRAM are
the next best choices, EDO RAM is a last resort, and don't even
think about using DRAM for your gaming video board.
</P>
<P>
   Another point of confusion is the API _ application programming
interface _ that your video card supports. Game makers use three
primary ones: Microsoft's Direct3D, OpenGL and GLide. Many new 3-D
cards support all three APIs and cost anywhere from $69 to $199.
</P>
<P>
   Many new 3-D cards now also handle 2-D _ for non-3D stuff, like
DOS and Windows. If you get one that doesn't, you'll need an
available PCI slot, and it will come with a cable to connect it
with the 2-D card you're already using. The Voodoo2 chipset, by
3Dfx, is the current rage of the high-speed gaming community, which
also saw versions of Voodoo3 at Comdex '98. But there are plenty of
gamers who also rave about nVIDIA's Riva, ATI's Rage 128, Number
Nine's Revolution IV and S3's Savage3 cards.
</P>
<P>
   Any of these will be pretty astounding _ no matter whether
you're using PCI or AGP _ especially if you are upgrading from a
1Mb or 2Mb card.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want to explore high-end visuals even deeper and
you're flush with PCI slots, you can investigate SLI (Scan Line
Interleaving). That's the still somewhat experimental trick of
connecting two 3-D cards with a cable and theoretically doubling
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think I'll stay in the dungeon until they finish
working it out.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   http://www.soundblaster.com
</P>
<P>
   http://pcmech.pair.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sysopt.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www2.cybernex.net/(tilde)painter/hardware.htm
</P>
<P>
   ON USENET
</P>
<P>
   comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware.video
</P>
<P>
   comp.sys.ibm.pc.soundcard.games
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Yandel is an active Netizen and hard-core tech junkie who
built his first Web site in 1995 and partitioned his first hard
drive soon after. He is a graphics copy editor at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail: gyandel(AT)ajc.com
</P>
