<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LANGUAGE-DATABASE-R     01-11 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LANGUAGE-DATABASE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN LOOK IT UP, HOPEFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, language purists have rent their garments over the
use of the word hopefully to mean ``I hope,'' as in, ``Hopefully,
that will never happen again.'' Such use, they assert, arose in the
rule-smashing 1960s. For many, it was and remains a sign of the
decline of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes Fred Shapiro, associate librarian at Yale Law
School, using a powerful new computer tool called JSTOR that
permits detailed searches of thousands of issues of scholarly
journals back to the 19th century. And, lo and behold, the use in
formal English of hopefully to modify a whole sentence goes back
easily to the 1930s. He has found dozens of examples before 1960,
including an 1851 citation that starts, ``Hopefully, not to say,
certainly, in that time . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's findings will appear in a forthcoming issue of the
journal ``American Speech.'' He has also uncovered a 1912 use of
``double standard'' referring to the gap between the treatment of
men and women 39 years before the Oxford English Dictionary's first
citation of it; a 1931 example of ``Native American'' for American
Indian, 43 years ahead of Oxford's first example, and a 1914 use of
``solar energy,'' 58 years earlier than any other known use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of language is being rewritten because of these
electronic tools,'' said Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   JSTOR, which is a nonprofit project to put online forgotten and
inaccessible scholarly journals, is likely to cause a great deal of
intellectual history to be revised. For the first time, biologists,
economists and mathematicians can trace the development of a
question over the last century.
</P>
<P>
   And as they do their research, they are discovering not only new
facts but something else: humility. Many new ideas are just old,
forgotten ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathematics has a long shelf life and there are important
ideas to be picked up from papers of 100 years ago,'' said Cathleen
Synge Morawetz, a professor emerita of mathematics at New York
University and a recent winner of the National Medal of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Morawetz said an intriguing possibility is that
forgotten computational problems abandoned decades ago because the
technology was unavailable can now be solved. ``This opens up huge
possibilities as people get used to the idea of accessing old
journals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   JSTOR, an acronym for ``journal storage,'' is the creation of
William Bowen, president of the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation. Bowen,
a former president of Princeton University, thought of the idea
after a 1992 board meeting at Denison University in Ohio, where he
is a trustee and alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting it was announced that the university wanted to
build a new library wing. When Bowen asked what was taking up so
much shelf space, it turned out to be mostly back copies of
scholarly journals. He suggested looking into ways to digitalize
them.
</P>
<P>
   Denison never got its library wing, but the world got JSTOR.
</P>
<P>
   The Mellon Foundation has put up about $5 million for JSTOR,
which has been in operation for more than a year. The computer data
base contains many of the issues of 67 scholarly journals in a wide
range of fields _ from mathematics to the social sciences. All back
issues of 100 journals are expected to be online by the end of this
year. JSTOR clients are mostly American university libraries, and
it is starting to sign up subscribers overseas. So far,
subscriptions are unavailable for individuals and commercial
enterprises, but the hope is to make JSTOR self-sufficient. The Web
site is www.jstor.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, people asked what the point of it all is since
nobody ever searches for 30-year-old articles,'' recalled Kevin
Guthrie, president of JSTOR, which is based in New York City. ``But
it turned out that nobody was using older literature because it was
impossible to get to and search. You had to stumble on something or
it had to be cited by someone else. Now you can ask a question and
search through the journals.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliana Mulroy, professor of biology at Denison, said she has
used the search tool to trace cross-disciplinary views of the Dust
Bowl that were a precursor to the current debate over global
warming. In the past, such research would have been enormously
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   What has struck Professor Mulroy is the way JSTOR will change
the class boundaries within academia. ``I don't have to be at
Harvard or Berkeley to have access to a first-class library
anymore,'' she said. ``I can do this research sitting in my
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said he has been excited to hear from small colleges in
the Appalachian mountains and from housebound scholars using JSTOR.
</P>
<P>
   Some uses for the new files have been unexpected, Guthrie says.
The William and Mary Quarterly was expected to yield little from
its turn-of-the-century volumes, which were not research oriented
at the time. But those issues are filled with family names and
rosters of families' comings and goings in the early colonial
period, and genealogists have found them a rich vein.
</P>
<P>
   Linguists say digital libraries like JSTOR will reduce
dependence on searching through libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have people sitting around reading early books,''
said John Simpson, chief editor of the Oxford English Dictionary.
``But digital data bases like JSTOR are doing a lot to fill in the
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Informed of the new findings on ``hopefully,'' Sol Steinmetz,
former editorial director of the Random House Reference and
Information Division, said he was delighted. ``Even though there
are plenty of sentence adverbs, like frankly,'' he said, ``for some
reason people grabbed onto hopefully and wouldn't accept it. It's a
lot of nonsense. I'm sure people will be very surprised by what is
turning up. I consider it a pleasant shock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUANE-OWEN12-COX     01-11 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUANE-OWEN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury selection resumes in retrial of Florida slaying suspect
 &HT;    By Christine Stapleton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Four days after Duane Owen arrived on
Death Row in 1986 he wrote a polite ``to-whom-this-may-concern''
letter to police in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am corresponding at this time in regards to some murders
that I committed in your area,'' Owen wrote to the Lakewood, Colo.
police department. ``I am an honest person,'' he continued, saying
that he wanted to clear his past before he was executed.
</P>
<P>
   Owen, 37, had a history of teasing police about his crimes, and
Colorado police knew it. Two years earlier, he had played a
demented game of cat and mouse with detectives from Delray Beach
and Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roses are red, you pigs are blue, count up your victims, there
will be quite a few,'' Owen said during 24 hours of videotaped
interviews with detectives, during which he confessed to murdering
and raping a Delray Beach babysitter and a Boca Raton mother.
``Catch me if you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen's interviews with police have become the centerpiece of his
upcoming retrial for the 1984 murder of Karen Slattery, a
14-year-old Delray Beach babysitter. The Florida Supreme Court
reviewed the videotaped interviews in 1990 and concluded that Owen,
who was sentenced to death for Slattery's rape and murder, should
get a new trial because police violated his Miranda rights.
</P>
<P>
   During exhaustive questioning by detectives, Owen _ who did not
have a lawyer present _ twice said that he didn't think he should
answer questions. Police didn't follow up on his comments and
continued with the interrogation. Owen ultimately confessed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court in a later case said police could
continue questioning suspects if they make ``equivocal or
ambiguous'' requests to have an attorney present or to remain
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Harold Cohen, who is presiding over Owen's
retrial, has ruled that jurors should hear and see all of Owen's
statement to detectives regarding the Slattery murder. Lawyers
began picking the jury last week and will resume with jury
selection this week.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, once it's picked, will not learn about Owen's attempts
to contact Colorado police. Yet the letters and interviews _ which
have become public during the retrial _ offer more insight into
Owen's mind. Owen's attorney, Carey Haughout, now claims Owen was
insane when he attacked Slattery.
</P>
<P>
   When he was arrested in 1984 and charged with the murders of
Slattery and Georgianna Worden, a 38-year-old Boca Raton mother,
Owen became the focus of a massive media blitz. His conviction and
death sentence for Worden's murder still stand, although Owen has
one more appeal pending.
</P>
<P>
   Through two trials and an escape attempt, Owen made headlines.
He occasionally called the press room at the courthouse and
critiqued articles with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   There was no limelight on Death Row. His letters to police in
Colorado, however, brought Owen instant attention. Still, Colorado
police were skeptical. They had flown to West Palm Beach and
interviewed Owen in jail in 1984. Teresa Sue Knuth, 22, had
disappeared in Summit County about the same time Owen had lived
there and police thought they had to check out his murder claims.
</P>
<P>
   Their 1984 interview with Owen was ``cordial'' but ``no
information was developed to establish (Owen) as a primary suspect
in any offense within the state of Colorado,'' the Lakewood, Colo.,
police chief wrote.
</P>
<P>
   So after receiving Owen's 1986 letter, Colorado detectives told
Owen they wanted details this time: ``How the victims were killed
and weapons used? . . . were the victims' bodies left where they
were killed or were they removed to another area? . . . any items
stolen from your victims or removed from their bodies?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try and describe the victims,'' Owen responded. ``The
names will be hard because of the time lapse, but here goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Victim one was a ``hooker.'' He said he strangled her, then took
her panties. Victim two was beaten and buried near a campground
where Owen lived near Breckenridge. Owen included a map detailing
where he said he had buried her. Victim three was stabbed and left
on a road. Owen took her bikini bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Owen replied, he had ``stabbed, strangled and
beaten,'' nine females between the ages of 12 and 25 from Grand
Junction to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please send someone to visit me so that I may clear my horrid
past,'' Owen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On April 22, 1986, Detective Richard Eaton of the Summit County,
Colo. Sheriff's Office visited the Florida State Prison. Owen told
Eaton he had picked up a young woman hitchhiking and stabbed her
with a bayonet when she refused his sexual advances. Using
topographical maps, Owen showed Eaton where he buried the woman's
body.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton went back to Colorado and searched a square mile area with
a metal detector. He found nothing. Eaton and other detectives
videotaped the area and returned to Florida to show the tape to
Owen. Owen pinpointed the spot where he said he had left his car
and described the victim's clothing, which matched the clothes
Knuth was last seen wearing.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives narrowed the search area to 50 square yards and
dug, by hand, looking for the grave. And still found nothing. More
videos and aerial photographs were sent to Owen in July 1986. Owen
said the area looked familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives rented a backhoe and, with the help of the U.S.
Forestry Service, excavated more sites. They found no bodies. Owen
wanted to go to Colorado to show detectives the murder site.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, in August 1986, Owen clammed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time I must inform you that upon my attorney's
request, I no can longer talk,'' Owen wrote. ``I so regret this.
Until further contact by me, please take care.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of Teresa Knuth remains unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still can't completely eliminate him as a suspect,'' Eaton
said. ``But he's not any more insane than Bundy was.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Eaton wonders if Owen wasn't just trying to get
off Death Row for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on Death Row with Bundy and the idea of getting little
trips, maybe that's where it came from,'' Eaton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview last year Owen said he was lying about
the Colorado murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just stupidity,'' Owen said about his letters to
Colorado police. ``I was just mad and sent them out on a wild goose
chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen also said he was angry at Delray Beach and Boca Raton
detectives, whom he felt had violated his rights and made false
promises to keep him talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have done some wrong in my day,'' Owen said, ``but I
think they violated my rights.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7635 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MEDICARE-REVIEW-NYT     01-11 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEDICARE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXING MEDICARE: LIGHT AT A TUNNEL'S END
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A tense exchange last week between two liberal
members of the National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of
Medicare moved the group toward a dramatic agreement. The members
agreed to develop a plan to radically revamp Medicare by giving its
beneficiaries a fixed sum of money to buy private or public
insurance. In short, the use of vouchers _ something liberals have
shunned in education _ might be good for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vladeck, a former administrator of Medicare, who is a
staunch defender of the basic fee-for-service plan, began the
debate by proposing that Medicare officials get stronger powers to
restrict some medical practices, to negotiate fees and to favor
participation by some physicians over others.
</P>
<P>
   A dissenting member, Stuart Altman, a Brandeis University
professor, argued that Vladeck's proposals might result in
excessive governmental control. He could support them only if
Medicare moved to a system of competing public and private health
plans that would give the beneficiaries attractive ways to opt out
of the traditional government program. .
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck eventually chose Altman's competitive model, which put
him in temporary alliance with at least 10 other commissioners; 11
votes from among the commission's 17 members are needed to forward
a recommendation to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus may be more illusory than real. Much more has
to be agreed on before Vladeck, Altman and other Democratic
appointees will agree on a voucher plan to send to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, primarily a fee-for-service health plan serving about
40 million elderly, pays nearly any bill submitted by any doctor on
behalf of any enrollee. There is little supervision of physician
care. The system excludes prescription drugs and other benefits
routinely provided by private insurance plans but does not hold
down costs. As the baby boomers begin to retire, Medicare costs are
expected to soar to about 5 percent of aggregate income by 2020
from about 2.5 percent today
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to change all that are eight Republican appointees of the
advisory commission along with its chairman, Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., and Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. They envision Medicare as a
health care system similar to the one covering federal employees,
who can choose from many insurance plans. Under one version, the
beneficiaries would in effect receive a voucher enabling them to
enroll in either the traditional government plan or in a private
managed-care plan. Each plan would offer an identical package of
core benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The tricky step is assigning a dollar value to the voucher. Many
economists favor plans setting their own premiums. Then the
government would pay a certain amount, say, 75 percent of the cost
of the average plan. The beneficiaries would pay the remaining 25
percent, receiving rebates if they chose inexpensive plans. Under
some versions, the government would provide subsidies for
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   This voucher system _ which proponents call premium support _ is
designed to encourage innovation and to pressure plans to keep
their premiums low. Proponents point out that this plan exposes the
beneficiaries to little risk because it ties the dollar value of
the voucher to the premiums that health plans actually charge in
the market. That way, the voucher will not fall below the amount
that families need to buy the government-mandated benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck and some of the other Democratic appointees disagree.
They are skeptical that private plans will be affordable to
moderate income families or that the government can adequately
supervise the market.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Steelman, a Republican appointee, says that the
commission will have to save enough money to cover the future
deficit in the current program and save more money to pay for any
new benefits that the commission adds. Democratic appointees worry
that the savings cannot be achieved without depriving the
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have so far refused to consider raising taxes to
pay for any new benefits. Ms. Steelman cites the ugly backlash in
1989 after Congress taxed every beneficiary in order to add
benefits that many elderly already received from their former
employers. The uproar forced Congress to repeal the new benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats say the only way to make adequate health
benefits universal is to make them mandatory. Vladeck and Altman
are unlikely to approve a voucher plan that lacks sufficient
revenues for drugs and other essentials and fails to cover
low-income families. They lean toward raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other potential sources of dispute. Should the
commission close some of the future deficit by raising the age of
eligibility? And how will it encourage private plans to cater to
AIDS patients and others requiring expensive care? So what seemed
like an easy consensus last week could quickly break down. The
commission may wind up agreeing only to small-bore fixes that would
keep the program solvent for a few more years. And even if it does
propose a radical overhaul, Congress might not go along.
</P>
<P>
   Yet something of potential importance occurred last week.
Vladeck and other defenders of the current system know they cannot
make traditional Medicare work well unless Congress gives it the
power so long withheld. But, Altman says, the road to the best
fee-for-service plan possible runs right through the voucher
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
