   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NEWSTAND _ Newsstand column. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. This week: How to
deal with 401(k) tampering and other consumer questions. (Grieg,
Austin American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SMALLSTUFF _ Y2K. Such a small problem. Some say bank accounts
will be erased, the stock market will crash. We are told we will be
left penniless, groveling for food like animals. People will
starve. Planes will fall out of the air. There will be panic in the
streets. Gunfire. Bloodshed. Armageddon. To all that I say: Big
deal. Once again, we're sweating the big stuff. It's the small
stuff that's going to get us. What I want to know is if my Walkman
is going to work. That's right. If the world is going to catch on
fire, it better do it to the tune of whatever I have playing. If
not, I'm in big trouble. So in an attempt to uncover the larger
conspiracy of this ugly phenomenon, I have set out to see what the
true impact of Y2K will be on the common man, namely me.
(Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman). 25. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TRUMPETAWARDS _ Coverage of Monday's Trumpet Awards at CNN.
Among the honorees: Bryant Gumbel, Jessye Norman and Smokey
Robinson. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CATS _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta, international city, can put another
feather in its cap: It has hosted ``Cats'' more than any place
else, not counting London and New York. 13 times, to be exact. In
celebration, we offer ``Cats'' by the numbers. It opens at the Fox
Tuesday. And it's returning next year, too. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).10.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
