<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     01-11 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Jan. 11, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-PREDICTION (San Francisco) _ In October, the U.S.
Geological Survey is scheduled to issue, for the first time in
almost a decade, a ``probabilities'' report _ an official estimate
of how soon, and on which faults, the Bay Area is likely to
experience an earthquake. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   LESBIANS-METHODIST (San Francisco) _ The Rev. Don Fado knew it
was a big deal when he resolved to bless the relationship of a
lesbian couple, against the express will of the United Methodist
Church. The Sacramento pastor had searched his conscience and
determined he could do nothing less, even at the risk of his
calling.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ARKANSAS (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Waitresses at the
International House of Pancakes in the capital city of Clinton's
home state are backing impeached President Clinton in his fight to
keep his office. That seems to be the majority view in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MONEY (Austin, Texas) _ Now begins round two of the
Texas tobacco fight. While the last bout pitted Texas against Big
Tobacco at the courthouse, the statehouse is the next setting in
the high-stakes saga. The curtain rises Tuesday on the legislature
convenes to decide how to spend the historic $17.3 billion
settlement Texas struck with the tobacco industry last year. By
NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHOELESS-HOUSE (Bethelehem, N.Y.) _ First, there were no hats in
the house. Now there's a move afoot to shed your shoes at the
doorstep. As Americans become exposed to new traditions through
shifting immigration patterns and increased travel abroad, the foot
has come under fire. Urban and suburban dwellers in the know, now
request that you leave your dirty shoes at the door. By KIMBERLY
MARTINEAU.
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN-AUSTIN (San Antonio) _ A cache of rare Texana artifacts
going on sale Friday makes one thing clear: The Father of Texas,
Stephen F. Austin, was no Betsy Ross. In a March 4, 1836, letter,
Austin proposed and sketched a somewhat convoluted flag design. By
MARINA PISANO.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-NITRO (San Francisco) _ Touted by its promoters as a
euphoric elixir that can boost your mood, burn fat, rev up your sex
life and even send you off into blissful slumber, a trendy new brew
known as Blue Nitro has hit San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   TEDDY-ROOSEVELT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Even though Theodore Roosevelt
is placed among the handful of our greatest presidents, he grew
into the role and brought the nation along with him. For all his
achievements in conservation, regulating railroads, refereeing big
business and big labor, historians give Roosevelt the highest marks
for bringing the power and prestige of the presidency up to today's
stature and expectation. By FRED LeBRUN
</P>
<P>
   MONEY (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-TEACHING (San Francisco) _ The 63 students who enrolled
in Peter Navarro's economics course at UC-Irvine last spring had a
choice: Take a seat and listen to the lectures, or take off and on
your way out grab a multimedia CD-ROM containing simulated
lectures. Is ``cyberlearning'' an educational fraud or the wave of
the future? He wanted to answer that question for himself. By
GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   BANKAMERICA (Charlotte, N.C.) _ One of Bank of America CEO Hugh
McColl's favorite paintings in his office is a commissioned work
titled ``Take The Money And Run.'' It shows the bad guys making
their getaway from a bank called ``Republic.'' Fittingly, McColl's
former NationsBank Corp. merged with Texas' Republic Bank in 1988,
setting off a wave of acquisitions that culminated with the
marriage to San Francisco's BankAmerica Corp. in 1998. By GEORGE
RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANIMATION (Undated) _ We are in a comedic golden age. With
all due apologies to Walt Disney, Chuck Jones and the giants of the
1930s and '40s, we are now in an unsurpassed time for animation.
This goes for television as well as the movies. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Why do leaves turn brown in
the fall? What is the largest shark ever caught on a fishing rod
and reel? Easy enough, right? Nope. Of the thousands of entries in
the annual Examiner Outdoor Quiz, it was one of these two questions
that stymied nearly all. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ On Friday, the day the members of
the U.S. Senate got together to work out procedures for Bill
Clinton's impeachment trial, I took an impromptu public opinion
survey. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Late last month, U.S. Rep. Bob
Inglis, R-S.C., posed a somber question to his congressional
colleagues about the future of American values. ``Are we a nation
based on truth or moral relativism?'' he asked. ``Does the truth
matter?'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-STORE (San Francisco) _ Barnes and Noble may be a wonderful
company to work for. But in the world of independent booksellers,
the expectations for corporate takeover are no different from any
other business: lower pay, fewer benefits, stricter rules, rigid
adherence to the bottom line. To say nothing of termination. And,
please, let's say nothing of termination. By AL MCKEE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
