<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODALE-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODALE'S HEALTHY LIVING 
 HEALTH BRIEFS  
 FOR RELEASE MON., JAN. 18, 1999  
 EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes electronic art of two women eating breakfast. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 EAT UP TO PREVENT STROKE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Experts have suspected that getting more potassium in your diet
may lower stroke risk _ now a large, eight-year study backs that
up.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Harvard University tracked 43,738 men, ages 40 to
75, and found that those whose diets were richest in potassium, as
well as cereal fiber and magnesium, had a ``substantially reduced''
risk of stroke (Circulation, Sep. 22, 1998). (A parallel study
involving women is underway.)
</P>
<P>
   The apparent protective effect was especially strong in men with
high blood pressure, says study leader Dr. Alberto Ascherio, an
associate professor of nutrition and epidemiology at Harvard's
School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   But even men with normal blood pressure can enjoy a lower risk
of stroke by reducing their intake of processed foods (they tend to
be low in potassium) and loading up instead on potassium-rich
edibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best sources are vegetables, because they have high
potassium/calories ratios,'' Ascherio says. ``Fruits are also
good.'' Some top picks: tomatoes (or tomato juice), spinach,
bananas and oranges (or orange juice).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Don't use potassium supplements without consulting your
doctor, Ascherio warns. Potential risks include gastric irritation,
ulcers, and even arrhythmias in some people. &QL; 
 &UR; PATCH REDUCES INJECTION PAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new adhesive skin patch makes shots, stitches and other minor
procedures much less painful. According to Dr. Steven J. Weisman,
professor of anesthesiology and pediatrics at the Medical College
of Wisconsin in Milwaukee, the patch (called the EMLA Anesthetic
Disc) delivers a mixture of the commonly used anesthetics lidocaine
and prilocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was primarily designed for children, but adults can use
it as well,'' he says. Since the patch takes an hour to work, some
doctors may prescribe the patch ahead of time for patients to apply
before their appointment. &QL; 
 &UR; DO YOU NEED TAMOXIFEN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drug tamoxifen has been shown in recent studies to help
prevent breast cancer, but it does have health-threatening side
effects. There are possible fatal side effects from taking
tamoxifen, such as pulmonary embolism and uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Md., has
developed a computer program that can assist you and your doctor in
weighing your options.
</P>
<P>
   After prompting you to answer a series of questions, such as
your age and health history, the program calculates your estimated
5-year and lifetime risk of breast cancer, and compares your risk
with women who participated in the Breast Cancer Prevention Trial.
It also provides information from tamoxifen research studies. The
result may be a suggestion that you discuss tamoxifen and other
prevention options further with your doctor.
</P>
<P>
   More commonly, it may put you at ease, says Leslie G. Ford,
associate director of the Early Detection and community Oncology
program in the division of cancer prevention at the institute.
``Most women overestimate their risk of breast cancer,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called ``The Breast Cancer Risk Assessment Tool,''
comes on a standard computer disk for PC or Mac and is available
free by completing the Risk Assessment Tool order form on the
institute's Web site at cancertrials.nci.nih.gov. You can also call
(800) 4-CANCER (422-6237). You can also ask your health-care
provider if he can make the program available to you. &QL; 
 &UR; BREAKTHROUGH PROCEDURE HEALS DAMAGED EARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delivering antioxidants directly to delicate hairlike nerve
cells within the inner ear seems to undo noise-induced hearing
loss. ``When exposed to traumatic noise levels, the ear releases
free radicals,'' explains Dennis McBride, program officer for
biomedical science and technology at the Office of Naval Research
in Arlington, Va. ``These free radicals can cause the cells
responsible for hearing to die.''
</P>
<P>
   However, researchers have discovered that antioxidant medication
delivered directly to the inner ear through a miniature tube can
mop up enough free radicals to prevent permanent damage _ if the
treatment's given within six hours of the exposure to noise. The
procedure has restored full hearing in five patients tested thus
far, and trials are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   McBride, whose research team developed the technique, speculates
that the procedure may become generally available within months. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Rodale Press Inc. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Visit Prevention's Healthy Ideas web site at www.healthyideas.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
