A7718 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODALE-ALTERNATIVE-ME     01-11 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODALE-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODALE'S HEALTHY LIVING 
 ALTERNATIVE MEDICINE: HOT REMEDIES FROM ONE RED-HOT PEPPER
</HEADLINE>
  Includes 100-word sidebar. 
 FOR RELEASE MON., JAN. 18, 1999  
 EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION 
 By VARRO E. TYLER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to red peppers, the same heat that makes your
tastebuds tingle can banish some annoying health problems.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether you call this herb capsicum, cayenne pepper,
red pepper, chili pepper or paprika, red-hot peppers of any variety
do more than just fire up your food.
</P>
<P>
   The source of red pepper's sizzle is the chemical capsaicin,
usually extracted as a mixture of several closely related compounds
that are very pungent. The capsaicin content of different red
pepper varieties ranges from zero to about 1.5 percent. This
variation accounts for the range of differences between sweet bell
peppers, spicy jalapenos and super hot habaneros. The hotter the
pepper, the more capsaicin it contains _ thus, the more healing
power.
</P>
<P>
   The best proven medicinal use of capsaicin is as a topical
painkiller. Very small amounts of capsaicin (0.025 percent to 0.075
percent) are added to cream bases and applied locally to provide
relief from obstinate pain. Arthritis pain, cluster headaches and
various kinds of neuropathies and neuralgias (painful nerve
conditions) respond well to capsaicin creams. These creams are
thought to deplete substance P, a neurotransmitter or ``messenger''
in the nerves, if substance P is depleted, pain sensations can't
reach the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Capsaicin cream must be applied three or four times daily for
two or even three weeks before it becomes truly effective. For a
few days, at least, it can sting, but you may find that such
stinging is a small price to pay for relief from unrelenting pain.
Neurologists tell me that the stuff really works. Don't get
capsaicin cream in your eyes, in open wounds or on sensitive mucous
membranes _ the burning sensation will be more than you expected.
</P>
<P>
   If you chomp down on a really hot pepper, your eyes will tear,
your nose will run a little, and you'll even sweat some _ sure
signs that capsicum is increasing the flow of various bodily
fluids. You'll feel less stuffy and you'll cough much less, so
you'll feel better. Because red pepper thins thick mucus, your
cough will expel it more easily. One of my favorite cold remedies
is any good chicken soup with a dose of red pepper tossed in.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, in spite of its pungent properties, capsicum
has an ancient folkloric reputation as a digestive aid. It is
recommended for easing flatulence (gas) and stomach cramps as well
as stimulating digestion and relieving indigestion. For a soothing
brew, try adding 1/4 teaspoon hot red pepper (more or less
depending on your tolerance) to 1 cup of hot tea. Don't use red
pepper for digestive purposes if you have an active stomach ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a toothache, try chewing a hot chili pepper to
obtain temporary relief. It's said to be as effective as clove oil.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you can make your own warmup powder for cold feet by
adding ground red pepper or red pepper flakes to talc or
cornstarch. Start by adding just a small amount of each and
increasing it gradually until you find the right amount for you.
Dust lightly in your socks to keep your feet warm.
</P>
<P>
   The powder works as a counterirritant. It causes the small blood
vessels under the skin to dilate, providing extra blood flow and
warmth to the area where it is applied. Use it cautiously _ don't
get it in your eyes or mucous membranes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, red pepper is used by some as a blood anti-clotting agent
and cholesterol reducer. There's really not enough scientific
evidence, however, to promote this use.
</P>
<P>
   It's been said that red pepper can cause stomach cancer. Here's
my opinion: It is estimated that 25 percent of the world's
population eats red pepper daily. If it were significantly
carcinogenic, trust me, many more people would have the disease.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Don't worry about it, unless you consume lots more
than the U.S. average of 6.9 pounds per person per year. Besides,
hot peppers are a good source of healthy antioxidants and vitamins
A and C.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hot Tip: &LR;  If you've bitten into a pepper that causes an
intolerable burning sensation in your mouth, don't drink water _ it
won't help and will only spread the irritation. Instead, try
chewing a textured food such as rice. That absorbs the capsaicin.
Alternatively, drink a glass of cold whole milk. Its fat content
will dissolve the capsaicin.  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: CAPSICUM AT A GLANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Common names: red pepper, cayenne pepper, chili pepper,
paprika
</P>
<P>
   + Scientific names: Capsicum species, especially C. annuum and
C. frutescens, their hybrids and varieties
</P>
<P>
   + Benefits: topical analgesic, expectorant, sore-throat remedy,
digestive aid, toothache treatment, foot warmer, food flavoring
</P>
<P>
   + Possible side effects: severe irritation of the mouth and
throat following consumption, severe irritation on contact with
eyes, injured skin or sensitive body areas
</P>
<P>
   + Herbal fact: The hotness of hot peppers is often measured on a
scale devised by pharmacist Wilbur Scoville in 1912. Sweet bell
peppers have zero Scoville units. Jalapenos measure about 5,000.
Habaneros measure about 200,000 to 300,000. Pure capsaicin is 15
million. Humans can detect capsaicin at levels of one part per
million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Varro E. Tyler is America's foremost expert on herbs and
plant-derived medicine. He is dean emeritus of the Purdue
University School of Pharmacy and Pharmacal Sciences and
distinguished professor emeritus of pharmacognosy. He is also
author of more than 300 scientific articles and 18 books, including
``The Honest Herbal'' (Pharmaceutical Products Press, 1993). &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Rodale Press Inc. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Visit Prevention's Healthy Ideas web site at www.healthyideas.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
