<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7719 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODALE-COVER-NYTSF     01-11 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODALE-COVER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODALE'S HEALTHY LIVING 
 IS YOUR WATER SAFE TO DRINK?  
 FOR RELEASE MON., JAN. 18, 1999  
 EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes electronic art of a glass of water. 
 By CAROL KEOGH  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water is vital to life. But is it safe to drink?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a wimpy ``maybe.'' A lot of things can happen to
your water before it touches your lips. The safety of your home
supply depends on the quality of its source _ and that source is
subject to both the whims of Mother Nature and the carelessness of
human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you get water in one of three ways: from a public
utility that's regulated by the state and federal government, from
your own private source _ usually a well _ or bottled. Here's how
they stack up:
</P>
<P>
   + Public water: two thumbs up most of the time. There are
notable and well-publicized exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   + Well water: It may or may not be safe, depending on both the
quality of the underground water and the diligence of the homeowner
in caring for the well.
</P>
<P>
   + Bottled water: Almost always safe, but it may not be as
``pure'' as you think.
 &UR; PUBLIC WATER: USUALLY SAFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Public water is tested, analyzed and treated so it will do you
no harm, says Patti Kay Wisniewski, an environmental scientist at
the Environmental Protection Agency. ``The water is safe to
drink,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That should be good news to the 85 percent of you whose tap
water comes from a municipal source. Except...
</P>
<P>
   What about those news reports that some of New Jersey's public
wells test high for radium and that some of California's public
wells are contaminated with a gasoline additive? What about the
403,000 people in Milwaukee who were sickened in 1993 when a
parasite known as cryptosporidium crept into their water supply?
What about E. coli bacteria, lead, and pesticides?
</P>
<P>
   You can lay the radium problem at the feet of Mother Nature.
When uranium in surface rocks decays, it naturally turns into
radium, which moves into the underground water supply, as happened
in New Jersey. The gas additive leak most likely was the result of
human error.
</P>
<P>
   Cryptosporidium _ as well as bacteria and viruses _ gets into
public water when human and animal wastes enter lakes and rivers
from sewage plant overflows and city and farm run-off, the latter
of which is probably also responsible for any pesticide residue.
And while lead sometimes leaches from water distribution pipes,
it's more likely to be coming from inside your home.
</P>
<P>
   Constant monitoring reveals most of these problems, and then
steps can be taken to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   But the system doesn't work perfectly. Both the federal
government and your state require your water supplier to test
regularly for contaminants, including bacteria, radioactive
elements and certain toxic chemicals. And if they find a problem,
your water company is required to notify you and tell you what to
do _ such as boil your water.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation's 170,000-some public water systems comply
faithfully with testing and notification requirements. The ones
that don't are fined by the state or federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent investigation by USA Today revealed that as many as
40,000 U.S. water systems violated testing requirements and purity
standards last year, putting 58 million people at risk. The
investigation also found that state and federal officials took
action against only about 10 percent of violators between 1994 and
early 1997. And more than a quarter were repeat offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, however, has recently taken action to
assure you that your water system is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water systems are now required to issue annual reports, called
Consumer Confidence Reports,'' Wisniewski says. ``This law took
effect in September 1998, and the companies have until next October
to produce them.'' The reports will come with your water bill, but
will also be available at libraries and schools, and in local
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Consumer Confidence Reports are already accessible on the
World Wide Web. Check out the Web site at www.EPA.gov/ogwdw. Select
``Local Drinking Water Information.'' There, you can click on your
state, then your county, and finally on your own water utility and
see what's in your water.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you're ever notified of a problem, call the EPA's Safe
Drinking Water Hotline at (800) 426-4791 and get some on-the-spot
expert advice.
 &UR; THE TREATMENT TRAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But testing is only one aspect of the very complex job being
performed at the other end of your water main. Your water is
processed in what utilities call ``the treatment train.''
</P>
<P>
   It's filtered to remove clay, silt, organic debris,
microorganisms and some minerals. Then any tiny particles that slip
through the filters are clumped together so they become heavy
enough to sink. Finally, the water is disinfected, usually with
chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, enough chlorine is used to treat the water all the
way from the plant to your home. Chlorination does an excellent
job, but it has a downside. It generates disinfection byproducts
that, with long- term exposure, have been associated with a risk of
cancer or other adverse health effects.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA says that to avoid these unwanted byproducts, more water
suppliers are disinfecting with ozone instead. Call yours to find
out what treatment is used. In the meantime, you can remove these
unwanted disinfectant byproducts with a carbon filter.
 &UR; WELLS AND YOUR WELL-BEING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wells, which serve about 15 percent of Americans or 23 million
people, are not regulated by most states nor the federal
government. The responsibility is entirely on you to see that your
water is safe. There are three steps you need to follow to make
sure your well water is safe to drink.
</P>
<P>
   + First, protect your well site:
</P>
<P>
   _ Locate your well at least 50 feet from your septic tank and
100 feet from its drain field.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disinfect it, if needed, with bleach solution or hypochlorite
granules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mix pesticides and herbicides as far away from the well as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep all hazardous substances out of your septic system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Properly dispose of products such as leftover paint, solvents,
used oil and batteries (don't dump them down the sink or in the
yard).
</P>
<P>
   _ Channel all runoff water away from your well.
</P>
<P>
   + Second, inspect your well regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Check the well casing for holes or cracks. Also check the cap
often to make sure it's tightly in place, so that it will continue
to keep out insects, small rodents, and surface runoff.
</P>
<P>
   + Third, test it-at least once a year for some contaminants, but
immediately if you notice changes in the smell or taste of the
water or you and your family are getting sick more often.
</P>
<P>
   You can't test for everything, because it would cost a fortune,
Wisniewski says. ``Instead,'' she says, ``test for likely
contaminants, such as coliform bacteria. If you live in an
agricultural area, test for pesticides, herbicides and nitrates.''
</P>
<P>
   If you need help deciding what to test for, contact your state
or local health department. If a contaminant is found, ask the
health department for assistance. Or call the EPA's Safe Drinking
Water Hotline, which also offers technical assistance.
 &UR; BOTTLED WATER: WHAT'S BETWEEN THE EARTH AND YOU? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water carries with it the myth that it's so pure it
gushes straight from the earth's depths into those pristine bottles
_ virtually untouched by human hands. While it true that bottled
water has no chlorine, no weird off-tastes and no odors, and is
certainly is safe to drink, it has been touched _ plenty _ on its
way to your home.
</P>
<P>
   It's processed, or at least bottled, in manufacturing plants
that are inspected by the Food and Drug Administration every five
or six years. ``We look at the facility to determine if bottled
waters are produced under safe and sanitary conditions,'' says an
FDA administrator. Individual states also inspect plants regularly.
On top of that, the International Bottled Water Association
commissions NSF International, an independent testing organization,
to conduct annual surprise inspections of its members' facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the bottlers test the source water for chemical
contaminants such as benzene or pesticides a minimum of once a
year, for microorganisms such as E. coli once a week, and for
inorganic compounds such as antimony, arsenic, lead and zinc, among
others, once a year. They also test for radiological contaminants
such as radium about once a year.
</P>
<P>
   If chemical contaminants are found, they are removed from the
water. In addition, most bottled waters produced in the United
States have been disinfected, says a spokesperson for the FDA. The
reason you don't taste chlorine is that most bottlers disinfect
with ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Imported water must meet federal regulations too. It's subject
to sampling and testing at entry into the United States, says a
spokesperson for the FDA. IBWA member companies with facilities
abroad are subject to the same surprise inspections.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be sure of the safety of your bottled water, look
for the letters IBWA on the label. Members of the association are
held to a higher standard than bottlers who are not.
</P>
<P>
   They must follow a model code that is stricter than the FDA'S,
says Adele Logan Galen, vice president of communications for the
IBWA. If you want to know if your favorite water is bottled by an
IBWA member, call the association at (800)-WATER11 (928-3711). Or
check their Web site for Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) at
www.bottledwater.org.
</P>
<P>
   All bottled waters aren't the same. Water quality can vary among
brands. ``Sometimes (bottled water) is just water from a public
system that has been `polished,'' Wisniewski says.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 25 percent of bottled water sold in the United
States comes from public water supplies. It is further processed by
the bottler, in which case the label does not have to say what the
source is. Sometimes, however, it hasn't been further processed. By
law, then, the label must indicate that the water is from a public
source. Which means you're paying an awful lot for that pretty good
thing that's already flowing from the tap. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Rodale Press Inc. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Visit Prevention's Healthy Ideas web site at www.healthyideas.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
