w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELANIE-GRIFFITH-IN-A     01-11 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELANIE-GRIFFITH-IN-ANOTHER-DAY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELANIE GRIFFITH'S WALK ON THE WILD SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Melanie Griffith in a scene from
``Another Day in Paradise.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Melanie Griffith is a Hollywood star from head to toe, from her
immaculately coiffed blonde hair to ... to ...
 &HT;    All right, why is each of her nails a different color?
 &HT;    ``I have two little girls,'' Griffith says, laughing. ``I also
have lots of nail polish sitting around, and it's the holiday
season. I just thought it would be fun for all three of us.''
 &HT;    She sighs.
 &HT;    ``But my youngest, Stella, is only 2,'' she adds, ``so the test
was whether Stella could sit still long enough for her nails to
dry. I bet you can guess the answer.''
 &HT;    The idea of the glamorous Griffith as a hands-on mom is hard to
picture, but no harder than her latest onscreen role, in ``Another
Day in Paradise,'' opening Jan. 22.
 &HT;    Griffith plays Sid, a heroin addict who isn't above taking care
of business with a 12-gauge shotgun. She and her
small-time-criminal boyfriend (James Woods) recruit another pair of
misfits _ a teen-age runaway and his girlfriend (Vincent Kartheiser
and Natasha Gregson Wagner) _ into a downward-spiraling series of
shockingly violent scams.
 &HT;    Having struggled with much-publicized substance-abuse problems
in the past didn't make her role any easier, the actress says.
 &HT;    ``I was doing drugs in the '70s,'' she says matter-of-factly.
``I never experienced the kind of life that's in the movie.
Everyone was into cocaine, but heroin was definitely a no-no. I
never faced the kind of addiction that Sid has.
 &HT;    ``Looking back, though,'' she adds, ``I went though some pretty
wild nights. I guess the most important thing for me was hoping
that, when I went to bed, I'd wake up in the morning and get
excited about living again. There were lots of times when I didn't
even care if I got up. I had to work to get over that.''
 &HT;    Preparing for the role, Griffith spent some time with real
addicts.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to find out how people behaved on heroin,'' she says.
``Many of them function pretty normally _ you wouldn't know they
were doing it, even though it was destroying them. That helped me
give my character some depth, and not just turn her into a
drug-crazed cliche.''
 &HT;    In what may be the most shocking moment in the film, Sid uses a
syringe to inject heroin into her neck.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't in the script,'' she says. ``But I met a junkie who
told me how he used to do it, because it was the only place he
could find a vein that hadn't collapsed.
 &HT;    ``At least it wasn't painful to film,'' she adds, ``because the
syringe had a collapsing needle and it didn't even break my skin.
There's no way I would ever stick a needle into my own body.''
 &HT;    Griffith took the role at the urging of Woods, who also
co-produced ``Another Day In Paradise,'' which director Larry Clark
_ whose previous film was the controversial ``Kids'' _ adapted from
the celebrated novel by ex-con Eddie Little.
 &HT;    ``Jimmy called me up and said, `You have to do this f---in'
movie, I'm sending the script over and you've got to read it right
now and tell me what you think of it,''' she recalls. ``So I read
it, and I knew he was right. I knew it would be challenging, but
the script was amazing.''
 &HT;    The production sparked rumors of angry confrontations between
Woods and Clark, who after an altercation with co-producer Stephen
Chin at the film's premiere announced that he was entering a
facility for lapsed substance abusers.
 &HT;    Asked about the mood on the set, Griffith shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I don't know if you could call making this film fun,'' she
says. ``It was hard, and we had a very low budget. It's a tough
story, and it wasn't like everyone was laughing a lot _ it was
pretty heavy and difficult. You had to really put yourself out
there.''
 &HT;    The highlight of each day, the actress says, was setting aside
her emotionally draining character and going home to her children.
 &HT;    ``I take a lot of comfort in knowing that my kids won't accept
me if I ever bring my work home,'' she says, smiling. ``It was
great to just be a mom, to feed them dinner, get their baths ready
and help them with their homework.''
 &HT;    Griffith's family is more complicated than most, including her
son Alexander, whose father is actor Steven Bauer. Then there's her
daughter Dakota, by ``Nash Bridges'' star Don Johnson _ whom
Griffith married twice, once in her teens and once in her 30s _ and
Johnson's son Jesse, whose mother is actress Patti D'Arbanville.
 &HT;    Rounding out the mix is Stella, Griffith's daughter by Banderas.
 &HT;    ``My kids get moved around over the holidays,'' she admits.
``Antonio and I took Stella to Spain. Alexander and Dakota went
skiing in Aspen with Don, and then he took them to Jamaica. But
next year, we'll have everyone with us.
 &HT;    ``I can't say that I'm raising my children the way I was
raised,'' says Griffith, whose mother is the actress Tippi Hedren.
``My mother was great and I love her, but I was still 14 when I
pretty much left home. I just wanted to be in love and have kids of
my own. I didn't give my mom much choice _ I was pretty headstrong.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't want that for my children, to be out on their own
at such a young age.''
 &HT;    However much she enjoys being a mother, Griffith is equally
determined to be a success as Banderas' wife.
 &HT;    ``I've never met anybody like him,'' she says. ``Antonio is so
talented and knowledgeable about things like literature and music,
yet he's extremely humble. He's also an incredible father _ not
just to our daughter Stella, but to all my kids.
 &HT;    ``And he's so gorgeous,'' she adds with a wicked grin. ``He's
very romantic and so am I, maybe because we're both Leos and we've
both been around the block a few times. I really make it a priority
to keep the romance in our relationship.
 &HT;    ``But Antonio takes care of that, too,'' she says. ``I remember
he proposed to me on a beach in North Carolina at sunset. He got
down on his knee and asked me to marry him. It was beautiful.''
 &HT;    The pair recently completed filming ``Crazy in Alabama,'' in
which Banderas directs his wife and, in cameo appearances, two of
her children.
 &HT;    ``It's a dark comedy set in the '60s,'' she says, shaking her
head as she tries to describe it. ``It's about a woman with seven
children who's been mistreated by her husband until she can't take
it anymore. She puts rat poison in his coffee, cuts off his head
with an electric carving knife and puts it in a Tupperware bowl,
and heads for Hollywood to try to get on `Bewitched.'
 &HT;    ``But behind the humor is a very powerful statement about women
freeing themselves from abusive relationships.''
 &HT;    To say the least, it's another offbeat role for a onetime
ingenue _ she peaked with her Academy Award-nominated performance
in ``Working Girl'' (1988) _ whose most recent roles have been
anything but, including her ``Paradise'' addict and the shrill
Charlotte Haze in ``Lolita'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``I'm 41,'' she says, ``and I can't pretend that I'm going to
play the ingenue anymore. Besides, it's not that much fun anyway.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I'll keep on playing drug addicts, but I'm going
to go for interesting parts, and if they're in low-budget,
independent movies I won't care, as long as it gives me a chance to
do something different.
 &HT;    ``Some people said it took courage for me to play an addict,''
Griffith adds. ``I didn't see it that way at all _ I just saw it as
a wonderful challenge. That's what I'm looking for in my life.''
