<HEADER>
A7763 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JON-STEWART-IN-THE-DA     01-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JON-STEWART-IN-THE-DAILY-SHOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `DAILY' WORLD OF JON STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jon Stewart in a scene from ``The Daily
Show.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He was never the class clown.
 &HT;    Jon Stewart didn't have time for that growing up in Lawrence,
N.J. He needed his wit for other things, such as making money.
 &HT;    ``My senior year of high school, I got a job,'' he recalls. ``So
I signed myself out of school everyday at 1 p.m. after clowning
around with the secretaries, who thought I was hilarious or that I
had an illness.''
 &HT;    Before they could think twice, the skinny Jewish kid who was a
walking punch line was out the door.
 &HT;    That's the deal with Stewart. Funny, yes, but with a purpose.
Right now, for example, he's being funny to promote his two films,
the current teen science-fiction epic ``The Faculty'' and the drama
``Playing By Heart,'' due to open Jan. 22.
 &HT;    But don't forget his book, ``Naked Pictures of Famous People''
(Rob Weisbach Books, 1998), which is still selling well.
 &HT;    And neither of those is even his main gig: Since Jan. 11,
Stewart has been the host of ``The Daily Show,'' the Comedy Central
staple.
 &HT;    Not bad for a guy whose most prominent previous credit has been
a flop talk show on MTV, 1995's ``The Jon Stewart Show.''
 &HT;    Fortunately, his predecessor on ``The Daily Show,'' Craig
Kilborn, gave him a lift. Literally.
 &HT;    ``I'm a little shorter than Craig,'' Stewart says with a mock
grimace, ``so he sent me a telephone directory to sit on for my
first show!''
 &HT;    The tone of the show has very much reflected Kilborn's persona,
and Stewart expects that now it will evolve to reflect his own.
 &HT;    ``The changes will be slow over the next few months,'' he says,
``but I'm sure I will assert a lot of my point of view into the
writing. Craig never did any of the writing _ that will be one big
change.''
 &HT;    The cable-deprived can catch Stewart at their neighborhood
multiplexes in ``The Faculty,'' as a teacher whose students suspect
him of being an alien monster.
 &HT;    ``I was definitely not one of the high-school kids,'' he jokes.
``This isn't `Beverly Hills 90210,' where the guy with gray hair is
still in 11th grade. I think one of those kids on `90210' will have
a hysterectomy before they go to college.''
 &HT;    In ``Playing By Heart,'' Stewart co-stars with Sean Connery and
romances Gillian Anderson. Classy company, but the comedian remains
unimpressed with himself.
 &HT;    ``Working with Gillian I felt like the poor man's Mulder,'' he
jokes. ``Put me next to Sean Connery in the film, and everyone will
be going, `Who is the skinny young guy?'''
 &HT;    Things don't go well with Anderson in the film _ in fact, it's
more or less the date from hell, with a huge mastiff playing a key
role. In reality, though, Stewart says he's never had a date that
was even not-so-good.
 &HT;    ``They've actually all been magic,'' he says. ``You know, I
don't really date. I get a sense that I'm attracted to someone and
that's just it. And we don't date.
 &HT;    ``We mess around for a little bit and leave it at that, or we go
out for a long time.''
 &HT;    His current girlfriend, a graphic designer named Tracey, is
someone he actually met on a blind date three years ago.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, it was just after my show on MTV had been canceled,
so I was just happy to get the action,'' he says, laughing. ``My
days of hitting on Jennifer Aniston were over. I was happy to be
back in the world.''
 &HT;    That world began in Lawrence, not far from Princeton University,
where Stewart grew up as the son of a physicist and a teacher.
 &HT;    ``I was very pleasant,'' Stewart recalls. ``Smallish. I don't
think I was a troublemaker. Nah, I had a lot of pretty good
friends. I played a lot of sports.
 &HT;    ``This was back in the days when kids played outdoors and used
their arms and legs to run,'' he adds. ``We didn't have Nintendo.''
 &HT;    Even more than now, he says, he was a cutup.
 &HT;    ``The problem I had in high school is that I didn't want to
abide by what I thought were unreasonable rules,'' Stewart says.
``I wasn't stealing cars, but as a senior I thought being in school
for such a long time was a waste of my time. That's why I got that
job.''
 &HT;    One thing was clear by the time he graduated.
 &HT;    ``I was voted `Best Sense of Humor' in high school,'' he
recalls. ``That was about the only accreditation I have as far as
being funny _ otherwise you have to take my word for it.''
 &HT;    After earning a psychology degree from the College of William
and Mary in Williamsburg, Va., Stewart returned to nearby Trenton,
N.J., where he worked as a waiter and as a bartender while trying
to break into the world of stand-up comedy.
 &HT;    ``My first gig ever was at The Bitter End club,'' he says. ``I
followed four Doors cover bands. You felt the history, that Woody
Allen once performed there, Bill Cosby was there. But, believe me,
they were long gone by the time I arrived!''
 &HT;    He was driven to succeed, Stewart says, if only to escape being
a waiter.
 &HT;    ``Waiting tables made me feel like the ultimate `Nothing Man,'''
he says. ``I would grumble, `Just tell me what you want. I'll go
and fetch it to you, and hopefully this will all work out.'
 &HT;    ``I liked being a bartender,'' he adds. ``I was like, `You want
booze? You gotta come to the J-Man.' I also got to ply the pretty
girls with shots.''
 &HT;    Don't picture Tom Cruise in ``Cocktail'' (1988), though.
 &HT;    ``No, I was more like Zero Mostel in `The Front' (1976),'' he
deadpans, evoking the shambling, desperate comedian on the brink of
suicide.
 &HT;    Doing ``The Daily Show'' won't keep him off the big screen,
however, despite his insistence that ``I think I will pace myself
to do one film every 35 years.'' He's currently filming a role in
the Adam Sandler vehicle ``Big Daddy,'' set for release next
summer.
 &HT;    The plot, he says, is basically ``One Man and a Baby.''
 &HT;    ``I play Adam's best friend,'' he explains. ``I go to China for
a few weeks to work. Someone drops a kid, supposedly mine, on our
doorstep, and Sandler has to keep him alive until I get home.''
 &HT;    It's no stretch for Stewart and Sandler to play best friends,
since they're pals of long standing.
 &HT;    ``Adam's still the same guy he has always been in terms of being
funny and original,'' Stewart says. ``He's really sticking to his
guns and doing what got him here. What makes him so successful is
that he's staying to what he knows and what he thinks is funny. He
hasn't changed it _ he just made it better.''
 &HT;    Which, as it happens, is pretty much what Stewart has in mind
for himself, as well.
 &HT;    ``It's either keep it the same and keep it funny,'' he says,
``or go back to Zero Mostel time.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
