<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRICIA-ARQUETTE-IN-THE-HI-LO-COUNTRY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICIA ARQUETTE: ACTING TO THE BEAT OF A DIFFERENT DRUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Patricia Arquette with Woody Harrelson in
a scene from ``The Hi-Lo Country.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Talk about peer pressure.
 &HT;    Patricia Arquette is from a family of actors _ grandfather
Cliff, father Lewis, sister Rosanna and brothers Alexis and David
inclusive _ and, though she says she never felt competitive toward
her siblings, it was never easy.
 &HT;    ``I caused myself a lot of grief not knowing if I could or would
be able to act at all,'' she recalls. ``But our parents always
raised us feeling very different from each other and special in our
own ways.
 &HT;    ``I was just worried about what I would do, who I would be,''
she says by telephone from a Los Angeles hotel. ``I realized that
you just have to educate yourself about as many things as you can
and, later, you'll figure out what you're going to do. You want to
be well-rounded, talk to a lot of people, so that you have as many
choices and chances as you want in life.
 &HT;    ``But I just felt incredible pressure to do something.''
 &HT;    ``Something'' turned out to be acting, but it could have been
marine biology or midwifery.
 &HT;    ``Marine biologist was weird, because I always loved the look of
underwater, but I didn't know that much about fish and didn't
really want to go into the ocean,'' she says, laughing. ``I was
very interested in being a midwife, though. I knew a lot about the
birth process, and was always fascinated by that.
 &HT;    ``What I decided to do was to try acting for a year, from 18 to
19,'' she recalls. ``Then I could say I tried one of my dreams and
it did or didn't work out. I didn't want to spend 30 years trying
to follow a dream and then be bitter about it.
 &HT;    ``I thought if the acting didn't work out, I'd just try to
realize one of my other dreams.''
 &HT;    Twelve years later, it's still working out. Arquette graduated
from television work to such features as ``A Nightmare on Elm
Street 3'' (1987), ``The Indian Runner'' (1991), ``Ethan Frome''
(1993), ``True Romance'' (1993), ``Beyond Rangoon'' (1995),
``Flirting with Disaster'' (1996) and ``Lost Highway'' (1997). She
may not be a superstar _ like, say, her husband Nicolas Cage _ but
she's working regularly, which not every actress can say.
 &HT;    Her latest film, ``The Hi-Lo Country,'' opens around the country
throughout January. A sprawling western directed by Stephen Frears,
it's set in post-World War II New Mexico, where Arquette's Mona is
married to one man while attracted to two others, small-time cattle
ranchers played by Billy Crudup and Woody Harrelson.
 &HT;    Frears, director of ``My Beautiful Laundrette'' (1983) and ``The
Grifters'' (1990), is much admired in Hollywood, and Arquette
admits that she didn't want the role when she initially agreed to
discuss it with him.
 &HT;    ``I just wanted to meet him so that someday I could work with
him,'' she says. ``I didn't think I was right for Mona. She's so
enigmatic, and I didn't understand how to play an enigmatic
personality. I also didn't particularly like the choices she was
making in her life.
 &HT;    ``Stephen and I talked about it,'' the actress recalls, ``and I
said, `I see her as this woman who has this little smell coming out
of her skin, that men and women notice, that draws people to her.
She's not rich, but she knows how to dress and how to do her nails
and hair.'''
 &HT;    To her surprise, Frears agreed, and Arquette found herself in
the film.
 &HT;    ``I had to break the role down, little by little,'' she says.
``I had to find Mona's concept of femininity, her daily rituals,
and then I had to think about her love and her hate for each of the
characters, and their love or hate for her.
 &HT;    ``At the end of the day, she's a woman who needs a lot of
attention and love. Even if she's being mad and quiet, she wants
you to hear, very loudly, that she's mad and quiet.''
 &HT;    Working with Frears was everything she'd hoped, the actress says
_ though the Englishman, best known for his intimate, small-scale
films, wasn't the obvious choice for a prairie-set story.
 &HT;    ``He surpassed my expectations of him being a gentle and
generous director,'' Arquette says. ``He's always been good with
his female leads. He's mystified by women because, to him, they're
enigmatic.
 &HT;    ``Also, Stephen loved westerns as a boy,'' she adds, ``and you
can feel that nostalgic beat in the movie, that sort of
old-fashioned flavor and romance.''
 &HT;    Arquette giggles.
 &HT;    ``But he did have to tutor himself about `What is a rodeo?'''
she says. ``He had to ask, `How do you lasso something?'''
 &HT;    The actress has three other films due later in 1999. Roland
Joffe's black comedy ``Goodbye Lover'' casts her as a
``realtor/homemaker/slasher,'' while she plays a party
girl/hairdresser in ``Stigmata,'' a ``psycho/spiritual/detective
horror movie.''
 &HT;    Especially dear to her heart is the just-wrapped ``Bringing Out
the Dead,'' which co-stars her husband and was directed by Martin
Scorsese, who co-produced ``Hi-Lo Country.'' It's about a troubled
paramedic (Cage) and a woman he meets on a call.
 &HT;    ``It's been interesting to work together,'' Arquette says.
``It's heavy material, so it takes a lot of concentration. It's
nice at the end of the day to have him around.''
 &HT;    Cage recently said he plans to work steadily for the next five
years, to strike while the $20-million-per-film iron remains hot,
even if that means squeezing other areas of his life, family
included. Obviously this affects Arquette's career, but if she has
any problem with it, she's not talking.
 &HT;    ``I'm not as aggressive about my career now as I have been at
different moments,'' she says. ``I've never really been a gigantic
go-getter.''
 &HT;    Movie stars or not, she says, everyone has to go through periods
when their careers take center stage.
 &HT;    ``All people work hard,'' she says, ``especially when they're
young. Why should we be exempt from that? In the old days, a guy
would go off to war for 10 years. We certainly have a lot more
communication and a lot more time together than some people.
 &HT;    ``So I don't feel so bad for us.''
 &HT;    After all, if one of the two is going to earn the megabucks, it
figures to be Cage. Arquette's filmography attests to her penchant
for independent features with riskier stories and more challenging
characters. ``Indian Runner,'' ``True Romance,'' ``Ethan Frome''
and ``Beyond Rangoon'' rank among her favorite films, even though
collectively they didn't make any money to speak of.
 &HT;    ``I say `Yes' to something if I like it when I'm reading it or
if I'm really intrigued by a director or a cast,'' she says. ``I
say `Yes' if I meet a director and he's got an interesting take on
the story.
 &HT;    ``I say `Yes' if the film is different from things I've done
before, if the role is different from me or even similar to me. I'd
do more mainstream films if I liked the scripts.''
 &HT;    Either way, it looks as if the world will have to get by without
one more marine biologist or an extra midwife.
 &HT;    ``I never thought I'd be here now,'' she says, ``so I'm
surprised, pleasantly surprised with what's happened for me.
 &HT;    ``But there's more I want to do,'' she continues. ``I want to do
a goofball comedy, and I don't want to be the straight man. I want
to be really goofy, really silly. I do so many serious movies ...
''
 &HT;    Arquette sighs.
 &HT;    `` ... I just want to do one that's funny and happy.
 &HT;    ``I want to make a movie called `The Happiest Movie on Earth,'''
she says, laughing. ``It's going to be the happiest movie of all
time.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
