<HEADER>
A7765 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARRY-WATSON-IN-7TH-H     01-11 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRY-WATSON-IN-7TH-HEAVEN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRY WATSON'S OWN KIND OF HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Barry Watson in a scene from ``7th
Heaven.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a question of edge.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what constitutes that ill-defined quality is hard to
say, but it's important in Hollywood. And it's causing Barry Watson
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging out in his trailer between scenes on his film ``Killing
Mrs. Tingle,'' due out in July, the ``7th Heaven'' heartthrob says
that he almost didn't get the part, which is his first major
big-screen role.
</P>
<P>
   ``My character in this is kind of edgy, and just before I read
for this part, I'd read for another movie and they said I wasn't
edgy enough,'' he recalls. ``And that character wasn't even as edgy
as this character.''
</P>
<P>
   A young woman passing his trailer pauses and does a double take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you Jared Leto?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently a starstruck fan has somehow gotten onto the studio
lot and mistaken one hunky young actor for another.
</P>
<P>
   Watson gets a good laugh out of that. Earlier, he had talked,
not entirely happily, about how much people are recognizing him
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he answers, smiling. ``He's the one that's edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson may or may not be edgy, but he and ``7th Heaven'' are
definitely hot. How hot? The WB network is already running weekly
repeats of the series on Sunday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Watson plays Matt Camden, the oldest son of the sizable brood
being raised by Eric (Stephen Collins), a minister, and Annie
(Catherine Hicks). Though the show is produced by Aaron Spelling,
noted jigglemeister and teen-soap impresario, by his standards it's
downright wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   So is Watson, who came to Hollywood in 1989 at age 15 _ and
promptly turned tail and returned to his Texas home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too young,'' he admits today.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, he gave acting another shot
and, after appearing on shows such as ``Malibu Shores,''
``Baywatch'' and ``The Nanny,'' landed in ``Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is just a lead-up to the real scoop on Watson,
which is the matter of Bucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got everybody calling me `Bucky' on `7th Heaven,''' he
explains, ``because Stephen Collins and I kind of get away from
what's scripted sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this whole thing for a spin-off called `Bucky and the
Rev,''' he continues deadpan, ``where he and I are on the streets
fighting crime. He calls me Bucky and he's the Rev, so it's Bucky
and the Rev. And this is a story line I would like to get on the
show _ when the cops can't get it done, they call Bucky and the
Rev.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson brought Bucky with him to the set of ``Mrs. Tingle,''
written and directed by Kevin Williamson, creator of ``Dawson's
Creek'' and screenwriter of ``Scream'' (1996) and ``Scream 2''
(1997). ``Dawson'' debutante Katie Holmes stars as an honors
student alternately menaced by and menacing an uptight teacher
played by Helen Mirren.
</P>
<P>
   Mirren may be a highly respected veteran of the prestigious
British stage _ and the popular ``Prime Suspect'' television series
_ but she got the point of Bucky immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been called Bucky on the set, Helen is now Lulu,''
he says. ``And don't tell Stephen Collins this, but she wants to do
a spin-off called `Bucky and Lulu.' And I kind of like it better,
because I think that Helen could kick Stephen Collins' ass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing a big struggle scene with her, and Helen was
slapping me around,'' he adds, laughing. ``My jaw is just finally
feeling better from a week and a half ago. So maybe I might say,
`Screw Stephen,' and have `Bucky and Lulu.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, who wants to see a reverend fight crime?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there was ``The Father Dowling Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' he admits. ``Actually, you know what? I think
Tom Bosley might kick Stephen's ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Given all this, you might gather that Watson would be something
of a handful on a wholesome, religious-themed show such as ``7th
Heaven.'' And he does seem to bristle at its conventions, though he
admires its sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ```7th Heaven' is what it is, and it's a great show,'' he says.
``We've done some really, really great episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it can only go so far,'' he adds. ``You can only go so far
with certain scripts, because the audience wants to laugh or they
want to cry, and they want to see something sweet at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ministers have kids,'' Watson says, ``and their kids are going
to act wild and do stupid things. I haven't got to the point yet
where my character's doing stuff that's really rebellious, even
though I'm supposed to be the rebel of the show. I'm still
waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebellious like what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to kill the dog,'' he says deadpan. ``I wanna kill. I
want Matt Camden to kill Happy and not care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have all these letters from animal-rights activists, and I
love animals _ but I just think it'd be funny if I killed the
dog,'' he says gleefully. ``I see Emmy-award-winning show right
there, all over the place!''
</P>
<P>
   It might even be edgy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
