<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOPNOTCH-TRAVEL-WEB-SITES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND  
 21 WEB SITES FOR TRAVEL IN '99 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As the Web has grown, so have the number of Web sites promising
us ways to travel cheaper, faster and better. But between the
promise and the reality, there's a wide gulf indeed. Here are 21
sites that are really worth consulting before hitting the road in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. BizTravel.com (www.biztravel.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This site is fast, informed and efficient. While it's made a
name for itself among the laptop-toting road warriors who populate
airports everywhere, it's also pretty good for leisure travelers.
</P>
<P>
   For do-it-yourselfers who enjoy planning their own flights,
finding their own hotel accommodations and choosing restaurants
from a remarkably diverse and well-informed database, this is one
of the best.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. Expedia (www.expedia.com), 3. Preview Travel
(www.previewtravel.com) 4. Travelocity (www.travelocity.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expedia is Microsoft's on-line travel agency. Preview is the
preferred on-line travel agency of AOL users. Travelocity is owned
by American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   They're all front-runners in the do-it-yourself travel-agent
sites. They can all be used to book an entire vacation, from
airline seats to hotel rooms and car rentals. Each one offers
deals, sale fares and specials.
</P>
<P>
   They all feature fare finders and can be used to find
consolidator fares, get maps and keep track of frequent-flier
miles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. WebFlyer (www.webflyer.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether its frequent-flier program reviews, updates or changes,
tips on getting more for your miles or planning a trip around those
ubiquitous blackout dates, WebFlyer, the Web site of InsideFlyer
Magazine, is the best site around.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. American Airlines (www.aa.com), 7. Continental
(www.flycontinental.com) and 8. United Airlines (www.ual.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These sites are the domestic carriers with the most
forward-thinking Web sites, offering weekly specials via their Web
sites or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   On the sites, it's easy to check schedules, fares and, in the
case of Continental, get rewarded with bonus miles for booking
online.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. Sidewalk (www.sidewalk.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although somewhat limited in breadth, Sidewalk provides detailed
music, restaurant, sightseeing and shopping listings for Boston,
Chicago, Denver, Houston, Minneapolis/St. Paul, New York City, San
Diego, San Francisco, Seattle, Sydney and Washington DC. It aims to
be a city magazine. It's not quite there yet, but it's not bad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. Digital Cities (digitalcities.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving Sidewalk a real run for its money, this may be the best
city guide on the Web, with 57 cities and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Go into the New York site, for example, and get food maven Ed
Levine on bagels, ``Passport to New York'' restaurant reviews and
tips on where to buy electronics.
</P>
<P>
   There are no hotels here, but there is plenty of local insight
on dining, shopping and movies with links to local papers and local
reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 11. Fodor's (www.fodors.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Craving a steakhouse during a trip to Grand Canyon National
Park? Want to know if the Sheraton in downtown Anchorage has a
health club? Curious about the best way to bring Spot on an
airplane? This remarkably well-organized and detailed site can
answer all these questions and many more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 12. Rough Guides (http://travel.roughguides.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This provides instant access to the Rough Guides travel guide
series, which are written with the independent traveler in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 13. Time Out (www.timeout.co.uk) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go to a site that has an English flair. This site takes the best
of Time Out's really good city guides and city listing magazines
and puts them on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 14. AutoPilot (www.freetrip.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get lost with AutoPilot, which can give fast and
accurate driving directions from point A to point B in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 15. GORP (www.gorp.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GORP is the acronym for the Great Outdoors Recreation Pages. A
lively mix of travelogue, gear choices and suggestions for skiers,
bikers, hikers, sea kayakers and virtually anyone else who loves to
be in the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 16. SkiNet (www.skinet.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The site of Ski and Skiing magazines offers one-stop shopping
for snow conditions, equipments queries and travel tips.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 17. Quikbook (www.quikbook.com), 18. Express Reservations
(www.express- res.com) and 19. Hotel Reservations Network
(www.180096hotel.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These are three of the best hotel brokers in the country.
They're good for finding discounts on big city hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 20. State Department (www.travel.state.gov/travel_warning.html) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel safely by scanning the official site of the State
Department before going. Here's where to learn about the political
situation and street crime conditions in every country from
Afghanistan to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   It offers Consular Information Sheets for each country,
including the location of the U.S. Embassy or Consulate, health
conditions, minor political disturbances, entry regulations as well
as crime and security information. There are also Travel Warnings,
which are issued when the State Department decides that Americans
should avoid travel to a certain country.
</P>
<P>
   These currently include such countries as Algeria, Colombia,
Iraq and Sudan. There are Public Announcements as well, which
signal short-term trouble in various parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 21. TheTrip.Com (www.thetrip.com) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wondering when a flight will arrive? This site shows, in
