<HEADER>
A7841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ANIMATION-HNS &LR;      01-11 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDY MARKS ITS GOLDEN AGE ON TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television is lame. There is nothing new. Been there, seen that.
The half-hour comedy is dead.
</P>
<P>
   All true, to a point. But there are fleshed-out sitcom
characters; they're just not flesh and blood.
</P>
<P>
   We are, in fact, in a comedic golden age. With all due apologies
to Walt Disney, Chuck Jones and the giants of the 1930s and '40s,
we are now in an unsurpassed time for animation. This goes for
television as well as the movies.
</P>
<P>
   And we mean prime-time television, not the hyped-up Saturday
morning fare for the Cocoa Puffs crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoons allow writers to go to bizarre yet cogent extremes to
either make a point or get a laugh. Although the hyper-realism is
effective in animation, these outer limits just wouldn't work in
live-action comedies. Really, would you like to see the same
character savagely murdered and eaten by rats in a sitcom week
after week?
</P>
<P>
   Yet it works on ``South Park.'' To the list of worthy prime-time
animated comedies you can add two more: ``The PJs,'' which debuted
Sunday night on Fox and will run Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m. Eastern
(check local listings) starting this week, and ``Dilbert,'' based
on the classic comic strip, which instantly becomes one of UPN's
best shows when it debuts Monday, Jan. 25, at 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PJs'' is a funny, acerbic look at inner-city life using
the technology of foamation puppets and created by Eddie Murphy.
Murphy stars as the voice of Thurgood Stubbs, the cranky
superintendent of the Hilton-Jacobs Projects. And the
three-dimensional characters themselves sort of look like the
``California Raisins'' from those commercials of a decade or so
ago, especially since they come from the same production company.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Dilbert,'' if you ever read the comic strip about
office-life dysfunction, you will be up to speed on this animated
show. The comic strip and half-hour cartoon are virtually the same
_ except it is a lot harder to clip out a television show and tape
it to your cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   The two new shows join an already formidable list of nighttime
animated/Claymated offerings (arguably) being made for adults.
Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``South Park'' (Comedy Central): Crude, rude, and, at its
best, the funniest show on television. The show is struggling to
retain its first-year brilliance of last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Space Ghost Coast to Coast'' (Cartoon Network): My favorite
childhood cartoon (after, of course, my favorite actor ever, Bugs
Bunny) is now my favorite late night talk-show host on Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Celebrity Death Match'' (MTV): Hanson and the Spice Girls
literally eviscerate one another. Now that's entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``King of the Hill'' (Fox): You know Hank Hill. He lives down
the street from you, on the left. Yeah, that guy.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bob and Margaret'' and ``Dr. Katz, Professional Therapist''
(Comedy Central): Cartoons for adults who really are adults.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't mentioned the grandaddy, a show that has been
around since few in the country heard of Bill Clinton. Not only is
this comedy legendary animation, but it should now be examined in
the historical context as one of the greatest comedies in
television annals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' has been around nine years now, five years past
the expected lifetime of a sitcom. What makes the run astonishing
is that the show has gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Sunday night staple, which grew out of a ``Tracey Ullman
Show'' skit, is now in syndication. Compare its new episodes with
ones of say, 1996: It's no contest. Today's Homer and crew win.
</P>
<P>
   There really is no time comparable to today: the 1962 season
comes closest with ``The Flintstones,'' ``The Jetsons,'' and the
lesser ``Beany &AMP; Cecil.''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, for us nostalgic types, we have the whole Cartoon
Network, while Nickelodeon scores big with ``Rugrats'' (which
premieres a new season, and new baby Dil Jan. 18 at 8 p.m.
Eastern), ``Doug'' and ``Hey Arnold!''
</P>
<P>
   So remember that great television comedy is not dead. It's just
not real _ yet more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
