<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EC-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION SCANDAL JOLTS EUROPEAN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Throughout its history, the central government of the
European Union has been one big yawn.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Today, staid Brussels is simmering with scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission, the bureaucracy that runs the EU, has
been rocked by charges of corruption, nepotism, and sleazy politics
reminiscent of New York City's Tammany Hall machine or Boston's
city government under James Michael Curley. About $5 billion of
last year's $107 billion budget cannot be accounted for. There are
assertions that untold billions have been squandered in fraud and
contracts to companies cozy with or related to some of the 20
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the European Parliament will vote whether to
dismiss the 20-member commission over the issue. The balloting
ensures that this situation will be considered the first major
corruption scandal to hit the European Union since the French
visionary Jean Monnet dreamed it up over 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, members of the European Parliament demanded that
two of the commissioners at the center of the allegations step down
to avoid Thursday's vote. Under European Union guidelines aimed at
avoiding factionalism, the Parliament cannot fire individual
commissioners but can vote out the entire commission.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Cresson, the former French prime minister who is now in
charge of education for the European Union, and Manuel Marin, who
heads the European Union's Third World development arm, refused to
resign, saying they have done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has been bubbling for months, but it exploded last
month when a Dutch auditor working for the commission sent a
34-page report to the Parliament charging that commissioners were
awarding contracts to friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament responded by refusing to approve the European
Commission's account of how it spent its 1996 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners created even more enemies when they responded by
suspending the whistleblower, Paul van Buitenen, a civil servant
who says his only motivation is being an ``honest man.''
Commissioners said van Buitenen violated rules by leaking the
information.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension infuriated most of the 626-member Parliament,
though it remains unclear if there exists the two-thirds majority
necessary to get rid of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could not be worse, with the European Union just
embarking on its most ambitious effort yet to create a United
States of Europe: the launch of a single currency in 11 of the 15
European Union countries. Already, those Britons opposed to Britain
joining the single currency have pointed to the scandal as evidence
that the nation would be unwise to surrender more of its
sovereignty to a bunch of corrupt bureaucrats in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Denman, the Englishman who served as the European
Commission's representative in Washington, said it would be foolish
for his countrymen to avoid further European integration because of
the scandal. If anything, Denman said, it is extraordinary that
there has not een a major scandal before.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the former lecturer at the Kennedy School of Government
at Harvard University does not dismiss the seriousness of the
scandal. He considers it, however, an inevitable part of the
maturation process of the European Union. And he sees the scandal's
roots not with Jacques Santer, the current European Commission
president, but with Santer's predecessor, Jacques Delors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delors was very good at politics. He wasn't good at
administration,'' said Denman.
</P>
<P>
   Denman said the scandal is a warning to the EU that it had
better implement tough sanctions for fraud and mismanagement found
within national governments or forego popular support for the
assumption of more responsibilities currently held by the national
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   This unfolding saga is as intriguing as Edwin O'Connor's ``The
Last Hurrah,'' the novel based on Curley's corrupt machine in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buitenen, who emerged from obscurity when he became the
whistleblower, asserted last  &UR; week &LR;  that his telephone was tapped
and that he was being followed by European Commission security
guards who trained rifles with telescopic lenses on him. He said he
fears for his life and has moved his family out of their home here.
</P>
<P>
   Cresson, 65, has always been mired in controversy. She once
suggested that most Englishmen are homosexual, and compared the
Japanese to ants. She dismisses allegations that staffers in her
department were routinely awarding contracts to friends and family
are part of a smear campaign against her.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the normally mild-mannered Santer was stunned
when the press conference he called here to defend his commission
was turned into an inquisition on his wife's real estate holdings.
A Belgian reporter asked if he had any comment about reports that
police in Luxembourg, where Santer was once prime minister, were
looking into claims of financial improprieties surrounding three
homes that the Santers own in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   At that same press conference, Finnish commission member Erkki
Liikanen defended his wife against charges that she is benefiting
from a contract she secured on behalf of the Finnish government
from the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Santer dared members of Parliament to censure him
and the commission. Now, his planned address to the Parliament may
be the only way to prevent the dismissal of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's defenders, including Alan Donnelly, leader of
the British Labour delegation in Strasbourg, insist that this is a
case of sloppy administration, not greed-driven corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Donnelly acknowledges that the commission has reform
itself. ``The commission,'' he said, ``has to realize that it has
to make a substantial improvement in its procedures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
