<SLUG> BC-SCI-GUAM-CALENDAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUAM CAVE SCENE MAY BE ANCIENT CALENDAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Newly discovered cave paintings on the Pacific
island of Guam show what may be the earliest depictions of
astronomical knowledge recorded in that region, an astronomer
reported here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings, discovered just six weeks ago during a hike in
the countryside by University of Guam astronomer Rosina Iping, show
people gazing at specific constellations of stars and at what may
be a depiction of a unique 16-month calendar used by some early
Micronesian navigators.
</P>
<P>
   Iping described her findings here at a meeting of the American
Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings are of particular interest because they represent
a separate and unusual development of astronomical knowledge and a
calendar very different from those developed in other early
cultures in China, Europe, and the Middle East. For one thing,
these early navigators, who routinely crossed wide stretches of
open ocean, developed a highly unusual calendar based on the
positions of stars. Most other peoples around the world based their
calendars on the movements of the sun or moon.
</P>
<P>
   The cave paintings have not yet been dated, but certainly were
made before the first Spanish ships arrived in the region five
centuries ago and may be far older, Iping said. Anthropologists
estimate that Guam was first populated at least 3,500 years ago by
the Chamorro people, whose paintings have been found in numerous
caves on the island and on other islands in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The cave that Iping stumbled upon while hiking on Guam's north
coast turned out to be one that was apparently used as an ancient
burial site, and she found some small fragments of human bone in
the dirt of the cave floor. There were also fragments of pottery of
a style that is known to predate European contact, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A laboratory at the University of Georgia is now working on
dating pottery fragments from the cave, which were found close to
the newly discovered paintings. Archeologists have already examined
the paintings and confirmed their authenticity as ancient Chamorro
art, Iping said.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Chamorro 16-month calendar was part of a body of
secret navigational lore that was passed along from father to son
for centuries by the Chamorros. Historian Vince Diaz of the
University of Guam has recorded many of the details of this ancient
lore through interviews with a present-day traditional navigator,
one of the last of his kind, on the nearby island of Puluwak, where
the ancient methods are still practiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old navigators never wrote anything down,'' Iping said.
``It was a secret knowledge passed along to the sons,'' in a series
of lessons, known as ``unfolding the mat,'' that led to becoming a
palu, or navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Their unusual calendar included a year divided into 16 months of
unequal length, based on the different constellations that were
visible above the eastern horizon just before dawn. Similarly, it
was the constellations seen rising or setting over different parts
of the horizon that provided key directional information to the
traditional navigators to guide them to specific islands. This was
combined with a knowledge of currents, marine animals, reefs, and
waves and methods for estimating distance traveled and the effects
of drift to guide the ancient navigators to their destinations
across vast stretches of ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Among the paintings Iping found in the cave were a series of 16
circular markings across the cave wall and 16 more arranged
vertically. Because the number 16 had such significance for the
local people's reckoning of the passage of the year, Iping said,
``it's clear to me that it's a calendar.'' In the 16 unequal months
of their system, she said, the year began with the winter solstice,
marked by the constellation of Aquarius above the eastern horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Another painting in the cave, close to the calendar markings,
depicts a person looking at the clearly depicted constellations of
Cassiopeia and the Southern Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
