<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-IMAGE-BOS &LR;      01-11 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-IMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT LIGHTS, DIM HOPES IN THE CITY OF LITTLE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Why is it that most observers thought Mayor Thomas M.
Menino was off his rocker last year when he suggested that Boston
should host the Democratic National Convention in August 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of events always go to other cities, people thought.
Bigger cities, ones with more clout, like New York, Chicago, or Los
Angeles, itself a strong candidate to get the convention. Or,
displaying a certain smugness, people said the big events go to
cities like Atlanta, Miami, or Houston that need the convention
trade to distinguish themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But many Boston natives, longtime residents, and pundits still
wisecrack that this city is either incapable or unworthy of hosting
such an event.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention, which is to be awarded next month,
will propel the host city into the national spotlight for nearly a
week. As many as 40,000 people will spend about $150 million on
hotels, food, drink, and transportation. About 15,000 attendees
will be members of the press. If the convention comes, the focus on
Boston will be very different from other times the press has
descended on the city in recent years, to cover the trial of Louise
Woodward, murders at women's health clinics, or the Charles Stuart
case.
</P>
<P>
   This time there'd be little negativity, just the
well-choreographed celebratory glow of warm summer downtown days
and cool waterfront nights in arguably Boston's best season.
</P>
<P>
   Menino, in fact, argues that this city is a laboratory for the
Democratic programs pushed by President Clinton and Vice President
Al Gore. He says the city can show off lower crime rates due in
part to community policing, can boast a cleaner harbor, improved
schools, and an entrepreneurial zeal in everything from software to
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   But our civic psyche is so downbeat that we don't dare to think
that Boston will get the brass ring (any more than we think the Red
Sox will win the World Series or the Patriots stay in
Massachusetts), even though the city has gone from being one of 28
wannabes to one of three finalists; even though the city upped its
ante by $1 million last week in an effort to knock the competing
bids by LA and Denver out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Boston needs to get the Democratic convention for a reason
that has nothing to do with money or publicity. Maybe it needs it
so that Bostonians can feel better about their own city. If others
come to Boston and revel in its beauty, its accessibility by foot,
its tidy neighborhoods, as thousands of curious visitors do in
every season, then maybe we will start to value more highly what we
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that we are in the same league, if
not as New York and Los Angeles, then certainly as San Francisco,
New Orleans, and Philadelphia,'' says Jerome Rogoff, a Newton
psychiatrist. ``We are a very big city in terms of population and
the money that is here, but it is very curious why we shy away from
these things. I know from my own experience with the American
Psychiatric Association, I go to all of their conferences and they
have been in every major city but Boston. Why do we hide like that?
I wonder if there is some kind of mass inferiority complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, a lifelong Massachusetts resident and outgoing
national chairman of the Democratic National Committee _ which,
with Colorado Governor Roy Romer, its general chairman, and with
input from party politicians _ will decide where the convention is
held, said Boston just does not think of itself as ready for prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the weather, maybe it's the long shadow cast by New
York City, but Boston doesn't expect to win. We get baseball's
All-Star Game this summer, but it's been so long since it was here
last (39 years), even that seems like a mirage. And, we all know
the only reason Major League Baseball decided to come back to
Boston was to say goodbye to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, Boston has not seen itself as a city that
could compete and win at the highest levels for some of the biggest
prizes,'' says Grossman. ``It was often `When we have a new
convention center . . .' and `If we have a new stadium . . .' When
and if.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Hynes Convention Center is considered too
small for many conventions, and the old Boston Garden was not
air-conditioned, which made holding a summertime convention there
highly improbable. And when the bid to host the convention was
announced last January, Boston was considered a longshot because of
its lack of hotel rooms and the scars of the Big Dig (another
program that shows government money in action).
</P>
<P>
   While Boston is filled with history and many firsts _ from the
telephone to the US subway _ our Puritan heritage may make it
unseemly to extol those facts. But there may be more to Boston's
traditional reluctance to vie against other cities for convention
riches and positive publicity: fear of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why so many people think the convention will go to
Los Angeles for political reasons. Massachusetts, after all, is an
unchallenged Democratic stronghold; California, on the other hand,
is the nation's richest electoral prize with 54 votes _ and its
first Democratic governor in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a natural tendency to sort of prepare yourself for
the worst,'' says Philip Levendusky, a psychologist and vice
president of network development at McLean Hospital in Belmont.
``If we are rejected, it can be a real slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   And if, by chance, Boston does happen to win, conventional
wisdom locally has it that our good fortune will not be because the
city is a jewel that deserves to host such an event, but rather
because Grossman and US Senator Edward M. Kennedy somehow pulled
the requisite strings.
</P>
<P>
   Levendusky says that logic comes from avoiding presenting the
city as a wonderful, livable place with friendly inhabitants and
great architecture and natural beauty, because if we are rejected
after that kind of promotion, then it would be almost too much to
bear. Yet Hollywood, that beachhead of trendiness, has found the
Boston area plenty attractive recently, setting _ and shooting _
films here ranging from ``Good Will Hunting'' to ``Next Stop
Wonderland'' to ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also that aspect to the legendary provincial smugness
of some Bostonians that states the Athens of America doesn't need a
National Football League franchise nor a Democratic National
Convention to prove how great we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugness like that often is defensive,'' says Rogoff. ``It can
mask an inferiority feeling: that we don't quite measure up to the
big time. We are not in the big time and may not want to be in the
big time, because it is so much better to be small, and excellent
and pure.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino, however, the ultimate local mayor, is out there leading
with his heart and his chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sometimes sell ourselves short,'' Menino says. ``I visited
Atlanta, and they were so boastful about what they had. But then
they tell you not to leave the hotel and walk around at night
because it is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really opened my eyes that any convention for Boston is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino says he felt initial reluctance from various businesses
and groups whose support he needed to make Boston's bid viable.
``It was like they had to do this, because the mayor was asking
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That Boston could host such a big event seemed to many, well,
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought it was beyond belief,'' says Patrick
Moscaritolo, president of the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau. ``It was more hype, more political rhetoric. I actually
think that many of the people from the on-site selection committee
probably felt that as well. Well, guess what? Boston is still in
the running.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said Menino had a stroke of brilliance in promoting
Boston during the site commitee visit. He took members on an early
morning walking tour of the city and ``they were blown away by the
experience,'' Grossman recalled.
</P>
<P>
   If Boston should get the convention, the boost to civic pride
would be incalculable. And perhaps our appreciation of history and
who we are would grow as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our claims to fame are relatively subtle and highly
sophisticated,'' says Levendusky. ``There is our education system,
particulary the universities, and no one can rival us. But after
that, the list sort of runs out. We have a nice coastline and we
are near Cape Cod, and it is a pretty city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bragging rights that would come along with'' landing the
convention, he says, ``the self-esteem and personal pride, it would
buoy people's moods and put a spring in our step. Anytime a city is
able to garner that positive notoriety, it has a tremendous effect
on the populace.''
</P>
<P>
   For some observers, just competing hard and getting this far has
resulted in a more positive, congenial attitude in Boston's
business community, where turf wars often have impeded progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of how we view ourselves and how we compete, this
will go down in the books as a high point, at a time when Boston
looked at itself and said, `The mayor is right. We can do this,' ''
says Moscaritolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the ultimate outcome,'' says Grossman, ``Boston
is already a winner because this has thrust Boston into the highest
rank of American convention cities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-BRUSTEIN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     01-11 1798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BRUSTEIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... Beckett plays.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Just to pin down your aesthetic. Some people have said that
the Huntington is more of a writer's theater and ART more of a
director's theater. Is that a simplification?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think there's any truth in it. We wouldn't have a
permanent company of actors if we were a director's theater. Our
actors are not here simply to serve directors, they're here to
expand their artistry and insofar as directors can help them,
that's great. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, if you look at the roster of playwrights that we have
both produced and discovered, I think you'll find that we have a
fairly distinguished group of writers in our stable as it were.
Writers love to be produced here and are welcome here and we
cherish playwrights supremely and we exist as a theater to serve
playwrights, and to serve texts. There's never been any question
about that. . . . We've done plays by most of the major playwrights
and we've never done ``A Christmas Carol'' or Gilbert and Sullivan,
so I don't think that's an accurate way of describing us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Talk a little bit then about how directors have freedom to
play with the text.
</P>
<P>
   A. Our main function with classical text, which I assume is what
you're talking about, our main function is to get to the spirit of
the work. The worst way to (do that) is to put on a traditional,
literal rendering of the work from another language or another age.
That's what's known as deadly theater. That's what Peter Brook
called it, and that's what it is. You ought to have your detectors
out when you see it, too, because it's deadening all of us, it's
destroying our souls. I find bad theater, deadly theater, is more
destructive of my spirit than almost anything I can think of. I
think that's why people have so little tolerance for theater as
opposed to the movies. The movies are very rarely deadly in the way
that theater is deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Theater is deadly when it is too respectful, when it is too
orthodox, when it is too conventional, and when it thinks it's
performing a good deed when it thinks it's sticking to the absolute
letter as written. I just don't believe this. I think the way to
bring a text to life is to treat it as if it has just been written,
to ignore all previous productions, to act as if a play of
Shakespeare or Moliere or Racine had just come across the literary
desk for the first time and you're looking at it and think it's
terrific and you want to find a way to put it on. That means
cutting through all the contrivances and all the conventions and
all the orthodox ways it had been done in the past and trying to
imagine what the playwright had in mind when he wrote it. That
comes out differently than most classical productions do. As far as
taking liberties with works from another language, I think the same
thing is true.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So would you position yourself 180 degrees from Harold Bloom,
who says that high-concept directors are the curse of Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on which director. There are high-concept
directors who I think are the curse. But he said that he saw two
dreadful productions of ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' in his life.
One was Peter Brook's great circus production, and the other was
Alvin Epstein's and I know you saw that and approved of it. For
Harold to go to that production and say it was one of the two worst
productions he'd ever seen in his life, he must be bats. He's
theater-deaf. I had this conversation with him actually down in
Princeton (N.J.). I pleaded with him to realize that Shakespeare's
not Shakespeare until he's acted on the stage. He's not meant for
reading, he's meant for the stage . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was on a cable TV show with Elliot Norton and he singled
you out for going beyond naturalism and demanding more of
audiences. I think he speaks for a lot of people for whom ART
symbolizes excitement and daring. There are a lot of other people I
talk to who say they've canceled their subscriptions because of
some of the things we've just talked about, the liberties taken
with classics, or a style that might be too avant-garde or
emotionally detached. What are your critics missing?
</P>
<P>
   A. &UR;  &LR; With us, audiences are always going to have split opinions.
If they don't, we're not doing our job. Any work that has any
ambitions, that's advanced in any way, is going to divide an
audience. Any new idea divides an audience. We have to accept that
as a faith. It's not something I want. I would prefer unanimous
praise and a full house and a wild box office. But if we're going
to be true to our calling, we have to accept the fact that some
people are not going to like what they see. And other people are
going to be ecstatic about it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we do a play that gets middle reactions, and that
makes me think we're not doing our job, if everyone's mildly
amused; the word ``middle'' just bothers me. I don't like
middle-brow theater. I don't like middle-class theater. I don't
like middle-age theater. I just don't like the word ``middle.'' I
think it's got to be either high or low. Or both. Shakespeare mixed
his genres. He had low clowns and he had kings and queens and
aspiring heroes and he didn't see anything wrong with mixing these
two. The one time he wrote a middle play was ``Merry Wives of
Windsor,'' and he wrote a real middle-class play because Elizabeth
wanted him to write another play about Falstaff and it was a
disaster. It was the worst play he ever wrote because his heart
wasn't in it. So I think it's inevitable that we're going to have
our critics, as you say, and I would just hope that they would
reflect on what's getting them so upset and see that maybe we've
touched something in them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have a number of distinguished alumni, Cherry Jones being
the obvious one. Will we see her back at the ART?
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh yeah, she'll definitely come back. She's a very beloved
friend and she almost came back for ``How I Learned to Drive.'' She
was originally cast in that. We chose it for her. She loved the
play, but she got this movie and she couldn't do it. . . . We'll
find ways of getting all the alumni back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How about directors? Have &UR;  &LR; people like Robert Wilson and
Julie Taymor priced themselves beyond . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. No, we're talking to Robert Wilson right now about a
production of (Strindberg's) ``A Dream Play,'' which we hope he'll
be able to do next season. I had talked to him about it some years
ago and he's done it now in Stockholm and he wants to do it for us.
He's the perfect director for that play. Julie Taymor probably has
a schedule that's full now until the third millennium, but she
remains a very close friend and I'm sure if she has something open
in her schedule, she'll come up here and do something with us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Reflect on the productions that you're most proud of.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's like asking which of your children you love the most.
But I think `` 'night, Mother'' is a play I'm very proud to have
produced. It was turned down by about 30 theaters before we got it.
There was every reason in the world for us not to do it. It was a
kitchen play, a realistic play, but it was a damn good play and I
thought it had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   I like a lot of the work that Bob Wilson has done for us,
particularly ``the CIVIL warS'' and ``Alcestis.'' (Andrei) Serban's
productions for us are some of the best classical productions done
in this country, sometimes in the world. I know that sounds
hyperbolic, but I think he is a world-class director, particularly
of Shakespeare. His ``Twelfth Night'' was exquisite, his
``Sganarelle'' was marvelous, his ``King Stag'' was terrific. I
thought his ``Taming of the Shrew'' was great. Richard Eder said
his ``Merchant of Venice'' was the best Shakespeare he ever saw. I
know you didn't like it (laughs).
</P>
<P>
   I like (Andrei) Belgrader's work. He's a great farceur, he finds
that area where farce and dreams meet. . . . I thought Ron
Daniels's ``Henry'' trilogy was stunning. ``Henry V'' was as
beautiful as anything I've seen, although the GI analogy was stupid
and exactly the kind of Shakespeare I don't like, that tries to set
it in a different time. Serban's Shakespeares sometimes seem to be
set in modern time, but they're not, they're set in panhistorical
time. They may be modern clothes, but there are also traditional
clothes or historical clothes as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Jungle of Cities'' was a very powerful production. The
first ``Waiting for Godot'' we did, Belgrader's, was an
extraordinary young ``Godot'' in the same way that David Wheeler's
was an extraordinary old ``Godot.'' It was nice to be able to do
those two versions. I'm very proud of the new plays we've done.
(Novelist) Don DeLillo's ``Day Room'' was as good a first play as
any that's been done since Sheridan's ``The Rivals.'' It's very
hard to write a good first play. That was a beauty. It's wonderful
to get a writer to move out of his normal field of accomplishment
and into the theater. Because we need the best writers we can get,
and there are certain novelists who are instinctive dramatists.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet's work with us is something we're very proud of and
cherish. We're happy we've become his first home. This was the
proper place to launch ``Oleanna,'' with that wall of political
correctness; it was perfect as far as starting that talk, that
debate. We also value Anna Deavere Smith's presence here. It's not
yet produced any works of art, but it will.
</P>
<P>
   (Brustein later added to the list of favorite productions the
pairing of ``King Stag'' and ``Six Characters in Search of an
Author'' that the company takes on tour as well as the operas of
Philip Glass.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What happens to the ART after Robert Brustein?
</P>
<P>
   A. It will be in good hands . . . I've been just the caretaker
of this place and it needs a younger caretaker at some point, not
in the immediate future, but soon. I hope I'll have some say in who
that person is, and I hope whoever it is will maintain the idea of
a company and obviously will have a whole aesthetic of her own or
his own to express. But I hope it will be a challenging one that
will continue to ask a lot of audiences and will draw on the great
good will that we've been experiencing for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   I'm full of gratitude to this area for effectively being the
best audience we ever hoped to play to. We go places where we get
standing ovations and we get this cyclical applause in Russia that
signifies you've got something terrific. This audience is not
demonstative, but it is as brilliant, as intelligent in its
responses, and as in tune with what you're doing as any in the
world. We've found our audience and I'm full of praise for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
