u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORRECTIVE-WALKER-BOS     01-11 0139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIVE-WALKER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Eds.: Newspapers that used the Boston Globe story WALKER-COLUMN
(k) by ADRIAN-WALKER, which moved Jan. 8, will wish to use the
following corrective.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Globe column by Adrian Walker stated incorrectly that
former Senate President William M. Bulger was among a number of
legislators fined in 1992 by the Massachusetts Ethics Commission,
and that the commission's budget was then promptly cut. Bulger has
never been fined by the Commission. Fourteen past and present
legislators were fined as a result of activities in 1992, but the
fines were imposed in 1994 and 1995. Although the House attempted
to cut the commission's budget in 1995, the Senate, then headed by
Bulger, resisted the cut. The funding was restored by a
House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DVD-BOS &LR;      01-11 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DVD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVED QUALITY, HIGHER SALES FUEL VHS, DVD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually everyone in the movie business is smiling. Theatrical
releases for 1998 reached an all-time high of $6.97 billion, as
estimated by the Hollywood Reporter. Ticket sales nearly reached
the 1.5 billion mark, the highest since the late '50s.
</P>
<P>
   And the home video business is doing even better. Early last
year, the gross revenues for movies on home video surpassed the
income generated by a film's release in theaters. Now, the home
market is leading the way. Sales and rentals of VHS and DVD for
1998 are now estimated at nearly $9 billion and that figures to
climb exponentially this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the home video business, long the
evolutionary inferior to its big screen brother, is asserting
itself _ in a big way. And they plan to ride a new technology into
the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, about a half-dozen industry analysts and
officials said that no one believes home video will ever replace
cinemas. But the additional financial clout may create shorter
windows between a theatrical release and availability on home video
with some suggesting that there may come a day when a film is
released simultaneously in theaters and on home video.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, theater owners took the patron for granted,
refusing to upgrade their houses,'' said a retired studio executive
who asked that his name not be used. ``Because of the pressure from
home video, many new megaplexes come with stadium seating and
terrific sound. It's like the early days of TV when the wide-screen
was used to get people out of the house. The success of the home
market has really helped everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   To add a further boost to the burgeoning marketplace, DVD
(digital versatile disc) has taken the industry by storm.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Truman Show'' comes out on home video on Tuesday , it
will be sold on VHS with a price tag in the $90 range. But, on the
same day, it will be released on DVD for sale in the $25 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popularity of the DVD format caught everyone a little bit
by surprise,'' said David Miller, marketing head for MGM.
``Everyone from the filmmakers to film buffs are excited by the
format. It took a while to get started, but it's now the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is particularly excited because it puts MGM in an
enviable position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a terrific library with all the MGM wide-screen
classics and musicals that look and sound great on DVD,'' he said.
``And the added features help as well.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, technology restrained the home video market. The VHS
soundtracks couldn't match the Dolby digital and Surroundsound of
megaplexes, and images were mushy compared to their theatrical
counterpart. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   DVD, the visual equivalent of an audio CD, has a superior image
and sound but what really enhances the format are the additional
features. Most titles come with subtitles in Spanish and French, so
they can be shipped internationally at no additional expense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two versions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Hitchcock's ``Strangers on a Train'' features the shorter
American version on side A of the disc while the British version,
with a different ending, is on side B. Take your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' looks and sounds
clearer on DVD than its original release in Cinerama. The disc,
picking up 40,000 bits of information per second, actually exposes
some of the process shots used in the Dawn of Man sequence. The
faraway mountains look like painted backdrops so, sometimes, too
much additional information can break down cinema's illusory
powers.
</P>
<P>
   In Hitchcock's ``Psycho,'' Universal includes an in-depth
documentary with extensive interviews with screenwriter Joseph
Stefano and star Janet Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing that makes DVDs so attractive is the price,''
said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   While many retail video stores feature DVDs, including HMV,
Tower, and Best Buy, the Internet's Amazon.com, Reel.com, and
Netflix.com are also ready to serve and ship with a credit card and
a click of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   While many titles retail for $29.95, the Internet providers
offer deep discounts. Reel.com, for example, has many titles for
$14.95 plus $3.95 for shipping. They also included a $5 gift
certificate with several recent orders. They also use Priority mail
so discs arrive within 2 to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   The initial fears that consumers wouldn't welcome a new
technology, especially those who invested in laser discs, have been
put to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to collect these movies,'' said Miller. ``Like
books and music they want to display them as an indication of who
they are _ as an extension of their personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, when you factor in the price of a movie theater ticket at
around $15 a pair plus popcorn and a soft drink and parking, the
price of a DVD can be cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect sales to be up at least another 50 percent by the
end of the year,'' said Reel.com CEO Julie Wainwright. ``It's hard
to keep up with the demand. Frankly, the success of the DVD has
taken everyone by surprise. Thirty-five percent of our December
business was in DVD. The only problem we have now is a
manufacturing one. We stock every title, very deep, in our
warehouse. But the manufacturer can't manufacture them fast enough
to meet the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Divx format
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about Divx?
</P>
<P>
   This format, pushed by the mega-retailer Circuit City, has
encountered some early technical and marketing problems. Originally
designed as an alternative to the video store, the format (which
stands for digital video express) allows the consumer to order a
movie title on a disc that's time-based. The consumer can watch the
movie during a specified period before the content is erased. The
disc also can be purchased if the consumer wishes to add it to his
library. It's a variation on pay-per-view that, so far, lacks
widespread support in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a confusing format that requires a ton of text support
and not one of our customers has ever asked for it,'' said
Wainwright.
</P>
<P>
   DIVX aside, the film industry from top to bottom is smiling. The
time between when a film opens in a theater and is available on DVD
will be shrinking this year and, given the burst of enthusiasm for
the format, thousands of additional titles will become available in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The money is pouring in from all sides. Even the most cynical
commentators don't see it stopping soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
