<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-SATIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAP HAS MALAYSIANS SINGING A NEW TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Malaysia's paternalistic prime
minister, Mahathir Mohamad, has received a lot of bad press lately
for harshly suppressing dissent. Many outsiders, then, might be
surprised to hear the lyrics of Huzir Sulaiman, 25, an actor,
playwright, and rapper who performs at local nightclubs:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm mad as hell, I refuse to shut up
</P>
<P>
   The country I love is totally (expletive) up
</P>
<P>
   If you march in the streets 'cause you can't keep quiet
</P>
<P>
   They'll bash your (expletive) brains out and say that you riot
</P>
<P>
   I am a Malaysian, I love this land
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion the problem is the old man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong stuff only months after Mahathir crippled a fledgling
opposition movement by arresting his rebellious deputy, Anwar
Ibrahim, and putting him on trial on sex and corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time when artistic ferment seems to run parallel to
popular expressions of dissent or unhappiness,'' Sulaiman said.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's guilt or innocence is beside the point to the
middle-class audience listening to Sulaiman at All That Jazz bar.
At issue to them are the rights of average people in Malaysia. If
Anwar, once the nation's second most powerful politician, can be
hauled off in handcuffs, brought to court with a black eye, and
held without bail while a docile press toes the government line,
what could happen to regular citizens?
</P>
<P>
   Yet Malaysia is full of contradictions. Although it has fewer
freedoms than many would like, it has more than Mahathir's critics
acknowledge. It tolerates barbed political satire and, on occasion,
officially sanctions it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Malaysian opposition figures and protesters have been
recently silenced, their calls for greater democracy have found a
powerful voice through art, music, theater, and writing.
</P>
<P>
   An evening of political songs and readings at an upscale pub
hardly seems a petri dish for revolution. The sedate, well-dressed
audience chose the club rather than a protest rally held across
town on this particular night. But programs like this, repeated in
hotel ballrooms, art galleries, and film cafes across the capital
over the past months, reflect a growing discontent among Malaysia's
elite with the political status quo. And that, more than street
protests, could lead to change.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaiman cautioned that artists involved are not necessarily
Anwar supporters. ``Even people staunchly in favor of the prime
minister. . .have concerns about the independence of the judiciary
and the conduct or misconduct of the police; about the increasing
autocracy of the government and the use of Draconian laws,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the art inspired by recent political turmoil is
trenchant and angry, more of it is playful and ridicules authority.
Singer Rafique Rashid spoofs Anwar's ouster over a sex scandal in
``Fifty Ways to Lose Your Leader,'' by adding politicians to his
version of Paul Simon's classic:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just dig up some smut, Mat
</P>
<P>
   Buy a little time, Daim
</P>
<P>
   Don't mess with him, Lim
</P>
<P>
   Just set yourself free.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even allies of greater democracy are not exempt from mockery.
Take Rashid's ``Al Gore Rap,'' inspired by the US vice president's
controversial speech at a dinner here in which he praised
Mahathir's critics:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well I'm the vice president of the United States
</P>
<P>
   My name is Al Gore and I'm here to aggravate
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if you think I'm rude
</P>
<P>
   I got my batik shirt and I'm a real cool dude. . .
</P>
<P>
   So do your `reformasi' now and have no fear
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the satay, I'm outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rashid said it is easy to make his work humorous with material
to work with such as the introduction at Anwar's trial last month
of a purportedly semen-stained mattress. ``You want some real
entertainment?'' he asked. ``Go to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashid and Sulaiman acknowledge that if they tried to perform at
a ``reformasi'' rally or publish in a newspaper, they would
probably be silenced or arrested for sedition. But because their
audiences are mostly sedate professionals, the special police who
monitor their shows have not explicitly tried to gag them.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy provides protection, Rashid said. ``Politicians don't
want to be seen as not having a sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think the government tolerates them to disprove those who
charge that Malaysia stifles free expression. Even as authorities
detained Anwar's top associates and cracked down with water cannon
and batons on street protesters, officials hired an irreverant
comedy troupe to entertain delegates at a recent international
conference _ with the government as the butt of the jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from 21 nations, including the United States,
were flabbergasted when the Instant Cafe Theatre lampooned their
Malaysian hosts at the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum in
November. The delegates all knew of the arrest of Anwar, a
free-marketeer who has many friends in Western governments, and of
the suppression of his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows raised when, to the tune of Gloria Gaynor's ``I Will
Survive,'' performers lambasted Mahathir _ and much of the nation _
for blaming foreign fund managers, such as George Soros, for
Malaysia's economic problems:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We must believe, we are the best
</P>
<P>
   And don't listen to the nasty rumors from the Western press. . .
</P>
<P>
   So we don't cry, 'cause we deny
</P>
<P>
   We'll blame the Jews, La Nina, and we'll tell ourselves more
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When angry Malaysian lawmakers raised in parliament the audacity
of the Instant Cafe Theatre, Mahathir is said to have dismissed the
issue, saying the government has more important things to worry
about than an acting company.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, recounted Jo Kukathas, the Instant Cafe Theatre's
director, the troupe has been summoned by officials who say, ``We
love your show, but maybe you shouldn't mention politics or the
economy.'' But, she said, ``That doesn't make sense, since satire
is what we do. We feel we must do what we do or people will regard
authority as sacred cows, rather than as servants of the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
