<SLUG> BC-NEWNGL-CRIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS EYE ROSY TRENDS IN US CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the United States celebrates newly minted numbers about
safer streets, collared criminals, and a murder rate in startling
free-fall, criminologists warn that all crime _ as the late House
Speaker Tip O'Neill once said of politics _ is local.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, that local story is a civic leader's dream: the
nation's lowest homicide rate, sustaining a trend that has placed
the region among the country's least murderous areas for 12
generations.
</P>
<P>
   But specialists, wary of data blended from Bangor to Burbank,
say New England's sanguinity and the hopeful aggregate figures
nationwide mask pockets of regional violence that defy simple
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   While police commissioners in Boston and New York can trumpet
1997 crime statistics that evoke a 1950s' Ozzie-and-Harriet
tranquility, officials in Baltimore and New Orleans struggle
against a despair reminiscent of the shoot-'em-up '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cultures of violence in the United States,'' said
David Hackett Fischer, a history professor at Brandeis University.
``The difference in rates of violence among different American
regions is greater than those among many European nations.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Massachusetts is not without its share of violence.
According to the most recent statistics, the rate of violent crimes
such as rape, robbery, and assault is slightly higher here than the
national numbers, which declined 7 percent in 1997, extending a
six-year trend.
</P>
<P>
   But the striking disparity is a murder rate that shows that
homicide is more than three times as likely to occur in some
Southern states than it is in New England.
</P>
<P>
   New England's lower homicide rate has its roots in the 19th
century. Higher rates of bloodshed across the Southern highlands
have persisted for as long as crime statistics have been compiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen some dramatic improvements,'' said Dwayne Smith,
chairman of the criminal justice department at the University of
North Carolina at Charlotte. ``But in the final analysis, when you
talk about crime, you're talking about a very localized
phenomenom.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   --A recent US Department of Justice analysis of national
homicide trends from 1976-97 shows that murders, particularly those
involving guns, are especially high in Arkansas, Louisiana,
Oklahoma, and Texas. They are relatively low in New England and
across the northern Great Plains.
</P>
<P>
   --While murders in Boston dwindled to 35 last year, its lowest
since 1961, the body count in Baltimore soared to 314, the ninth
straight year that city has recorded 300 or more killings, ranking
Baltimore with Gary, Ind., New Orleans, and Detroit among America's
deadliest cities.
</P>
<P>
   --According to a recent FBI report, 1997 crimes reported to
police dropped 3 percent in big cities but rose 1 percent in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists are nearly unanimous that upbeat statistics
suggesting homogeneous low-crime from coast to coast obscure
important, regional distinctions about what crimes are being
committed by whom. But there is little agreement about why those
differences linger, or, for that matter, why overall crime has
dropped so dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there is no singular factor,'' said Eric
Monkkonen, a homicide expert and history professor at the
University of California at Los Angeles. ``It would be great if
there was one thing we could point to, but we can't. It's not just
policing. It's not just the involvement of the churches. It may be
random things that none of us understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients of Boston's success story have been
well-documented. Community policing, after-school programs, an
involved clergy, and a diminished appetite for crack cocaine have
made an unmistakable difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is geographically concentrated and it just doesn't have
the poverty that places like Gary, Ind., or New Orleans have,''
said Jack Levin, director of the Brudnick Center on Violence at
Northeastern University. ``The crime in Boston, no matter how bad
it ever was, never looked like it was unmanageable _ so people took
a chance and got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in some places, say Baltimore, it looks overwhelming and
beyond human control,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts point to the graying of the Baby Boom
generation, a demographic colossus that helped drive crime rates up
in the '70s and early '80s, as the key factor in diminishing crime
rates, others say the answer is not much more difficult than
Economics 101.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that Cleveland and Baltimore and Memphis sort of
lead the pack not just in violent crime, but also lead the pack in
the poverty index,'' said James Alan Fox, dean of Northeastern's
College of Criminal Justice. ``If you improve the socio-economic
conditions, your crime rate will improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Criminologists who monitor regional crime rates say
socioeconomics goes only so far in explaining fluctations in crime.
History and geography, they suggest, offer other clues.
</P>
<P>
   Murder is often personal in the South, the climax of a lover's
quarrel or a barroom fight, the experts said. In other regions,
homicide more frequently occurs between strangers, resulting when
other crimes _ such as robberies _ are botched and take a fatal
twist.
</P>
<P>
   The murder rate in Arkansas, Louisiana, Oklahoma, and Texas was
8.4 per 100,000 residents, according to the most recent FBI
statistics. That was 3 1/2 times the murder rate in New England,
where it was 2.4 per 100,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Murder rates in those two regions range from 1.4 in New
Hampshire to 15.7 in Louisiana. Massachusetts' murder rate was 1.9
per 100,000 residents in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty, reinstated by the Supreme Court in 1976,
seems to have played little part in the equation. In Texas, for
example, 165 people have been executed since the state reinstituted
the death penalty in 1982. The last execution in Massachusetts was
in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the 11 states of the Confederacy accounted for eight of
the 20 states with the highest murder rates among 14- to
17-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is a subculture of violence whereby using violence
to solve disputes is seen as more appropriate than in the rest of
the country,'' Fox said. ``Down South, you might take it outside.
Up North, you might take it to court.''
</P>
<P>
   As the specialists continue to analyze factors, including
effects in cities where the crack epidemic started after the
mid-1980s and lingered longer, that may explain regional crime-rate
swings, the larger and rosier nationwide picture also is under
rigorous review.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kenneth Land, a sociology professor at Duke
University who studies crime rates, said the decline in murder of
spouses has to do with the advent of battered women's shelters,
improved emergency trauma treatment, and the collapse of the
neighborbood barroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one drug for which there's well-documented evidence
of excitation to violence, it's alcohol,'' Land said. ``It used to
be you'd have a guy sitting there having his boilermaker and the
next thing you'd know there's be a trivial argument that would lead
to a death.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Zimring, a law professor and the director of the Earl
Warren Legal Institute at the University of California at Berkeley,
said the newest nationwide statistics represent a watershed in US
criminology.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1964 and 1974, the national homicide rates roughly
doubled, said Zimring, who noted that in the 20 years following
1974, the rates fluctuated up and down by about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we're pushing beneath that bottom so that we have a
structural change in the level of homicide risks in American
cities,'' he said. ``It's a real turning point in American lethal
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Barnett, a statistician at MIT's Sloan School of
Management, said no one anticipated such a precipitous drop in
crime and, therefore, no one should rush to explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really very startling,'' Barnett said. ``I'm
absolutely delightfully startled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never believed and can't think of a single
criminologist who would have suggested that Boston would have 35
homicides last year. It's something to be celebrated. And then
there are questions that need to be answered about all of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
