</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SINKS EVEN LOWER IN SLEAZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- It is sick enough that Kenneth Starr has not only
advertised but actually timed a ``garbage'' indictment to influence
President Clinton's impeachment trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But it is mind-boggling that Starr would do so while trying to
bury testimony by a witness who shreds the credibility of Kathleen
Willey, especially since Starr and House impeachment managers have
been bending heaven and earth to get Willey's allegations of a
presidential semi-assault into the Senate proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Starr got his headlines last week by arranging for the
indictment (on perjury and obstruction charges) of former Willey
close friend Julie Hiatt Steele on the same day the Senate
proceeding had its ceremonial commencement. And House Judiciary
Committee chairman Henry Hyde's impeachment minions used the
indictment to claim that the Willey case belongs in the Senate
trial and that it is another reason why a ``full'' trial with
witnesses is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is Hyde's credibility that is undermined by the
Willey case. There is an emerging, bipartisan consensus in the
Senate that Hyde should bear a heavy burden to show that he has
developed a case worthy of a full trial and that it is
well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   What Starr has tried to bury, ever since he received it last
April, is the grand jury testimony of a witness who puts the Willey
and Steele matters in a dramatically different light. The witness
is another former close friend of the Virginia woman, Harolyn
Cardozo, whom Willey called on her cellular telephone on the day in
question in 1993, when Willey later claimed she had been virtually
assaulted by the president in a hallway next to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had Willey's phone records, which showed the call was
placed to Cardozo and lasted 47 minutes, 4 seconds; and the records
resulted in a subpoena from the prosecutor's office. They did not,
however, result in the story that Starr wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familiar with her testimony last April 4,
Cardozo contradicts Willey's story of an incident that left her
supposedly shaken, fearful, and full of fury and disgust as far as
Clinton was concerned. To the contrary, there was no story of
assault, but one about a woman who sounded pleased and anxious to
see the president as much as she could.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the testimony is that Willey was actively plotting over
the phone about how she could find ways to see him, including ways
of obtaining Mrs. Clinton's schedule in order to learn when she
would be away from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a seamy JFK reference, Willey was also alleged to have
said that if she played her cards right she could be the Judith
Campbell Exner of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Cardozo's testimony is especially significant because of the
length of the phone call. It is Steele's story that Willey _ in
addition to asking her to lie about her encounter with the
president _ also asked her to say that she had called Steele on her
cellular telephone to tell her what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   It is also significant because it corroborates the sworn
statements about the same, pleased Kathleen Willey that were made
by Linda Tripp, who appears to have been present for everything
that happened at the White House during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   Cardozo was hauled back before the grand jury last month. At
this point, however, Starr was trying fruitlessly to develop dirt
on her father, bigtime Democratic Party fund-raiser Nathan Landow,
who also knew Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, however, has never tried to use her Democratic
connections (her husband is another prominent Democrat, Michael
Cardozo, who at one point chaired Clinton's defense fund) to
impeach her testimony. She was, after all, his witness, and his
investigators confirmed her close friendship at the time with
Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he tried to bury her testimony, while focusing his
oppressive resources on Julie Hiatt Steele in an invasive
investigation that included the circumstances of her child's
adoption in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   I'm convinced a first-year law student could smash Starr's case
against Steele, but its flimsy nature is irrelevant anyway. Its
real purpose is to pad the weak impeachment file.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, if Starr had ever found anything directly culpable,
it would have been put into an official referral to the House
instantly. But as the entire history of his investigation shows,
not having a case does not prevent him and his House friends from
trying to make one anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
