<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM TRENT TO TROY AND BACK AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   TRENT LOTT: The Senate majority leader stuck his foot in his
mouth _ and later backpedaled _ when he questioned the timing of
last month's bombing of Iraq. But he redeemed himself in a big way
by pushing fellow senators toward a bipartisan approach to
President Clinton's trial on articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's insistence on devising trial procedures that Republicans
and Democrats could live with set him up for criticism, of course _
especially from members of the Mississippi senator's own party.
Unlike some congressional colleagues who have meekly caved in when
pressured by anti-Clinton zealots obsessed with drumming the
president out of office, Lott has shown _ so far, at least _ that
he can take the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who don't appreciate him now may one day thank him
for steering a statesmanlike course and saving the GOP from one
more self-destructive blunder in its pursuit of the president.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: Political prognosticators are talking up
the first lady as a potential candidate for the Senate, guessing
that she might go after the seat held by retiring New York Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad idea when you stop and think about it. If she
starts campaigning right away, she can tell Bill that she's too
busy to help him pack if he gets booted out of the White House. If
Bill doesn't get booted, a Senate campaign will give Hillary an
excuse to get away from the bum for days and weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: Can the Comeback Kid survive the ``Trial of the
Century'' in the Senate? Can he talk his way out of one last jam?
Can the man whose motto is ``Never, ever quit'' hang on by his
fingernails just once more?
</P>
<P>
   Well, O.J. Simpson beat the rap in the last ``Trial of the
Century'' after leaving a trail of blood from the murder scene to
the foot of his bed. If it hadn't been for the stain on Monica
Lewinsky's dress, Slick Willie might have left no trail at all.
</P>
<P>
   STROM THURMOND: Give the ol' boy a round of applause. Acting as
president pro tem of the Senate, the 96-year-old senator from South
Carolina did a nice job presiding over the formal opening of the
impeachment trial. Yes, he had somebody feeding him the scripted
dialogue, but he delivered every line flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond was the perfect senator to get the ball rolling _ he's
darn near old enough to remember the last time a U.S. president was
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH DOLE: The former Cabinet officer/Red Cross chief is
gearing up to run for the Republican presidential nomination in
2000. As we saw when she stumped for hubby Bob Dole in the 1996
election, Mrs. Dole is a dynamic campaigner. If only Bob had been
half as dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN ASHCROFT: The sanctimonious senator from Missouri has
decided not to run for president. Good decision.
</P>
<P>
   TROY AIKMAN: Why is everybody picking on Troy? This guy is one
of the greatest quarterbacks who has ever played pro football, and
if he's had some rough times of late, it's because his Dallas
Cowboys teammates haven't been carrying their share of the load. No
quarterback _ not John Elway, not Dan Marino, not even ex-Cowboy
Roger Staubach _ can win a football game by himself.
</P>
<P>
   These people who keep screaming that Aikman is over the hill had
better hope that he doesn't decide to pack it in. If they think
their favorite football team is horrible with Aikman, wait till
they see what the Cowboys look like without him. Cowboys fans
everywhere will be begging him to return.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN RYAN: If ever a baseball player deserved to be voted into
the Hall of Fame, Ryan is the player. Never mind the seven
no-hitters, the 5,714 strikeouts, the 53 major-league records he
set during a 27-year career that began with the New York Mets and
ended with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan isn't merely a Hall of Fame athlete; he's a Hall of Fame
human being, a role model for young and old alike. If there were
more Nolan Ryans in big-time sports, the sports world wouldn't have
an image problem.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
