<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A DEMOCRACY, STUPID 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On Friday, the day the members of the Senate got
together to work out procedures for Bill Clinton's impeachment
trial, I took an impromptu public opinion survey.
</P>
<P>
   At four stops during an afternoon snowstorm _ one for gas, one
for groceries, one at a drug store and one at a newsstand _ I asked
the people who took my money what they thought about what's going
on in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The woman at the gas station/convenient mart told me that she's
sick of hearing about it. The supermarket cashier observed that
they're all a bunch of creeps down there. The woman behind the
register at the drug store warned me not to get her started, so I
didn't. And the guy at the newsstand said it's all a bunch of
bullfeathers, that he would have lied, too, and that he was a lot
more interested in the NBA finally starting up because he has been
getting killed on his football bets.
</P>
<P>
   None of which should have surprised me, I suppose, but it did.
I'm a political junkie married to a high school government teacher.
This is about all we've talked about recently _ at the top of our
lungs, by the way. My bride and I have different views on all this.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, though, the potential removal of a president of
the United States by the Senate _ an event of truly towering
historical significance _ seems a matter of monumental
inconsequence. Hey, the weather is rotten and almost everybody has
a job these days, and who has time to worry about this political
stuff?
</P>
<P>
   I heard the same thing on television Friday morning from around
the country. A reporter in Chicago told some network interviewer
that heavy snow and Michael Jordan are much bigger news there than
Bill Clinton. A reporter from Kansas City was saying that George
Brett getting into the Hall of Fame was interesting to his
audience, not this.
</P>
<P>
   At century's end, then, we seem to be witnessing an intriguing
phenomenon _ a nation of 270 million mostly satisfied people
increasingly uninvolved in their country's democracy, no matter how
rowdy and bizarre that democracy might become. A recent Harris poll
found 91 percent of Americans feeling good about their overall
quality of life, 84 percent happy with their standard of living and
fully four in five feeling just ducky about the community they live
in.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, their faith in the government that has
presided over the development of all this comfort has declined
dramatically since the 1950s and early 1960s, the nation's last
extended period of peace and prosperity. The Gallup organization
reports that only 8 percent of Americans believe that very few
politicians are crooks and that 3 percent believe they're all
crooked. Seven in 10 Americans think the country needs better
political leadership. Three in five Americans bemoan a collapse of
national moral values. Fewer than one in three Americans trust
government to do what's right ``most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of such disaffection, fewer people than ever
seen to be keeping up with the news. In this government town, two
of the four network affiliate television stations have more people
watching their prime-time entertainment programming than watching
the station's primary newscast. Fewer than half of Americans now
vote in national elections, fewer than a third in state elections.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Because, it seems, we're mostly fat and happy and more
interested in entertaining ourselves than in our civic
responsibilities. Yes, it's possible that, in a few weeks, a
president will be ejected from office for the first time in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not Oprah, and it's not the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   So, really, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
