<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-STORE-HNS &LR;      01-11 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GENTEEL BOOKSELLER TO CORPORATE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AL McKEE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last fall the university bookstore at which I
have worked for almost 15 years became the target of a possible
takeover by a big national bookstore chain.
</P>
<P>
   What a hypnotic moment when a long-dreaded prospect such as this
one comes to pass. The gates into the Roman Circus open, and there
they are, just as imagined _ lions.
</P>
<P>
   The new titan may be a wonderful company to work for. But in the
world of independent booksellers, the expectations for corporate
takeover are no different from any other business: lower pay, fewer
benefits, stricter rules, rigid adherence to the bottom line. To
say nothing of termination.
</P>
<P>
   And, please, let's say nothing of termination.
</P>
<P>
   A once-genteel profession, publishing and selling books is now
as rowdy a business as wildcatting for oil. Consider the turbulence
in the industry: soaring stock prices for the on-line book ordering
service Amazon.com, panic at major publishing houses over
record-setting returns of unsold books, contracts canceled, authors
dropped. And all the while, big media companies devour small
presses like hogs in a vineyard. For the executives who direct it,
this fiscal rough-and-tumble must be pure adrenalin; for those of
us at the retail level, it is excess stomach acid.
</P>
<P>
   The average bookseller does not thrive on risk. In a children's
story he would be the porcupine _ a prickly personality masking an
essentially docile nature. Many of us in the trade are aspiring
writers and artists, actors and musicians _ and never mind that
part about aspiring. Our creative temperaments are fully developed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us choose this line of work for the same reason people
choose to be cab drivers or fishermen: to steer clear of the
regular business world. What a rude trick that the global economy
now presses that world upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Rude trick or not, it happens. So here is a message for my new
corporate bosses. If this deal goes through, I'll be happy to
acquaint you with our shop's peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   I can explain, for example, my system of taping pieces of paper
_ unfinished business _ to the wall beside my desk, a wall which
now looks like one of those public bulletin boards in China. I can
explain why our senior buyer may need an extra minute to finish his
telephone orders _ so as to trade baseball stories with a
publisher's rep in Chicago he has known for years. I can introduce
you to the customer who insists on ordering books before they are
published and to the professor who requires for his class an
out-of-print textbook that he wrote himself.
</P>
<P>
   And I can help you with the scheduling _ most of us skip our
daily breaks, preferring to pause on the sales floor, now and then,
to chat for half an hour about hot new movies or the latest Cormac
McCarthy novel.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt you will wish to change some of these practices. No
doubt we will have no choice but to comply. On one point, however,
expect resistance: At our bookstore, we are not inclined to smile
upon a dress code.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Al McKee, who works in a university book store, is a free-lance
writer in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1343EST &QL; 
