<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GEARS UP FOR SHOWDOWN OVER TOBACCO MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas lawmakers who begin a new session Tuesday
face a showdown over how to spend the $17.3 billion settlement
struck with the tobacco industry last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers will have their eyes on about $1.7 billion in tobacco
money for the upcoming session, the first installment of the
settlement that will be spread over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark settlement _ the largest negotiated between a
single state and the major tobacco companies _ averted what was
expected to be a drawn-out trial in federal court. Texas sued the
industry seeking to recover costs for smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Competing interests are revving their engines at the legislative
starting line, preparing for a race that could end in millions of
dollars to fund a host of pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of folks that want a piece of the pie that
are not a part of the piece of the pie right now,'' said House
Speaker Pete Laney, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is how much money the federal government will try
to get from the settlement as compensation for its share of the
Medicaid health program for poor people.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, for example, seeks money for a proposed children's
cancer institute at the University of Texas Health Science Center.
Former Attorney General Dan Morales, who helped lead the lawsuit
against the tobacco companies, helped tentatively negotiate $200
million from the tobacco settlement for the proposed center.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point ... the nickel is still in the air,'' said Dr.
John P. Howe III, president of the Health Science Center. The
ultimate outcome, he said, will only be available on the last day
of the legislative session, May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the state's leading lawmakers who control the purse
strings of the Legislature signed a memorandum of understanding
with Morales last year regarding the tobacco money. Rep. Rob
Junell, D-San Angelo, and Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant,
agreed to ``use their best efforts'' to secure funding for the
pediatric cancer center and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   While both lawmakers still say they plan to remain true to the
agreement, both cite ``the will of the Legislature'' as the
overriding factor in any talk of how state funds are spent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the memorandum of understanding, several other cities and
academic institutions will receive money for various health care
projects. These projects include $100 million to the University of
Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston; $50 million to the
Texas Tech Health Science Center; and $50 million to the University
of Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With an expected budgetary surplus and the windfall from the
tobacco settlement, those dependent on state funds are licking
their chops.
</P>
<P>
   Another big-ticket item dependent on the tobacco settlement is
the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), which would help
cover the up to 1.3 million Texas children who are currently
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative panels already have recommended that lawmakers agree
this session to give $151 million in state funds to help match
federal money for the program. CHIP allows states to craft their
own strategies for providing affordable health coverage to more
than 10 million uninsured children nationwide. The program targets
children who have fallen through the cracks of the Medicaid safety
net: those whose families earn too much to qualify for Medicaid but
not enough to buy insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1345EST &QL; 
