</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLING A FOUL ON MALDEN HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every schoolboy basketball player knows the rules: Commit too
many fouls and you'll be thrown out of the game. At Malden (Mass.)
High, it's the consequences for transgressions off the court that
aren't so clear.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Dean, an 18-year-old sophomore, is in Malden's lineup
this season despite his admission in court last May that he
sexually assaulted a 15-year-old classmate in a school stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   The judge continued Dean's case without a finding provided he
behaves himself for five years. That had little impact on the
defendant. A few months later, Dean was in trouble again, this time
for sexually harassing a classmate at Pope John XXIII Central High
School, a Catholic school in Everett where he transferred last fall
after Malden refused to let him play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, failing grades made him academically ineligible for sports
at Pope John, so last month Dean returned to Malden High, where
apparently all is forgiven if you can make a jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the basketball team had already been
chosen, room on the roster was found for Dean. He is playing on
orders from the school superintendent over the objections of the
new principal, Peter J. Lueke, the longtime athletic director,
Barry Fitzpatrick, and the arresting police officer, Kevin Molis,
who is assigned full time to Malden High.
</P>
<P>
   We'd like to hear Superintendent George E. Holland's reasoning,
but he did not return our calls. Others suggest that fear of a
lawsuit prompted the decision to let Dean play.
</P>
<P>
   That's hard to swallow. The school's athletic code of conduct
could not be more clear: ``It must be understood that participation
in athletics at Malden High School is a privilege, not a right. . .
. If an athlete, in any way, detracts from the image of the team,
school or community, whether it be on the field, the school, or
outside school, he/she will be dealt with by the coach or a higher
authority and punishment applied.''
</P>
<P>
   An athlete caught smoking for the third time, for example, is
off the team. But an admitted sex offender is eligible to play?
</P>
<P>
   Malden High also has a written policy against sexual harassment.
In capital letters, the school handbook warns: ``IF YOU DO IT, IT
WILL NOT BE TREATED LIGHTLY AND WILL NOT BE TOLERATED.'' It does
not say, ``unless you can set a pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps school administrators suffer from selective memory. It
has happened before in this case. Sister Kristin Hokanson says ``a
key factor'' in her decision to admit Dean to Pope John last
September was a glowing recommendation from his school adjustment
counselor at Malden High School, George Lyons. Lyons's letter made
no mention of the sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known Leland since he was a child. He has always
conducted himself as a gentleman with staff,'' Lyons wrote. I guess
he thought that as long as Dean was a gentleman to adults, it
wouldn't matter to Sister Hokanson that he was sexually abusive to
a student.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. The principal of Pope John understandably feels
misled by a letter that focused on Dean's ``passion for sports,''
which Lyons described as ``a definite plus,'' responsible for
Dean's ``positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not told. If I had known about that incident, the
outcome would have been quite different,'' Sister Hokanson says.
</P>
<P>
   She only learned of the sexual assault after Dean had withdrawn
from Pope John in November. That information might have been
helpful when a student and her parents complained that Dean had
made sexually explicit comments to her outside the school building.
``He was disciplined through our internal procedures,'' Sister
Hokanson says, ``but I do not understand why Malden withheld the
information about the prior incident.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a low rumble in Malden about the Dean case. Because no
one in authority has addressed the issue publicly, coffee shop
indictments are being issued against the principal and the athletic
director, the very people who objected to Dean's playing ball.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes at a time when residents were feeling optimistic
about the city's educational progress. Lueke is getting high marks,
even from those who supported a competing candidate to head a
school that has 28 countries and 17 native languages represented in
its student body.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the Massachusetts Education Reform Act is pouring
into the city; five new schools are under construction. But all
those shiny new facades won't represent real change if the old
lesson of tolerance of sexual assault is what's being taught
inside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
