<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT'S SHAME BELONGS WITH CONGRESSIONAL ACCUSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No doubt the rightward-leaning Republicans in the House of
Representatives believe they accomplished a huge part of their
agenda against President Clinton when their partisan effort
succeeded in making him only the second president in American
history to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   They believe, based on the history surrounding the other
impeached president, Andrew Johnson, that regardless of the outcome
of the Senate trial, the tag will become Clinton's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as difficult as it may be to set the record straight, the
wrong people are being relegated to history's political ``hall of
shame'' with the ``I'' label attached.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that historians and the media still write
impeachment beside the names of Johnson and Clinton as if they were
guilty of crimes so serious against the United States that they had
to be removed in order to restore democracy. But that was not the
case with either man.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being impeached sounds far more serious than being
charged with a crime, particularly when the charge is against the
president. And it further suggests that they had to commit a
serious crime in order for the House to levy such a serious charge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite impeachment, history has proven in Johnson's case, as it
will eventually in Clinton's, that the shame of impeachment should
not be on the two presidents wrongfully charged with ``high crimes
and misdemeanors.'' Rather, it should be on the Republican members
of Congress who shamelessly manipulated the impeachment process to
achieve their own agenda _ removing the president who opposes their
views.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson had simply followed the post-Civil War agenda of the
radical Republicans to punish the South instead of following
through on President Lincoln's policy of reconciliation, he
probably would not have been impeached.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the radical Republicans also passed the Office of
Tenure Act, which forbade a president from removing any Cabinet
official during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson declared the act unconstitutional, as the US
Supreme Court later affirmed, and fired a radical Republican in his
Cabinet, Secretary of War Edwin Stanton, the radical Republicans
began the impeachment process against Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Edmund G. Ross, the radical Republicans would have
succeeded in their plans to convict and remove Johnson and replace
him with one of their own, the Senate president pro tem. That would
have been a coup d'etat, posing more of a threat to democracy than
anything Johnson did. But Ross, a radical Republican, become an
unsung hero when he cast his vote against impeachment, resulting in
Johnson's acquittal by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   History and the media would better serve by more properly
describing this episode. The coup failure is more significant than
describing the event by saying ``Johnson was the only president to
be impeached'' until this year. That's a longer description, but it
is also historically more accurate and fairer to Johnson's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, many of those right-leaning Republicans are
saying almost smugly _ while some Democrats are saying sadly _ that
history will forever judge him through the taint of impeachment,
suggesting that what he did was serious enough to warrant a Senate
trial to determine whether he should leave office.
</P>
<P>
   But in Clinton's case, his affair with Monica Lewinsky is so far
removed from being a ``high crime and misdemeanor'' that the
resulting charges of ``perjury'' and ``obstruction of justice''
make a mockery of our Constitution and all three branches of our
government.
</P>
<P>
   The reason a private affair _ something more than a few
Republican congressmen are familiar with in their own lives _has
resulted in serious criminal charges against Clinton can be traced
easily and directly to the Republican right. It's no secret that
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, as disclosed in various news
accounts, is closely associated with the right.
</P>
<P>
   Spending more than $40 million in over four years of
investigating Clinton for everything from Whitewater to Travelgate,
and ending up only with a perjury trap set for the president
involving Lewinsky, suggest more was involved than a simple pursuit
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Senate moves into its trial mode, House Republicans
are pursuing with zeal an effort to further vilify Clinton at the
trial and push toward a vote for conviction and removal.
</P>
<P>
   As with Johnson, it would be far more accurate for history and
the media to portray this episode as the second attempt at a coup
against a president, using impeachment as the weapon. In both
cases, the coup attempts were led by extreme Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, as the Senate proceeds with the case, right-leaning
Republicans can be reminded that history, and the American people,
will treat them as these Republicans have treated Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
