<HEADLINE>
COACH DESERVES A HIGH GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's not too early in 1999 to choose a hero of
the year. Let's nominate Ken Carter. He is the basketball coach of
the Richmond Oilers, a high school team dominant in the
Alameda-Contra Costa Athletic League and ranked third statewide in
their division.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers enjoyed a 13-0 record until the coach padlocked the
gymnasium and locked up the basketballs. Since he started
forfeiting games, players now spend their two-hour practice session
not shooting hoops, but studying in the library. They will do so
until their grades improve.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond, an industrial city of 92,000 across San Francisco Bay
from San Quentin, is a big basketball town and has been since
Carter himself set the school's all-time scoring record in 1977.
Ditching the Oilers' prospects for glory, the coach said, ``I want
young men to understand that basketball is just one small portion
of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this guy crazy or what? Naive? Old-fashioned? ``This is
really important to me,'' the coach said. ``How many of these young
men are going to make their living playing basketball?'' He
answered his own question when interviewed by the local media.
``About one in 500,000, maybe,'' he replied. ``It's more important
that we produce good citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Although just seven members on the roster were in academic
trouble, he benched the entire varsity and junior varsity squads, a
total of 45 players. The league requires a grade point average of
2.0, but Carter demands more. His son Damien, a sophomore, has a
3.5 GPA, but he's also logging extra library time because, coach
Carter says, ``This is a team sport.''
</P>
<P>
   A team sport? Coach, do you own a television set? Basketball is
now a solo endeavor. It's not the bounce pass or the rebound, but
the celebratory slam-dunk that hits the highlight shows.
</P>
<P>
   Carter did not participate in the historic struggle that ended
last week, when the billionaires and millionaires of the National
Basketball Association chose to inhabit a peaceable courtside
kingdom. Much like an Iran vs. Iraq war, their labor dispute
engendered public attitudes ranging from distracted apathy to an
earnest wish for heavy casualties on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But diehard fans were edging toward despair. The prospect of
empty sofas and deserted divans was chilling in this winter of
discontent. How would NBA fanatics know which sneakers to buy?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Carter's benched players will, like casual fans, enjoy a
vacation from hoopster hype. This will allow time to sharpen the
focus on what's wrong with most major-league sports. Celebrating
too much over too little has reduced the importance of team in team
sports.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite athletes was Art Monk, a pass-catching
artisan at Syracuse University, then the Washington Redskins and
New York Jets. When he scored a touchdown, he did not gavotte,
pirouette, or implode in a paroxysm of choreographed glee.
</P>
<P>
   What did he do? Art Monk handed the ball to the referee. Like
Barry Sanders, the Detroit Lion running back, he treated the end
zone as a familiar place, which he'd seen before and which he
expected to see again.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, noncelebratory touchdown is rare precisely because it
is an eloquently unspoken tribute to 10 teammates who helped one
arrive there. The National Football League tried to ban end-zone
convulsions with penalties for unsportsmanlike conduct. This action
goaded cockier players into celebrating 10 yards before they
scored, accelerating the aging process of their coaches. One day a
brave coach will fine a premature celebrant $1,000 per inch.
</P>
<P>
   A self-conscious salute has become a scoring ritual for the
Denver Broncos in pro football and the Pittsburgh Penguins in the
National Hockey League. It looks as silly as sundry other versions
of the dance named for St. Vitus. Anyone seeking further
information on St. Vitus can check with coach Carter's benchees.
They can be found in the Richmond High School library.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
