<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLULMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWF SEEKS TRULY HONEST PERSONALS AD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; read the personals. I'm not in the market for someone. Not at
the moment, anyway. I read the personals looking for clues to the
state of relations between the sexes. And I read them for fun too,
I admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, scanning the personals in the Globe's Calendar section,
I see there are fewer ``soul mates'' wanted than there were a few
years ago. And there aren't as many men as there used to be who use
the word ``gentleman'' as a self-description. What are we to make
of this? Or is it obvious? There are, however, more women who use
the term ``gentlewoman'' to indicate that they're . . . what?
Well-educated? Well-behaved? Not to be trifled with?
</P>
<P>
   Fewer women are looking for ``Prince Charming.'' And fewer men
are looking for their ``dream girl.'' Long, romantic walks are
still a personal-ad staple. But almost nobody wants to drink wine
in front of a fire anymore. They'd rather be golfing, or skiing, or
antiquing. Spontaneity is much sought after. Sensuality too. And
fitness. Both sexes continue to prize a sense of humor. But
kindness and caring are making inroads as desired qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never change. The overwhelming majority of men and
women who advertise describe themselves, variously, as attractive,
handsome, pretty, beautiful, adorable, awesome, striking, sexy,
gorgeous, cute, appealing, etc.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to all the people who aren't good-looking? Where do
they advertise? Is there a special place somewhere for those who
can't bring themselves to boast (or to lie) about their looks?
``Plain, portly SWM, peculiar habits, enjoys TV, pizza, beer,
sitting around doing nothing, seeks older woman who reminds him of
his mother, for mutual recrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't see ads like that, and for good reason, I suppose.
Although occasionally there's an ad like this one: ``Night
worker/DWF, 38, n/s, 5'7'' full figured, average looks, enjoys
traveling, camping. . .'' There's something very appealing about
that ad. If Diogenes were walking among us with his lamp, looking
for an honest woman, he'd find her on page 36 of last Thursday's
Calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Syatt, the local singles dance tsar, tells of two people
who found one another through the personals and arranged to meet.
They arrived at the appointed place but failed to recognize one
another because they'd both lied so extravagantly about their
looks. I wonder if this happens a lot. Maybe that's why so many
people who advertise are hoping to meet someone with a sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   I'm struck by how much more wildly creative men are than women
when it comes to describing themselves in the personals. Here's a
selection of words and terms in the Men Seeking Women section of
last week's Calendar. Housebroken. Gymnophile. Multifarious.
Overeducated. Spiritual humanitarian. Robert Redford type. Richard
Gere look-alike. Charlton Heston look-alike. Simply irresistible.
Diamond-in-the- rough. Litterateur. Controlling. Complete package.
Enjoys NPR, body surfing. Blue-blooded. Comfortable in the
wilderness or museum. Eccentric. Quippy. Aware. Bon vivant. A heart
three times bigger than other men.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, women seem to be somewhat less imaginative
in describing themselves, although there are those who take flight,
to wit: ``High Tech beauty . . . Danish version of Vivien Leigh . .
.''; or ``Dorothy by day, Catwoman by night. . .''; or ``Plymouth
Rockette. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Almost always there's the odd gem to be found in the personals.
My favorite from last week's is this: ``God's Teeth. Seeking Andie
MacDowell look-alike 40 to 60.''
</P>
<P>
   I wish him luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
