<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-11 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
81-YEAR-OLD WIDOW SHOULD CASH OUT OF ANNUITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a widow 81 years old. My income consists of a pension
and Social Security totaling $12,936 a year, an interest in a
midwestern farm that brings me $6,000 to $9,000 annually, and the
yield from $52,000 in money market accounts and a short-term bond
fund. I also have an annuity which will be worth $296,00 in April.
I can then opt for a $2,400 monthly payment for life, (10 years
certain,) or I can cash out and face a 4 percent surrender charge.
Or I could wait two years, earning a lower rate than the 5.75
percent it now pays, and there would be no surrender charge. I have
spoken to a financial advisor, and he wants me to surrender the
annuity and transfer the proceeds to a variable annuity account
invested in a diverse portfolio of mutual funds. What do you think
of this plan?
</P>
<P>
   O.W., Chula Vista, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, let's consider what would happen if you were to cash
out. If you went with the variable annuity plan and withdrew $2,400
a month, how long would the money last? If your returns on a
variable annuity account of $284,160 (reflecting the surrender fee)
were 6.5 percent, it would be good for 15.4 years. If you had
average returns of 8.14 percent, it would last 19 years, taking you
to the century mark. Or you might decide to take a smaller monthly
payment, calculating to preserve your capital. For example, if you
withdrew $1,494 a month and realized 6.5 percent returns on the
total portfolio, you would have no erosion of your principal.
</P>
<P>
   Tempting as it is to wait through the two years so you could
bypass the surrender charge, I'm inclined to side with your
advisor. (If there were no decline in the earnings, you'd have to
realize investment returns of 7.93 percent to draw even with the
value which you would have if you waited out the two years. But the
decline in returns for those final two years probably is sufficient
to make it unattractive to wait.)
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not quite so enthusiastic about the fund portfolio the
advisor is proposing; you list a half-dozen suggested funds, but
give no projected allocation of your money among them. These range
from funds tracking the Standard and Poor's 500 Index and world
stock funds at one end to the kind of things I'm more comfortable
with for a person such as yourself _ government securities and
other fixed-income holdings _ at the other. I suspect that your
advisor put the proposed portfolio together so that it might have
the potential to achieve a considerably higher growth rate than the
6.5 percent I used in most of my calculations. If I were you, I'd
put the brakes on this thinking, settling for a likely lower rate
of return and a higher degree of safety. I suggest you direct that
the portfolio be no more than 35 percent invested in stocks, and
I'd be happier if the number were 20 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So yes, I would cash out the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 59 and plan to retire at age 60. I have a total of
$800,000, mostly in money markets and the like. It's evenly divided
between taxable and tax-deferred accounts. I have to live off this
capital, but I don't know where to put it so I can have a steady
income every month. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   I.T., Irvine, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I wish I knew something about your standard of living _ how
much money you feel you need to be comfortable. In the ideal
situation, you could make do on about $38,500 a year _ which would
allow you to invest $650,000 so as to produce that income and leave
another $150,000 invested for growth, to protect you against the
very credible threat of future inflation. This presumes a portfolio
average return of 6.5 percent on the fixed- income side. If you
followed this plan, you would not only be well protected against
inflation, but your principal would be growing rather than receding
as you age.
</P>
<P>
   But you also could simply invest the entire $800,000 in a
fixed-income portfolio, drawing $50,000 a year with a reasonable
assurance that there would be very little erosion - - and more
likely a small appreciation _ of your principal. As for inflation,
if you adopt this plan you could simply rely on that sizable
$800,000 nest egg for protection; in later years, as your
short-term expenses increased through inflation, you could begin to
tap into capital, being fairly confident that there would be enough
money there to last you out.
</P>
<P>
   Or finally, you could take the bold step of projecting that
you'll last no longer than age 90 _ or any other number you select.
Using the example of age 90, you could then invest the entire
$800,000 in a 6.5 percent fixed-income portfolio and withdraw
$4,956 a month, or $59,472 annually. If you died precisely at age
90, you would die precisely broke. If you don't reach that age, you
could make some nice bequests. But it gets sticky if you have
underestimated your longevity. I've been trying for years to locate
a story I read some decades ago, probably by Somerset Maugham or
Joseph Conrad. It involves a philosophical middle-aged fellow who
bought a fixed annuity of ten years or so, using his entire life
savings for the purchase. He calculated that a decade of pleasure
without toil was all a man should expect of this world, and he
would take his while he was in good health _ and then bump himself
off. He began in stout resolve, but after 10 years of easy living,
he had softened, and the end was ugly. Does anybody out there
remember the name or author of that one?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, however you decide to proceed, I'd suggest a
fixed-income portfolio consisting 50 percent of a good GNMA fund
such as those offered by Fidelity or Vanguard, 25 percent in a
solid high-yield, or junk, bond fund, again widely available, and
the final 25 percent in a mixture of money market funds, CDs, and
short-term bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   You'd probably get more than 6.5 percent average returns, but a
margin for error is a nice thing, eh? And if you do decide to put
some of the money in stock as your hedge against inflation, I'd
take a plain vanilla approach, going with a fund tracking the
Standard and Poor's 500 Index and using a 36-month dollar cost
averaging discipline to establish your position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 65 years old and my wife is 64. I have a company pension
and we both receive Social Security benefits. I also work
part-time, earning $5,000 a year. I have a 401(k) plan now worth
$370,000 and an IRA account of $75,000. My wife has an IRA worth
$50,000. We have never made any withdrawals, and I feel we should
start soon. What is the minimum we should start withdrawing in
order to avoid future penalties?
</P>
<P>
   R.A., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are no penalties per se involved with IRA withdrawals,
but rather a rule which stipulates that you must begin a sequence
of minimum withdrawals beginning after the owner of an IRA reached
age 70 1/2. Basically, the rule involves a calculation with one
figure based on the life expectancies of the owner and beneficiary
and other being the IRA balance. For example, if you were to wait
until you were 70 years old, you would be required to divide the
balance of the your IRA and 401(k) accounts by 21.1, withdrawing at
least that much as taxable income. Each year, as you and your
beneficiary grow older, the divisor gets lower, and the amount you
must withdraw tends to grow accordingly larger. I say ``tends to''
because that first withdrawal represents only 4.73 percent of the
balance. The odds are that if your money is invested well, the
internal growth of the account will exceed the amount of the
withdrawal in the early years _ although that wouldn't necessarily
be true if your investment returns are negative or low. But a
decade later the formula would call for a withdrawal representing
7.8 percent of the balance, and the withdrawal could well exceed
internal growth. Of course, if you have volatile holdings such as
stocks, all bets are off, since it's nearly impossible to predict
the year-end portfolio value with any precision.
</P>
<P>
   Let's consider what would happen if you waited until age 70 to
withdraw from your own tax-deferred accounts. Presuming 8 percent
average annual portfolio growth from now until then, your accounts
would be worth $649,737. Thus your first mandatory withdrawal must
be at least $30,793. For many people, this would be sufficient to
drive them into a higher tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider what would happen if you were to begin withdrawals
early. Suppose you were to take out $2,000 a month starting now.
The result, maintaining the assumption of 8 percent average annual
returns, would be that after five years the account would be worth
$503,745. With that balance, your first mandatory withdrawal would
be $23,874 _ which would at least suggest that there would be no
big bump in your taxable income once you reach the age of mandatory
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   These calculations, of course, are made without regard to your
overall tax situation, and they also don't include your wife's IRA.
You'll have to juggle with various figures to calculate the
withdrawal sequence that best suits your specific tax situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kenneth Hooker will answer selected investors' questions. Send
letters, including your name, address and telephone number, to:
Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
