<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Jan. 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-CONFLICT (Kinshasa) _ A fundamental reworking of the old
rules of Africa may be unfolding in the Congo war. By explicit
agreement, African nations are not supposed to invade one another.
But critics of Uganda and Rwanda, Congo's neighbors to the east,
say they did exactly that. By Norimitsu Onishi and Ian Fisher.
(With photo and map).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ More shooting, this time over northern
no-flight zone. Iraq radar painted U.S. planes, which then shot at
a missile battery. By Steven Lee Myers. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-COUNCIL-IRAQ (United Nations) _ Whatever happened to the
Security Council? It seems paralyzed over what to do next on Iraq.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Moshe Ahrens, former foreign and
defense minister and mentor of Netanyahu, announces he's running
for prime minister. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   POLLARD-SPYCASE (Washington) _ Developments in the Pollard case;
Albright recommends against release.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-DISARM (Dublin) _ The British Northern Ireland
secretary has proposed a compromise on disarmament, essentially
agreeing with Sinn Fein _ it's not required until May 2000. By
James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ARRESTS (Jakarta) _ The military has arrested 11
soldiers after acknowledging that four protesters on Sumatra died
after being beaten by security forces. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MURAL (Johannesburg) _ In a country with lots of
memorials to British and Boer victories, a South African artist has
created an unusual post-apartheid mural. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Lede-all on the impeachment issue,
with filings from White House and possibly prosecutors. By James
Bennet. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   With TEXT, if developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ What happened to the censure
idea? Some Democrats are still talking about it. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ No one is pretending that the
Senate trial is an accurate mirror of what happens in a criminal or
civil courtroom; but the varied connections between the accused,
some of his accusers, and other parties show precisely how unusual
this case is. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-GROWTH (Washington) _ The growth of Medicare slowed
last year; a look at some of the reasons. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ENGLISH (Washington) _ The high court says it will not
take a case that raises the question of whether a state may require
its employees to speak only English. By not taking the case, an
Arizona Supreme Court ruling, throwing out the law, stands. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Gore is announcing a package of
anti-sprawl tax incentives and federal grants in a speech today,
saying economic growth depends on creating more ``livable
communities'' and preserving open spaces. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PRAIRIE-DOG-DEBATE (Amarillo, Texas) _ The National Fish and
Wildlife Service may declare the lowly prairie dog a threatened
species _ a notion that is greeted by private ranchers and farmers
in places like the Texas Panhandle with the same sort of
incredulity that might greet the notion of declaring cockroaches a
threatened species in New York. By Rick Lyman. (With photo and
map.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIVE-RETURN (Lac du Flambeau, Wis.) _ The growth of tribal
gambling in recent years, with jobs in casinos, hotels and shops,
has breathed at least a whisper of prosperity across the nations of
Indian Country, and sparked homecomings. After more than a century
of American Indians leaving reservations for cities and towns, many
tribes have started to see a reversal in that trend. By Dirk
Johnson. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-CLEANUP (Detroit) _ Detroit has yet to clean up its
streets following last week's snow storm. The city never plowed
residential streets and now things are stuck. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESDAY-CULT (Denver) _ Fourteen members of a doomsday cult
deported from Israel spent Sunday holed up in hotel rooms as
relatives waited anxiously in the downstairs lobby, hoping for some
form of contact.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Microsoft is expected to begin
its defense today with the direct testimony of Richard Schmalensee,
an economist at MIT. The morning session, a closed one, is about
Microsoft's company-by-company pricing practices in dealing with
makers of personal computers. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMANSACHS-SHAKEUP (New York) _ Developments concerning
management changes at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-STOCKSWAP (Frankfurt, Germany) _ British American
Tobacco buys Rothmans International from Richemont of Switzerland
and Rembrandt of South Africa in a $7.5 billion stock swap.
Richemont and Rembrandt will wind up with a 35 percent stake in
BAT, which is making the acquisition to bolster its presence in the
luxury cigarette business and increase its share of the Western
European market as it tries to challenge Philip Morris. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   DEBT-BUYBACK (Washington) _ The Treasury is exploring whether to
use spare cash to buy back government debt from investors. Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-STOCKS (Undated) _ The National Association of
Securities Dealers discusses how to deal with the speculative
frenzy in Internet stocks. In other Net developments, Broadcast.com
splits its stock and Compaq buys Shopping.com for $220 million in
cash to expand into Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELLSOUP-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Campbell Soup says net income
in the current fiscal year will not meet expectations, and it
announces a cost-cutting program. Its stock falls more than 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BANKS (Hong Kong) _ Foreign banks are angry about China's
announcement on Sunday that Guangdong International Trust and
Investment will file for bankruptcy and that creditors will have to
go through China's legal system to claim what they are owed. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
40 points, or 0.4 percent; but the Nasdaq index was up 17 points,
or 0.7 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 0.2 percent in Tokyo and 0.8
percent in Hong Kong. They fell 1.9 percent in Frankfurt, 1.3
percent in London, 6 percent in Brazil, and 0.9 percent in Mexico.
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Details TK.
</P>
