<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 
!!! 1/2 ``A Civil Action'' Based on the landmark Woburn toxic-waste
case in which two giant corporations were sued for poisoning well
water with toxins that eight families claimed caused the leukemia
that killed their children, this film is fascinating in proportion
to its departures from the familiar script for a Hollywood
courtroom thriller. Exchanging the usual clear-cut issues and
resounding triumph of justice for ambiguity, complication, and
darkness, it's powered by strong performances: John Travolta's
cocky ambulance-chaser turned humble; Robert Duvall's shrewd legal
antagonist; all the actors projecting the decency and dignity of
the family members. (PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Thin Red Line'' Terrence Malick's long-awaited film of
James Jones's epic World War II novel about a rifle company on
Guadalcanal is distinguished by its attempt to alternate the usual
hellish battle scenes with introspective moments depicting what's
going on the hearts and minds and memories of the GIs. As it
stands, it's most of the way toward being a great film. Had Malick
been given more time to trim and shape it, it might have seemed
more a classic, and less a screenful of the ingredients of one. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
