<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERS-OF-LOS-CABOS-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 MEXICO'S LOS CABOS: EVER-POPULAR CRUISE PORTS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE showing El Arco (the arch), the signature
landmark of Los Cabos in Mexico, is available free of charge. El
Arco is a large orange-colored arch of stone. The slide is
available by mail (or overnight delivery, using your FedEx or
Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to purchasers of this
article. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   From the 1940s to the 1960s, the 18-mile stretch of beaches,
coves and lagoons at the tip of western Mexico's Baja Peninsula was
an exclusive hideaway for the rich and famous, according to Bob
Schulman, an airline executive from Aurora, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he says, you could spot the silky set's private
planes and yachts everywhere. Erroll Flynn, Tyrone Power, Lana
Turner and the gang came down for a few days to fish in waters
teeming with marlin and sailfish. Some stars hunted; others cut a
quiet deal away from the office.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, a rutted dirt road linked the two main cities:
Cabo San Lucas (Cape of St. Luke) at the southern end of the strip
and San Jose del Cabo (St. Joseph of the Cape) at the northern end.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the region encompassing the two cities, as well as the
resort hotels dotting the stretch between them, is called Los Cabos
(the Capes), or Cabo for short. And mature travelers from the
United States now pour in from some of the top cruise ships, and on
the jets of a half-dozen major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   All told, about 22 different cruise ships stop at Cabo each
year, some once a week. Cabo typically hosts two to four ships a
week from Carnival, Royal Caribbean, Princess and Holland America.
They anchor a half-mile out on the bay at Cabo San Lucas. From
there, it's a 10-minute ride by ships' tender or water taxi to the
dock.
</P>
<P>
   On shore, visitors usually have the better part of a day to take
in as much of the city and surrounding areas as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman says it's easy to get around. Just sign up for a
four-hour motorcoach tour at the cost of about $15 a person. Or, he
suggests that several travelers share a rental car and reduce
sightseeing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a four-wheel motorbike called an ATV
(all-terrain vehicle), which can be rented for three hours for
about $45.
</P>
<P>
   To share a van with three or four others, the tab for a ride
from Cabo San Lucas to San Jose del Cabo and back runs about $8 per
person. Or for a closer look at how residents live, take a local
bus between the two towns with many stops along the way _ all for
about $1 per person one way.
</P>
<P>
   World-class fishing is still a big draw (200-pounders are
considered lightweights here), but rods and reels are fast sharing
the stage with mashies and putters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, developers have created four championship golf courses,
Schulman says. Each is a well-watered oasis surrounded by deserts,
spiky Joshua trees and breathtaking views of the Sea of Cortes.
</P>
<P>
   If cruise passengers return for longer stays, they can bed down
in one of the area's 30-plus resort hotels, which offer close to
4,500 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon are another 1,500 rooms that are being built by such
chains as the Ritz Carlton and Fiesta Americana. Local officials
predict growth to as many as 10,000 rooms _ half the size of
Mexico's premier resort at Cancun _ over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Among the luxury hotels that have sprouted on Cabo's beaches and
hillsides in recent years are the Westin Regina, Melia Cabo Real,
Las Ventanas al Paraiso, Pueblo Bonito and its all-suite sister
resort the Pueblo Bonito Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The two latter hotels, which look out on the bay from El Medano
Beach, typify the area's distinctive Mediterranean-style
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Cabo's dining spots range from fast-food franchises (McDonald's,
Domino's Pizza, KFC and so forth) to traditional Mexican eateries
to the gourmet offerings of fine restaurants with names such as
Alfonso's, Peacock's and Da Georgio's.
 &UR; ABOUT THE TOWNS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nestled along a mile-long bay, Cabo San Lucas (population
35,000, and growing fast) is where the action is. Shops, designer
arcades and dozens of lively cantinas line the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Baja Peninsula ends about a mile out from the city at a huge
rock formation called El Arco (the arch), Cabo's signature
landmark.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's most awesome natural wonders, El Arco is
often shown in the TV series ``Land's End,'' which was taped around
Cabo.
 &UR; SAN JOSE DEL CABO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to upbeat Cabo San Lucas, San Jose del Cabo is a
laidback, pleasant city of meandering streets and lush palm groves.
It is home to 24,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose made the maps in 1730 when the Jesuits built a mission
there. It later gained some prominence as a trading center for
passing ships.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman says that despite a recently completed golf course and
seven resort hotels, San Jose still retains the charm of its
colonial heritage.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests a visit to the funky little town of Todos Santos
(All Saints) 75 miles up the coast where the 200-year-old village
offers a mix of some 3,000 locals, mostly farming families, and 350
or so North American expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   Their paintings, carvings, stoneware and other crafts are sold
in galleries that dot the village's pot-holed avenidas. With the
artists have come some toney restaurants, one of which, the Cafe
Santa Fe, is worth the trip, Schulman says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Todos Santos' best-known landmark, the Hotel
California _ the one in the Eagles' song of the '70s. Back then,
the inn was a favorite haunt for hippies wandering across western
Mexico. They rented hammocks for $2 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman spent an hour or so in the hotel's bar listening to _
what else? _ Eagles' tunes blasting away virtually nonstop on the
CD player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a time capsule from the '70s,'' said one pub
patron, a dentist from Mexico City who was playing hooky from a
convention in Cabo. ``I just can't wait to tell everyone I was at
the real Hotel California. And I've got a Hotel California T-shirt
to prove it.'' (At $20 each, no less.)
</P>
<P>
   For information about Cabo, contact your travel agent or call
the Mexican Government Tourism Office at (800) 446-3942.
</P>
<P>
   Another source is a special fax line offering rundowns on Cabo's
hotels, attractions and shopping. Dial (541) 385-9282 and follow
the instructions to receive free faxes from various Mexican
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.) &LR;  &QL;
