A7900 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAST-MINUTE-SKI-TRIP-     01-11 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAST-MINUTE-SKI-TRIP-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING THE SLOPES AT A MOMENT'S NOTICE 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE showing a skier in action is available by mail
(or overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery
number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The urge to suddenly hop on a plane and head for the mountains
of Utah or Colorado is the dream of many skiers and snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that with a bit of planning, any skier can head
for the hills at a moment's notice. In fact, with the exception of
Christmas and Presidents' week, the entire ski season is fair game
for a last-minute trip at a price that won't inflict bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the clear advantages to traveling at the last minute is
having much more control over the weather. That's been especially
important during an early ski season like this one, when warm
temperatures and lack of snowfall made for less-than-ideal
conditions in the Rockies and New England but left Lake Tahoe
resorts like Squaw Valley and Northstar-at-Tahoe with a snow
bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling last-minute allows skiers to seek out the optimum
conditions to make the most of their limited skiing time.
</P>
<P>
   Some ski tour operators have been known to promise skiers that
they can get them to the slopes within 24 hours. That's certainly
possible, but getting documents like airline tickets sent to a
skier via overnight mail makes such extreme short-notice trips
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Most ski tour operators, travel agents or central reservations
offices can't promise such a quick turnaround. The minimum amount
of time for last-minute Western ski trips, from either the East or
West Coast, is typically three days. The cost, remarkably enough,
is usually the same as it would be three months out plus whatever
the FedEx charges are.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in the age of Web travel, last-minute ski vacations
may be one of the last vestiges of an established system that
relies on travel agents, ski tour operators or a ski resort's
central reservations office to make travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is airfare. Try to get a domestic airline ticket from
the Web or directly from an airline without a seven-day advance
purchase or a Saturday night stay and the fares are prohibitively
expensive, often full-fare economy.
</P>
<P>
   But travel professionals such as ski tour operators negotiate
contracts for cheap, bulk-rate airfares with the airlines months
before the season commences. Provided that those seats are still
available, they have access to them up to 24 hours before a flight
leaves. What's more, bulk airfares are not subject to Saturday
night stay-overs or advance-purchase restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   To find these unsold fares, the best last-minute strategy is to
avoid flying weekends, to take whatever airline is available and to
be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ski tour operators, the central reservations offices of
major ski areas have access to these fares and packages as well.
One advantage to working with them is that they know their
properties inside and out. They're geared to act as a clearinghouse
for unsold rooms, which are generally sold for the same price as an
advance booking.
</P>
<P>
   They know which hotel or condo has a last-minute cancellation or
who may be offering a discount during a slow week. They can be
especially helpful to skiers who are driving to their destination,
whether it's Colorado's Summit County or Vermont's Green Mountains.
Without air to worry about, there's a lot more flexibility in days,
arrival times and location.
</P>
<P>
   Availability, of course, is the key. Skiers stand a much better
chance of getting into ski resorts with a large number of beds _
places like Vail or Killington _ than they do at smaller resorts
like Big Sky or Taos.
</P>
<P>
   And as the saying goes, money isn't everything. Even skiers who
want and can afford pricier lodgings such as The Sonnenalp in Vail
or The Little Nell in Aspen may find that they're in such demand
that they're all but impossible to get into at the last minute. But
with flexible expectations, it's possible to find accommodations in
a place that's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are flying, and assuming cost is a consideration,
the cheapest flights are usually to the larger airports that serve
multiple resorts, such as Denver, Colorado Springs, Salt Lake City
and Reno. All of these airports benefit from direct flights and
airline competition.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to ski areas like Aspen, Jackson Hole or Telluride is
more problematic. A two-flight destination means purchasing two
last-minute tickets, perhaps on two different airlines, which
sharply reduces the odds of getting a good price and actually
getting on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the time factor to consider. Many last-minute trips
are just three or four days long. An extra flight eats into skiing
time and greatly increases the chance of weather-related delays.
</P>
<P>
   To optimize last-minute travel options, think seasonally. In the
late season, count on going after April 1 to take advantage of a
season's worth of snow, not to mention empty airline seats and
hotel rooms. Here are some ski tour operators to contact:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Any Mountain Tours, &LR;  1012 South Cleveland St., Arlington,
Va., 22204; (800) 296-6686; www.anymtn.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lynx Ski Travel, &LR;  P.O. Box 3699, Breckenridge, Colo., 80424;
(800) 422-5969; www.colorado.net/lynx
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Moguls Ski and Snowboard Tours, &LR;  4876 Sterling Drive,
Boulder, Colo., 80301; (800) 666-4857; www.skimoguls.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ski Vacation Planners, &LR;  545 Cedar Lane, Teaneck, N.J., 07666;
(800) U-CAN-SKI; www.skivacationplanners.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance travel
writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
