contracts for cheap, bulk-rate airfares with the airlines months
before the season commences. Provided that those seats are still
available, they have access to them up to 24 hours before a flight
leaves. What's more, bulk airfares are not subject to Saturday
night stay-overs or advance-purchase restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   To find these unsold fares, the best last-minute strategy is to
avoid flying weekends, to take whatever airline is available and to
be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ski tour operators, the central reservations offices of
major ski areas have access to these fares and packages as well.
One advantage to working with them is that they know their
properties inside and out. They're geared to act as a clearinghouse
for unsold rooms, which are generally sold for the same price as an
advance booking.
</P>
<P>
   They know which hotel or condo has a last-minute cancellation or
who may be offering a discount during a slow week. They can be
especially helpful to skiers who are driving to their destination,
whether it's Colorado's Summit County or Vermont's Green Mountains.
Without air to worry about, there's a lot more flexibility in days,
arrival times and location.
</P>
<P>
   Availability, of course, is the key. Skiers stand a much better
chance of getting into ski resorts with a large number of beds _
places like Vail or Killington _ than they do at smaller resorts
like Big Sky or Taos.
</P>
<P>
   And as the saying goes, money isn't everything. Even skiers who
want and can afford pricier lodgings such as The Sonnenalp in Vail
or The Little Nell in Aspen may find that they're in such demand
that they're all but impossible to get into at the last minute. But
with flexible expectations, it's possible to find accommodations in
a place that's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are flying, and assuming cost is a consideration,
the cheapest flights are usually to the larger airports that serve
multiple resorts, such as Denver, Colorado Springs, Salt Lake City
and Reno. All of these airports benefit from direct flights and
airline competition.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to ski areas like Aspen, Jackson Hole or Telluride is
more problematic. A two-flight destination means purchasing two
last-minute tickets, perhaps on two different airlines, which
sharply reduces the odds of getting a good price and actually
getting on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the time factor to consider. Many last-minute trips
are just three or four days long. An extra flight eats into skiing
time and greatly increases the chance of weather-related delays.
</P>
<P>
   To optimize last-minute travel options, think seasonally. In the
late season, count on going after April 1 to take advantage of a
season's worth of snow, not to mention empty airline seats and
hotel rooms. Here are some ski tour operators to contact:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Any Mountain Tours, &LR;  1012 South Cleveland St., Arlington,
Va., 22204; (800) 296-6686; www.anymtn.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lynx Ski Travel, &LR;  P.O. Box 3699, Breckenridge, Colo., 80424;
(800) 422-5969; www.colorado.net/lynx
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Moguls Ski and Snowboard Tours, &LR;  4876 Sterling Drive,
Boulder, Colo., 80301; (800) 666-4857; www.skimoguls.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ski Vacation Planners, &LR;  545 Cedar Lane, Teaneck, N.J., 07666;
(800) U-CAN-SKI; www.skivacationplanners.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance travel
writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
