<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-BRUSTEIN-2TAKES     01-11 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BRUSTEIN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BRUSTEIN: THE ART OF THE MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert Brustein set up shop at the American Repertory
Theatre at Harvard 20 years ago after his departure from the Yale
School of Drama. At 71, he shows no signs of mellowing, continuing
to present plays in an uncompromisingly modernistic and
postmodernistic style. Not only do the plays often divide
audiences, but his theater criticism, mostly for The New Republic,
has sparked debates about multiculturalism and any number of other
issues facing the contemporary theater world. Following is an
edited transcript of an interview with the ART's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you define Robert Brustein's and the ART's aesthetic,
and do you sense that it has changed over the 20 years you've been
here?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let me sum it up this way. I think my whole career as an
artistic director, and as a critic, has been devoted to try to
persuade people that theater can be something more than
entertaining, that the theater is worthy of the same kind of
serious attention as classical music and the novel and dance,
ballet, the opera. This seems fairly obvious, but there was a time
when it wasn't obvious, when the values of theater were being
determined by Broadway and it was a Broadway of much higher
achievement than today's Broadway. So it included everything. It
included serious drama, but it was also primarily commercial. And
people, most Americans, really have a sense that the theater is
commercial and that they go there to have a good time and it's not
a vehicle for art, and I believed it was. . . . I'm really talking
about a theater that tries to break frontiers and push past
boundaries and enter new terrain, where possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This may be the same way of asking the same question, but
what would you like your legacy to be?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's a tough question to answer. As artistic director one
legacy I hope would continue is the idea of a resident company of
actors and designers and directors and, sometimes when we can
afford it, playwrights, because I continue to believe that's where
the most valuable work is done. The company work is the best, most
sensible way to create theater and I'm full of regret that there
are so few companies left in the country. I think that theater
without a company is nothing that interests me very much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So, you don't feel, as Peter Altman at the Huntington said,
that when you have a permanent company you end up programming for
that company, so if you have an all-white company you would never
do &UR;  &LR; a black play because you have a predominantly white company?
</P>
<P>
   A. But the object is to have an integrated company and if your
purpose is, when you speak of a balanced season, (to do) a black
play and a Chinese play and an Asian play or a white play . . .
that kind of season doesn't strike me as very creative unless you
find very good plays. To me, if you find a play by a black person
that's brilliant, then you get a cast to do it, but the play has to
generate the interest rather than vice versa, rather than the need
to do a black play to balance multicultural concerns. So my answer
would be if we come across a great black play as we did with ``The
America Play,'' for example, we bring in a black company or work
with members of our own company who are black.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The Huntington has championed the works of writers like Tom
Stoppard and Brian Friel, August Wilson, Athol Fugard, writers who
if I'm correct you're not terribly fond of . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. I like Fugard. I like him more as a saint of the theater than
I do as an artist of the theater. I like some of August Wilson. Tom
Stoppard I think of, as I've said before, as a university wit, a
very clever fellow. But the kind of deeper resonances that I look
for in the theater he doesn't have. He may develop as he gets
older, he's still a young fellow (laughs). But, right now, he's
interested in verbal and artistic tricks and they're very amusing,
but to me they're not worth the time of rehearsal, and with all
that effort that goes into producing, you better believe in what
you're doing and you better believe that it has a deep bottom or
else there's no sense in doing it. This community loves Stoppard
and I wish I could be more responsive to that attraction, but I
just wouldn't feel happy with myself. Yet. He hasn't produced that
play yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There isn't an aesthetic then that all those writers point
to, a naturalistic aesthetic that turns you off?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's not naturalism that bothers me. I think that, to be
really honest, naturalism is to be sought after. It will never die.
It's a very important expression of the theater. It's a kind of
middle-brow realism that turns me off. The values _ the ethical and
social and political values of many playwrights don't interest me
right now, they seem rather flat and obvious. I'm much more
interested in the values of an Irish writer like Martin McDonagh,
for example. Maybe because he's a bad boy, he's not a good boy like
Brian Friel. He's a bad boy, so he gets at things that Brian Friel
doesn't get at and I'm much more interested in Caryl Churchill, for
example, than I am in Tom Stoppard because she has a metaphysical
aspect to her work and she goes into strange subterranean areas
that . . . Stoppard's mind is entirely intellectual and his
achievements are entirely intellectual, whereas she's on to
something unconscious and dreamlike. That appeals to me more.
</P>
<P>
   I guess if you want to know what my aesthetic is, it can't be
summed up in a single sentence, but certainly it has to do with
plays that do touch on the dream life in some way and that don't
leave us alone after they're over. They follow us home and invade
our dreams, invade our sleep and haunt us, and I don't think the
more intellectual, witty dramatists do that. I love Shaw but I
don't think Shaw did that except in one play, ``Heartbreak House,''
and I don't think Stoppard does that and I don't think Brian Friel
does that. Friel is a very able writer who just doesn't touch my
nerves. August Wilson is potentially a very profound poetic writer.
I think he was, frankly, misled by directors into more prosaic
areas, that if he is given latitude he will write very beautiful
and pointed plays. ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' for example, I
think is probably his best play. ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone''
does turn on these haunting, mysterious areas of life that the
others don't. The others are quite predictable and as a result
prosaic, which I think is a shame, because he's a poet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Looking back over that whole debate with him (August Wilson)
_ literally the Town Hall debate (in New York) and the whole
artistic debate over black separatism _ do you think you've been
misinterpreted on that score?
</P>
<P>
   A. I was really quite astonished at the incompetence of a good
number of the reporters that reported on the event. There were one
or two that got it right; most of them didn't. They completely
misunderstood what they saw or heard and that's why it was
important to me to republish in my own book, ``Cultural
Calisthenics,'' what I had actually said because the Times had four
different stories on it and only one story was correct.
</P>
<P>
   . . . Truly, I am very much in favor of good black theater and
very much in favor of what Wilson's in favor of, identifying those
theaters and channeling foundation money to them instead of bribing
white theaters to do black plays, which is what a lot of
foundations are doing. The real issue that was the core of that
debate was the issue of segregation, which was no longer the
segregation of blacks by whites but now the segregation of blacks
by blacks, in the case of Wilson, who was really demanding that no
black actor should ever appear in plays written by whites. I
thought that was an outrageous thing to say and very damaging to
the spirits and to the careers of very good black actors, many of
whom love playing Shakespeare and love being in Ibsen and love
doing Beckett plays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
