<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7918 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-JEW-BOS &LR;      01-11 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBTLE SATIRE PUNCTUATES `JEW OF NEW YORK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE JEW OF NEW YORK 
By Ben Katchor 
Pantheon, 97 pp., illustrated, $20 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any cartoonist since Charles Schulz can be said to capture
the spirit of Everyman, then Ben Katchor can. But unlike the
creator of ``Peanuts,'' the New York-based underground comic-strip
artist makes his Everymen adults, vaguely middle-aged and largely
middle-class working stiffs who wander a world populated by lost
souls and misplaced Old World remnants. His character Julius Knipl,
who figures in Katchor's two previous books (``Cheap Novelties''
and ``Julius Knipl, Real Estate Photographer'') and various
alternative newspapers, pounds the pavements questioning the great
little mysteries of the city: How, for example, sign letterers
convince upper-story commercial tenants to buy their services for
signs clearly not legible from the street, and why the men who sell
8-foot balloons on street corners invariably pick the wrong
corners. In his latest book, ``The Jew of New York,'' Katchor uses
the same sense of the absurd to explore various religious and
theatrical subcultures of the 1830s _ simpletons, con men, and all.
</P>
<P>
   Sound weighty? Despite its undercurrent of social satire, ``The
Jew of New York'' is not particularly heavy stuff: In Katchor's
scratchy drawings, men imitate beavers, slapping the water with
bare feet instead of tails, and a master plan is laid for
carbonating Lake Erie. But it is far from the usual comic strip,
relying on angular, Ben Shahn-style illustrations and quirky,
interlocking plot lines for its appeal. Often compared to film
noir, Katchor's drawings evoke a nostalgia for the way the city
appeared to us as children: towering, dark, and mysterious. His
stories follow suit, noting the detail (the buttons on a suit, the
smell of herring) that a child would, particularly if that child
was raised in (or raised on stories of) New York's Jewish Lower
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   With his Pulitzer-winning retelling of a Holocaust story,
``Maus,'' Art Spiegelman should have laid to rest the notion that
comic strips (excuse me _ ``graphic novels'') cannot be art. But
Spiegelman's fellow underground comic-strip artists _ including
Katchor _ had been laying the groundwork for years before the 1986
``Maus,'' using thought balloons to encapsulate Existentialist
thought and crosshatching to evoke darkness of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   With this third book, Katchor takes the next step, following
almost literally in Speigelman's footsteps. ``The Jew of New
York,'' in fact, came about in 1992 when the Jewish weekly The
Forward finished its serialization of Spiegelman's ``Maus II'' and
was searching for a replacement. For the weekly, Katchor wove a
fictional tale around a real character, Mordecai Manuel Noah, who
in 1825 bought a small island in the Niagara River between New York
and Canada and tried to establish it as a Jewish homeland, a
proto-Israel in the New World. Katchor, who had created pieces for
Spiegelman's Raw magazine, spun the convoluted story (in which Noah
is a minor, but catalytic, character) into 52 installments, each of
which was ``passionately followed,'' The Forward's cultural editor
told The New Yorker after the series's completion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of its genesis in serial format, ``The Jew of
New York'' also resembles a Charles Dickens work, albeit with a
Yiddish accent. Its cast of misfit characters goes through the same
kind of adventures and strange meetings designed to keep readers
hanging on, and the added visual element shores up the wilder and
more exotic plot twists. Will Maurice Ketzelbourd, the baptized Jew
turned beaver-pelt trader, ever meet Miss Patella, the one-legged
actress whom he idolizes? A playbill from one of her shows floats
between panels, and a pamphlet on the dangers of onanism punctuates
a chapter. Will Nathan Kishon, the disgraced kosher butcher, wander
through the wilds of upstate New York forever? Graphic (but not
disgusting) illustrations make his shame clear as they compare
kosher and non-kosher beef tongues. Will Isaac Azarael's shipload
of mother-of-pearl buttons ever come to shore? And who exactly is
the man in the India-rubber suit?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to these questions wrap up ``The Jew of New York''
in a marvelously satisfying denouement, its subtle satire bringing
about some amusingly moral endings. And if the day looks too
bright, too modern, after the book is done, Katchor's work is rich
enough to invite a second and a third read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
