</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BODY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAIL HARRIS GETS SPIRITUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BODY &AMP; SOUL 
Host and executive producer: Gail Harris 
On: PBS (check local schedules) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five years ago, with workplace demands multiplying so
fast that her professional life was bursting at the seams, veteran
broadcast journalist Gail Harris did something that not every
skeptical reporter would make time to do.
</P>
<P>
   She began to meditate.
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, that daily half-hour of self-willed tranquility
helped her cope with the stress of ``absolutely going at 190 miles
an hour all the time.'' It also got Harris thinking more
systematically about a subject that had intrigued her for some
time: the connections between mind and body, and the alternative
approaches to medicine built upon those connections.
</P>
<P>
   So after leaving WABU-Ch. 68, Harris formed a production company
and spent two years making a 13-part series on holistic health and
spirituality, ``Body &AMP; Soul,'' which began in Boston Jan. 10 and
will air on 60 other PBS stations across the country, a number
expected to grow to 120 by spring.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Harris will explore nontraditional routes to healing
and ``wellness'': lowering blood pressure through the ``relaxation
response'' of meditation, enhancing well-being through ``mindful
eating'' and slowing down the pace of life, using tai chi to combat
the ravages of age, augmenting traditional cancer treatments with
acupuncture and massage (an episode that focuses on Leonard Zakim,
executive director of the Boston branch of the Anti-Defamation
League).
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of the series is really to ask: How can we stay
healthy? And how can we live our lives in a way that's more
satisfying?'' said Harris. ``I'm trying hard to demystify this
stuff, to demarginalize it, to say `Take a look.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With a longstanding reputation as a serious journalist,
including a national news Emmy for a documentary on Hiroshima,
Harris has solid credentials for the task she has set for herself:
to do the sort of ``serious, credible reporting'' on alternative
medicine she feels has been absent since Bill Moyers's 1993 series
``Healing and the Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy to give this the once-over-lightly that
television is famous for,'' she said. ``I felt strongly that if I
could get there first, I could raise the bar for anyone who comes
behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after arriving at WBZ-Ch. 4 as a reporter in 1977, Harris
joined Shelby Scott on the anchor desk, creating one of the first
female anchor teams. Five years later, after picking up a master's
degree in public administration from Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government, Harris began a four-year coanchoring stint with
Christopher Lydon on Channel 2's ``10 O'Clock News.'' She moved on
to become a correspondent for ABC's ``Nightline,'' then in 1990
signed on as anchor of the nightly newscast of the Monitor Channel
(only after she was guaranteed she could write her own copy).
</P>
<P>
   After that channel shut down in 1992, Harris began
executive-producing a nightly show of news and analysis for
BU-owned Channel 68 and hosting a half-hour interview program. (She
also moderated the nationally televised debate in 1994 between Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy and GOP candidate Mitt Romney, and ``The People's
Voice'' series of specials cosponsored by the Globe and WBUR-FM in
1996).
</P>
<P>
   Along with those roles, Harris was also director of special
programs at Channel 68. At one point, the station had 30 hours a
week of local programming _ and Harris had begun to meditate in her
off-hours.
</P>
<P>
   She makes clear that she believes meditation and other
``complementary therapies'' are just that, and not substitutes for
traditional medicine. ``If I break my arm, I'm not going to stand
on the corner and hum,'' she said. ``I'm going to get myself to
Mass. General.''
</P>
<P>
   In exploring the intersection of spiritual-emotional health and
physical well-being, ``Body &AMP; Soul'' takes a determinedly how-to
approach. For instance, the first episode ends with a ``guided
meditation'' for viewers; episode two illustrates ``mind-body''
exercises designed to prevent age-associated memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``These concepts can be difficult to explain on television; I do
not believe anyone has attempted to do a guided meditation
before,'' said Harris. ``But I wanted to show people how accessible
these techniques are.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``New Age'' has been applied to some of the techniques
Harris tries to illustrate, but it's not a term she embraces. ``To
me, this is not New Age as much as it is ancient wisdom,'' she
said. ``Meditation and acupuncture and massage have been around for
centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative medicine is rapidly growing in popularity: Harris
cited studies showing that 83 million Americans resorted to such
therapies last year. She believes that baby boomers in particular
are receptive to alternative medicine because ``we are starting to
realize it's possible to stay healthy as we get older,'' and are
consequently drawn to medical approaches that ``look at the whole
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomers may also turn to alternative therapies because they feel
overwhelmed by the onrush of technology and the hectic pace of
contemporary life, according to Harris. ``So many of us, we're
stuck in fast-forward. Everybody I talk to says, `I've got so much
going on; my life is out of control.' What we're trying to show in
these programs is: `Guess what? You can regain control of your
life, in time-tested ways,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Harris herself is scrambling to finish
writing a 300-page book, ``Body &AMP; Soul: Your Guide to Healthy,
Happiness and Total Well-Being,'' the series' companion publication
that is due out early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I get this book done, I'm going in for a good
massage,'' said Harris with a laugh. ``I've promised myself that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
