<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WEIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDITH WEIR EXPERIMENTS ON UPSHAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A piece that doesn't in some way experiment isn't being brave
enough,'' says Judith Weir, a composer noted for her imagination,
her originality _ and her bravery.
</P>
<P>
   This week soprano Dawn Upshaw, conductor Sir Simon Rattle, and
the Boston Symphony Orchestra present the world premiere
performances of Weir's new orchestral song-cycle ``Natural
History.''
</P>
<P>
   The work represents another stage in a long ongoing series of
collaborations among Weir, the orchestra and the conductor. Weir
entered the orbit of the BSO in 1975 when she was 21 and became a
composition fellow at Tanglewood. Later she wrote an overture for
the BSO, ``Music, Untangled,'' which Grant Llewelleyn conducted at
Tanglewood and in Symphony Hall. She has served as
composer-in-residence for Rattle's City of Birmingham Symphony
Orchestra and has written many works for that orchestra and its
individual members; she is currently composing a large work for
chorus and orchestra that will be a feature of Birmingham's season
in 2000 and a culmination of Rattle's special millennium project.
</P>
<P>
   Weir was born in Aberdeen, Scotland, and came to music through
playing the oboe in youth orchestras. ``In the end, I did earn a
music degree,'' she said in a recent telephone conversation from
her home in London. ``It was only then that I formulated any clear
idea that being a composer was what I really wanted to be. In my
teens, I had many interests in all the arts, the way so many
teenagers do, but music was the one that took over. My family was
very fond of music, but the idea of having a professional career in
the arts was not something any of us were familiar with, and
becoming a composer isn't the sort of ambition I would have spoken
to anybody about.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir came to Tanglewood because of a chance meeting with a
legendary Tanglewood figure, composer Aaron Copland. ``I had
vaguely heard of Tanglewood. Then Copland came to my hometown of
Aberdeen for a big festival of youth orchestras. I was still a
student, but had a piece of mine played, and Copland somehow heard
it. I had a short conversation with him and asked him about
Tanglewood, and he ended up by very kindly writing me a reference
for the entrance procedures.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Value of Tanglewood &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weir says although she had strong training in Scotland and
England, she found the Tanglewood experience particularly valuable.
``I was studying at Cambridge University, which at that time was a
very old-fashioned academic environment; fugue and counterpoint
were taught, but not contemporary music, and there was no
opportunity to hear your music played. I came to this environment
at Tanglewood where I was surrounded by my contemporaries, some of
them very much further on with their ideas than I was, and music
was all around. Olivier Messiaen was the composer-in-residence that
summer. I idolized his work, but didn't even know he was still
alive! My teacher was Gunther Schuller, to whom I still feel very
grateful because he is such a practical thinker about music. I
would like to stress how grateful I am for this experience _ the
whole thing was paid for, including my airfare. You can't imagine
how much it means to a young person to receive that kind of
hospitality. It does sow a feeling of lifelong connection with
Boston and the orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir's music has been regularly performed by two of Boston's
leading new-music ensembles, Richard Pittman and the Boston Musica
Viva and Dinosaur Annex, whose artistic director, composer Scott
Wheeler, was a Tanglewood classmate of Weir's. The Music Production
Company has also produced performances of her work. She spent a
term studying computer music at MIT (``computers were very
different back then''), and has held residencies at Harvard
University and the New England Conservatory of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Weir has established herself as one of the
principal composers of her generation. She has won a particular
reputation for dazzling achievements in chamber opera, but there is
something vividly theatrical about nearly all her music.
</P>
<P>
   Weir says she doesn't really know how Dawn Upshaw came to be
interested in her music. ``The commission came from the orchestra,
and with her blessing, though she hasn't sung any of my other music
as I know. Nevertheless, when I met her, she seemed quite familiar
with my work; she does her homework. It was through the commission
that we got together _ her summer as a Tanglewood fellow was long
after mine. . . . Long before I had any idea of working with her, I
owned some of her CDs, and out of sheer choice and for the pleasure
of it I had been to a number of her concerts. Among the qualities
of her singing I was thinking of when I wrote the cycle was how
incredibly clear she is with text _ she tells stories in music. So
obviously I had to choose a text that has interest and intellect in
it. Dawn also has a very opulent voice, so obviously the piece had
to give expression to that as well. My choice of texts from
Chuang-Tzu allows her do do story telling, these are little
stories, but they also express heightened philosophical states, and
that's where the tonal qualities of her voice come in. I think of
these four pieces as recitatives and arias, and she is one of the
few singers who is as good at one as she is at the other.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The BSO in her ear &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weir also had the sound of the Boston Symphony Orchestra in her
ear as she wrote. ``I've heard them for more than 20 years now, and
I've also been working regularly with Simon Rattle. Simon is a
great enthusiast for all the orchestras he conducts, and from time
to time he would say to me, `You simply must write something for
this or that BSO player. It is very typical of him to point out
things that he enjoyed hearing.'' Like all composers, Weir also
takes a longer view. ``Of course I hope all the other wonderful
sopranos and orchestras will want to do this piece too!''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Weir's works have been inspired by Chinese and
specifically Taoist works; in her program note for ``Natural
History'' she writes that she thinks of the piece as a kind of
Taoist ``Carnival of the Animals.'' The four songs are called
``Horse,'' ``Singer,'' ``Swimmer,'' and ``Fish/Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have for some time considered Taoism to be the most helpful
of established philosophies in the conduct of modern life,'' Weir
says. ``I've been interested in Chinese thought for a very long
time. I've studied t'ai chi, and I started reading Chinese
literature in translations in the Penguin Classics. I've tried at
various times to start learning Chinese, but there isn't a big
enough space in my life to do that properly. I suppose (composer)
John Cage was another route to this. Even in my teens, I got
interested in the way he used the ``I Ching,'' and I still have my
copy of that from those years.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir has written many works of specifically Scottish character,
but even more that are not. ``I have lived both in England and in
Scotland. After I was a student, I lived and worked in Scotland for
some years, which was a bit different from going immediately to
London. I had more of a sense of being a pioneer, of trying to get
things going. Also I have a big interest in folk music, not just
Scottish folk music, but Scotland is a country with a living
vernacular tradition that isn't phony. Without having to work very
hard, I had access to a very different side of music that fed into
my own work. I wouldn't want to suggest that my music is entirely
Scottish, but you can't escape your upbringing and breeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir has no trouble with characterizing herself as an
experimental composer. ``When I was growing up in the end of the
'60s and through the '70s, it was a time of great experiment; there
was no alternative really. I still admire what I call experimental
music in all its possible guises, and one of the things I would
hate the most would be to be thought of as a conservative composer,
as one who simply upholds old values''
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, for her, in ``Natural History'' was reconciling
the large orchestra with the solo singer. In her program note, she
says she hopes that the orchestra will provide ``the natrualistic
scenery'' for the stories the soprano is singing. ``Really, I
couldn't think of too many examples in music history of successful
pieces for solo singer and orchestra _ Mahler and Strauss brought
it off, and so did Berlioz. I love `Nuit's d'ete.' For me the
problem was to find a way of using the bigness of the orchestra
without overwhelming the singer, to have a big orchestral sound and
an intimate sound from the soprano, who has her own space in the
composition. The experiment in this piece is the extreme
juxtaposition between those two things. I didn't want to cheat and
make the orchestra play quietly all the time!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
