<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTORY ASSISTANCE: DIALING UP DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Competition offers consumers some great benefits, but
unfortunately it tends to come with a lot of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Directory assistance is a good example. It used to be so simple.
You dialed 411 to find a local number and 1 plus the area code plus
555-1212 for long-distance numbers. Rates and service were
generally uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But all that's changed. Now prices and the quality of listings
vary dramatically from company to company and even within the same
company. AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom both offer two directory assistance
services and at both companies the more expensive service actually
delivers less.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, for example, charges $1.40 for up to two listings on its
traditional directory assistance service, which is reached by
dialing an area code plus 555-1212. By dialing 00, the same AT&AMP;T
customer would pay just 95 cents for the same two listings. And he
wouldn't need to look up the area code and could even get a free
connection to the number.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom has a similar deal. Its 555-1212 service is
available only to its customers and costs $1.40 for up to two
listings. Its new, heavily promoted 10-10-9000 national directory
assistance service is open to anyone, costs 99 cents and provides
up to two listings and a free connection.
</P>
<P>
   Confusing? Just wait. Other companies are also eager to snare
some of the estimated 8 billion calls made to directory assistance
each year. And the market should grow, given the phone number
changes arising from the explosion of new area codes around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   By June, Bell Atlantic expects to begin offering its national
411 service in Massachusetts. For 95 cents, customers can dial 411
and obtain local listings or up to two long-distance listings.
</P>
<P>
   Although AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom, and Bell Atlantic all tell you
their directory assistance services can be used to track down local
and long-distance numbers, Bell Atlantic is the only cost-effective
choice on the local front.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom will charge you their full price for each
local listing, while Bell Atlantic is currently required to give
Massachusetts customers 10 free local listings each month and
charge 37 cents a call after that.
</P>
<P>
   The other cautionary note about 10-10-9000 is the ``free''
connection. If you're an MCI WorldCom customer, you're connected
and charged the rates provided in your MCI WorldCom calling plan.
But if you're not a customer, you'll be charged the highest rates
MCI WorldCom offers.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel A. Simon, chairman of the Telecommunications Research and
Action Center, a Washington-based consumer group, said he is
uncomfortable with the 10-10-9000 plan since it entices people to
use it when they might be better off elsewhere. His recommendation:
Use the Internet to search for numbers whenever possible and avoid
all charges. (TRAC offers access to many of the Internet directory
assistance sites at its web site: www.trac.org.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Internet approach is that many of the
databases are not up to date. We checked listings for a couple that
moved to Tucson in August and couldn't find their number on any of
the Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The same problem exists to a lesser degree with directory
assistance provided by phone companies. ``Your service is only as
good as your database,'' said Fred Voit, communications analyst at
the Yankee Group consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, local Bell companies have the best phone records,
since customers moving in and out have to contact them to obtain or
shut off local phone service. The Bells sell access to their
databases, but some companies have balked at paying.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T struck off on its own several years ago, setting up its own
phone number database. It went through a withering shakedown
period, when operators couldn't seem to find even the most basic
numbers. The situation has improved, but company officials
acknowledge their database could be better.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic says it will pay for access to other Bells'
databases in high-calling areas such as California and Illinois,
but not in many other parts of the country. MCI WorldCom says its
policy is to buy access to all the Bell networks, but spokesman
Brad Burns said that's not always possible because some of the
Bells charge excessive rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic spokesman James Smith said the long-distance
companies are blaming the local Bells to hide the fact that they
are making very large profits on directory assistance. According to
Smith, if a company hires Bell Atlantic to provide directory
assistance for the Northeast and uses Bell Atlantic operators, Bell
Atlantic charges 30 to 40 cents a call. If the company uses its own
operators and just uses Bell Atlantic's data base, the cost is
about 10 to 15 cents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With companies charging 95 cents to $1.40 for each directory
assistance call, ``there's an awful lot of margin built in there,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD deal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one would call us hip when it comes to music. After all, one
of us listens to the ``Titanic'' soundtrack while driving a station
wagon and the other listens to Aretha Franklin in a minivan. But we
do know a good deal when we see it, and the latest CD and tape
offering from Columbia House is worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get us wrong. Columbia House still offers ``free'' CDs
that aren't really free, doesn't disclose all costs to consumers up
front, and doesn't carry the latest releases. But it finally has
done away with the annoying requirement that club members mail in a
card each month if they don't want that month's featured release.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask our members what they don't like about the club,
it's that they get shipments they don't want,'' said Sharon Kuroki,
executive vice president of music marketing at Columbia House, a
joint venture of Warner Music and Sony. Columbia House has 8
million members.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``no-more-cards'' offer is being featured in TV ads, on
the back of last week's Parade magazine, and in direct-mail
solicitations. The direct-mail solicitation offers 12 CDs or tapes
for ``free'' with an obligation to buy five more over the next two
years at full price. You can also buy another CD at 60 percent of
the full price and get two more ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   We keep putting ``free'' in quotation marks because the CDs
aren't exactly free. Shipping and handling charges apply, although
Columbia House doesn't say how much they are in its ads or give a
number to call. Even Pam Marshall, the membership director who
signed Columbia House's direct-mail solicitation, doesn't exist.
The company operator said the name is a pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   On the initial order with the direct-mail offering, you have to
pay shipping and handling charges of $2.19 per item, which works
out to a total of $26.28 for 12 CDs or tapes. After that, the fee
is $2.59 per item.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these excessive fees, the deal is attractive. If you
buy the club's highest-priced CDs at $16.98, the basic offer nets
you 17 CDs for $124.13, or $7.30 apiece. If you take the additional
offer for three more, the average price drops to $7. And the price
drops even further if you buy lower-priced CDs, opt for tapes, or
take advantage of ubiquitous two-for-one deals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweepstakes concerns
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doyle Kint of Ayer, Mass. asked us for help in getting a
long-awaited $600 refund from Travel Group International, a Florida
agency we wrote about last year involved in sweepstakes-related
travel scams. The group collects names from sweepstakes boxes at
major athletic centers, including the FleetCenter last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Later by phone, Travel Group calls participants to announce that
they ``won'' a vacation to Florida or the Caribbean. However, the
trip is hardly free after it assesses extra fees on your credit
card. Some customers even fail to get any tickets, while others are
disappointed by the arrangements once there.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Kint had agreed to pay $600 for a vacation for
two, but then never got any tickets. He demanded a refund and has
waited a year to no avail. After several phone calls to the group
on Friday, Carmen Torres, customer service manager for Travel
Group, said she personally has ordered the refund and provided us
with a reference number to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   --Discover fees go up. The folks at Discover Card notified
customers last week that fees for returned checks, paying late, and
going over the limit are increasing from $25 to $29. They also
reserved the right to make additional changes in the card agreement
in the future with 15 days notice rather than the current 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1443EST &QL; 
