<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-11 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HO-HUM SESSION COULD TAKE SURPRISING TURNS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Regular legislative sessions traditionally begin
with a lot of fanfare in Texas, partly because they are held only
every other year.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonial excitement of the Legislature's opening day may
be even more feverish than normal this week, fueled by the
Republican takeover of the state's executive branch, a new
presiding officer in the Senate, Gov. George W. Bush's second
inauguration and his anticipated launch of a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   This session will doubtlessly make some kind of mark on Texas
because it will produce several hundred new laws and make spending
decisions affecting the quality of education, health care and other
life essentials for millions of people. Every session does that.
</P>
<P>
   But after the adjournment gavels fall May 31 in the House and
the Senate, this legislative edition may be best remembered for
being unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   A few pending issues _ or a surprise controversy or two _ could
put this session on the map. But, so far, the high anticipation and
sense of drama that hovered over the past two legislative sessions
are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bush's arrival in the governor's office and his
four priorities, which he often recited in mantra-like fashion,
dominated lawmakers' workload. And, thanks to the cooperation of
Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock and House Speaker Pete Laney, the new governor
got what he wanted _ tougher restrictions on damage lawsuits,
tougher laws against juvenile crime and significant changes in
public education and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't as successful during the 1997 session, when his
property tax relief proposal inspired legislative leaders to
attempt an overhaul of the entire state tax structure. The reform
effort failed, and the governor managed to salvage only a modest
amount of property tax savings. But the effort itself dominated
lawmakers' debate and made for a memorable session.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is beating the drums for tax relief again this year, and
legislators, yielding to his overwhelming popularity and aided by a
budgetary surplus, will probably give him a lot of what he wants.
But even the governor is already indicating that other spending
needs probably will force him to scale back the $2.6 billion in tax
cuts he proposed during his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A tax reduction of that size, which may sound huge collectively,
would hardly be an earth-moving event for most Texans. Broken down
by individual taxpayers, the typical savings would probably be only
a few dollars a month _ not the sort of tax relief that would put
this legislative session in the hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   The tax debate could be more significant if the Legislature
attempts again to restructure the tax system. But there may not be
much stomach for that kind of ordeal two sessions in a row,
particularly since the governor won't be encouraging it.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few issues, however, that, if successfully
addressed, could make a significant difference for many Texans and
rescue the upcoming session from the also-ran category.
</P>
<P>
   One is the proposal, strongly supported by Bush and Rick Perry,
the new lieutenant governor, to establish a program that would
allow some students to use tax-supported vouchers to attend private
school.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher proposals have been hard fought _ and killed _ in
previous sessions, with Republicans leading the fight for the
program. Bush and Perry say they would create a limited program
with vouchers restricted to children from low-performing public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of the limits imposed _ and regardless of one's
opinion of the idea _ the establishment of a program allowing tax
dollars to be used to pay tuition and other charges at private
schools could have major effects, sooner or later, on taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential earth trembler is the effort, unsuccessfully
brought before the Legislature two years ago, to deregulate the
electric utility industry. A resolution of this issue could have
far-reaching effects on how consumers and businesses obtain
electricity _ and how much they pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   A successful effort to rewrite the 123-year-old Texas
Constitution, a difficult proposition proposed by two key
legislators, would be a huge legislative achievement and, of
course, make this session anything but unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   So could a surprise issue, the kind of thing that suddenly
becomes a big deal for lawmakers, wakes up a sleepy session _ and
reminds everyone that pre-session predictions can be, oh, so
premature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1458EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
