<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEPHEN-AUSTIN-HNS &LR;      01-11 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPHEN-AUSTIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS OF TEXAS FOUNDER TO BE AUCTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARINA PISANO  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A cache of rare Texas artifacts going on sale
Friday indicates that the father of Texas, Stephen F. Austin, was
no Betsy Ross.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 4, 1836, letter, Austin proposed and sketched a
somewhat convoluted flag design to David G. Burnet, the future
provisional president of the fledgling Republic of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It included a depiction of the British Union Jack (in red), 13
stripes (in green and white), the sun, the head of George
Washington within the sun, the words ``In his example there is
safety'' below the sun and the Texas national motto, ``lux
libertatis'' (light of liberty) over the sun's rays.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Lone Star flag _ a white star on blue with
red and white blocks _ would win the day.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's letter to his fellow revolutionary remains one of the
most fascinating papers to emerge from Texas' fight for
independence from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of 13 Austin letters, including 12 to Burnet, written
between 1830 and 1836, available for sale at the 45th Annual Winter
Antiques Show. The event opens Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the Austin collection: $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth every penny, said Kenneth W. Rendell, a noted dealer
in rare and historic letters, diaries, manuscripts and documents
who is handling the sale.
</P>
<P>
   But a Texas historian said the letters may be worth that much to
collectors of signed originals, but not to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenneth Rendell knows his market. He undoubtedly feels he can
sell them to someone at that price, but they are not worth $1.25
million to us, even though we would love to have them,'' said Don
E. Carleton, director of the Center for American History at the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The center recently was named the recipient of the de la Pena
diary, which is being donated by financier Charles Tate and Thomas
O. Hicks, owner of the Texas Rangers and the Dallas Stars hockey
team.
</P>
<P>
   The two Texans bought the 1836 diary of Mexican army officer Lt.
Col. Jose Enrique de la Pena for $350,000 at an auction in Los
Angeles in November.
</P>
<P>
   The seller was John Peace III, whose father acquired the memoir
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell rated the Austin letters more highly: ``In my 40 years
doing this work, I can't actually think of a more exciting
collection in terms of the spirit of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what struck me right from the beginning. It really
captures the spirit of what became Texas. In reading the originals
_ in holding the originals _ you really get a sense of Texas
happening, of it emerging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, you get a great Lincoln letter or a great George
Washington letter. But you don't see a whole country emerging the
way it does in this correspondence,'' Rendell said.
</P>
<P>
   The letters trace the evolution of Austin's thinking about Texas
independence as events in and out of Mexico changed dramatically.
The words convey excitement, doubts and resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first Austin is pro-Mexican, and he's sure he can work
within the framework of Mexico,'' Rendell recounted. ``Then, he
goes to Mexico City, and he wants more independence for Texas, but
still as an independent state within Mexico. He pins his hopes on
(Gen. Antonio Lopez de) Santa Anna, of all people. Then he starts
talking about the spirit of independence and how Texas really has
to go its own way.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1833, Austin carried a petition of grievances to Mexico City
from Texas. Not only was the petition ignored, but Austin was held
there for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anna gained supreme power in Mexico in 1834. He led the
siege on the Alamo at San Antonio two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend _ all goes well and glorious for Texas _ the whole
country is in arms and moved by one spirit, which is to take Bexar
and drive all the military out of Texas,'' Austin enthusiastically
wrote to Burnet when armed conflict erupted in October 1835.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who settled hundreds of families in Texas didn't
enjoy independence for long. He died of a fever at age 43 in
December 1836, while serving as the Texas republic's secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   After tracing the provenance of the 13 letters, Rendell said
they are the only major group of Austin correspondence to change
hands in 100 years. They belonged to Burnet's descendants until the
mid-1950s, when they were sold to an ``assiduous'' collector, as
the sale literature puts it.
</P>
<P>
   The collection has remained in that person's family until now.
In a field where discretion and confidentiality are paramount,
Rendell would not disclose the seller's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
