<SLUG> BC-TV-LOCH-NESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NESSIE KEEPS 'EM GUESSIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BEAST OF LOCH NESS 
part of PBS ``Nova'' series 
When: Tuesday, Jan. 12, 8 p.m. 
On: PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest known creature to swim its waters is the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, there's Nessie. Perhaps. Nessie: the serpentine
monster lurking in the murky depths of Great Britain's largest body
of water, Scotland's Loch Ness. First ``discovered'' in 1933 and
brought to international fame with a ``photo'' taken the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   Does she live and breathe? Have she and/or her offspring been
there 60 million years? Is she the dinosaur that time forgot? Or is
she but a figment?
</P>
<P>
   Yet another expedition _ again helmed by Nessie-hunting vets,
MIT-trained investigators Robert Pines, 72, and Charles Wyckoff, 81
_ was mounted in 1997. The searching techniques, photographic and
sonar, are more sophisticated. Their obsession is countered by
hopes that are measured.
</P>
<P>
   Nova was there for the week-long journey and broadcasts ``The
Beast of Loch Ness'' Tuesday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And . . . as you may have gathered: No sighting, no confirmation
of beast on videotape. (If there had been one, you would have known
about it long before now.) The local witnesses swear they've seen
something; the sonar turns up unexplained, large moving images . .
. But, alas, they acknowledge the ``tracking and imaging'' requires
resources beyond their means and luck.
</P>
<P>
   The two main theories are that Nessie is a pleasaur, a
preshistoric creature _ a snake-like whale _ that escaped
extinction or a large sturgeon or eel passing in and out of the
loch. Each theory makes sense; each has some holes.
</P>
<P>
   The show, beautifully photographed, begins with the search, then
backtracks for a historical overview of Loch Ness. This is one
murky body of water, with visibility severely limited. There are
interviews with a variety of scientists, chats with locals who
claim to have seen Nessie, and a debate over the authenticity of
Dr. R. Wilson's photo. Local folks who are interviewed don't seem
fanatically possessed by Nessie. There seems to be no conspiracy.
They say simply they've seen what they've seen and you can take it
at that.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of repeated testimony can certainly tip the scales in
a court of law. But in science, corroborating eyewitness accounts,
no matter how convincing, are not proof. A sonar reading of a large
mobile object, while encouraging _ something is out there _ is not
proof. Wyckoff, who died last year, 10 months after the expedition,
and Pines hope at the least they inspire a new generation of
explorers. That seems likely. Hope springs eternal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
