<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SNITCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNITCH' A TALE OF SLEAZY LAW ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SNITCH ON PBS's FRONTLINE 
When: Tuesday, 9 p.m. 
On: PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Snitch,'' a ``Frontline'' offering, is a distressing and
depressing 90-minute program about the nation's so-called war on
drugs. It's about the pressure to convict _ the guilty and the
highly criminal at best, the innocent or the lowly criminal, if
that's the way it shakes down. It's about the mandatory sentencing
laws hastily enacted during the crack cocaine wave of the late
1980s. It's about the overwhelming power that someone's _ anyone's
_ word, truthful or not, has if the government has placed a target
on your chest. It's about how the screws are turned on drug users
or low-level dealers, and how their families are drawn into the
case and destroyed. It's about the collateral damage _ the
inevitable innocent casualties. It is, of course, about race.
</P>
<P>
   In a better world, the entire nation would watch ``Snitch,'' and
tomorrow those viewers would raise such a clamor that Congress
would have to take notice. (Tape ``NYPD Blue'' while you watch
this.)
</P>
<P>
   We all know jail construction is a growth industry. We've all
seen the statistics that jails are overrun with people convicted
for drug use or sale. How do they all get there?
</P>
<P>
   Producer-interviewer Ofra Bikel delves into the dubious world of
those who inform for a price, that is, snitches. The price is not
money, but freedom _ or reduced prison time. The deals threaten to
turn us into a ``society of informants,'' suggests Jonathan Turley,
a law professor at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snitch'' begins with Tony, who was convicted of selling drugs
several years after he had left that business. But people in the
drug business ratted him out. In jail, he says he found out, ``you
have a prison population _ guys that are doing life sentences who
will do anything to get out of prison. In my case, there were
actually people who were reading the newspaper . . . called the
government and said, `Hey, I can testify against this person.'''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the lawyers says, snitches lie only when their mouths
are moving.
</P>
<P>
   How did the laws get this draconian? Eric Sterling, a former
counsel to the chairman of the US House subcommittee on crime,
calls it the politics of hysteria. ``The whole thing is kind of
cobbled together with chewing gum and baling wire. Numbers are
picked out of the air. And we see what the consequences are of that
kind of legislating.'' When Len Bias, a star basketball player at
the Univsity of Maryland, died from a cocaine overdose when he was
celebrating being drafted by the Boston Celtics in 1986, it hit the
late Speaker of the House Tip O'Neill close to home. His zeal to
get a bill approved set off a stampede. According to ``Snitch,''
mandatory sentencing was tacked onto the bill just before the House
recessed. There were no hearings. The Drug Enforcement Agency was
not called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the sentencing, Sen. Orrin Hatch says mandatory
minimums were necessiated because of ``these soft-on-crime judges
we have in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   Says attorney Dennis Knizley: ``We're trading our paranoia to
get rid of thse drugs for our consistitutional rights.'' Knizley
defended Clarence Aaron, who is serving three life terms for
selling cocaine. It was his first offense. He was ratted out by a
self-avowed drug kingpin, who bargained for a more lenient
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Still in jail is Joey, languishing for 10 years because he sold
$500 worth of LSD to an undercover policeman. Prosecutors suggest
his time might be reduced if his father could turn in some drug
dealers. An entire town, Uniontown, Ala., is decimated as a big
dealer testifies against family, friends and neighbors. Homes and
farms are forfeited.
</P>
<P>
   There's the case of a prominent California lawyer, Patrick
Hallinan, whose client turned against him and told police he ran
the marijuana smuggling business. ``You know, when you have a war
there's only one point of a war: that's to win. So whatever impedes
victory, you throw out of the way . . . And so this war on drugs
has led to corruption of the American justice system. It's led to a
corroding of the moral fiber of this country. I don't mean the
drugs, I mean the kind of things where you can call the wife to
testify against the husband. When you can threaten the child to
testify against the father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
