<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-60MINUTES-SFCHRON &LR;      01-11 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-60MINUTES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TICK OFF THE OLD BLOCK: `60 MINUTES' SPINS OFF INTO WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Officially, it's ``60 Minutes II,'' and it
premieres Wednesday. The question is whether it's ``60 Minutes II
Much.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because in an act of uncommon delicacy, CBS News is
placing its stout but slightly shopworn image on the line as it
attempts to duplicate ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, cluck the journalism priests, there could be a ``60
Minutes III'' and ``60 Minutes IV,'' along with overheated stories
about homicidal husbands and the latest sextuplets. You know, the
``Dateline NBC'' disease.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears were palpable at a weekend press conference in which
the ``60 Minutes II'' executive producer and correspondents
preferred instead to spout such language as ``cathedral of
journalism'' and ``the ghost of Edward R. Murrow.''
</P>
<P>
   (The ghost of Edward R. Murrow, for the record, smokes
Chesterfields and watches C-SPAN.)
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, ``60 Minutes II'' ought to be a perfectly
respectable newsmagazine. But if it does ever come to a ``60
Minutes III,'' watch out. The jig is up.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Junior will be a chip off the old block _ the ticking
stopwatch, three stories a week and, usually, letters and
commentary. It's just that the names are changed. Instead of Mike,
Morley, Ed, Steve, Lesley and Andy, we'll get Dan, Charlie, Bob,
Vicki, Carol and Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Rather, the ``CBS Evening News'' and ``48 Hours'' anchor
who is possibly overextended and forced to rely heavily on news
producers. No problem, the onetime Texas ditch-digger said at the
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked stripped to my waist in 115-degree temperatures
for minimum wage with no benefits, thank you very much,'' Rather
said. ``And that was work. We worked from early dawn 'til way well
after dark moving dirt. Now that's real work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This passion of mine, this joy of mine, it takes hours, it
takes time, it takes some juggling the schedule around. But listen,
I have worked for a living, and this beats working any day of the
week.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlie Rose, the late-night PBS interviewer, who is notable
largely for not being Bryant Gumbel. CBS is paying upwards of $5
million a year to Gumbel, who is supposed to be one of television's
top interviewers, and omits him from ``60 Minutes II''? Clearly
Gumbel is in bad odor at his adopted network. The view is that
Gumbel would benefit from a lot more self-motivation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Simon, a tough and cosmopolitan reporter in the classic
``60 Minutes'' mode. Simon covered the Vietnam War, was jailed by
the Iraqis and has even endured a preliminary screening session
with legendary ``60 Minutes'' producer Don Hewitt, who is pitching
in with ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon recounted, ``When the lights went on in the screening room
after my first piece was screened, Don Hewitt said, `The woman who
you touted as your central character _ I hate her. Get her out of
the piece. Your on-camera close _ it's the open. Your narration
sounds like you were singing in the shower and got soap in your
mouth.' And that was just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was over, and I was wandering through the corridor,
looking for a window that opened more than two inches, Josh Howard,
a senior producer, came up to me and said, `You know, Bob, that was
a really good screening.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vicki Mabrey, whose fortunes have been propelled by tragedies.
That's the news biz. She was a not-so-prominent correspondent in
the CBS Dallas bureau when the Branch Davidian standoff developed
outside Waco, Texas. She was also involved in reporting the Midwest
floods of 1993, the crash of TWA Flight 800 and the death of
Princess Diana. Mabrey is the only black correspondent on the new
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carol Marin, on the roster as a ``contributor,'' has a satchel
of local and national reporting awards. But she earned her
sainthood as a co-anchor at WMAQ-TV, the NBC-owned station in
Chicago. In 1997, the station foolishly hired Jerry Springer as a
sweeps-month news commentator. Marin quit. Her courage vaulted her
to a Peabody Award and to CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jimmy Tingle, a comedian and commentator who will be the new
program's version of Andy Rooney, presumably with less scary
eyebrows. Tingle, who wasn't at the Pasadena press conference,
specializes in political humor and has been seen on the MSNBC cable
channel. He could prove to be the riskiest addition to ``60 Minutes
II.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the three stories each week will be a ``60 Minutes
Classic'' piece, an old segment from the original show that's been
updated for the new program.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Classic'' segments will save some wear and tear on the new
correspondents, but executive producer Jeff Fager acknowledged that
they'll serve another purpose, too. They will be a reminder to the
viewer, a visual link between the original ``60 Minutes'' and its
knockoff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; CBS' labored decision to clone ``60 Minutes'' was all too
conspicuously unpopular with Hewitt in the beginning and spawned
what Rather calls ``scenes that were reminiscent of some Verdi
opera'' as news stalwarts beat their breasts and protested the
heresy of the new program.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Fager as the executive producer calmed the internal
critics, Rather said. Fager was executive producer of the ``CBS
Evening News'' from 1996 to 1998, a period when the program was
rediscovering hard news.
</P>
<P>
   Fager, at the press conference, tried diplomacy when he was
asked about possible frayed tempers and competition for stories
between the Sunday ``60 Minutes'' team and the Wednesday ``60
Minutes II'' team. There will be times when the two programs chase
the same story, he said, and he left it at that.
</P>
<P>
   In stepped Rather, leaning forward onstage in his blue-and-white
striped shirt, red tie and broad suspenders. Unlike his colleagues,
Rather had shed his jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me try to be helpful to my friend,'' Rather said. ``He
just gave you an answer he has to give you. Here's the way it
works. At my age and stage, I no longer have to give those answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, look, Mike Wallace gets what he wants, and the rest of us
get the right to fight over it. And that's the way it should be,
because he's earned that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, that's the way it works. If Mike wants to do it,
he gets to do it. The ones he doesn't want to do or doesn't know
about, then the rest of us have the right to squabble over it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, to quote another eminence grise of CBS News, that's the way
it is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
