<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD THE BODY TAKE DOWN THE HAMMER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 17)  
 (Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the 20th century, it seemed the sobriquet was in
decline. These nicknames of affection or derision, from the French
slang  &UR; soubriquet &LR; , ``a chuck under the chin,'' enlivened the
political language of a previous era. From  &UR; the American Fabius &LR; 
(Washington) to  &UR; the Machiavelli of Massachusetts &LR;  (John Adams) to
 &UR; the Sage of Monticello &LR;  (Jefferson), American presidents sported
these monikers. Jackson was  &UR; Old Hickory &LR; , and Grover Cleveland was
 &UR; the Man of Destiny &LR;  to some,  &UR; the Stuffed Prophet &LR;  to others.
Teddy Roosevelt was  &UR; the Rough Rider &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Then the long night of innocuous desuetude set in. Only in
sports and crime were heroes and villains immortalized with
sobriquets. Honus Wagner, the great Pittsburgh Pirate shortstop in
the first two decades of the century, was called  &UR; the Flying
Dutchman &LR;  for his speed and Germanic background (based on the 1841
Richard Wagner opera, ``Der Fliegender Hollaender'').
</P>
<P>
   According to Brenda Wilson and James Skipper Jr., making a case
for socio-onomastics in the December 1990 Names, the Journal of the
American Name Society, Honus Wagner was responsible for the
nickname of his Pirate teammate John Barney ( &UR; Dots &LR; ) Miller. When a
sportswriter asked Wagner the name of the rookie trying out in the
infield, the heavily accented Dutchman replied, ``Dot's Milla.''
Miller proudly carried the nickname  &UR; Dots &LR;  through a 12-year career
in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a change in cultural orientation during the
past century,'' note the onomastic linguists, ``from one where
there was a sense of solidarity and common identity rooted in
tradition and personal relationships.'' Military leaders tried to
keep it going: from the Civil War's Gen. Winfield Scott _  &UR; Old Fuss
and Feathers &LR;  _ to World War I's  &UR; Black Jack &LR;  Pershing, to the
Second World War's  &UR; Old Blood and Guts &LR; , applied to Gen. George
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball in midcentury preserved the tradition: After Babe
Ruth's  &UR; the Sultan of Swat &LR;  came  &UR; Joltin' Joe &LR;  DiMaggio, also known
as  &UR; the Yankee Clipper &LR; , and Stan ( &UR; the Man &LR; ) Musial. And today, we
have Mark ( &UR; Big Mac &LR; ) McGwire and Frank ( &UR; the Big Hurt &LR; ) Thomas. In
football, Elroy ( &UR; Crazylegs &LR; ) Hirsch was succeeded by Jerome ( &UR; the
Bus &LR; ) Bettis. You can find more sobriquets in popular music: Frank
Sinatra was  &UR; Ol' Blue Eyes &LR; , Billie Holiday was  &UR; Lady Day &LR;  and
Benny Goodman  &UR; the King of Swing &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But it was in organized crime that the dwindling practice of
awarding a title based on a quality best held on. A previous
century's Billy ( &UR; the Kid &LR; ) Bonney and Jack  &UR; the Ripper &LR;  led to
 &UR; Scarface &LR;  Al Capone and Frank ( &UR; the Enforcer &LR; ) Nitti.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas B. Kirkpatrick, president of the Chicago Crime
Commission, sent me his latest report on leader profiles in the
``Chicago outfit'' once headed by Tony Accardo. It includes the new
boss, John ( &UR; No Nose &LR; ) DiFronzo, his adviser, Joe ( &UR; the Clown &LR; )
Lombardo, and area boss John ( &UR; Johnny Apes &LR; ) Monteleone. Crime
figures in other ethnic groups cannot boast such colorful
nomenclature.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, sobriquets have been making their way back into
politics, often based on modifications of first names:  &UR; Landslide
Lyndon &LR;  Johnson,  &UR; Tricky Dick &LR;  Nixon,  &UR; Slick Willie &LR;  Clinton (that
last stolen from the bank robber  &UR; Slick Willie &LR;  Sutton, from his
habit of slicking down his hair as well as his smooth way with
safes). Ronald Reagan had a good run as  &UR; the Great Communicator &LR; ,
but it was President Clinton who successfully styled himself  &UR; the
Comeback Kid &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   That reversal of trend, with all its socio-onomastic resonance
in a return to personalization of leadership, picked up speed late
last year with the election of James G. Janos to the governorship
of Minnesota. The former professional wrestler ran under, and
serves under, the service mark he registered in the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office, ``Jesse ( &UR; the Body &LR; ) Ventura,'' which he
established as the exclusive ``nickname and not the name of any
other particular living individual.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of that came the emergence, during the House of
Representatives' impeachment debate, of Majority Whip Tom ( &UR; the
Hammer &LR; ) DeLay. He's not happy with it: ``Sometimes I'm a little
blunt and forthright in what I believe, and that's created an image
I don't think I am, quite frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't knock it, Tom. Beats  &UR; the Screwdriver &LR;  or  &UR; the Monkey
Wrench &LR; , or as President James Buchanan described himself,  &UR; the Old
Public Functionary &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   PARADIGM SHRIFT
</P>
<P>
   The chastisement of the president continues to churn up quotes
that call for correction or amplification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I for one would have very strong opposition,'' Sen. Dianne
Feinstein of California told CNN, as reported in The New York
Times, ``to any kind of  &UR; star chamber &LR;  proceeding that's held in
private.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Squad Squad, spotters of tautologous
redundancies, landed heavily on that one.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Star Chamber &LR;  was a room constructed in 1347 in the royal
palace at Westminster, its ceiling decorated with ``starres
gilted.'' In the next century, Henry VII created the Court of the
Star Chamber in that room, and its tyrannous abuses under James I
and Charles I made it synonymous with oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Although some historians insist that it was as public as any
other criminal court, the  &UR; Star Chamber &LR;  _ abolished in 1641 by the
Long Parliament _ is now remembered for operating in secrecy.
Therefore, the Feinstein formulation of `` &UR; Star Chamber &LR;  proceeding
that's held in private'' is indeed redundant, and needlessly
verbose, superfluous, prolix and repetitive, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is we need to commence the trial,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky. ``Otherwise, it just completely makes short
shrift of the action of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   What is a  &UR; shrift &LR; , anyway, and aren't there any long ones?
</P>
<P>
   To  &UR; shrive &LR;  is a religious term meaning ``to give absolution to,
after penance.''  &UR; Shrift &LR; , the noun, varies in meaning from the
confession of sin to the penance offered or the absolution that
results.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Short shrift &LR;  was coined by Shakespeare to describe a brief
confession before execution. In ``Richard III,'' Ratcliffe tells
the condemned Hastings: `` &UR; Make a short shrift &LR; ,'' because the duke
``longs to see your head.''
</P>
<P>
   It has lost its confessional sense and now means only ``make
quick work of.'' Surely McConnell could not have been thinking of
his phrase's macabre origins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
