<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     01-11 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: WEIGHING CAESEREANS IN DOLLARS AND CENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my twin sons were born 29 years ago, fetal monitoring was
not a routine part of labor and delivery, and there was no way to
be certain the babies were doing OK while my uterus tried in vain
to expel them. So when the doctor announced after many anxious
hours of unproductive labor that he was going to have to deliver
them by Caesarean, my response was, ``I don't care if I cough them
up as long as they're alive and healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Obstetricians and perinatologists who study childbirth say that
such feelings are widely shared by mothers-to-be and their doctors.
Anxiety about the well-being of the fetus during labor usually
overrides concerns about the cost or consequences of Caesarean
surgery and even whether surgery is truly necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine years ago, only one birth in 20 was by Caesarean and
there was little reason to question whether some of these
operations could be avoided. In most hospitals, they were done only
when a surgical delivery was deemed necessary to preserve the
health of the mother or her baby.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1980s, things had changed drastically. Fetal monitors
came into wide use that could indicate, sometimes wrongly, trouble
for a fetus awaiting birth, prompting doctors to intervene with an
emergency Caesarean. Malpractice suits, too, were on a precipitous
rise, prompting doctors to be overly cautious about fetal
well-being during labor and a baby's chances of withstanding a
vaginal delivery undamaged. And, as more women had surgical
deliveries for first births, still further surgeries were scheduled
for subsequent deliveries because sometimes the same reason that
prompted the first Caesarean was still present and because there is
a small but real risk of uterine rupture if a woman with a scarred
uterus has a vaginal delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Caesarean rates _ and, consequently, costs of childbirth _ were
soaring in most hospitals, peaking in 1988 at a quarter of
deliveries. In some hospitals two of five babies were born by
Caesarean. Then came pressures from consumer groups, insurers and
government agencies to curb unnecessary surgery and the risks it
entailed. Guidelines were issued to help doctors more accurately
assess the need for Caesareans, and dozens of studies were done
demonstrating that most women who had one Caesarean could safely
deliver vaginally in later pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Caesarean rates nationwide have only inched down _ to 21
percent at last count, far from the target of 15 percent that the
government and many experts believe is appropriate. They point out
that quite a few hospitals, including some with a fair number of
high-risk patients, already have rates at or below 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, last week in The New England Journal of Medicine, four
obstetrical specialists from Boston, headed by Dr. Benjamin Sachs
of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, questioned the wisdom of
pressing toward a numerical goal without adequately monitoring the
consequences to mother and baby of doing fewer Caesareans. They see
economic pressures, not concern for maternal and fetal well-being,
as the driving force behind efforts to lower Caesarean rates, and
maintain that rates should be determined by risks to mothers and
babies of vaginal delivery, not by insurance companies' efforts to
cut costs. They say much more research is needed to assess the
safety of vaginal versus Caesarean delivery under various
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, pregnant women are not equipped to be the sole
determinants of how their babies should be delivered. While they
should be encouraged to express preferences, the final decision
should be made in consultation with the attending doctor and
sometimes by the doctor alone. To participate intelligently, a
woman must be well-informed before she goes into labor about the
benefits and risks of the various delivery options under various
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Caesarean rates are necessarily higher in high-risk pregnancies.
These might include mothers with serious health problems like heart
conditions or diabetes or with infections that could be spread to
the baby during a vaginal delivery. Another consideration is the
mother's age. Older women tend to have less efficient labor and
more complications. The risk of stillbirth is greater, too. Then,
too, many older women having first babies had great difficulty
conceiving and can ill-afford to risk losing a baby and having to
try again to get pregnant. Thus, doctors might be more inclined to
push for a Caesarean in an older first-time mother than to risk
damaging the baby in a vaginal delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems with babies, such as extreme prematurity,
multiple births, breech presentation and poor performance on a
fetal monitor, also have to be factored into the delivery decision.
Even though obstetricians know that monitors often make mistakes
and indicate trouble when the baby is fine, it is hard for a doctor
to ignore a monitor that signals that the baby is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Women who previously had a Caesarean have different
considerations. Most doctors and hospitals now encourage such women
to attempt a vaginal delivery the next time. And studies have shown
that 60 percent to 80 percent of such women who do try to deliver
vaginally can do so without mishap. (The babies of those who try
and fail are delivered by Caesarean.) However, even in the best of
circumstances, in 1 percent of cases where vaginal delivery is
attempted following a previous Caesarean, the uterus ruptures along
the weakened scar line, resulting in a hemorrhage and sometimes a
hysterectomy for the mother and emergency Caesarean to deliver the
baby.
</P>
<P>
   In most hospitals that offer courses in natural childbirth,
there are also courses in vaginal birth after Caesarean, which goes
by the acronym VBAC. Introductory sessions outline the benefits and
risks of vaginal birth for these women and can help them decide
whether they want to attempt it. The Boston experts, among others,
insist that the decision to attempt a vaginal delivery after a
Caesarean should be made by the mother, not the doctor, hospital or
insurance company. And if that attempt is to be made safely, the
hospital must be prepared to act instantly if uterine rupture
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Women also need to be flexible about their childbirth decisions.
Generally, women should strive for a vaginal delivery but never
insist on it when the attending physician recommends against it.
While a Caesarean clearly has risks, during and after the surgery
(anesthesia, infection, pain and longer post-birth recovery), so
has a complicated vaginal delivery. When, for example, labor gets
sluggish and the baby fails to progress at a reasonable rate
through the birth canal, doctors often try to assist the process
with a contraction-stimulating drug that has its own potential
complications.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the baby has inordinate difficulty getting through the
narrowest part of the pelvis, doctors may assist with forceps or,
increasingly now, with a vacuum suction device applied to the
baby's head. In a small percentage of cases, these instruments
cause cranial bleeding or hairline skull fractures and may even
damage the baby's brain. So, every procedure has a risk that must
be weighed against the benefits to mother and baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
