<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT     01-11 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(jt) 
 BY HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A Cloud Over Air Travel &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By enabling millions of people to go places they never could
before, air travel is changing society.
</P>
<P>
   It may be changing the weather as well.
</P>
<P>
   The hot, humid exhaust produced by jet engines forms
condensation trails, a familiar sight high in the sky, particularly
near air travel corridors. Under certain conditions, satellite
images have shown, these contrails can spread into thin layers of
cirrus _ those wispy clouds of ice crystals that occur above 20,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Now a French researcher, studying cloud reports from land and
ship stations over 10 years from 1982 to 1991, has shown that the
occurrence of cirrus clouds increased by an average annual rate of
1.1 percent over land, and 3.5 percent over oceans. (During the
same time, air travel, as measured by consumption of aviation fuel,
increased at an annual rate of 3.2 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the increase was particularly marked in
parts of the world, like the North Atlantic, that are heavily
traveled air corridors. But an increase was also noted in the
lightly traveled North Pacific. The researcher, writing in the
journal Nature, notes that this region is downwind from the east
coast of Asia, which has heavy air traffic. He suggests that tiny
particles of soot in the jet exhaust may be traveling downwind and
becoming the seeds for ice crystals elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Those crystals reflect sunlight during the day. And cirrus
clouds may trap some warm air at night. So all that jetliner
traffic might be contributing, however slightly, to daytime cooling
and nighttime warming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fossil Find Ages Whales &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A fossil find in the foothills of the Himalayas in northern
India has pushed back the earliest known date when whales walked
the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The fossil, a jawbone and three molars found in a layer of rock
that is 53.5 million years old, is about 3.5 million years older
than any other whale fossil, and represents a new species,
according to the American and Indian scientists who described the
find in The Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. They
named it Himalayacetus subathuensis.
</P>
<P>
   Whales are thought to have originated as land mammals on the
edge of the Tethys Sea, an ancient body of water that separated the
Indian subcontinent from the rest of Asia. Whales, the theory goes,
slowly ventured into the water in search of food, eventually
evolving into the sea-dwelling creatures we know (losing their legs
and nostrils, among other things, along the way).
</P>
<P>
   Other whale fossils, including one from Pakistan that was
previously the oldest-known one, have been found in deposits that
were associated with land mammals. The new fossil was discovered in
an oyster-bearing marine deposit. That, and analysis of the oxygen
isotopes found in the tooth enamel, indicate that himalayacetus
spent time on land and in the sea. This reinforces the idea that
early whales were amphibious and fed on fresh- and saltwater fish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preserving a Population &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Populations of many vertebrates go through cycles, building
steadily and then crashing spectacularly, again and again. There
has been much speculation as to why this happens, but no firm
answers.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Britain, for example, populations of red grouse
regularly crash every four to eight years. Now, researchers from
Britain and the United States have determined that a common theory
as to why this happens _ that the birds become infected by a
parasitic worm, which affects breeding _ is correct.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who wrote about their work in the journal
Science, performed a classical test of the theory. If a parasite is
causing the population to crash, they reasoned, removing the
parasite (by treating captured birds with a worm-killing drug)
should allow the birds to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what happened, in four local populations studied
and treated over four years. Predicted cyclic crashes did not
occur. The researchers found that in order to prevent a crash, only
about 20 percent of a population needed to be treated.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adding Illusion to Sound &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Listen to a favorite recording on a stereo system, and the
sounds appear to originate from the speakers across the room. But
listen to the same performance through headphones, and the sounds
seem to come from inside the head.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is due to several factors. For one thing, an
outside sound usually reaches the two ears at slightly different
times and intensity levels, allowing the brain to determine the
source.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered in recent years that the external
ear, known as the pinna, also provides important cues by acting as
a filter, increasing, reducing or delaying sound waves before they
hit the ear drum.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon, which scientists dryly refer to as the
``head-related transfer function,'' is lacking when the sound
enters the ear directly from a headphone. But it can be simulated
by electronic filtering that creates ``virtual auditory space,''
that is, the illusion that the sound is coming from outside the
head. Such filtering could have applications in simulators and
computer games, for example.
</P>
<P>
   One question is how much the filtering has to match that of a
human ear in order to maintain the illusion. The answer, according
to a study by researchers from Boston University, is not much. The
researchers, reporting in Nature, showed that listeners could not
distinguish a virtual external sound from a real one even when most
of the fine detail of the filtering _ the amount of increase or
reduction over the full range of frequencies _ was removed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1558EST &QL; 
