<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BANKING RIFE WITH POTHOLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Banks have won a public trust that few other
institutions can claim.
</P>
<P>
   When you open an account, you probably don't spend time
wondering about the safety of the institution. But if you are
considering an Internet bank, you have to be extra careful.
</P>
<P>
   There are legitimate Internet banks out there, such as
Houston-based CompuBank.
</P>
<P>
   However, there have been cases where con artists have set up
what looked like a legitimate bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet banking is one of the easiest frauds to perpetrate
because it takes nothing to put up a home page,'' said Catherine
Ghiglieri, Texas banking commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have found as many as nine fraudulent bank Web sites,
said David Barr, spokesman for the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.,
which insures deposits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FDIC SITE PROVES TROUBLESOME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FDIC has an online site for checking out banks, but it may
be more trouble than it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that when I tried to verify the legitimacy of
Net.B(at)nk in Alpharetta, Ga., a federally insured online bank
that shows up regularly on lists of institutions with high interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   I started by going to the FDIC's Web site at www.fdic.gov. From
there I clicked on ``Consumer News'' and then ``Suspicious Internet
Banking,'' which allowed me to reach my goal _ the ``FDIC
Institutions Search Engine.'' This is supposed to tell you whether
a bank has a legitimate government charter to conduct business and
is insured by the FDIC.
</P>
<P>
   Don't automatically presume that a bank is fraudulent because it
doesn't quickly show up on the FDIC's list. My experience is a good
example.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be sure you are doing everything just right or else
you won't find any information.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into trouble there with Net.B(at)nk, because I used the
letter ``A'' rather than the ``at'' sign when I typed the name into
the search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Even when I corrected that mistake, I was unable to find
Net.B(at)nk on the FDIC's list. I called Barr for guidance and even
he couldn't pull up the thrift. He finally confirmed it is on the
FDIC's list of insured institutions by e-mailing a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   I was able to find the institution on the Web site only after
Barr e-mailed me Net.B(at)nk's FDIC certificate number.
</P>
<P>
   I then entered the name and the certificate number. Still no
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Barr suggested I type in just the certificate number.
Voila! The bank pops up. Of course that won't work for the average
consumer because few people even know banks have certificate
numbers. (A later search using the bank's name did bring up the
information.)
</P>
<P>
   There is another way to use the FDIC's site for checking an
online bank. Check the ``Inactive'' list of institutions. If the
name of the bank shows up on the inactive list, someone may have
lifted the name and used it to name the so-called Internet bank,
Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   A better alternative is to check the legal status of the entity
you are questioning by calling the FDIC's Consumer Call Center at
800-934-FDIC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the online bank is based in Texas, check the Web site of the
Texas Department of Banking. To do that, go to the Web address,
www.banking.state.tx.us, and click on ``Institutions the department
supervises.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also has information on how to file a complaint
about a bank. You also can call the banking department in Austin at
512-475-1300.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A DEFINITE RED FLAG &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steer clear of commercial banks and savings associations if they
are not chartered by either the federal government or a state
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely won't want to send money to a bank that's not
even licensed to conduct banking business,'' Ghiglieri said.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid institutions making outlandish claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest red flags is unusually high interest rates
on their deposits,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing can be said if a company is offering abnormally
low rates on loans.
</P>
<P>
   Another red flag is if an entity that claims to be an Internet
bank has no physical address, Barr said. Look for a phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to the bank's Web address.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's something like `www.geocities.irstinternetbank.com,'
that may be a clue that it's somebody in their basement using
Geocities' free Web page to set something up,'' Barr said. ``If
there is a bank operation on the Internet, it's going to be
`www.firstinternetbank.com.' There won't be a prefix between the
two.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
