<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-TRAVEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLY BUY TRAVELERS CHECKS AND EURO READY TO GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't straighten euro bills in your wallet or clasp a euro
coin in your hand for three years. But you can spend the new
European Monetary Union's currency in 11 countries by buying
American Express traveler's checks in denominations of 50, 100 and
200 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The checks are embossed with pastel-colored world maps with
instructions in English, French and German, and have been available
since the Jan. 1 start of the European Monetary Union. The official
currencies, however, won't begin circulating until Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, euros are already hot. The topic of a special fall
Newsweek edition and lengthy pieces of prose in The Wall Street
Journal, euros are dominating discourse among Europe's shopkeepers,
who must make the transition to the new currency without turning
off tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of using a euro-denominated travel check is that
you can use it in any of the 11 euro-affiliated travel zone
countries,'' said Victoria Handwerk, an American Express
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read every day that restaurants in Paris are starting to do
their menus in euros, and I think a lot of places in the travel
industry are already doing dual pricing. How quickly that spreads
to the small towns remains to be seen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Euro traveler's checks are good in Austria, Belgium, Finland,
France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   For now, governments in Britain, Denmark, Greece and Sweden have
opted against joining the European Monetary Union. Greece didn't
meet the economic standards to qualify, according to The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   But while traveling among the 11 participating countries, euro
checkholders won't have to waste time standing in foreign-currency
exchange lines or risk losing money on exchange fees.
</P>
<P>
   And Americans returning home who otherwise might be left holding
extra German marks or guilders not spent in Amsterdam could simply
hold onto their extra euro traveler's checks until they get back to
one of the participating countries.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-year transition period, clerks at France's
supermarkets, for example, are expected to mark everything from
potatoes to toothpaste in francs and in euros.
</P>
<P>
   If countryside taverns haven't followed suit, euro traveler's
checks may be cashed for national currencies at local banks or
American Express travel offices, Handwerk said.
</P>
<P>
   American Express also plans to continue to offer traveler's
checks in foreign currency denominations for participating euro
countries until the individual currencies are phased out in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have warned that the lengthy transition time will cause
monetary confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's financial leaders, however, have argued that the
unified euro will result in a stronger currency that competes well
against the U.S. dollar and the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   To buy American Express traveler's checks in euros, contact your
bank or local exchange bureaus, travel agencies or the American and
Canadian Automobile Associations. American Express card holders
also can order the checks by calling toll-free (800) 221-7282. The
checks will arrive by mail.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
