<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW GOOD WORDS FOR BILL CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the grinding accusations, may we hear just a few kind words
for Bill Clinton, man and president? The mortal mix of good and
bad, vice and virtue, whom we've twice picked to lead us.
</P>
<P>
   Our instincts did not betray us. He is what we saw. A basically
generous person. Big of mind and heart. Prodigious physical
energies and unrelenting drive. He hasn't used his talents or
office to enrich himself, and he is far kinder to his critics than
they to him.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, faults for sure! And they are well-publicized. But we were
never blind to these when we thought he could help our country in
its troubles. And help us he surely has!
</P>
<P>
   Do Clinton's good deeds count for naught? I discern in him more
good than bad. Let's see him whole and weigh the balance before
pronouncing final, fatal judgment. Wouldn't we wish such treatment?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a reflection of us from whom he came. Nurtured in the
bosom of our humanity, brought up in the culture of an indulgent
generation, he is flawed and imperfect, as are we all _ a microcosm
of modern America with all its contradictions. It is we, as well as
he, who are on trial.
</P>
<P>
   We chose him. Polls say two-thirds of us still want him. And
they presume a mighty, almost godlike power, those 100 mortals in
the U.S. Senate, if they pronounce the American people wrong,
decree that we may no longer have the president we chose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, but he lied!'' I hear accusers say. And have they never
stretched the pure, harsh truth of their own most private thoughts
and deeds? Not once concealed a secret failing of theirs to protect
the ones who love and trust them? Then let these sinless choose.
</P>
<P>
   But wait! May they not first consider the good the man has done?
The positive examples that he's set?
</P>
<P>
   They speak of truth. Then weigh the truth of his promises to us,
the people. Clinton said he'd try to balance our national budget.
And this he's done. First time in 30 years! Since Lyndon B.
Johnson! Other presidents pledged this result quite solemnly but
didn't bring it off. Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd promote the nation's economic growth. During his
six years, we've enjoyed the longest period of continuous economic
growth in America's history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to hold inflation down, and cost-of-living
indices have been steadier in these six years than in any
comparable period in statistically recorded memory.
</P>
<P>
   He and Vice President Al Gore promised to reduce the federal
bureaucracy. Critics scoffed in cynical disbelief. But they've done
it. There are fewer federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the plight of the working poor, Clinton swore to
raise the minimum wage and pursue policies that create more jobs
for people cast off by corporate downsizing, mergers and
globalization. At least partly as a result of his efforts,
employment numbers are higher than ever in American history.
Unemployment has been lower _ for longer _ than ever before!
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, on balance, has made good on his word to the
American people. In the big things. The things related to his job.
In his contract with us.
</P>
<P>
   Some who now clamor for the president's public humiliation on
grounds of lying have been out to destroy his presidency since he
first took office. A persistent remnant have accused him of
assorted crimes from Day One. They tried to prosecute him legally
over Whitewater, over poor Vince Foster's suicide, over personnel
files, over replacing travel office employees, over campaign
donations.
</P>
<P>
   No president in my personal recollection has been so
relentlessly hounded and verbally abused as has Clinton. Rep. Newt
Gingrich called him and the first lady ``enemies of normal
Americans.'' Rep. Dan Burton referred to the president as a
``scumbag.'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey said ungentlemanly
things about Hillary Rodham Clinton. A cottage industry floods the
Internet with outrageous accusations implicating the president
personally in the deaths of countless individuals. Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott hinted that the president ordered military action
against Iraq for partisan political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not responded to any of these in kind. He has been
patient, gentlemanly, restrained, rising above the scatological
level of almost unbearable personal calumny. Even now, he continues
working steadily, daily, on the public business to which his oath
of office commits him.
</P>
<P>
   Is all this not a decent example for our children? A worthy
lesson in public civility and good manners? Clinton has been
consistently gentle and generous with even his most strident
critics. Bigger than vengeance. Never overbearing in victory. Last
year in a White House ceremony, he awarded the Medal of Freedom to
his recent presidential opponent, Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   To those who insist that justice will not be done until Clinton
is publicly punished, let me ask: Do you really suppose he hasn't
been punished, probably more hurtfully than we can imagine?
Harassed for five years by a prosecutor with a huge staff and
unlimited public funds. Bled dry financially and driven deeply into
debt in his own legal defense. Publicly embarrassed by daily
recitations to all the nation of his most private sins? Now
publicly condemned and formally ``impeached'' by the House! Just
how many pounds of flesh must we demand?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is imperfect. But he has been a good president. I
marvel at his and Hillary Clinton's physical endurance and mental
stability. And I wonder how anyone other than a fool, a saint or a
masochist would ever want to be our president.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
