A8120 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     01-11 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GOOD SAMARITAN MIGHT HAVE SAVED THIS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard not to think about James Richard Robinson and the way
he must have died. He was 14, poor and alone.
</P>
<P>
   That's how they found him on Christmas Eve, anyway. Shirtless
and face down in a creek of freezing water. A photograph of him
showed cheeks with traces of baby fat, but his eyes were not at all
the eyes of an infant or even a 14-year-old. They were much older
and sadder.
</P>
<P>
   The headline over the latest story of his life read ``Death of a
Dream.'' But you only had to look into his eyes to know that if
James ever had a dream, it died long before his body turned cold
that December day in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   To dream is to have hope for the future. But for too many kids,
the future is that short period of time between now and the moment
when they have to figure out where they'll get their next meal or a
place to sleep. Tomorrow doesn't figure into their thinking. And I
suspect that with a convicted child molester for a father and a
mother who allegedly struggled with drug abuse, that's how it was
when James died.
</P>
<P>
   I read his story, meet the people whose lives he touched, and I
can't help but remember the parable of the good Samaritan. You may
recall the story of the Jew who, on his way from Jerusalem to
Jericho, was stripped, beaten and left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the story goes, a priest came and passed without offering
help. So did a Levite. But when the Samaritan saw him, he bound his
wounds and took care of him. The Samaritan had such compassion, in
fact, that he prepaid the man's bill before going on his way.
</P>
<P>
   And so I couldn't help but wonder whether James would have met a
similar end had he had the benefit of a good Samaritan. What would
have happened, for instance, if one of the adults in his life _ his
mentor, a schoolteacher, a Child Protective Services official _ had
stayed around long enough to make sure he was provided the tools he
needed to survive? What if his parents had put aside their needs
for his?
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, I was struck by the Rev. Roosevelt Sutton's
scolding of James' parents on the day of his funeral. ``That's me
lying there!'' the reverend shouted. ``I'm lying there because my
parents started to neglect me!''
</P>
<P>
   As a news reporter, I've covered tragedies like this a million
times, it seems. For a time, local ministers, at least, were
calling news conferences with regularity to denounce crime in the
black community.
</P>
<P>
   But like the priest in the parable, they look on, they show up
at the funerals and do nothing. It is a lot easier to pass judgment
than to help.
</P>
<P>
   There were people, though, who did try to help James. People
like Vernon Newton, head of the Fort Worth chapter of a mentoring
group called the Buffalo Soldiers, and Patricia Scott Barron, a
grandmother who gave him a safe place to stay, who fed him on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the problem was that James didn't respond. I've met
teen-agers like that. I work with some in the Birthing Project,
teen-age mothers so needy they don't even realize they need help. I
also know adults who give up trying, who throw in the towel the
minute things turn tough, and I've heard people say you can't make
someone accept a helping hand if they don't want it.
</P>
<P>
   I tell these people they're right, but none of us has a right to
quit trying to help others help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, police were still trying to piece together the final
days of James' life. Even as he was buried, there was no official
cause of death. Blood tests are pending. So is a $1,000 reward for
information, provided foul play was involved.
</P>
<P>
   We may never know what happened to James Robinson, but we ought
to make sure it doesn't happen to another child.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
