<HEADER>
A8122 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDRIVERRANGE-TEX     01-11 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDRIVERRANGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLICE OF TIME: WIND RIVER RANGE PROVIDES A TRIP THROUGH NATURAL
HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD MASON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In earth history, it was not long ago. The best general date
for it was ten million years ago _ when the central Rocky
Mountains, which had long since taken form as we know them, were
buried up to their chins. Only the highest peaks remained
uncovered. ... The summits of the Wind River Range were hills
....''
</P>
<P>
   _ John McPhee, ``Rising From the Plains''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Wyoming Rockies are no longer buried in volcanic ash, and
the Wind River Mountains are considerably higher than hills. Our
tiny backpacking expedition explored the question in exhausting
detail.
</P>
<P>
   On a memorable August day, we climbed above the tree line in
this unique part of the world, up past the remnants of ancient
glaciers, around boulders they left behind, back in time.
</P>
<P>
   When the glaciers lost their grip on west central Wyoming long
ago, the lazy, ash-choked rivers on McPhee's ancient plain
straightened and gathered speed, slicing down through rock and fill
alike. The result is a spectacular cross section of natural
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every period in the history of the world is represented in
Wyoming,'' McPhee writes in his book, which makes an excellent
traveling companion.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to be a rockhound to enjoy the wonder of Wind
River country, although you'll see them chipping away on rocks by
the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to shoulder a pack, either. Near Lander, Wyo.,
you can drive up Sinks Canyon to see the Popo Agie River disappear
into a limestone cave. Po-PO-zha, rhyming with ``ambrosia,'' is the
consensus pronunciation, but feel free to add your variation to the
multitude.
</P>
<P>
   The river reappears just down the road in a tranquil pool called
the Rise. In the most plausible explanation of its disappearing
act, limestone veins offered less resistance than the surrounding
granite when the glacial melt gathered speed.
</P>
<P>
   Sinks Canyon State Park hosts a speakers' series on Tuesday
evenings during the summer featuring geologists and other experts.
Call the Lander Chamber of Commerce for details at (307) 332-3892.
</P>
<P>
   Up the road a bit, past the University of Missouri geology camp,
turn off on Wyoming 131 and climb 2,000 feet to a broad sweep of
fill that survived the floods. Motorists can drive for miles along
this lush, forested plateau _ a striking contrast to the arid
plains below.
</P>
<P>
   Or drive through the Wind River Canyon on U.S. 20 north of
Shoshoni. Unique in the world, Wyoming rivers set their courses
with no regard for the mountains buried beneath them. Here, the
Wind River cut the Owl Creek Mountains in half as it sliced down
through thousands of feet of sediment.
</P>
<P>
   Signs along the highway identify the geologic strata it passes
through with the river boiling alongside, still working its way
down to the continental basement.
</P>
<P>
   The Wind River becomes the Bighorn River north of the mountains.
Settlers named it twice because they couldn't conceive of a stream
that flowed into the mountains and came out the other side.
</P>
<P>
   This is geology that shaped history. Travelers on the Oregon
Trail followed the Sweetwater River through this part of Wyoming,
in part because it blasts right through Wyoming's granite hills.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades later, the Union Pacific railroad exploited a thin
remnant of volcanic fill stretching east to Cheyenne. The
gangplank, as geologists call it, allowed UP to lay tracks to the
summit of the Rockies with nary a switchback. Interstate 80 follows
the same route today.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling, empty Wyoming is less blessed by air service. United
Air Lines offers an occasional bargain flight from Dallas//Fort
Worth Airport to nearby Riverton, Wyo. But plane fare is just a
down payment. Tourists need a rental car to see this country, and
the miles pile up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a car trip that links the Wind River country with
Yellowstone National Park 180 miles north. Yellowstone's fire,
added to the Wind River's wind, ice and rain, makes the trip a
grand slam in continent-building.
</P>
<P>
   We drove to Wind River country in a marathon spanning two days
and 1,100 miles. I'm too frugal to leave a rental car at the trail
head with the meter running.
</P>
<P>
   These trails are congested, by backpacking standards. The
National Outdoor Leadership School in Lander and the university
geology camps scattered through the area are spreading the word
about the Wind River Range.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't disappoint. The middle fork of the Popo Agie roars
down steep canyons in its lower reaches. Then it turns as peaceful
as the Trinity in August for long stretches above 9,000 feet in
elevation.
</P>
<P>
   The meadows and pine forests at this height rest atop remnants
of the ancient fill. At one spot, we gazed two miles across a
canyon to see the plateau continue on the other side like the
distant end of a collapsed bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there is no easy feat. The charm of Wind River country
is its surprising horizontal nature, but its trails seem to be
mostly up or down. Its canyons are young and steep by mountain
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Its peaks are old and weathered. The Wind River range lacks
soaring grandeur because glaciers ground the peaks to unimpressive
nubs. But there's still wonder above the tree line. The glaciers
carved out vast, barren bowls beneath the weathered peaks and
dotted them with lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Our destination on this trip was Ice Lake, the highest in a
string of lakes stretching west from Chimney Rock Mountain. Our
final push, above the glaciers, took the better part of a day.
</P>
<P>
   Cresting the rim above Ice Lake at 3 p.m., we paused to rest on
a slope strewn with boulders the size of cars. Mosquitoes rose from
the grass to greet us, flying groggily in what passes for the heat
of the day at 11,000 feet. Ice Lake doesn't thaw until August.
</P>
<P>
   Glistening below, silver threads linked the lake to the last
vestiges of ice on the mountain rim and to its sister lakes below.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to imagine that the glaciers melted yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
