r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-PREDICTION-HNS &LR;      01-11 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-PREDICTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEOLOGISTS HOPE TO PREDICT QUAKE ACTIVITY IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Someday a big earthquake will strike the San
Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   When and where no one can know for sure. But geologists hope to
make a few intelligent guesses between now and October, when the
U.S. Geological Survey is scheduled to issue, for the first time in
almost a decade, an estimate of how soon, and on which faults, the
region is likely to seriously shake.
</P>
<P>
   To make the report as authoritative as possible, geologists have
launched one of the grandest research campaigns in the history of
geology, the Bay Area Paleoearthquake Experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Geologists plan to dig numerous windows into the past: at least
15 deep trenches along major faults this year alone. With luck, the
trenches will enable them to learn how frequently quakes have
struck different faults over the past 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   And that might enable them to estimate where the next quakes
will strike and when. The experiment ``will be a major step forward
in our understanding of earthquake hazards in the San Francisco Bay
area,'' said geologist William Lettis, a leading figure in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Geologists will be able to identify and date signs of past
quakes on the dirt walls of the trenches. In this way, they hope to
learn whether quakes strike certain faults in cycles or clusters,
rather than randomly.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 72 scientists, geologists, and seismologists are
involved in this probability study,'' said David Schwartz, the
project coordinator for the USGS.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Cluff, another geologist close to the USGS study, said he
expected the research would show the likelihood of another major
quake in the Bay area ``may have increased to as much as 80 percent
likelihood over the next 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A magnitude 7.0 quake could occur at any time on any of the
eight or nine segments of big faults that traverse the greater Bay
area,'' said Cluff, who is the head of geosciences at the Pacific
Gas and Electric Co. PG&AMP;E, which is concerned about quake threats
to its power lines and facilities, is funding most of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff, the past chairman of the state Seismic Safety Commission,
said the likeliest faults to quake over the next three decades are
the northern part of the Hayward Fault, which runs through
Berkeley, Oakland and Richmond; the Hayward's northern extension,
called the Rodgers Creek Fault, which passes through Santa Rosa in
Sonoma County; and the segment of the Calaveras Fault that runs
from near Anderson Reservoir east of Morgan Hill to Danville.
</P>
<P>
   Geologists began digging the trenches in September. The study
aims to determine the dates of past quakes ``on the San Andreas,
Hayward, Rodgers Creek, San Gregorio, Calaveras, Concord-Green
Valley, Greenville and Maacama faults,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The next probabilities report is scheduled for release on Oct.
15, 1999 _ two days before the 10th anniversary of the Bay area's
last severe quake: the magnitude-7.1 Loma Prieta quake that killed
67 people and caused $6 billion in damage in San Francisco, Santa
Cruz and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the USGS issued a probabilities report estimating a
two-thirds chance of another quake with a magnitude of 7.0 or
higher anywhere in the Bay area between then and 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ``we've learned about the faults'' in the region,
thanks partly to new trenching, said USGS quake specialist Bill
Ellsworth. Hence, the 1999 report's forecasts of quake likelihoods
should ``be much more robust than they were in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
