u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGISLATURE-OUTLOOK-H     01-11 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-OUTLOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING FEW CRISES, 76TH LEGISLATURE CAN FOCUS ON WINDFALLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Legislature, legendary for its fiery
political debates and wacky proposals, opens a 140-day session
Tuesday that will be marked by a conservative agenda and a liberal
amount of spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and legislative leaders, relishing the
scarcity of crises and the record budget surplus, are setting a
tone of harmony, bipartisanship and preparation for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``My priority is public education, and my second priority is a
tax cut,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that this session, his third as governor, will be
cordial unless warfare erupts over the 2000-2001 state budget, how
to spend the surplus and &UR;  &LR; money from the state's tobacco
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a conflict, that's where the conflict will be,''
Bush predicted. ``I would hope that the session is a relatively
calm session. There's a chance that it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Several sources have said that Bush, a likely candidate for
president, and his staff have put out the word that this session is
to be one of affability.
</P>
<P>
   The 150 House members and 31 senators will attempt to grant some
tax relief, improve schools, toughen welfare rules and deregulate
electric utilities. When they're not tackling major policy issues,
they'll tinker with laws that affect daily life in Texas for at
least the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a healthy Texas economy and a windfall settlement with
tobacco companies, there will be enough money to maintain current
services, lower some taxes and make significant investments in
big-ticket items, including some of those promised by Bush in his
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership's wish list also includes new roads, better child
services and teacher pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   With a long list of campaign promises to fulfill, Bush vowed not
to ``disrupt'' the 76th Legislature as he tests the waters for his
possible presidential bid in 2000. He has yet to form a formal
``exploratory'' committee to raise money, but he might as early as
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will disrupt the process is if I'm not here,'' Bush said
in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit that I'm interested and I'm thinking about running for
president. I haven't made up my mind yet. And I'm certain there's
going to be _ particularly during this legislative session _ a lot
of speculation'' about his motive, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov.-elect Rick Perry, the first Republican to win the
office in modern times, plans to work with Bush and the Senate's
GOP majority on a conservative agenda built around improving public
schools and lowering taxes through cuts and credits.
</P>
<P>
   Perry joins Bush in supporting recycled proposals to limit
access to abortions and reimburse families that send children to
private schools. Perry will begin presiding in the Senate after he
and Bush are inaugurated Jan. 19. Then the new lieutenant governor
will appoint the Senate committees that will plow into the
session's work _ including the 700 measures that were already on
file last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate lends itself to a very bipartisan approach. You've
got to have 21 votes (a two-thirds majority) to get out a piece of
legislation,'' Perry said. About 5,000 bills are usually filed,
though only one in five meets final approval.
</P>
<P>
   While the GOP holds a narrow majority in the Senate, Democrats
still hold a dwindling majority in the House, where Speaker Pete
Laney, D-Hale Center, is expected to be re-elected Tuesday to a
fourth term. Unlike Perry, Laney said he isn't pushing an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   He said his top objective is representing his Panhandle
district, but he joins Bush and Perry in endorsing tax relief and
some version of electric utility deregulation if it lowers costs
for average consumers. Laney discourages members from treating the
budget surplus like a pie that must be divided and devoured. He
wants it allocated to necessary and lasting projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money needs to be an investment into the future,'' Laney
said. ``You've got to look down the road rather than just dividing
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that's what members have been doing _ in their dreams _ for
about a year. Last January, former Attorney General Dan Morales
announced a $17 billion settlement over tobacco-related health-cost
claims, and a few months later, then-Comptroller John Sharp
projected that on Aug. 31, 1999, the state would end the 1998-99
fiscal cycle with a hefty surplus, after spending the budgeted $85
billion. The Texas Constitution requires that the state ``pay as
you go,'' a rule that limits spending to projected revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The income numbers for the next two-year budget period _ which
as usual are tied to fluctuating economic factors including oil
prices, interest rates and spending patterns _ continue to evolve.
Last week, Sharp's surplus projection was cut by about $700
million.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander on Friday estimated that the
surplus _ excluding tobacco settlement proceeds _ would be $5.6
billion, with total income of $94 billion. Not all of the surplus
is up for grabs, however, because of projected increases in the
cost of some existing programs and a constitutional spending cap.
Only about $2 billion might be available, according to House
Appropriations Committee Chairman Rob Junell, D-San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the projected income ``appears it's more than needed to
meet the basic needs of the state,'' Bush said. ``And the question
is, what'll we do with the money?''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has a detailed priority list for the cash pile. He
wants $2 billion devoted to property-tax relief and $600 million
worth of sales-tax and small-business franchise cuts plus new tax
credits for research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also is pressing for $1.6 billion for education, of
which $1 billion ``will go to local districts for teacher pay _ a
decision to be made by local elected officials.'' The remainder
would be divided among initiatives to boost school construction;
end social promotion; promote reading; and underwrite textbook
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Perry backs those spending priorities but emphasizes his support
of a program to fund master reading teachers and a statewide
database on gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Perry have also teamed to support two
conservative-backed measures that have repeatedly failed in recent
sessions _ private-school vouchers and new abortion restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   A pragmatic Bush said only a limited, ``pilot'' voucher program
has a chance in the Democrat-controlled House, where the issue
routinely fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to say as a society Texas is bold enough to try. If
it works, great. If it doesn't, we tried,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion proposals on file would mandate either parental consent
or notification when minors seek the procedure. ``Either one is
fine with me,'' Bush said. However, staunch House opposition
appears unabated this session.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional abortion and voucher issues are among scores that
will be addressed by lawmakers and promoted by the more than 1,400
lobbyists registered, with causes ranging from helping the elderly
to promoting specific businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hired advocates will be involved in the session's
most talked-about quandary _ how to deregulate the electric
industry. Utility titans are grappling with smaller competitors for
long-term stakes in the Texas power market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the big boys fighting the big boys, and we just
need to make sure that those of us on the receiving end of it still
have a dependable source of electricity at a reasonable price,''
said Laney, a cotton farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, too, endorses deregulation, but notes, ``We're not
interested in proposing a plan that raises the prices to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   While that battle is waged, the citizen legislature, dominated
by lawyers and people in business, will follow tradition by
pressing simpler measures as varied as life itself. Bills already
on file would affect Houston annexation efforts; stiffen
drunken-driving standards; toughen standardized tests for
schoolchildren; restrict telephone solicitors; increase teacher
retirement benefits; repeal the anti-sodomy law; and bolster
regulation of tattoo parlors.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals would abolish front license plates; create a
state parking permit for the handicapped; limit liability for year
2000 (Y2K) computer disruptions; bolster affirmative action; refine
open records and meetings laws; move primary elections from March
to May; update campaign finance laws; require more county-jail
inmates to contribute to their upkeep; and create the punishment
option of a life sentence without parole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
