<HEADER>
A8174 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SINUS-SURGERY-ART     01-11 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SINUS-SURGERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINUS SURGERY AT EDGE OF BRAIN GETS SAFER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GABRIELLE GLASER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is early on a winter morning at the Massachusetts
Eye and Ear Infirmary here, and Dr. Ralph Metson is executing what
has been until now one of the most demanding, difficult and
dangerous procedures in the treatment of sinus disease.
</P>
<P>
   With a variety of drill bits, he bores into bone blocking the
frontal sinus, separated from the brain by one of the thinnest
bones in the body. One infinitesimally small slip by Metson could
result in leaked spinal fluid, impaired vision or lost sense of
smell for the 58-year-old patient.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Metson, a clinical professor of otolaryngology at Harvard
Medical School, seems completely relaxed as he calls for larger
bits and suctions, operating less than a millimeter from the brain.
His ease, on this day at least, is bolstered by a new tool that
makes this type of operation much less risky.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, otolaryngologists performing difficult sinus
surgeries had to inch a lighted tube called an endoscope to guide
them through the twisting sinus chambers. For guidance, the only
map was a CT scan, which the surgeon could glance at while trying
to navigate by feel, through the the walnut-size cavity above the
eye, near the olfactory bulb, the optic nerve and the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Metson is aided by a machine called the Stealth Station,
which follows a map of a patient's sinus much the way Global
Positioning Systems guide a cruise missile to its target. The
Stealth Station is one of several such machines in use around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes surgeons feel so much better,'' said Metson, who is
45. ``Before this, you couldn't ever be really sure. You didn't
always know where you were going.''
</P>
<P>
   For endoscopic sinus surgery, more than 70 Stealth Stations
systems operate around the United States; the Massachusetts Eye and
Ear Infirmary here was among the first to use them. The machine,
approved by the Food and Drug Administration in 1996, allows
surgeons to take standard CT scans and transform them into
three-dimensional images. It was first developed for use in
neurosurgery.
</P>
<P>
   The monitor atop the Stealth Station, a dishwasher-size box,
shows the CT scans of James Reardon, a retired pile worker from
Billerica, Mass., as well as a computer image of his face. On the
scans, the sinuses are clearly outlined, and Metson's surgical
probes are represented by red cross hairs. Reardon's head is held
in place by a curved headset outfitted with light-emitting diodes,
or LEDs, that transmit infrared rays that are captured by small
cameras in a bar above the operating table.
</P>
<P>
   Metson's instruments, too, are outfitted with LEDs. The Stealth
Station tracks the placement of Metson's instruments with an
.87-millimeter margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   A second monitor carries a magnified image transmitted by a tiny
camera inside the instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my kids I'm in here playing Nintendo all day,'' Metson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The product, developed by Sofamor Danek, a company in Memphis,
Tenn., is now sold by Xomed Inc. in Jacksonville, Fla., under the
name of LandmarX. It costs $160,000, and requires extensive
training for surgeons already well versed in the use of endoscopes.
But it can help offset the likelihood of complications in the most
difficult cases. A similar machine, called the Insta-Trak, made by
Visualization Technology Inc. in Wilmington, Mass., uses
electromagnetic transmitters to track the surgeon's devices. It is
in use in 125 hospitals nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Reardon is among the 20 percent of cases serious enough to
require surgery, and his history, which includes two failed
procedures, made him a particularly good candidate for using the
new technology, Metson said.
</P>
<P>
   He is among 37 million Americans who suffer from chronic
sinusitis, an inflammation or infection, which has become the
nation's most common long-term disease. Defined roughly as having
three or more sinus infections a year, chronic sinusitis costs the
nation an estimated $2.4 billion a year in surgeries, office visits
and medicines. In 1992, the National Center for Health Statistics
showed that Americans missed 73 million workdays to sinusitis from
1990 to 1992, up from 50 million in 1986-1988.
</P>
<P>
   Intangible costs are just as great. A 1994 study showed that
those with chronic sinusitis reported more pain, depression and
fatigue in their lives than did patients with angina, chronic heart
failure and back pain. ``It's an epidemic with enormous impact in
this country,'' said Metson, who studies the subject extensively.
</P>
<P>
   Like clusters of grapes, the sinuses surround the carotid
arteries, as well as the optic and olfactory nerves. They are
separated from the brain by a fragile bone called the lamina
paprycia, thin enough to see through.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the sinuses is not fully understood. Experts
dispute whether they exist to equalize barometric pressure,
regulate air temperature going into the lungs, or whether they
simply evolved when humans began walking upright and needed a
lighter head. When they function normally, the cilia of the sinus
trap pollen, dust, viruses and bacteria and flush them out through
the back of the throat to the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   But when the sinuses are infected, they can cause problems.
Bacteria from the sinuses can spread to the lungs, eardrums and
even the brain. Meanwhile, pollution and allergies contribute to
the rising number of sinusitis cases. At the same time, diagnostic
tools like CT scans and endoscopes also make identifying the
disease easier.
</P>
<P>
   Medical treatment for chronic sinusitis includes antibiotics,
decongestants, antihistamines to control allergy symptoms and nasal
steroid sprays. In extreme cases, patients use oral prednisone.
</P>
<P>
   Until the advent of endoscopes, the only way to clear diseased
tissue surgically or create better drainage for the frontal sinuses
was to make external incisions just below the eyebrow. To operate
on the maxillary sinuses, which rest beneath the eyes and above the
teeth, surgeons had to make incisions in the gumline.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of the estimated 300,000 sinus surgeries performed
each year are done through the nostrils, with endoscopes. But many
are far from perfect: Some patients, like Reardon, must have
``revision'' surgery, to remove scar tissue left by earlier
procedures or extensive disease. Complications occur in about 6
percent of cases.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread use of endoscopes and lasers, as well as improved
surgical tools, has revolutionized sinus surgery. But it is a field
in which new technology is sometimes viewed with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McNamara, 43, an otolaryngologist in Washington who is a
clinical professor of otolaryngology and neck surgery at Georgetown
University Medical Center, recalls his early days as a resident,
when he taped his patients' CT scans to an X-ray view box in the
operating room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me to just be common sense, but it wasn't
standard practice at the time,'' McNamara said. ``The old school
folks wondered what I was doing. The same thing happened when
monitors came in, to magnify that incredibly small space. I felt
better having better visualization. But a lot of them say they're
more comfortable by feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, McNamara uses the Insta-Trak system for extremely
difficult cases. ``But it is not below the standard of care to not
use them,'' he cautioned. ``You don't want to put capable people in
a position where if they don't use them, they're liable. These
machines are great, marrying computers with technology and allowing
the surgeons to know where they are. But you do have to be careful.
You don't want to have someone use this just because his hospital
has it. You want someone who's familiar with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
