<P>
   CONGO-CONFLICT (Kinshasa, Congo) _ From its earliest imagination
in the minds of outsiders hungry for its riches _ gold for traders
and souls for missionaries _ Congo has rarely belonged to itself
alone. Now this huge and unsteady state has become a battlefield of
soldiers from no fewer than six foreign nations. It is a war that
has as much to do with problems outside of Congo as inside it. A
fundamental reworking of the old rules of Africa may be unfolding
in the five-month-old Congo war. By Norimitsu Onishi and Ian
Fisher. With photo and map. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-COUNCIL-IRAQ (United Nations) _ Whatever happened to the
Security Council? It seems paralyzed over what to do next on Iraq.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   reefer:
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ On Monday came the clearest sign
yet of just how much Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
estranged the Israeli political establishment, left and right.
Netanyahu's political godfather, Moshe Arens, 73, a former defense
and foreign minister, announced that he would challenge his
one-time protege for the leadership of the Likud Party in party
primaries. The primaries will select the Likud candidates for the
national elections on May 17. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
