<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      01-11 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PRO &AMP; CON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Should drug companies use celebrities, like the Baltimore
Orioles' Cal Ripken, in advertisements for prescription drugs? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRO: Until recently, pharmaceutical companies focused
advertising efforts on prescribing doctors, inundating them with
vast numbers of ``throw-away journals'' that invariably bypassed
their targets and ended up in the trash. More recently,
pharmaceutical companies have discovered that they achieve greater
success pitching products directly to the public. Recently, there
has been an explosion of several excellent drugs to treat
depression, migraine headaches, allergies, hypertension and stomach
disorders. In each class of these drugs, several more or less
equivalent versions have been introduced. The drugs are generally
safe and effective. Since the drugs are inherently good, there is
no reason celebrities should not be hired to promote a product,
since the intent is simply to raise market share. There is some
societal good in having celebrities pitch products because more
patients with hypertension or depression may present themselves for
treatments. Bringing more patients into the medical fold is
certainly good for my business.
</P>
<P>
   _DR. DARYL M. ISAACS, Internist, New York University Medical
Center and Beth Israel Hospital
</P>
<P>
   CON: Celebrity endorsements are effective because we begin to
believe that the product embodies whatever it is we admire most
about the celebrity. After all, Who doesn't want to be like Mike?
These products are drugs, not shoes or jockey shorts. In addition
to their benefits, They may carry a variety of side effects and
risks, especially if used improperly. It is misleading to feature a
famous person as a picture of health and attribute that to the
benefit of a drug, suggesting that a little pill could create those
qualities. To use celebrities to endorse products they do not use
is unethical. As my patients' advocate, I am offended for those who
do suffer from such conditions. However, neither do I see anything
redeeming in an advertisement that features a celebrity who uses a
pharmaceutical. To classify a particular person's benefit from a
drug just because he is famous is misleading. Treatment choices
should be made individually between a physician and a patient.
There are plenty of other products besides drugs to keep
celebrities in the money.
</P>
<P>
   _DR. BRIAN K. JEFFERSON, Internist, Johns Hopkins Hospital's
Department of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: Following the Trail of Adolescent Angst &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, traditional wisdom holds, are sullen, prickly
creatures, prone to mood swings and sudden outbursts of temper. But
new research suggests that for some adolescents depression _ in
particular, symptoms like lack of enjoyment in everyday activities
or frequent thoughts about death _ signals an increased risk of
serious depression in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 776 adolescents followed over a period of nine
years, researchers at the New York Psychiatric Institute found that
teen-agers who exhibited ``subclinical'' depressive symptoms _ that
is, symptoms not severe enough to warrant a psychiatric diagnosis _
were two to three times as likely to suffer episodes of major
depression in young adulthood. In particular, the symptoms of
anhedonia, or the inability to experience enjoyment, and thoughts
about death were associated with a higher risk of adult depression.
``If you're an adult with a psychiatric problem, there's a good
chance that your problem started in some form when you were a
kid,'' said Dr. Daniel Pine, an assistant professor of clinical
psychiatry who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects in the study, which appears in this month's
American Journal of Psychiatry, were interviewed in 1983, when they
were between 9 and 18, and again in 1985 and 1992. In 1983 and
1985, parents were also interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies demonstrated that teen-agers whose symptoms were
severe enough to meet the diagnostic criteria for major depression
were more likely to suffer from depression as adults. But the
researchers wanted to find out if ``subthreshold depression'' _
what many parents might dismiss as normal moodiness _ also could
predict later illness.
</P>
<P>
   Not every teen-ager with depressive symptoms went on to develop
major depression, Pine said. But parents should consider seeking
professional advice, he said, if the symptoms are severe enough to
cause the teen-ager distress, or trigger problems in school or
social relationships. For example, chronic feelings of guilt,
changes in sleep or appetite, fatigue, poor concentration,
prolonged sadness, or a loss of interest in activities that were
once enjoyable, can all be symptoms of depression, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSCLES GROUPS: Stretches Make the Arms Grow Stronger &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A recent study indicates that adding stretching to a
weight-training routine may actually improve strength, in addition
to increasing flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by Dr. Wayne Westcott, director of fitness
research at the South Shore YMCA in Braintree, Mass., followed 53
participants in a 10-week strength-training program. Each subject
worked out on 13 standard weight-training machines. After each
exercise, one group stretched the muscles just used before moving
to the next machine. A second group moved from machine to machine,
then followed with a separate session of six stretching exercises.
The third group did no flexibility exercises.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 weeks, all participants became more flexible and
stronger. What surprised the researchers was that the subjects who
stretched also showed marked increases in strength _ 37 percent and
54 percent differences compared with 29 percent. The most
significant gains were exhibited by the group that stretched after
completing the strength-training circuit. Westcott said he believed
this group benefited from the one-on-one stretching instruction
they received. While the other groups had an instructor present for
the initial run-through, subsequent sessions were not closely
supervised. ``Just the presence of an instructor motivates the
subject to work harder at an exercise,'' he said. The next step, he
added, will be to replicate the study without that variable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody pays lip service to stretching,'' Westcott said,
``but for most exercisers, myself included, stretching is the first
thing to go.'' While he cautions against reading too much into one
small study, Westcott is no longer cavalier about making stretching
a part of his own routine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
