<HEADLINE>
WOMEN DOCTORS' PAY LAGS BEHIND THAT OF MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women in medicine have made phenomenal strides over the past 30
years. They are everywhere, in every specialty, and they account
for half of all medical students; women even play doctors on
television _ with their trusty husky male nurses, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the progress, female physicians still suffer from
what might be called stipendicitis: an acute failure of the wallet
to perform as expected. According to the latest Physician
Compensation and Production survey, the average incomes of female
doctors continue to lag behind those of their male counterparts,
not just by a few thousand dollars, but by tens of thousands, and
in some specialties by more than $100,000 a year. And, as the above
chart, published in Physicians Weekly, demonstrates, the gap lately
has widened for a number of specialties, rather than diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is an annual polling of the membership of the Medical
Group Management Association, the nation's largest organization of
doctors who work in group practices. It gathered responses from
group practices representing 36,000 physicians, about 5 percent of
the nation's total _ a respectable sampling by survey standards.
The doctors reported their total compensation for the year,
including bonuses and honoraria, how many patients they had seen,
the total amount they had billed patients and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, doctors' salaries appear to be remaining fairly flat,
with swells and troughs depending on specialty and region. Heart
surgeons are in great demand, and so ``cardiology (invasive)'' is
one of the most lucrative of all specialties, although for unknown
reasons their average compensation fell 8 percent in the last year
to $326,527. By contrast, urologists' salaries climbed an average
of 3.65 percent, to $230,339, itself a 4.12 increase from the year
before, buoyed, no doubt, by increased concern about the prostate
gland, and their ability to write Viagra prescriptions. Cities like
New York, Boston and Los Angeles are so glutted with the medically
pedigreed that median salaries of doctors on either coast are
considerably lower than those of practitioners in the South and
Midwest. And for female healers everywhere, their incomes have a
particularly saddle-shaped sag to them.
</P>
<P>
   There is no single or simple explanation for why women's average
compensation is uniformly so much less than the men's. Some of the
disparity is a result of statistical skewing, arising because for
many specialties the number of male practitioners far exceeds the
number of women. For example, in the category of invasive
cardiology, 513 men were included in the survey but just 26 women.
Even in a specialty like family practice, which has attracted many
women to its fold, the survey represents results from 2,914 males
but only 581 females.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason for the difference is patient volume. Most of a
doctor's income is based on the number of patients seen, and male
doctors generally see more patients per year than female doctors
do. Among noninvasive cardiologists, for example, the men reported
seeing an average of 1,645 patients; the women, 1,356. Yet patient
load alone cannot account for the salary gap. If the average
cardiologist's income is divided by the average patient volume, the
men end up earning $163 per case to the women's $144. In
obstetrics/gynecology, the men average $76 a patient, the women
$68.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this discrepancy the fact that female physicians usually
spend comparatively more time with each patient. One study found
that male physicians managed to dispense with the majority of their
patients in less than 11 minutes each, while female doctors could
manage such celerity with only a third of their case load. The
result? The women earn less for more.
</P>
<P>
   What the survey data do not reveal is whether the men have more
experience and seniority than the women, and thus are able to
charge more for their skills. Nor does the poll say whether men
earn relatively more because they are more likely to be
moonlighting as, say, high-paid biotechnology consultants or guest
speakers at pharmaceutical meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the widening of pay gaps in many disciplines between
last year and this, researchers at Cejka and Co., the health care
consulting firm that sponsors the annual survey, said that the
apparent retrograde trend is probably spurious.
</P>
<P>
   They predict that women will soon return to the business of
catching up, particularly as more women enter the most lucrative
surgical specialties. Here is one suggestion: Women, follow the men
_ patients, that is. With all those male baby boomers on the brink
of prostate consciousness, the future of urology looks swell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
