<HEADER>
A8199 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ALIEN-TISSUE-2TAK     01-11 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ALIEN-TISSUE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING HARMONY IN THE MARRIAGE OF CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Wash., Pa.)   (af) 
By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In mythology, fire-breathing monsters with lions' heads, goats'
bodies and serpents' tails are well-known chimeras.
</P>
<P>
   In humans, chimeras form when cells from two people live side by
side in one person, during and after such diverse events as
pregnancy, organ transplantation and blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   Now the effects of chimerism are attracting new notice, both for
their benefits and their problems. New findings are beginning to
explain how the body's reaction to alien tissue can enhance
survival of donor grafts after transplantation surgery yet give
rise to some disorders not only during pregnancy but many years
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new approach to human disease,'' Dr. Selim Aractingi in
Paris said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Aractingi's team at the Tenon Hospital may have solved a mystery
of why many women itch from a rash in the last weeks of pregnancy.
The rash apparently is caused by fetal cells that escape from the
mother's womb and lodge in the skin, Aractingi's team reported on
Dec. 12 in Lancet, a journal published in London. It is the newest
evidence of chimerism's role in human disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dr. J. Lee Nelson and her colleagues at the Fred
Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle reported the first
evidence linking cells that escaped from a fetus into the mother's
bloodstream to development of a disease in the mother years after
pregnancy. The disease, known as scleroderma, affects the skin and
other organs. It is an autoimmune disorder in which the body
mysteriously attacks its own healthy tissues. The condition strikes
women four times as often as men.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sergio A. Jimenez's team at Thomas Jefferson University in
Philadelphia has extended the findings.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1992, Dr. Thomas E. Starzl's team at the University of
Pittsburgh showed that, in patients with transplanted organs, cells
that escaped from donor tissue migrated to the skin and persisted
up to 29 years after transplantation. The traffic is two way: The
patient's own cells migrate to the transplanted organs where they
continue to exist with donors cells. At the same time, donor cells
move into the recipient's tissues.
</P>
<P>
   The rash that the French team studied tends to develop over the
arms, abdomen, thighs and buttocks in about 1 percent of pregnant
women. The skin eruption usually comes on after the 34th week of
pregnancy and is transient, generally fading after the baby is
delivered. The rash can recur in subsequent pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The rash varies in severity but usually requires little
treatment: Steroid ointment for women with intense itching, and
awaiting delivery for those with a milder form.
</P>
<P>
   The rash goes by many names, usually long ones that describe
nothing more than itching and the type of rash. So doctors use
acronyms. The two most common are: PEP (for polymorphic eruptions
of pregnancy) and PUPPP (for pruritic urticaria papules and plaques
of pregnancy).
</P>
<P>
   Aractingi, a dermatologist, studied tiny pieces of skin taken
from two groups of pregnant women. One group consisted of 10 women
with the rash who were bearing male fetuses. The other group served
as a scientific control and was made up of 26 women without the
condition. Half of the women without the rash were carrying male
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Although the rash occurs in women bearing fetuses of both
genders, the French team chose to study only those bearing male
fetuses because it was easier to detect the DNA in the Y male
chromosome in laboratory tests.
</P>
<P>
   The French team found the male DNA in 6 of the 10 women with the
rash, but in none of the 26 women without the ailment. The
technique used may not have been perfected enough to detect the
cells in the remaining 4, the French scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Aractingi said his study of the fetal-cell link in the rash of
pregnancy began about three years ago before he knew of Dr.
Nelson's study. But the French study was slowed by ``disappointing
technical difficulties,'' Aractingi said.
</P>
<P>
   Aractingi said his team's next step was to try to identify the
type of fetal cell that lodges in the skin to determine how the
cell causes the itchy skin reaction. Identification is needed
because different cells presumably cause different kinds of
reactions in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the rash was thought to have little medical
importance. But in light of Dr. Nelson's findings in Seattle,
Aractingi's report raises intriguing questions about the long-term
significance of the rash. Do such chimerisms go awry to cause an
auto-immune disorder later in life? The answers might someday shed
light on this and other common ailments of adults.
</P>
<P>
   Aractingi also said that he intended to follow the women in the
study over time to determine whether nothing happens or whether
they develop auto-immune disorders.
</P>
<P>
   If such a long-term link is established, then scientists may
need to develop tests to identify people at risk for the long-term
hazards if chimerism goes awry. If so, scientists would aim to
develop immunizations and other therapies designed to stop
development of a disease in an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have likened pregnancy to transplantation because the
mother's body does not reject the fetus even though it is, in
effect, foreign tissue. Starzl and other transplant researchers
have learned a lot about chimerism from human and animal
transplants. Dr. Nelson said that she believed that transplantation
was directly linked to the immune system's role in pregnancy. That
role allows the mother's body to live in a chimeric condition.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson said she and other scientists were looking at four
sources of chimeric cells that might be factors in human diseases.
Two involve transfer of fetal cells to the mother and maternal
cells to the fetus. A third is from one twin to another. And a
fourth is from blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   Starzl said he now considers chimerism a prerequisite for
long-term organ acceptance. The transplant operation not only
replaces organ function but introduces a small piece of the donor's
immune system into the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, immunosuppressive drugs are required to control the
two-way traffic of cells and then allow donor and recipient cells
to coexist peacefully. Chimerism explains why some transplant
recipients can stop taking immunosuppressive drugs without
rejecting an organ, Starzl said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups elsewhere are experimenting with other forms of chimerism
in heart transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Starzl and Dr. Rolf M. Zinkernagel of the University of Zurich
in Switzerland reported in The New England Journal of Medicine last
month that the mechanisms by which certain microbes are able to
exist in humans closely resembles the chimerism that confers
permanent acceptance of a transplanted organ. The fate of the
microbes and the donor organ is largely determined by where the
cells migrate in the body, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   To direct further research in chimerism, Aractingi is organizing
a meeting in Paris in September. It would be one of the rare
meetings of scientists interested in the wide range of chimerism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
