<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CENTURION-ART-2TA     01-11 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CENTURION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DREAM OF ETERNAL FLIGHT BEGINS TO TAKE WING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like giant feathers slowing rising on the winds to
impossible heights, large gossamer wings made of wispy plastics and
light composite materials are flying at altitudes where few
airplanes have soared.
</P>
<P>
   Following a recent round of successful test flights, engineers
are modifying an unmanned flying wing called Centurion for an
attempt at becoming the first aircraft to achieve sustained level
flight at 100,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion is the latest in a line of solar-powered flying wings
that have steadily pushed up altitude records for remote-controlled
and propeller-driven aircraft. Last August, a predecessor aircraft
named Pathfinder-Plus, using sunlight to generate power for its
electric engines, set an unofficial world altitude record for
propeller planes of 80,201 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of these studies is to build a fleet of relatively
inexpensive drone aircraft that can routinely operate at these
extreme altitudes for scientific and commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion and similar drones are part of a program sponsored by
NASA to develop remotely piloted aircraft that can loiter at the
edge of the atmosphere, far above normal air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made an enormous amount of progress in a relatively
short period of time,'' said Jeffrey Bauer, deputy manager for
NASA's Environmental Research Aircraft and Sensor Technology
Program. ``We have identified the technologies that are needed and
now have to figure out how to make them work together, but we don't
see any large showstoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Several aircraft sponsored by the ERAST program, which was
established in 1994 and has an annual budget of about $20 million,
each had a successful series of test flights last year, including
the Centurion. ``We are close to making the transition from test
vehicles to vehicles that are ready for scientific and commercial
applications,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hope that solar-powered versions of Centurion and its
successors will revolutionize studies of the upper atmosphere, a
crucial but difficult-to-sample region important to climate change.
</P>
<P>
   There, at altitudes from 12 to 20 miles above the Earth,
engineers envision aircraft that eventually will be able to stay
aloft for days or weeks at a time, performing jobs previously
relegated to space satellites, but cheaper and better. Such planes
could serve as communications outposts in the sky, relaying
telephone or pager signals, or follow hurricanes and other adverse
weather systems, constantly monitoring their progress and studying
their behavior, as well as performing surveillance, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   These aircraft, carrying a new generation of miniature sensors
and scientific instruments, would be able to linger in the lower
regions of the stratosphere studying chemical interactions many
scientists believe are damaging the Earth's protective ozone layer.
And scientists say flying such planes over the planet's poles could
provide valuable insight into the seasonal ozone holes that appear
each year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, such craft could help monitor and measure carbon
dioxide and other so-called greenhouse gases accumulating in the
atmosphere that some scientists believe are contributing to global
warming and possible climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wide range of potential jobs for high-altitude
robot craft, NASA is looking at developing a range of aircraft,
including more conventional designs than solar wings. Last summer,
Aurora Flight Sciences of Manassas, Va., conducted four successful
flights under the ERAST program with its Perseus B, a drone powered
by a turbocharged piston engine turning a propeller attached to the
plane's tail.
</P>
<P>
   The Perseus B, essentially a 2,200-pound powered glider with a
conventional wing-and-tail configuration, reached 60,000 feet with
a 180 pound payload, said Aurora president John Langford. In tests
planned for this summer, Aurora hopes to increase the plane's
endurance at this altitude to eight hours, and reach 24 hours or
more the following year. ``At that point, we can go into production
and offer leased flight services to the scientific market,
including universities, national laboratories and others,''
Langford said.
</P>
<P>
   Current methods of doing studies in the upper atmosphere have
severe drawbacks. Satellites can peer into this region with remote
instruments, but they orbit too high to do direct air sampling.
High-flying aircraft, such as the U-2 and SR-71 spy planes, can
operate at 70,000 feet or more, but they can only stay at these
altitudes for a few hours and are very expensive to operate. In
addition, some spy planes fly so fast that they disturb the air,
which interferes with direct sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Balloons have been a mainstay of high-altitude studies for
decades, but they can leak gases that pollute air samples and are
notoriously hard to control, as has been evident in recent years by
the many failed attempts by balloonists to circle the globe.
</P>
<P>
   These shortcomings call for new methods to study the upper
atmosphere and some scientists and engineers see slow-speed,
long-duration robot aircraft as the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion has drawn a great deal of attention because a
solar-powered craft like this has the potential of becoming the
long-desired ``eternal airplane'' which seldomly has to land. And
Centurion is a steppingstone to an operational craft called Helios
that would be essentially an airborne satellite, according to its
builder, AeroVironment Inc., of Monrovia, Calif., a company that
specializes in electric-powered vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion is a giant, superlight wing with no tail that evolved
from smaller models AeroVironment started building 15 years ago. In
the early 1980s, the company got a secret government contract to
build a pilotless, solar-powered, propeller-driven craft that could
stay at high altitudes for weeks at a time. AeroVironment built a
prototype, called Pathfinder, which made nine, battery-powered
flights in the summer of 1983 before the project was canceled when
it failed to meet specifications.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1704EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
