<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEDDY-ROOSEVELT-HNS &LR;      01-11 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEDDY-ROOSEVELT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLBENT RIDE USHERS IN A NEW PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Adirondack Mountains were cold, sullen, and
drizzly on that Friday the 13th in September 1901. It was the
middle of three such days that left the ground soaked, trails slick
and visibility measured in feet and fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   A thick mist drifted around Col. Theodore Roosevelt and his
guide, Noah LaCasse, who were resting briefly along the shore of
Lake Tear of the Clouds. It was there at 1:25 p.m., while leaning
against a rock and sharing a tin of ox tongue with his guide, that
the vice president saw a man loping up the trail toward them.
``That's Harrison Hall, isn't it?'' Roosevelt asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is,'' responded the guide.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months into a new century, the number of people in a vice
president's world was small enough that the recognition of a casual
acquaintance like Hall would not have been considered unusual. Just
as when Roosevelt, exactly a day later, stepped down from a
carriage in Buffalo into a huge, milling crowd anxiously awaiting
his arrival and called out by name a policeman he had met on a
previous trip.
</P>
<P>
   The message that the panting, 53-year-old Hall ran nine miles to
deliver was indeed a fateful one ... for Roosevelt and for the
nation. Arguably, the message _ that President William McKinley
would not survive an assassin's bullet after all _ set in motion
the modern American presidency and rushed the nation headlong into
the 20th century, whether or not its citizens were ready.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt certainly wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Theodore Roosevelt is placed among the handful of
our greatest presidents, he grew into the role and brought the
nation along with him.
</P>
<P>
   For all his achievements in conservation, regulating railroads,
refereeing big business and big labor, and giving working Americans
the ``square deal,'' historians give Roosevelt the highest marks
for bringing the power and prestige of the presidency up to today's
stature and expectation.
</P>
<P>
   At first Roosevelt could not imagine becoming president in such
a manner. But by the time he took the oath of office in Buffalo
before federal Judge John R. Hazel, he characteristically accepted
the situation as it was, then embraced its possibilities with all
the bristling vigor and dash that was his personal stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The note Hall gave Teddy was from William Loeb, Roosevelt's
secretary, who had remained in Albany to monitor McKinley's
condition by phone. He relayed the news to the last telephone on
the line closest to Roosevelt, at the Lower Tahawus Club. The news
itself was a shock, because McKinley's surgeon, Dr. Charles Burney,
had been persuasive the president was out of danger.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, on Sept. 6, as the opening strains of a Bach
cantata sounded at Buffalo's Temple of Music, the president,
standing at the head of a reception line at the opening of the
Pan-American Exposition, had been shot twice at point-blank range
by a self-described anarchist, Leon Czolgosz. An utterly bored and
politically trivialized vice president had been lunching at Isle
LaMotte in Lake Champlain, a guest of the Vermont Fish and Game
League, when he received the horrifying news.
</P>
<P>
   He and Loeb set out immediately by train for Buffalo, where
Roosevelt spent two deeply uncomfortable days trying to be gray and
quiet in the background as Mrs. McKinley and family and friends
fretted over the president. Not easy for an ambitious, energetic
extrovert once described by a friend _ not a critic _ as compelled
to be at the center of every stage, the bride at every wedding, the
corpse at every funeral.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley and Roosevelt were not friends.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt thought the lawyer-farmer from Canton, Ohio, merely
politically ``clever.'' Roosevelt had been foisted on McKinley as a
running mate by New York Republican boss Thomas Platt, who in turn
was eager to get the reform-minded governor out of the state,
pronto. So Roosevelt was made vice president and perfectly
miserable. Yet when he took the message from Hall at Lake Tear,
Roosevelt looked away and, shaking his head, muttered,
``complicated, complicated. But I don't want to become president
through a graveyard. I would rather work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Without saying another word Roosevelt packed the lunch away and
started briskly down the trail. By 5:30 p.m., they were at the
comfortable Upper Tahawus Club. The vice president changed his
soaked and muddy clothes, ate a light supper and awaited more
information before setting out for Buffalo. His wife wondered why
he didn't set out immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been there once,'' he explained. ``And that shows how I
feel. But I will not go to stand beside those people who are
suffering and anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   Word did come, at about 11 p.m., that the president was failing
quickly, and Roosevelt set right out in a pitch black, dreadful
night for a hellbent ride to the presidency that is the stuff of
lore and legend. David Hunter, who was superintendent of the Lower
club, drove Roosevelt by buckboard the 10 miles from Upper to Lower
Tahawus, pulled by a 1,400-pound bay that had been skidding logs
all day. That took two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Orrin Kellogg then drove the next leg with his team to a
roadhouse, hotel and coach stop known as Aiden Lair. The rain
picked up, and Roosevelt, with one small overnight bag in tow,
covered his legs with Kellogg's raincoat to keep off the
splattering mud. Along that stretch, about an hour before reaching
the Lair, Theodore Roosevelt, six weeks shy of his 43rd birthday,
became the 26th president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley had died in Buffalo at 2:15 a.m. on Sept. 14. Mike
Cronin, legendary proprietor of Aiden Lair, drove the last and most
spectacular leg of Roosevelt's 35-mile ride from Upper Tahawus to
North Creek, the end of the Delaware and Hudson rail line, where a
special train waited to whisk him down to Albany and then over to
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Lair had a phone, so Cronin knew McKinley was dead but said
nothing to Roosevelt. ``It wasn't my place to tell him. I didn't
want to burden the man,'' he would later say. Roosevelt didn't find
out until North Creek, when Loeb told him.
</P>
<P>
   Three days of rain had left the 16-mile dirt road from Aiden
Lair to North Creek a treacherous, soupy quagmire of wheel ruts and
slides. Yet Cronin had his ``fast-stepping'' span of black Morgans
running flat out, careening down the mountainside. Roosevelt
insisted. There was no Secret Service escort, no media pack, no
aides. Just the new president holding a kerosene lantern that cast
a light as far as the harnesses, and Cronin gritting his teeth and
praying. Pitch black and slick as a weasel the whole way, an
exercise in pure faith. The horses would stumble, and all Roosevelt
would say was, ``Keep up the pace. Faster.''
</P>
<P>
   They fortunately encountered no other traffic, which in the
total darkness could have been disastrous. Cronin covered the 16
miles in one hour and 41 minutes, a record with buckboard and team
that stands to this day. Cronin, the president, and well-lathered
Morgans Frank and Dick thundered over the planks of the bridge at
North Creek just as dawn was poking a rosy finger.
</P>
<P>
   The train, complete with aides and entourage, was anxiously
waiting and pulled out moments later. America and the 20th century
were waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1704EST &QL; 
