<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CENTURION-ART-2ND     01-11 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CENTURION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: meet specifications. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The program was revived in 1994 by the Defense Department and
declassified. The Pathfinder prototype reappeared after being
stored for a decade in a secret location, but the new project, to
build a long-duration surveillance plane, was canceled shortly
thereafter when it lost funding. NASA then took over the project
and used new technology to make a larger version of the craft,
called Pathfinder Plus.
</P>
<P>
   W. Ray Morgan, an AeroVironment vice president who directs its
Design and Development Center, said that when the early Pathfinder
program was declassified, the only facts that remained secret were
the name of the original sponsor and the craft's intended mission.
``We have entertained ourselves endlessly around here speculating
on who and what they were,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   The original Pathfinder had six engines and a wingspan of 98
feet, while Pathfinder Plus grew to eight engines and a 121-foot
wing. Centurion dwarfs both with 14 engines _ each of which turn a
twin-blade 79-inch propeller _ and a 206-foot wingspan, wider than
that of a Boeing 747 jumbo jet. The wing of the craft measures 8
feet from front to rear, is only about 11.5 inches thick and rests
on four fairings or pods that contain its landing gear and
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft, which has an empty weight of only about 1,175
pounds, so far has cost about $7 million to design and build. It is
so light because it is fabricated from tough carbon fiber and
graphite epoxy composite materials, as well as the Kevlar fabric
used in bulletproof vests, Styrofoam, and a plastic film covering.
The wing is built in five segments; a 44-foot-long center section
is flanked by two panels on each side that individually measure
slightly over 40 feet. The outermost panels have a noticeable
10-degree upsweep to help lateral stability in flight and a slight
upward twist at the tips of the trailing edge.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said each wing section is so stable it can fly on its
own, allowing the plane to get bigger, while still remaining
controllable, by adding new sections. ``It's an airplane you can
buy by the yard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works like several aircraft flying in close formation, but
they happen to be structurally interconnected,'' Morgan added.
</P>
<P>
   The plane flies at only 17 to 21 miles per hour. With no rudder
or tail, it turns and banks by slowing down or speeding up
different motors on the outboard sections of the wing.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion successfully made its first three flights this past
November and December at NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center at
Edwards, Calif., but the craft flew on its backup lithium-sulfur
dioxide batteries and not solar power. Engineers said they did not
want to risk damaging the craft's delicate and expensive solar
power cells on these low-level early flights designed to test
stability, handling and load carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, AeroVironment only has enough of these special solar
cells to cover one of the plane's five sections. The
high-efficiency silicon cell arrays, which convert 19 percent of
the sun's rays striking them into electricity, cost about $1.8
million per section and the company needs another $7 million that
has yet to be funded to finish four more panels.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion was airborne a total of about three-and-a-half hours
on its maiden flights, only venturing a few hundred feet off the
ground to check the craft's handling and its extensive automatic
control system. On its final flight, it carried a 600 pound
simulated payload that was about half its empty weight. ``This
flight went a long way in showing that even though solar-powered
airplanes appear delicate and fragile, they really have the muscle
necessary to do big jobs,'' said John Del Frate, Dryden's project
manager for solar aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers plan to add another section to Centurion, giving it a
span of almost 250 feet, for the next series of flights this spring
or summer. Although these trials also will be battery-powered,
Morgan said this configuration should be able to reach the
100,000-foot goal when solar cells are installed, perhaps in
another two or three years, depending upon funding.
</P>
<P>
   There is a debate over whether a robot drone really needs to fly
as high as 100,000 feet to meet most scientific objectives because
operating this high penalizes the aircraft's performance. For every
additional 13,000 feet of altitude, air density drops in half and a
plane has to fly 40 percent faster to stay up, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Helios, the ultimate solar plane, is being designed to work
between 50,000 and 70,000 feet and stay there for weeks using solar
power by day and a rechargeable fuel cell system at night.
</P>
<P>
   However, Morgan said, a goal of Centurion is to operate at
100,000 feet because of a 1996 challenge from NASA administrator
Daniel Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldin felt that if we could operate at 100,000 feet, it would
prove that NASA could fly a plane in the thin Martian atmosphere
under similar conditions, which they want to do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
