<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME GRIST FROM THE CYBERMILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Let's begin this week with a few notes, a few newsy
tidbits and a few interesting Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   - Ever wonder why so many companies lend their names to things
like college football bowl games? A recent press release from
Insight in Tempe explained one reason: Web page hits. The press
release said hits (visits by computer users) to the computer
marketing company's Web site (www.insight.com) soared 917 percent
after the televised Insight.com Bowl in late December.
</P>
<P>
   - So you want a wireless telephone but can't make heads or tails
out of all those confusing ads on television? Here's an answer:
Wireless Dimension. It's a cool Web site operated by a company out
of Washington state. It allows users to compare wireless plans
available in their areas. The site has won rave reviews from the
likes of ``Fortune'' magazine and the ``San Jose Mercury News.''
</P>
<P>
   Check it out at wirelessdimension.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Jupiter Communications says nearly $40 billion worth of
transactions were expected to have been made online during 1998. A
study of that estimate and of who's doing the selling has lead
another company, Internet Valley Inc., to develop what it's calling
the ``iFactor.'' This rating supposedly indicates a particular
company's chances for doing well _ or poorly _ in future e-commerce
activities. Internet Valley is big on Microsoft, giving it a high
iFactor rating of 6.91. But IBM, which had high sales, was
nonetheless given a low iFactor rating of 0.336. Go figure. If you
feel like diving into this business, check out the Web site at
www.internetvalley.com/sales97.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Gotta love that e-mail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The recent motion picture ``You've Got Mail'' makes you want to
run out and send somebody e-mail, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   So many people are doing just that these days, it might be a
good time to remind ourselves that some caution is warranted when
it comes to sending and receiving e-mail and when participating in
online chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some basic things to remember:
</P>
<P>
   - Assume everything you write in an e-mail or chat room will be
made public and can live forever on the Internet. So think twice
before calling somebody a name or before revealing personal
information about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   - Take everything you read in e-mails or in chat rooms with a
grain of salt, especially if the information is from someone you've
never heard from before. People often assume false identities while
online and often tell lies just to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   - Keep those screen name profiles to a bare minimum if you don't
want to attract unwanted e-mail or intrusions into your personal
life.
</P>
<P>
   - Think it would be fun to meet an online ``friend'' in real
life? NEVER do it alone. Always have someone with you. And NEVER do
it in a secluded spot. Arrange the meeting somewhere very public,
such as a shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   - NEVER give out your home phone number, address or online
passwords to someone online, even if they claim to be important,
such as an online security officer for America Online or some other
service. (The obvious exception to this rule is if you go to a
commercial Web site and purchase something.)
</P>
<P>
   - Do not respond to nasty, hateful, pornographic or otherwise
unwanted e-mail. Doing so can lead to more electronic junk, not
less. If it's really bad or possibly illegal, don't hesitate to
send a copy to your Internet service provider or local law
enforcement agencies. Anything illegal in real life is illegal
online, too.
</P>
<P>
   - Parents should be aware of how much time their kids are
spending online each day (or night). More than a few hours can be
an indication of a problem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
More MP3 news to use &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week's column on MP3, the relatively new file compression
format that allows near CD-quality music to zip around the
Internet, prompted several e-mails from interested readers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian wrote to tell us of yet another format, VQF, which he
claims is even better than MP3. I haven't had a chance to check VQF
out, but anyone who's interested is encouraged to check out
www.vqf.com.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, John dropped me an e-mail to tell me about the ``CD
Streamer'' by Superplanet. ``CD Streamer provides the `ripper' and
playback features similar to MP3,'' John wrote. ``It creates
compressed audio files in a proprietary format and the compression
seems about the same as MP3. Playback quality, at least on my 400
mHz Pentium II (what else?) is CD quality.'' Check it out at
www.superplanet.com.
</P>
<P>
   One reader asked whether it's possible to invest in the MP3
phenomenon. I'm sure there are several avenues to do so, but one of
the most obvious is to invest in Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc.,
which makes and sells the palm-sized MP3 player called Rio. The
company's stock (NASDAQ ticker symbol: DIMD) has been trending
upward over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   A reader named William appeared to disagree with my belief that
most MP3 titles sounded pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think there is little difference in quality between
formats,'' William wrote, ``but played on a high resolution stereo
system, the compression in MP3 is VERY apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tian wrote in to tell us about a new MP3-related Web site that
went online as recently as Jan. 3. It's called ShoutCast. Find it
at www.shoutcast.com. The site uses WinAmp (one of the shareware
programs that can be used to play MP3 files on your PC) as a
transmitter/receiver for news and music over the Internet. Check it
out!
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a Macintosh user, wrote to say that he's had trouble
downloading MacAmp (the Mac equivalent to WinAmp). I'm at a loss to
explain his problem. Anybody out there know of anything special Mac
users need to do in order to obtain a copy of MacAmp? Let me know,
and I'll pass it on.
</P>
<P>
   I'm excited about the possibilities made possible by MP3. But,
apparently, not everyone else out in cyberland agrees. A recent
online survey, for example, asked people what event they thought
made the biggest impact on music during 1998. More than 50 percent
listed the death of Frank Sinatra. Less than 10 percent named the
advent of MP3. Oh well. &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
