<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-11 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS THE UNION'S STATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton insists he will deliver his State
of the Union speech as scheduled before the Congress that is in hot
pursuit of him, despite the awkwardness of it all and the urging of
some Republicans and Democrats to duck the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   If he sticks to the present timetable, he will deliver the
annual address to a joint congressional session on Tuesday, Jan.
19, the day his defense team will begin presenting its case to the
Senate. His aides have said he will consider shifting the date a
few days but will not postpone it until after a trial of unknown
length has determined his fate.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has he gone for the suggestion that he submit his report in
writing, as presidents did until Woodrow Wilson broke the pattern
by appearing in person.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is right to stare down the legislative branch and
demonstrate to the public that although Congress has him on the
run, he hasn't gone into hiding. Such a performance would reinforce
his repeated efforts all last year to reassure voters that he
continues to conduct the nation's business despite his personal
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene will be politically tense for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   California Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat who deplores
Clinton's behavior but believes he has been unfairly hounded by
partisan investigations, said it would be ``almost schizophrenic''
for him to try to sell his agenda in the well of the Senate at this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Sen. Rick Santorum, a Republican who has been an
unrelenting Clinton critic since he arrived in the Senate four
years ago, said it would ``create acrimony within the chamber.''
Presumably he really meant it would deepen present Senate acrimony,
since partisan divisions are already apparent over issues of
witnesses, standards for conviction and trial duration.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it will be another bizarre chapter in an extraordinarily
bizarre saga that burst upon the world one year ago, shortly before
Clinton gave last year's State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody realized then the extent of the scandal. The president
was full of beans, promising popular programs to improve education,
protect Social Security and expand Medicare, the Peace Corps and
child care subsidies. The upshot was he so dominated the public
agenda that the Republicans looked clueless all year and got dubbed
the `'impeachment party'' for want of serious policy alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   But now the president is preparing to discuss his plans and
hopes for future legislative achievements before a co-equal branch
of government that is simultaneously debating whether he should
have a future at all.
</P>
<P>
   What he has going for him is that he will give the speech on
television, where the drama is likely to attract a huge audience.
He will reach beyond the Capitol chamber to millions of viewers,
among whom a sizable majority is already inclined to root for him,
if the polls are correct.
</P>
<P>
   The president's continuing popularity is his strongest resource
as his disgusting sexual behavior is paraded daily in the national
media. And that popularity is based in part on the perception of
him as a fighter, a president who works at his job and has the
interests of ordinary Americans at heart.
</P>
<P>
   He has been at great pains throughout this period to convince
folks that his personal debacle has not weakened the presidency
itself or his ability to function within it. This requires him to
juggle a two-track life, one in public that seems normal and one in
private that struggles to fend off disaster.
</P>
<P>
   He goes through the public motions of being president with
amazing agility, recently entertaining Ohio Sen. John Glenn and his
fellow astronauts, attending a birthday party, making an upbeat
speech about economic prosperity. After his visit, Glenn observed
that Clinton was so engaging and cheerful that if you didn't
already know something was wrong, you wouldn't know anything was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Being essentially shameless, Clinton is likely to pull off his
appearance before Congress with aplomb. It will have little impact
on the trial, which has its own momentum and internal politics. But
at least nearly half the chamber will be on his side during his
performance. The Democrats have little choice if they wish to
retain the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clinton's accusers be as devious as he is? Can they contain
their hostility long enough to look serious about national issues?
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans could walk out in a demonstration of
self-defeating partisanship that would drive their negative poll
numbers further into the basement. They could sit on their hands at
every presidential proposal, betraying a stubborn unwillingness to
work with him. They could jeer and scowl and look petty before a
national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could put up a good political front, as he does. They
could listen politely. And they could ponder the fact that if the
Senate does not convict him, as now expected, they will have to
deal with him for two more years whether they like it or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
