<HEADER>
A8294 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUZZLEMASTER-TEX     01-11 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUZZLEMASTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT SILVERS ISN'T REVEALING THE SECRET OF HIS PHOTOMOSAICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From a distance, the faces on the posters or magazine covers are
familiar _ Abraham Lincoln and Princess Di, Marilyn Monroe and
Mickey Mouse _ images that in themselves are scarcely worth a
second look.
</P>
<P>
   But come closer. Inch by inch, Abe and Di, Marilyn and Mickey
begin to blur, while hundreds of other tiny images come more
clearly into focus. One of Lincoln's eyes, it turns out, is not
part of a single image, but a collage of photos _ somber, bearded
Civil War officers, or Union troops posing for the camera, or
Lincoln himself at the battle front, in a stovepipe hat. A photo of
John Wilkes Booth lurks somewhere on the image, too. Marilyn's
face, meanwhile, is actually a computer-generated mosaic composed
of past Life covers, shrunk into tiny tiles.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the new pop art form dubbed photomosaics by its young
creator, MIT grad Robert Silvers, a form that has become almost
Warholian in its popularity. Silvers' Lincoln poster is the biggest
seller in the history of the Library of Congress gift shop, for
example. In the past four years, photomosaics have appeared on the
covers of Newsweek (Princess Di); Life (Marilyn); Playboy (Marilyn
again); and Sports Illustrated (Tiger Woods). Bill Gates received a
Silvers portrait as a birthday present. Al Gore has one on order.
Throw in two coffee-table books, music videos, posters, puzzles and
cereal boxes, and there's suddenly the makings of a pop art empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an aesthetic riddle,'' Michael Naumann, publisher of a
Silvers coffee-table book, said of the art form in Newsweek. ``It
asks two questions simultaneously: What is it, and how is it
done?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Silvers says of his unlikely stardom. In
addition to his work, Silvers' Web site (www.photomosaic.com) now
depicts the young techno-artist hobnobbing with Playboy models and
Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not the sort of popular renown expected for a guy
who once planned on the more cloistered existence of a corporate
computer programmer. But then Silvers, 30, who developed
photomosaics as a graduate student in MIT's media lab, has always
stood a bit apart from the techno-geek crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Plymouth, Mass., he is the son of a salesman and
therapist, neither of whom are technologically adept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got my mother an iMac,'' Silvers says. ``She has a hard
time doing the simplest things. Like copying a file. Same with my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   And from early childhood, computers were just one of two abiding
passions. Photography was the other. As a boy, Silvers says, he was
constantly seeking photo subjects, making shot after shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my father asking why I was wasting so much film,''
Silvers says.
</P>
<P>
   An ironic question, as it turns out. At the University of
Massachusetts, Silvers decided to keep photography as a hobby, but
pursue computer programming for a living. Then, while he was still
an undergraduate in 1991, an artist and scientist named Ken
Knowlton introduced Silvers to the concept that would eventually
allow a blending of his twin passions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a portrait (Knowlton) did of a man using seashells,''
Silvers says. ``He literally picked them off the beach and rotated
them and arranged them to look like a portrait. Up close you could
see only the shells and far away only the face. I became fascinated
with the image on two different levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowlton never divulged his method. But for Silvers, the idea
had taken root. At MIT four years later, while pondering ideas for
a class project and a master's thesis, Silvers returned to
Knowlton's premise, but replaced seashells with photographs. He
designed the photomosaic software over one sleepless weekend, then
in a single computer stroke produced the image of a friend from an
unrelated photo collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chill,'' Silvers remembers. ``It was what I had
envisioned. It proved to me that I was going to be able to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Silvers refined the software during the rest of his time at MIT.
But his novel images found a broad audience even before he received
his master's degree in media arts and sciences. Early on, the media
lab newsletter published a photomosaic of a former MIT president.
Editors at Wired magazine saw the newsletter, and requested a cover
of their own, which caught the eye of editors at Life.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, both Silvers' art and his story have been
featured in a growing list of national publications and network
television shows: The tale of unlikely stardom, and of the
compelling marriage between technology and art.
</P>
<P>
   Silvers described his methods in a recent interview, using as an
example his recent Newsweek cover of Princess Diana, a mosaic
composed of floral photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Once he selected the image of Diana, Silvers turned to a more
daunting task, finding the photos to make up the individual mosaic
tiles. From a photo collection of 60,000 images, Silvers manually
culled 7,000, trimming each so that flowers filled each image. The
photos were scanned into his computer, and put to work by Silvers'
software program.
</P>
<P>
   Every individual photograph was considered electronically for
every spot on the face of Diana, which was also divided by computer
into a tightly gridded matrix. The computer sought the best
solution for each tile in terms of brightness, color and shape. In
the end, 900 images made up Diana's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then, when that's done, I may run the whole process over
again several times with different parameters,'' Silvers says.
``Finally I go over it by hand. Any tiles that look objectionable
to me, either close up or at a distance, I can replace with an
alternative. I designed the software to make certain decisions for
me, but to leave the rest of the decisions for me to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly spend a lot of time working on what I consider the
most important features of a person, which is their eyes,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Silvers now receives far more requests for mosaics than he and
his small company, Runaway Technologies, could ever entertain. But
he has found the time for a portrait of King Hussein of Jordan, a
present from his wife, Queen Noor. Silvers' portrait of actor Jim
Carrey adorned the publicity poster for ``The Truman Show.''
Silvers' rendering of the famous Marilyn Monroe nude was also on
display on last month's cover of Playboy's 45th-anniversary
edition.
</P>
<P>
   Each mosaic runs about $75,000, give or take, Silvers says. He
now drives a Humvee with bulletproof glass and night vision
capability, and can indulge himself when it comes to photo
equipment. He has filed for patents to discourage potential
imitators and has shown a knack for marketing. But despite the
Warholian popularity, Silvers says he disdains Warholian glamour.
He has lived in the same home for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't supposed to be a big commercial business, and I'm
not going to license everything I can,'' Silvers says. ``I'm not
going to crank out images as fast as possible, because I want it to
be done by me, as art.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
