<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SENIORS-BALANCE-A     01-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SENIORS-BALANCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCING EXERCISES KEEP INJURIES AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Statistics show that falls among older adults _ often the cause
of serious injury _ can be prevented in many cases with a program
of exercises specifically geared toward improving balance and
posture.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of the American Geriatric Society reports that
one-third of people over 65 fall at least once a year, many of them
incurring injuries like broken hips that may never properly mend.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that age-related falls are caused in part
by a reduced sense of balance and a loss of ability to judge body
placement. Aging causes a loss of sensitivity in special receptor
cells, called proprioceptors _ found in the skin, muscles, joints
and tendons _ that process information about the body's orientation
as it moves through space. As the sensitivity of these cells
diminishes with age, they provide the brain with less of the
sensory information it needs to maintain balance. Slower reflexes
and decreased muscle strength, combined with loss of eyesight and
depth perception, also contribute to a diminished sense of
equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   But there is evidence that older adults can reduce or reverse
some of these effects by including in their fitness regimen
exercises geared toward improving balance, and, as a result, become
less accident-prone. A 1996 study performed at the Department of
Neurology at the University of Connecticut School of Medicine in
Hartford looked at 110 elderly men and women. After three months of
regularly performing movements aimed at sharpening balance, the
vast majority of subjects restored a level of body control and
posture stability similar to those three to 10 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything else balance is a skill,'' said John
Blievernicht, president of Sports Health CARE Inc., a Chicago
medical rehabilitation clinic. ``And like any other skill, you've
got to constantly practice it to preserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blievernicht recommends exercises like lunge or walking
movements on a low-standing balance beam, standing on one leg, and
abdominal crunches done while leaning backward over an oversized
plastic ball. Walking across a low wooden beam, for example,
requires a constant correction of knee, hip and head alignment. All
of the muscles from head to toe must work with proper
synchronization for a person to glide across the beam without
extending the arms for balance or teetering off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Blievernicht says this is a difficult task for many people at
first, but that with proper training and supervision, most can
master it _ and moves like it _ in just a few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, these exercises awaken reflexes and teach body
awareness and control on a subconscious level,'' he said. This can
translate into lasting improvements in posture and overall quality
of movement, Blievernicht added, regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes looking to improve performance, people recovering
from injuries, and anyone with postural problems should also
consider working on balance and body awareness,'' said Risa
Halpern, director of physical therapy at Plus One Physical Therapy
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This message is slowly beginning to make its way into the
mainstream: Many health clubs now offer classes that involve props
like Physioballs, a brand of the large plastic balls used in the
abdominal crunch exercise; balance beams; wobble boards, and other
devices designed to improve balance. At Crunch Fitness, a national
chain of fitness clubs, exercisers in the popular Rebounding class
jump up and down on a miniature trampoline for 45 minutes to
sharpen balance, coordination and agility.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Halpern thinks balance and posture-correction exercises
are best taught one-on-one or in small groups supervised by
trainers or physical therapists with extensive knowledge of anatomy
and proper body alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike many other forms of traditional exercise, this is about
quality rather than quantity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gina Allchin, general manager of the Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell
corporate fitness center, agrees. ``It's hard to teach subtle
nuances of body posture and movement in a classroom packed with
people,'' she said. Ms. Allchin advises starting out slowly, doing
no more than 10 minutes of balance work, two or three times a week.
``This type of training is deceptively challenging and can leave
you feeling exhausted and sore if you overdo it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   BALANCE BEAM WALK: Walk slowly across a low wooden beam while
maintaining tall posture, keeping the knees aligned forward and
hands relaxed at the sides.
</P>
<P>
   FULCRUM: With arms relaxed at the sides, stand on one foot with
the other leg held behind and a few inches off the floor. Lean
forward and maintain balance.
</P>
<P>
   BALL CRUNCH: Lie across a large ball with feet placed hip-width
apart. Do abdominal crunches while trying to keep the ball as still
as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
