<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARYSHNIKOV-KABUKI-AR     01-11 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARYSHNIKOV-KABUKI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARYSHNIKOV FLIRTS WITH KABUKI
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(ms) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mikhail Baryshnikov has specialized in unearthing the
unusual in dance. Now he is branching out again. Tuesday night he
will perform choreography drawn from traditional Japanese forms in
``Dance With Three Drums and Flute,'' a new solo created for him by
the Kabuki star Tamasaburo Bando. The piece will be performed in
Baryshnikov's single performance at St. Mark's Danspace Project in
the East Village to raise money for Dancers Responding to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov put the program together after being asked for help
by Hernando Cortez, a dancer with Baryshnikov's White Oak Dance
Project who founded Dancers Responding to AIDS with Denise Roberts,
a former Paul Taylor dancer. They chose an intimate downtown space
to avoid ``all that uptown hoopla,'' Ms. Roberts said. Money raised
by the group is used to help people in dance with HIV, the AIDS
virus, and for grants to other groups that respond to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dance With Three Drums and Flute,'' set to music to be
performed live by Rosen Tousha, Baryshnikov takes a gradual
18-minute voyage from mystic near-stillness to the turbulence of an
impassioned Kabuki warrior. The dance grew out of collaborative
work he did this summer with Tamasaburo, a member of the honorary
Kabuki family of Bando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamasaburo-san and I have known each other for many years,''
said Baryshnikov, stretched out on the floor of a gleaming studio
at City Center as a physiotherapist gave his legs a prerehearsal
massage. ``I had the privilege of watching him putting his makeup
and costume on before performances. Then a mutual friend said, `Why
don't you guys try to figure something out together?' It took us
six years to nail our schedules down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamasaburo based the new dance on traditional forms from Noh to
Kabuki. ``He intentionally mixed them,'' Baryshnikov said, ``and
tried to put his own point of view into the perspective of this
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The solo is a rechoreographed version of a duet Tamasaburo
created for himself and Baryshnikov. ``There is no context or
story,'' Baryshnikov said. ``Some of the movements mean something
in Kabuki theater, like dancing with a fan or a hop on one leg.
That is a given. But in this dance they just mean movement. And
from my point of view it is close to modern dance, or mime, in the
purity of the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with Tamasaburo for three months and remembering earlier
visits to Japan, Baryshnikov said, he began to see something of
Japanese dance in work by Martha Graham. ``There is a certain
stillness, a sculptural quality _ that deadness or shell that burns
from inside _ that is very Japanese and is projected in her work so
much,'' he said, talking of one similarity.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments in ``Dance With Three Drums and Flute'' that
recall the feeling of fatefulness in ``Heartbeat,'' a solo
Baryshnikov performed at City Center in 1997 in which electrical
impulses in his moving muscles were captured and amplified by
equipment created by the sound sculptor Christopher Janney.
Baryshnikov finds a similar mysticism in Tousha's music, based on
traditional Japanese themes. At times, performing the score, ``he
holds his breath and sends his spirit around the world,''
Baryshnikov said the composer told him, ``and when it comes back,
he knows to exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, which is not for review, also features previews of
work by Neil Greenberg and Mark Morris that are to be performed
later by Baryshnikov and White Oak. Tickets are $1,000, which
includes receptions before and after the performance, and are
available from Dancers Responding to AIDS, at Broadway Cares/Equity
Fights AIDS. Information: (212) 840-0770.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TORTOISE-SHELLS-A     01-11 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TORTOISE-SHELLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF TORTOISES, HARES AND THE PEOPLING OF EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tortoise and the hare, paired together in Aesop's fable,
have been reunited by archeologists in an ingenious index for
measuring the growth rate of early human populations.
</P>
<P>
   The index, based on the proportions of slow and fast-moving prey
in ancient trash heaps, shows that from about 100,000 to 50,000
years ago the first human inhabitants of the east and north
Mediterranean were extremely few, a mere handful of people who were
probably dispersing from an ancestral homeland somewhere in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The size of early populations figures in many discussions about
the genetic and cultural evolution of early humans. The new finding
is important because it confirms estimates derived on a quite
different basis _ from analyzing the DNA of living people around
the globe _ that the earliest human populations were extremely
small. Geneticists have calculated, for example, that the early
human population of sub-Saharan Africa was once as small as 6,900
people, and that the group that left Africa to colonize the rest of
the world may have numbered as few as 500.
</P>
<P>
   These estimates, based on variations in DNA, are better than
guesses but fall way short of hard fact.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary Stiner, an archeologist at the University of Arizona in
Tucson, has now developed an alternative method of tracking early
human population density. The method does not yield precise numbers
but shows in a relative way how population density may have
changed. She and colleagues at Hebrew University of Jerusalem and
Harvard report their findings in the current issue of the journal
Science.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stiner's method is based on analysis of the bones of small
prey animals found at Paleolithic sites in Israel and Italy. She
and her colleagues find that slowing-moving animals like tortoises
predominate at the lowest level of the Israeli site, yielding to
hares, rabbits and partridges at later periods.
</P>
<P>
   The switch in prey was occasioned not by a desire for
gastronomic variety, Dr. Stiner says, but rather by the fact that
animals that were easier to catch were consumed first. Only as the
tortoises and shellfish became scarce did the Paleolithic people
start to go after the more evasive prey. The ratio of slow to fast
prey over time is thus a measure of the number of mouths round the
campfire, Dr. Stiner believes.
</P>
<P>
   Tortoises, which were baked in their shells, are slow to
reproduce and very sensitive to predation _ a tortoise population
will collapse when 7 percent have been eaten. ``People weren't
damaging these tortoise populations, yet half of the total game
brought to the site is tortoises,'' Dr. Stiner said. ``The
implication is that the number of people must have been very low.''
</P>
<P>
   The proportions of fast prey at the two sites shoots up, as if
reflecting an increase in human population density, at around
44,000 years ago at the Israeli site and 23,000 years ago at the
Italian site.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ian Tattersall, a paleoanthropologist at the American Museum
of Natural History, said Dr. Stiner's article was the first
archeological attempt he had seen to get close to the issue of
early population change, even though it was not 100 percent proof.
Dr. Henry Harpending, a population geneticist at the University of
Utah, also said the article was ``one of the first to get a grip on
the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest groups of humans may have numbered just a few
hundred each, according to Dr. Ofer Bar-Yosef, a Harvard
archeologist and co-author of Dr. Stiner's paper. ``The mating
system among humans requires 250 to 400 people so as not to cross
the incest taboo,'' he said. These early bands were mobile, moving
from one site to another when food got scarce.
</P>
<P>
   But as the landscape filled up with people, mobility decreased,
and the need to catch more elusive prey would have been a powerful
spur to innovation. This is the process presumably reflected by the
tortoise-hare index. The demographic packing ``contributed to the
rapid acceleration in human material culture, technology, and the
beginning of sedentary settlements that occur toward the end of the
Pleistocene,'' Dr. Stiner said. The Pleistocene, the period of the
last great ice age, ended around 10,000 years ago, shortly after
the first domestication of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some archeologists, like Dr. Richard Klein of Stanford
University, believe a genetic change underlay the emergence of
behaviorally modern humans, marked by the flowering of art and
technology that occurred in the archeological record starting about
50,000 years ago. Tattersall, on the other hand, said it was ``hard
to imagine there was a genetic change that spread through the world
in a short period of time.'' He believes the agent of change was
the development of language, built on genetic abilities acquired
many thousands of years earlier but not put to use.
</P>
<P>
   Bar-Yosef also favors the idea of a latent genetic ability in
the first anatomically modern humans that was not triggered until
much later. ``We have to assume the genetic changes happened at
around 100,000 years ago but the cultural change doesn't happen
before 48,000 years ago,'' Bar-Yosef said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he basically agreed with the proposals of the population
geneticists that anatomically modern humans all came from somewhere
in sub-Saharan Africa. ``I belong to the supporters of the
out-of-Africa hypothesis,'' he said, ``but my point is you have the
mutation early, so it's like old wine, with at least 60,000 years
of cultural evolution brewing. Even these early anatomically modern
humans are not making anything different from the Neanderthals
until the cultural change that happened 50,000 years ago. It was a
change in technology that responded to socioeconomic requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stiner plans to explore the tortoise-hare index at other
sites in Africa, Asia and Europe, with the hope of learning more
about early human demographics. ``The increase in human population
density was one of the factors contributing to the process of
evolutionary change, selecting those who applied new solutions to
old problems,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
