A8321 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ARKANSAS-HNS &LR;      01-11 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARKANSAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FACES DIVIDED LOYALTIES ON HIS HOME TURF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The waitresses in the International House of
Pancakes at University and Markham are supporting President Clinton
in his fight to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   The sign outside the IHOP read, ``Pancakes make people happy.''
Inside, waitress Katherine Lupiner was setting down plates of
chicken fried steak and short stacks in front of three generations
of a family dressed in Sunday best, talking about how good the sun
looked coming through the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the cash register, Lupiner shook her head over the
impeachment process. ``I think it's been blown up,'' she said. ``I
don't think Clinton has to explain everything he does, not to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment debate has drawn definite lines in Little Rock.
Letters to the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette tend to support Clinton,
the state's former governor, but the newspaper's editorials have
been critical of him.
</P>
<P>
   Lupiner, who moved from Sacramento, Calif., to Arkansas ``to
slow down,'' doesn't think Clinton will be convicted and removed
from office by the Senate, saying, ``He's done a lot of good
things. I hope he stays.''
</P>
<P>
   The House voted last month to impeach Clinton on charges that he
committed perjury and obstructed justice in an effort to cover up
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   IHOP Waitress Renee Watson said that Clinton should remain in
office. ``What happened was between him and Hillary and Monica,''
she said. ``It's none of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's cut back unemployment, brought a lot of jobs to
Arkansas,'' Watson said. ``He shouldn't be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Tom Adam, manager of the Guesthouse Inn, removing Clinton
from office makes sense. ``I don't like the man. I don't believe in
the man,'' he said of Clinton. ``I think they should impeach him
and get it over with. Stop jacking us around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got things to take care of that aren't getting done,
bridges, roads, Social Security, health care. I tell you, I don't
trust the system anymore, I don't trust what they're doing. It's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hill from IHOP, Nina Freeman, a part-time van driver
for the Guesthouse Inn, said she's had more than enough of the
impeachment process. ``I think it's a bunch of garbage,'' she said.
``I don't like any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who Bill Clinton sleeps with; that's his wife's
problem,'' said Freeman, who also works as a secretary in the
state's pollution control department.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, people are caught between reluctant support
of Clinton and lingering embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-Gazette, in a editorial, said: ``Some day, some
how, you knew this would all catch up with him ... and so, when it
does, even the most dramatic of scenes are drained of their drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the incessant use of the word `Historic' by the
television anchormen lacks color, conviction and suspense, the very
stuff of history ... the whole scene has the air of a Greek drama
dumbed down for the modern reader; stripped of its nobility, its
hubris reduced to calculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Neidhardt, a registered nurse, said the president's
conduct in the Lewinsky affair was ``not something they should
impeach him for, but Bill Clinton should have seen how this was
going to affect his family, how it would affect the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This not only hurts his wife, his child, but it hurts the
nation more than anyone can tell. I am so ashamed for Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Neidhardt said she hadn't voted for years out of disillusionment
with the government before she got caught up in Clinton's
gubernatorial campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got elected, I thought he'd be good for the state,
good for the country,'' she said. ``Now, I guess, I'm pretty much
back where I started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
