<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ZOOM-960(2Takes)-T     01-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ZOOM-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT '70S SHOW FOR PRETEENS RETURNS ON PBS WITH A NEW LOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   My son Jack, all of 8 years old, is staring at the TV. We've
just finished watching the first two episodes of ``Zoom,'' the new
show for kids 6 to 12 that debuted last week on PBS, and this is
all that comes out of his usually far more active mouth. He's not
reaching for the PlayStation, though. I take this as an encouraging
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Jack, would you watch it again?''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about it. ``Yeah. If I knew when it was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack may never have seen anything like it, but I have.
Something, in fact, almost exactly like it. Twenty-six years ago,
the first cast of the first Zoom'' show brought to public
television a message of kids-can-do-anything, preteen empowerment.
``Zoom'' zoomed to the top of the PBS charts, becoming its second
most-popular show, right behind ``Masterpiece Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's young fans were called Zoomers. They spoke in
Ubbi-Dubbi, wanted to do a Zoom Do, became hooked on games like
Miss Mary Mack and Fannee Doolee and sent an average of 10,000
letters per week to the seven kid-hosts, suggesting games, riddles,
recipes, skits and topics for discussion that actually became the
content of the program. ``Zoom'' was for kids and by kids, and
members of the cast, in their matching striped shirts, became the
viewers' virtual TV friends.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Zoom,'' produced once again by WGBH in Boston (yes,
Zoomers, it's got that same famous 02134 address) is remarkably
like the old ``Zoom.'' Some details have changed, and thanks to
better technology, the interactive opportunities for viewers have
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   But the old ``Zoom'' never faced the competition of all-fun,
all-the-time private cable networks with their marketing mavens and
high-dollar budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Why re-''Zoom'' now? Will kids care?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Keiko, with two dark Baby Spice-style ponytails gathered in sky
blue scrunchies, smiles into the camera, her braces reflecting
lights from the set. ``Ed L. of Marblehead, Massachusetts,
challenged us to see how long we could keep a feather up in the air
without letting it touch the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   She turns to the other ``Zoom'' cast members, who are loosely
gathered near one of the tall, neon orange and yellow letters that
spell out the name of the show against the set's black background.
Seven identical pairs of black canvas tennis shoes start moving as
the kids work out a system that goes from random cries of ``I've
got it!'' to directives on whose turn is next. The game goes on,
untimed, until the red feather nests in the crook of Jared's neck.
Zoe reaches forward and sucks her breath in to draw the feather
out. But she goes too far. The feather is in her mouth. Game over.
Giggles abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoom'' rolls merrily, almost quietly, along. There's a short
video on a kid who likes to ride in hot-air balloons with his
uncle. Keiko makes a bunny cake in cafe Zoom. Alisa introduces a
Zoom Zinger from Jenna M. of East Bridgeport, Conn., a word game
that requires kids to actually remember what homonyms are.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kate Taylor of WGBH knows her ``Zoom.'' Her first job was as the
contributions editor for the show in the '70s, which meant she got
final say on which of the 10,000 viewer letters would become part
of each show. Now she's the executive producer of the new ``Zoom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's kids are looking for more substance,'' she begins.
``This is a show that challenges them to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Nickelodeon channel's The Big Help
environmental challenge to kids is some proof that kids today
indeed are looking for activities with meaning.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Zoom'' not only challenges kids to do good, but also to do
something radical _ ``if you like what you see, turn off the TV,''
the cast croons in the opening song.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Taylor and other WGBH executives, along with those at
PBS and the Corporation for Public Broadcasting (which provides
part of the funding for the show), all hope that the turn-off isn't
permanent and that viewers will re-''Zoom'' _ fast. Over the years,
the public broadcasting network has done fewer and fewer programs
for school-age kids, and the hardest part may be ``getting them to
PBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Once kids are there, though, Taylor points out that the new
``Zoom'' has a huge advantage over the old one. ``The interactivity
is so much more exciting with the advent of the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. On the ``Zoom'' site (www.pbs.org), kids can find
the secrets of Ubbi-Dubbi and play Zoom Zingers. They can download
instructions for science experiments and recipes like Dirt Pudding,
read poems and stories, and check out movie reviews from other
kids.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   With a click, they can even add their own poems, stories, games,
riddles and reviews to the mix. If they do, they'll get their names
listed in the Limelight, like Ali M., age 13, of Arlington; Whitney
F. of Keller; and Walker S. of Colleyville, just a few of the 2,930
kids who had sent in stuff before the third episode of the series
even aired.
</P>
<P>
   The new interactivity goes beyond the home computer. Ten museums
across the country, including the Fort Worth Museum of Science and
History, have Zoom Zones, where kids are supplied with materials to
complete the problem-solving activities from the show's new Habits
of the Mind curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Taylor _ and I _ eventually acknowledge this fact: It may simply
be time for ``Zoom'' again because the Zoomers of the '70s are
today's moms and dads.
</P>
<P>
   I set my VCR for Day Three of the show. Jack hadn't asked me to,
but the truth is that as a former Zoomer, I hope that maybe he'll
connect with the show the way I did. Having watched a ``Zoom: Best
of the 70s''video that WGBH produced to help kick off the new show,
I was shocked and only slightly embarrassed to find how much I
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Hubi, frubiends! A skinny girl appeared on the screen, and the
name Tracy formed itself in a dusty part of my brain. And then
there was the tall blond girl next to her. Ah, Nina. If only she
would sing ``The Cat Came Back'' ... And there was Bernadette, with
that swinging arm thing she did that looked so cool.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jack will watch ``Zoom.'' Maybe other kids will, too.
After all, the average child now watches about 31 hours a week of
TV, according to the 1998 PBS Roper Youth Report.
</P>
<P>
   It's an $8 million-a-season gamble on the part of public
television. Even now, ``Zoom'' execs are trying to get funds for
next season while they continue to edit the 40 episodes shot this
summer. ``The second season is the hardest sometimes,'' says
Taylor, who undoubtedly remembers that the first ``Zoom'' survived
into its second year only after a viewer letter-writing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Will channel-surfing preteens care? Maybe with a little
encouragement from parents like me, kids will learn where to find
``Zoom'' on the remote. Maybe the relatively quiet show won't seem
so odd.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, someday, empowerment will offer more appeal than the
PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Museum of Science and History is one of 10 sites
nationwide chosen to be a part of a community outreach pilot
program for the new ``Zoom.'' Here, and in the other Zoom Zones,
kids have access to the show's Web site, where they can get ideas
for science experiments, games and riddles _ or send in their own
ideas for possible inclusion on the PBS show. They'll also find
materials to do some of the Zoom projects and a computer to enter
data from experiments so that it can be collated on a national
basis.
</P>
<P>
   While directors at each site have some leeway in how to
interpret the activities of the Zone _ as a full-outreach van
program, a complete gallery, or an area within an existing museum
exhibit _ the concept is the same: Give kids more ways to interact
with the TV show as they explore principles of math and science. In
Fort Worth, a group of middle-schoolers from Fort Worth's Applied
Learning Academy are Zone volunteers, designing exhibits and
facilitating games and experiments with museum visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for the Zone through the end of ``Zoom's'' first season
comes from a grant from the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
