<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PSYCH-ART-2TAKES-     01-11 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PSYCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO THE COUCH: A REVIVAL FOR ANALYSIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychoanalysts, it would seem, have reason to be gloomy: These
are difficult times for the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Once the undisputed rulers of American psychiatry, analysts now
stand at the margins of a field where drug treatments and
short-term talking therapies predominate. Analytic patients are in
short supply: Without insurance reimbursement, even those who still
desire the four or five sessions per week typical of full-fledged
psychoanalysis can rarely afford to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   In managed-care circles, analysis has become a synonym for
treatment that costs too much and achieves too little. And the
profession fares little better in the public forum, where Woody
Allen remains an icon of endless self-absorption, and Freud-bashing
enjoys unflaggingly popularity as an intellectual sport.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the psychoanalytic community these days, there is little
hand wringing and only an occasional foray into nostalgia. In a
field notorious for its insularity and resistance to outside
critique, the threat of extinction has inspired a new vigor, a
frenzy of self-examination and the urge to reach out and connect
with the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a retrofitted psychoanalysis that is humbler,
hipper, more communicative, and considerably more tolerant than it
has been since Freud first floated his revolutionary notions in
Vienna. The rigid neo-Freudian orthodoxy that long held a lock on
American psychoanalysis has gradually given way to a gentler
theoretical pluralism, and, in a major sea change, analysts are no
longer required to have medical degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In an echo of the early days of the profession, when Melanie
Klein, Karen Horney and others were leading figures, women are once
again a strong presence, offering a feminist perspective on
traditionally male-oriented theory. And the old figure of the
silent, austere, authoritarian psychoanalyst is slowly being
replaced with a new model who is just another human being and not
averse to uttering a word or two.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such shifts will succeed in rekindling public interest
and replenishing the dwindling supply of patients is anyone's
guess. But they represent a new determination to stick around for
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a field that in its most vital aspects is changing,
wants to change, and is trying to think about what it is and what
it wants to be,'' said Dr. Kimberlyn Leary, associate director of
the University of Michigan's Psychological Clinic and a trainee at
the Michigan Psychoanalytic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Dr. Leary _ as a woman, an African-American and
a psychologist rather than a medical doctor _ at the annual
meetings of the American Psychoanalytic Association, held in
Manhattan recently, in itself was proof that much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Even a decade ago, the yearly gatherings of the association,
which was founded in 1911 by American followers of Freud and
remains the dominant psychoanalytic organization in the United
States, were populated by gray-haired men in dark suits, the
atmosphere one of sober formality.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings included no press room because, in the view of many
members, the less psychoanalysis appeared in the press the better.
Discussions focused narrowly on psychoanalytic technique and
practice, with little acknowledgment of events in the outside
world. And the tenor of the annual meetings, like that of the
discipline itself, was exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the attendance roster at the recent meetings
included many younger analysts, a large group of women, and at
least a few minorities. Panels addressed issues like race,
adoption, homophobia and sexual abuse. A session on ``Intuition,
Unconscious Communication and Thought Transference,'' vied with a
discussion group on the ``Applications of Psychoanalysis to
Sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts spoke of their work in atypical settings: with baseball
teams, in nursery schools, with police departments trying to combat
community violence. And different theoretical perspectives _
including the British school of object relations, Heinz Kohut's
self-psychology and Lacanian analysis _ were listed in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps the most striking difference was in how the analysts
at the meetings talked about their interactions with patients.
``The degree of certainty in the way we talk has changed,'' said
Dr. Marvin Margolis, a former president of the association. ``We're
a little more modest, more hypothetical about our interventions and
how we frame them.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once the analyst was seen as an authority who took charge
of treating the patient's pathology, most analysts now describe the
analyst-patient relationship as a collaborative endeavor, in which
the patient is a full partner. Many practitioners have abandoned
the notion that the analyst should be an entirely blank screen,
revealing no emotions or personal details.
</P>
<P>
   And while most analysts embrace the fundamentals of Freud's
``talking cure,'' _ the power of unconscious images and fantasies
to influence behavior, the importance of childhood experiences in
shaping development and the central role of transference, or the
replaying of early patterns of relating to others within the
analytic treatment _ few adhere inflexibly to a unified theory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they practice a kind of utilitarian eclecticism,
drawing upon different psychoanalytic schools as needed in the
treatment of individual patients.
</P>
<P>
   In any field, a transformation of this magnitude does not take
place overnight, and the changes in Freud's ``impossible
profession'' began long before the managed care revolution. In the
1960s, psychoanalysis, ascendant in psychiatry departments across
the country, was hugely successful _ and enormously over-confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a monopoly,'' said Dr. Arnold Richards, a New York
analyst who is editor of the Journal of the American Psychoanalytic
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1980s there were increasing signs of malaise. In
academic departments, psychoanalysts were rapidly losing ground to
psychiatrists with a more biological approach to mental illness. In
the public arena, interest in Freud's legacy was declining.
</P>
<P>
   Growth of the psychoanalytic association, which now has 3,200
members, about a third of the psychoanalysts in the United States,
came to a standstill, while the average age of members rose.
Enrollment in training institutes, which peaked at 1,194 students
in 1980, had dropped to 909 by 1989.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, a generation of American-born analysts
began to chafe at the conservatism and restrictiveness that
characterized the field's elders, many of them Europeans who
immigrated to the United States just before or after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   One antidote to these complaints, many believed, would be an
injection of new blood, and it came in 1988, when, in response to a
restraint of trade suit by psychologists, a settlement agreement
overturned the psychoanalytic association's longstanding policy of
restricting analytic training to candidates with medical degrees,
opening the field to lay analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal was a vindication of sorts for Freud, who did not
believe a medical degree should be a prerequisite to becoming a
psychoanalyst. And the past decade has seen an upsurge of
applicants to psychoanalytic institutes from a variety of
non-medical disciplines, including social work, psychology,
history, literature and sociology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, the latest year for which the association
has figures, 381 of 990 candidates training in 29 psychoanalytic
institutes around the country did not have medical degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps the biggest transformation in the way psychoanalysis
views itself and its place in the world came with the arrival of
new leaders, armed with a sense of urgency about the plight of
psychoanalysis and a determination to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Pyles, president of the psychoanalytic association,
is one example. Unlike his predecessors of a few decades ago, who
prided themselves on a scholarly detachment and made no attempt to
promote their profession's image, Pyles is a political activist.
</P>
<P>
   He urges his colleagues to learn how to walk into a
congressman's office and explain what psychoanalysis is and why it
is important in under five minutes, in an effort to win support for
issues like the protection of patient privacy and insurance
coverage of long-term therapy.
</P>
<P>
   He has broken down traditional barriers, reaching out to other
mental health organizations like the American Psychiatric
Association, and calling for ``a new vision of ourselves as
psychoanalysts of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   And with other leading psychoanalysts he is shepherding a
variety of projects designed to increase public knowledge and
broaden the field's influence. ``Ever since I was in training, this
attitude of psychoanalysis having to exist in some isolated
hothouse has driven me nuts,'' Pyles said recently. ``I think it
damn near killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   No amount of reform is likely to please the field's harshest
critics. And within the analytic community itself there are some
who argue that the changes have come too fast, that politics have
been substituted for scholarship, and that the core of the
discipline is being diluted by competing theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good deal of uncertainty where there used to be a
lot of conviction about the way psychology worked,'' said Dr.
Nathan Hale, a historian and author of ``The Rise and Crisis of
Psychoanalysis in the United States'' (Oxford University Press,
1995). ``The whole theoretical structure is up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   But if, as the slogan goes, attitude is everything,
psychoanalysis in its new incarnation probably has a better chance
of surviving than it once did.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a Prozac-smitten society, where quick fixes are the
rule, Freud's emphasis on deeper meaning and the unconscious mind
still exerts an appeal. Psychoanalytic patients may be scarce, but
psychoanalytic ideas inform a variety of academic disciplines and
provide the basis for a wide range of ``psychodynamic'' therapies.
</P>
<P>
   And psychoanalytic training still attracts newcomers: Dr. Leary,
for example, said she was drawn by the rather antiquated notion
that an encounter between two human beings could produce healing
and change. ``It's about as low tech as you can get,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Vaughan, a trainee at the Columbia University Center
for Psychoanalytic Training and Research, said, ``You do analytic
training because you can't not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first look at it,'' Dr. Vaughan continued, ``it
doesn't make sense, but if you really value seeing how people's
minds work in depth you get addicted to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, what will ultimately keep the field alive, said Dr. Owen
Renik, a San Francisco analyst who is chairman of the
psychoanalytic association's program committee and the author of a
forthcoming book chapter, ``Getting Real in Psychoanalysis,'' is
not the enthusiasm of practitioners but the ability of
psychoanalysts to help their patients, and to persuade the public
that they are able to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what you call yourself,'' Renik said, ``if you
help people feel better, word gets out. If you don't help people, I
don't care how good your marketing is, you'll go down the tubes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
