<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COURT-DISPUTES-2T     01-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COURT-DISPUTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT-APPOINTED SCIENTISTS ARE NO PANACEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Alice Dreger is assistant professor of science and technology
studies at the Lyman Briggs School of Michigan State University.)  
 (af)  
 By ALICE DREGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember that television advertisement for some over-the-counter
pain medication in which a soap-opera actor announced at the start
of his endorsement, ``I'm not a doctor, but I play one on TV''?
This is just the sort of conflation of acted-science and
real-science that led a federal judge overseeing lawsuits over
breast implants to appoint a panel of four scientists to decide the
central factual question of the case: Do implants cause immune
disorders?
</P>
<P>
   The panel studied relevant scientific research and found no
statistically significant difference between the incidence of
immune disorders in women who have had implants and those who have
not.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Angell, the executive editor of The New England Journal
of Medicine, has hailed this process as a solution to the ``junk
science'' that often floods court cases that hinge on scientific
facts. Angell correctly noted that typically in these cases
``experts are hired by lawyers on both sides to present their
opinions. But they are not required to cite scientific evidence _ a
vague reference to their own `experience' or `unpublished research'
will often do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Angell has long argued that in such cases we need ``a
dispassionate panel of experts'' with ``no stake in the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   While I share with Dr. Angell a concern over ``junk science''
and a concern for justice, I think she is too quick to envision the
court-appointed scientist as St. Peter at the gates of heaven,
judging true from false, superhuman, above earthly affairs. Let me
make clear that I am not disagreeing with the findings of the panel
in the implant case. But I wish to point out some serious problems
with this imagined ideal.
</P>
<P>
   First off, it is a damaging myth that passion merely clouds the
vision, with no compensatory effects. In fact, passion can allow a
scientist to surge past the clouds formed by accepted wisdom and
reach new discoveries tamer colleagues would not.
</P>
<P>
   We should not assume that people who exhibit little passion in
fact have little, nor should we assume that people who are
passionate could not possibly be right, or better at figuring out
what is right than the next person.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Dr. Barry J. Marshall, the young Australian
physician who discovered that peptic ulcers are caused by a
bacteria, Helicobacter pylori. Marshall's colleagues, stuck firmly
in the received wisdom that ulcers are caused by psychological
stress, thought his idea absurd. They ignored for years the
evidence for a bacterial cause of ulcers _ evidence Marshall was
able to see.
</P>
<P>
   So convinced was Marshall that he was right, he used himself as
a guinea pig, drinking the bacteria to prove that it turned his
once-healthy stomach diseased. Passionate? Yes. Passionate enough
to push until his colleagues finally recognized the truth of his
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the charge of being ``too passionate'' (translation:
``too passionate to be right'') is usually held against people
advocating change _ intellectual, social, institutional _ and
rarely against establishment scientists.
</P>
<P>
   I know a senior physicist who is so passionate about quarks that
he probably has erotic dreams about atoms, but no one doubts his
ability as a physicist. On the contrary, his passion wins him
awards and financing, and it probably should. But if an activist or
upstart points to scientific evidence that, say, an established
industry is harming people by burning toxic chemicals, he or she is
very often written off as ``too passionate,'' and up springs the
admonition that real scientists are dispassionate.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem of discounting certain voices stems from a
general inability we seem to have as humans to attribute more than
one major identity to any given person. Just as schoolchildren are
sometimes astonished to discover that their teacher is a parent,
too, people are often astonished that one could be an intellectual
and a person with a social and political identity as well, and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   So we prefer to think of ``good'' scientists as disembodied,
dispassionate. And we tend to assume that the only people who
contribute usefully to scientific matters are those specifically
trained and working as science professionals, but neither is this
so.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the late Marjory Stoneman Douglas. Ms. Douglas' formal
education was in English and she made a name as a writer, yet she
was best known for her careful observation and fierce advocacy of
the Florida Everglades. Her obituary in May in The New York Times
noted that she made her case for saving the Everglades ``with a
rare blend of science, local lore and history, and shimmering
writing.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A move toward court-appointed scientists could have the effect
of shutting out people like Ms. Douglas and Marshall, minority
voices that often turn out to lead the way. The value of people
like these _ the kind of challengers unlikely to be appointed by a
judge _ is that they see where others have blind spots.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, recognizing the fact that all people have biases and
blind spots, the judge in the implant case appointed four
scientists instead of only one. If scientists were St. Peter, we
would have needed only one. This is why I prefer the term ``courts
of scientists'' to ``science court'' _ the former recognizes the
human factor brought to any court case, whether or not adjudicated
by scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that all people have biases and blind spots,
appointing a panel of many scientists certainly seems better than
appointing one. Our scientific system has worked so well because it
often requires peer (group) review of studies and claims.
</P>
<P>
   But a science court could interpret very narrowly the term
``peer'' and leave out people who disagree with the scientific
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   A science court might also, given that scientists continue to be
mostly white and mostly male, tend to represent only part of the
population, and this would raise the question of whether a ``jury
of one's peers'' means something entirely different scientifically
than legally. (In the implants case, three of the four appointed
scientists were women, a gender ratio that _ perhaps purposely? _
did not reflect the scientific community at large.)
</P>
<P>
   All good scientists strive for accuracy and fairness, but
historians of science have repeatedly shown that a scientist's
background shapes his or her vision. The ever-passionate Louis
Pasteur conceived his brilliant experiment to disprove spontaneous
generation because he was a Catholic who found spontaneous
generation heretical.
</P>
<P>
   I offer this example specifically because Pasteur was right
about spontaneous generation; biases are necessary and often good _
we just need to be aware of them and to balance them whenever
possible. Otherwise we assume too much is ``fact'' set in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistical significance'' is a good example of something that
looks to many people like simple fact. Statistical significance _
the cut-off point scientists use to say ``more than this much
evidence counts as proof, and less than that much doesn't'' _ when
you get right down to it is arbitrary. Scientists use that cut-off
line because it has worked pretty well. But that does not mean
someone (like an upstart or activist) cannot or should not question
a particular conclusion that something is or is not proved.
</P>
<P>
   The question ``Does it work well?'' is really the ultimate test
in science. We use statistical significance because when we do we
tend to develop, for example, effective, safe drugs. So I hope we
will keep asking the question ``Does it work?'' as we move toward a
science court system.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, without a built-in test that allows us to see whether or
not the new system is working, its use will be unscientific. My
question, then, to Dr. Angell and to other proponents of science
courts is this: How will we know whether science courts are really
working for justice?
</P>
<P>
   In her editorial, Dr. Angell correctly noted that what led to
our needing court-appointed scientists was the fact that ``judges
are not trained to evaluate scientific testimony.'' As a
consequence, judges tend to let in anyone claiming to be
scientific.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of going in the direction of science courts, why not
solve the basic problem? Why not require that judges who sit on
cases dependent on scientific facts have training in scientific
reasoning? Turning to science courts instead of educating judges
seems to be the equivalent of throwing up one's hands in the face
of scientific illiteracy. And more problematically, it assumes
literacy comes (only) with a degree in science.
</P>
<P>
   Given all these considerations, science courts will, I predict,
tend to be inherently conservative, that is, more likely to believe
the claims of the established, and more likely, when in doubt, to
rule in favor of the establishment rather than risk having the
public realize that scientists cannot immediately answer every
question put to them.
</P>
<P>
   If this does happen, ultimately science courts will feed into
the lazy public assumption that scientists are St. Peters (or
worse, devils), instead of very smart, often wonderfully passionate
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
