<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE NIGHT SKIES LEAVES US MOONSTRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are halfway between blue moons, so-to-speak, in one of those
rare months with two full full moons.
</P>
<P>
   Which could account for the recent actions of Congress, the
Midwest's terrible winter weather and the National Basketball
Association's expectations that we're going to accept an
abbreviated season.
</P>
<P>
   It's not very often we get two full moons in one month _ the
first one this month was Jan. 2, and the next is Jan. 31 _ which
some scholars suggest is the import of the saying ``once in a blue
moon,'' or rarely.
</P>
<P>
   And this year is all the more rare in that we are to have two
months in which there are pairs of full moons. March 2 and March 31
also will be full moons. And we'll have a partial lunar eclipse
July 28, as well as a total eclipse of the sun Aug. 11. Observing
all that happening in the night sky should be a whole lot more
interesting than watching still one more
asteroid-headed-toward-Earth doomsday movie.
</P>
<P>
   There are as many explanations, all of them vague, about the
derivation and meaning of blue moon as there are asteroids now
heading toward earth. Originally, it was meant as a complete
absurdity. A 16th-century proverb stated: ``Yf they saye the moune
is beleue, We must believe that it is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the meaning became closer to ``hardly ever,'' such
as those rare months in which there are two full moons.
</P>
<P>
   If this be a month of moonings, so to speak, perhaps we need
consider how our moon has proved to be an odd metaphor, indeed.
Apollo astronaut Frank Borman was no poet, but he pretty much said
it: ``The moon is a different thing to each one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   What might have happened to Shakespeare's Romeo if that hapless
lover had declared: ``But soft! What light through yonder window
breaks? It is the west, and Juliet is the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   And how might things have gone in nursery-book land if the cow
jumped over the sun, which would have required some revising of
that rhyme so the dish might run away with the bun.
</P>
<P>
   Since my 5th-grade teacher first read us the poems of Alfred
Noyes, I have silently recited, at seeing clouds racing across the
moon: ``The wind was a torrent of darkness among the gusty trees,
The moon was a ghostly galleon tossed upon cloudy seas ...''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and Hart had to rewrite the song at least three times
before ``Blue Moon'' became a hit. It's first version was titled
``Prayer'' and was to have been sung by Jean Harlow in an MGM
musical, ``Hollywood Party,'' which really was an update of MGM's
``Hollywood Revue Of 1929.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harlow wouldn't do the film and the song was shelved until
Rodgers and Hart were asked for a song for ``Manhattan Melodrama,''
with Clark Gable and Myrna Loy. Hart reportedly just rewrote the
lyrics and called it ``The Bad In Every Man.'' A song publisher
suggested they lyrics couldn't be marketed, and Hart suggested
``something corny like `Blue Moon.''' And the lyrics were again
rewritten for what became one of the duo's largest hits. ``Blue
Moon'' sold more than 1 million sheets of music and the Marcels'
1961 recording also was a million-plus seller.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet Beethoven had the same trouble trying to market his
``Moonlight Sonata.'' And Debussy no doubt ran into similar
problems trying to sell ``Clair de lune.'' If Beethoven had called
his piece ``Blue Moon Sonata,'' it might have become a platinum
record for Liberace.
</P>
<P>
   People have been fascinated by the moon for a long, long time,
even before Sen. Strom Thurmon was born. And our moon has figured
in some wonderful hoaxes. Back in 1835, a New York Sun reporter
fabricated a story about a British astronomer having discovered
winged men and wild animals on the moon with the aid of a powerful
new telescope.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's circulation increased almost ten-fold, and the
hoax story inspired a women's organization to raise money for
sending missionaries to the moon. Since then, we've spent billions
to send emissaries there and they've not managed to return with so
much as a slice of green cheese.
</P>
<P>
   That saying, coincidentally, meant uncured cheese the same way
we talk about green fruit. No one actually believed the moon was
colored green, any more than Andy Williams believed the moon was in
the river.
</P>
<P>
   There are pale yellow moons and ghastly white moons and yes,
even bluish moons. That bluish cast is said to be caused by
atmospheric dust particles filtering out certain parts of the
moon's reflective light.
</P>
<P>
   Blue is considered off-color by many, which is why some flicks
are called blue movies. Etymological resources hold that the name
derives from the old Chinese practice of painting the outside of
brothels a bright blue.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Monday, that being the one traditionally spent on sinful or
fattening indulgences, comes just before Lent. Blue gowns in Old
England was a term for prostitutes, derived from the blue dresses
worn as uniforms when prostitutes were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   All this we can ponder once in a blue moon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
