<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-T     01-11 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEL FINE: THE CELTIC BAND LOST TRIBE IS IN FINE FORM ON ITS DEBUT
CD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lost Tribe first formed in Dallas-Fort Worth out of the
ashes of Rakish Paddy in 1987, the band's name was a reference to
the variety of music John Burleson and John Delaney wanted to play,
which verged from Ireland to Scotland to the Celtic Brittany area
of France to America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says Burleson, ``it's a joke about how spread out we are.''
</P>
<P>
   And spread out they are: Burleson and Delaney live down around
Austin, Betsy Cummings Ener makes her home in the country near
McKinney, Texas, and Mike Hryekewicz, after moving to Portland,
Ore., for several years, has settled in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Such movement has meant death (or at least personnel changes) to
many a band, but Lost Tribe has not only held ranks but prospered,
continuing to play club shows, festivals (including the North Texas
Irish Festival), weddings and the like at the rate of one to two
shows per month. They also found time to record an excellent debut
CD, ``The Bonny Wooden Witch,'' this past spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really needed something to sell at shows,'' Burleson says,
``and what took so long was just not getting organized enough to do
it. I'm glad we did it when we did, though, because there are some
tunes that were written recently, such as ``Betsy's Wedding,'' that
we put on the CD. We just laid off shows last May, June and July
and met up and did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Full of robust playing, ``Witch'' is an uncommonly good CD of
Celtic music; both Ener and Delaney sing very well, Hryekewicz's
fiddle-playing is laudable throughout, and Burleson excels on
guitar, banjo and bodhran.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Witch'' really stand out, though, is how smartly
sets of reels or jigs are arranged. The band's ability to stitch
different songs together and make them flow invites comparisons to
fairly recent debuts by both Dervish and Nomos, as well as classic
recordings by De Danann.
</P>
<P>
   This ability is even more notable considering that between them
the members play nine instruments _ again and again, they choose
just the right combination for a given set, or song within a set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrangements are as important as finding a tune, or
more,'' says Burleson. ``When we're apart we work on the tunes,
getting the licks down, but when we're together we work on the
transitions between tunes and what will make it the most effective.
A lot of tunes evoke a certain instrument. Each one has a different
feel, and often you can hear a tune and know it was composed for
pipes or flute.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Hryekewicz moved to Oregon, the band never considered
breaking up, Burleson says. Gigs are booked only on weekends, and
the members often mail songs back and forth before settling on
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of, `Buy this record and learn this song and
we'll put it between these tunes' and like that,'' he says. ``It's
the folk process _ passing songs around. And we do get together for
rehearsals.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement works so well, he says, that ``we've never had
to turn down a gig because of where we lived. And having Mike in
Tulsa now makes it easier. Now he can just drive to shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Burleson says they recorded enough material for an entire second
CD. Lost Tribe will continue, he says, with the only immediate goal
being to keep playing and, hopefully, make a second CD fairly soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to play bigger, quieter places,'' he says. ``We'd
really like to get locked into that vicious cycle of selling a
bunch of CDs and making another one and another one.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
