<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8349 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PACZYNSKI-PROFILE     01-11 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PACZYNSKI-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOHDAN PACZYNSKI, STAR-STRUCK VISIONARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(James Glanz writes for Science magazine.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ When he was 14 and growing up in 1950s Poland,
Bohdan Paczynski started observing the flashing and flaring of the
double stars called binaries through a 10-inch telescope outside
his hometown of Warsaw. Now, with the constellation Orion gently
shimmering over his shoulder like an alighting falcon, Paczynski
stands on a bridge above Lake Carnegie on a chilly evening here and
explains his proposal to record panoramic images of the entire sky
_ all of it _ several times each and every night, ``endlessly,'' as
he puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers, and anyone else who wanted to view the images over
the Internet, would use them as a sort of cosmic surveillance
camera to find thousands of relatively bright but undiscovered
exploding stars, binaries, pulsating stars, quasars and comets, not
to mention the dozens of house-sized asteroids that whip through
Earth's immediate neighborhood every day.
</P>
<P>
   These fluctuating features of the sky are so unexplored, and the
necessary equipment is so unimposing, that an astronomer who shares
Paczynski's enthusiasm plans to set up an observing station amid
the bright lights of New York City _ on the grounds of the American
Museum of Natural History on Central Park West _ and hopes to make
modest astronomical discoveries there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can discover some asteroids from Manhattan,'' Paczynski
said with deadpan understatement, his hands jammed into his coat
pockets, ``this would bring excitement to the field.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a knack for generating excitement, and for sniffing out
scientific openings where others see impossibility, that has made
Paczynski's mind one of the world's leading engines of astronomical
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   That role is all the more notable considering that Paczynski, a
professor at Princeton University, has for decades been a
theoretical astrophysicist. It is a calling that often leads far
from real sky-watching, but Bohdan Paczynski (pronounced BOG-don
pah-CHIN-ski) has made it his business to spur the observers into
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always looked five or 10 years ahead,'' said Dr.
Michael Shara, an astronomer at the Space Telescope Science
Institute in Baltimore, where he heads the office that allocates
observing time for the Hubble Space Telescope. ``While he does
sometimes have wild, far-out ideas, he grounds them firmly in
physics. He makes these terrific predictions that jog the observers
to go out and either support him or shoot him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Paczynski's scientific bombshells was a recognition in the
1980s that the cataclysms in space called gamma-ray bursts, which
had accidentally been discovered by satellites launched to monitor
nuclear tests, probably originated billions of light-years away
rather than in this galaxy. To be visible from such vast distances,
gamma-ray bursts would have to be the brightest objects in the
universe for the few moments during which they shine. That view was
at first scorned by virtually all other astronomers but has been
spectacularly confirmed by telescopic measurements in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   His vision has also led to an entirely new field of astronomy,
based on a 1986 calculation in which Paczynski showed how
electronic cameras and fast computers could help astronomers
capture a phenomenon first predicted by Albert Einstein, in which
the gravity of one star or planet can briefly act like a lens and
``magnify'' the light of a more distant star. Many astronomers
doubted that the effect, called gravitational microlensing, would
ever be seen, but it is now routinely observed in searches for
everything from planetary systems and dim, distant stars to a
mysterious constituent of the cosmos called dark matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think it revolutionizes astronomy,'' said Dr.
Rosanne Di Stefano of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for
Astrophysics of gravitational microlensing, which she called ``a
whole different way of looking at the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Paczynski effectively took up permanent residence in the United
States on Dec. 13, 1981. On that day, the Polish leader Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski declared a military crackdown while Paczynski,
his wife and two children were on a sabbatical in this country.
``At that time things looked really bad,'' Paczynski said in an
interview. ``The reports from our friends, whatever we read in the
media here, gave an impression that things were actually worse than
under Stalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later he concluded that panic had amplified the reports,
but he had already accepted a position at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Paczynski seems neither pleased nor especially bitter about his
decades of coping with Communist rule, viewing it as an
inconvenient fact of his life that Westerners have difficulty
understanding. The post-World War II Warsaw to which his parents
moved from Lithuania was far from prosperous and still half in
ruins. But both his parents had jobs, and he said that every family
he knew, including his own, covered income shortfalls with heavy
borrowing from friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, it was a bit like a credit card here,'' Paczynski
said. ``So the same concept functioned in Communist Poland.''
</P>
<P>
   But if everyone was borrowing, where did the money come from?
``I never figured that out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Professionally, his big break came thanks to his mother. When he
was 14 she contacted a professor at the Warsaw University
Observatory whom she knew from her university days in the city now
called Vilnius, Lithuania, and said she had a son who was very
interested in astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   That was how Paczynski got the chance to observe so-called
``eclipsing binaries'' through a small telescope outside Warsaw
each summer. Such stars are born in pairs and whirl around each
other in such a way that one occasionally passes in front of the
other, eclipsing it as seen from Earth. If the eclipsed star is
much brighter than the other, the combined brightness _ all that
can be seen through a small telescope _ can dip by a factor of 30
or 40 for a few hours, then return to normal. ``This is pretty
spectacular, at least for a young kid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   He followed the mostly older students at the observatory to
college in Poland, and then to a research assistantship at Lick
Observatory in California, where he had the good fortune to work
for Dr. George Preston, the noted astronomer who is soon to retire
from the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about 48 hours to figure out that he was smarter
than I was,'' said Preston in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his emigration, Paczynski is viewed as a major figure in
the recent revival of astronomy in Poland, forming numerous
partnerships with researchers, including the Optical Gravitational
Lensing Experiment, whimsically called OGLE, a highly successful
microlensing search led by Dr. Andrzej Udalski at the Warsaw
University Observatory. Paczynski has also created a conduit for
students to study in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is basically a legend in Warsaw,'' said Krzysztof Stanek,
an astronomer at the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics
who originally came to the United States from Poland to study with
Paczynski.
</P>
<P>
   One of those research partnerships involves Dr. Grzegorz
Pojmanski, an astronomer at Warsaw University Observatory who is
running a pilot project for Paczynski's latest passion _ what he
calls the All Sky Automated Survey. Paczynski's pale blue eyes
blazed with his customary enthusiasm as he gave a rapid-fire
explanation of how the survey has the potential to rake in tens of
thousands of unknown binary stars of every description. Most modern
telescopes peer in great detail at tiny specks of the heavens,
missing the overall picture, he said. Large-scale surveys produce
invaluable snapshots of the sky, but cannot keep track of what
varies, pulsates or flares up and disappears forever.
</P>
<P>
   There are asteroids, too, to spot. On any given day, about 10
asteroids 100 feet or so across and 100 asteroids 30 feet across
tear past Earth at a distance closer than the Moon. Many can be
briefly seen with small telescopes. More elaborate equipment could
pick up the stellar explosions in distant galaxies called
supernovae or the faint optical ``afterglow'' of gamma-ray bursts.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just the celestial phenomena that are already
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that we just do not know what unexpected things
may be there,'' Paczynski said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the project published the results of its first look
at a small section of the sky. Paczynski has secured just under
$100,000 in private financing to observe a section 10 times larger
over the next three years; at the end of that time, he and other
astronomers plan to make a proposal to the National Science
Foundation for financing of a major expansion of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Turner, the University of Chicago astrophysicist who
is spokesman for the Sloan Digital Sky Survey, which has just begun
producing a giant snapshot of a quarter of the northern sky, among
other studies, agreed with Paczynski's assessment. ``We know very
little about things that go flash in the night,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Those views are backed up by the first observations by
Pojmanski, who rigged an electronic camera and a simple telephoto
lens with a 3-inch aperture to scan a small patch of sky over and
over. In two months of observations, taken from the grounds of the
Las Campanas Observatory in Chile, Pojmanski turned up 130 fairly
bright variable sources, three-fourths of which were previously
unknown pulsating stars and eclipsing binaries.
</P>
<P>
   A system to monitor the entire sky would involve sites around
the world, with a clearinghouse to store data received over the
Internet. Paczynski said he would favor a loose confederation of
observers, some of whom could be amateurs. (Indeed, Tom Droege, a
retired engineer from the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory and
an amateur astronomer, has also proposed surveying the sky on a
regular basis.)
</P>
<P>
   Paczynski already has a dedicated convert to the confederation
philosophy in Shara, the Hubble astronomer, who is set to join the
new astrophysics department at the American Museum of Natural
History and become curator in astronomy there. Not only does he
think the all-sky survey could surpass all previous searches for
novae and ``dwarf'' novae _ his own areas of specialty _ but he
also has bigger game in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enthusiastic about trying to set up one of the sites for
this thing in New York City,'' he said. ``Which might sound like a
crazy thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan, he acknowledges, is a less efficient place than a
Chilean mountaintop for discoveries, but with the right
photographic filters and electronic cameras, he said, enough of
Manhattan's light can be blocked to make the project workable. The
station would serve as a demonstration of the pilot project in
Chile, as an educational project and as a possible source of
discoveries on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from gaining the experience of running a small telescope,
New Yorkers might ``even get to discover an asteroid or two,'' said
Neil deGrasse Tyson, director of the Hayden Planetarium. ``And if
you do,'' Tyson said, ``you get to have it named after you.''
</P>
<P>
   Paczynski said that scientists might even learn something if
students could tinker with the new data. ``Usually young kids are
fantastic at computer problems,'' he said, in what sounded like an
updated appeal to the same lure of the telescope that had started
him on the starry path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
