<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARNEGIE-HALL-2TAKES-     01-11 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNEGIE-HALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW STAGE FOR CARNEGIE AND A NEW LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Plans for Carnegie Hall's third concert space, a
flexible, technologically up-to-date chamber music hall that is
scheduled to open during the 2001-2002 season, were formally
unveiled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by the violinist Isaac Stern,
president of Carnegie Hall, and Sanford I. Weill, its chairman, at
the Rose Museum next to the main hall. An exhibition about the
space and its history _ since 1891, it has been a recital hall, an
Off Broadway theater and, most recently, the Carnegie Hall Cinema _
opened Monday at the Rose Museum and runs through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The hall is expected to cost about $50 million, and in
recognition of a $10 million grant toward its construction, it is
to be named the Arthur and Judy Zankel Hall at Carnegie Hall. The
performance space itself, however, is to be called the Judith Arron
Auditorium. Ms. Arron was the executive director of Carnegie Hall
from 1986 until her death in December, and the new hall was one of
her initiatives. The auditorium was named for Ms. Arron after Weill
and his wife, Joan, donated $5 million to the project.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Hall's programming for the 1999-2000 season, which
opens with a performance of the Mahler Fifth Symphony by Lorin
Maazel and the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra on Sept. 29, was also
announced, as was the appointment of Pierre Boulez as the second
holder of the Carnegie Hall Composer's Chair. Boulez succeeds Ellen
Taaffe Zwilich.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Carnegie Hall's programming is the start of a
multiseason ``Perspectives'' series in which Boulez, Daniel
Barenboim and Maurizio Pollini will each perform in programs
emphasizing the 20th century. As part of this series and in other
concerts, 28 works will have their world, United States or New York
premieres at the hall next season.
</P>
<P>
   The new hall, with a capacity of up to 640 people, depending on
which of three stage and seating configurations is used, will be
significantly larger than Weill Recital Hall, which seats 268, but
dwarfed by the 2,804-seat main hall.
</P>
<P>
   The new hall, which is being designed by Polshek Partnership
Architects, will have three levels. The first is a street-level
entrance on Seventh Avenue, where the lobby of the Carnegie Hall
Cinema was. It will have a new marquee, and its exterior will mesh
with the rest of the landmark building. The second level,
underground, is a mezzanine that can seat 140 and also has a lobby,
coat check, bar and restrooms. Another level down will be the
parterre, which can seat 500 and has its own lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The flexibility is largely in the parterre floor, with a system
of sectional lifts that allow for either an end stage (with or
without an orchestra pit), a center stage or a flat floor with no
stage. When a stage is used, the lifts make it possible for the
audience area to be flat or raked. The seats will be on a series of
chair wagons that can be quickly moved between the hall and an
adjacent storage garage.
</P>
<P>
   Wiring to accommodate audiovisual, recording and communications
systems will be installed as well, giving Carnegie what Ms. Arron
described in an address to its board last fall as ``the capability
to take our work from the corner of 57th Street and Seventh Avenue
to all corners of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Hall has raised about $40 million for the project,
including nearly $13 million from the City of New York and $2
million from New York State. Construction is scheduled to begin in
the summer. No specific programming was announced _ the hall won't
open for another three seasons _ but the new space is expected to
be used for chamber music, contemporary music, musical theater,
chamber opera, dance, children's events and professional training
workshops.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999-2000 season at the main hall and Weill Recital Hall,
meanwhile, includes 130 concerts. Of particular interest are those
in the Perspectives series, in which the featured musicians will
work in performing and teaching collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   Barenboim begins his contribution as a pianist in a recital with
the tenor Placido Domingo (Jan. 30, 2000). Domingo's appearances on
the opera stage and with orchestral accompaniment have been
plentiful, but his recital with Barenboim will be his first New
York recital with piano accompaniment. Barenboim will also conduct
the Chicago Symphony in three programs (March 4 to 6, 2000), with
repertory that includes Bruckner and Mahler symphonies, Boulez's
``Notations I-IV'' and the New York premiere of his ``Notations
VII,'' as well as the New York premiere of Elliott Carter's first
opera, ``What Next,'' which has a libretto by Paul Griffiths, a
contributing music critic for The New York Times. Just after the
Chicago Symphony programs, Barenboim is to coach pianists and
conductors in Mozart in a two-day workshop with the Civic Orchestra
of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Barenboim is to be the soloist in the Schoenberg Piano Concerto
under the baton of another Perspectives artist, Boulez, during a
series in which Boulez conducts the London Symphony Orchestra
(March 10 to 13, 2000). Boulez's repertory will also include his
``Originel''; the Ligeti Violin Concerto, with Christian Tetzlaff,
and works by Gyorgy Kurtag, Salvatore Sciarrino (a piano concerto,
with Pollini as the soloist), Olga Neuwirth, George Benjamin,
Stravinsky and Mahler. Boulez will direct a workshop on
20th-century chamber music (Nov. 17 to 19), followed by
performances with his Ensemble Intercontemporain (Nov. 19 to 21).
</P>
<P>
   Pollini's contribution to Perspectives includes two piano
recitals, with works by Beethoven, Schoenberg and Stockhausen (Oct.
10) and Boulez and Debussy (March 20, 2000), as well as a
collaboration with the Juilliard String Quartet in a program that
includes Beethoven, Schoenberg, Berg, Webern, Stravinsky and Chopin
(Oct. 20), and appearances with the Arnold Schoenberg Choir, both
at Carnegie Hall and, under its sponsorship, at the 92nd Street Y
(March 28 to April 6, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Some of Pollini's contribution is curatorial: besides his
performances, his series includes the Philadelphia Orchestra's
performance of the Shostakovich Symphony No. 14, conducted by
Wolfgang Sawallisch (Oct. 19); the performance by James Levine and
the Met Orchestra of John Cage's ``Atlas Eclipticalis'' (Nov. 7),
and the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra of Amsterdam's performances
of Varese and Ligeti works, conducted by Riccardo Chailly (Feb. 10,
2000).
</P>
<P>
   Barenboim, Boulez and Pollini will also present ``Perspectives''
concerts in the 2000-2001 season. Another project at Carnegie Hall
is the American Composers Orchestra's ``20th Century Snapshots''
series, conducted by Dennis Russell Davies. Four of the 10 thematic
installments in the series are due next season. Included is the
premiere of a work by Laurie Anderson commissioned for the series
as well as world premieres of works by Muhal Richard Abrams and
Daniel Roumain, the New York premiere of a scene from Philip Glass'
``White Raven'' and the New York premiere of Alvin Singleton's ``56
Blows.''
</P>
<P>
   Other works commissioned by Carnegie Hall for performance next
season are a vocal work by John Corigliano, to be performed by
Sylvia McNair; a chamber work by Brian Ferneyhough, and a vocal
chamber work by John Musto. Boulez, Carter, Ms. Zwilich, Louis
Andriessen, Milton Babbitt, Tan Dun, Chen Yi, Hannibal Lokumbe,
Wolfgang Rihm and Frederick Rzewski have been commissioned to write
short works for ``The Carnegie Hall Millennium Piano Book,'' which
the pianist Ursula Oppens will perform.
</P>
<P>
   Works by Krzystof Penderecki and Joan Tower will have world
premieres, and works by Boulez, Maazel, John Adams, Richard
Danielpour, Einojuhani Rautavaara and Poul Ruders will have New
York premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestras visiting Carnegie Hall next season include the Berlin
Philharmonic (with Claudio Abbado), the New York Philharmonic (with
Kurt Masur), the Cleveland Orchestra (with Christoph von Dohnanyi),
the Boston Symphony Orchestra (with Seiji Ozawa), the Oslo
Philharmonic and the Pittsburgh Symphony (with the director they
share, Mariss Jansons), the National Symphony (with Leonard
Slatkin), the Montreal Symphony Orchestra (with Charles Dutoit) and
the San Francisco Symphony (with Michael Tilson Thomas). The Met
Orchestra will present its sixth season at the hall, and the
Philadelphia Orchestra will offer five concerts in celebration of
its centenary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
