<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-SPRAWL12-COX     01-11 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPRAWL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, sensing the emergence
of a new political issue that could ultimately benefit Vice
President Gore's presidential bid next year, has designed a
multibillion-dollar plan to stop the march of new homes, malls and
business parks, and make urban areas more livable.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected Tuesday to announce plans for the
federal government to spend nearly $1 billion a year to buy
undeveloped land in urban areas for parks and preservation as a
hedge against future development.
</P>
<P>
   It would mark a major shift in land acquisition policy. Over the
last decade, with budget deficits running high, the federal
government has purchased hardly any open land.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's anticipated announcement follows an initiative
announced Monday by Gore to create a ``Better America'' bond
program that would generate $10 billion to help local communities
preserve green space, reduce traffic congestion, protect water
quality and clean up abandoned industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new livability initiative represents meaningful federal
support for our 'smart growth' effort already underway in central
Texas,'' said Rep. Lloyd Doggett (D-Texas), who was on hand for
Gore's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Known around the White House as Gore's ``livable communities
agenda,'' the initiatives are part of the 2000 budget Clinton will
submit to Congress next month.
</P>
<P>
   They come on the heels of a national election last November in
which voters approved nearly 200 state and local ballot initiatives
on curbing urban sprawl, signaling the maturing of a political
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, for example, voters approved a $75.9 million bond
issue for the park and recreation system that included about $40
million for parks and bike trails around Austin.
</P>
<P>
   However, the most dramatic example of anti-sprawl sentiment in
last fall's election was Ventura County in southern California. A
huge majority stripped their elected supervisors of the power to
approve new subdivisions and put it in the hands of the voters
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his announcement Monday, alluded to last year's
election. ``We are taking citizens' concerns to the very top of our
national agenda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this issue has finally trickled up to Washington
from the grass roots,'' Holly Minch, a spokeswoman for the Sierra
Club, said Monday. ``The environment is a winning political
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is preparing to run for the Democratic Party's 2000
presidential nomination, has long been identified with the
environmental movement. As a U.S. senator, he wrote a best-seller,
Earth in the Balance, which warned that the engines of civilization
had brought humankind to the brink of ecological catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, Gore has softened his approach,
concentrating on the politically palatable notion of improving
living conditions, particularly in the voter-rich suburbs of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Home Builders (NAHB) , which in the
fall complained of being ``demonized'' by environmentalists in
``smart growth'' initiatives, issued a politically cautious
statement in response to Gore's announcement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ruma, the NAHB's incoming president, said he welcomed
the vice president's involvement in the issue but questioned such
an imposing role for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preservation of open space beyond the backyard can best be
accomplished through local comprehensive plans that bring builders,
citizens and government officials together to provide needed
housing while protecting the environment,'' his statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sierra Club President Carl Pope said the administration's
initiatives are ``a good first step'' toward addressing urban
sprawl, which he labeled ``the fastest growing threat to our
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1970, more than 19 million acres of rural land has been
developed, according to the Sierra Club. The current rate of
development uses 400,000 acres a year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ``Better America'' bond program unveiled by Gore, some
$9.5 billion would be generated over the next 15 years for
investments by state and local governments to preserve green space,
create or restore urban parks, protect water quality and clean up
abandoned industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the taxpayer would be about $700 million over the
first five years, but the administration had no cost estimates for
the final 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Also as part of Gore's ``livable communities'' agenda, the
administration will propose spending $6.1 billion on public transit
next year, nearly 5 percent more than the current level of
spending, to ease traffic congestion . The administration also
wants to spend another $2.2 billion to help local communities come
up with better transportation.
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
