today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
ALI-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ You may not know the name, but you know
the face. It's a face we've watched grow up on the TV hit ``Fresh
Prince of Bel Air,'' where Tatyana Ali played Will Smith's younger
sister Ashley for five seasons. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
TITANIC-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ In ``1776,'' Peter Stone, who wrote
the story and the book for the musical, uses the famous line
attributed to Benjamin Franklin, ``We must indeed hang together, or
most assuredly we shall all hang separately.'' In ``Titanic,''
which just arrived for an eight-week run at the Ahmanson Theatre,
Stone's message is similar, though unspoken: We most assuredly are
all in the same boat. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8373 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALI-MUSIC-LADN     01-11 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALI-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENCINO ACTRESS HITS MUSIC CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; You may not know the name, but you know the face.
</P>
<P>
   It's a face we've watched grow up on TV's ``The Fresh Prince of
Bel Air,'' where singer and college freshman Tatyana Ali played
younger sister Ashley alongside Will Smith for six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who was 11 when ``Fresh Prince'' started and 17 when it
ended, began her first semester at Harvard a few months ago even as
her debut single, ``Daydreamin','' was peaking at No. 6 on the
national singles chart.
</P>
<P>
   The good-natured Ali, appearing in the forthcoming feature film
``Jawbreaker,'' said working with actor-rapper Smith taught her
about comedy _ and to expect the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the camera went on, he'd do whatever he wanted,'' said
Ali, who turns 20 on Jan. 24. ``I certainly learned improvisation
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also guided Ali through the wilds of the music business.
After encouraging her to sing, Smith signed Ali to his production
company, Will Smith Enterprises, and landed a deal with Sony's MJJ
Music label. Her hip-hop-laced debut album, ``Kiss the Sky,''
co-produced by such pop-r&AMP;b hitmakers as Rodney Jenkins, Shawn
Stockman (Boyz II Men), Vincent Herbert and Narada Michael Walden,
was released in August.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he signed Ali, Smith joked: ``Because she is almost as
talented as I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who applied to 10 top colleges and was invited to attend
all of them, deferred her Harvard enrollment while working on the
album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm such a pessimist because I thought the one school that
accepts me, I'll go to,'' Ali said. ``But I got accepted to all of
them. So, I did a road trip. I knew I wanted to go to an East Coast
school. I had this whole Princeton ideal of cobblestone streets and
beautiful lawns and students sitting under the trees doing their
homework. I visited everywhere, but I really liked Boston a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Ali planned to study biological anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a class just so I would know right away,'' she
explained. ``And I know that I'm not going to major in that anymore
because I hate that class. It's a genetics class and I just can't
stand it. One of the classes I really like is African-American
studies and I'm doing really well in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali, whose parents and two teen-age sisters live in Encino,
stays in a dorm suite with five other students. At first, the
freshman class was a bit cowed having a TV star in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew I was coming,'' Ali said. ``It took about a
month for everyone to chill out. It was like little interview
sessions on every corner. The only thing that freaked me out was
during freshman social activities, kids would ask to take a picture
with me. And I didn't know how to deal with it because this was my
home. I remember I told this one girl, `I'm going to graduate with
you. We're going to take classes together and be in study groups
together and party together. It's really not that much of a big
deal.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They got over it, especially the people I live with who see me
in my robe walking down the hall with my toothbrush. They see me as
just another person. And everyone's gotten really protective of me.
A lot of people in my building who I don't necessarily know tell me
if someone's asking for me or hanging around the dorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali has a part in Columbia-Tristar's ``Jawbreaker,'' a dark
comedy about three teen-age girls who accidentally kill their best
friend. The film, which also stars Rose McGowan and Pam Grier,
opens Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tiny role,'' Ali said. ``I play a really snobby
cheerleader who wants desperately to be prom queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali's audience expanded over the winter when she was featured on
an oft-repeated Disney Channel special also starring teen
heartthrobs 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times when I've had club dates where it seemed
the people were too old,'' Ali said. ``And I get up on stage and
I'm completely welcomed. I've done huge arena shows with thousands
of people my age, which is probably the most difficult thing to do
because you're performing in front of your peers. And then I've
done Nickelodeon shows for little kids and that's been fine. So, I
just don't know who my biggest fans are. I've been surprised a few
times.''
</P>
<P>
   One staunch admirer is Jeanann Saigbah, 13, of Lowell, Mass.,
who calls Ali ``an inspiration. She's the best. I like her as a
singer and actress and person. I think she's the nicest person I've
ever heard about. I'm her No. 1 fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali recently released the dance-oriented ``Boy You Knock Me
Out,'' the second single from ``Kiss the Sky,'' which recently hit
No. 5 on Billboard's Heatseekers album chart for new artists. When
the disc came out, she was unsure how it would be received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought no one's gonna like it, no radio station's gonna
play it, nothing will happen with it,'' Ali said. ``If people know
you as an actor, they're not always as willing to accept you as a
singer. I didn't really have a plan because this wasn't supposed to
happen. All through my career I never really had a goal so I never
had a map to show me how to get there. The only real constant in my
life is school.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali has been proving her ability on stage with weekend shows
while plans are being worked out for a tour this summer with a
backing band.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard my song (`Daydream') played live, it was
the most incredible rush I've ever experienced in my life,'' she
said. ``I was so giddy on that stage, it was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who attended the Buckley School in Sherman Oaks while
working on NBC's ``Fresh Prince,'' plans to move back to Los
Angeles after college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encino is my home,'' the singer said. ``Once I learned how to
drive, I was driving over the hill a lot and doing all sorts of
things all over the city. The Valley has always been good to me.'' &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
