<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-PUBLIC12-COX     01-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-PUBLIC12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS TO SEEK TO OPEN IMPEACHMENT DELIBERATIONS
 &HT;    440&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two senators launched a campaign Monday to warn the
public that after round-the-clock news coverage at the start of
President Clinton's impeachment trial, they may be closed out of
the final stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many American people know that our debates are
going to be secret,'' Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said as he announced
an effort to overturn a longstanding rule that requires the
senators to shut the doors at the trial's end and decide the fate
of the president in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned through the years that sunshine is best
political disinfectant,'' Harkin said as he attempted to enlist the
public to protest the secrecy rule.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Rule 24,'' the procedure would allow open coverage
for arguments and other trial proceedings, including any witness
testimony, but not for debates on motions or deliberations on the
final verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who is co-sponsoring the
Harkin resolution: ``It would be a profound mistake for us to start
off for the first two weeks, and then all of a sudden, when we go
into our deliberations and have our debate on these important
questions, we essentially shut the public out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone said it would be necessary for ``closure'' and
``healing'' to have all of the Senate debates open for TV coverage.
Turning off the cameras and closing out the press would ``invite
distrust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both senators have been staunch defenders of the president.
Harkin dismissed the case against Clinton on Fox-News TV as a
``sham'' and ``a pile of dung.'' Wellstone has offered similar,
although less colorful, sentiments. But the two Democrats insisted
that partisanship played no part in the secrecy issue.
</P>
<P>
   They said they have found sympathy from colleagues in both
parties for opening the deliberations, although none has have
publicly joined them.
</P>
<P>
   It may require strong public pressure for the Harkin-Wellstone
proposal to prevail. A two-thirds majority is needed to overturn
the impeachment procedure, which was first drawn up for the
Senate's impeachment of President Andrew Johnson in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   The Harkin-Wellstone proposal ``obviously has an uphill
battle,'' said Ed Amorosi, spokesman for Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., a
member of the Senate leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gregg is open'' to the idea, his aide said. But like most
members, the senator is awaiting the advice of senior members such
as the Senate's unofficial historian, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., or
Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala. Neither of those senators had an immediate
response to the measure to open all proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One factor that could could work against the measure is the
experience last Friday, when deeply divided senators met in closed
session and emerged with a unanimous accord on ground rules for the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senators have lavishly extolled that private session, and some
have suggested that it should be a model.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is noteworthy that we achieved our bipartisan agreement in
a closed session,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., told CNN. ``We are
...much better able to relate to each other and deal with each
other and reach compromises when we are not under the glare of the
cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said that if the cameras are allowed, the Senate would
be more likely to become ``a sort of feuding bunch of people with
partisan agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., agreed in part, saying that he
would object to the Harkin-Wellstone resolution if it required that
all procedures be open. ``I think our motivation ought to be to
have whatever can be public be public,'' Dodd said, adding that he
wanted to keep the option of closing proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that view, Harkin said that some closed-door
meetings of the Senate ``do have a certain benefit,'' but he said
that official proceedings of the full Senate must be conducted in
public.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
