<P>
   I was relieved. In my mental cinema, I had imagined
single-celled squatters, this time ensconced in the nerve clusters
that lace around the digestive tract. Parasite nests and
inflammation located here produce ``mega syndrome.'' in 6 to 10
percent of those infected, the gut enlarges because the nerves that
control the rhythmic squeezing of peristalsis die. Such nerve
damage can afflict other hollow organs too. Miguel had been spared
the indignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senora, if you are right, could I give this infection to my
family?''
</P>
<P>
   No, I said. Except for occasional cases of maternal-fetal
transmission, intrafamilial spread of T. cruzi does not occur,
except by the feces of reduviids.
</P>
<P>
   But did he, in fact, have Chagas' disease? Our best bet: the
antibody test for T. cruzi performed at the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One week after drawing his blood, I heard from a technician in
Atlanta. Miguel's serum was unequivocally positive.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, the real question facing Miguel was heart
transplantation. If Miguel had a transplant, he would need to take
drugs to rein in his immune response and prevent rejection of his
new heart.
</P>
<P>
   I could tell him that patients with endstage Chagas' disease had
gotten new hearts. But early results of transplantation had been
dismal. Most patients died within a year from new colonies of T.
cruzi sprouting not only in their new heart but in their skin,
brain and other organs. The drugs used to prevent organ rejection
created an open playing field for parasite growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Miguel made his own decision. He declined to be
placed on the transplant list, and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, I heard he had died. He was one of more than
40,000 who lost their lives that year to a hidden intruder in the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Claire Panosian is a professor of medicine in the division of
infectious diseases and director of travel and tropical medicine at
UCLA Medical Center.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
