<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EROTICA-THEATER-REVIE     01-11 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EROTICA-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EROTICA PROJECT': A `PREOCCUPATION' IS PUTTING IT LIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One midnight in Paris some years ago, three friends
and I took a bad recommendation and ended up in the sort of club
where the minimum order is a $100 bottle of champagne. We sighed,
ordered and sat back for a little late-night conversation, or so we
thought. Suddenly a movie screen appeared and a series of truly
vulgar sexual cartoons began to play.
</P>
<P>
   That terrible feeling of being trapped at a pornography display
returned last Friday night at Joe's Pub, the Public Theater's new
cabaret and lounge. Some will say that the show's title, ``The
Erotica Project: Cunning Stunts,'' should have been a hint.
</P>
<P>
   The mercifully brief, intermissionless production consists of
eight women _ mostly young, mostly gorgeous, mostly in the skimpy
little black dresses of the fashion moment _ standing at
microphones and talking dirty in breathy phone-sex voices.
Propriety prevents my quoting much of the dialogue, but one of the
less risque lines is ``because your warm tongue is the fountain of
the universe'' and the word ``wet'' is used a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   There are, in the middle of this, two excellent sequences. One
is ``Threesome,'' performed with quiet power by Rebecca Nelson, the
story of a young woman's menage a trois with her boyfriend and his
best friend, the excitement and the irrevocable regrets.
(Afterward, the narrator observes, she and her boyfriend ``smell
like Clay's skin.'') The other is ``Mary Magdalene,'' performed
with style and conviction by Caroline Burwell, in which the
audience meets the biblical prostitute as an impressionable
teen-age girl who falls for a sexy radical while he's preaching the
Sermon on the Mount. (``I hear He's dangerous and know that I am
already in love with Him.'') Still, the sequence is sure to offend
many since it includes vivid descriptions of oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the production, written by Lillian Ann
Slugocki and Erin Cressida Wilson and directed by John Gould Rubin,
is just titillation and anger. Perhaps the low point is
``Soapbox,'' performed by Christen Clifford, which declares that
feminism is a plot to keep her from having a happy, healthy, active
sex life. When Ms. Clifford announces, ``My vagina is not your
soapbox,'' only one thing comes to mind: just how fabulous Eve
Ensler's Off Broadway show ``The Vagina Monologues'' was.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE EROTICA PROJECT'S CUNNING STUNTS
</P>
<P>
   Written by Lillian Ann Slugocki and Erin Cressida Wilson;
directed by John Gould Rubin; set consultant, Narelle Sissons;
costume consultant, Kaye Voyce; lighting consultant, Philip D.
Widmer. Presented by Joe's Pub/the Joseph Papp Public Theater/New
York Shakespeare Festival, George C. Wolfe, producer. At the Joseph
Papp Public Theater, 425 Lafayette St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Caroline Burwell, Christen Clifford, Kit Flanagan, Rebecca
Nelson, Dee Pelletier, Corliss Preston, Christine Sang and Melinda
Wade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
