<HEADER>
A8424 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARTH'S-FIRST-CITY-SC     01-11 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH'S-FIRST-CITY-SCIENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUS VALLEY: THE WORLD'S FIRST CITY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE: a colorful map
of the Indus Valley; an excavation site, most likely the world's
first public bath, in Mohenjo-Daro; an eclectic mix of jewelry from
Allahdino; and the skeleton of a Harappan man. They can be sent by
mail (or overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery
number) to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By SHANTI MENON  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (D istributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The railway linking Lahore to Multan in Pakistan is 4,600 years
old. In truth, the rails were laid down in the middle of the 19th
century, but to build the railway bed, British engineers smashed
bricks from crumbling buildings and rubble heaps in a town called
Harappa, halfway between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1856, Alexander Cunningham, director of the newly formed
Archaeological Survey of India, thought the brick ruins were all
related to nearby seventh-century Buddhist temples. Local legend
told a different story: The brick mounds were the remnants of an
ancient city, destroyed when its king committed incest with his
niece.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cunningham nor the locals were entirely correct. In
small, desultory excavations a few years later, Cunningham found no
temples or traces of kings, incestuous or otherwise. Instead he
reported the recovery of some pottery, carved shells and a badly
damaged seal depicting a one-horned animal, bearing an inscription
in an unfamiliar writing. That seal was a mark of one of the
world's great ancient civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Vedas, the oldest texts of the subcontinent, dating from
some 3,500 years ago, made no mention of it, nor did the Bible. No
pyramids or burial mounds marked the area as the site of an ancient
power.
</P>
<P>
   Yet 4,600 years ago, great cities arose along the floodplains of
the ancient Indus and Saraswati rivers in what is now Pakistan and
northwest India.
</P>
<P>
   The people of the Indus Valley were a highly organized and
stupendously successful civilization. They built some of the
world's first planned cities, created one of the world's first
written languages, and thrived in an area twice the size of Egypt
and Mesopotamia for 700 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're finding at Harappa for the first time is how the
first cities started,'' says Mark Kenoyer, an archaeologist at the
University of Wisconsin in Madison. Kenoyer, who was born in India
to missionary parents, has been excavating at Harappa for the past
12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kenoyer's archaeological evidence suggests that the city got its
start as a farming village around 3300 B.C. Situated near the Ravi
River, Harappa lay on a fertile floodplain. But the key to
urbanization was its location at the crossroads of several major
trading routes. Traders from the highlands of Baluchistan and
northern Afghanistan to the west brought in copper, tin and lapis
lazuli; clam and conch shells were brought in from the southern
seacoast, timber from the Himalayas, semiprecious stones from
Gujarat, silver and gold from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of goods allowed Harappans to become traders and
artisans as well as farmers. And specialists from across the land
arrived to set up shop in the new metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   By 2200 B.C., Harappa covered about 370 acres and may have held
80,000 people, making it roughly as populous as the ancient city of
Ur in Mesopotamia.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the haphazard arrangement of Mesopotamian cities, Indus
Valley settlements all followed the same basic plan. Streets and
houses were laid out on a north-south, east-west grid, and houses
and walls were built of standard-size bricks.
</P>
<P>
   They were also devoted to sanitation. Nearly every Harappan home
had a bathing platform and a latrine, says Kenoyer, and some Indus
Valley cities reached heights of 40 feet. Each neighborhood had its
own well, and elaborate covered drainage systems carried dirty
water outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   The towering brick cities, surrounded by sturdy walls with
imposing gateways, reminded early researchers of the medieval forts
in Delhi and Lahore. But Kenoyer thinks the walls were created to
control the flow of goods in and out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get into the city, you had to pay a tax,'' Kenoyer
explains. ``If you produced things, you had to pay a tax to take
goods out of the city. This is how a city gets revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the tax collectors and those they served remains
a mystery. Indus Valley rulers did not immortalize themselves with
mummies or monuments. They did, however, leave behind elaborately
carved stone seals, used to impress tokens or clay tabs on goods
bound for market. The seals bore images of animals, the most common
being the unicorn, a symbol that originated in the Indus Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Frustratingly, though, those seals carry inscriptions that no
one has been able to decipher. Early Mesopotamian cuneiform was
thought to be the world's first written language, says Kenoyer, but
the Indus Valley script emerged independently around the same time
_ at least by around 3300 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the language remains a mystery, so too will the
identities of the Indus Valley elites. Kenoyer thinks each of the
large cities may have functioned as an independent city-state,
controlled by a small group of merchants, landowners and religious
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They controlled taxation, access to the city and communication
with the gods,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While the balance of power may have shifted between these
groups, they seem to have ruled without a standing army.
Sculptures, paintings and texts from Egypt and Mesopotamia clearly
illustrate battles between cities. But in the Indus Valley, not a
single depiction of a military act, of taking prisoners, of a human
killing another human has been found.
</P>
<P>
   Excavators have turned up some hints of the wealth an individual
could accumulate. Two decades ago, in the rural settlement of
Allahdino, near modern Karachi in Pakistan, archaeologists stumbled
upon a buried pot filled with jewelry, the secret hoard of a rich
landowner. Among the goods was a belt or necklace made of 36
elongated carnelian beads interspersed with bronze beads. It was
most likely made by a group of artisans over a period of two or
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Such intensive devotion to craftsmanship and trade, Kenoyer
argues, is what allowed Indus Valley culture to spread over a
region twice the size of Mesopotamia without a trace of military
domination.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, between 1900 and 1700 B.C., the extensive trading
networks and productive farms supporting this cultural integration
collapsed, Kenoyer says, and distinct local cultures emerged.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that the Indus River shifted, flooding many
settlements and disrupting agriculture. It is likely that when
these smaller settlements were abandoned, trade routes were
affected.
</P>
<P>
   But the legacy of the ancient Indus cities and their
craftspeople remains. In the crowded marketplaces of Delhi and
Lahore, as gold and jewels are weighed in bronze balances, it's
hard to imagine that a 4,000-year-old Harappan bazaar could have
been terribly different.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Shanti Menon is a researcher/reporter for Discover
magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
 &UR; (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
