<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between polar air and a moderating air mass over
the South will become established from Kansas to western New
England. A series of weak disturbances in the jet stream, which
will be flowing parallel to this newly formed front, should induce
patches of wintry precipitation as pockets of mild air are drawn
north and colder air pushes south.
</P>
<P>
   Light to moderate snow will fall from western New York to Maine
with more than six inches possible on the higher terrain of western
New England. Scattered snow showers will become mixed with rain and
sleet along the Northeast coast. A little light snow or drizzle
will dampen the central Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Much warmer air will occupy the Southeast as high pressure moves
offshore. The return flow of milder, moist air from the Gulf of
Mexico into the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys will
produce a few patches of light rain. The southern Plains will stay
quite mild, but chilly air will arrive from the north Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frigid conditions will cover the northern Plains and upper
Middle West as Arctic air circulates southward. Low pressure
developing over Kansas will trigger light snow farther north.
Patches of light snow are expected in the northern Rockies along a
stalled front.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will be dull with showers along the coast. Fog in
the Central Valley will persist. The interior West and deserts of
the Southwest will stay sunny and rather mild. Offshore winds will
keep readings above seasonal levels in coastal areas of southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Downslope Windstorms
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusts were clocked at 96 mph at Estes Park near Denver,
Colo., early Monday morning. Fierce winds also gusted to 80 mph at
Boulder, Colo., a town infamous for its ``downslope windstorms.''
Such windstorms develop over the eastern foothills of the Rockies
in winter when speedy westerly winds near the summits careen down
the lee side of the mountains, sometimes attaining speeds over 100
mph. The fiercest winds typically occur as low pressure passes
north of the affected region, a path that favors both strong winds
aloft and sinking air over the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
