<HEADLINE>
`SNITCH': A DRAGNET THAT GIVES SHARKS A LEASE ON LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes are at end of review.) 
(Time, channel are for the New York metropolitan area. Check local
listings.) (ms)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Snitch,'' the outdated slang insult for an informer, is back
in fashion, and along with it a new career for drug dealers and
users, which Tuesday night's ``Frontline'' charges is corrupting
the nation's criminal justice operations. Relying mainly on horror
stories of low-level drug suspects who are serving long prison
terms on evidence supplied by more culpable pals and collaborators,
the producer, Ofra Bikel, makes a case that the famous war on drugs
is being perverted by incentives that reward the guiltiest and
punish the less guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute report returns to the late 1980s, when the crack
cocaine epidemic drove Congress to enact hasty tough minimum
sentences for drug trafficking. Offenses that might once have
brought probation now carried 20 years to life in prison. Moreover,
Congress tagged on a conspiracy amendment that called for heavy
sentences for even minor participants in a drug sale and made their
convictions much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, these laws, which one of their devisers now
blames on an ``incredible conjunction between politics and
hysteria,'' created an incentive for convicted dealers to make
deals with prosecutors, trading accusations against former friends,
neighbors and family members in exchange for a reduction in their
own long sentences. The prosecutors proved eager to credit the
self-serving accounts of felons, whose reputation for reliability
is not high. ``Do I feel that snitches lie?'' asks a defense
lawyer. ``Only when their mouth is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   One repentant snitch, who says he won a reduced sentence by
lying about seeing a friend selling drugs, asks: ``What are you
going to do? You going to take that life sentence?''
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday night you can meet a man with a clean record who was
peripherally involved in a drug sale and was turned in by four
buddies, all of whom faced life sentences. The charges against him
consisted exclusively of their testimony. These ``cooperating
individuals,'' as the prosecution politely calls them, won reduced
terms, and he wound up with life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The cases of apparent injustice are affecting and not
implausible, but like any account that draws largely on defendants
and their lawyers, you may be left less than certain that you are
getting a straight story. At the least ``Snitch'' adds another
count to critics' indictment of a costly policy that has jammed
prisons with nonviolent and, as life on the street goes, relatively
inoffensive offenders.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   FRONTLINE
</P>
<P>
   Snitch
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night (Channel 13, New York, at 9)
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced and directed by Ofra Bikel; Susan Fanshel,
editor; Katie Galloway, associate producer; Will Lyman, narrator.
For `Frontline': David Fanning, senior executive producer; Michael
Sullivan, executive producer. A Frontline co-production with Ofra
Bikel Productions Corp.
</P>
