<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     01-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH PROMOTION CAN PROVE DIFFICULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. I was just promoted, and there is no doubt I am
in way over my head. There is so much to do, and just about
everywhere I turn, I find responsibilities that I do not know how
to handle. I was happy and successful in my prior position, and I
am thinking of asking for it back. Do you have any suggestions?
T.M.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not uncommon for newly promoted employees to feel
overwhelmed, overworked and over their heads. However, the fact is
that these are initial feelings, and before you take any action,
you need to give yourself some time.
</P>
<P>
   You should take immediate steps to identify the key job
priorities and the extent to which you have the expertise to handle
them. If there are some glaring gaps, you should put together a
personal plan to develop the necessary skills.
</P>
<P>
   In putting together this plan, you can include a combination of
readings, classes, and discussions with your manager and
significant others at work. Research continues to find that one of
the key sources of employee growth and development is through
interaction with associates on the job.
</P>
<P>
   If you return to your former position now, without exhausting
every possible strategy in order to succeed in your new position,
you will be left with lingering doubts for the rest of your career.
To be fair to yourself, you should do all that you can to work this
job, rather than let the job work you.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I interviewed for a job over a month ago and was told that it
came down to two people, but the company felt the other person was
better qualified and hired him. A couple of days ago I got a phone
call from one of the owners and he said that things did not work
out with the other person, and he offered the job to me. I'm not
sure I want to work for a company where I was the second choice.
What do you think? G.F.
</P>
<P>
   A. Just because you were the company's second choice does not
mean that the company views you as being second rate. In reality,
the company narrowed its job search down to two first-choice
candidates, one of whom seemed stronger.
</P>
<P>
   You can stand on ceremony and conclude that if the company did
not want you, then you do not want it. Or, you can step back and
recognize that the opportunity that originally attracted you to the
company more than likely still exists. You should go back and meet
with the owner and with some of the people with whom you would be
working. Spending more time at the company can definitely help you
make the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   You are not going to be permanently labeled as the second-choice
employee, unless you affix this label to yourself. If the owner
thought you were anything less than outstanding, he would not be
offering you the job now. The company may well have made a hiring
mistake a month ago, but if you walk away from this job offer, you
may be making one now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have a fairly new employee in our office who frequently
talks about her old company. She claims that they had better
policies and procedures, and she keeps trying to change the way
work is done here. Is there a way to get her to focus more on what
we are doing and less on what she did? A.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. New employees who focus on the workings of their old jobs can
be a source of new ideas or a source of new aggravation. The best
way to deal with them is through open two-way communication.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all of the employees, not just the vocal new ones,
should have frequent opportunities to express their ideas regarding
better ways in which their department or even the company can
operate. This can be through a combination of meetings, informal
discussions, designated committees and suggestion systems.
</P>
<P>
   The employees' recommendations that appear to have merit can be
implemented or at least tested, while those that are not feasible
can be referred back to the employees for further analysis and
revision. It is important for the employees to receive feedback on
their suggestions, regardless of merit.
</P>
<P>
   This approach may help your new employee channel her ideas more
effectively and perhaps bring more balance into her approach to
this job. However, if she is so focused on her prior job that she
is interfering with the productivity of her associates, then it is
time to give her some feedback regarding the importance of
concentrating more on where she is going and less on where she has
been.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
