<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Jan. 12. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WOLVES (Phoenix) - Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said wolves are
here to stay in Arizona, and he meant it. Despite a quartet of
unsolved wolf killings, disappearances and recaptures, a new round
of wolf releases will soon bring more wolves than ever to the wilds
of eastern Arizona as biologists begin the second year of a highly
controversial wolf reintroduction experiment. Some wolves may even
arrive by helicopter as researchers attempt to keep the
captive-bread wolves as wild as possible by minimizing their
contact with people. Meanwhile, ranchers continue their opposition
in the federal courts, while environmentalists continue to post a
$50,000 reward for the arrest of those responsible for last year's
wolf killings. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ENGLISH-ARIZONA (Phoenix) - The U.S. Supreme Court finally has
driven stake into the heart of Arizona's ``English only'' law,
ending a tortuous 10-year appeal by supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of the road,'' said Bob Park of Arizonans for
Official English. ``There isn't any place else for us to to with
this matter.'' By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KEATING (Undated) - U.S. District Court Judge in Los Angeles has
set a hearing for Monday at which prosecutors are expected to
announce their intention to retry former savings and loan chief
Charles H Keating Jr on charges that he looted Lincoln Savings. By
JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the `'A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEGAY-NAVAJO (Undated) - In 1975, Kelsey Begay was drowning in
``dark waters,'' what Navajos refer to as alcoholism. Fresh from
the jungles of the Vietnam War, he lived on the streets of Los
Angelos, far away from his homeland on the Navajo Reservation. But
Kaibeto, a tiny Navajo community an hour from Page, beckoned. Begay
returned home and today is sworn in as president of America's
largest Indian tribe. By BETTY REID and BILL DONOVAN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMPUTER-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Let's begin this week with a few notes,
a few newsy tidbits and a few interesting Web sites: Ever wonder
why so many companies lend their names to things like college
football bowl games? A recent press release from Insight in Tempe,
Ariz.,
</P>
<P>
   explained one reason: Web page hits. The press release said hits
(visits by computer users) to the computer marketing company's Web
site (www.insight.com) soared 917 percent after the televised
Insight.com Bowl in late December. By DAVID HOYE. Story moved in
the ``F'' category. &QL; 
