<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: JAZZ, MARVIN HAMLISCH, JAMES BOND, VAN GOGH, NORMAN
JEWISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHOSEN FEW
</P>
<P>
   Art Farmer, Dave Brubeck and Joe Henderson have been named 1999
American Jazz Masters by the National Endowment for the Arts.
Farmer, the trumpeter and fluegelhorn player; Brubeck, the pianist
and composer, and Henderson, the tenor saxophonist, each receive a
fellowship including a $20,000 honorarium. Bill Ivey, chairman of
the National Endowment for the Arts, said the three musicians
``have enriched this country with their astounding artistic
achievements.'' They join such previous honorees as Dizzy
Gillespie, Betty Carter, Miles Davis and Sarah Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE BATON ...
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Hamlisch is on the move. Under a two-year contract
starting with the 2000-2001 season, Hamlisch, the composer,
conductor and pianist, will assume the new post of principal pops
conductor of the National Symphony Orchestra in Washington. In
joining the National Symphony, Hamlisch will leave the Baltimore
Symphony Orchestra when his four-year tenure as principal pops
conductor ends in June 2000. But he will retain that title with the
Pittsburgh Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   MACHO MEN
</P>
<P>
   It's James Bond versus the hero of ``The Full Monty'' in the
next 007 adventure. Yes, Pierce Brosnan, as Bond, Ian Fleming's
British agent, will face off against Robert Carlyle, who led the
male strippers in the hit 1997 comedy. In the new film, ``The World
Is Not Enough,'' which went before the cameras Monday, Carlyle
plays a villain who has a bullet lodged in his brain, making him
impervious to pain. Oil is the bone of contention. The film is to
be released in November.
</P>
<P>
   HANG TIME
</P>
<P>
   After 10 months of renovation, the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam,
home to an unrivaled collection of his paintings, will reopen on
June 24. The first exhibition is to focus on Vincent van Gogh's
younger brother, Theo, a 19th-century art dealer and Vincent's
principal sponsor. It will also feature more than 200 works by
their contemporaries. With the museum closed, many of its
best-known works were exhibited at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington during the fall and will be seen from Sunday through May
16 at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Others are on display
until May 2 at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   PICKED TO WIN
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sure-fire winner at this year's Academy Award
ceremonies: the Canadian producer and director Norman Jewison. When
the honors are distributed on March 21 in Los Angeles, Jewison, 72,
will receive the Irving Thalberg Memorial Prize for ``creative
producers whose work constantly reflects a high level of quality in
cinema production.'' Jewison's films include ``In the Heat of the
Night'' (1967), an Oscar winner as best picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
