<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ENGLISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REJECT APPEAL ON ARIZONA'S ENGLISH-ONLY LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday refused to review a
former provision of the Arizona constitution that made English the
state's official language but was struck down as restricting free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The justices without comment let stand an Arizona Supreme Court
decision that the English-only rule illegally required state
business to be conducted in English. The state court said the
provision violated the First Amendment's guarantee of free speech
by depriving non-English-speaking residents access to information
about the government and preventing them from having ``meaningful
communication'' with state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans for Official English, an ad hoc group that initiated
the controversial law, argued in vain to the U.S. Supreme Court
that the First Amendment does not apply to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Constitution prohibits the government from
restricting the free speech of citizens. However, the Arizona
provision limits only the government's speech, requiring that the
state conduct its business in English, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods, pressing the state's
opposition to the English-only rule, told the justices that the
advocacy group has not been harmed by the provision's removal and,
therefore, has no legal standing to fight for its reinstatement.
Several Arizona elected officials and state employees, in a
separate brief, said the state supreme court was correct in finding
a First Amendment violation and urged the justices to reject
Arizonans for Official English's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' action Monday marked the second time the case has
been before the high court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled in favor of the provision's
opponents, saying the former state worker who opposed the
English-only law had left government service and had no standing to
continue her challenge.
</P>
<P>
   However, after the Supreme Court's decision, the Arizona elected
officials and state employees renewed the First Amendment fight,
losing at the trial level but winning in their appeal to the
Arizona Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans for Official English and its spokesman, Robert D.
Park, launched a ballot initiative that resulted in the 1988
adoption of the English-only rule. The provision, which was Article
28 of the state constitution, required Arizona to ``take all
reasonable steps to preserve, protect and enhance the role of the
English language as the official language of the state of
Arizona,''
</P>
<P>
   Under the provision, no government document was valid unless it
was written in English. Exceptions to the English-only rule allowed
the use of other languages in state documents referring to the
teaching of foreign tongues in public schools. State agencies were
also allowed to use other languages to protect public health or
safety and to ensure that the rights of criminal defendants and
crime victims were protected. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
