<SLUG> BC-COUSINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cousins acquires N.C. firm
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cousins Properties Inc. has acquired the Atkins Group,
a Charlotte, N.C., real estate firm. The acquired firm's principals
will pursue development opportunities in the Carolinas for Cousins
and oversee marketing and leasing there.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the transaction weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based real estate investment trust named W. Henry
Atkins senior vice president in its office division. The other
principal of the firm, C. David Atkins, was named vice president in
the office division.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the latest of several affiliations Cousins
Properties _ whose portfolio is dominated by metro Atlanta holdings
_ has established with local firms in Southeastern markets and
California since it embarked on a strategy of geographic
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins, which owns and develops large office complexes and
retail centers, already has two projects underway in Charlotte. The
largest is Gateway Village, a multi-use urban project that includes
the one-million-square-foot Bank of America Technology Center, a
joint venture with the bank. The other is a 500,000-square-foot
downtown office tower acquired in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sallye Salter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
