u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSICO-COKE-COX     01-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSICO-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Though 1998 brought economic challenges, Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Co. is chugging right along, Chief Executive M. Douglas
Ivester said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our '98 volume growth is coming in a bit below our long-term
target of 7 to 8 percent worldwide, but not much below. Earnings
will likely be down from 1997,'' Ivester told a packed house at the
Rotary Club of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The final numbers will come out when Coca-Cola releases
fourth-quarter earnings, expected before month's end. But the
showing should be no surprise, given the company's warnings in the
second half of last year that results would be dragged down by
comparisons to one-time gains recorded in 1997. The company also
cited global economic uncertainty and weak currencies in several
major markets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. were estimating that
Coca-Cola would hit a fourth-quarter earnings target of 30 cents
per share before Ivester's December announcement that
lower-than-expected volume would drop earnings to 24 or 25 cents
per share.
</P>
<P>
   The expected earnings reduction has somewhat clipped Coca-Cola's
wings on Wall Street, bringing the company's stock down 26 percent
since July. It closed Monday at $66.12 1/2, down $1.87 1/2.
Overall, though, 14 of 24 analysts who follow the company currently
have buy or hold ratings on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who seldom speaks before a crowd as he did Monday, told
of the ``tremendous opportunity'' he sees for the world's No. 1
soft drink company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to chuckle sometimes when I read that some analyst is
fretting about our 'global exposure.' I hate to tell them, but
that's the idea,'' he said. ``We are cognizant of the events of
1998 _ but they don't alter our long-term view.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Coca-Cola sold nearly 16 billion cases of its soft
drinks in 197 countries last year, including 11 billion cases
outside North America. That's about a billion more cases than the
company sold in 1997 _ and there's no end in sight, Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worldwide, people will drink 48 billion servings of
refreshment today, but only a little more than 1 billion of those
servings are ours. In 10 years, with population growth, the world
will drink 55 billion servings a day,'' he said. ``Now we don't
have to get all of that. But if we get just 2 billion of that we
will double our company's size.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he said, the company plans to continue building its
brands and acquiring new ones. Last month, Coca-Cola said it would
spend $1.85 billion to acquire Cadbury Schweppes' soft drink
operations in all of the 120 countries where the London-based
company does business except the United States, France and South
Africa. It's still in negotiations to acquire Orangina, owned by
French-based Pernod Ricard SA.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can look for more significant developments from us
later this year,'' Ivester said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during a question-and-answer session, Ivester confirmed
reports that the company is ``cautiously'' investigating entering
the domestic bottled water business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottled water is a tricky subject. There's an awful lot of
water sold, but there's not an awful lot of money made selling
water,'' he said. ``We never said we're in this business for
growth. We're in this business for profitable growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is well prepared for the introduction of the Euro,
which does not appear to pose any ``detrimental'' concerns, as well
as Year 2000 computer conversions, which should be completed by
June 30, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester didn't have much to say regarding rival Pepsico's plans
to spin off its company-owned bottling operations in an initial
public offering this spring that's expected to raise $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Pepsico's plans, Coca-Cola will keep its gaze set
on the tried and true market-by-market approach to selling soft
drinks, Ivester said. Pepsico's stock closed Monday at $40.87 1/2,
down 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey H. Gramig writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
