<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN12-     01-11 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Falcons want the NFL's king of kings to know poetic justice
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In its face, the script for this NFC Championship
might have been written 182 years ago by the smash-mouth poet Percy
Bysshe Shelley: ``My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:/Look on my
Works, ye Mighty, and despair!''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, mighty enough themselves, are given little chance
against Minnesota, a team already primping for coronation. Vegas
set the opening line at 10 points. The Vikings beat Arizona by
three touchdowns and warned they hadn't played all that well. The
headline writer at the Atlanta Journal-Constitution newspaper
captured the prevailing thought: ``Yikes, it'll be the Vikes.''
</P>
<P>
   To look on Minnesota's works is indeed to feel unease. The
Vikings have lost only once, have scored more points over the
course of a regular season than any team ever. But this is to say
that any rush toward despair should be halted forthwith. Teams like
the Vikings have been beaten before. By, not coincidentally, teams
like the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   We remember the Buffalo Bills as forlorn Super Bowl foils, but
we forget how omnipotent they seemed when first they reached the
land of Roman numerals. Plying the cutting-edge no-huddle offense,
the 1990 Bills scored 44 points in the first playoff game and beat
the Raiders 51-3 for the AFC title. Alongside this sleek
assemblage, the New York Giants seemed plodding. The plodders won
by a point.
</P>
<P>
   Ottis Anderson trundled for 102 yards. The journeyman Jeff
Hostetler kept drives moving interminably. The Giants held the ball
for 40 minutes and 33 seconds. Sometimes the best defense is an
offense that won't yield the ball. What team leads the NFL in time
of possession? Why, the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It's instructive that the team that held the record for points
before Minnesota didn't win a championship. The 1983 Washington
Redskins _ Joe Theismann and John Riggins, Hogs and Smurfs _ were
favored in Super Bowl XVIII but lost 38-9. The best-ever offense
smacked into an even better defense.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders cornerbacks Lester Hayes and Mike Haynes muzzled the
Smurfs. Nose tackle Reggie Kinlaw overpowered center Jeff Bostic,
squelching Riggins. Derrick Jensen blocked a Redskins punt for the
game's first touchdown. (Quoth Dan Reeves: ``The quickest way to
lose a game is to have a punt blocked.'') Jack Squirek intercepted
a screen pass to break it open before halftime. Marcus Allen rushed
for 191 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson led the NFC in rushing. The Falcons' defense led
the conference in rushing defense. How far can you go by doing
those two things? Only all the way. The 1974 Pittsburgh Steelers
were decided underdogs in the AFC title game, the thinking being
that the Raiders had essentially won the Super Bowl by eliminating
Miami on Clarence Davis' catch the week before. But Franco Harris
and Rocky Bleier rushed for 209 yards and the great Steelers front
four limited Oakland's rushers to 29. Pittsburgh won 24-13 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   And Ozymandias, self-described ``king of kings''? Well, he lost,
too. In Shelley's poem, the haughty inscription quoted above was
found on a shattered statue in the desert _ ``that colossal wreck .
. . '' Sounds like a game plan to me.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
