<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Running back Anderson bestows gifts upon blockers
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons' season-long feel-good party
continued Monday, when running back Jamal Anderson rewarded his
offensive linemen and three other blockers with 36-inch flat-screen
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   The blockers helped Anderson rush for a franchise-record 1,846
yards on an NFL record 410 carries in the regular season and
another 113 yards and two touchdowns on 29 carries in Saturday's
20-18 playoff victory against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, giant TV boxes were scattered in the locker
room for left tackle Bob Whitfield, left guard Calvin Collins,
center Robbie Tobeck, right guard Gene Williams, right tackle
Ephraim Salaam, tight end O.J. Santiago, fullback Bob Christian,
and tight end/fullback Brian Kozlowski.
</P>
<P>
   The units retail at one Atlanta video store for $1,044 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're state of the art,'' Santiago said. `` 'Jam' is that
kind of guy. There are a lot of great running backs, but to have
guys that lay it on the line is important, too, and he knows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson surpassed the 1,000-yard mark in the 10th game
with a 31-carry, 100-yard, two-touchdown effort in a 31-19 victory
against San Francisco on Nov. 15, Whitfield put in the order for
TVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to get us 20-inch TVs,'' Whitfield said.
``When he'd have a big game, we'd be going, 'The gift is getting
bigger.' When I saw that big box, I said, 'He's the greatest
running back ever.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a fifth-year pro who finished as the NFL's
second-leading rusher behind Denver's Terrell Davis, who had 2,008
yards, also scored a franchise-record 14 rushing touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He has one more year left on his contract, calling for a salary
of $1.6 million. He has earned $850,000 in bonuses for rushing
yardage, which will be added to next season's salary. Anderson also
has earned bonuses of $30,000 for being named first-team All-Pro,
and $25,000 for being voted to start in the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
