A8481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NOTES12-C     01-11 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings warn Falcons: Don't expect to hear
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER PARK, Minn. _ From one dome team to another, the Vikings
say this to the Falcons: Too bad you have to come to our house.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that Atlanta has to face the explosive Minnesota
attack, but the Metrodome crowd rates among the loudest in the NFL,
and Viking players are feeling no pity that their dome-dwelling
adversary in Sunday's NFC Championship game have to endure what
promises to be the loudest crowd of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've earned that advantage,'' running back Leroy Hoard said.
``Everybody had the same opportunity we had to gain it. We won 15
games _ that's got to count for something. I was standing next to
Robert (Griffith), yelling at him and he couldn't hear me. That's
how loud it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the noise was fan-generated, but the Metrodome also
employs a sound system that blares everything from sound effects to
rock music. To that, Hoard said, ``So, am I supposed to feel sorry
for (the Falcons)? I don't think so. It's an advantage we earned.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle John Randle said, ``We couldn't hear (Sunday
against Arizona), so how could the other team?''
</P>
<P>
   Fancy formations
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings used 15 different formations in their first 16 plays
on Sunday against Arizona, and the young defense seemed confused by
the constant movement, shifting and, at times, odd lineups. Hoard
said it was much to-do about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was like smoke screens,'' he said. ``A lot of
movement and stuff to run the same play we always run. So it comes
down to: Are you trying to stop a formation or a play? Plus, we
still have to execute, no matter if they're confused or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The most confusing formation appeared to be when the Vikings
lined up with running back David Palmer as the shotgun quarterback,
with regular quarterback Randall Cunningham at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick added: ``We did
nothing we haven't done all year, except that we only used Palmer
(at QB) on third down. We've got great talent, and the thing is to
involve everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoard said he can throw the ball, but he hasn't been given the
opportunity _ for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can throw the ball far, but I have no touch,'' he said. ``I
can throw it 70 yards. So if I'm called on to throw it, it's going
70 yards, whether someone's out there or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are hoping Randall McDaniel's knee and Jake Reed's
and Orlando Thomas' hamstrings will be healed by Sunday. McDaniel
was listed Monday as probable, with Reed and Thomas questionable.
``That's where depth comes in,'' Green said. ``We hope they can go,
but if not, we'll put somebody else in there and go. Everybody's
injured this time of year. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
