A8482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS12-COX     01-11 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson marks the spot for Vikings defense
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER PARK, Minn. _ Right between the 3 and the 2 on Jamal
Anderson's jersey, the Minnesota Vikings have placed an imaginary
target ``X.'' Anderson, a Pro Bowl running back, is definitely a
marked man, the perceived single most important facet of the
Falcons' assault. Minnesota's thinking: Cut off the head, and the
legs will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Much of their defensive preparation this week will evolve around
limiting Anderson. The Falcons lead the NFL in time of possession,
a key element against the record-setting Vikings' offense. Simply,
they can't score if they're not on the field.
</P>
<P>
   That's where stopping Anderson comes in for Minnesota's defense.
It's a unit that has size, but that physical condition is not what
coach Dennis Green believes will be enough to handle Anderson, who
had 1,570 yards in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a running team, and the No. 1 element against them has
to be quickness,'' Green said. ``Then you have to have toughness.
Then explosiveness and then attitude. I didn't mention size. We
like big guys. But that's not the key. We know they're going to
come at us, but we have to negate (Anderson) with quickness,
toughness, explosiveness and attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings know that Anderson seldom is tackled by the first
defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you end up being a single tackler (against Anderson), you'd
better be good, because we've seen him run through guys,'' said
nose tackle Jerry Ball, who anchors the Minnesota interior line.
``He's got the power of Natrone Means, but the quickness of Barry
Sanders. He has great lateral movement. Someone like Garrison
Hearst only runs straight ahead. But people like Emmitt Smith,
Barry Sanders, Jamal Anderson, they hit holes that aren't holes _
they're creases. They make creases holes and get through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Anderson's quick feet and vision allow him to cut back
for yardage, Ball said, so it's vital for the Vikings to have
backside pursuit. ``Yeah, he shifts gears and goes the other
direction. He can sense a different hole is there,'' Ball said.
``So we have to watch the backside, because he's like Barry
Sanders, cutting against the grain.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Green is not expecting the Vikings to run over
Atlanta, as they have so many others this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point of the season, stopping the run and controlling
the ball is something you have to do,'' Green said. ``They have a
fine running game. But they were 14-2. They have a complete team. I
know it's not going to be like the Jacksonville game or Baltimore
or even Arizona, where we scored a lot of points and ran away. It's
going to be a close, hard-fought game that'll go 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
