<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PRO-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside pro tennis: Korda receives cold reception from players
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Petr Korda, whose positive test for steroids was made known last
month, has arrived in Melbourne a week before the Australian Open
to find what amounts to a lynch mob of players wanting him to go
home.
</P>
<P>
   Jonas Bjorkman suggested that the International Tennis
Federation ban Korda from defending his title. Jason Stoltenberg
said he wants Korda to withdraw on his own. Richard Krajicek
demanded that the ITF explain why Korda was spared the mandatory
one-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The ill will toward Korda started Dec. 22, when the ITF
announced that Korda had tested positive for the steroid Nandrolone
at Wimbledon and was being stripped of points and $94,529 in prize
money won there.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Korda did not knowingly take any prohibited
substance, an independent appeals committee eliminated the ITF's
one-year suspension. Under pressure from players, the ITF last week
appealed that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Korda has declined to speak about the case this week, but he
said at the time, ``I have never cheated, and I have never taken
any steroid to increase my performance on the court. When I first
heard the news, I thought it was a bad joke. . . . Now, I suppose I
will always have a black mark on my back for the rest of my life
and never be able to clean it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Korda's response apparently hasn't moved many of the players.
Bjorkman, who lost to Korda in a five-set quarterfinal last year at
the Australian, told The Age newspaper in Melbourne that the ITF
was ``scared'' to crack down on a top player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cheat, you should be suspended for two, three, four,
five years,'' Bjorkman said. ``I think it is the worst decision the
ITF (ever) made.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoltenberg, ranked 27th, said there is widespread anger and
even talk of a boycott in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think they're saying that to show how strongly they
feel about him not playing,'' Stoltenberg said. ``And I support
them in what they're saying. It's silly that he hasn't been
punished for a level-one steroid.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, who called Korda ``gutsy'' for playing through the
controversy, pressed the ITF for a fuller explanation, which could
come Saturday at a mandatory ATP Tour players meeting in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek's questions: If Korda is guilty, why no suspension? If
he is innocent, why any penalty at all, and why aren't the tests
more reliable?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ITF really did make some kind of mistake with the test,
it's very bad for Petr,'' Krajicek said, ``because now he's got the
name, and it's going to be very tough to shake it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players asked that no one pass judgment until the ITF
explains its position further. ``I really prefer not to see such an
outcry for a lynching,'' Todd Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Aussie great Pat Cash, expressed what apparently is the
prevailing opinion among players: ``How . . . can you take steroids
accidentally?''
</P>
<P>
   In Korda's native land of the Czech Republic, the tabloid Blesk
was equally unsympathetic with a headline last week that screamed:
``Petr, the truth or get out!''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly. . .
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Challenge is making a pitch for Boris Becker and
defending champion Pete Sampras to play in the April 26-May 2
tournament at Atlanta Athletic Club. . . . Steffi Graf could face
Serena Williams in the second round of the Adidas International
this week in Sydney. The winner probably would get Venus Williams
in the third. . . . The draw for the Australian Open will be
announced Friday. . . . Best new face of 1999 thus far has been
Australian 15-year-old Jelena Dokic, the U.S. Open junior girls
champion who beat No. 15 Sandrine Testud and No. 4 Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario last week in the Hopman Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
