u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TOILET-TRAINING-2     01-11 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TOILET-TRAINING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIATRICIANS RENEW BATTLE OVER TOILET TRAINING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)  (nk) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toilet training is not rocket science, says John Rosemond, a
syndicated columnist and best-selling author of parenting books. He
considers it ``a slap to the intelligence of a human being that one
would allow him to continue soiling and wetting himself past age
2.'' The process, he says, should be as simple and straightforward
as housebreaking a four-month-old puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. T. Berry Brazelton, the noted pediatrician, says there is
more to it than that. Parents who force toilet training, he says,
can cause lasting problems. ``Don't rush your toddler into toilet
training or let anyone else tell you it's time. It's got to be his
choice,'' Brazelton advises in a television commercial for Pampers
``Size 6'' diapers, suitable for children 35 pounds and over. What
does he think about Rosemond's arguments? ``They sound very logical
_ for a puppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the newest round in the toilet training wars.
</P>
<P>
   The previous round was won by parenting experts like Brazelton
and Dr. Benjamin Spock, who schooled a generation of 1960s parents
in a more flexible toilet training approach.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few decades, the age at which toddlers become
diaper free has been creeping upward. In 1957, 92 percent of
children were toilet trained by the age of 18 months, studies
found. Today, that figure has plunged to less than 25 percent,
according to a large-scale Philadelphia study. Only 60 percent of
children have achieved mastery of the toilet by 36 months, the
study found, and 2 percent remain untrained at the age of 4.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, though there are no hard statistics, pediatricians say
they are seeing more children with toilet training problems,
including withholding of urine and stool, chronic constipation and
wetting and soiling by older children. Dr. Bruce Filmer, an
associate professor of pediatric urology at Thomas Jefferson
University in Medical School in Philadelphia, for example, says
that he and other pediatric urologists have noticed an increase in
referrals of young patients experiencing problems with both daytime
and nighttime urinary control.
</P>
<P>
   And these developments combined have nourished a multibillion
dollar diaper industry, which last year racked up $545 million in
training-pant sales, and spurred the introduction of the
giant-sized diaper, designed for toddlers well past the terrible
twos.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of diaper-clad 3- and 4-year-olds, however, does not
amuse Rosemond, a family psychologist who advocates a return to
traditional child rearing practices, and he has decided to do
public battle on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of columns, published in more than 100 newspapers
last month, he blamed delayed training on wishy-washy parenting
inspired by ``Freudian mumbo-jumbo.'' In particular, he pointed at
Brazelton, professor emeritus of pediatrics at Harvard Medical
School, who in the 1960s pioneered the ``child-centered'' parenting
approach, recommending that parents let their children decide when
to become diaper-free.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing tendency for parents to leave the timing of
toiling training up to the child, Rosemond asserted, is largely
responsible for the rise in toilet training difficulties. Delayed
training, he said in a telephone interview, can also lead to
discipline problems because mothers spend too much time being
servants for their children and do not make the transition soon
enough to ``authority figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rosemond concedes that Brazelton has been giving the
same advice for decades, he also criticized the pediatrician for
serving as a consultant to Pampers, a division of Procter &AMP; Gamble,
and for appearing in the Pampers commercials. ``I think it's a
fairly blatant conflict of interest,'' Rosemond said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brazelton said he believed that the rise in toilet
training problems is the result of too much pressure on kids _ not
too little. The increase can be traced to the escalating demands of
modern life, he said. centers often require that children be toilet
trained in order to enroll, and working parents end up leaning on
their kids to comply. Nannies and baby sitters share the
responsibility for training. ``Parents are feeling very guilty and
people like Rosemond are making them feel more guilty, not less,''
Brazelton said. ``And the child's only recourse is to withhold
urine or stool in protest.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his relationship with Pampers, which also provides
funding for his research, Brazelton said he is proud of his
association with the company. ``It took me a long time to decide to
do it, but I'm absolutely convinced that it was a wonderful thing
to do,'' he said. ``I'm certainly not doing it to keep kids in
diapers. It's just the opposite: Pampers is willing to go along
with me to make it easier for mothers to let kids be open to toilet
training when they are ready.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Going along,'' of course, is not all that difficult for
Procter &AMP; Gamble which, like its competitor Kimberly-Clark, maker
of Huggies, recognizes a bonanza when it sees it. Wendy Strong,
director of corporate communications for Kimberly-Clark, said the
company's own marketing research confirms that toddlers are toilet
training later than in the past: At 18 months, only 12 percent of
children were trained; 85 percent were trained by 30 months, the
company found. Huggies, too, just began offering customers a Size 6
diaper, but the company also makes ``training pants'' for toddlers
of 38 pounds or more, a product category, Strong said, that
Kimberly-Clark ``expects to grow to more than a billion dollars by
2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever expert's school of parenting parents decide to follow,
they run no risk of confusing the philosophies, or the methods
themselves. Rosemond offers a toilet training technique he calls
``Naked and $75,'' which he recommends that parents embark upon
with their two-year olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stay home from work with your child for a few days, you
let the child walk around the house naked all day long,'' he said.
The parent puts the potty where the child spends most of his time,
and moves it when necessary to keep it nearby. Every so often, the
parent reminds the child to use the potty when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children at this age do not like urine and feces running down
their legs,'' Rosemond said. ``When they have an accident they stop
and start to howl, and the mother comes along and says `Well, you
forgot to use the toilet.' She puts him on the toilet, wipes him
off, speaks reassuringly to him. And within three days, or five
days, he's doing it on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The 75 dollars, he added, is for the carpet cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Brazelton, also the author of best-selling
parenting manuals, discourages parents from expecting their child
to potty train in a few days. The pediatrician recommends that
parents buy a potty chair and ``show children what is expected of
them at 2, what we are all doing and why it is important.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rate at which training occurs should be left up to the
child. ``If your child is afraid of the potty chair, don't put
pressure on him to use it. Put toilet training aside for a month or
two and give your child time to get used to the idea of the potty
and to be comfortable with it,'' Brazelton advises in a
step-by-step guide available on the Pampers Parenting Institute web
site (www.pampers.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``Be patient and positive,'' the pediatrician suggests. ``As
with any new skill, your child will master toilet training in
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In his experience, Brazelton said, 85 percent to 90 percent of
children will embrace toilet training soon after they first show an
interest. ``But the others are saying that there are other issues
they're trying to deal with, like day care, like parents who are
extremely busy. The child gets confused and maybe even angry and
withholds. And at this point I think you have to be able to say,
`This has got to be up to you.'''
</P>
<P>
   For parents, the bottom line seems to be: Whatever works.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Saren, for example, a Manhattan attorney, said that she
tried introducing her son Matthew to the potty when he was 3. ``But
I think looking back on it that I started when I was ready, not
when he was ready,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For months, nothing seemed to work, not bribes, not the books
``Once Upon a Potty'' or ``Everyone Poops,'' not ``big boy''
underwear. Finally, she said, Matthew decided the time was right _
when he enrolled in day care at 3 and a half. ``Seeing the other
boys poop in the potty'' seemed to do the trick, she said. ``I
would fall into the category of thinking that you just leave them
alone and they'll come to it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other mothers _ Rosemond said his daughter-in-law is one example
_ find the ``stay-at-home-and-do-it-in-three-days'' approach works
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Many pediatricians, on the other hand, say their experience has
landed them much closer to the Brazelton than the Rosemond camp.
</P>
<P>
   Filmer, for example, said that he has seen many parents become
embroiled in battles with their children if they try to force
toilet training within a defined period of time. ``Goodness me, you
talk to these parents and they will tell you that their children
formed almost a fear of toilet training,'' Filmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Taubman, a pediatrician in the department of
gastroenterology and nutrition at Childrens Hospital in
Philadelphia who has a private practice Cherry Hill, N.J., agrees
that early toilet training was a phenomenon of an earlier, less
mobile time, when most mothers stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a child trained by 2 can be done, but it is probably
done at a cost. It takes a tremendous effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Taubman says he has a hunch, though he does not yet have
data to support it, that there is a window of opportunity, perhaps
near the age of 2 or 2 and a half, ``when kids really want their
parents to get excited if the kids poop.'' If this opportunity is
missed, toilet training may take much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman is one of the few people who have collected systematic
data on toilet training: In 1997, he published the first large
scale study of children's reactions to toilet training since the
1960s, a report on 482 children in suburban Philadelphia. The study
appeared in the journal Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to assessing the ages at which most children now
train, Taubman found that on average, boys trained later than girls
and that the average age at which parents introduced toilet
training was at 23 months.
</P>
<P>
   There was no relationship, Taubman found, between when a child
was trained and the mother's work status, the presence of siblings,
the child's scores on measure of behavior, or whether or not the
child was in day care.
</P>
<P>
   About 13 percent of the children in the study had trouble with
toilet training, withholding stool and/or refusing to use the
toilet. But the vast majority of these children, Taubman said,
``resolved the problem without intervention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
