<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FLORIDA-RACETRACKS-$ADV17-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HORSEPLAYERS, IT'S GULFSTREAM FANTASY TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   (For release Sunday, Jan. 17.)  
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For New York horseplayers, January is the cruelest month. The
excitement of the late-fall Breeders' Cup, horse racing's
equivalent of the Super Bowl, has long since faded away, and the
local action, such as it is, has moved to the dreary confines of
Aqueduct. There, hard by John F. Kennedy Airport, shivering
jockeys, stung by the icy wind off Jamaica Bay, thrash their
blue-collar mounts across the frozen dirt, witnessed by sparse
crowds made up of the desolate and the desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of these die-hard fans nourishes a fantasy, and it's
right on the overhead simulcast monitors that transmit the signal
from Gulfstream Park outside Miami. Just a three-hour flight away,
happy horseplayers in sunglasses and loud shirts are watching
first-class racing against a backdrop of swaying palms and tropical
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sight to make the heart ache, and many a bettor, driven
mad by the vibrant purple Gulfstream sign above the starting gates,
has cracked under the pressure and booked passage south. Wandering
the grandstand and the clubhouse at Gulfstream, you can see them,
the most downtrodden of the New York railbirds, mysteriously
transplanted to racing's winter paradise. They wear the dazed look
of prisoners who have won a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing has its times and seasons. In spring, the talent,
and the attention of racing fans, moves to the Kentucky circuit, as
the most gifted 3-year-olds gear up for the Kentucky Derby. At the
height of summer, Saratoga opens for business in the East, and Del
Mar revs up on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But in the dead of winter, from early January to mid-March,
Gulfstream is the place, as top jockeys and trainers from the
Midwest and the East migrate south, lured by bigger purses and a
steady diet of important stakes races like the Donn Handicap, the
Hutcheson Stakes, the Fountain of Youth Stakes, the Pan American
Handicap and the Gulfstream Park Handicap. The highlight of the
meet is the $750,000 Florida Derby, often a launching pad for
horses en route to Kentucky and the Run for the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Six days a week, Gulfstream offers good, competitive racing in
an idyllic setting. The blindingly white race-track building, a
three-level affair, is enormous and well equipped, without the long
lines that torment New York horseplayers. Service is efficient and,
with rare exceptions, polite, another sharp contrast.
</P>
<P>
   The self-service betting machines all work, although there could
be more of them, and there are well-organized race-replay stations
where bettors can call up past races for profitable study. The
betting infrastructure is sound, in other words. Gulfstream also
offers simulcast betting on at least 10 other tracks, including
Aqueduct, which means that vacationing New Yorkers can look at what
they left behind and gloat. This year, as a kind of bonus,
Gulfstream will reopen for three days, Nov. 5 to 7, to play host to
the Breeders' Cup, which takes place on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream is easy for newcomers to master. Agents stationed at
the information counters just inside the grandstand and clubhouse
entrances field any and all questions, from the location of
restaurants to the ins and outs of placing a bet, and on Saturdays
and Sundays the track offers lecture-demonstrations on betting at
12:30 and 3:30 in the Inside Track Room. The wisest first step,
however, is to ask for a ``Welcome to Gulfstream'' brochure. It
folds out into a color map of the race track with instructions on
how to place a bet and what the different bets mean. It also
includes short descriptions of the track's cafes and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   So much for orientation. With brochure in hand, walk over to a
nearby booth and pick up a Daily Racing Form ($3 plus tax, or
$3.25) and, if you must, one of the myriad tipsters' sheets that
claim to offer special insights into the day's races. Then proceed
to the paddock area, at the rear of the building, where before each
race the horses are led around the English-style wood-chip walking
ring fringed with violets and lavender. Watch with a keen eye. Does
your horse have fire in his eye and a bounce in his step? Does he
exude a winner's confidence? This is the time to look up close.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the race _ you can cash that winning ticket
later _ take up a position on the clubhouse terrace right next to
the path that leads from the walking ring to the track. This is
where the jockeys emerge, faces covered in dirt, to report back to
the trainer and, in most cases, to answer the $64,000 question:
What happened? You can overhear some fascinating conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Tour the grandstand side of the walking ring, making sure to
stroll through the Garden of Champions, a formal walk lined with
obelisks whose plaques honor equine greats that have run at the
track, like A.P. Indy, Spectacular Bid and Holy Bull. The area is
decorated with beds of impatiens, geraniums and Dusty Miller,
forming a patriotic red, white and blue pattern. Cigar, the
wonderhorse who reeled off 16 straight victories before retiring in
1996, gets a special tribute in the form of a life-size bronze
statue and flower beds in the stable's colors.
</P>
<P>
   Now to the races. For a good view, buy a reserved seat, which
costs $3 in the clubhouse and $2 in the grandstand. The extra money
is worth it. With no heads in the way, and a good second-floor
vantage, you can get a perfect view of the action without having to
stand up. Besides, it's a pleasure to relax before each race and
survey the track and infield, a beautifully landscaped greensward
punctuated by banks of salmon, red and silver flowers (49 beds in
all, with 52,000 annuals), royal palms, and the box-shaped hedges
arranged along the turf course at precise intervals. On the
infield's enormous lake, a miniature red-and-white paddlewheeler
called the Suwanee River putts back and forth aimlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath. The sun is shining, the palms are swaying,
and a tropical breeze wafts the buzz and murmur of the crowd. You
hold what is undoubtedly a winning ticket. Life doesn't get any
sweeter. To ice the cake, Gulfstream has imported Tom Durkin, the
familiar voice of New York racing, to make the calls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If hunger strikes, Gulfstream abounds in fast-food concessions
and snack stands, some with Mexican and Cuban dishes, and fancier
fare is offered at a handful of restaurants. The Royal Palm Dining
Room and its covered outdoor annex, the Terrace Dining Room, occupy
prime real estate, on the ground floor at the clubhouse turn. This
year Gulfstream has brought in Levy Restaurants, the company that
owns Spaggia and Bistro 110 in Chicago, to run the track's food and
beverage services.
</P>
<P>
   For the Royal Palm, Levy has laid out a glorified brunch buffet,
called the chef's table, where for $18.95 diners can construct a
meal from appetizers to dessert. The a la carte menu is priced from
$6.95 to $14.95. There is a $1 seating charge at the Royal Palm and
Terrace. For reservations, call (954) 457-6254.
</P>
<P>
   The Rooftop Bar and Grill, on the second-floor clubhouse level,
is more casual, with fancy sandwiches (hickory-smoked ham and
Gruyere cheese on a pretzel loaf, for example) and fanciful drinks,
like the splendor in the grass martini. Menu prices run from $5.95
to $12.95. The high rollers head for the Turf Club, a more formal
dining room on the third floor of the clubhouse, where the
offerings, priced from $4.95 to $13.95, include crab cakes with
lemon aioli, red snapper with saffron couscous and pan-roasted
garlic chicken. Men must wear jackets, and nonmembers must pay $10
to enter. For reservations, call (954) 457-6255.
</P>
<P>
   Warning. All race-track dining rooms steer favorite customers to
the best tables _ the ones along the windows _ and condemn
unfamiliar faces to Siberia. At the Royal Palm, I was seated at a
table behind a pillar and a view-blocking overhang. At the Turf
Club, although I had made reservations the day before, the hostess
installed me at the one table that lacked a television monitor, so
I could not tune in Aqueduct. A modest amount of pleading and
complaining brought some relief, although not a coveted trackside
table.
</P>
<P>
   There's something perverse, in any case, about sitting indoors
to watch an outdoor sport, especially one that takes place under
limpid blue skies, with the thermometer poised at a perfect 78
degrees. Savor the moment. With a cold beer in one hand and a
promising trifecta ticket in the other, saunter over to the rail
and, for one race at least, watch the herd thunder down the
homestretch, preferably in the right order.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, there's a payoff. Win or lose, when the race is
over, drop by the simulcast monitors and take a look at Aqueduct.
Admit it, doesn't that feel good?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
