<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes gives 'a speech to govern' By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Orman and John Stanfill knew Roy Barnes when he was a
boy working at his family's general store in Mableton.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, they stood beneath a perfect blue sky and watched Barnes
take office as governor of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always real outgoing,'' said John Stanfill, 65. ``I
knew he was going to be a preacher or a politician, one.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes sounded a little like both in his 15-minute inaugural
address Monday. After an election last fall that was one of the
most divisive in state history, he appealed for people of both
parties and all races to join together.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 4,000 offered only polite applause, but Barnes'
well-wishers, such as the Stanfill brothers, gave him high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no zinger lines, but there was a whole tone of
working together,'' said Sen. David Scott (D-Atlanta). ``It was
conciliatory.''
</P>
<P>
   While the speech might not have been the most exciting of
Barnes' political career, ``I was excited about the content,'' said
state Rep. Terry Coleman (D-Eastman).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a speech to govern,'' Coleman added, ``not a campaign
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans could find little to criticize in Barnes' first
speech as governor. ``He put out his hand to us,'' said Rep. Steve
Stancil (R-Canton). ``I hope he lives up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, the Barnes administration got off to an
auspicious start. While the last few governors had chosen to take
the oath of office indoors, Barnes bucked that trend in favor of
the steps on the west side of the Capitol, the traditional site for
inaugurations in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He was rewarded with clear skies and tolerable, if brisk,
temperatures. In fact, the sun shone so brightly that Barnes had to
forego using a Teleprompter because of the glare.
</P>
<P>
   While those who attended the inauguration in person enjoyed
perfect weather, some who watched on TV or the Internet experienced
technical problems. A live feed on the state's Web site was briefly
interrupted, and some MediaOne cable system customers in Atlanta
lost signals from local stations that were carrying the speech.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests that Barnes' inauguration speech, and the
attending ceremonies, will barely be remembered compared to his
accomplishments as governor. Nevertheless, for those who were
there, Monday was an historic day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important to our state,'' said Earl Daniels, a Georgia
State University student who walked over after class to witness the
event. ``It's important to our government and to our way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Walston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
