<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE WEB  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are three independent sites on the World Wide Web, each of
which intends to be your main or only stop for arranging travel.
They all succeed, at least to some extent; they also all fail, to
some extent. They are all worth a look. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON-LINE PLANNING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.travelscape.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Architected to fully automate and individualize personal
travel planning,'' as it promotes itself, Travelscape is crammed
with just about every-thing needed to arrange, or ``architect,'' a
journey. There are sections devoted to cities, hotels, booking,
``hot deals,'' vacations, free trips and, happily, help. If the
on-screen help is not good enough, there is a toll-free telephone
number ``for further assurance of travel integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   On the opening page, a few packages are spotlighted. If you know
where you want to go, you can fill out a form for the service to
check rates and schedules for flights and hotels, either together
or separately. I said I wanted to leave Newark on Feb. 13, fly to
New Orleans, and return Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took to pour a fresh cup of coffee, a new screen
had appeared with three flight options, two of them from La Guardia
Airport rather than Newark, and five hotels in New Orleans. The
free trip, a kind of sweep-stakes, was from Los Angeles to Kauai,
Hawaii, but to enter the contest you must provide such personal
information as name and address and are encouraged, but not
required, to contribute additional information. (``How many
vacations do you take per year?'' None of your business.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``hot deals'' were for rooms at five ``luxury-level hotels''
in New Orleans, ostensibly at 15 percent to 50 percent below the
usual rates. Even though I was booking more than a month before my
trip, none of the hotels had any hot-deal rooms available.
Travelscape is still worth a look, and maybe even a stay. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LINKS GALORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.tripspot.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tripspot, a self-styled ``travel sweetspot,'' has little
original content. It offers links to scores of other Web sites,
some relevant but many not. It is certainly easier to find an
airline, hotel or cruise here than to ride out on the wild wild Web
without a scout. And, as with more and more sites, you can shop
here, too; the so-called unclaimed baggage center sells books,
music, videos, electronic gear, clothing and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The ``library'' is heaped with travel books and other
publications. It is too easy to get distracted in Tripspot. I ended
up in a site full of dumb quotations, which was fun but had nothing
to do with arranging a trip. A sample: Duffy Daugherty, the late
college football coach and sports analyst, about a player: ``Not
only is he ambidextrous, but he can throw with either hand.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEAT SHEETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.previewtravel.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preview Travel says it gives you free access to the same
information travel agents use. There is a destination guide (from
Fodor), hotel, air and car reservations, and vacation and cruise
packages. Separate sections are farefinder and carfinder,
emphasizing low prices, and a business-travel subsection with maps,
weather forecasts and a currency converter, where you can create a
cheat sheet to carry on a foreign trip.
</P>
<P>
   There are two long lists of currencies, alphabetically from the
American dollar to the Venezuelan bolivar, and the program converts
from the currency selected in the left-hand list to the currency
selected in the right-hand list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
