<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-HNS &LR;      01-11 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS ATTACK IMPEACHMENT CASE AS BASED ON `MYTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for President Clinton on Monday declared
the president innocent of charges contained in the articles of
impeachment and said the perjury case against Clinton was based on
``myth.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House arguments came in its formal response to the
Senate summons officially notifying Clinton that the Senate would
start his impeachment trial Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, House prosecutors in the Senate trial, led by
Judiciary Committee Chairman Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., filed a trial
memorandum backing up their contention that Clinton's actions
warrant removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Both documents were opening salvos in the second Senate
impeachment trial in the nation's history. House prosecutors start
the proceedings Thursday with up to 24 hours of argument, followed
by an equal amount of time for the White House legal team. After
that, senators will submit written questions and likely decide
whether to dismiss the case or call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-page White House response reiterated many of the basic
points that Clinton's lawyers made during House impeachment
hearings: Clinton neither lied to the grand jury nor obstructed
justice in hiding his affair with Lewinsky. And in any case, the
impeachment articles are too vague and do not ``meet the
constitutional standard for conviction and removal,'' the response
said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the 50-page House document recited most of the points
gone over at the same hearings: Clinton lied about his sexual
relationship with Lewinsky and obstructed justice by covering it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the memorandum charged Clinton with lying in his
Aug. 17, 1998, grand jury testimony when he said he had not had
``sexual relations'' with Lewinsky under the definition provided to
him by lawyers representing Paula Jones in her sexual harassment
lawsuit. It also charged the president with participating in an
``on-going scheme'' to obstruct the Jones case and the grand jury,
and to ``tamper'' with witnesses to get them to testify falsely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is not about sex or private conduct,'' the House
prosecutors argued. ``It is about multiple obstructions of justice,
perjury, false and misleading statements and witness tampering _
all committed or orchestrated by the president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers did not file a motion to dismiss the
charges, a move that likely would come after both House prosecutors
and the White House legal team complete their opening arguments
before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Signed by White House Counsel Charles Ruff and Clinton's private
lawyer David Kendall, the response said the perjury charge
contained in the first article is based on a ``myth'' that the
president failed to admit a relationship with the former White
House intern. The article approved by the House last month said
Clinton in his grand jury testimony lied about ``the nature and
details of his relationship'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony, Clinton acknowledged ``an improper
intimate relationship'' with Lewinsky, and that he had been alone
with her on certain occasions, the White House team said. That was
in marked contrast to his Jan. 17, 1998, deposition in the Paula
Jones lawsuit, in which he denied having had ``sexual relations''
with Lewinsky and could not recall whether they had ever been
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But White House lawyers argued that Clinton is not on trial for
statements under oath in the Jones deposition because the House
specifically rejected an impeachment article based on that
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House managers should not be allowed to prosecute before
the Senate an article of impeachment which the full House has
rejected,'' the response said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also characterized the perjury article as
``vague,'' explaining it ``fails to identify any specific statement
by the president'' that is an alleged lie. But the response then
goes on to say the impeachment article lumps ``multiple instances''
of alleged perjury together.
</P>
<P>
   This could set up a situation in which senators who believed
Clinton lied in one instance but not in the others would have to
vote for the entire first article, making it possible for House
managers to garner the 67 votes necessary for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Were the alleged mistruths packaged in individual articles,
senators would have to vote on each one, making conviction less
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking people to vote on multiple charges without
giving them the ability to look at each charge, weigh the evidence
and make a reasoned judgment,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the second article, alleging obstruction of justice, White
House lawyers said Clinton encouraged Lewinsky to file a ``limited
but truthful affidavit'' after she received a subpoena in the Jones
case on Dec. 19, 1997. In that affidavit, Lewinsky denied a sexual
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The response also says Clinton was unconcerned about gifts he
had given Lewinsky being subpoenaed by the Jones lawyers, and that
he did nothing out of the ordinary to help Lewinsky land a job in
New York. The document cites several instances in which Lewinsky
said that no one ever directed her to lie or promised her a job in
exchange for silence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on Capitol Hill, two Democratic senators, Tom Harkin
of Iowa and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, said they planned to move
to open up the full range of Senate impeachment deliberations to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Senate impeachment rules provide for an open trial but would
require deliberations on procedural questions, motions or on a
verdict to be done behind closed doors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
