<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft12-cox     01-11 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft12-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WINDOWS PRICING DOMINATES MICROSOFT TRIAL
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The secretive world of Windows pricing practices
took center stage Monday at the Microsoft antitrust trial even as
the company released testimony arguing that the software giant sets
its fees too low and enhances its products too often to be branded
as a monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   In winding up its case, the government contended that Microsoft
manipulates the prices it charges computer makers to load Windows
on their machines so as to reward its allies and punish its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The data gathered from Microsoft and the computer firms under
Justice Department subpoenas was presented by economist Franklin
Fisher after U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will
issue a verdict, sealed the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson acted after Lee Levine, a lawyer for some news
organizations that are covering the landmark trial, argued that
Jackson should open all but the most ``confidential sensitive
information'' to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys for Dell Computer Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.,
two of the largest computer makers and both ardent supporters of
Microsoft, urged the judge to keep the pricing information hidden.
While both lawyers were allowed to attend the closed session, they
reportedly promised Jackson that they would not reveal what they
heard to their respective clients.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's pricing charts were coded by name and his data was
redacted to show only the deviation from the mean that Microsoft
charged each manufacturer. Nevertheless, Microsoft lawyers
successfully held that the government's encoding system could be
broken.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, who made the case for keeping the trial open, said he
knew of ``no precedents'' in high-profile antitrust trials where
the testimony of a witness _ as opposed to sensitive documents _
was taken in secret.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, in newly released testimony, Microsoft's first
witness, economist Richard Schmalensee, disclosed that the company
had sold 125 million copies of Windows 95 for more than $7 billion
_ an average price of $56.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensitive sections of Schmalensee's testimony also were
excised from public scrutiny _ such as the actual prices that
Microsoft charges its various customers for Windows. The economist
wrote, however, that a monopolist would set its charge ``at least
16 times'' higher than what is currently levied to load Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Schmalensee estimated that if Microsoft could raise the price of
Windows by 5 percent, it could raise its pre-tax revenues by an
extra $173 million. A 10 percent increase, he wrote, would earn the
company an additional $345 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a profit-driven firm not known for leaving money on
the table pass up such easy money?'' Schmalensee asked. ``No one,''
he suggested, ``could possibly conclude that Microsoft enjoys the
quiet life of a monopolist.''
</P>
<P>
   A document filed earlier in the case by another economist, David
Sibley, places the price Microsoft charged most companies for
Windows 95 at $65 _ with up to an another $16 off in promotional
discounts for its best customers. The current version of the
operating system, Windows 98, retails for $89, although ``street''
prices are often sharply lower.
</P>
<P>
   In open court, Fisher testified that Microsoft can set its
prices as it chooses, in part because computer makers effectively
have no choice except to buy Windows, which is being shipped on
more than 95 percent of newly minted personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, David Boise, the government's lead
lawyer in the case, said he ``could not answer'' whether Microsoft
had changed its pricing practices in response to the allegations
``because he might have to touch on matters that were under seal.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
