<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-SMOKE-RESTAURANTS-     01-11 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SMOKE-RESTAURANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT GROUP DISPUTES SMOKING BAN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Banning smoking in some Massachusetts restaurants did
not hurt their business, according to the largest study to date of
the economic impact of municipal smoking bans in eateries.
</P>
<P>
   However, the researchers acknowledged problems with their
approach _ measuring meals-tax receipts in communities with smoking
bans _ and the Massachusetts Restaurant Association strongly
disputed the findings.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which covered 1992 through 1995, compared meals-tax
receipts in 32 towns that adopted smoking bans to 203 towns that
did not. The study did not include Boston, which adopted a
restaurant smoking ban last autumn.
</P>
<P>
   On average, revenue in the smoke-free-dining communities rose 4
percent, compared to 2 percent in those without smoking bans. After
accounting for seasonal trends and local demographics, ``Our models
failed to find a statistically significant effect of local,
smoke-free policies on restaurant business,'' said study co-author
William J. Bartosch of the Center for Health Economic Research in
Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of complicating issues in the study, however.
Thirteen of the 32 communities adopting bans did so during 1995, so
only a few months of revenue data were available from after their
bans took effect. Another 17 of the 32 adopted bans during 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Many chain restaurants also report sales from several outlets in
one filing to the Department of Revenue that is not broken down by
town, a problem the researchers could only partially correct for.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, for example, a town that adopted a restaurant smoking
ban in 1995, was dropped from the comparison because it is the
corporate headquarters of the Bertucci's pizzeria chain, and the
database lists all Bertucci's tax receipts for that town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meals-tax database can potentially over- or underestimate
the meals-tax receipts of any single community, and it is
impossible to perfectly match meals receipts with communities,''
Bartosch and Gregory C. Pope wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Potter, a senior official with the Westborough-based
restaurant association, said his group has tried to conduct its own
analyses, but has been warned by the Revenue Department that ``you
really can't use these meals-tax figures'' to calculate trends
because of problems with how the data are collected.
</P>
<P>
   Potter said his members' experience is that ``you definitely can
see them hurt business if it's a highly restrictive ban,'' but that
ordinances that reserve up to 30 percent of seats for smokers do
not hurt revenues.
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod, for example, anecdotal reports indicate that recent
restaurant smoking bans in Chatham and Orleans have helped push
business to neighboring Brewster, Eastham, and Harwich, Potter
said. None of those towns was in the study.
</P>
<P>
   In Dorchester, Nanina's Italian restaurant reported that
receipts dropped by $1,500 a week after a smoking ban took effect
in October, prompting the restaurant's owners briefly to flout the
ban before getting slapped with a $300 fine and agreeing to back
off and install a bar where diners could smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hartzfeld, chief executive officer of the 35-unit Back Bay
Restaurant Group operation, which includes Paparazzi, Charlie's and
Hillary's restaurants, said he has seen ``no impact'' on sales in
communities such as Boston where local authorities consulted with
restaurant owners first and allowed special smoking areas insulated
from non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But they lost 10 to 11 percent of business at a Chestnut Hill
Paparazzi restaurant where the city of Newton totally banned
smoking without consulting restaurant managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it is done with foresight and participation from business
owners, it has not had a negative impact,'' Hartzfeld said.
``There's something to be said for a well-thought-out,
well-planned-for ban'' that allows for smoking in bars or creates
segregated smoking areas.
</P>
<P>
   The study was funded by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation's
Substance Abuse Policy Research Program and published in this
month's Journal of Public Health Management and Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1907EST &QL; 
