</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON12-COX     01-11 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS FOR DISMISSAL OF IMPEACHMENT CHARGES
 &HT;    Eds: Material from this story will be included in IMPEACH, which
is moving later for those wanting a roundup of all daily
impeachment developments.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton entered a formal ``not guilty''
plea Monday to impeachment charges, arguing that none of the
accusations, even if proved, would warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   In its formal 13-page response to four perjury charges and seven
obstruction of justice charges pending before the Senate, Clinton's
lawyers launched a multi-pronged legal and constitutional assault
on the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   The legal brief maps out the lines of defense the White House
intends to use in the trial. It doesn't take a lawyer, however, to
grasp the two central points of the White House defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The charges in the articles do not constitute high crimes and
misdemeanors,'' states the first heading in the lawyers' preamble.
''The president did not commit perjury or obstruct justice,''
states the second.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, prepared under Clinton's guidance, his 11-person
legal team makes the case that all the charges against him in the
two articles of impeachment should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers stopped short of making a formal motion for
dismissal, however, opting instead to comply with the unanimous
will of the Senate to hear opening arguments first.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to go forward on the schedule set out by the
Senate. ...Then there'll be a time for motions,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're at the final stage of this process, and we can do it two
ways: we can do it fairly and expeditiously, or we can do it fairly
in a process that's open-ended and takes months and months,'' said
Lockhart. ''We prefer the former rather than the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan adopted in a 100-0 vote Friday, the Senate will
hear, beginning Thursday, up to 24 hours of presentations from
Clinton's accusers. Over a period of about three days, the 13 House
``managers'' will present evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Clinton's defense team will have 24 hours starting Jan. 19
to make its case. After that, the Senate will question both sides
and then vote on a motion to dismiss the case, with a simple
majority required to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   If that motion fails, the trial moves forward into a second
phase more complicated _ both legally and politically _ than the
first. The divisive, and as yet undecided, issue of whether to call
witnesses will move quickly to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds majority of the Senate would be needed to convict
Clinton, a finding that would require him to leave office
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers said Friday, however, they expect the Senate
to dismiss the charges after phase one of the trial. On Monday,
they laid out their strategy for that phase, attacking the charges
against him on multiple fronts.
</P>
<P>
   As a first line of defense, Clinton's lawyers argue simply that
none of the charges meets the constitutional test of an impeachable
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The charges in the articles do not rise to the level of 'high
Crimes and Misdemeanors' as contemplated by the Founding Fathers,''
the White House brief argues, ''and they do not satisfy the
rigorous constitutional standard applied throughout our Nation's
history. Accordingly, the Articles of Impeachment should be
dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House brief confronts each separate charge with
head-on denials.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the perjury charges, Clinton's lawyers assert, for
instance, that it is ''a myth'' that the president lied about his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky during
grand jury testimony last Aug. 17, during which he read a statement
acknowledging that his encounters with her ''did involve
inappropriate intimate contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers go on to argue that the perjury charges
against Clinton are ''fatally flawed'' because they bundle all four
allegations into a single article. Under that structure, Clinton's
attorneys argue, he could be found guilty if two-thirds of the
Senate agreed that he committed perjury on any combination of the
charges, even though they might not agree in those numbers on any
one specific charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''This creates the very real possibility that conviction could
occur even though Senators were in wide disagreement as to the
alleged wrong committed,'' Clinton's lawyers stated. ''The
president could be convicted even though he would have been
acquitted if separate votes were taken on each allegedly perjurious
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers also specifically deny that he urged Lewinsky
to lie under oath when she testified in December 1997 in the sexual
harassment case of former Arkansas state employee Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ''The President denies that he encouraged Ms. Lewinsky to lie if
and when called to testify personally in the Jones case,'' the
White House brief states.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from Lewinsky's own testimony, the White House lawyers
argue that she made exculpatory statements _ testimony that would
exonerate Clinton _ that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr ignored
in his report. For example, the brief states that Lewinsky
testified, ''No one ever asked me to lie and I was never promised a
job for my silence.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment article does not accuse Clinton of telling
Lewinsky to lie. It charges him with urging her to make a statement
under oath that he knew to be ''perjurious, false and misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   That charge comports with the accusation levied by Starr in his
report last September to the House Judiciary Committee summarizing
his inquiry into the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the president did not expressly instruct her to lie,
according to Ms. Lewinsky, he did suggest misleading cover stories.
And, when she assured him that she planned to lie about the
relationship, he responded approvingly,'' the Starr report states.
</P>
<P>
   In a handwritten statement to Starr's office, for example,
Lewinsky wrote that ''The President told Ms. L to deny a
relationship, if ever asked about it. He also said something to the
effect of if the two people who are involved say it didn't happen _
it didn't happen,'' according to the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
