<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Jan. 17) 
(JT) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Panama Canal Tours
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there cruises through the Panama Canal other than long
ones, perhaps tours that would include a passage through the canal?
_ Ellen Hanley, Muskegon, Mich. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Panama is starting to be discovered by visitors other than
those on the decks of cruise ships, and a good one-stop-shopping
place for touring the country is Panama Discovery Tours. This
booking agency for Panama Jones, a Panama City tour operator,
offers several standard tours encompassing various regions, and can
customize them, according to Linda Rice, a travel consultant at the
Panama Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   One tour spends six days mainly in the Panama City area. It
includes guided excursions in the city and the Canal Zone, and a
full-day transit of the canal, which includes food and drinks.
There is also a visit to the Summit Tropical Gardens and Zoological
Park to see the macaws, toucans and other wildlife, and a cruise to
Taboga Island. This tour costs from $599 to $1,375 a person, double
occupancy, depending on the level of accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The Panama Discovery Tour is two days longer, adding trips to
the Anton Valley, about two and a half hours west of Panama City; a
pontoon boat expedition to Gatun Lake islands to see the culture of
the Embera Indians, and a tour to the Conquistador-era ruins at
Portobello. This tour costs from $922 to $1,924 each, double
occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Panama Discovery uses Argo Tours for marine transportation. This
company offers half-day canal tours to the Pedro Miguel Locks from
Pier 18 in Balboa on Saturday mornings, with full-day trips through
the canal one Saturday a month. These cost $75 and $125. The
company uses two ships, the 96-foot Islamorada, a 1912 wooden
vessel, and the 1977 steel-hulled Fantasia del Mar, 117 feet with
three decks.
</P>
<P>
   Panama Discovery Tours, Post Office Box 130, Clarita, Okla.
74525; (888) 726-2621, fax (580) 428-3499; www.panamalcanal.com.
Argo to fix spacing of lines and web address is in Balboa, Panama,
and can be reached at (507) 228-4348 or (507) 228-6069, fax (507)
228-1234 or (507) 211-0844; its Web site is www.big-ditch.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area Cooking Schools
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in San Francisco in May. Are there cooking schools
there with one-to-three-day sessions? _ E.A. Fentress, Jackson,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   A. ``The 1999 Guide to Cooking Schools,'' published by Shaw
Guides ($22.95) and available on the Web at www.shawguides.com,
lists dozens of recreational cooking schools in Northern
California, so it depends on how far afield you want to travel. The
wine country of Napa, Sonoma and Mendocino Counties is a center of
such schools.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco itself, the California Culinary Academy offers
six-hour sessions on Saturdays in the Civic Center area. The
classes are broken into groups of 10 to 20 and are hands on, led by
a chef. Afterward, the classes dig in to a buffet of their work in
various ethnic cuisines, vegetarian cooking or baking. Sessions
cost $130. Contact the Weekend Program Manager, 625 Polk Street,
San Francisco, Calif. 94102; (800) 229-2433; www.baychef.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tante Marie's Cooking School was started 20 years ago and is
still run by Mary Risley, who studied at Le Cordon Bleu and La
Varenne. The school's professional classes teach classic French
cooking, but recreational classes cover a wide variety of cuisines,
according to Peggy Lynch, administrator of the school, which is on
Telegraph Hill.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor can choose from weeklong vacation cooking schools
($550), two-day weekend sessions ($250), and individual classes
($40 to $75). The school uses its own faculty and guest
instructors, who are chefs or cookbook authors. The May schedule
will be out in March, Ms. Lynch said. Contact her at 271 Francisco
Street, San Francisco, Calif. 94133; (415) 788-6699, fax (415)
788-8924; www.tantemarie.com.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, by Barge
</P>
<P>
   Q. Four of us would like to charter a barge in Europe to see a
few countries from canals or rivers. Can you provide any resources?
_ Pamela J. Caldwell, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   A. Barging is particularly popular in France, perhaps less so in
other European countries. Barges or river boats can be charted with
or without crews. This mode of leisurely touring is probably best
supplemented by taking along bicycles, or renting them at the
various stops.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies charter boats in France, but few offer
itineraries that cross borders. Le Boat, an American company, deals
with several charter outfits offering dozens of cruises in France,
the Netherlands, Germany, Britain and Ireland, but only one route _
along the northern branch of the Canal de l'Est in Alsace-Lorraine
_ allows a brief crossover from France into Belgium, according to
Debbie Petermann, president of Le Boat. Other routes include the
Canal du Midi in southern France, the Canal de Bourgogne and a
network of canals in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Prices, like the itineraries, cover a wide area, but for a
smaller vessel, expect to pay $900 to $2,000 a week. These rates
include the boat, galley gear _ but not food _ bedding and some
taxes. Fuel, maps, bikes and parking are extra. Contact Le Boat at
10 South Franklin Turnpike, Ramsey, N.J. 07446; (800) 992-0291, fax
(201) 236-1214.
</P>
<P>
   Offering similar charters in France is American Media Tours, 16
West 32d Street, New York, N.Y. 10001; (800) 969-6344, fax (212)
465-1636. This company, which deals with France only, offers
cruises in the Loire Valley, Burgundy, Alsace and on the River
Charente.
</P>
<P>
   Among German companies renting boats is Kuhnle Tours, 4
Nagelstrasse, D-70182, Stuttgart; (49-711) 164-820, fax (49-711)
164-8260. Eva Irina Muehleck, a company spokeswoman, said that
while none of its itineraries crossed national borders, rentals
could be arranged on the lakes of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania in
Germany, and many rivers and canals in France, the Netherlands and
Ireland. Rates for a boat for four start at $535 to $900 in low
season to about double those at peak times, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands, the province of Friesland has numerous lakes
and canals to explore _ and just as many charter boat operators.
Many of them offer seven-night motor yacht rentals that include a
day of supervision by an instructor and guide before you continue
on your own. Prices run from about $190 to $600 a person, based on
five to a boat.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about these companies, contact Friesland
Holland Tourist Information, 38 Hoofdstraat West, NL-8471 HV
Wolvega; (31-561) 615-364, fax (31-561) 617-818.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
