<HEADLINE>
US PROPOSES CUT IN LOBSTER FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fearful that New England's most valuable fishery is in
danger, the National Marine Fisheries Service has proposed new
limits on lobster fishing in federal waters in an effort to stop a
lobster trap ``arms race'' that is decimating the sexually mature
population.
</P>
<P>
   The federal trap limits and other requirements apply only to
about 20 percent of the industry, the 3,400 lobstermen licensed to
set traps more than 3 miles off shore. Federal regulators will need
help from sometimes-reluctant state governments to stop
over-fishing for lobsters in the 80 percent of lobstering that
occurs closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   But National Marine Fisheries Service officials said their
regulations, aimed at rebuilding the lobster industry over the next
decade, will allow the agency and states from Maine to North
Carolina to work together to reverse the ominous trend of fishermen
setting more and more lobster traps each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real reduction in the amount of gear that's out
there. It's the first step toward reducing the arms race,'' said
Andrew Rosenberg, deputy director of the National Marine Fisheries
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the American lobster business appears to be
booming: the catch rose by 20 percent from 1995 to 1997, when
lobsters accounted for 27 percent of the Northeast's fishing income
and provided 50,000 jobs. Maine and Massachusetts alone account for
three quarters of the total catch.
</P>
<P>
   But federal biologists say the boom masks an impending disaster
if nothing is done as lobstermen catch increasing numbers of young
females before they can spawn the next generation of lobsters.
Almost half the legal-sized female lobsters were removed from the
Gulf of Maine each year from 1982 to 1993, they said, a dangerous
trend that has continued.
</P>
<P>
   Lobster states, working through the Atlantic States Marine
Fisheries Commission in Washington, have agreed that the lobster
population should recover over the next decade, and groups of
fishermen now are devising rules to meet that goal. However, some
state legislatures are resisting a crackdown on lobstering; for
instance, Rhode Island recently allowed more lobstermen into the
industry, increasing the fishing pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service rules would allow the
Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission to lead on lobster
conservation, automatically adopting their rules in federal waters
for consistency. However, if the states don't do enough, the
service promises to crack down independently.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federal limits on lobster traps would grow
tighter over the next two years, while requiring lobstermen to
choose between fishing less than 30 miles offshore or fishing
exclusively in the more-distant offshore waters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rosenberg said the federal plan may not be enough. ``I'm
an optimist, but I'm just nervous that this fishery is going to
take a downturn,'' he said. ``My frustration has been . . . that we
are going to be behind the curve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
