<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-GROWTH-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE SPENDING GREW IN 1998 AT SLOWEST ANNUAL RATE EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on medicare growth is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The growth of Medicare slowed last year to a
virtual halt as spending in the giant health insurance program for
the elderly rose by just 1.5 percent, the smallest increase since
the beginning of the program in 1965, new government data show.
</P>
<P>
   The slower rate of growth will probably add a few years to the
life of the Medicare trust fund that pays hospital bills for the
elderly. And it may temporarily relax the pressure on Congress to
redesign the program. But officials said that it does not
fundamentally alter the long-term outlook for Medicare, which will
incur immense new costs as baby boomers become eligible after 2010.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Medicare spending last year grew more slowly
than the federal budget as a whole, which increased by 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown shows the effects of congressional curbs on
payments to hospitals and home health care agencies and the results
of a federal crusade against Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Medicare spending rose by an average of
$12.8 billion, or 10 percent, a year. But in 1998, it grew just
$3.1 billion, to a total of $213.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are all rightly concerned about the growth of future
costs, Medicare right now is amazingly well behaved,'' said Robert
Reischauer, former director of the Congressional Budget Office.
``Nobody is really sure why Medicare spending has slowed down quite
as much as it has. The only thing we can be sure of is that it
won't last.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Medicare beneficiaries grew last year by slightly
more than 1 percent, to 39 million. So the average increase in
Medicare spending for each beneficiary was close to zero, budget
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The experts offer several explanations. Congress intentionally
curbed payments to hospitals, home health agencies and other health
care providers in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, and the savings
so far have exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and hospitals have historically absorbed such cutbacks
without reducing services to patients, but there is evidence that
some beneficiaries are having difficulty gaining or keeping access
to home health care services.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay within their Medicare budgets, home health agencies
are avoiding higher-cost patients, chronically ill patients and
those who need the most care,'' said William Dombi, vice president
of the National Association for Home Care.
</P>
<P>
   Health maintenance organizations, saying their costs are rising
faster than the payments they receive, have dropped more than
400,000 Medicare patients from their rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Federal efforts to curb fraud and abuse also appear to have
slowed the growth of Medicare. Health care executives said the
federal investigation of Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. had sent a
chill through the hospital industry and encouraged greater
compliance by health care providers of all types, including
doctors, who fear prosecution for submitting false claims.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has pumped money into such investigations for several
years, and June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of
Health and Human Services, has led a crackdown on Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Scully, president of the Federation of American Health
Systems, which represents 1,400 for-profit hospitals, said:
``People in hospitals _ the billing clerks and their supervisors _
are generally scared to death of being investigated for billing
errors, accidental or intentional. Revenues are dropping because
hospitals are being ultraconservative in their billing practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's growth last year was significantly slower than that
of private health insurance plans. In a recent survey of 207 large
employers, Towers Perrin, a management consulting concern, found
that the cost of employee health benefits increased 4 percent on
the average last year, with an increase of 7 percent forecast for
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the Congressional Budget Office predicted that
Medicare's Hospital Insurance Trust Fund, which pays hospital bills
for the elderly, would run out of money in 2010. But health policy
experts now say the trust fund will probably not be depleted until
some time after 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund had been expected to lose $4 billion in 1998, but
instead it posted a surplus of nearly $1 billion. The trust fund's
revenues, mainly from payroll taxes, were $2 billion higher than
expected, thanks to a strong economy, and spending was $3 billion
less than projected by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Spending from the hospital trust fund declined last year by
one-half of 1 percent, to $136.7 billion. Spending for doctors'
services and other items covered by a separate trust fund rose by
5.1 percent, to $76.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Moon, a public trustee of the Medicare trust funds,
said, ``The 1997 Balanced Budget Act will do more than people
thought to hold down Medicare costs.'' For example, she said,
``spending on home health care declined from 1997 to 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Delays in the payment of claims also seem to have slowed the
growth of Medicare spending last year. Federal officials and
government contractors are taking more time to scrutinize claims
for errors and fraud, and these delays may have been worsened by
changes in Medicare computer systems, needed to get ready for the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, health officials said, government data show a greater lag
between the time when patients are treated and the time when
Medicare pays hospitals, nursing homes and home health agencies for
those services.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare pays a fixed amount for each beneficiary admitted to a
hospital, and the government measures the average complexity, or
cost, of all the Medicare cases at each hospital. This ``case mix
index,'' which had been been rising for many years, declined last
year, officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal spending on Medicaid, the health program for poor
people, which also pays for large amounts of nursing home care,
rose last year by 5.9 percent, to $101 billion. This was larger
than the increases in 1995 and 1996, when Medicaid spending grew an
average of 3.6 percent a year. But, aside from those years, it was
the smallest increase since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The steep decline in welfare rolls has contributed to a
reduction in the number of Medicaid recipients, and this in turn
has held down Medicaid costs. Welfare officials acknowledge that
some people who leave welfare are entitled to Medicaid but do not
receive it, because they do not understand their rights or are
discouraged by the difficulties of obtaining coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
