</P>
<P>
   GOLDMANSACHS-SHAKEUP (Undated) _ Goldman Sachs Group LP's Jon
Corzine quit Monday as co-chief executive after the world's biggest
investment banking partnership withdrew plans to sell shares to the
public and lost hundreds of millions of dollars trading bonds in
its fourth quarter. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom right)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Microsoft began its trial defense
Monday with an economist from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology bearing a massive tome of written testimony with a
simple message _ Microsoft's business practices are good for
consumers and any government meddling with the software industry
would likely do more harm than good. By Steve Lohr and Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom center)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-STOCKSWAP (Frankfurt, Germany) _ British American
Tobacco PLC announced plans Monday to acquire Rothmans
International for about $7.5 billion, the biggest but probably not
the last cigarette-industry combination this year. The deal would
unite the second- and fourth-largest tobacco companies in the world
and put British American within striking distance of the Philip
Morris Co. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
