<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-MURAL-ART-NYT     01-11 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MURAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POST-APARTHEID TRIBUTE: ART LEADING THE PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa, a nation top-heavy
with ponderous memorials to British and Boer victories, is
struggling to come up with a few catchy post-apartheid monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy. The ever modest Nelson Mandela has not posed for
a colossus yet. The bronze statue in East London of Steve Biko, the
anti-apartheid activist who was beaten to death by the police in
1977, is widely acknowledged to be a nice idea, dreadfully molded.
</P>
<P>
   The statue of the new mayor of the little dorp of Wepener, put
up to counterbalance the old one of the brutal 19th-century
Kommandant Louw Wepener, lost some of its luster when the mayor was
accused of car theft and check kiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulus who were killed at the Battle of Blood River finally
have their own memorial near the great circle of bronze wagons that
the Afrikaner victors put up, but Blood River is several miles back
of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, take heart. Right now, in the very center of
Johannesburg, Reshada Crouse is finishing her mural. It's grand,
it's romantic, it's a knockoff of Delacroix's ``Liberty Leading the
People.'' But there's something oddly familiar about the faces.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Mandela or Tutu or Biko among them. After a bit,
though, it becomes clear: You've seen them on the afternoon soaps.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crouse is not making fun of the genre. Nor of liberation.
Her mural _ she can't make up her mind whether it is called
``Revolution'' or ``Passive Resistance'' _ is a testament to the
role that theater people played in the anti-apartheid struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Her commission, which comes from a government-financed arts
foundation, is to adorn a big public space: the Civic Theater,
Johannesburg's equivalent of Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was an art student,'' she said, ``there was always a
lot of pressure on us to do `political art,' which I thought was
just a phony, because no visual artist was going to change
anything. But theater was different. Because of the shows put on
overseas, Athol Fugard's plays for example, there was a lot of
outside pressure on the Nats'' _ the ruling National Party in the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't the French Revolution,'' she said. ``It didn't get
that violent here. In the end it was intellectual pressure that
brought the Nats to their knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crouse is a serious artist, but she has done the official
portraits of army commanders and reserve bank governors without
losing her sense of whimsy. Her official version of Gen. Constand
Viljoen, army commander during apartheid, is a double portrait,
which slyly reminds viewers that he had a twin brother in the
anti-apartheid movement. It also features his favorite cows and
favorite assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The mural, on which she has labored in the Civic's lobby for a
year, is a minefield of allusions. It may be realistic, she said,
``but it's surreal. It's not linear.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first draft, when she entered the contest, was ``very
politically incorrect'' _ a Zulu street battalion led to freedom by
her 19-year-old ``Aryan beauty'' of a daughter in combat boots. Her
written description, which bested 54 other entries, promised a
final version equally black and white, male and female.
</P>
<P>
   The battalion mutated into ``a gypsy caravan of traveling
players'': playwrights like Athol Fugard and Paul Slabolepszy,
producers like Mannie Manim and Barney Simon, founder of the
defiantly integrated Market Theater.
</P>
<P>
   John Kani, now the managing trustee of the Market, marches in
his ``Othello'' robes; Nomsa Nene, now a loudmouth game show host,
wears her humble maid's uniform from ``Poppie Nongena'' and pushes
a mop.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape is full of African aloes, twisted spikes that
contain healing juices. Over it all waves what Ms. Crouse, with her
quirky eye, calls ``the toothpaste flag.'' As soon as she says it,
the noble pennant of the new South Africa is ruined for you. You
realize that it does look as if it had been squeezed out of a tube
of Aquafresh.
</P>
<P>
   At lower right are three guerrillas with guns and machetes. One
is obvious: the television heartthrob Sello Maake ka-Ncube. The
others, less well known, look wrong somehow. Nick Boraine, who
fiercely resembles David Bowie, wears a bustier and opera gloves
with his M-16. Jamie Bartlett has a red clown nose.
</P>
<P>
   These are not mistakes. In Fugard's early play ``Woza Albert,''
black men playing whites don red noses, so Ms. Crouse is signaling
that Bartlett is black.
</P>
<P>
   In Boraine's case, she is echoing something she learned from
startled war correspondents: in the cruelest civil wars in Africa,
from Zaire to Sierra Leone, a few fighters charge into battle stark
naked, while others wear blond wigs and bras.
</P>
<P>
   ``When societies go completely anarchic, people cross-dress,''
she said. ``And I wanted to show the sexual arousal men find in
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The central figure of Liberty has caused her the most grief.
Kani said he would not appear in a tribute to black liberation with
a white Miss Liberty. Ms. Crouse agreed, and persuaded Sibongile
Mngoma, a singer and actress, to pose. But Ms. Mngoma later decided
not to be captured for posterity half-nude. She is now in the
background, in what looks like a bikini.
</P>
<P>
   Camilla Waldman, a white actress, agreed to let her own full,
slightly pregnant, figure be used. ``We put dark makeup on for the
photo shoot, but I've still got to disguise her, make her at least
Creole,'' Ms. Crouse said. Ms. Mngoma's aunt, the diva Sibongile
Khumalo, understood her niece's reluctance and said Ms. Waldman
would do, with adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Make her nipples pitch black and give her
dreadlocks, and she'll be fine,''' Ms. Crouse said.
</P>
<P>
   When the political corrections to the mural are finally done,
Ms. Crouse knows exactly where she wants to hang it. Bisecting the
upper lobby is a sort of peninsula of mirrors that was built in a
more elitist era. It is the VIP box, and the mirrors are two-way
glass. They let the mighty join the lobby crowd at intermission,
but without the proletariat being able to gawk back at them. Ms.
Crouse sized her canvas to fit precisely over the biggest mirror.
</P>
<P>
   And what does she hope that viewers will feel on seeing her
greatest work?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a kid, you'll say, `Oh, look, there's so-and-so from
TV!' If you know Delacroix, you'll have a whole post-modern
explanation for it. And if you're from America and you know
absolutely nothing, you'll have to read the plaque.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
