<SLUG> BC-GORE-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE UNVEILS OPEN SPACE INITIATIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Touting proposals to preserve open spaces and tame
urban sprawl, Vice President Al Gore launched Monday what is
expected to be a week's worth of initiatives that could provide a
foundation for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the American Institute of Architects, Gore unveiled a
program to provide federal support for communities that seek to
purchase land for parks, old industrial sites, or land to preserve
water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The open space initiative would be accomplished by floating $9.5
billion in bonds that state and local governments could use as a
financing mechanism to purchase land.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore proposal, to be included in the administration's
upcoming budget, would provide for $700 million in federal tax
credits, which would make it cheaper to finance the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the urban sprawl initiative are a 16 percent
increase in funds for public transit, and $50 million in grants to
local groups to design strategies to control growth.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the purpose of the proposals was to create ``livable
communities, comfortable suburbs, vibrant cities and green spaces
all around and in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement was the first of what aides say will be a
week of initiatives from the vice president. On Tuesday he is
expected to propose tax incentives for education and job training
and on Wednesday will propose empowerment grants. At the end of the
week the vice president is expected to speak on trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   The series of policy announcements come as the vice president
positions himself for a bid for the White House in 2000. Analysts
say that by focusing on these initiatives, he may be trying to
distance himself from the impeachment trial in the Senate and to
show that he is serious about governing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of being vice president in a second presidential
term is that gradually you are given more opportunities for
stepping out and taking the lead with new initiatives, allowing you
to act presidential before you're president,'' said Thomas Mann,
political analyst at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   But Mann noted that the urban sprawl issue Gore is promoting is
not one that has been important to the most traditional Democratic
voters, such as organized labor and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake to see this as distributing goodies to
the base. This is different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said using government as means to push planning could
alienate those who believe that individuals should have the right
to live or develop land wherever they chose.
</P>
<P>
   However, the issue could resonate with suburbanites _ key swing
voters _ particularly in the crowded northeast corridor, who
believe that their neighborhoods have become over developed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, a Republican,
championed a $1 billion program to save open space and farmland
that was approved by voters in the Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   John Casbarian, the associate dean of the School of Architecture
at Rice University in Houston, called the Gore open space plan, ``a
smart idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Casbarian said that Houston parents could have used the bond
concept recently when they tried to save undeveloped land next to
the Rice School.
</P>
<P>
   Casbarian said the heavily wooded land has served as a buffer
between the school and busy intersection. But then the owner razed
the land for a high density development and the parents were unable
to raise enough money to buy the property.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
