<P>
   CONGO-CONFLICT (Kinshasa, Congo) _ From its earliest imagination
in the minds of outsiders hungry for its riches _ gold for traders
and souls for missionaries _ Congo has rarely belonged to itself
alone. Now this huge and unsteady state has become a battlefield of
soldiers from no fewer than six foreign nations. It is a war that
has as much to do with problems outside of Congo as inside it. A
fundamental reworking of the old rules of Africa may be unfolding
in the five-month-old Congo war. By Norimitsu Onishi and Ian
Fisher. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With photo and
map. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-COUNCIL-IRAQ (United Nations) _ The United States is
finding itself increasingly isolated in its Iraq policy as a
growing number of Security Council members and Arab nations support
lifting an embargo on Iraqi oil sales or significantly relaxing
sanctions in other ways to relieve the suffering of the Iraqi
people. But contrary to what the Iraqis may hope, there is also
solid agreement that long-term international supervision is needed
to prevent Iraq from acquiring prohibited weapons. Among proposals
to be discussed are the creation of a new inspection system and
ways to monitor money that Iraq would earn if it sold oil freely.
By Barbara Crossette. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-UTAH-IMAGE (Salt Lake City) _ The Olympic scandal, with
reports of bribes, a land deal and possibly prostitutes, used to
steer the 2002 Winter Olympics to this clean cut Western city has
tarnished this city's effort to project a new high tech,
cosmopolitan image to the world. On Monday the evolving scandal
apparently claimed its latest victim as Salt Lake's mayor, Deedee
Corradini, announced that she would not run for a third term,
crushing her dream of presiding over the Olympics here. By James
Brooke. (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   reefer: MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Microsoft Corp. begins
its defense in the government's antitrust lawsuit with an economist
from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology bearing a massive
tome of written testimony with a simple message: Microsoft's
business practices are good for consumers, and any government
meddling with the software industry would likely do more harm than
good. By Steve Lohr and Joel Brinkley. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TOILET-TRAINING (Undated) _ Toilet training is not rocket
science, says John Rosemond, a syndicated columnist and
best-selling author of parenting books. He considers it ``a slap to
the intelligence of a human being that one would allow him to
continue soiling and wetting himself past age 2.'' The process, he
says, should be as simple and straightforward as housebreaking a
four-month-old puppy. Dr. T. Berry Brazelton, the noted
pediatrician, says there is more to it than that. Parents who force
toilet training, he says, can cause lasting problems. ``Don't rush
your toddler into toilet training or let anyone else tell you it's
time. It's got to be his choice,'' Brazelton advises in a
television commercial for Pampers ``Size 6'' diapers. What does he
think about Rosemond's arguments? ``They sound very logical _ for
puppies.'' Welcome to the newest round in the toilet training wars.
1800 words. By Erica Goode. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
