<HEADER>
A8556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPIC-KIOSKS-COX     01-11 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-KIOSKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1996 Olympics lawsuit settled
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A $6 million trial over Olympic kiosks could have
stretched over a month and revealed details of one of the most
troubled companies involved in Games vending.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the lawsuit was settled Monday, a week after jury
selection began in Fulton County Superior Court and before openings
statements were made. Details of the deal, including a dollar
amount, are confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties are satisfied; they're very happy with the
settlement,'' said attorney Vanessa Vargas of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas represented 11 individuals and corporations who claimed
they were bilked after spending at least $10,000 for each of dozens
of souvenir booths. They said the defendants provided no goods or
services that were contracted.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants included Creative Travel Service, which garnered
nationwide publicity during the 1996 Games after it brought 3,000
teenagers from across the country to work at the souvenir booths.
The youths returned home after finding they had nowhere to stay and
nothing to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Garland, an Atlanta attorney representing the defendants, did
not return a phone call Monday. Defendants also included companies
the kiosk buyers say were set up to carry out the sales and their
backers New Orleans retailer Raed Halum was among those who sued.
He and four family members and friends bought 27 kiosks for
$270,000, hoping to make more than $1.35 million in profit.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement did ``not really'' get all their investment back,
Halum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm OK with it,'' he said. ``It would have been better, it
could have been worse. We figured, you take your losses and run and
it's been two and half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels the way I do. Nobody's thrilled, but we feel
it's the best we can do so let's take it and end it.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Fulton County lawsuit involving Olympic vendors was
dismissed before reaching trial.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, vendors sued B.G. Swing Games Management Inc. and
its president, Munson Steed. B.G. Swing, the city's former
marketing representative, leased city streets and sidewalks during
the Olympics and Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors claimed they were mislead and fraudulently induced to
sign contracts with B.G. Swing. The suit sought $25 million in
punitive damages, but did not specify compensatory damages. Other
defendants included the city and the Atlanta Economic Development
Corp., now called the Atlanta Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the suit was dismissed by a judge in May 1997, who later
threw out remaining claims against Steed.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors in October voluntarily dismissed what was left of
their case, although they may refile. Their attorney, Louis
Levenson said that should happen within a week. And in April,
Atlanta businessman Andrew Adler was convicted in South Carolina of
defrauding a T-shirt supplier out of more than $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
