<HEADLINE>
ARENS TO CHALLENGE NETANYAHU IN LIKUD PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS) 
(rk) 
 By   DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The clearest sign yet of just how much Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has estranged the Israeli political
establishment _ both left and right _ came Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's political godfather, Moshe Arens, 73, a former
defense and foreign minister, announced that he would challenge his
one-time protege for the leadership of the Likud Party in party
primaries. The primaries will select the Likud candidates for the
May 17 national elections .
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true my relations with Benjamin Netanyahu, because of
the age gap, were in many ways like father to son,'' Arens said
Monday. ``But that doesn't change the situation the Likud is in
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing defections of ``first-rank people'' from Likud and
pronouncing the party to be in crisis, Arens, a hawkish and
straightforward old-timer, became the second challenger for the
Likud title and the eighth candidate for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   It is a field so crowded _ particularly with army generals _
that Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon interrupted a recent
ribbon-cutting ceremony to congratulate one participant, a former
army chief of staff, for not throwing his hat in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to run, Arens relied on a poll of Likud voters. The
poll favored Netanyahu, with 57 percent of the voters' support. But
it showed Arens, who retired from politics five years ago, at 22
percent, ahead of the other challenger, Uzi Landau, who had 7.5.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts consider it highly unlikely that Arens could
unseat Netanyahu but do not rule it out. The primaries will be on
Jan. 25 to select candidates for Parliament and prime minister.
Some 160,000 party members are eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu voiced no concern. ``I can assure you that I have no
doubt that I will receive the overwhelming support of the Likud
voters in the Likud primaries and, indeed, of the citizens of
Israel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An aircraft engineer trained in the United States, Arens is
fluent in English and was ambassador to the United States during
the early 80s. It was then when he hand-selected Netanyahu, who was
the marketing manager for a furniture company, for a future in
politics. Arens hired the man whom he knew as the son of Benzion
Netanyahu, an Israeli historian, to be the diplomatic liaison aide
for the embassy. From that time Arens helped guide Netanyahu's
career.
</P>
<P>
   But Arens, who was defense and foreign minister under Yitzhak
Shamir, a previous Likud prime minister, grew disenchanted with
Netanyahu the prime minister. He wrote frequent newspaper columns
that criticized Netanyahu's political and diplomatic moves,
particularly in the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   After the prime minister signed the latest peace agreement in
October, his party fell into shambles, because Netanyahu's approval
of the accord signaled the end of an ideological era for the Likud,
which was born to oppose territorial concessions. Netanyahu lost
many supporters who felt betrayed or that they could not trust him.
</P>
<P>
   Arens reportedly came forward when younger members of the Likud
chose not to oppose Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Likud young guard got weak knees, the elders of the
tribe had to take up the reins, and they have put Moshe Arens in
the forefront,'' Nehama Duek, a political analyst, wrote in a
newspaper, Yediot Ahronot.
</P>
<P>
   Two younger Likud members defected rather than go up against
Netanyahu, who despite his inability to hold his government
together is an aggressive and charismatic campaigner. Dan Meridor,
one of the party's aristocrats or ``princes,'' left to run for
prime minister as a centrist, and Benny Begin, son of the late
Prime Minister Menachem Begin, resigned to campaign at the head of
a new right-wing party.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prime minister revealed no embarrassment, political
commentators said Netanyahu received the ultimate rebuke when his
mentor officially abandoned him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in another newspaper, Maariv, Menachem Rahat described
the move as an effort ``to beat his pupil and inherit his place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The creator,'' the writer said, ``defied his creation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
