<HEADLINE>
OLDER TRAVELERS TURN TO INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 17.) 
(ms) 
 By BETSY WADE     
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elderhostel and Interhostel, which offer travel for vigorous
older people, have entered cyberspace, putting their catalogs on
Web sites. And in November, Elderhostel began taking registrations
electronically through its site.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the elderly have discovered that e-mail is the ideal way
for the sleepless to communicate with the world, they have also
apparently found that the Internet is an efficient way to shop.
Since Elderhostel began Internet registration in November, a
spokeswoman said, 1,000 clients, or 5 percent of those signing up
in the period, took the electronic option, plus 50 who used it to
change earlier registrations. This is out of Elderhostel's estimate
of a total of 325,000 ``older learners'' who signed on in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic registration is expected to grow, but the process
will never be as zip-zip-zip as ordering socks through the Web: One
trip does not fit all. People who have traveled with these
organizations know what to expect: dormitory rooms or cabins,
bathrooms shared with a battalion, meals at cafeteria tables, lots
of walking and carrying of one's own bags.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet may pose problems for the uninitiated.
Spokeswomen for both organizations said that phone discussions with
applicants were frequently necessary to be sure that they realized
that air fare is or is not included, or that they have not
neglected to read notices that special menus are not available,
cobblestones are hard to navigate and applications by frail people
are discouraged. There are plenty of warning flags in the paper
catalogs, but using Web sites, it is easy to sign up before
reckoning with the realities.
</P>
<P>
   Those without computers should know that they have not been
betrayed in the race for spots in popular Elderhostel courses: the
thousands of listings in each fat newsprint catalog _ or on the Web
_ all have a single date for a lottery for registration spots.
Until then, all applications _ mail, fax, phone and electronic _ go
into the hopper.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery for places in Elderhostel's first spring-summer
international listing was held in November, and for domestic
courses, Jan. 5. Programs in these listings that still have space
are open to registration, first come, first served. In this
situation, once you have an Elderhostel identification number,
registration through the Web on a business day between 9 a.m. and 9
p.m., Eastern time, is supposed to bring immediate confirmation if
there is space.
</P>
<P>
   The principal registrant for Elderhostel programs must be at
least 55; there is no age limit for an adult companion. This
organization's ``intergenerational'' programs usually involve a
child or grandchild under 25, and the program descriptions usually
indicate what age is appropriate. These adult-child programs can be
picked out on the Web site through the use of a search engine
there, and they are separately indexed in the paper catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Since Elderhostel stopped using Social Security numbers for
identification, catalogs normally arrive with randomly assigned
identification numbers. If there is no number, one may be obtained
through the Web during business hours. People getting their initial
information off the Web can also get a number electronically.
</P>
<P>
   An Elderhostel spokeswoman, Heather Baynes, said employees could
help applicants on the toll-free number, (877) 426-8056. All
applications by Internet, fax and phone require the use of a Visa,
Mastercard or American Express card.
</P>
<P>
   Interhostel, which usually offers only foreign travel, has
distributed its early summer catalog with 26 programs. Later
listings, for July into fall, will be mailed by the end of this
month; the information will also be on the Web site. These programs
are open to people over 50 and to their companions of at least 40.
</P>
<P>
   This organization breaks out its adult-child offerings into a
separate Familyhostel catalog for summer, which has been mailed.
The intended age for children here is 8 to 15; adults may be
parents or grandparents, but there must be at least one child and
one adult in each registration. There are 10 programs in this
catalog, plus the organization's first domestic trip, a New England
Sampler, with a base at the organization's home, the University of
New Hampshire, in Durham. This one is offered from July 11 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   Interhostel has no lottery for places, but accepts registrations
as it goes along. The Web site has a place to enter registration
information, including the number of the applicant's Visa,
Mastercard, Discover or American Express card. But people
submitting this material electronically should not assume that they
are registered until they get a phone call back from the
Interhostel office. According to Carol Bense, a spokeswoman, the
organization does not assume that applicants have read all the
rules and caveats until there is direct discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of trips listed in the catalogs. Space was
still available in the first week in January.
</P>
<P>
   _From April 25 to 30, Elderhostel at the Coastal Retreat Center
on the Isle of Palms near Charleston, S.C., is offering courses on
family history, Martin Luther and ``Diaries From Dixie'' from the
Civil War period, which covers the journals of Mary Boykin Chesnut
and two others. The cost is $420.
</P>
<P>
   _In New York, the American Institute of Banking and the South
Street Seaport are offering an Elderhostel course called
``Navigating Wall Street: Institutions at the Epicenter of World
Finance.'' This is offered May 6 to 11 and June 3 to 8. The
students stay in a hotel at the financial center; the fee is $575.
</P>
<P>
   _In Montana from June 6 to 26, an Elderhostel program is offered
at the Lewis and Clark Interpretive Center in Great Falls: ``Lewis
and Clark: Explorers at the Portage'' and ``Agriculture on the High
Plains.'' ``Strenuous program,'' the note on the explorers'
sessions says, ``the equivalent of two courses.'' The fee is $425.
</P>
<P>
   _Interhostel is offering a new program, the Villas of Rome and
Florence, from May 14 to 28, through the auspices of the Lorenzo de
Medici Institute. Five nights are spent in Florence, four in
Viterbo and four in Tivoli, with a one-day trip to Rome. With air
fare from Newark, meals and double-occupancy hotel rooms, this
costs $3,285.
</P>
<P>
   _A new Familyhostel trip is ``Spain and France: Basque Country
and Paris,'' offered June 29 to July 9 under the auspices of the
American University of Paris. The hotel in the Basque area is on
the beach at St.-Jean-de-Luz, and there are excursions into Bilbao
and San Sebastian. With air fare from Newark, the price for one of
two in a room ranges from $2,595 for a child 8 to 11 to $2,895 for
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Interhostel,  &LR;  University of New Hampshire Continuing
Education, 6 Garrison Ave., Durham, N.H. 03824; (800) 733-9753, fax
(603) 862-1113, www.learn.unh.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Elderhostel,  &LR;  a nonprofit educational organization, is at 75
Federal St., Boston, Mass. 02110; (877) 426-8056, toll-free fax
(877) 426-2166, www.elderhostel.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
