<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN, OF TWO MINDS, CONTEMPLATES CROMWELL  
 STANFORD TO REOPEN MUSEUM AFTER 10 YEARS  
 WILLY, NOW FREE, IS RECEIVING VISITORS  
 A LEGENDARY LEIPZIG COFFEEHOUSE REOPENS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17)  

</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 400th anniversary of the birth of Oliver Cromwell, one of
the most significant figures in British history, will be both
celebrated and investigated in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Cromwell headed the only republic that Britain ever had,
from 1653 to his death in 1658. Born in Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire,
in 1599, Cromwell, a landowner and local politician, rose to become
lord general of all the parliamentary forces in Britain's civil
wars of the 1640s.
</P>
<P>
   After the defeat of King Charles I, he became Lord Protector of
England, the head of state. Historians cannot agree whether
Cromwell was an ambitious tyrant in pursuit of power or a tolerant,
enlightened figure who sought to create a stronger and fairer
country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 museums and institutions plan to explore Cromwell's
legacy through exhibitions and events, and some of his major
battles will be re-enacted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the year's events are ``Cromwell: Warts
and All,'' an exhibition at the Museum of London through Feb. 28,
telephone (44-171) 600-3699; ``Cromwell Collections: Past, Present
and Future,'' at the Cromwell Museum in Huntingdon, near Cambridge,
April 1 to June 27, (44-1480) 375-830; and ``That Great Impostor,''
an exhibition examining Cromwell's image in literature and
politics, from April 26 to Sept. 30 at Sidney Sussex College,
Sidney Street, Cambridge, where Cromwell was a student, (44-1223)
338-800.
</P>
<P>
   On April 25, Cromwell's birthday, there will be a re-creation of
a 17th-century street market with traders, entertainment and
displays in Huntingdon, (44-1480) 388-057. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historical re-enactments will include a St. George's Day
Festival at Wrest Park Bedfordshire, 50 miles north of London, with
military displays on April 24 and 25. And one of the largest
historical events in Europe, including major re-creations of Civil
War battles, will take place at Kirby Hall, Northamptonshire, 80
miles north of London, on Aug. 14 and 15. Both will be staged by
English Heritage, (44-171) 973-3457. The Civil War Society will
present re-enactments and other activities at the Tower of London
from Oct. 24 to 31, (44-171) 709-0765. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: John Goldsmith, Museums Officer, Cambridgeshire
County Council, Heritage Services, Castle Court, Shire Hall,
Cambridge CB3 0AP; (44-1233) 718-136, or
www.cromwell.argonet.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University's renovated and expanded museum _ home to
the largest Rodin collection outside the Musee Rodin in Paris _
will reopen next Sunday after having been closed for nearly 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has been renamed the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor Center
for Visual Arts, in honor of the philanthropists who made major
donations to the $36.8 million project. The Cantors have also
contributed more than 180 Rodin works to Stanford. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When its original sandstone-colored neo-classical complex opened
in 1894, the Leland Stanford Junior Museum _ as it was then known _
rivaled in size the two great American museums of the time, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York and the Museum of Fine Arts
in Boston. But the 1906 San Francisco earthquake leveled all but
the central pavilion of the museum and set into motion years of
decline. After the Loma Prieta earthquake of 1989, the remaining
structure was closed as unsafe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old building has now been restored and a wing has been
added. With 21 indoor and outdoor galleries, the center can play
host to midsize traveling exhibitions, the first of which will
feature 120 Picasso prints from the Norton Simon Museum in
Pasadena, on view until March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Recent gifts and loans on view will include a large painted
concrete-and-resin figure by Claes Oldenburg, nine bronzes by
Willem de Kooning, and one of Richard Serra's massive Cor-Ten steel
works.
</P>
<P>
   The Cantor Arts Center is at Lomita Drive and Museum Way on the
Stanford University campus in Palo Alto. It is open Wednesday to
Sunday; admission is free. Information: (650) 723-4177.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the movie ``Free Willy.'' Now, you can see
Willy, on an Oceanic Society Expeditions tour. Keiko, a killer
whale whose confinement in a small tank in Mexico City inspired an
international rescue effort (and the movie), was returned this
summer to his original home _ the waters off Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, from May 30 to June 9, will include a visit to Keiko
in his natural sea pen (a netted-off enclosure that allows the
whale to interact with other marine life) off the Westmann
Islands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Willy may be free, but the trip isn't: it's $2,940 a person,
double occupancy, including air fare from New York, tours,
accommodations and meals (except for some dinners). Contact Oceanic
Society Expeditions, Fort Mason Center, Building E, San Francisco,
Calif. 94123; (800) 326-7491.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated Arabic Coffe Baum in Leipzig, Germany, reopened in
November after having been closed for seven years. Famous for the
artists and intellectuals who frequented it, including the
composers Richard Wagner and Robert Schumann, the Coffe Baum is,
along with the Procope in Paris, the birthplace of the European
coffee tradition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coffe Baum, or coffee tree, opened in 1720. It is named for
the Baroque relief above the portal: a sandstone carving showing a
Turk sitting under a coffee tree, passing a cup of coffee to a
cherub. It is said that August II (the Strong), Duke of Saxony,
drank coffee here. Schumann had a regular table, and Gotthold
Ephraim Lessing, the German playwright and critic, was another
influential guest. Others included Liszt, Goethe and the
turn-of-the-century artist Max Klinger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the first time visitors may explore the entire four-story
building, where many rooms are themed. In the Schumann Room, for
instance, there is a portrait of Schumann from 1828, when he
visited the Coffe Baum for the first time. This sober, ground-floor
room is paneled in dark wood guests are served on bare acorn
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional red velvet booths and mirrors decorate the Viennese
Cafe, and the walls of the Lehmann Room (named for the original
owners, who ran it first as a guesthouse in the late 1600s) are
hung with portraits of the most famous guests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coffee Museum covers the history of coffee culture in Saxony
from the 18th to the 20th century, and displays Arabian coffee
vessels, a collection of coffee cups, the steps in roasting coffee
and typical coffeehouse games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A choice of coffees is offered on the second floor. Regular
espresso costs $2, a melange $2.25, and the specialty coffee called
August the Strong is $6. Pastries and full meals are served on the
third floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum and cafe, at 4 Kleine Fleischergasse in Leipzig,
(49-341) 961-0060, are open 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.; admission is free.
For tours, call the city museum, (49-341) 965-1321 or (49-341)
965-1323.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
