</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TALK TO PALESTINIAN COUNCIL, PERES BACKS NEW STATE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (Eds: See also ISRAEL-POLITICS) 
(jw) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Far from the nasty bickering of the
Israeli election campaign, Shimon Peres, the former Israeli prime
minister, swept into Ramallah Monday with a covey of fellow Nobel
Peace Prize winners to promote his vision of peace, delivering the
first address by an Israeli to the Palestinian legislative council.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene evocative of the good will that accompanied peace
efforts when Peres was prime minister, he was given a warm ovation
by council members after he expressed support for an independent
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our deep hope that the Palestinian people will gain
independence,'' Peres, an architect of the 1993 Oslo accords on
interim Palestinian self-rule, told the council. ``It is our common
interest to see a Palestinian state taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Palestinian state as a result of an agreement,'' Peres
added, alluding to statements by Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, that he reserves the right to declare statehood on May 4,
when talks on a permanent peace are supposed to end under the Oslo
accords. ``An agreement will take place about a Palestinian
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience included several foreign statesmen who had arrived
with Peres. Their presence was a reminder of the broad
international support Israel maintained under Peres' leadership,
when he pressed ahead with peace efforts that have in effect been
suspended by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The guests included former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
Archbishop Desmond Tutu and former President F.W. de Klerk of South
Africa, as well as former Egyptian Prime Minister Mustafa Khalil,
who helped negotiate the Camp David peace accords in 1978. All are
members of the international board of governors of the Peres Center
for Peace, which promotes cooperative projects involving Arabs and
Israelis. The board traveled here Monday as part of its second
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Peres, the gray-haired former leaders seemed like a
group of peace pensioners _ no longer in power, but still wielding
moral authority. ``They take on the aura and role of a collective
conscience, and they do make a difference,'' said Hanan Ashrawi, a
Palestinian legislator.
</P>
<P>
   After the council meeting, the visitors met with Arafat, the
only Nobel Prize winner present who is still governing. Peres
greeted him warmly, kissing him on both cheeks, and compared him to
Israel's first prime minister and state-builder, David Ben-Gurion.
``As an Israeli, I pray and wish for your success,'' Peres said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat responded with a policy speech, his first detailed
response to the freezing of the latest Israeli-Palestinian accord
by Netanyahu ahead of national elections set for May 17. Netanyahu
contends the Palestinians have failed to meet their commitments
under the accord, which was signed in Washington on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot understand how in political, legal or constitutional
terms one can freeze international agreements approved legally by
an elected parliament once one engages in domestic elections,''
Arafat said. ``Are they going to stop the peace process with Egypt?
Are they going to stop the peace process with Jordan?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Nobody can freeze life and its essential requirements for six
months,'' Arafat added. ``Further erosion of peace under the
pretext of elections should never be permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a possible declaration of statehood on May 4, Arafat told
a reporter that it was ``still under discussion,'' and he was vague
about it in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are important dates that cannot be ignored, bypassed or
let slide without proper accounting and a proper decision,'' Arafat
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coming of May 4 is one of these important dates,'' he
added. ``We cannot bypass that date simply because one of the
parties wants to keep it hostage to its narrow domestic
calculations.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat asserts that he is free to declare statehood on May 4,
because that is when talks on a permanent peace are supposed to end
under the Oslo accords. Netanyahu has called such a declaration a
breach of the accords, which require negotiations to reach a final
settlement. He has warned that Israel will annex parts of the West
Bank if Arafat proclaims a state.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., who joined Peres and spoke to the
legislative council, warned Palestinians against a unilateral
declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli elections will take place on May 17,'' he said.
``Don't do anything on the fourth of May, because all hell will
break loose, and all of your advantages and gains will go down the
drain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
