<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-PROFIT-COX     01-11 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-PROFIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An Atlanta firm offers words, likeness of Martin Luther King
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (l) lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. had a dream, but who
knew the late civil rights leader would one day have his own music
CDs, an MTV special and a star-studded animated feature?
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years after his assassination, an Atlanta-based
company called Intellectual Properties Management is merchandising
the martyr with a line of products hailed by some as a savvy
business venture, but criticized by some King stalwarts for
commercializing his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In a multimedia strategy timed to coincide with the King
holiday, IPM and 20th Century Fox Home Entertainment today are
unveiling ``Our Friend, Martin,'' a direct-to-video cartoon movie
featuring the voices of Whoopi Goldberg, Angela Bassett, James Earl
Jones, John Travolta and Susan Sarandon.
</P>
<P>
   IPM also teamed up with R&AMP;B music label Motown to release a
soundtrack with performances by such diverse acts as Sheryl Crow,
Salt-N-Pepa, Montell Jordan and Brian McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, MTV will chronicle King in its rock 'n' roll
documentary series ``BIOrhythm,'' which also has profiled slain
rapper Tupac Shakur and Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is the best way to re-introduce King to young
people who speak a totally different language than just a
generation ago,'' said Phillip Jones, the chief executive officer
of IPM, which has an exclusive agreement with the King family to
manage the marketing of King's words and likeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of young people in a contemporary paradigm is
MTV, the Internet and interactive learning. The information
revolution has changed the way they think, and we have to change
the way we convey his message.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the video and CD comes two years after Jones
forged a multimillion-dollar publishing deal with Warner Books, a
subsidiary of Time-Warner. The partnership has resulted in five
books, including a new ``autobiography,'' actually written by
Clayborne Carson, editor of the King Papers Project at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   There's more coming, including King-related Web sites; an
autobiography by King's widow, Coretta Scott King; and a memoir by
King's youngest son, Dexter, president of the Martin Luther King
Jr. Center for Non-Violent Social Change and a Morehouse College
chum of Jones'.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jones nor his corporate partners would discuss financial
details of their various projects or how profits and royalties are
being distributed between IPM and the King estate. Jones said
revenues will be plowed back into the King Center to continue its
work. Dexter King and Coretta King could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Matlock, president and CEO of Matlock &AMP; Associates, the
public relations firm that advises the King family, lauds Jones for
reviving King's message while providing a potential windfall for
the cash-strapped King Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``King's message is just as important today and just as relevant
as it was 30 years ago,'' Matlock said. ``Phillip has been smart
and creative enough to figure out how to keep King's message and
his dream alive without exploiting it. He's extremely focused and
dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   But the marketing plans approved by the family and implemented
by IPM are part of a larger controversy over whether King's legacy
is property owned by his family or whether he is such a national
icon that his work belongs to history.
</P>
<P>
   IPM and the estate remain fiercely protective of rights to
King's work. In two high-profile cases, the estate has challenged
news organizations over their use of King's words. The estate sued
USA Today for printing the ``I Have a Dream'' speech without
permission, dropping the suit in 1993 after the paper agreed to pay
a fee. In July, the King estate lost a copyright infringement
lawsuit it filed against CBS News, which aired a documentary about
the 1963 March on Washington. That case is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones maintains that King purposely copyrighted his work while
he was alive, a clear indication he intended his heirs to reap any
financial benefits it might generate after his death.
</P>
<P>
   But other King confidantes are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have unquestionable love and respect for the King family,
but the thing that gets me is the kids trying to make money from
his memory,'' said the Rev. Hosea Williams, one of King's closest
aides. ``They were so young when he was murdered and do not know
the same Martin Luther King Jr. that I knew. He never let us put a
price tag on anything he did. He would have approved of
distributing his message, but he would never have accepted a dime
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Orange, a trusted King lieutenant, has not seen
the merchandise that IPM has released, but says he's concerned that
it may detract attention from King's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``His spirit wasn't about money, his spirit was about helping
the least of these and all of God's children,'' Orange says.
</P>
<P>
   Much of King's work is copyrighted, which means it is generally
protected from being used by others without his consent. There are
limited exceptions, such as a news organization that disseminates
copyrighted information as part of its coverage, says Michael
Landau, an associate professor at Georgia State University who
specializes in intellectual property issues.
</P>
<P>
   The King estate's efforts to define King's image has extended
into other areas. In 1995, the King family and the National Park
Service butted heads over competing plans to build a new King
exhibit, a dispute that resulted in the family temporarily banning
the park service from giving tours of King's birth home. The family
drew criticism that it was trying to turn the historic site into a
gimmicky theme park, a charge Jones and the Kings have denied. Both
sides eventually worked out their differences _ the Park Service
opened an $11 million visitors center in 1996, and the family's
plans for an interactive exhibit of its own are on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Jones says many of his critics don't understand that IPM's
marketing efforts represent the next chapter in the civil rights
movement: the battle for economic independence.
</P>
<P>
   An entrepreneur with ``a hip-hop sensibility,'' Jones speaks
passionately about the Kings' ``moral courage.'' In the next breath
he's comparing himself to DreamWorks SKG movie mogul Jeffrey
Katzenberg and rhapsodizing about corporate synergies that enable
media conglomerates such as Time-Warner and Disney to retain
control over products they create.
</P>
<P>
   Rakishly handsome, Jones dresses in the latest BCBG fashion
eyewear, drives a black Mercedes-Benz convertible and is fond of
clothing by FUBU, a ubiquitous African-American designer whose logo
is an acronym for ``For Us, By Us.'' He won't reveal his age, but
associates say he's in his early 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also is part owner of the now defunct Atlanta Live dance
club in Buckhead, once a favorite hangout for celebrities and
wannabes. The club is being relocated to Bankhead Highway, and the
new site is undergoing a $1 million renovation in hopes of opening
in late February. In addition to projects developed with the King
estate, Jones also is trying to sell several television series,
including a Saturday morning cartoon and a black prime-time soap
opera.
</P>
<P>
   Jones sees no contradiction in melding '60s social activism with
brashly aggressive marketing techniques of the '90s as a way of
reaching a generation of people who may consider King's life a
stale history lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following the plan that Dr. King left for us,'' says
Jones, in his office at the King Center. ``If Dr. King were alive,
he'd be on the Internet, and he'd approve of computers. I feel I'm
a man of my time, and I'm using my special talents to create new
products, images and works of art that can inspire and educate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
