<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-VIDEO-COX     01-11 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-VIDEO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A-list stars, savvy effects propel cartoon
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (l) lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few flesh-and-blood actors have re-created the
commanding presence of the late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
on-screen, and few TV writers have bothered coming up with story
lines about the slain civil rights leader that appeal to adults and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Friend, Martin,'' a direct-to-video movie debuting today
in retail outlets, clears both hurdles (mostly) with a 'toon
version of King. It's got a little of something for everybody,
including the voices of a multiracial A-list Hollywood cast, a plot
reminiscent of ``Back to the Future'' and ``Forrest Gump''-style
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   The movie centers on a black Atlanta sixth-grader named Miles;
his white best friend, Randy; their overachieving Latina
schoolmate, Maria; and an overweight white bully, Kyle. During a
class trip to King's birth home on Auburn Avenue, they are
magically transported back in time to key moments in King's life,
from his baseball-loving boyhood to the civil rights marches he led
across the Jim Crow South.
</P>
<P>
   What's most striking about ``Martin'' is the use of still
photography and sepia-toned stock footage blended seamlessly with
the animated characters. At one point, Miles and Randy are seen
cheering among the crowd of actual participants in the 1963 March
on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The racial hatred of the '60s is wisely toned down for younger
viewers, although it includes scenes of cops directingfirehoses and
sicking dogs on young marchers. The N-word is never used, but
derogatory references to African-American characters as
``coloreds'' and ``you people'' hint at the raw prejudices of the
era.
</P>
<P>
   LeVar Burton gives voice to the young King, then passes the
microphone to King's real-life son Dexter, who on occasion can
summon the same chest-rattling cadence that became his father's
oratorical trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Adults already familiar with the story may catch themselves
playing who's who with the cartoon cast. Whoopi Goldberg's soulful
rasp is easily recognizable as the voice of Mrs. Peck, the kindly
tour guide. And James Earl Jones as Daddy King is a no-brainer. But
it gets trickier trying to figure out which characters are voiced
by Ed Asner, Danny Glover, Angela Bassett, Oprah Winfrey, Samuel L.
Jackson and John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   While it's heavy-handed in spots, ``Our Friend, Martin'' is a
kid-friendly video for younger viewers who may be hearing King's
enduring message of racial tolerance for the first time, and a
reminder for older viewers who may have forgotten it.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-VIDEO-COX     01-11 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-VIDEO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A-list stars, savvy effects propel cartoon
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (l) lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few flesh-and-blood actors have re-created the
commanding presence of the late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
on-screen, and few TV writers have bothered coming up with story
lines about the slain civil rights leader that appeal to adults and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Friend, Martin,'' a direct-to-video movie debuting today
in retail outlets, clears both hurdles (mostly) with a 'toon
version of King. It's got a little of something for everybody,
including the voices of a multiracial A-list Hollywood cast, a plot
reminiscent of ``Back to the Future'' and ``Forrest Gump''-style
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   The movie centers on a black Atlanta sixth-grader named Miles;
his white best friend, Randy; their overachieving Latina
schoolmate, Maria; and an overweight white bully, Kyle. During a
class trip to King's birth home on Auburn Avenue, they are
magically transported back in time to key moments in King's life,
from his baseball-loving boyhood to the civil rights marches he led
across the Jim Crow South.
</P>
<P>
   What's most striking about ``Martin'' is the use of still
photography and sepia-toned stock footage blended seamlessly with
the animated characters. At one point, Miles and Randy are seen
cheering among the crowd of actual participants in the 1963 March
on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The racial hatred of the '60s is wisely toned down for younger
viewers, although it includes scenes of cops directingfirehoses and
sicking dogs on young marchers. The N-word is never used, but
derogatory references to African-American characters as
``coloreds'' and ``you people'' hint at the raw prejudices of the
era.
</P>
<P>
   LeVar Burton gives voice to the young King, then passes the
microphone to King's real-life son Dexter, who on occasion can
summon the same chest-rattling cadence that became his father's
oratorical trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Adults already familiar with the story may catch themselves
playing who's who with the cartoon cast. Whoopi Goldberg's soulful
rasp is easily recognizable as the voice of Mrs. Peck, the kindly
tour guide. And James Earl Jones as Daddy King is a no-brainer. But
it gets trickier trying to figure out which characters are voiced
by Ed Asner, Danny Glover, Angela Bassett, Oprah Winfrey, Samuel L.
Jackson and John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   While it's heavy-handed in spots, ``Our Friend, Martin'' is a
kid-friendly video for younger viewers who may be hearing King's
enduring message of racial tolerance for the first time, and a
reminder for older viewers who may have forgotten it.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
