<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKAMERICA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK PRESIDENT VOWS TO REACH OUT TO WEST COAST CUSTOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ One of the favorite paintings of Bank of
America chief executive Hugh McColl is a commissioned work titled
``Take The Money And Run.'' It shows the bad guys making their
getaway from a bank called ``Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, McColl's former NationsBank Corp. merged with
Republic Bank of Texas in 1988, setting off a wave of acquisitions
that culminated with the marriage to San Francisco's BankAmerica
Corp. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   McColl smiles as he gazes upon the painting, but his Old South
conviviality and hospitality are bundled with a deadly serious
competitive business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlotte has always been about business and nothing else,''
said McColl, 63, smoothly shifting gears from discussing art to the
business at hand: making the San Francisco merger work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything in our power to make this a
successful merger,'' McColl said recently in a wide-ranging
interview in the gleaming 60-story bank headquarters in Charlotte.
``I want it to be the best place to work, best place to do business
and the company that matters the most to its communities, and that
is exactly what I am about, and I'm going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl is the chairman and chief executive of BankAmerica Corp.,
the parent corporation of Bank of America, which now serves 22
states.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to California this week, he will try to alleviate
post-merger fears and the perception that the new Charlotte-based
institution is insensitive to its California customers.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank seeks to grow rapidly, McColl said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of NationsBank and BankAmerica, announced last spring
and finalized in the fall, was quickly followed by sharp criticism
as San Francisco grappled with losing one of its oldest corporate
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected resignation of former BankAmerica chairman and
chief executive David Coulter, McColl's heir-apparent, created only
further distrust. This was compounded by the post-merger departure
of several top women executives, which was perceived to be the
result of a less-than-supportive atmosphere for diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in San Francisco and California quickly demanded that
the new bank disclose whether it would maintain its commitments to
diversity and lending to minority communities and threatened a
review of government accounts managed by BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   McColl's trip to the West Coast is an effort to turn around what
has become a public relations fiasco for the merged bank.
</P>
<P>
   McColl is considered a progressive here, and his Charlotte
supporters say McColl has a long-held commitment to diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, McColl supported a black candidate for mayor. And
last year, he helped defeat four of the five members of the
Mecklenburg County Commission who voted to cut $5 million for
Charlotte's arts programs to demonstrate disapproval of the
Charlotte Repertory Theatre's production of a play with gay themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my career I've judged people on results ... and I
certainly don't care what their lifestyle choices are,'' McColl
said. ``Within the law we did everything possible (contributing
money to defeat the group of five), and those of us individually
contributed tons of money. I was inflamed. It was bad for the city
and narrow-minded.'' Four of the five were defeated in re-election
bids.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, McColl has applied the same unabashed approach
to building a banking empire. His pride in that growth, he and his
Charlotte friends insist, is rooted in a belief that diversity is
his bank's salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The news reports in San Francisco that the merger revealed a
cultural divide that caused women executives to leave and the
perception that a Charlotte-based parent company cannot appreciate
California's social and business values have stung McColl
personally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot written about eight or 10 people who have
left the company and very little written about the 170,000 people
who work here,'' he said. ``One would have thought that logic would
say to people that NationsBank could not have become what was the
second largest bank in the U.S. through a series of mergers _ which
is more than 600 different banking companies _ if they did not have
an environment in which talented people could succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond perception, the political repercussions of the criticism
could cost the new bank business.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors have
questioned whether the city, Bank of America's major customer in
Northern California, should continue doing business with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Other political figures also have questioned the new bank's
commitment to community reinvestment.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the barbed reaction to the aftermath of the merger
there is a sense of seller's remorse in California _ lament that
the old Bank of America, which gave Walt Disney his first $100 loan
and sold the bonds to build the Golden Gate Bridge, has slipped
away.
</P>
<P>
   McColl said he wants to build a united but diverse bank that
will serve California well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be responsive to California and to
California's needs. In fact, we will take more risk than the old
Bank of America did,'' he said..
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now one company, and all the new teammates who come to
our company I view the same way that I view the people who came
from Texas, Missouri, Florida or wherever. This may be a foreign
concept to some people, but it's just the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl derided the perception that a macho climate permeates the
Bank of America, that some women are unwelcome or uncomfortable in
a company where the chief executive, a Marine veteran, rewards high
performers with toy hand grenades.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this company is is demanding,'' McColl said. ``It is
results-oriented. It measures people on results only. And facts. It
does not deal with fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The glint that so often shimmers in his blue eyes momentarily
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people find that environment very threatening,'' he went
on. ``Others find it extremely rewarding, and we pay well for
people who produce results. Am I aggressive? Am I ambitious, all
those things? Absolutely. But that does not include destroying the
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McColl's lack of specifics on the allocation of philanthropic
contributions and community reinvestment money _ federal law
requires banks to serve all segments of their service areas without
excluding low or moderate income or minority areas _ is still the
No. 1 issue for merger critics in California.
</P>
<P>
   John Gamboa, executive director of the San Francisco-based
Greenlining Institute, a nonprofit advocacy center that seeks
greater access to capital, jobs and credit for low-income and
minority groups, asked the Federal Reserve in a Dec. 29 letter for
additional public hearings into the merger. He said they would
``demonstrate that the initial supporters of the acquisition were
misled and no longer support the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl said the reason he wouldn't cite specifics about
community reinvestment was to maintain flexibility to serve
individual regions and neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   McColl added that the bank would be more than generous in
philanthropic spending and would shift some contributions from
colleges and universities to early childhood education and cultural
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arts are important in civilizing a society,'' he said.
``They make us come together, from different socioeconomic levels,
and this impresses upon us the worth of mankind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
