<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOPPARD-BARD-ART-2TA     01-11 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOPPARD-BARD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: TOM STOPPARD IN LOVE, WITH SHAKESPEARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MEL GUSSOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Tom Stoppard completes an arc that
began in 1967 with ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' his
first produced stage play. Taken in the context of the playwright's
other work, the two are primary instances of Stoppard in love _
with Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   As he has said, ``Rosencrantz'' is a play about ``Hamlet'' as
seen by two people, both outsiders to the court, ``driving past
Elsinore'' and wondering what is happening in the state of Denmark.
Serving as an involuntary act of criticism, the play also deals
with what Shakespeare left out of ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love,'' a film with a screenplay by Stoppard
and Marc Norman, is about how Shakespeare wrote ``Romeo and
Juliet,'' or, rather, how he should have written ``Romeo and
Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing a monumental writer's block and unable to finish a work
titled ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter,'' the movie's
Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) is also lovelorn until he meets Viola
de Lesseps (Gwyneth Paltrow), a wealthy lady who desperately wants
poetry in her life and joins Shakespeare's company disguised as a
man.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of having a writer, especially a real one, as the
protagonist of a movie or a play is fraught with pitfalls. Van Gogh
can paint; Mozart can compose (and we can hear the music), but how
does one dramatize the act of writing? Think of the movie ``Dr.
Zhivago,'' when Omar Sharif stared out a window and thought of Lara
and then magically, and unconvincingly, began to write.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the success of ``Shakespeare in Love'' is the intensity
of Fiennes' performance, for example, in the scene in which he
practices writing his signature. The quill pen dives into the ink
pot and then crackles on parchment. Or the swiftness with which the
director, John Madden, moves from the writing to the rehearsal of
the play, underlining the immediacy and the spontaneity of
Shakespeare's art.
</P>
<P>
   Should the screenwriter use the author's words? That question is
answered here with an emphatic affirmative. Quotations from
Shakespeare are artfully inserted so that they seem like common
speech, as in a minister's overheard threat, ``A plague on both
your houses.'' This Shakespeare is always listening, as Trigorin
does in ``The Seagull,'' storing lines away for future use.
</P>
<P>
   In passing he profits from a seemingly casual barroom tip from
his rival, Christopher Marlowe, who suggests that he consider using
the plot device of two warring families. Wisely, Shakespeare
removes all piratical references and changes the title to ``Romeo
and Juliet.'' The ``real life'' story seen on screen is filled with
parallels to the play, starting with the fact that both pairs of
lovers are star-crossed.
</P>
<P>
   One striking difference between ``Shakespeare in Love'' and
``Rosencrantz'' _and most of Stoppard's other work _ is that the
movie is unabashedly a love story. In the past it has often been
said that his plays were intellectually dazzling but that he
averted his eyes (and his pen) in matters of romance.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally lust entered his realm, as in ``Dirty Linen,'' his
mischievous mockery of Parliamentary sexual shenanigans in Britain,
as timely today as it was in 1976. With ``The Real Thing'' in 1981
he began shedding more of his inhibitions. In that play the leading
character, himself a playwright presumably speaking for the author,
said that whenever he tried to write a play about love, it came out
``embarrassing, childish and rude.'' But at least the character
could talk about his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of ``Indian Ink'' in 1995, Stoppard approached the
subject more forthrightly, conjuring a wistful romance between an
English poet and an Indian artist in the 1930s. That play, which is
scheduled to have its United States premiere in February at the
American Conservatory Theater in San Francisco, has a nude scene,
the first in a Stoppard work since ``Jumpers.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new movie, he fully embraces love's comedy and drama. The
character of Shakespeare is overcome by his passion, putting
himself and Viola in jeopardy as they pursue their ardent
courtship. Love proves to be creatively invigorating. Soon he is
rushing from the lady's bedchamber to his desk, plunging into his
play while also dashing off sonnets to Viola _ no Dark Lady _
comparing her to a summer's day. She becomes his muse: Viola as
Juliet and Shakespeare as Romeo inspire the play.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Rosencrantz,'' the movie is both Stoppardian and
Shakespearean, which is to say it is an antic original but also
respectful of its source. In effect ``Shakespeare in Love'' treats
``Romeo and Juliet'' as ``Rosencrantz'' did ``Hamlet,'' as a
necessary subplot. In each case Stoppard plays fair with
Shakespeare, although in the movie he takes literary license with
his life. With so little information available, he could be freely
inventive.
</P>
<P>
   In the years between ``Rosencrantz'' and ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' he has often drawn from reality, especially when dealing
with literary matters. ``Travesties'' cross-pollinated events in
the lives of James Joyce and Tristan Tzara with a performance of
Oscar Wilde's ``Importance of Being Earnest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde himself makes a cameo appearance in ``The Invention of
Love,'' Stoppard's latest play, an imaginative exploration of the
life and philosophy of A.E. Housman. A central theme of that work
is Housman's thwarted love for a Cambridge classmate, a passion
that generated the author's most deeply felt poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Another writer on Stoppard's landscape is Arthur Schnitzler. He
has adapted several of Schnitzler's plays, most notably
``Undiscovered Country,'' which is Shakespearean both in its title
(taken from ``Hamlet'') and its scope. In ``Arcadia,'' a crucial
offstage role is played by Lord Byron, who was once a guest in the
house that is the play's setting.
</P>
<P>
   Neither in his art nor his mien could Stoppard be described as
Byronesque. But because he is a playwright of ideas, he has been
called Shavian. As an artist he bears a debt to Samuel Beckett and
as a reader and book collector he has a particular fondness for the
work of Ernest Hemingway. More than anyone else, however,
Shakespeare remains his master.
</P>
<P>
   One should not forget his middle careering of ``Dogg's Hamlet,
``Cahoot's Macbeth,'' interrelated plays. The first was written to
be presented on a double-decker London bus, the second a living
room ``Macbeth'' as it might have been staged in Prague during the
years of Soviet repression.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the core of ``Dogg's Hamlet'' is a hilarious 15-minute
version of ``Hamlet'' that cuts Shakespeare to the quick. It is a
gauntlet tossed in the faces of those who favor the fuller length.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dogg's Hamlet,'' Shakespeare, appearing for the first time
as a character in a work by Stoppard, delivers the Prologue,
running ``Something is rotten'' right into ``To be, or not to be,
that is the question.'' Later, when Hamlet refrains, ``To be, or
not to be,'' Ophelia rudely interrupts him and he responds,
posthaste, ``Get thee to a nunnery.''
</P>
<P>
   After this condensation there is a breathless 90-second encore
in which ``To be'' is not to be, and there are exclamations rather
than questions.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Stoppard takes a more leisurely
approach, opening up his story to include the world of Elizabethan
theater: its factionalism, chicanery, self-interest and rigidity.
Periodically, Stoppard has touched on theatrical matters: the play
within the play in ``The Real Thing'' and in ``The Real Inspector
Hound.'' But in ``Shakespeare in Love'' the theater is center
stage, and all contemporary resonances are intentional, as when an
actor asks a producer his identity and the man replies, ``I'm the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth herself, as incarnated by Judi Dench, proves to
be a figure of surprising liberality, at least in the arena of
theater and romance. In addition to Marlowe, John Webster is in the
lineup as a youth with a sadistic streak, and there is more than a
hint that the lady Viola will inspire a future Shakespearean
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was Norman's idea. Other than that, the division of
labor between the two screenwriters is not specified. But the
dialogue has the linguistic limberness of Stoppard at his wittiest,
as when Shakespeare persuades the actor Ned Alleyn to play Mercutio
by telling him that his is the title role. Or when confronted with
a crisis, the woeful company manager (Geoffrey Rush) says, ``The
show must ... you know.'' Shakespeare urges him to finish his
sentence, ``go on.''
</P>
<P>
   As his authorial signature the playwright has infiltrated his
work with references to characters named Boot and Moon. In ``The
Real Inspector Hound,'' Birdboot is a first-string drama critic,
Moon one of the second string, and they are soon caught up onstage
in a spoof of an Agatha Christie thriller. There are no Boots or
Moons in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' although in what might be
considered a Stoppard note, the film begins with Rush having his
booted feet burned by an angry creditor. In the place of critics,
there is Simon Callow as the imperious Master of Revels, and the
Queen herself is withering in her criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Stoppard has also managed to insert the name Chamberlain into
almost all his plays. Like Alfred Hitchcock, Chamberlain wanders
onstage (as a member of the British Parliament in ``Dirty Linen'')
or remains just offstage (a man in a taxi in ``Hapgood''). The
mention is a tip of the writer's hat to his secretary, who was a
Chamberlain before she married. He once explained that he put the
name in to wake her up when she was typing his manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   To one's knowledge, his movies (``Despair,'' ``Empire of the
Sun'' and others) have been Chamberlain-free, until ``Shakespeare
in Love.'' The reference fits very naturally into the movie because
Richard Burbage's acting troupe was known as Chamberlain's Men. One
actor in that company, a hopeful playwright, was, of course,
William Shakespeare, brought vibrantly to life in Stoppard's new
film.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
