<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAR-THEATER-REVIEW-AR     01-11 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAR-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAR EAST': A POIGNANT BUT UNEVEN POSTWAR ROMANCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis., R.I.)   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Sparky Watts first shows up at a naval base
outside Tokyo in ``Far East,'' A.R. Gurney's uneven but poignant
new play at Lincoln Center, his future is in his face. It's an open
face, transfused with that raw hopefulness often seen in young men
starting the first chapter of their adulthood. Yet there is also a
trace of anxiety, of defensiveness in his eager smile, a sense that
whatever hopes he may harbor are somehow already under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Sparky, played with winningly eloquent awkwardness by Michael
Hayden, speaks with the cocky confidence and reflexive air of
entitlement that belong to children of affluent, old-line American
families, the kind of WASP clans that Gurney has always written
about. He is also, very clearly, a prisoner of these very traits
and knows it.
</P>
<P>
   What Sparky seeks in the exotic realm of the play's title is
transformation, the abandonment of a claustrophobic social
identity. His fears that he will never achieve this are what make
him interesting, and you can sometimes read in his expressions the
anticipation of regrets of a lifetime to come.
</P>
<P>
   Regret is Gurney's specialty, and it is what has given his plays
an emotional clout beyond their status as brittle comedies of
upper-middle-class manners. From early works like ``Children'' to
``Later Life,'' his 1993 variation on Henry James' short
masterpiece on lost opportunities, ``The Beast in the Jungle,''
this dramatist has created a gallery of wistful characters for whom
class is destiny. Even his most defiant rebels, the ne'er-do-well
son of ``The Middle Ages'' or the autobiographical playwright of
``The Cocktail Hour,'' remain tethered by their roots.
</P>
<P>
   For Gurney, as well as his alter ego Sparky, ``Far East,'' which
opened Monday night at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater in an
impeccably realized production, represents a serious bid for escape
from the world that has defined him. Throughout his career, the
author has been criticized for working on too small a canvas, for
creating mere tempests in martini glasses. Here, he tries hard to
extend his thematic reach, to find in Sparky's coming of age a
mirror for the U.S. rediscovery of itself after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1954, the play centers on Sparky's love affair with a
Japanese woman, a romance inspired by events in Gurney's life and
previously alluded to in his ``Middle Ages'' and ``Love Letters.''
``Far East'' turns this admittedly familiar situation into an
opportunity to consider such hefty subjects as U.S. involvement in
both Korea and Vietnam, homosexuality in the military,
life-sacrificing espionage and Eastern vs. Western notions of
femininity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of weight to place upon the play's slender,
gracefully sloped shoulders, and the evening is least satisfying
when it self-consciously announces its political significance. It
should also be noted that in embracing the cliches of
soldier-in-love dramas common to postwar films like ``From Here to
Eternity'' and ``Sayonara,'' Gurney doesn't always transcend them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is good in ``Far East,'' especially the scenes
portraying Sparky's ambivalent friendship with an officer's wife
(played to perfection by Lisa Emery), is as good as anything Gurney
has written and a vast improvement over his recent, clunky
``Overtime'' and ``Labor Day.'' Like its hero, ``Far East'' never
quite becomes what it wants to be. Under Daniel Sullivan's
first-rate direction, however, the production is a welcome reminder
of the appeal of its author's gliding dialogue and structural
elegance, as well as of the troubled, rueful heart that informs all
of Gurney's work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the evening is delicious. The set designer Thomas
Lynch has created a scenic poem of cultural conflict, with
backdrops that evoke the fine-lined delicacy of traditional
Japanese art, corrupted by signs of a nascent Western invasion. Pay
special attention to the witty representation of a golf course near
Tokyo. The look of the show, moreover, reflects the very form of
the play, which incorporates touches of Noh theater in telling
Sparky's story.
</P>
<P>
   A single performer (Sonnie Brown) in traditional Japanese
costume sits on an elevated platform, reading the dialogue of minor
characters and signaling changes of scene with a sweeping clack of
two blocks of wood. She also implicitly represents the girl whom
Sparky, a Milwaukee brewery heir and naval reserve officer fresh
from officer's training school in Newport, R.I., meets and falls in
love with, a character we get to know only through discussion of
her by others.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown defines a cultural element that is in effect the
proverbial China shop, suddenly invaded by a herd of shortsighted
American bulls. These invaders include Capt. James Anderson (Bill
Smitrovich), Sparky's commanding officer, who is still mourning the
loss of a son in the Korean War, and his wife, Julia (Ms. Emery), a
former Voice of America employee who remains a self-styled American
voice, reminding her husband's men of what they left behind, by
organizing weenie roasts, dance classes and tennis matches. There
is also Bob Munger (Connor Trinneer), Sparky's roommate, a nervous
young man with a droll manner and obvious ambivalence about being
in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Ambivalence is the keynote of each of these characters, who
desire to be something other than what they are and are troubled by
a concomitant sense of bad faith. Sparky is tested in different
ways and to varyingly successful dramatic effect by the claims of
each of these three other people in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Smitrovich and Trinneer both turn in fine, understated
performances, but they bear the ungainly brunt of the most
blatantly political aspects of the play. It's when Sparky faces off
with Julia, in a pas de deux of mutual attraction and irritation,
that ``Far East'' flies. Julia, it turns out, comes from a
background similar to Sparky's and knows one of his relatives. She
is the siren call of everything Sparky is running from. She is also
determined, from very mixed motives, to sabotage the young man's
relationship with the Japanese woman with whom he has set up house.
</P>
<P>
   Julia is by far the play's most fully drawn character, and Ms.
Emery is absolutely splendid in the role, giving her levels of
shading that go beyond the script. Her voice filtered through a
high-WASP lockjaw that somehow avoids caricature, her body a study
in angular composure, she is a knotty mixture of determination and
inhibition, of witty, self-aware intelligence and instinctive
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   When she and Hayden execute a cha-cha in a dance class at the
officer's club, you know that something dangerous is happening and
not just because of the suggested erotic attraction. Each knows
what the other really is, and their similarities will be what undo
their respective attempts to get beyond what they have come from.
Far East is clearly not far enough for these refugees from the WASP
nest, and the scene hums with a subliminal resonance that says far
more about the American character than the play's shorthand
discussions of war, police actions and political betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible, of course, not to think of that other restless
officer's wife played so memorably by Deborah Kerr in ``From Here
to Eternity,'' a movie which, by the way, is alluded to in ``Far
East.'' Julia, of course, is never going to find herself lying in
an adulterous embrace in a bathing suit on a beach as the waves
wash over her.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in which Gurney tantalizingly raises the possibility
of such a thing happening, however, is priceless, a seduction
botched by good manners. It is a sterling example of what this
playwright does best: finding boundless, tragicomic wistfulness in
people of unconquerable limitations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAR EAST'
</P>
<P>
   By A.R. Gurney; directed by Daniel Sullivan; sets by Thomas
Lynch; costumes by Jess Goldstein; lighting by Rui Rita; original
music and sound by Dan Moses Schreier; stage manager, Roy Harris.
Presented by Lincoln Center Theater, under the direction of Andre
Bishop and Bernard Gersten. At the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater,
Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   With: Michael Hayden (``Sparky'' Watts), Bill Smitrovich (James
Anderson), Lisa Emery (Julia), Connor Trinneer (Bob Munger), Mia
Tagano and Toshiro Akira Yamamoto (Stagehands) and Sonnie Brown
(Reader).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
