</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELLSOUP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICE FALLS AS CAMPBELL SOUP ANNOUNCES DROP IN EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blaming the weather for sluggish sales of its biggest brand, the
Campbell Soup Co. warned Monday that its earnings in the current
quarter would be off by 18 to 23 cents a share, significantly lower
than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, the company said its sales
of condensed soup, those familiar red-and-white cans that make up
two-thirds of Campbell's sales and earnings, had been depressed by
unusually warm weather in November and December and would not
improve meaningfully before its second quarter ends on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is based in Camden, N.J., also said that
shipments would be down ``significantly in the near term'' and that
the effect would be felt for the full fiscal year, which ends on
July 31. Earnings for the year are expected to be $1.90 to $1.95 a
share, down from the $2.13 consensus on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement sent the company's share price into a tailspin.
Trading was halted briefly in the morning as the price plunged more
than $7 and hit a 52-week low. The shares finished the day at
$45.375, down $6.875, or about 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dale F. Morrison, Campbell's chief executive, said that soup
sales for the fiscal year were hurt by the weather in late 1998,
which he called the warmest ``since 1200, when Empress Irene
blinded her son Constantine and vowed to marry Charlemagne.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts seemed unimpressed by the history lesson. As cause for
the problems, they cited not atmospheric conditions but unrealistic
expectations heralded by company management.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, the company came out and said the market for
condensed soup would grow 4 percent,'' said Nomi Ghez, a food
analyst for Goldman, Sachs. ``And there was nobody who believed
them. They built inventories on the assumption that consumption
would grow, because that's what they decided. It's the confusion
between reality and wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Three analysts downgraded the stock after the conference call,
and others said they wondered whether the company's board might
consider a sale to make things right with shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campbell could be attractive,'' said John M. McMillin, an
analyst for Prudential Securities, who asked Morrison in the
conference call whether he had spoken to the Dorrance family, which
has five members on the board and whose patriarch, John R.
Dorrance, started Campbell. Morrison did not answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison, who has been relentless in his optimism about the
company's prospects for growth, said in the conference call that
despite increased spending on marketing, condensed soup sales would
grow by only 1 percent to 2 percent for the year. Recent marketing
campaigns included tie-ins with popular children's television shows
such as ``Blue's Clues'' and ``Rugrats'' and efforts to make
condensed soup more relevant to consumers with recipes and store
displays aimed at the time-pressed home cook.
</P>
<P>
   To try to lift sales, the company also brought out television
commercials that showed various contemporary family scenes,
including a young girl dropped off at her new foster home and a
family merrily making a casserole using a can of soup.
</P>
<P>
   All of that _ together with a spinoff of underperforming
businesses that was completed last year, a companywide campaign
that has employees wearing ``Growth'' pins on their lapels and
healthy expansion of other Campbell businesses like Pepperidge Farm
cookies and V8 Splash soft drinks _ was not enough to overcome a
decline in condensed soup that has continued for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's executives continued to say Monday that they were
making progress, but analysts were highly skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is trying to move mountains in terms of consumer
behavior change,'' McMillin said. ``To blame all of this on the
weather is too much to take. The big problem is they spent a lot of
dollars on marketing and the needle didn't move at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ghez said her recommendation on Campbell shares would remain
at ``neutral,'' despite the drop in price. ``I don't believe this
is a buying opportunity,'' she said. ``The fact is, the total soup
category is not growing very much because people do not sit down to
dinner so often, soup is not portable and people eat out a lot and
eat on the go.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also said Monday that it had come up with a plan to
reduce inefficiencies on its manufacturing side that should save
the company $100 million a year, starting in the fiscal year 2000.
The company also hired an executive from PricewaterhouseCoopers,
the accounting and consulting giant, to examine how else it might
cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   In response, analysts seemed to think that the company should be
concentrating on bolstering its sales, not on cutting back where it
could. ``Whether or not they are doing supply-chain management is
not the issue,'' said Jaine Mehring, an analyst for Salomon Smith
Barney, who cut her rating last month on fears of an earnings drop.
She said the magnitude of the decline Monday was larger than she
had forecast.
</P>
<P>
   McMillin expressed the mood of disappointment that prevailed on
Wall Street Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their desire was to be `Best in Show,' '' he said, recalling
an oft-voiced goal of Morrison and others at Campbell. ``Now
they're really in the doghouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
