</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCGAMBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carolina takes aim at gambling matters
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Video poker. Casino boats. A lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Like a band of Atlantic City conventioneers, the South Carolina
General Assembly finds a gambling smorgasbord on its list of things
to do.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly convenes today in the wake of a tumultuous
November election that featured the ouster of an incumbent governor
who opposed the video poker industry and the election of a
challenger who advocated a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Southern states that have turned to gambling for
revenue _ Georgia, Florida, Kentucky, Virginia and Louisiana run
lotteries while Mississippi allows casinos _ South Carolina is
figuring out how to maximize its take on some games of chance while
prohibiting others.
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama Legislature also will consider a lottery bill this
session. Tennessee, which rejected a lottery proposal last session,
may review another one this year. In Virginia Beach, Va., the City
Council soon will deal with the proposed docking of a casino boat
there.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina not only will consider a lottery, a prime
campaign plank of incoming Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges, but also
whether to tightly regulate or ban video poker and whether to
prohibit casino boats that have begun to ply territorial waters of
the Palmetto State.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the different gambling elements are coming in, and there's
no way to stop it,'' said state Rep. John Hawkins, a Republican
attorney in Spartanburg.
</P>
<P>
   In a conservative bastion where politics are shaped by the
Christian Coalition and the Legislature has declared milk the state
beverage, video poker payoffs became legal in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Republican Gov. David Beasley called the machines a
``cancer'' that eats away at those who play them.
</P>
<P>
   That stand, said Laura Woliver, a political scientist at the
University of South Carolina, ``mobilized every single convenience
store owner who could pay his mortgage with three or four machines
in the back near the men's room.''
</P>
<P>
   The video poker lobby donated huge sums to Hodges, making an
indispensable contribution to his victory.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime opponent of poker payoffs when he was the House
minority leader, Hodges now is lobbying the Legislature to pass a
referendum that would allow voters to decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges wants the referendum set for 2000 when legislators will
be up for re-election and pressed on their video poker views.
Analysts say the maneuver is an attempt to keep momentum by the
Democrats, who had seemed before the November elections on the
verge of extinction. Traditionally, Democrats have favored
legalized gambling; Republicans have opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Video poker generates about $3 billion a year in South Carolina
compared with the $1.7 billion in annual sales produced by the
Georgia lottery. Poker detractors complain the industry is
underregulated and undertaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's going to separate the men from the boys is
how much we decide to tax these rascals,'' said Hawkins, the
Spartanburg representative. ``I support a very high tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strongest proponents of video poker _ those who
receive campaign contributions from the industry _ are trying to
shut down fledgling casino boats as they edge toward a coastline
boom. Poker people don't want the competition.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled the only way to prevent the boats from
running casinos once they reach the three mile territorial limit
offshore is for the Legislature to outlaw such wagering.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Victori Casino began sailing out of the Little
River fishing village near the North Carolina border. Now at least
two other developers say they may start sailing even in the face of
legislative opposition.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent incursions by so-called cruises to nowhere, the
Charleston City Council has passed ordinances that would keep the
boats off its coast.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Joe Brown (D-Columbia) has modified his view of
gambling over the years. Six sessions ago, he favored riverboat
gambling because of its promised job growth. Today, he's a sponsor
on a bill that would stop casino boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our harbors filled up with casino boats,'' Brown
said. ``I know it creates some jobs, but I'm not sure whether it
would cause more problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A lottery for education may be a more palatable form of gambling
for Christian conservatives who quote biblical passages in their
opposition to legal wagering. ``People do not perceive the lottery
like they perceive video poker or casino gambling,'' said Whit
Ayres, a Republican pollster who worked for Beasley. ``In the first
place, the lottery is run by the state. Second, a lot of people
don't see it as gambling. . . . One-third of religious
conservatives wanted a lottery.'' South Carolina residents account
for an estimated 5.5 percent of total sales in the Georgia Lottery
_ the highest out-of-state percentage. In the fall, the top Georgia
Lottery retailer was Dad's Restaurant No. 2 in Lavonia near the
Georgia-South Carolina border.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
