</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-MEN-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, EVERY MAN A SPORTSMAN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Nothing, it seems _ not an NBA lockout nor
thwarted balloon expeditions _ can dampen designers' enthusiasm for
athletic inspirations. As it turns out, it is not outer space that
will define the start of the new millennium in fashion, but sports,
those pastimes and professions that supply iconography and
innocence at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Designers gazing into the future are inspired by the details and
functionality of clothing for snowboarding, skiing, motorbike
racing and fitness generally. What is clear from the men's wear
shows for fall 1999, which began here last Friday and continue
through Wednesday, is that in sports, designers have found a deep
well of ideas for the turn of the century. The sports element in
fashion promises to be much more than a yearlong trend; no doubt
fashion in the year 2000 will also be full of references to it.
</P>
<P>
   In Jil Sander's luxurious casual collection, the spirit of
sports was one subtly suggestive element, like a dabble of paint in
a Jackson Pollock painting. By contrast, John Bartlett's references
in his designs for Byblos were as obvious as the padded vests he
paired with side-zip pants. The sports theme was picked up with
bravado by Donatella Versace for Gianni Versace in flamboyant ski
pants with furry and feathered trim bursting from the seams.
</P>
<P>
   Was it well-placed confidence or blind fear that drove Ms.
Versace to put her clothes on the same stage as Iggy Pop? It is
enough to say that an oxygen-sucking performance by the phenomenal
Iggy Pop (the inspiration for the glam-rock character in ``Velvet
Goldmine'' played by Ewan McGregor, who was in the audience here)
did not eclipse her work. In a sense, the house of Versace has
always done glam.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace confidently merged touches of glamour in T-shirts in
chain mail and relaxed trousers with side zippers near the ankle.
Monster coats of leather trimmed with huge collars of fox or wolf
were thrown over slim suits. Gothic letters spelled out the house
of Versace's signature on leather pieces and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   As styled by William Mullen, a freelance stylist and
contributing editor to Interview magazine, this was casual glamour,
displaying the humor and nonchalance necessary to make such clothes
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Gianni Versace said he felt a strong urge to move
beyond music to sports. His sister, who succeeded him after he was
slain in Miami Beach, has paired the two, making the combination
appear the most natural of fusions.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said he is fascinated by snowboarding culture and the
design details of snowboarding clothes. The sport's burly
masculinity, which is Bartlett's forte, found expression in ample
sport jackets and trousers in white or herringbone cut with the
fullness of snowboarding pants. Frissons of fluorescent color
outlining zippers or flashing like beacons through a fog of gray
trousers and jackets gave the energy of 'board clothing to high
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The same energy was at full throttle in Alessandro Dell'Acqua's
collection, one of his best. Casting aside the cerebral musings
that have sometimes led him astray, Dell'Acqua made a convincing
case for blazing yellows and reds in peel-off sweaters layered one
upon another. This smart, passionate sportswear was balanced with
sober trousers in black or a bird's-eye print, cut loose and long
with zippers at the hem.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum of athleticism derives partly from designers'
desire to imbue softness and comfort _ two culturally feminine
qualities _ with a veneer of masculinity. For all the progress of
women toward athletic parity, sports are still essentially a man's
game. For designers, it is easy to talk about sensuality and luxury
in men's wear when the fundamental inspiration is sports. It lends
credibility to Vivienne Westwood's knit sets and dresses for men _
yes, for men _ that one of her models, a Briton, Chris Eubanks, is
a boxer, engaging in the most brutal of modern sports. In keeping
with her new consideration of actually selling clothes (as opposed
to merely making a stir), Ms. Westwood, who is to open her first
American store in SoHo in Manhattan in the spring, showed an
accessible collection, with suits in velveteen or wool chalk
stripes, and beaded sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sander seems to understand better than anybody the synergy
between men's designer clothes and athletics. ``It's function,''
she said. Tiny zippers, hidden at the hem of trousers paired with a
slick black hooded pullover, spoke of the rich simplicity the
designer is after. Orange pants burst from beneath a stark camel
coat, a mix of the rebel and the orthodox present on many runways
in Milan. White trousers for men were also ubiquitous, another
attempt by designers to push men forward, but not too far.
</P>
<P>
   Austere as they are, Ms. Sander's designs are often more than
the sum of their parts. This element was missing from the attempt
by the Richard Edwards design team to bring depth to bare-bones
fashion. Adding motocross quilting to jackets and trousers and
molding appealing sweatshirts from tactile wools like alpaca and
mohair were some of the nicer ideas of the team, Richard Bengstrom
and Edward Pavlick. But their own voices were lost somewhere;
instead, there was a preciousness to these street-inspired clothes.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Dirk Bikkembergs' presentation in a museum of
science and technology was highly personal. Amid the ammunition
exhibits, the Bikkembergs show began with burly ribbed turtlenecks
in olive and cadet-style shirt and tie combinations, segueing
neatly into nylon ski pants with matching high-neck pullovers.
Bursting from the neckline of one of the pullovers was a furry ring
that lent a splendid glamour to such a utilitarian garment.
</P>
<P>
   A bit startlingly _ for no one is really ready to face the next
year so soon _ Bikkembergs called his collection ``2000,'' which it
is, in European fashion parlance: fall-winter 2000. As designers
weigh the coming of the new millennium and are unconsciously
swayed, it is evident that they are considering what a
new-millennium collection will look like.
</P>
<P>
   For many it includes something of the old and something
futuristic _ the classic with the ultramodern sport fabric, as
exemplified by the combination of fur skin with industrial nylon
that Tom Ford utilized for Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion is a greedy animal, and so it asked more of Ford than
the few, albeit interesting, style mixes he chose to give. An
evolution of one trendsetting Gucci look from last season, the
velvet jacket, was given the rich patina of garnets, rubies or
sapphires. Ford threw the jackets over white T-shirts, as he did
almost everything, and paired them with magnificent jeweled jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as a counterweight to the collection's whimsy were sober
militaristic jackets, coats and trousers with red piping, all a bit
too literal. (Only a policeman's plumed helmet was missing.) By his
own count, Ford showed 19 pairs of decorated jeans, and he called
the display a deliberate overstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Should Ford be excused for coasting? No, he shouldn't. Still,
having set the trends for several seasons to come, he can afford
to.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many propositions that Ford made more than a year ago
(and that have been picked up by other designers) is fur for men.
Ford now uses it in vests and in mottled calfskin and goatskin
coats.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Paul Gaultier, too, played up the sporty element of fur,
cutting sheared furs into sweatshirts and sweaters. Layering on old
hits of his, like a champagne body stocking and his signature
wide-lapel jacket, Gaultier turned a new hand to painted jeans,
silky nylon sweatshirts, knee-length trousers with motocross knee
padding and sequined sweaters. The message is clear: fur this time
cannot be taken too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana got the trend right, making
baggy flannel trousers with deep fur cuffs. But they went
dreadfully wrong with pants made entirely of fur. It looked
awkward, and it's been done.
</P>
<P>
   The theme for Dolce and Gabbana this season was fishermen and
children, and except for the fur pants, they told the story well.
They returned to the shrunken sweaters and beaded floral knitwear
they have done before, freshening them with tooled leather jackets
and vests, gently tailored Angora coats and full trousers.
</P>
<P>
   For Naoki Takizawa, designer of the men's collection at Issey
Miyake, the elements of old and new were represented in wonderful
suits and coats to which he had applied a series of creases
resembling the folds in origami. To see this kind of innovative
application is to observe a design intellect at work. That the
postscript to such originality was the most pedestrian ski jacket
proves, unfortunately, that every designer at some point gets swept
along by a trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
