</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAINAUG12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes ready to get to business after inauguration
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pomp and circumstance of Gov. Roy Barnes' new
administration gave way to the day-to-day challenge of crafting the
``new Georgia'' he proposes to lead into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, the Democrat who became Georgia's 80th governor in front
of a crowd of about 4,000 who braved crisp 40-degree weather, is
expected to waste little time pressing his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of his transportation package that would create a
regional authority to help relieve metro Atlanta's traffic gridlock
could be introduced in the state legislature within the next two
weeks. And he'll make his case for an increase in homestead
exemption as part of a budget proposal unveiled to lawmakers on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Barnes eschewed details to outline a broader
vision of where he believes Georgia could be, propelled by
diversity and education, and of how far the state has come since
the last time a century dawned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, let us celebrate a new Georgia,'' the 50-year-old
Democrat challenged from the outdoor stage set up in front of a
banner-draped Capitol. ``Together, we lift up the weak and weigh
down the wicked, we reduce illiteracy and reform health care, cut
taxes and improve services.''
</P>
<P>
   After placing his left hand on his worn, red-leather Bible and
taking the oath of office from Chief Justice Robert Benham _ a
classmate at the then-recently integrated University of Georgia _
Barnes used his 13-minute address to try to knit the state together
after an election year of racially charged campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor called on ``those who once sought to divide us
to work with us,'' and warned ``those who play with the fire of
racial hatred . . . they will surely be burned.'' Returning to his
campaign promises, Barnes pledged to make education a top priority
and not allow a scenario in which ``the ringing of gunshots drowns
out the ring of the school bell.''
</P>
<P>
   A 22-year legislative veteran and long-time student of state
government, Barnes harkened back to the changes since a governor
last took office at the turn of a century, a time when few
Georgians completed elementary school and half the state's
residents were denied the right to vote because of their skin
color.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia must again take mighty steps to tackle the new threats _
such as air pollution and problems in health care delivery _ that
are on the horizon, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating the speech, Michael Binford, a Georgia State
University political scientist, said: ``There's a lot of symbols, a
lot of hope for the future, but there's not a lot of specifics he
can be pinned down on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor, who followed Barnes in taking the oath of
office, was more specific as he paid homage to his south Georgia
roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there are counties in the state that have been left
behind economically,'' Taylor said. ``For the growing, prosperous,
most developed part of the state to be indifferent to those
counties . . . is not smart, it's not right, and it's not
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, Barnes provoked comparisons to departing Gov. Zell
Miller, who shared the inaugural stage along with six other former
governors but uttered only a few scripted words as he turned over
the state seal. Missing from Barnes' address were the mountain
metaphors and crisp images political observers had come to expect
from the man who leaves office after two terms as perhaps the
state's most popular chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The open-air ceremony to transfer power, a tradition in Georgia,
also marked the start of the 40-day General Assembly session, a
period often fraught with partisan fighting and political
turbulence. But regardless of party, most legislators found little
over which to disagree with the new governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything to quibble about,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah). ``Republicans at this
point are very comfortable with Roy Barnes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, opening day held few surprises, with the House
installing Tom Murphy for his 13th term as speaker, which the
74-year-old Bremen Democrat has hinted may be his last. Murphy is
the nation's longest-serving state House speaker. Barnes and
Taylor, who won election in part on the strength of the black vote,
fittingly started their first day in office at an ecumenical
service in a predominantly black church in southwest Atlanta.
There, ministers from at least four faiths called Barnes ``our
dream-keeper'' and likened him to Moses, leading the Israelites out
of bondage in Egypt. But they warned of the fickleness of the
electorate and the news media at the first sign of hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only a handspan between a pat on your back and a kick
on your duff,'' the Rev. Gerald Durley, pastor of Providence
Missionary Baptist Church warned. ``Never forget the handspan,
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathey Pruitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
