<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS HAS MORE TRICKS IN RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. &UR;  &LR; _ It wasn't Keyshawn's receptions and it wasn't
Keyshawn's end-around plays. It wasn't even the sight of Keyshawn
sticking his loquacious head into a scrum and coming up with a
loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Keyshawn Johnson sighting that sticks the longest from
the Jets' playoff victory Sunday is his plucking the last
desperation pass by Jacksonville as a member of the Jets' defensive
backfield.
</P>
<P>
   This is when football gets really good, when the coach sends out
his best athlete, his stud, his dude, to take a walk on the wild
side.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Jets were up by an insurmountable 10 points in
the final seconds, it was still a galvanizing vision when the Jets'
wide receiver dashed toward the ball, elevated himself and came
down with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just put him in there for his height,'' said Bill Parcells,
the Jets' coach. ``It's just like in basketball, where you put your
tallest guy under the basket for the rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, football is nothing like basketball. Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar could dribble the ball, if needed, and Magic Johnson
could play point guard or center from one play to the next, and
Michael Jordan is the best defensive player of his time as well as
the best offensive player.
</P>
<P>
   Football is so compartmentalized, so specialized, that players
are either offensive or defensive. They wear green jerseys in
practice or they wear white, and on Sunday they wear the same
uniforms but huddle in separate units on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   It is great fun to see turnovers, when players undergo instant
role reversal. Vinny Testaverde, the quarterback, the one player
who is not supposed to be roughed up in midweek practices, deserves
to take a ritual training meal with the macho linebackers for the
way he pursued a Jaguar running with a recovered fumble on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The player made a dumb mistake _ overtrained football players
are not universally good at improvisation _ and coughed up the
ball, and Keyshawn recovered it. It makes you want to bring back
the old days of one-platoon football, when footballers were
footballers.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, somebody breaks the mold, usually a defensive
back like Deion Sanders or Rod Woodson at receiver, or a
quarterback like Randall Cunningham or Kordell Stewart given
license to run with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The most imaginative coaching move in the past generation was
when Mike Ditka of the Bears recognized that the gigantic defensive
tackle, William Perry, would be difficult to haul down with the
ball in his hand. Football hasn't been the same since that rogue
whale went out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is more imaginative than the average coach. He insisted
that his use of Keyshawn on defense was no ad-hoc,
let's-do-the-play-right-here-in-the-garage stratagem, sending in
the tall guy because he was having an enchanted afternoon. Nor was
it a belligerent response to the sloppiness that allowed a Jaguars
touchdown on the final heave of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, at the end of the first half, we were thinking they might
go for a field goal,'' Parcells said. ``But at the end of the game,
we wanted another defensive back. We've been working on that for at
least six weeks. You've got to run the play in practice, so
everybody will know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why they herd reporters into dismal press rooms rather
than let us watch practice. Who knows? By accident, one of us might
observe something.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty going on behind that dyspeptic stare of
Parcells. He always seems to have a running back like Dave Meggett
who can throw a pass, or a receiver like Johnson who can run with
the ball. Parcells often gambles on fourth down, and is still
remembered in New England for a failed pass off a fake punt
(against Denver, as a matter of fact).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when the Patriots beat the Jaguars for the
conference championship on Jan. 12, 1997, one successful play had
been practiced for four years without ever being used.
</P>
<P>
   Attention to detail has helped Parcells become the first head
coach to take three different teams to conference championship
games. On Sunday, as he drove home to South Jersey, Parcells was
already working out this week's practice schedule, and where he
would deploy all his players on the extra-wide jet he had requested
for a road playoff game, many, many weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells likes to think up new variations on old themes, but he
doesn't necessarily want to use them because that probably means
the Jets are behind. Having exposed Keyshawn the runner several
times this year, he has now exposed Keyshawn the defender. Parcells
allowed Monday that, yes, there could be more surprises where those
came from.
</P>
</TEXT>
