<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: OUT FROM VERSACE'S SHADOW; GUCCI BUZZWORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ In time, Antonio D'Amico, who on Monday night
introduced his first signature collection, will be known simply as
a designer. But for now he must bear the weight of being known
primarily as Gianni Versace's companion of 14 years, even though
for 13 of them he worked at Versace SpA. Most recently he was
designer of Istante and Versus Sport.
</P>
<P>
   Elton John, who was the closest of Versace's celebrity friends,
flew to Milan to attend D'Amico's show. He came to support him,
``because he's my friend and he's been through hell in the last two
years,'' John said, adding, ``I think you should show support for
people when they are trying to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion shows can be like family weddings, with keen observation
paid to who attends and who does not. On Saturday, John missed the
Versace presentation by Donatella Versace. The singer, who attended
Ms. Versace's first solo show following the death of her brother
Gianni in August 1997, immediately tried to dispel the rumors that
there was a rift between him and the Versace family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no war,'' he said. ``I was in LA and just couldn't
deal with the Versace show on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico's partner in his new business is Massimo Lotti, a former
designer at Jean-Charles de Castalbajac, a French fashion company.
D'Amico, whose theatrical show was lavish even by European
standards, said that he did receive money upon Versace's death, but
that it was not financing his venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did get money,'' he said. ``Gianni was very generous. But
I'm not using it. I'm using my own money that I saved to start the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually ambitious move, D'Amico introduced men's wear
and women's wear simultaneously. Prices range from about $200 to
$400 for knitwear and $600 to $1,500 for suits. Spacewear, his
less-expensive line, includes jeans and T-shirts. The lines will be
made in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, who will be 40 on Jan. 21, feels he has an angel on his
shoulder. Versace, he said, told him to open his own company.
Still, the call from beyond was not enough to lure Santo Versace,
the late designer's brother and the chairman of Versace, nor Ms.
Versace, to the debut of D'Amico.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ms. Versace said she had to leave for Paris on
Monday morning to prepare for her couture presentation there this
month.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico said that his relations with the Versaces remain good,
``but things have changed.'' He departed the house a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay,'' he added. ``But after Gianni's death I
couldn't find any solace there. It was difficult to be there.
Everything was so painful.''
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript, there was no Istante show this season. Versace
S.p.A. will close the diffusion line, Santo Versace said. Versace
officials would not give further comment. Bloomingdale's is among
the American stores that carry the line.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI BUZZWORD: TAKEOVER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is at the center of discussions once again in Milan, and
not just for what Tom Ford, its designer, has put on the runway.
Just six months ago, the fashion world in Milan was on the edge of
its seat during show week, awaiting news on a possible Gucci
takeover by Prada. That never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the city is abuzz again, and this time it is Bernard
Arnault, the chairman of LVMH Moeet Hennessy-Louis Vuitton, who
holds the cards. Fashion insiders were surprised by the news last
week that LVMH had raised its holdings of Gucci shares to more than
5 percent. LVMH officials are expected to say more this week.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a potential corporate suitor is apparently fixed on
Gucci, Gucci itself has been doing a little shopping around. The
company is looking for some possible takeover targets in the luxury
goods sector, said one knowledgeable executive of Gucci.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
