<HEADLINE>
GIANTS TO PLACE WOOTEN AND GRAY IN EXPANSION DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, every National Football League team _ except the
four still in the Super Bowl playoffs _ must submit the names of
five players who will be available for next month's expansion draft
to stock the roster of the 1999 Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   The league has said it will make the names of the 130 players
public by Friday, but Giants officials who spoke on the condition
of anonymity said that starting free safety Tito Wooten and nickel
cornerback Carlton Gray were expected to be among the five listed
by the team. The Giants seem eager to part with Wooten.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected to be on the Giants' list was little-used
cornerback Kory Blackwell. Team officials said in meetings last
week that the team considered placing the starting defensive
tackle. Robert Harris. and a reserve safety, Brandon Sanders, on
the list of five. But Harris apparently escaped the list.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft is Feb. 9. The four teams still in the
post-season have been granted extensions and do not have to
identify their five players until after their seasons have ended.
No team can lose more than two players in the draft, and once a
team has had a player selected by Cleveland, that team can withdraw
two others from its list of five.
</P>
<P>
   Wooten, Gray and Harris are each scheduled to make in excess of
$2 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   If a team is considering cutting a high-salaried player, as the
Giants are with Wooten, there is a salary cap advantage to having
him selected by the Browns since the majority of his contract is
removed from his former team's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Wooten's poor play and conditioning lapses last season irked
teammates. It is unlikely that the Browns will take him, both
because of Wooten's declining level of play and his off-the-field
problems in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the Browns are required to use 38 percent of their 1999
salary cap _ estimated to be in the $60 million range _ on players
they select in the expansion draft. So Cleveland will have to take
some high- or medium-priced NFL veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, signed off waivers at the start of the 1998 season, is one
of four starting or former starting cornerbacks under contract to
the Giants. The others are Phillippi Sparks, Jason Sehorn and
Conrad Hamilton. Hamilton is a restricted free agent whom the
Giants expect to retain even if it means matching most any offer he
receives.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, it seems Gray is the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has said he does not want to remain with the Giants unless
given a chance to start, but that may not be possible given the
logjam at cornerback. The Giants have said in the past that they
will try to trade Gray if he isn't happy.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, one of the stars of the division-winning 1997 Giants,
had an injury-prone year. His value also dropped with the improving
play of his backup, Christian Peter. The Giants think that Peter
has improved enough to start.
</P>
<P>
   Another Giant in the spotlight this off season will be
linebacker Marcus Buckley, who was ineffective against the run this
season as the team's new strongside linebacker. Ryan Phillips may
take over that job anyway, or the Giants may have to sign a veteran
run-stopping linebacker to play on first down for Buckley, who is
more suited to pass coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Coach Jim Fassel interviewed Tony Wise, the former
Chicago Bears and Dallas Cowboys line coach, for the team's vacant
offensive line coach's job. Wise is the Giants' first choice for
the job filled by John Matsko the last two seasons. Matsko was
dismissed by Fassel last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' other top candidate is Jim McNally, the former
Carolina Panthers line coach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
