<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ White House lawyers tell the Senate
that President Clinton should not be removed from office, saying
that the articles of impeachment against him are based on
misconceptions about his testimony to a federal grand jury and his
efforts to keep his relationship with Monica Lewinsky secret. But
House prosecutors back up their contention that Clinton's actions
warrant removal from office. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PRESIDENT (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore outlines
proposals to preserve open space and tame urban sprawl, themes that
are expected to provide a foundation for his presidential campaign
next year. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ENGLISH (Washington) _ The Supreme Court declines to
revive an Arizona law declaring English the official language of
the state and requiring that it be used for all state business. By
STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LEGISLATURE (Austin, Texas) _ Ending an 18-month lull in
lawmaking, the 76th Legislature will be sworn in Tuesday in
family-oriented, standing-room-only ceremonies in the House and
Senate chambers. The House will elect Democratic Rep. Pete Laney to
be the speaker for a fourth two-year term. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATURE-OUTLOOK (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush wants
to use a surplus to fund $2 billion in property tax cuts and $1.6
billion in school initiatives. But new calculations have shrunk the
surplus since Bush made his campaign pledge last summer. And the
last time he tried to cut taxes, the Legislature granted only a
small portion of his proposal. By JOHN GONZALEZ. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ If you are considering an Internet
bank, be extra careful. There are legitimate Internet banks out
there, but there have been cases where con artists have set up what
looked like a legitimate bank. ``Internet banking is one of the
easiest frauds to perpetrate because it takes nothing to put up a
home page,'' said Catherine Ghiglieri, the Texas banking
commissioner. By PAMELA YIP. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MULGREW-VOYAGER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Like her character, Capt.
Kathryn Janeway of the USS Voyager, Kate Mulgrew wants to go home.
For Mulgrew, single mother of two teen-age boys, home is freedom
from 80-hour workweeks and shots that can go on until 3 a.m. By
MIKE McDANIEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ President Clinton insists he will
deliver his State of the Union address in person before the
Congress that is out to get him despite the awkwardness of it all.
He's right to stare the lawmakers down. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The ceremonial excitement of
the Texas Legislature's opening day may be even more feverish than
normal this week, fueled by the Republican takeover of the state's
executive branch, a new presiding officer in the Senate, Gov.
George W. Bush's second inauguration and his anticipated launch of
a presidential race. But after the adjournment gavels fall May 31,
this session may be best remembered for being unremarkable. By CLAY
ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFC (Undated) _ Back at the start of the season, who would
have thought that Minnesota and Atlanta would be the two teams
playing in the NFC Championship Game? And who could have imagined
that the two teams would enter with a combined record of 31-3. By
JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-AFC (Undated) _ The New York Jets are the just the kind of
team that could cause problems for the high-flying Denver Broncos
in this week's AFC Championship Game. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
