<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-SPRAWL-PLAN-NYT &LR;      01-11 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPRAWL-PLAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION UNVEILS PLAN TO PRESERVE OPEN SPACE AND COMBAT
SPRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Story includes previously budgeted GORE-POLITICS) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Almost 50 years after new federal highways and the
G.I. Bill made it easier for Americans to move from crowded cities
to leafy suburbs, the Clinton administration is proposing an
ambitious program to combat the modern-day consequences of the
exodus: traffic jams and sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its latest budget request, the administration is
seeking to commit almost $10 billion _ more than $1 billion of it
in new spending _ to local governments and communities for programs
that preserve open space, ease traffic congestion and promote
economic development in a way that some states are calling ``smart
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which the administration calls its Livability
Agenda, draws together and expands programs from more than a dozen
agencies, making it the largest commitment ever by the federal
government to the issue of planned growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In too many places across America, the beauty of local vistas
has been degraded by decades of ill-planned and ill-coordinated
development,'' Vice President Al Gore said on Monday, announcing
the program. ``Plan well, and you have a community that nurtures
commerce and private life. Plan badly, you have what so many of us
suffer from first-hand _ gridlock, sprawl and that uniquely modern
evil of all too little time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was careful to explain that the proposal limits the federal
role to encouraging neighboring jurisdictions to solve problems
together. The government's role, he said, ``should never be that of
beauty commissar.''
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials are promoting the proposal as a
bold stroke, bringing together such traditional adversaries as
environmentalists and developers, states like Maryland, Oregon and
New Jersey, as well as many local communities and conservation
groups, have been attacking problems of boundless growth for years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the problems finally attracted large-scale
federal attention because so many state and local officials have
been trumpeting their efforts and clamoring for federal help. In
last year's election, he said to illustrate the point, more than
200 jurisdictions had growth initiatives on the ballot, ``and most
of them passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Parris Glendening of Maryland, a Democrat and a leading
promoter of ``smart growth'' development, accompanied Gore on
Monday and said in an interview, ``The federal government has been
behind the states on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the most important thing,'' he added, ``is that the
federal government has paused to consider to what extent American
politics has contributed to the sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement on Monday was the first of several he
intends to make this week, highlighting administration budget
requests. As is typical of such proposals, the administration did
not explain how it expects to pay for the new spending. The
Republican Congress regards many administration initiatives as just
a starting point in budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that Gore has been chosen to present
issues like sprawl, worker training and Empowerment Zones largely
because he has been the administration's point man on them for six
years. On Tuesday, President Clinton is scheduled to expand upon
the issue of preserving open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcements also put the vice president in a spotlight
for issues his aides say will become major themes of his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The largest single item of new spending in the administration
growth proposal is a five-year $700 million program that will allow
state and local governments to issue no-interest ``Better America
Bonds'' to lenders, who would claim a tax credit for the life of
the bond, rather than receive interest. The money would be used to
preserve parks and open spaces, protect water supplies and develop
abandoned industrial sites for commercial use _ all vital
components to controlled growth.
</P>
<P>
   Gore predicted that the bonds could leverage as much as $10
billion in investment around planned growth areas.
</P>
<P>
   Another component of the proposal is what Gore described as the
largest ever federal budget request for public transportation _
$6.1 billion, a 16 percent increase over last year _ to help pay
for new projects that ease traffic congestion and reduce air
pollution through regional cooperation in fixing roads, expanding
public transportation systems and developing alternative routes.
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposal was generally praised by
environmental groups like the Sierra Club, whose executive
director, Carl Pope, called it ``a good first step,'' toward
reversing 50 years of sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   But business groups, including the National Association of Home
Builders, whose members would seem to be affected by restrictions
on developement, also found something to cheer. Charlie Ruma, the
in-coming president of the home buildings group, said the proposal
would help by clearly defining zoning regulations. But he objected
to the notion that the federal government would be helping
communities buy land to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``States should not be in the business of buying property,''
Ruma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
