A8641 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-PERFORMANCE-     01-11 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-PERFORMANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY TO BEEF UP ADVERTISING ON LESSER-KNOWN FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Chastened by weak sales, Fidelity Investments says it
is inching back into tried-and-true solutions to peddle its mutual
funds. The nation's largest fund firm hopes to overcome a gaping
chasm between its fund returns, among the best in the business, and
fund sales, which have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging it may be a while before investors return in
force, Fidelity is tweaking its much-watched advertising campaign
to focus on products and homespun investing wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see more product advertising,'' Robert C.
Pozen, head of Fidelity's investment business, said Monday.
``You're going to see a shift in the advertising that follows up
with focuses on specific funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The change, already evident in Boston-based Fidelity's
5-month-old television and print advertisements, starring investing
icon Peter Lynch, represents how Fidelity is racing to turn the
tide against a sharp falloff in sales.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the company has performance numbers to sell.
Fidelity stock funds were the top gainers among the industry's 10
largest fund firms last year, according to new figures released
Monday by Kanon Bloch Carre, an investment consulting firm in
Boston. The ranking was calculated according to asset weighting,
which compares large fund firms with each other rather than with
smaller, fleet-footed shops that can more easily produce hot gains
in their first years.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, as Fidelity struggled with high turnover among
portfolio managers and internal chaos, it ranked last out of 10 in
the survey. Since then, Pozen has whipped things into shape,
expanding research units, making it more attractive for portfolio
managers to stay on board, and more rigorously analyzing which
stocks do well and why.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have paid off. According to Kanon Bloch, Fidelity's
US diversified equity funds returned a hefty average 26.07 percent
last year. The Vanguard Group, whose sales of index and other funds
have alarmed other fund firms, ranked third, with an average return
of 20.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the payoff for Fidelity has been only partial. Despite lower
returns, Malvern, Pa.-based Vanguard has trampled Fidelity and
everyone else in sales, vending four times as many funds, or $44
billion worth, as Fidelity over the the first 11 months of last
year, according to Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Fidelity quietly began placing newspaper ads
touting specific funds and their Morningstar ratings, a key selling
point. Previous Fidelity campaigns earlier this decade touted
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in focus comes amid criticism of Fidelity's original,
Lynch-led advertising campaign, whose costars, comedians Don
Rickles and Lily Tomlin, have been lost on some viewers. Fidelity
wants to lend a new generation of lesser-known funds marquee appeal
after well-known funds such as Magellan _ which produced
eye-popping returns under Lynch _ and Contrafund were closed to new
investors for size reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while for people to shift focus from those very
popular brand names to lesser known funds,'' Pozen said, citing,
among others, Dividend Growth, Blue Chip Growth, and Fidelity Fund.
In other words, good performance takes a while to translate into
stronger sales, since investors ruminate over past returns before
buying new funds.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio managers at Fidelity, which has around $716 billion in
assets under management, pulled off strong gains last year by
piling into the large growth stocks that have hogged most of Wall
Street's returns.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, a news release from Oliver, Wyman &AMP; Co. said
Fidelity's former chief risk officer, James Lam, had joined the New
York-based consulting firm as director of a new unit focused on
global risk strategies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
