<HEADLINE>
FREYDA KOPLOW, 91; 1ST FEMALE MASSACHUSETTS BANKING COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Freyda (Peck) Koplow, Massachusetts' first female
banking commissioner, died in her sleep Sunday at Deaconess Waltham
Hospital. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   As banking commissioner, Mrs. Koplow was the first woman to head
a major department of the executive branch of the state government.
She was appointed by Governor John Volpe in 1967 and reappointed by
Governor Frank Sargent in 1970. She served until 1975.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, she served as a Brookline representative in the
Legislature from 1955 to 1967.
</P>
<P>
   When she took over as state banking commissioner in 1967, she
oversaw 1,800 state banks, credit unions, finance companies, and
collection agencies with combined assets of $13.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the Feb. 10, 1968, issue of Business Week magazine
described her as a ``soft-spoken, no-nonsense grandmother of six,''
who ``has played her new role with the aplomb of a State Street
banker _ whether conducting a hearing on a proposed merger,
inspecting a site for a new savings bank branch or licensing a
small loan company. With equal imperturbability, she summons top
officers of the state's banks to iron out problems uncovered by her
150 bank examiners.''
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Mrs. Koplow spoke of her devotion to her job:
``I'm not the type who whips up a bowl of batter while scanning the
latest issue of American Banker.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Willimantic, Conn., she graduated from Boston University
in 1930 and earned a master's degree in social research at Simmons
College in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   While raising her children, she was active with the Brookline
chapter of the League of Women's Voters. She made her first
successful run for state representative after her children were off
to college.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, she was appointed by President Ford to a Presidential
Commission on Electronic Funds Transfer that helped to lay the
groundwork for automated teller machines and other forms of
electronic banking.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves three sons, Richard of Lexington, Michael of Woburn,
and Kenneth of Cambridge; three sisters, Edna Sulman of Madison,
Wis., Mildred Robinson of Boca Raton, Fla., and Ruth Swatsburg of
Waterford, Conn; a brother, Albert Peck of Delray Beach, Fla.;
seven grandchildren; and seven great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
