u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES12-C     01-11 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons notebook: Brooks to feel the heat
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every coach in Suwanee will be working quadruple
overtime this week, but perhaps Falcons defensive coordinator Rich
Brooks is going to have to apply himself more than ever .
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons (15-2) line up against the Vikings (16-1)
Sunday in Atlanta's first-ever NFC Championship game, the team in
purple will bring the highest-scoring offense in NFL history to the
Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can get to (quarterback Randall) Cunningham before he
launches those passes, you've got a chance,'' Brooks said. ''But
even when you get pressure, he's got the mobility to buy time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, people focus on the combination of wide
receivers Cris Carter (78 catches, 1,011 yards, 12 touchdowns) and
rookie Randy Moss (69 catches, 1,313 yards, 17 touchdowns).
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will mix up their secondary coverages as much or
more as they did against San Francisco in last Saturday's 20-18
playoff win.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Moss was not on that team, and they had Bolliver Shagnasty
out there at receiver, you would double Carter all the time but you
can't do that,'' Brooks said. ''Then you expose the rest of your
defense to the running game, and (Andrew) Glover's a pretty fair
tight end, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will be off today, although coaches will work well
into the evening formulating game plans. They will practice
Wednesday and Thursday, likely in Suwanee rather than the Georgia
Dome if the weather warms. After a light practice Friday morning,
the team will depart for Minnesota, as per NFL rules.
</P>
<P>
   Not talking turkey
</P>
<P>
   James Sims, the agent for running back Jamal Anderson, met
Friday with Falcons general manager Harold Richardson to talk again
about extending the fifth-year player's contract, which expires
after next season. No deal is imminent, and little or no progress
is expected the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would describe (the talks) as assessment discussions,
looking at where everything stands,'' Sims said. ''We're going to
let the dust settle.''
</P>
<P>
   No Moss here
</P>
<P>
   Falcon coach Dan Reeves said that in last April's draft he
didn't give a thought to using the team's No. 13 pick in the first
round to select Moss instead of Georgia Tech linebacker Keith
Brooking. The talented player's questionable background made the
decision for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings took Moss with the No. 21 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was never a consideration here,'' Reeves said. ''I felt his
past was such that we couldn't take a chance. He's a guy you pull
for . . . he's done so much for the league. But at the point we
were picking, there was no way we could gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were trying to get people in the stands, and we couldn't
stand the negative publicity that you would get if you take someone
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said cornerback Ronnie Bradford, who did not play
Saturday after suffering a slight shoulder separation Dec. 27
against Miami, could have played, but a decision was made to let
the shoulder continue resting. . . . Reserve safety Devin Bush, who
plays chiefly in the nickel and dime defenses, has a strained
hamstring that is the most serious injury suffered Saturday. He
anticipates practicing Wednesday, however. . . . Fullback Bob
Christian, whose season ended Dec. 13 when he tore ligaments in his
left knee, was supposed to have surgery today, but pushed it back
to early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves cited the play of wide receiver Mathis (five
catches, 71 yards), Anderson (113 yards, two touchdowns on 29
carries), and quarterback Chandler (13 of 19, 169 yards) on offense
for the Falcons' win Saturday over the 49ers. Defensively, he
mentioned linebackers Cornelius Bennett (eight tackles) and Jessie
Tuggle (eight tackles), and strong safety William White (two
tackles, two interceptions). . . . The play of the linebackers was
a reflection of the fact the defensive line did an outstanding job
tying up 49er blockers. . . . Brooks said crowd noise had nothing
to do with the decision to stunt less along the defensive line in
the second half against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
