<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AMERICAN TOBACCO WILL BUY ROTHMANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (jw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ British American Tobacco PLC announced
plans Monday to acquire Rothmans International for about $7.5
billion, the biggest but probably not the last cigarette-industry
combination this year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would unite the second- and fourth-largest tobacco
companies in the world and put British American within striking
distance of the Philip Morris Cos. It comes at a time when
cigarette producers, under heavy criticism in the United States,
have been racing to consolidate their worldwide positions.
</P>
<P>
   Through its American subsidiary, Brown &AMP; Williamson, British
American Tobacco owns brands like Lucky Strike, Benson &AMP; Hedges,
Kent and Viceroy. Its cigarettes are also top sellers in China and
other parts of Asia. Rothmans, based in the Netherlands, has little
presence in the United States but has a strong base in Europe and
Africa with relatively expensive brands like Rothmans, Players and
Dunhill.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies together produce about 900 billion cigarettes
a year, or 16 percent of the world's total. Their combined revenue
would be about 10 billion pounds or more than $16 billion, compared
with revenue around $25 billion for Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal would probably accelerate the
consolidation and reorganization in the industry as smaller
companies slip further and further behind the top two competitors.
The RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., whose R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. is
the world's third-biggest tobacco concern, has already indicated
that it will try to sell or spin off its international cigarette
business _ possibly in the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger is likely to trigger further global
tobacco-industry consolidation,'' said Martin Feldman, an analyst
with Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``Philip Morris is a very
aggressive competitor, and the new No. 2 company will be well
capitalized, have a good management and a very powerful balance
sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothmans is owned by Richemont A.G., a financial holding company
based in Switzerland, and the Rembrandt Group, a South African
investment company. Both of those are effectively controlled by the
Rupert family of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, BAT will issue a mixture of new common and
preferred stock that will give Richemont a 35 percent stake in the
enlarged company _ also to be called British American Tobacco. It
will pay its current shareholders a final dividend of 16 pence and
a special interim dividend of 4 pence on July 1. Rothmans, in turn,
will pay a dividend of 150 million pounds to Richemont and
Rembrandt.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after a year of drastic change. Like all other
tobacco companies active in the United States, British American is
settling class-action suits brought by smokers and state
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the pressure from those suits, the former BAT
Industries spun off its nontobacco businesses, mostly insurance
companies, last year by pooling them with a business owned by the
Zurich Group of Switzerland. British American Tobacco is the
leftover tobacco business.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move would strengthen BAT both in terms of its
market position and its financial strength. The strength of
Rothmans lies in premium brands, and its business is outside the
United States. BAT's brands are mostly sold at standard prices, and
the company has heavy exposure in the United States. As a result,
the two companies complement each other.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rothmans comes to the deal with a stronger balance
sheet, which should shore up BAT.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger represents a major step forward in the achievement
of our vision to become the world's leading international tobacco
company,'' British American Chairman Martin Broughton said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were pleased by the announcements, quickly bidding up
shares of British American Tobacco. In New York, the company's
American depository receipts rose $2.6875, or nearly 15 percent, to
$20.625.
</P>
<P>
   Richemont's stock, traded in Switzerland, and Rembrandt's stock,
in South Africa, also jumped in response to news of the deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until Monday, many experts had predicted that BAT might try to
acquire RJR Nabisco's international cigarette businesses. RJR has
been under heavy pressure from the investor Carl Icahn to sell its
international operations, and company executives have strongly
indicated their interest in soon doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition announcement makes it much less likely that BAT
will bid for the business. But both Broughton and Johann Rupert,
chief executive of Richemont and chairman of Rembrandt, made it
clear at a news conference in Switzerland that they were interested
in additional acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Broughton and I have spent a lot of time discussing the
enlarged British American Tobacco group's future strategy,'' Rupert
said, adding that the strategy would be ``a mix of organic growth,
investment in new markets and selective acquisitions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
