<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enough with happytalk, Dolphins have real problems
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's time to stop whistling past the
aquarium, er, graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Enough, in other words, with the They're Close Theory. That's
nothing more than happytalk, and happytalk is almost always a bunch
of fibs.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins, in current composition, are not close to
winning a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   They're not even close to playing in one.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you think the matter of finding a game-breaking wide
receiver and _ that's and _ a dangerous running back capable of
consistent production is as simple as stopping by the (free-agent)
market or plucking something off the shelves of the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the aftermath of the Dolphins' 38-3 weekend loss to the
Denver Broncos in the second round of the playoffs, the general
mood over Miami suggests it might be a good idea to place an order
for noisemakers and balloons sometime soon for a South Florida
championship party.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should think first about ordering an offense.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Dolphins, when in possession of the football, are
too often inept.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's offense is mediocre, at best, when measured against the
entire NFL. When measured against playoff teams, it's just plain
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Did you check out the Saturday and Sunday point totals of the
four teams advancing to the upcoming conference championship games?
Minnesota scored 41. Denver hung the 38 on the Dolphins. New York's
Jets went flying for 34. Among the NFL's Final Four, only Atlanta
(20 points) arrived without bags stuffed full of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It's fine that Jimmy Johnson has, in three seasons as head
coach, constructed a Miami defense that is usually very good and
sometimes excellent. But the Dolphins, quite frankly, would be
better off with a mediocre defense coupled with an offense that is
usually very good and sometimes excellent.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new age.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are more about scoring than they're about defense
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Super Bowls. The winning teams in the nine played in
the '90s have averaged 37.3 points per game against a defensive
yield of 19.0 points per game. That's way up from games played in
the previous decade when the average score was 33.4-14.8. And it's
way, way up from the pre-1980s when the average score was
24.3-11.2.
</P>
<P>
   Old CW: The best offense is a good defense.
</P>
<P>
   New CW: The best defense is a good offense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami won't be close to winning an NFL title until it finds a
couple of Johnson's precious ``playmakers'' who actually make those
plays on offense.
</P>
<P>
   It's very nice that the Dolphins _ and this is the umpteenth
acknowledgement _ have improved over each of Johnson's three
seasons. But he has used up the grace period. Miami played five
games this season against three teams _ Denver (twice), New York
(twice) and Atlanta _ still in the Super Bowl chase, and went 1-4.
And the four losses were by a combined 73 points.
</P>
<P>
   Close to excellence?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets won the AFC East crown right there in the Dolphins' own
division. Miami is closer, much closer, to being a Seattle or a
Tennessee than it is to being a New York or a Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Whistle past that.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
