<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mourning on the defensive
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Alonzo Mourning decided to be a strong voice in the
union, he just figured his image could not get much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reputation was tainted before I was part of the negotiating
committee,'' Mourning said Monday as he reported to the Heat's
practice facility for the first time in more than five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned about that. Now that we have a deal,
I have a job to do and I can't control people's feelings about me.
Throughout this whole process, I'm sorry if I stepped on anybody's
toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning stepped on them, and twist his heel into the entire
foot. Nobody had a stronger opinion and nobody made more
controversial comments than Mourning, who already is one of the
least popular players in the league.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody, with the possible exception of union president
Patrick Ewing, was more criticized.
</P>
<P>
   But Mourning isn't worried about the reception he'll receive
from his teammates or the fans. In fact, Mourning isn't convinced
he came out of this long, bitter labor dispute as the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys made me the target,'' he said to a small group of
writers. ``You all talked about me worse than (his teammates and
fans) did. Regardless of what was said and what was talked about,
it didn't stop me from accomplishing that goal to get the best
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning's teammates, specifically Tim Hardaway, questioned his
judgment when he said race was playing a part in the negotiations.
And other Heat, without mentioning Mourning, said a gag order
needed to be imposed on their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going through this whole process that we weren't going
to be able to please everybody,'' Mourning said. ``Everybody is
entitled to their own opinion, everybody forced their own opinion.
Everybody was saying the guys were getting antsy and there was
dissension developing. That didn't stop the negotiating committee
from doing their job to get the best possible deal for the
masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat owner Micky Arison, who was in the room opposite Mourning
during several negotiating sessions, admires Mourning for his
stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to give them a lot of credit for being the ones who
were willing to roll up their sleeves and work hard while other
guys sat at home and didn't care,'' Arison said. ``The fact that
certain things were said during a heated session hopefully
everybody will put it behind them and start to play ball because
that's what these guys do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning expects that's what will happen. He has talked with
Keith Askins, the most outspoken among Heat players against the
union, and both players said they respected each other's position.
Askins and Mourning are the Heat's co-captains.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning and Hardaway said everything is forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my colleagues and my teammates can't separate business and
playing basketball, and trying to accomplish a goal together, then
we have a big problem,'' Mourning said. ``And I don't think we'll
have that problem at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks CEO Dave Checketts said he is concerned Ewing's union
commitments the last five months cut into his conditioning.
Mourning, who is one of the hardest-working, dedicated players in
the league, said Pat Riley need no share those worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is in game shape,'' he said.? ``I maintained. I ain't
walking in here with no gut.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning may have set himself up for a larger role with the
union in the future as a successor to Ewing, who is 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about it, but if the opportunity presents
itself in the future, I would consider it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom D'Angelo writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
