<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smithsonian heralds new racial era in Stone Mountain
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In 1923, when Mount Rushmore sculptor Gutzon Borglum
began carving his massive bas-relief on Stone Mountain (Ga.), the
Ku Klux Klan began holding annual rallies at the memorial and in
the neighboring town of that name. Seventy-five years later, the
faces of Jefferson Davis, Robert E. Lee and Thomas ``Stonewall''
Jackson are as vivid as ever in the granite mountain, but the
imprint of the Klan has faded. In the January Smithsonian ($4),
writer Minna Morse talks to some of the town's 7,000 residents and
finds that, despite a number of Confederates in the attic, racism
is fast becoming a thing of the past. Stone Mountain's first black
mayor, Chuck Burris, says he hopes the world begins looking at the
mountain ``not as a symbol of racial hatred, but as a symbol of
racial healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the future: The Force will be with us _ again _ when the
``Star Wars'' prequel, ``The Phantom Menace,'' opens in theaters
May 21. In a rare interview, director George Lucas talks to Vanity
Fair ($3.95) about the film many in Hollywood expect to eclipse
``Titanic'' as the biggest money-maker of all time. If early
interest is any indication, the predictions are true. In New York
City, when three theaters showed a trailer for ``The Phantom
Menace,'' grown men took the day off from work to commute 90
minutes from Connecticut to witness the two-minute preview paired
with the dud ``Meet Joe Black.'' Starring Ewan McGregor as a young
Obi-Wan Kenobi and Liam Neeson as Qui-Con Jinn, the Jedi knight's
mentor, the film will introduce the typical ``Star Wars''
menagerie. One of Qui-Con Jinn's sidekicks is Jar Jar Binks, an
upright lizard, and Darth Maul, a menacing villain with a tattooed
face, will engage Obi-Wan in at least one light-saber battle. Annie
Leibovitz's dazzling pictures of the actors at work should whip
``Star Wars'' fans into a frenzy of anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Southern lit: It's amazing what an influx of cash will do.
Cushioned with contributions from publisher John Grisham, The
Oxford American ($5.25) keeps getting better. In the
January/February issue, the literary magazine publishes ``Young
Nuclear Physicist,'' a previously unpublished short story by the
late Walker Percy. The story centers on Ralph Budd, a homesick
Southerner in New York City, who takes out a personal ad in a
literary magazine. When he is flooded with responses, ``Ralph
reflected that he had discovered a new law in the economy of human
relations: that one makes a gain in the social field only with a
certain loss of dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   In another article of note, John Shelton Reed weighs in on
Atlanta's reaction to Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' with the
admonition that the city's residents should rejoice about being the
focus of the best-selling novel.
</P>
<P>
   More lit: Launching a magazine in the current crowded market is
a risky proposition. Launching a magazine about books is even
riskier. But three months after the premiere of Book ($4.95), the
Chicago-based publication has been chosen one of the year's
successful new magazines by Samir Husni, author of ``Guide to New
Consumer Magazines.'' With the returned popularity of reading,
Husni says, ``there's a better chance now than ever before that
this magazine will make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who loves books should embrace the new issue. In addition
to a cover story on T. Coraghessan Boyle, the magazine reprints
John Updike's address at the National Book Awards and looks at the
use _ and overuse _ of highly technical details in novels by
Patricia Cornwell, Tom Clancy and others. Other articles worth
reading include interviews with Haitian author Edwidge Danticat and
sci-fi master Ray Bradbury and a piece on the pros and cons of
using professional group leaders in book clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Apocalypse pretty soon: Despite groups of cult members marching
with signs proclaiming ``The End of the World,'' the chances of
Armageddon are pretty slim, Time ($2.95) reports. Yes, the Y2K bug
will cause a few glitches, but there's no need for anyone to cash
in his or her 401(k) funds, buy dehydrated food and move into a
cave. Well, not unless you're from Montana or you're a follower of
TV evangelist Pat Robertson, who insists that President Clinton
might use the predicted computer chaos as an opportunity to seize
power as a dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Radio ringmaster: Don Imus regularly skewers the high and mighty
on his syndicated radio show, and yet guests such as NBC's Andrea
Mitchell and ABC's Cokie Roberts keep returning. Even New York
Times columnist Maureen Dowd, incensed with Imus' airing of her
love life, admitted she would be back, Newsweek ($3.50) reports in
its cover story on the talk show host. Imus' secret, says Mitchell,
is his ability ``to get us to say what we really think. It's like
the conversation you have with your sources before the mike goes
on, before it gets all solemn.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
