<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An empty cage leaves an empty spot in our hearts and our daily
routine
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ground was hard from two nights of cold, and an
old shovel was the best we had. I wasn't able to attend the
service, held beneath a pair of tall loblolly pines in the back
yard, but arrived in time to see my son spreading mulch and then a
thick blanket of dead leaves over the spot. It was there they had
dug deep enough for the Starbucks box in which they wrapped her.
</P>
<P>
   Noah, I was told afterward, presided over the interment, his
mother and sister also present. One by one they offered their
thoughts on the solemn occasion, and then laid her to rest.
</P>
<P>
   There was no autopsy, no known cause of death, no sign of foul
play. Most likely, she had come to the end of her natural cycle and
that was it. A guinea pig lives about six years, and this one lived
four of them with us.
</P>
<P>
   I had opposed the idea from the start, knowing it would be left
to me to keep food in the bowl and water in the dispenser. I told
them so the first time I found both empty, and the second time and
the third time. I told them so and told them so.
</P>
<P>
   With pets come responsibilities, but gradually, and rather to my
surprise, they were carried out with reasonable regularity.
Cleaning the cage was always the one that got left to last, and it
was the one I wasn't going to do. I would feed her, and did. I
would clean and refill the water dispenser that hung from the side
of the cage, and did that also.
</P>
<P>
   In time, although I never admitted it, they became a routine
from which I took a private satisfaction _ so much so that I'd
sometimes tell Noah, ``Don't worry about Ginny. I know how busy you
are. I'll feed her and fill the water up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was fine with him, and it won me points for chipping in
with the chores.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first death in our family, only the least
significant. My children and I had returned home from a holiday in
Asheville, N.C., my wife staying behind, when I heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any interesting mail?'' I asked once the bags were unloaded
and in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but there was one thing _ Ginny died,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   She could see it caught me short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I filled her water on Friday,'' she said, ``and noticed on
Saturday she hadn't drunk much. Then, this morning, I looked again
and she was in her little hutch, on her side. I felt her and she
was stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife gently lifted her out of the cage in which she nibbled
daily at the green pellets in her bowl, snoozed at will and
daydreamed whatever guinea pigs daydream about and laid her in the
cardboard box for burial later. It fit her just right. She weighed
about 1 pound, most of it fur.
</P>
<P>
   With us, personal effects are left behind and it falls to
someone else to sort through them, not always certain what they
might have meant to us, discarding some, passing others along to
survivors for whom they sometimes are clues to thoughts
unexpressed.
</P>
<P>
   No such inventorying attends the death of a pet. You gather up
the accouterments of its existence for curbside pickup or, perhaps,
someone else's pet. In our case, these included a cage, a bowl and
water dispenser, a plastic canister in which her food was stored.
It was 10 minutes' work, no more.
</P>
<P>
   E.B. White once wrote of the death of a pig _ the kind that
squeals and gives bacon and ham, not this kind _ on his farm in
Maine and of the ``directness and dispatch about animal burial.''
The postmortems are businesslike and no one marks the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there is a sense of absence if not bereavement. Our
son's bedroom is across a hall from ours, and to the left. Passing
it in the mornings I was in the habit of glancing in and noticing
the cage in the corner. For a few days afterward I had to remind
myself that there was no need to check on the water anymore or the
food.
</P>
<P>
   On the kitchen island, a wedge of apple _ an occasional treat,
as rapaciously consumed as a child's dessert _ still reminds me of
her quick movements when a break from her unappetizing,
nutritionally balanced meal was dropped into the cage. It was the
only time I saw her move with alacrity. Seizing it in her jaws,
she'd scurry through the tunnel into the covered hutch where she
slept. To her, it must have been a hidey hole, safe from the world.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the neighborhood word passed quickly. Next door,
Stephanie Nash, 4, was upset; she enjoyed coming over, holding her
and stroking her. The pet manuals say guinea pigs like this,
although I was content to let the children do it.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, Sarah Tyler, 10, was likewise sad. But she
was busy with a burial of her own. Her frog died, quite
unexpectedly. Ours is a cul-de-sac crowded with kids. They will
have other pets, grow up and move on, leaving behind them the
unmarked graves where they learned that life is transitory and, for
that reason, all the more precious.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
