<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox Theatre has become `Cats' cradle
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta, international city, can put another feather
in its cap: It has hosted the touring show of ``Cats'' more than
anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're not among the 20,000 ticket holders for this week's
run, beginning tonight at the Fox Theatre, don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   The Andrew Lloyd Webber musical is virtually assured of
returning in 2000, according to Theater of the Stars producer
Christopher B. Manos.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the recent release of the ``Cats'' video has done
little to slow metro ticket sales for the show, Broadway's
longest-running musical and poster pet for blockbuster
whimsicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I've looked at how well sales are going in Atlanta
as a barometer of how `Cats' is going to sell elsewhere,'' says Jim
Kerber, the show's press representative. ``The city sets the trend
for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In feline celebration, we offer a numerical look at the show
that just won't stay away:
</P>
<P>
   13 _ The number of times the national touring company has come
to the Fox. (Memphis, in second place, has hosted it 10 times.)
</P>
<P>
   165 _ The number of cities to host the musical more than once.
</P>
<P>
   2 _ The number of cast members in this production from the metro
area: Jennifer Paige Chambers, who plays Cassandra, is from
Lawrenceville (Ga.). David Kirby of Atlanta is a standby for four
roles.
</P>
<P>
   7 _ The number of Tony Awards the show won in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   1981 _ The year ``Cats'' opened in London's West End, where it
is still playing.
</P>
<P>
   4,518 _ The number of seats at the Fox Theatre for ``Cats,'' the
largest venue at which the national tour performs. (The 900-seat
Lexington Opera House in Kentucky is the smallest.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats'' runs tonight through Sunday. $41-$19 at Ticketmaster.
Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E. , Atlanta, Ga. 404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
