<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    David Lynch plotting return to series TV
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ David Lynch, the filmmaker whose TV series
``Twin Peaks'' was one of the most talked-about shows ever before
it crashed and burned, is developing a new series for ABC called
``Mulholland Drive,'' named after a famous Los Angeles road. The
pilot starts shooting next month for a possible date on ABC's fall
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vintage David Lynch _ very reminiscent of `Twin Peaks,'
'' said Stu Bloomberg, chairman of ABC Entertainment, speaking to
the nation's TV critics here. But he added that Lynch and ABC
learned some lessons from the unraveling of ``Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has it really mapped out,'' said Bloomberg. ``He said,
`There are things if I had to do it over again I'd do differently.
I want to correct the mistakes I made with this new show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said ``Mulholland'' will have a large cast, like
``Peaks,'' and will have some of its characters in show business.
</P>
<P>
   Also ahead for ABC this fall:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Once Again,'' a drama created by Ed Zwick (co-producer of
``Shakespeare in Love'') and Marshall Herskovitz, about a divorced
couple who get a second chance at their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Snoops,'' a drama about private eyes from David E. Kelley.
Kelley says he will create the show and then let others write it,
so he can concentrate on writing ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The
Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``True Love,'' a romantic comedy starring Adam Goldberg
(``Saving Private Ryan'') and Julie Delpy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Guide,'' a comedy about relationships starring Christine
Taylor (``The Brady Bunch Movie'').
</P>
<P>
   And one that we won't be seeing: The proposed sitcom that would
reunite Mary Tyler Moore and Valerie Harper is officially dead.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
