<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some of musics greats in Atlanta for the Trumpet Awards
 &HT;    By Lyle Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Motown great Smokey Robinson will be there. Ditto
opera's Jessye Norman. And TV's Bryant Gumbel, model Tyra Banks,
track star Jackie Joyner Kersee, Rep. John Lewis, gospel's Kirk
Franklin and producer Debbie Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, they'll all be at CNN Center's Omni Hotel for TBS'
seventh annual Trumpet Awards, honoring African-American
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, Norman and Gumbel are winners of this year's awards
along with philanthropist Matel Dawson Jr., who in 1996 donated
$240,000 to the United Negro College Fund, and Eunice W. Johnson,
producer and director of the Ebony Fashion Fair.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton has sent a special video
message to the group (taped Thursday at the White House).
</P>
<P>
   This year's Trumpets also honor sports figures in the first-ever
Circle of Athletes. They are Joyner Kersee, football coach Eddie
Robinson and baseball great John ``Buck'' O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Other honorees are Dorothy Height, head of the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights, who'll get the Living Legend Award;
Lewis (D-Ga.), who'll receive the Pinnacle Award; and the late
Frank Sinatra, for his contributions to the careers of stars such
as Sammy Davis Jr. and
</P>
<P>
   Diahann Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Co-hosts for the invitation-only event are Allen and NAACP
leader Kweisi Mfume. Among the presenters: Banks, Franklin, May May
Ali and radio host Tom Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   The Trumpets, first handed out in 1993, were created by TBS
consultant Xernona Clayton. The event will be televised Feb. 21 on
TBS.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
