<SLUG> BC-US-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP TO EXPLORE STRATEGIC DEFENSE OF ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ High-ranking US and Israeli officials will meet in
Washington Tuesday to begin outlining a higher level of formal
cooperation on the defense and deterrence capabilities of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called joint strategic planning committee was created by
an almost unnoticed provision of the Wye Plantation Agreement,
which was signed at the White House last October. The memorandum of
agreement marks the first time that leaders of both countries have
signed a formal document of cooperation on Israeli security against
weapons of mass destruction. Their signatures are more significant,
officials said, than the more celebrated ``hiccups'' in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Uzi Arad, the foreign policy adviser to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, outlined the agreement for the new commission
in a talk with foreign policy specialists Monday at Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government in Cambridge. The agreement, noting
the threats of biological and nuclear weapons posed by a growing
number of countries, commits the United States and Israel to
achieving two specific goals: enhancing Israel's defense and
deterrent power; and ``upgrading'' military, strategic, and
technical cooperation between the US National Security Council and
the Defense and State departments, and their counterparts in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about to cross the threshold from a partnership to a
virtual strategic alliance,'' Arad said. ``Clearly there is a
desire to move to an elevated stage in our cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of the agreement is very far reaching,'' said
Graham Allison, the director of the Belfer Center for Science and
International Affairs at the Kennedy School, where Arad spoke to a
group of international security specialists. ``This is a major step
in the Israeli relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists questioned the benefits of the cooperation,
suggesting it could entangle the United States in Middle East
conflicts without providing any significant benefit.
</P>
<P>
   But Arad said the agreement was necessary to stop the
proliferation of biological weapons, and Russian sales to Iran of
materials and expertise to make nuclear weapons, which he
characterized as an even greater threat to Mideast security than
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``How will you deter another Saddam, perhaps better equipped?''
he asked. ``That is the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions against Iran, he said, have not stopped the sale of
technology and expertise from Russia. Instead, those sales have
moved underground through different countries, or simply continued
in defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``For commercial reasons, or strategic reasons, it has gotten
deeper,'' Arad said.
</P>
<P>
   A former Mossad official educated in the United States, Arad
defended his country against accusations that it was too nervous
about the threat from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to err on the side of underestimation and denial,'' he
said. In fact, he added, Israel has ignored for too long the
Iranian creation of the Shihad 3 short-range missle and is now
scrambling to improve its defense against a newer threat, the
Shihad 4.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the policy experts at the Belfar Center, which has
for several years cooperated in a so-called ``strategic dialogue''
with Israeli academics, questioned whether the agreement favors
Israel at the expense of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad public conversations, its almost embarrassing to
ask,'' Allison said, echoing the comments of several of his
colleagues. ``But it's the right question to ask: What's in it for
the US?''
</P>
<P>
   To that, Arad responded, ``The United States and Israel have a
joint interest in stability in the Middle East. Finding ways and
means to stabilize the Middle East in the face of developing
threats from missile and unconventional weapons in the possession
of rogue governments, we should be as partners.''
</P>
<P>
   The precedent concerned some at Harvard Monday. Other countries,
they said, could claim to be equally threatened by nuclear or
biological weapons and demand similar agreements with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense of being threatened is very genuine,'' Arad replied.
``I don't think there is any country in the world that has the same
kind of animosity and real threat as opposed to imagined threat,
than Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's meeting in Washington, representatives of the
National Security Council, the State Department and the Department
of Defense will plan the agenda for a more formal meeting in the
United States in February. At that time, officials will formulate
specific recommendations for cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
