<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS SECONDARY WILL TRY TO DISRUPT TESTAVERDE'S RHYTHM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Denver Broncos' strong safety, Tyrone Braxton, said
he knows how to bring out the worst in Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a great quarterback, but he's a streaky
quarterback,'' Braxton said Monday. ``You need to get pressure on
him where you get him in a bad rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, though, Braxton acknowledged that his opinion is
based on getting Testaverde, the Jets' quarterback, to revert back
to old habits, aware that the story line has changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't throw as many interceptions as he used to, so
that's going to be frustrating for us,'' Braxton said. ``We need to
be in the right place to make the plays when we have the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' pass defense has been viewed as the team's weak
link. But last weekend, it sent the Miami Dolphins' Dan Marino home
with a touchdown-less two-interception day in a 38-3 loss at
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five cornerbacks who can start for other teams, and I
don't think any other team can say that,'' cornerback Tito Paul
said. ``Plus both our safeties are Pro Bowlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this criticism has kind of taken us aback. We think it was
unfair and unwarranted. We've got pretty much the same secondary
that won the Super Bowl last season.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton, a 12-year pro, is again a big part of it. He was
replaced late in the preseason by rookie Eric Brown, was a backup
for much of the year but is a starter again.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday's American Football Conference championship game
against the Jets will be his 18th National Football League playoff
game, his fifth for the conference title. He played on Denver's AFC
championship clubs in 1987, '89 and '97 and on the '91 team that
reached the title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have an experienced player like Tyrone,'' said
Coach Mike Shanahan. ``Not only has he played well, but he's played
exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton, 34, is just glad he did not allow his confidence to
wane once he suffered the embarrassment of being replaced by a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a down time for sure, because I didn't feel like I was
contributing,'' he said. ``I was making a play here or a play
there, but it just wasn't the same feeling I've had _ each game
making a lot of plays. But I just had to adjust _ and stay ready _
and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton has only one other notable blot on his resume. He spent
much of the 1994 season languishing in Miami with the Dolphins,
having signed with them as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But the time in Miami may have saved his career. The Dolphins
moved him from cornerback to strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got to practice at safety without getting any pressure on
me, against one of the best quarterbacks ever in Dan Marino,'' he
said. ``When I came back here to compete for a job, it was like I
had played safety for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Braxton sees it, Denver's pass defense will determine
the team's fate on Sunday. And he's quite aware that the Jets have
a 1,000-yard rusher in Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been great against the run all year, so there's no
reason for me to believe we can't stop their run,'' he said. ``The
pass, we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton believes the sellout crowd at 76,273-seat Mile High
Stadium will give the Broncos a distinct advantage no matter what
plays the Jets use. He said the crowd noise ``will be at a whole
another level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to use hand signals, because it's going to be so loud
it won't do any good to yell,'' Braxton said. ``No one can hear you
out there. So we'll work on getting our hand signals down.''
</P>
<P>
   Braxton said it's no coincidence that veteran quarterbacks will
guide the teams in both conference title games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need some leadership because in a playoff game, anything
can happen,'' he said. ``You practice certain plays during the week
that you want to run, but then they always come out with something
different. You've got to be able to adjust, and you need a
quarterback who can adjust on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, the Broncos showed the 37-year-old Marino some
new coverages. And despite Marino's 16 years in the league, the
Dolphins were never in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Braxton promised that the Broncos will have a little something
different to show Testaverde. ``We'll see how he adjusts,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
