<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BIKO-NYT </SLUG>
 
A KILLER's IGNORANCE ADDS POIGNANCY TO BIKO CASE 
 (rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The release Monday of the full text
of a decision to deny amnesty to a police officer involved in the
death of the anti-apartheid activist Steve Biko contains an
interesting twist on history: The officer, who helped kill Biko in
1977, may have had no idea how important he was.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation
Commission found that the officer's amnesty application failed on
two grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Since he said the police had tackled Biko in self-defense, he
did not admit to a crime, so he could not be pardoned for one. And
by maintaining that he knew little about Biko, the founder of the
Black Consciousness Movement, the officer could not plead political
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for amnesty, the officer would have had to prove that
his crime was committed to suppress the anti-apartheid movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not satisfied that the application in respect of the
death of Mr . Biko complies with the act, and consequently, the
application is refused,'' said the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Gideon Nieuwoudt, who is in jail for other crimes,
maintained that Biko became violent, and that the officers were
defending themselves when they ``accidentally'' rammed his head
into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Biko's injuries were apparent almost right away, the officers
said. But for days he was left handcuffed in a ``crucifix''
position. Eventually driven a great distance for treatment, he died
before receiving any.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Nieuwoudt could face prosecution in the case. But
murder charges would require proving intent, and the statute of
limitations on lesser charges has run out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
