<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORE ANTIAIRCRAFT INCIDENTS IN NORTH IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American fighter jets attacked antiaircraft
batteries in northern Iraq in two skirmishes Monday as Baghdad
continued its defiance of American and British control of its
skies.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the American fighters had attacked after the
batteries had tracked them with radar, apparently in preparation to
fire. But the Iraqi antiaircraft forces did not fire, and the jets
returned safely to their base at Incirlik, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the strikes destroyed the batteries,
the Pentagon said, because of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's incidents fit an increasingly familiar pattern. Almost
every day now, Iraqi aircraft or antiaircraft weapons are
challenging American and British jets patrolling the northern and
southern no-flight zones established after the Persian Gulf war in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Iraqi MIG jets entered the southern zone Monday but
quickly left, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges follow a series of defiant threats, and some
retreats, from President Saddam Hussein's government, which has
vowed to end all cooperation with United Nations, including weapons
inspections and efforts by international relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Iraqi Parliament postponed a vote to reject United
Nations resolutions, including one that established its border with
Kuwait and those that the United States cited to created the
no-flight zones to protect Kurds in Iraq's north and Shiite Muslims
in its south.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, traveling to Japan, warned
Monday that any move by Iraq to withdraw recognition of Kuwait
would be ``a flagrant violation'' of resolutions that have stood
for nearly eight years.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the United States would strike again if Saddam
threatened Kuwait or Saudi Arabia or used force to crack down on
Iraqi Kurds. ``What we have said is that to the extent that he
poses a threat or moves against Kuwait or Saudi Arabia or the Kurds
in the north, that we are prepared to respond,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they believe that Saddam is trying
to find and exploit international divisions over how to enforce the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the challenges to American and British aircraft have
done little except invite strikes on Iraq's antiaircraft weapons.
And Baghdad's public statements have exposed its isolation from
important Arab countries like Egypt and Saudi Arabia. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright is to visit those two countries this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Monday's incidents occurred Monday morning near the city
of Mosul, Pentagon officials said. In one instance, two F-15E
fighter jets fired guided missiles at an antiaircraft battery after
detecting that the Iraqis had targeted them with radar, Pentagon
officials said. An F-16 fired a radar-seeking missile at an SA-6
surface-to-air missile launcher, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the commander of American forces in the region, Gen.
Anthony Zinni, announced that the United States would bolster its
force in the region. Eight more F-16s and four aerial refuelers
will join 182 aircraft now enforcing the southern no-flight zone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
