<SLUG> BC-MA-GREEN-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN GROUPS EYE CELLUCCI BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HILARY SARGENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A statewide coalition of environmental groups Monday
urged Governor Paul Cellucci to add about $20 million to next
year's state budget to protect water, curb sprawl, and ensure
``environmental justice'' in poor communities plagued by pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still playing catch-up in terms of dollars for
environmental programs,'' said Namrita Kapur, legislative director
for the Environmental League. ``New problems and responsibilities
have arisen over the last decade, but the environmental budget has
actually lost ground.''
</P>
<P>
   At a State House press conference, the coalition released its
recommendations for increased environmental funding in the Green
Budget 2000, which it hopes will influence Cellucci as he prepares
to submit his first budget later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended increase of $19.4 million calls for increased
support in three areas _ water quality, land use, and environmental
justice. These priorities reflect the consensus view among the
state's main environmental lobbies on where the state should focus
environmental funding.
</P>
<P>
   Kapur said insufficient environmental funding has created a
``deficit,'' but called the Green Budget a ``modest proposal'' that
would address the deficit over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed recommendations for water quality include $1.9 million
in pollution prevention, $1.5 million to enforce the federal Clean
Water Act, and $1 million to control non-native aquatic species
often responsible for clogging rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Massachusetts' increasing loss of farmland and open space
to development, the Green Budget calls for a $2 million increase to
fund farm preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental League also referred to environmental justice,
and called for $2 million in improvements at the state's
Metropolitan District Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about communities usually economically
disadvantaged, that are bearing a disproportionate burden of
unwanted environmental impacts,'' said Sha-King Alston, executive
director of the Environmental Diversity Forum. ``We have to do a
better job of making sure that poor communities and communities of
color have access to the resources to address and prevent
environmental problems,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposed increases included $925,000 for public tree
planting and $1 million to help local conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the governor followed the recommendations ``almost
line item for line item,'' Kapur said. ``I expect an even warmer
reception than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Durand, who Monday was sworn in as secretary of the
Office of Environmental Affairs, said that the Green Budget's
priorities are similar to his.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to work within the administration's budget,
but obviously there are priorities that I care about, and that the
administration cares about,'' Durand said. ``I think the governor
fully understands the need to protect our land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
