<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ENGLISH-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT DEALS FINAL BLOW TO SWEEPING ENGLISH-ONLY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ill., Pa.)  (jw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday turned down a
last-ditch defense of an Arizona law requiring public employees to
speak only English on the job. Without comment, the justices let
stand a ruling by the Arizona Supreme Court that the measure, the
most sweeping of two dozen state ``English-only'' laws, was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The state itself declined to defend the law, which has been a
divisive issue ever since Arizona voters approved it as a voter
initiative in 1988 by a bare 50.5 percent majority. Earlier,
Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods had interpreted the law
narrowly to require only that official state acts be pronounced in
English, and had defended it on that basis.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona Supreme Court, in its ruling in April, said the
measure had to be given its literal meaning, to require English to
be used by ``all government officials and employees during the
performance of government business.'' Read so broadly, the law
raised ``constitutional problems,'' Woods told the justices in a
brief that Gov. Jane Dee Hull joined.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal from the state Supreme Court ruling was filed by
Arizonans for Official English, the group that had sponsored the
initiative. The state court had deprived the government of the
right to control its own speech, the group told the justices. The
group's brief said that, contrary to the conclusion of the Arizona
Supreme Court, the law presented no problem under the First
Amendment because it involved no effort to control the content of
employees' speech.
</P>
<P>
   The state court held the measure violated the First Amendment
``by depriving elected officials and public employees of the
ability to communicate with their constituents and with the
public.'' Even when state employees are willing and able to speak
with residents whose English proficiency is limited, ``meaningful
communication in those cases is barred,'' the court said, also
ruling that the law violated the constitutional guarantee of equal
protection as well as the right to petition the government and to
participate in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two states have made English their official language,
most since the English-only political movement gained force in the
mid-1980s. Most of the laws are essentially symbolic statements,
however, and do not impose restrictions on employees' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time the Arizona law came before the Supreme
Court. Two years ago, the justices agreed to hear an appeal from a
federal court decision striking down the law, but dismissed the
case after deciding that it was moot; the Spanish-speaking state
employee who had challenged the law had left her job.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, a parallel lawsuit was working its way through the
state courts, brought by a group of elected officials, state
employees and a public school teacher. Once the state Supreme Court
had ruled and the state itself declined to appeal, it was a
question of some doubt whether the private group had standing to
pursue the appeal. The justices avoided that question Monday by
declining to hear the case, Arizonans for Official English vs.
Arizona, No. 98-167.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These were among the other cases the court dealt with Monday.
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE CAN SEARCH
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court refused to consider a case raising
the issue of whether police have the right to conduct a warrantless
search of a homeowner's trash when the trash can is adjacent to the
house or garage, well within the property line.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1988 case, the court upheld the search of a garbage can
left at the curb. But in the case Monday, an appeal from a
narcotics conviction, an ordinance in Urbana, Ill., prohibited
leaving trash at the curb, so Joseph Redmon, the owner of a town
house, placed his can for collection at the top of his 28-foot-long
driveway. A drug task force, which had him under surveillance,
searched the trash and found evidence of cocaine. That enabled the
agents to get a warrant to search the house, where they found more
incriminating evidence and arrested Redmon.
</P>
<P>
   The case produced a sharp split on the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago, which upheld the search and conviction by an
8-5 vote with several vigorously argued opinions. ``Most urban
dwellers would be shocked to learn that the portion of a driveway
immediately adjacent to the garage door is considered by this court
to be an `open field,' '' Judge Ilana Rovner said in one of the
dissenting opinions. Under Supreme Court precedents, police do not
need a warrant to search an open field. The case Monday was Redmon
vs. U.S., No. 98-243.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ABORTION MESSAGE
</P>
<P>
   Also without comment, the court turned down an appeal by the
Philadelphia public transportation agency from a federal court
ruling that it violated the First Amendment rights of an
anti-abortion group when it removed the group's posters from 25
subway and rail stations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The posters, for which Christ's Bride Ministries Inc. had
contracted and paid, contained the message: ``Women who choose
abortion suffer more &AMP; deadlier breast cancer.'' After obtaining a
letter from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services that
this health claim was misleading, inaccurate, and ``unduly
alarming,'' the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority
canceled the contract.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion in June, 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Philadelphia ruled that the agency's previous acceptance of ads on
abortion had established a public forum on the issue and prevented
the agency from censoring a particular message. The case was SEPTA
vs. Christ's Bride Ministries, No. 98-654.
</P>
</TEXT>
