<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS DEBATING WHEN TO INTRODUCE CENSURE RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-RULES) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just days before opening arguments in the
impeachment trial of President Clinton begin in the Senate,
Democrats are debating when would be the best time to try to put
forward a censure resolution, with some advocating sooner rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats argued on Monday that a resolution would stand a
stronger chance of passing immediately after opening arguments and
the first series of votes, tentatively scheduled for Jan. 26 _ one
on a motion to dismiss the charges, followed immediately by a
motion to depose witnesses. But many Republicans who oppose censure
and even Democrats who support it dismissed the prospect of a deal
so early in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The first vote on dismissing the charges, which is unlikely to
garner the simple majority required to pass, would nevertheless
serve as an indicator of whether the Senate can muster the 67 votes
needed to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If it is clear that the Senate does not have the votes to
convict at that time, an outcome many senators have predicted from
the start, several Democrats say it would provide the perfect
opportunity to push for a tough censure deal that may draw
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that brokering a deal on censure would be most likely
to succeed before taking an up-or-down vote on whether to convict
or acquit Clinton for perjury and obstruction of justice. They
contend that if Clinton were already acquitted, he would not be
inclined to accept a censure deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have a greater chance to build a bipartisan
coalition if the case is dismissed,'' said Sen. Robert G.
Torricelli, D-N.J. ``After acquittal, it may be difficult to build
a majority for censure.''
</P>
<P>
   There are as many as six different censure resolutions being
drafted by Democrats. The final resolution would likely embrace the
prevailing ideas in all of them to formulate one central proposal,
and is likely not to include any sort of fine or penalty that
Clinton would have to sign off on.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and some Democrats counter that the push for an
early censure resolution is likely to fail so early in the
proceedings. The idea is further complicated by the fact that any
censure resolution would require the cooperation of Sen. Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the majority leader, who is not disposed to turn to
censure so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans, and a few Democrats, oppose censure, either
because they view it as setting a bad precedent and unnecessary in
the wake of a deciding vote on Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that that's in the cards,'' said Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, D-Conn. ``I don't think you will get people to support a
combination of motion to dismiss and a censure right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Democrats would have a better chance drawing
Republican support for censure after an up-or-down vote on whether
to convict or acquit Clinton. It is highly unlikely that 67
senators would vote to convict Clinton _ there are 45 Democrats and
55 Republicans in the Senate _ but it would nevertheless give many
Republicans what they desire: a chance to vote to convict and
remove Mr. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, some of them may be willing to soften their
position on censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of dealing with the issue of censure, a lot of people
really want to bring the impeachment trial to closure before
consideration of censure,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe, a moderate
Republican from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Another moderate Republican, Sen. John H. Chafee of Rhode
Island, agreed. Censure, he said, ``ought to be postponed until we
have completed the work assigned to us under the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats pushing an early censure proposal return to the
argument that prospects for a tough censure resolution dim
significantly if and when Clinton is acquitted; Clinton may not be
willing to negotiate once he is off the hook, they say.
</P>
<P>
   What the Senate would likely wind up with, they say, is a
watered down ``sense of the Senate resolution'' that would be
earmarked for oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think Republicans would conclude that the best time to
exact a pound of flesh, the only time to exact a pound of flesh is
at the moment it is clear he won't be convicted and before the case
goes to a vote,'' said one Democratic senator.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who is not keen on censure, said he
would be willing to agree to a censure resolution immediately after
the first votes.
</P>
<P>
   It is at that time, he said, that ``you still have leverage over
the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
