A8687 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LEGISLATURE-HNS     01-11 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LEGISLATURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S PRESIDENTIAL AMBITIONS MAY PUT 76TH LEGISLATURE UNDER
SPOTLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ending an 18-month lull in lawmaking, the 76th
Legislature will be sworn in at noon Tuesday in family-oriented,
standing-room-only ceremonies in the House and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Though pomp and circumstance will dominate Capitol activities
for several weeks, the session will eventually get down to the
serious business of mapping a two-year spending plan; exploring
tax-relief options and dealing with a rare surplus of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Other contentious issues on the agenda include electric utility
deregulation and proposals to allow state-funded vouchers for
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   When the debates begin in earnest, leaders believe the
Legislature will be under a national media spotlight because of the
presidential ambitions of Gov. George W. Bush, who insists he won't
be distracted from his goals of lowering taxes, improving schools
and promoting a conservative agenda that includes toughening
welfare and abortion rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we meet the basic needs, it's important for us to have a
tax cut,'' Bush declared. He's hoping that disputes over how to
spend surplus tax revenues and a multibillion-dollar tobacco
settlement don't mar the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 181 opinions coming, most of whom are fresh off
elections, and it's going to be an interesting session,'' Bush
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a Democrat, will preside over the
GOP-dominated Senate until the Jan. 19 inauguration of his
successor, Rick Perry, a Republican. This week the only essential
business on the Senate agenda is to adopt operating rules that
Perry predicted will not change dramatically from the 1997 session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to balance a lot of competing interests. I'm going
to balance competing philosophies,'' Perry said, adding that
non-Texans might be tuning in as the session progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in a special spotlight and that's fine. We'll show
the rest of the country how we address some of these important
issues, like our children's education and electric deregulation,''
Perry added.
</P>
<P>
   The 150-member House will be sworn in by Bush's new Secretary of
State Elton Bomer, who took his own oath Monday. Then the House,
which still has a slight Democratic majority, will elect one of its
own _ Rep. Pete Laney, D-Hale Center _ to a fourth two-year term as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them seem to be ready to go to work. Eager,'' said
Laney, whose chamber includes a cross-section of Texans _ lawyers,
teachers, businessmen, ranchers and homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Laney expects no major changes in his chamber's rules, though he
said members will take steps to avert the procedural flaws that
nullify measures when they reach the House floor. He said a new
system of bill analysis is being crafted to reduce the number of
fatal ``points of order,'' which are objections based on
parliamentary mistakes during the committee review process.
</P>
<P>
   Though the session's opening week might not be substantive, it
will allow members to get acquainted, move into offices and
organize staffs. The 25 new House members and two new senators will
be introduced to colleagues. Numerous newly elected GOP statewide
office-holders will be making the rounds, as will scores of the
1,400 registered lobbyists and citizens here to support their
elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Both legislative chambers could see significant changes in key
committee and leadership assignments, and members are anxiously
waiting to find out if they won chairmanships or appointments to
prestigious roles on the House Appropriations Committee and the
Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Perry reveals his committee structure next week, but Laney isn't
predicting when he'll make public his selections. For now, it's all
being mapped out the old-fashioned way _ on a bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   The 140-day session ends May 31, Memorial Day. Lawmakers have
until mid-March to file bills without special permission from
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
