u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT     01-11 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT FIRST, JETS WILL BE IN A MENTAL GAME WITH BRONCOS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ It has been so long since they have let a game
get away from them _ back on Nov. 15, at Indianapolis _ that the
Jets have forgotten what it is like to lose their heads, or become
distracted, or get in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   That memory loss _ and the confidence that comes from it _ could
be the biggest factor of all in as they prepare for Sunday's
American Football Conference title game in Denver. Most teams have
been crushed by the Broncos before they even get warm, a pitfall
the Jets will have to avoid if they want to compete against a team
that has outscored the opposition in the first half by an
astounding 321-144.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go there thinking we have to score points to
win,'' Jets Coach Bill Parcells said Monday, a day after his team
advanced in the playoffs with a 34-24 victory over Jacksonville.
``Any team can be aggressive when it has the lead. The other team
presses a bit more. You have to stop that from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have a good halftime record themselves, with a 220-145
scoring edge. And they have been competitive in every game they
played except a 30-10 loss at St. Louis, a game in which Vinny
Testaverde replaced Glenn Foley at quarterback, then took over as
the starter.
</P>
<P>
   In those games, the Jets were never far behind, and it allowed
them to continue to run Curtis Martin. Most teams have to crank up
a passing game when they fall behind, abandoning the running game
and allowing the opponent to concentrate on the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has kept the club out of trouble while the Jets
patiently produced comebacks. Since he took over as the starter in
Game 6, the Jets have trailed at halftime only twice _ by 4 points
at New England and by 8 at the Meadowlands against Seattle. The
Jets came back to win both times. Testaverde overall record as a
starter is 13-1.
</P>
<P>
   That is a trait the Broncos' opposition has not shown this year,
although Denver defeated only five clubs with winning records,
including a crushing 38-3 defeat of Miami in their playoff game
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While several Jets spoke respectfully about the Broncos'
performance against Miami _ ``Wow!'' said Chad Cascadden _ the
players also felt that the Dolphins failed to show any aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``After winning in Kansas City, Miami, Buffalo and New
England,'' said fullback Keith Byars, ``we don't have to go on the
road and wonder if we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Parcells sounded upbeat Monday about the prospects of
a good effort against the defending champions. His team put on a
powerful offensive show, and did not allow several mental and
physical blips to stop them from defeating the Jaguars in what was
the first playoff game for more than half the Jets. It was also
their seventh straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a quick start will be the Jets' game plan, Parcells said
Monday. In fact, aggressiveness has become a Jets' trademark in
Parcells' two seasons. That and an ability to control the clock.
</P>
<P>
   This season's Jets have an extremely high third-down completion
percentage _ 46 percent _ and a better-than four minutes' edge in
time of possession. Would this help against the Broncos?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only if we score,'' said Parcells. ``We'll have to be prepared
to score, but it's the same for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He is conceding nothing to the Broncos, a team he has faced only
twice in the 1990s. Both games occurred when Parcells coached the
Patriots and Mike Shanahan coached the Broncos, and both were
Denver routs. Parcells was not putting too much stock in those past
performances, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a good Patriots team the first time we played
them,'' he said. ``The second time the game got out of hand and
anyway we played them early in the season. We were a much better
team by the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have their own inconclusive history against the
Broncos. They have not defeated them in Denver since 1978. They
have only faced them in Mile High Stadium three times since. The
last one opened the 1996 season, and was won by the Broncos, 31-6,
in Neil O'Donnell's debut at Jets' quarterback. The Jets finished
that season 1-15.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Jets and Broncos have played 26 times _
dating to 1960, when they were original American Football League
members. The Jets won 12 and tied 1. Testaverde is 0-2 against the
Broncos, losing in 1994, with Cleveland, and in 1996, with
Baltimore. John Elway is 3-2 vs. the Jets, dating to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, a Parcells team did have an easy time against the
Broncos. But that was many years ago. His Giants captured Super
Bowl XXI against them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
