<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 SENATORS PUSH FOR OPEN IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Minn., Ky., Conn. Wash.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CENSURE) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Democratic senators said Monday that they would
try to change the 19th-century Senate rule that requires closed
sessions for all debates on impeachment in which senators speak,
but odds are strong that the rule will be retained.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules established in 1868 for the trial of President
Andrew Johnson and still in force, senators must sit silently while
arguments are made and witnesses are questioned in open session.
When senators discuss among themselves motions on procedures and
even the final verdict, they must retire behind closed doors. Only
the final vote would be in public.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic senators, Tom Harkin of Iowa and Paul Wellstone
of Minnesota, said at a news conference that the rule was a vestige
of a time when the Senate did most of its work in secret. Today,
most of the Senate's business is conducted not only in public but
on television, and in the case of impeachment, Wellstone
maintained, ``people in the country should have the opportunity to
watch this debate and be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other senators disagree. It would require a two-thirds
majority to change the rule. As a practical matter, Senate rules
are almost never changed except by unanimous consent.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday on CNN, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
held that the impeachment debate would be more fruitful without
instant public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are much better able to relate to each other and reach
compromises,'' McConnell said, ``when we are not under the glare of
cameras, which I must confess leads some to the temptation to
grandstand and be partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating that this position was not strictly a Republican
one, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., agreed with McConnell. On the
same CNN program, ``Late Edition,'' Dodd said, ``Nothing will
compel the Senate more to move more rapidly, in my view, than the
notion they will have to sit there gagged day after day.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican senator, Slade Gorton of Washington, said in
an interview that he was not sure deliberations on preliminary
questions should be in public but that he favored opening the final
debate on the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said the motion to change the rule would probably not be
offered for a couple of weeks _ after the opening statements by the
House managers and President Clinton's lawyers and a period set
aside for senators to pose questions to both sides by submitting
them in writing and having them read by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, the presiding officer during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said he was bringing the matter up now because he did not
think the public realized that senators would not have public
debates on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The opening statements and the question period will be in public
session and on television. But unless Harkin and Wellstone prevail,
the next big step, a debate among the senators over whether to call
witnesses, would be closed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the debate on the Harkin-Wellstone motion to change the
rule on open sessions would itself be closed. But as would be the
case with all other closed sessions in which the Senate is
officially sitting as an impeachment jury, a transcript would be
kept and presumably released quickly to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2042EST &QL; 
