A8695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NYT &LR;      01-11 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN SAYS CONTRACT EXTENSION MADE HIM A BETTER COACH  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Like Bill Parcells in New York, Dan Reeves in
Atlanta and Mike Shanahan in Denver, Dennis Green, the Minnesota
Vikings' coach, is the biggest reason his team is one step away
from the Super Bowl. Green has guided the Vikings to the National
Football Conference title game against the Falcons on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Green is also on the verge of a financial windfall. A
victory against Atlanta and then a Super Bowl victory would make
Green the highest-paid coach in the league without a general
manager title.
</P>
<P>
   There are now two tiers of head coaches in the National Football
League; those like Seattle's Mike Holmgren or Parcells, who have
final say on everything, and others, like Green, who do not have
complete control written into their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If Green reaches his final two contractual incentives, meaning
the Vikings win a championship, it will put him at the top salary
tier of the latter group of coaches. He would rank ahead of coaches
like New Orleans' Mike Ditka, who earns a salary between $1.5
million and $2 million, San Francisco's Steve Mariucci, expected to
sign a contract worth about $1.5 million a season, and New
England's Pete Carroll, who earns between $1 million and $1.5
million a season.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the Vikings' owner, Red McCombs, signed Green to
a three-year, $4.65 million contract extension. Since the Vikings
finished the regular season 15-1 and are in the conference
championship game, Green has reached many of the incentives in his
contract, making the deal much more lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   According to a person with knowledge of Green's contract, the
Vikings coach has triggered five of seven incentives in his deal,
including bonuses for making the playoffs, winning the division,
securing home-field advantage, selling out the Metrodome for each
regular-season home game and surpassing a specific number of
overall victories (the exact number is not known).
</P>
<P>
   Reaching those incentives have already netted Green an
additional $325,000 to his base salary of about $1.55 million. If
Green goes on to beat the Falcons, he would earn an additional
$125,000, and if the Vikings win the Super Bowl, he would receive
another $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's a total of $700,000 in additional money Green could earn,
putting his possible total contract over $2.2 million for this
year, pushing him well past any coach who is also not a general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches remaining in the playoffs have similar bonuses in
their contracts, but a league executive said he believed Green was
one of the few with an attendance-incentive clause.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings this year were just the third team in league history
to post 15 regular-season victories, joining the 1984 San Francisco
49ers and 1985 Chicago Bears. They set a league record for points
in a season with 556, finished undefeated at home for the first
time since 1989, and Green's regular-season winning percentage of
.634 surpassed that of Bud Grant, the former Vikings' coach who had
a .620 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the contract gave him peace of mind. He insisted that
Minnesota would not be 16-1 if he wasn't signed to a long-term deal
and was forced to be thinking about his future while trying to
coach.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, the only thing on Green's mind are the Falcons,
one of the biggest tests the Vikings have faced all year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is the only team hotter than the Vikings. While
Minnesota hasn't lost since Nov. 1 against Tampa Bay, winning eight
straight games, the Falcons are on a 20-4 run going back to last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the first thing Minnesota would have to do to stop
Atlanta was stop running back Jamal Anderson, who this year rushed
for 1,846 yards and an NFC-high 14 touchdowns. What irritated Green
was that his defense missed too many tackles against Arizona's
Adrian Murrell on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't tackle well,'' Green said after the victory.
``That's something we're really going to have to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's defensive coaches weren't happy with some other
things that happened against the Cardinals, like the two penalties
in the red zone, allowing 1-yard touchdown runs on fourth down by
Arizona backs and the failure to sack quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between good and great is extraordinary
determination,'' Vikings defensive lineman Jerry Ball said. ``We
have to do better against Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
