<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COACHES-NYT     01-11 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 NFL TEAMS HIRE COACHES; SCHOTTENHEIMER QUITS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coaching merry-go-round in the National Football League spun
wildly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rhodes, dismissed two weeks ago as coach of the Philadelphia
Eagles, was named coach of the Green Bay Packers. Andy Reid, Brett
Favre's quarterback coach with the Packers, was named to succeed
Rhodes with the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   As an extra twist, Marty Schottenheimer resigned after 10 years
of coaching the Kansas City Chiefs to great success in the regular
season but not the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A key figure in all the twists and turns was Mike Holmgren, who
left the Packers last Friday to become the coach and general
manager of the Seattle Seahawks. The Eagles wanted Holmgren to
replace Rhodes, but with Holmgren unavailable, the Eagles took
Reid, a Packer assistant for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers needed a replacement for Holmgren and seemingly
wanted someone tougher. They turned to Rhodes and gave him a
four-year contract reported to be worth $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   At Philadelphia, Reid got a five-year contract believed to pay
$1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' hiring had to please the league's hierarchy, which had
been concerned that since Tony Dungy became the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers' coach after the 1995 season, the 23 head coaches hired
were all white, and blacks had rarely been interviewed. Now the
league, which has 31 teams, again has three black head coaches _
Dennis Green of the Minnesota Vikings, Rhodes and Dungy.
</P>
<P>
   Three head-coaching vacancies remain _ with the Baltimore
Ravens, the Chicago Bears and the expansion Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Rhodes earned five Super Bowl rings as a San
Francisco 49ers assistant, coaching there with Holmgren. When
Holmgren became the Packers' coach, Rhodes went with him. In 1994,
Rhodes left the Packers to become the 49ers' defensive coordinator.
He spent the last four years with the Eagles, starting with two
10-6 seasons and playoff berths before slumping to 6-9-1 and this
season's 3-13. His final Eagles team was last in the league in both
total offense and passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay finished this season 11-5 and lost the wild-card
playoff game to the 49ers. Ron Wolf, the Packers' general manager,
had said he wanted a coach who could provide ``a little electrical
shock'' for the players. Leroy Butler, their safety and a defensive
leader, expanded on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team will be tougher,'' Butler told The Milwaukee
Journal Sentinel. ``I think last year we had a lot of games where
we weren't tough and physical enough. Guys played tight. They
weren't worried about getting cut, but getting ridiculed.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Rhodes' return to Green Bay was unexpected. The
city's black population is small, and when he left he talked of a
limited social life and his daughters' isolation and loneliness
there.
</P>
<P>
   When Rhodes was the Packers' defensive coordinator in 1992 and
1993, Reid was an assistant on the staff, and they became close
friends. Still, Reid said last week that when the Eagles approached
him he did not talk to Rhodes about the job because, he said, ``I
don't want any influence like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles also interviewed Jim Haslett, the Pittsburgh
Steelers' defensive coordinator; Dom Capers, the Carolina Panthers'
deposed head coach, and Willie Shaw, the Oakland Raiders' defensive
coordinator. The Eagles signed Reid before he could go to Seattle
as Holmgren's offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   So at 40, Reid, who had never been a head coach at any level,
became the NFL's second-youngest head coach behind 35-year-old Jon
Gruden of the Oakland Raiders. Reid also became Holmgren's fourth
assistant _ after Rhodes, Gruden and the 49ers' Steve Mariucci _ to
become an NFL head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he planned a West Coast passing offense with a
dominant quarterback, although he lacks one. But he impressed
Jeffrey Lurie, the Eagles' owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's confidence comes right at you,'' Lurie said. ``His
preparedness, his commanding presence, his sense of leadership, it
was pretty dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who needed more assurance, Reid provided it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be pretty good at it,'' he said of his
new job.
</P>
<P>
   Schottenheimer was more than pretty good at Kansas City, where
his teams posted a 101-58-1 record over 10 years, second only in
the NFL to the 49ers' 123-37. Seven of his Chiefs teams made the
playoffs, but only one reached a championship game and Kansas City
lost it.
</P>
<P>
   His teams missed the playoffs the last two years, and this
season's team, with a 7-9 record, gave him his first losing season
in his 15 years as an NFL head coach. The worst moment came in a
Monday night game in November when the Chiefs committed five
personal fouls on the Denver Broncos' last touchdown drive in a
30-7 loss. Schottenheimer apologized. Lamar Hunt, the Chiefs'
owner, said the players' actions were a disgrace to the team and
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Schottenheimer, 55, said he did not know whether he would return
to pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it boils down to is this _ 32 years in professional
football,'' he said. ``I've been coaching for 25 years. I just felt
that given 10 years to get it done and we really didn't accomplish
it, I thought it was time to let somebody else step in and take
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
