u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      01-11 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FORMALLY DENIES IMPEACHMENT CHARGES, SEEKS DISMISSAL OF
CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton formally denied the impeachment
charges against him Monday and asked the Senate to eventually
dismiss the case because it fails to meet the constitutional
standard for ending his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, all Republicans, immediately responded that
the Democratic president's behavior in trying to conceal his affair
with Monica Lewinsky ``warrants conviction and removal'' from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In a refrain made familiar long before his historic impeachment
trial opened in the Senate last week, Clinton again acknowledged
his affair with Lewinsky, a former White House intern, but denied
lying to a grand jury or obstructing justice as he tried to keep
the affair secret.
</P>
<P>
   In a 13-page response to the two articles of impeachment
approved by the House, the president said the charges ``do not rise
to the level of `high crimes and misdemeanors' as contemplated by
the founding fathers, and they do not satisfy the rigorous
constitutional standard applied through our nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   While similar to arguments by the president's legal team and
Democratic supporters during the House impeachment hearings and
debate, the response filed Monday was the first since the Senate
last week officially opened his trial.
</P>
<P>
   While denying ``each and every'' allegation in the two articles
of impeachment, Clinton decided against filing motions at this time
seeking to dismiss the case until the Senate hears arguments from
House prosecutors and his legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the House prosecutors, or managers, filed no motions.
However, the 13-member team of managers, led by Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., is expected later to seek Senate permission to call
witnesses, including Lewinsky, to bolster the case against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart was asked whether the
president would personally answer questions at his Senate trial.
``I have no reason to believe that he will testify,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial, the first of a president since Andrew
Johnson in 1868, and only the second in U.S. history, resumes later
this week with the 55 Republican and 45 Democratic senators sitting
as jurors. A two-thirds majority is needed to convict and remove a
president. A simple majority is needed to dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging some resentment among House Republicans over the
Senate's unanimous decision last week to postpone any decision on
calling witnesses, Hyde said Monday this was ``not the time to get
angry.'' The senators will weigh the House prosecutors' evidence
and arguments.
</P>
<P>
   House managers will be prepared to present ``a compelling case''
for removing Clinton and hope the Senate will later be in ``a more
generous mood'' on the question of witnesses, Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``we wouldn't want to hang our hat just on the
question of witnesses,'' the Chicago Republican said during a break
in a closed-door strategy session with his team of managers.
</P>
<P>
   The documents filed Monday by Clinton's legal team and his House
prosecutors were a preview of their trial arguments and offered no
fresh perspectives on the evidence that fueled the Dec. 19,
party-line vote in the House to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's filing, his lawyers _ six private attorneys and
five members of the White House counsel's office _ outlined a
two-pronged rebuttal to the two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   First, the allegations of perjury and obstruction of justice are
unconstitutional because they are ``too vague to permit conviction
and removal of a duly elected president,'' Clinton's lawyers argue.
In addition, several accusations are unfairly lumped together in a
series under each charge.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Clinton is innocent of the charges, his lawyers assert
in the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, they say, the charges that Clinton lied or misled
grand jurors about his relationship with Lewinsky are false.
``There is a myth about President Clinton's testimony before the
grand jury, that the president failed to admit his improper
intimate relationship with Ms. Monica Lewinsky,'' the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton denied committing perjury when he answered
questions before the grand jury about earlier testimony in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, in statements he permitted
his attorney to make in the case, and in connection with his
responses to questions about alleged efforts to influence others'
testimony in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the article alleging obstruction of justice,
Clinton denied encouraging Lewinsky to file a false affidavit in
the Jones case, encouraging her to testify falsely if called to
testify or sought to conceal evidence in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   He also denied obstructing justice by trying to help Lewinsky
secure a job in New York, by allowing his attorney to make
allegedly false statements, by relating false statements to a
potential witness, presidential secretary Betty Currie, and by
making false statements to his aides.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecution team disagreed, saying the allegations in
the articles of impeachment are examples of ``an ongoing pattern of
obstruction of justice and witness tampering over a period of
several months'' which compromised ``the integrity of the entire
judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the seriousness of the charges against Clinton, the House,
in a 105-page rebuttal to Clinton's filing, noted that two of the
three federal judges impeached in recent years ``were removed for
perjury that had nothing to do with their official duties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for the presidency as an
institution, because if the president is not convicted as a
consequence of the conduct that has been portrayed, then no House
of Representatives will ever be able to impeach again and no Senate
will ever convict,'' the team of prosecutors wrote. ``The bar will
be so high that only a convicted felon or a traitor will need to be
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine a future president, faced with possible
impeachment, pointing to the perjuries, lies, obstructions and
tampering with witnesses by the current occupant of the office as
not rising to the level of high crimes and misdemeanors?'' the
House prosecutors said. ``If this is not enough, what is?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
