<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-WORTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUGING NFL TEAM VALUE ON SEATS AND SUITES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last September, when Alfred Lerner bought the expansion
Cleveland Browns for $530 million, Howard Milstein insisted that
the economics of the deal kept him from budging above $450 million.
On Sunday, Milstein and his partner, Daniel Snyder, agreed to pay
the estate of Jack Kent Cooke $800 million for the Washington
Redskins and their stadium, the most ever paid for a domestic
sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   So if a team that hasn't played a game is worth $530 million and
another that lost more than it won this season is worth 50 percent
more, what is the value of the Jets, who are 13-4, including
Sunday's playoff victory?
</P>
<P>
   How can the Jets not be soaring in value, like Yahoo or
Amazon.com? The team is playing Denver for the American Football
Conference championship; no-shows at Giants Stadium are virtually
nil; sales of league-licensed Jets merchandise are ascending, and
Coach Bill Parcells is a turnaround specialist in the mold of Louis
Gerstner, who masterminded the resuscitation of IBM.
</P>
<P>
   So how high has the Jets' value soared? Not much, say sports
finance experts, despite the team's improved fortunes. What
separates the Jets from the Browns and Redskins is stadium
economics, not won-lost record. In this world, your luxury suites
matter more than your quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' cash flow from Giants Stadium is mediocre. But the
Browns' cash take will be terrific. And the Redskins' pockets
runneth over with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets don't have good economics,'' said Paul Much, of
Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, an investment banking firm in
Chicago. ``The big difference is the revenues from luxury suites,
concessions, advertising and parking.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ozanian, statistics editor of Forbes magazine, which
recently valued the Jets at $259 million and the Giants at $288
million, said: ``The Jets' stadium economics is in the lower third
of the league. They won't get much better. I don't think it's
possible for them to get much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Those economics create a divide between teams because while the
National Football League shares more revenues than any other major
sport, there are some that it does not. All national television and
licensing revenues are shared equally. Visiting teams take home 40
percent of gate receipts, including revenue from club seats and the
game tickets for luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   But owners do not share the annual luxury suite rentals and
revenue from concessions, parking, advertising and stadium naming
rights. Teams with the most unshared money have more for free
agents and rich signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The leases for the Jets, Browns and Redskins show who is
winning:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a lease that expires in 2008, the Jets pay 15 percent of
gross receipts as rent to the New Jersey Sports &AMP; Exposition
Authority. The team gets 14{ percent of gross rentals from the 72
older luxury suites and one-third from 46 new suites and 120 club
seats (the revenue from the new suites and the club seats is split
with the Giants and the sports authority). The Jets also get half
the concessions cash from their games and 25 percent of the
authority's share from Giants games; 25 percent of net parking
revenues and 25 percent of the authority's share from Giants games
and 30 percent of revenues from nonscoreboard advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Browns will get nearly every cent from their new
city-owned stadium _ except for annual rent of $250,000 _ including
the revenues from 116 luxury suites and 9,500 club seats, which
pays for waiter service on cushy chairs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Redskins get everything from Jack Kent Cooke Stadium,
because the late Redskins owner built it for $170 million (plus
$70.5 million from Maryland for infrastructure work), and all the
cash glories that come with it: 80,116 seats selling for $40 to $60
each; 280 luxury suites renting for $60,000 to $160,000 a year, and
15,044 luxury suites going for $995 to $1,995 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein, whose family real estate and banking holdings are
worth billions, knew he was buying more than a team struggling on
the field. He was buying another bank. Whether the Redskins are
worth $800 million is questionable. Ozanian recently valued the
team at $403 million, based on the 1997 season, and figured it
would sell for $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they'd come in for less than the Browns because the
Browns have no major competition; the Redskins have the Ravens
nearby,'' he said. ``I am astonished. I just don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozanian suggested that Milstein and Snyder could sell part of
the Redskins to the public, a structure the NFL frowns upon but may
have to consider as franchise prices move toward the billion-dollar
level.
</P>
<P>
   With his football dream nearly complete _ pending NFL owners'
approval _ Milstein will sell his and his brother Edward's 45
percent share of the Islanders. The Milsteins thought it would be
easier to negotiate a deal with Nassau County to replace
revenue-scarce Nassau Coliseum. But even a new arena would never be
a hockey equivalent of the Cooke Mint _ or any other where the team
owns the arena _ because revenues would have to be shared with the
county.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gluckstern, who owns 45 percent of the Islanders, said in
a statement: ``We have been approached by and may consider a number
of potential partners who would reflect my own commitment to a
stable, strong and resourceful ownership group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
