</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLARD-SPYCASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVISERS RECOMMEND THAT CLINTON DENY CLEMENCY TO POLLARD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's key national security advisers
have recommended that Clinton deny clemency to Jonathan Jay
Pollard, an American who spied for Israel, administration officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has informed the White
House that there is no compelling foreign policy reason to release
Pollard, the officials said. The director of central intelligence,
George Tenet, sent a letter to the president Monday urging that
Clinton keep Pollard in federal prison, where he is serving a life
sentence for espionage. Secretary of Defense William Cohen made the
same recommendation more than a week ago, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The senior officials were responding to a White House request to
provide recommendations on the Pollard case by Monday. Attorney
General Janet Reno, the other senior administration official asked
to make a recommendation, has not yet responded, officials said.
But the Federal Bureau of Investigation has urged her to ask the
president not to free Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   During the Middle East talks at Wye, Md., in October, the
president agreed to conduct an accelerated review of the case in
order to placate Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel and
win his support for the peace agreement. On the last day of the
talks, Netanyahu demanded Pollard's freedom in exchange for
agreeing to the peace deal. But Clinton agreed only to review the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in other agencies saw Ms. Albright's recommendation as
significant, since the Israeli request for Pollard's release had
come as part of diplomatic negotiations. Her response that the
Pollard matter was not a significant factor in American-Israeli
relations could make it difficult for Clinton to argue that he must
release Pollard in order to save the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three reviews by the Clinton administration has been
prompted by Israeli pressure on the White House, but each time
Clinton's advisers have unanimously opposed Pollard's release. They
have consistently argued that Pollard was one of the most damaging
spies in recent American history, one who betrayed costly high-tech
spy satellites as well as agents working under cover overseas. A
former Naval intelligence analyst, Pollard spied for Israel for at
least 18 months in 1984 and 1985, and turned over enough highly
classified documents to fill a room, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard was arrested in November 1985, and, after pleading
guilty, was sentenced to life in prison in 1987 after then-Defense
Secretary Caspar Weinberger provided the judge in the case with a
classified report detailing the extent of Pollard's espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Pollard, with the help of the Israeli government and some
Jewish-American groups, has mounted a long-running lobbying
campaign designed to win his release. They have argued that, while
he did spy, he worked on behalf of an ally rather than an American
enemy. They add that he has already served long enough, and that
the government reneged on an agreement not to seek life in prison
at the time of his sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rejected such pleas in his two previous reviews of the
case in 1993 and 1996. But many in the national security community
have been deeply concerned that Clinton would finally give in this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet was so concerned that, during the Wye talks, he told
Clinton he would be forced to resign if Clinton released Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, officials said that the president has not
yet decided whether to release Pollard, and has no deadline for
making the decision. `Once we get in the viewpoints from the
relevant agencies, we will assess what direction the review needs
to take,'' said a White House official. ``This is not necessarily
going to be a highly structured thing.'' White House counsel
Charles Ruff and National Security Adviser Samuel Berger will play
key roles in advising the president on the decision, officials
added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
