<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CHARGES-BOS &LR;      01-11 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CHARGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES `TOO VAGUE,' CLINTON LAWYERS ARGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers opened their defense
Monday in his impeachment trial, arguing that the Senate should
drop the charges because they are grounded in ``myth,'' are ``too
vague,'' and are too minor to constitute ``high crimes and
misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Also meeting deadlines to file written briefs in the first
presidential impeachment trial in 131 years, House managers said
they will present ``overwhelming'' evidence that Clinton deserves
to be removed from office on charges that he lied to a federal
grand jury and obstructed justice to try to conceal his affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence contained in the record, when viewed as a unified
whole, overwhelmingly supports both charges,'' the House managers
argued in a 105-page brief. ``If this is not enough, what is?''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, as they have for months, presented starkly opposing
views of the evidence and summarized their cases in sharply
contrasting styles. The House produced a voluminous brief with
flourishes of outrage at Clinton's alleged actions, while Clinton's
team filed a tersely worded document aimed at scoring precise legal
points.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers, echoing an argument that failed in the House,
filed a 13-page document portraying the president's ``wrongdoing''
as the product of an adulterous husband trying to avoid public
embarrassment rather than corruptly interfere with a criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With House managers scheduled to begin opening arguments on
Thursday, the president's lawyers asserted that the charges ``do
not rise to the level of `high crimes and misdemeanors' as
contemplated by the Founding Fathers, and they do not satisfy the
rigorous consititutional standard applied throughout our Nation's
history. Accordingly, the Articles of Impeachment should be
dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the House managers, all conservative Republicans,
cast the impeachment trial as crucial to the nation's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for the presidency as an institution
because if the president is not convicted as a consequence of the
conduct that has been portrayed, then no House of Representatives
will ever be able to impeach again and no Senate will ever
convict,'' the House managers concluded in their brief. ``The bar
will be so high that only a convicted felon or a traitor will need
to be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, on the advice of Senate Democrats, decided to
forgo filing a motion to dismiss the charges until after both sides
have presented their opening statements. The House also waived its
right to file pretrial motions, which means the Senate will not be
in session Wednesday to rule on motions.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bipartisan pact reached last week, the Senate agreed to
postpone until Jan. 25 or Jan. 26 the questions of whether to
dismiss the charges or whether to extend the trial by granting a
request by the House managers to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry J. Hyde, the lead House manager as chairman
of the Judiciary Committee, Monday reiterated the group's desire to
call as many as 10 witnesses but refrained from criticizing the
Senate for putting off the question. ``This is a difficult time,''
Hyde said. ``This is not the time to get angry at the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde added: ``We feel that we will do a very good job and then
when we reach the point of asking for witnesses, we think the
senators will be in a more generous mood having heard our case.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hyde gives a brief introduction on Thursday,
Representative F. James Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin will deliver
for the House his opening statement, which he said Monday will be
``action packed.'' Representative Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas is in
charge of orchestrating the rest of the House's presentation, which
could continue Friday and Saturday, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have 24 hours over three days to present their
opening statements. Clinton's 11-member legal defense team is
scheduled to begin its opening statement next Tuesday, Jan. 19,
just hours before the president plans to deliver his State of the
Union address to a joint session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   As the president's lawyers and House managers prepared for the
first presidential impeachment trial since Andrew Johnson's in
1868, Clinton met during the day with Argentine President Carlos
Menem and entertained him Monday night with a black-tie state
dinner featuring a tango performance.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House broke with longstanding tradition by
refusing to permit reporters to cover the start of the meetings and
deciding against holding a joint news conference, even though Menem
had expected one.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the impeachment case and Lewinsky scandal were
expected to dominate the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``In looking at the schedule, we didn't think it was the most
productive use of his time,'' said Joseph Lockhart, the White House
spokesman. ``I also think that, given the prerogatives of the
Senate, that's where the discussions will be going forward on this
issue, and that's where it should go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Both briefs that were filed Monday strayed little from the
positions each side took during impeachment proceedings in the
House, where the two charges were approved on Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   In a new twist, though, Clinton's lawyers argued that the
impeachment articles violate Senate rules by dividing the charges
into multiple counts: four of lying under oath, and seven of
obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   With a two-thirds majority, or 67 votes, required to convict
Clinton of either charge, his lawyers argued that Clinton
ostensibly could be convicted of lying under oath, for instance, if
four different groups of 17 senators _ a total of 68 _ each
supported only one element of the four-count offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This creates the very real possibility that conviction could
occur even though senators were in wide disagreement as to the
alleged wrong committed,'' Clinton's lawyers stated. ``By charging
multiple wrongs in one article, the House of Representatives has
made it impossible for the Senate to comply with the Constitutional
mandate that any conviction be by the concurrence of two-thirds of
the members.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers also argued that both impeachment charges
are too vague because they fail to cite specific statements in
which Clinton allegedly lied to the grand jury and the specific
acts he allegedly undertook to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   The House document laid out a general account of the allegations
in each count, all of which were raised in the House proceedings.
But the brief promised more specifics during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The document states that ``it is not, and is not intended to be,
a substitute for a trial at which all of the relevant facts will be
developed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
