<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLISH-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S `OFFICIAL ENGLISH LAW' DEAD _ OR IS IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona's ``official English'' law is dead after more
than a decade of legal wrangling, but a national group, U.S.
English, is vowing to put the issue back on the state's ballot in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of the road,'' Bob Park of Arizonans for
Official English said Monday after the U.S. Supreme Court rejected
the group's appeal to revive the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's ruling, made without comment, represented the
final blow for Arizona's constitutional amendment, which declared
English the state's official language and required its use in most
government transactions. The Arizona Supreme Court struck it down
in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anyplace else for us to go,'' Park, of Prescott,
said. ``It's over and done with.'' Park ran for governor in 1998 on
the Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Yet national official English groups and their political allies,
including Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz., cast Monday's decision as merely
a speed bump.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect is localized to Arizona,'' said Eric Stone,
research director for U.S. English, a 1.3 million-member group
pushing to make English the country's official language.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said his group likely will return to the state in 2000
with a less-restrictive official English ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to rectify the situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four other states have passed laws designating English as
their official language. Arizona's law was seen as the toughest,
although it was put in legal limbo almost immediately after voters
narrowly approved it in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The measure declared English ``the language of the ballot, the
public schools and all government functions and actions.'' It
applied to all government officials and employees on government
business.
</P>
<P>
   Other languages could be used only to help students learn
English, to teach foreign languages, comply with federal laws,
protect public health or safety, or protect the rights of criminal
defendants or crime victims.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Stephen Montoya, who filed the original lawsuit
challenging the measure, called Monday's ruling the end of a ``long
and hard fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did I know that it would take 11 years to resolve the
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A group of elected officials and public employees joined Montoya
in challenging the amendment in state court in 1992. They said they
regularly speak Spanish with members of the public, many of whom do
not speak English well, and that a ban on doing so would keep them
from serving the public.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court ruled the amendment unconstitutional, and
the Arizona Supreme Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment violates the federal Constitution's free-speech
and equal-protection guarantees by creating ``a linguistic barrier
between persons and the government they have a right to petition,''
the state's top court said.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya predicted the U.S. Supreme Court's action would undercut
efforts by a California group to export a ballot measure banning
bilingual education to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion has affirmed the right of teachers to communicate
with their students in languages other than English,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any anti-bilingual education legislation that would undermine
the right of a teacher to communicate with a student other than in
English is going to be subject to some type of challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump last week introduced a bill modeled on Arizona's law,
making English the official language of the federal government and
requiring that all official government business be conducted solely
in English. It also would ban bilingual education and bilingual
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Stump called Monday's decision disappointing,
but added, ``I do not consider it a defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling may be an indication that this is an area in which
Congress should act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many advocates of official English agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some feeling that Congress can get away with
passing a very minimal law or leaving it up to the states. The
Supreme Court has foreclosed that option,'' said Jim Boulet Jr.,
executive director of English First, a national official English
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for Congress to fish or cut bait,'' Boulet said.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya hopes Monday's ruling ends the official English debate
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arizona realizes now that this issue is not
worthwhile,'' he said. ``English is not being threatened. Everyone
in Arizona either speaks English, is learning English or direly
wants to learn English.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the whole predicate for English only in Arizona _ that
English was somehow endangered or mortally challenged _ I think it
has been exposed to be a fallacy.'' &QL; 
Includes information from the Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
