<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SPLIT ON CLINTON MESSAGE TO CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week before President Clinton is scheduled to
deliver his annual State of the Union address, many of his
Democratic allies in the Senate are divided over whether he should
postpone the Jan. 19 speech because of his impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has caused a rare split between the two Massachusetts
senators _ Edward M. Kennedy, who wants Clinton to give the speech
as scheduled, and John F. Kerry, who backs a delay.
</P>
<P>
   In all, half of the six Democratic senators from New England
favor Clinton putting off his appearance before a joint session of
the House and Senate until the trial ends, while the others want
him to go ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
   With the White House, at least temporarily, refusing to delay
the president's date with Congress, the issue has caused a crack in
the Democratic unity seen so far in the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats _ ranging from the highly respected defender of Senate
prerogatives, Robert Byrd of West Virginia, to California Senator
Dianne Feinstein and Connecticut's two senators, Joseph I.
Lieberman and Christopher J. Dodd _ have joined some Republicans in
calling for Clinton to postpone his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Kerry, in one of his first public comments on the issue,
joined that chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be blind or obtuse not to acknowledge a certain
awkwardness in the evening, which could conceivably foster some
anger, and I would want to be very wary of that,'' Kerry said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally see no harm whatsoever'' in delaying the speech,
he added. ``I don't think people will interpret it as business
isn't being done. It's just acknowledging that a certain
presumptive process is going on on the Hill and you are going to be
deferential to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy and Senator Jack Reed, a Democrat from Rhode Island,
said Clinton should go ahead with his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the president does not delay his address,'' Kennedy
said. ``The nation's business is too important.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed agreed, saying Clinton ``should continue to advocate an
agenda for the American people, and one of the best places to do
that is the State of the Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a Democrat from Vermont, said Clinton
should delay the speech if the Senate trial is a day or two from
ending. But if the trial has weeks to go by next Tuesday, he should
deliver the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop of Democratic division, the House
Republican leadership Monday signaled it was moving ahead with the
scheduled date, ignoring some lawmakers' suggestions that the House
could ``disinvite'' the president.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Dear Republican Colleague'' letter sent Monday, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois and House Majority Leader
Richard Armey of Texas outlined the legislative calendar for the
next few weeks. It begins: ``The House will meet on January 19th
for the State of the Union Address.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton met Monday with advisers on his State of
the Union, while aides insisted he would go ahead with it. The
speech could come only hours after his lawyers are scheduled to
begin their opening statements in the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to give the speech on the 19th,'' said White House
press secretary Joseph Lockhart. ``I have every reason to believe
and no reason to believe otherwise that he won't be there on
January 19th, giving his State of the Union.''
</P>
<P>
   From the White House perspective, the prime-time address
presents the perfect juxtaposition for Clinton: He can show himself
focused on the nation's business, even as senators are holding an
impeachment trial that few believe will result in his removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not allow himself to get sidetracked from the people's
business,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he understood Clinton's rationale for not postponing
the speech. ``He thinks it's important to do the business of the
country, and this is the business of the country. He obviously
doesn't agree with the charges, and he does feel, as many of us do,
that the process was biased and partisan'' in the House, Kerry
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's really up to him,'' Kerry continued. ``It's a
judgment he's got to make in the context of his agenda. But I
personally don't see anything perjorative in delaying it. It might
even be taken as a sign of good will in respect to the obvious
awkwardness of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution does not require an annual State of the Union
address. It simply states that the president ``shall from time to
time give to the Congress information of the State of the Union.''
It does not specify when or how often.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington gave a brief State of the Union speech in
January 1790, but presidents from Thomas Jefferson to Theodore
Roosevelt have been content to send written messages to Congress.
Woodrow Wilson revived the speech format for the State of the
Union, and Harry Truman was the first president to use it to lay
out specific policy ideas, as Clinton now does.
</P>
<P>
   Political science professor Stephen Wayne of Georgetown
University, an expert on both Congress and the presidency, said
Clinton ``needs all the friends he can get up there right now, and
to the extent that some of them tell him don't do it, then I don't
think he should do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You don't want to alienate anybody at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
