<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS NOTEBOOK: PARCELLS WANTS TO WEED OUT ERRORS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The two old friends, a pair of obsessive
coaches, were gabbing in the Giants Stadium parking lot Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells' Jets had just defeated Tom Coughlin's Jaguars to
advance to the American Football Conference championship game. They
spoke for only five minutes. They go back to the Super Bowl Giants
of 1991, when Parcells was the boss and Coughlin was the receivers
coach.
</P>
<P>
   So, were they talking of old times? Or how heartbreaking defeat
was for Jacksonville? Or of how far Parcells had taken the Jets?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. They were discussing mistakes. This is what
drives them, and almost drove Parcells, crazy.
</P>
<P>
   For despite the 34-24 victory, Parcells had moments when he
wondered whether the Jets might blow this thing, that their playoff
inexperience was showing, that the dumb plays he warned could send
a team home might actually be unfolding before him. And he berated
himself for his own questionable call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you believe our guy tried to lateral?'' Coughlin moaned
to Parcells about one of the game's big plays, when Chris Hudson
unwisely tried a lateral after picking up Curtis Martin's fumble.
The ball was recovered by Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you believe the play at the half?'' countered Parcells,
speaking of how Otis Smith and Jerome Henderson were beaten by
Jimmy Smith on a 52-yard touchdown strike as the half ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe our guy tried to get it out of the end zone?''
retorted Coughlin, still smarting over the fact that Donovin Darius
unwisely tried to run out an interception, but instead was tackled
at the 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells came back with still another ``Do you believe ... .''
and then concluded, ``That's the way kids are today.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have mentioned special teamers being suckered by a
faked lateral from Reggie Barlow, who returned a kickoff 88 yards.
``We had someone assigned there,'' Parcells said Monday, ``and
three guys ran over and that left a bit of a hole up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the Vinny Testaverde interception, as well as a Wayne
Chrebet fumble and the Martin fumble. And there was Parcells' odd
decision for Testaverde to throw the ball into the end zone when a
field goal would have virtually clinched the game. (''I thought we
could have surprised them,'' Parcells said.)
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Parcells seemed unwilling Monday to dwell on errors. In
fact, he seemed almost solicitous of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you make mistakes the first time you play in cold
weather,'' he explained. ``We practiced in it, but it's not the
same. The last-second play at the half allowed them to breathe. The
pressure of these games _ I wouldn't excuse it, but it's our first
time in it. Maybe we're over it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the game did highlight his distress at some of the
special teams' play this season. That 88-yard return was the
longest the club had yielded. It has given up a punt return for a
touchdown during the regular campaign, something that the Jets
prevented all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has said that when next season's summer camp begins, he
will involve his experienced players more in the special teams. One
of them, Chris Hayes, produced three tackles against the Jaguars
and has been a strong performer all year.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells isn't happy unless he's unhappy, and he had a few
items to groan about Monday. He seemed to turn his attention more
quickly to Denver, though. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUST 2 FUMBLES FOR MARTIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells has always warned his players: ``If you fumble, I
won't play you.'' Curtis Martin has run 405 times this season,
including the playoffs. The lost fumble was only his second. That
average of one lost ball about every 200 carries is double that of
his predecessor, Adrian Murrell, now with Arizona, who fumbled
twice as often.
</P>
<P>
   A SUPER COMPARISON? &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jumbo Elliott compared the Jets' task on Sunday to his Super
Bowl-winning Giants' team following the 1990 season. The left
tackle recalled that the Giants played the National Conference
championship at San Francisco, which was heavily favored. They were
the defending Super Bowl champions. The Broncos, this year's
defenders, are favored by 8 points on Sunday for the American
Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Parcells said this is not the same. ``Certainly, San
Francisco was formidable, but they were the two-time Super Bowl
champions,'' Parcells said. And he believes his 1990 Giants team
had a better defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
