<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST GOAL FOR KNICKS IS SIGNING WARD
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ It was like a mixer, casual attire only. Topped
with a hairdo from the Bob Marley collection, an amiable Charles
Oakley popped into the Knicks' facility and met his replacement,
Marcus Camby, without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Mingling with various fringe free agents and local pickup-game
players, Allan Houston, John Starks and Charlie Ward also attended
the first day of informal workouts allowed by the league. After a
light scrimmage, Ward's future was one of the hotter conversation
topics. Facing an abbreviated training camp beginning around Jan.
18, the Knicks are in a bind to re-sign Ward as their point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has leverage, and his agent has a few contract numbers in
mind. With Chris Childs, the Knicks' demoted starter of last
season, setting the bar by making an average of $4 million over six
years, Ward's agent, Craig McKenzie, said Monday that a $5 million
salary ``was something we're looking at and is probably a good
starting point for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   As a part of an anticipated seven-year deal, Ward's contract
would be worth more than $35 million if he re-signs with the
Knicks. McKenzie also added that Ward, whose wife, Tonja, is a
lawyer with a successful career in New York, wants a no-trade
clause added to his contract. In the end, stability and loyalty may
mean as much to Ward as money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that is an issue,'' said McKenzie, who spoke to
the Knicks' president, Ernie Grunfeld, Monday. ``We haven't gotten
down to exact terms, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although teams cannot officially re-sign players until the new
collective bargaining agreement is reduced to writing around Jan.
18, McKenzie said that he expected an offer from the Knicks by the
end of the week. Other offers are bound to be spilling in as well.
Team officials from Toronto, Detroit and Orlando have also
contacted Ward's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the best opportunity and hopefully the Knicks will
be there,'' Ward said. ``Money is not going to send me one way or
the other. Money doesn't sway me. I enjoy playing here, and I've
been here for four years. This is the only place I know. The only
other place I'd feel comfortable would be Orlando. It's close to
home, and I visit there on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward has choices, but Oakley does not. Unless he is traded to a
team like the Lakers _ ``Hey, tell the Lakers I'm fit,'' Oakley
said as he went to work out _ he will finish out the
lockout-shortened season in Toronto. Oakley, who has a car wash
business in town and maintains a home in the New York area, ducked
in for a scrimmage. It was the five Knicks, past and present,
against a collection of free agents and local players.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd turn of events, Oakley found himself on the same side
as the player he was traded for. That put Camby in the awkward
position of being the host in Oakley's old home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached each other once we noticed each other was in
here,'' Camby said. ``It was like, `Hey, how you doing?' There was
no animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if he'd been to Toronto yet. He said that hadn't
been up there. That's a wise move because it's about 10 below zero
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a warmth surrounding Monday's workout. It was not the
turnout some of the Knicks had hoped for, but by the end of the
week, most of the Knicks are expected to be in town in preparation
for the opening of training camp next week. Among the main players
absent Monday were Larry Johnson, Chris Mills, Terry Cummings, Buck
Williams, Childs and Patrick Ewing, who left town for a
mini-vacation after leading the union through a draining six-month
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ewing is carrying about 20 extra pounds after hours of
inactivity during meetings and negotiating sessions, his teammates
did not seem concerned. Those who showed up Monday appeared in good
shape. Perhaps the non-Knick, Oakley, at age 35, was the fittest of
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a chance to run up and down with Oakley today,'' Starks
said. ``He gave us our fair warning: Don't come down the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks don't want to lose anymore to the other side,
especially Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important,'' Houston said, referring to
re-signing Ward. ``When you think about the core guys who have been
here, and are familiar with each other, Charlie is definitely one
of the guys high on the list. I think the whole team is comfortable
with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
