<SLUG> BC-TV-LYNCH-310-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID LYNCH WORKING ON DRAMA SERIES FOR ABC 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ Eight years after ``Twin Peaks'' flamed out
on ABC, director and producer David Lynch is preparing a new drama
for the same network.
</P>
<P>
   The show is called ``Mulholland Drive,'' and it will be a
candidate for ABC's fall schedule, Stu Bloomberg, ABC Entertainment
chairman, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said Lynch's pilot script arrived at the network last
week, ``and it is vintage David Lynch, very reminiscent of `Twin
Peaks,' and it was a blast to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg described the project as a contemporary drama set in
Los Angeles and featuring a large cast with ``their relationships
and their dreams and their turmoils.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's previous experience on ABC was spotty. ``Twin Peaks,''
the quirky drama he co-created with Mark Frost, premiered to
critical praise and healthy ratings in 1990 but had run its course
a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch tried a sitcom on ABC the next year. Called ``On the
Air,'' it was a manic comedy about television. It lasted less than
a month.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of ``Twin Peaks'' is generally attributed to a
creative stall on the part of Lynch and Frost, who seemed unwilling
to advance the show's gummy story line.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said that Lynch was aware of the ``Twin Peaks''
shortcomings and that in the case of ``Mulholland Drive,'' he ``has
it really mapped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other dramas in development for ABC include ``Once Again,'' from
``thirtysomething'' creators Edward Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz,
and ``Snoops,'' from TV's hottest drama producer, David E. Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Again'' involves a divorced couple that reunites,
Bloomberg said. ``Snoops'' is a detective show. Kelley is creating
``Snoops,'' but he told critics he expects to be less involved with
it than with ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   On the comedy front, ABC Entertainment President Jamie Tarses
said the proposed ``Mary Tyler Moore Show'' sequel with Moore and
Valerie Harper has been killed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
