<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO LAUNCH SATELLITES FOR GLOBALSTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co.'s commercial satellite launch business
continues to be one of the company's best opportunities for future
growth, as evidence by Monday's announcement that Boeing will
launch 28 satellites for the Globalstar telephone network.
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar, which is 42 percent owned by Loral Space &AMP;
Communications Ltd., apparently decided to use Boeing's Delta II
rockets after a Ukrainian rocket exploded in September, destroying
a dozen Globalstar satellites it carried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased we were able to respond quickly to Loral's
needs,'' said Gale Schluter, vice president and general manager of
Boeing Expendable Launch Systems in Huntington Beach., Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``These additional missions give us a robust launch manifest for
1999.'
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will launch six Delta II rockets this year and one in
2000 to place the 28 Globalstar satellites into low Earth orbits.
The rockets will be launched form Cape Cavaveral, Fla., and from
Vandenberg Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Boeing has 22 Delta II missions scheduled for this year,
including the six for Globalstar. Through 2001, Boeing's Delta II
launch manifest now shows 42 planned missions, though that is
certain to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications is potentially a $100-billion business, said
Marco Caceres, aerospace analyst with the Teal Group, a market
research firm. His speciality is commercial launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future growth for Boeing is clearly in space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing will not disclose financial terms of its launch
business, it reportedly gets about $55 million for a typical Delta
II launch.
</P>
<P>
   In February and April of last year, Boeing's Delta II placed the
first 8 Globalstar satellites into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The Globalstar system will need 48 satellites to become
operational, which should be in the third quarter of 1999. That is
later than planned because of the setback when the Ukrainian Zenit
rocket blew up shortly after launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition to our revised launch schedule of seven firm
launches on the highly reliable Delta II rocket substantially
increases our launch flexibility and robustness,'' Bernard
Schwartz, Loral's chairman and chief executive, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar will provide worldwide mobile and fixed
telecommunications services through its satellite constellation. It
will be the second such system in orbit. It's main competition is
Iridium, which completed its satellite constellation late last
year. Many of the Iridium satellites were launched on Boeing's
Delta II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
