<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cashing In Savings Bonds  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I have several U.S. savings bonds that are 12 years old
and no longer drawing interest. I contacted two banks, but they
won't cash the bonds for me. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  I can't imagine why those banks blew you off. Most
commercial banks are willing to cash up to $1,000 worth of E or EE
savings bonds at a time, even for noncustomers. They don't cash H
or HH bonds, but they will help you get the money by forwarding the
bonds to a Federal Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   So try another bank. Wells Fargo, for one, will help you.
</P>
<P>
   If you aren't a customer, bring along your driver's license or
other ID, such as your Social Security card. The bank will want to
be certain that you are entitled to cash the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   If you have more than $1,000 worth of bonds, you may have to
make multiple trips to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than do that, you might prefer to cash the bonds by mail.
Call the Federal Reserve's toll-free customer service line at (800)
333-2919 and request Form SD-120. Fill it out and send it back with
the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Eckert, a spokeswoman for the Federal Reserve Bank of San
Francisco, warns you to copy the serial numbers, so the bonds can
be replaced if your packet gets lost. Savings bonds are
automatically insured by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   After you cash your bonds, the institution handling the
transaction will send you (and the Internal Revenue Service) a form
indicating how much interest you received. The interest is subject
to federal income tax, but not to state or local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Too Old for an IRA?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am 64 years old, and my only retirement income will come
from Social Security. Is it too late to start an Individual
Retirement Account? I plan to work until at least age 70.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not too late _ and you should do it. If you depend
entirely on Social Security income, you will find it awfully
difficult to enjoy your sunset years.
</P>
<P>
   Make it a Roth IRA, rather than a traditional one. The great
thing about a Roth is that your investment gains accumulate
tax-free. With the other types of IRAs, you must pay taxes on the
gains when you withdraw the money.
</P>
<P>
   You can contribute up to $2,000 of your earned income per year
to a Roth for as long as you like. With the traditional deductible
and nondeductible IRAs, you must stop contributing no later than
age 701/2 and then must start withdrawing your money.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you contribute $2,000 annually to a Roth, and invest the
money in the stock market, or in a mutual fund that tracks the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. That is an aggressive and risky
strategy for someone your age _ but given your otherwise bleak
financial prospects, you might want to chance it.
</P>
<P>
   If you invest $2,000 per year until you reach age 75, and then
retire, your contributions will total $22,000. If your investments
compound at 10 percent annually _ the long-term stock-market
average _ your account will grow to more than $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market scares you, and you invest instead in
essentially risk-free U.S. Treasury issues or money market funds,
you will earn perhaps 5 percent per year. At age 75, your $22,000
in contributions will have grown to slightly less than $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Government Pensions
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a federal employee, entitled to a federal pension when I
retire. I have the option of taking less pension income during my
lifetime to provide a survivor benefit for my wife after my death.
My wife also works _ at a nongovernment job _ and will receive
Social Security after she retires. Would her Social Security
benefits be reduced if she also receives the survivor benefit from
the federal government?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: No _ but I can understand why you are puzzled. The rules
regarding Social Security offsets from government pensions are
extremely complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The key to your situation, says Leslie Walker, spokeswoman for
the Social Security Administration, is that your wife earned Social
Security benefits from her own job. Therefore, those benefits are
exempt from any offsets.
</P>
<P>
   If the situation is reversed, with your wife dying first, you
yourself could get hit by offsets. Because you will get a federal
pension, your survivor benefits from your wife's Social Security
account could be reduced or even eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Offsets stem from the fact that before 1984, government
employees did not pay Social Security taxes. Congress decided it
was unfair for these employees to draw full survivor benefits from
a spouse's Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   All federal employees hired from January 1, 1984, to the present
have been required to pay Social Security taxes, so the offsets
don't apply to them. But many people who worked for the government
before then did not pay the taxes and still don't.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who needs to know more about government pension offsets
should obtain Publications 05-10007 and 05-10045 from the Social
Security Administration. These publications will help you determine
whether you are subject to offsets, and to what extent.
</P>
<P>
   The toll-free telephone number is (800) 772-1213, and you also
can contact Social Security through its Internet Web site at
 &LR; www.ssa.gov. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
