r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON &LR;      01-11 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tech Stocks May Put on Brakes  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Those astonishingly fast-moving high-technology stocks had another
great day yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-laden Nasdaq composite index hit its seventh-straight
record, jumping 40.18 points to 2,384.59. It has risen 68 percent
since hitting a 52-week low on October 8.
</P>
<P>
   That phenomenal streak has some market experts worrying that the
high-tech race car may be nearing the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies are at the cutting edge of the U.S. economy, and
as a group, they are likely to enjoy outstanding sales and earnings
gains well into the coming century. But many of them are selling at
70, 80, 100 or more times earnings for the latest 12 months. A lot
of market-watchers find that tough to justify.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart J. Pillette of Pillette Investment Management in San
Francisco predicts a 10 to 20 percent ``near-term'' drop in tech
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Danville investment counselor Richard DelMonte extols high
technology as ``the engine that drives the economy.'' But he &LR; 
 &LR; expects tech stocks to lose at least 15 percent of their value in
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Intel, the chipmaker; Cisco, the
network-equipment-maker; and Lucent Technologies, which makes
telecommunications equipment, have ``great'' futures, DelMonte
says. ``They are making the hardware for companies that want an
Internet presence _ the Internet is going to grow on their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks that Cisco's stock is vulnerable at nearly 80
times earnings, while Lucent's is even more so at nearly 150 times
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other group offers more dynamic growth opportunities than
high tech,'' says Alfred Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Son in St. Louis. ``But this group has been up, up and
away lately.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that investors who are itching to buy tech shares
invest only half their money now. He advises saving the other half
for significant price pullbacks _ which he considers likely.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite tech stocks include Compaq Computer and Applied
Materials, which are ``dominating their segments of the market and
have a good history of growth and proven managements.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of reasons why tech stocks have surged lately.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, the economic outlook has improved. Tech
companies tend to be very sensitive to economic cycles.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian contagion, which generated so much terror among
investors during last summer's stock market sell-off, has caused
scarcely a sniffle on this side of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any worries about a marked slowdown in U.S. growth are
dissipating,'' says Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells
Capital Management in San Francisco. ``We are not looking at a
recession or even a dramatic slowdown, though growth will be
somewhat slower.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg says most tech companies are humming on all
cylinders. They have shown ``an ability to generate good unit
volume growth, and they also have been successful in cutting costs
to sustain profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg's colleague Jon Hickman, managing director and
senior portfolio manager with Wells Capital, says the ``backdrop
for tech spending is really positive.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be more and more traffic over networks of all kinds,
he says, ``not just the Internet, but corporate networks.
Telecommunications and data communications are going to be big
spending areas this year and in coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   While Y2K compliance has produced a flood of new business for
the software industry, Hickman says, there's no reason to fear a
slowdown after the problem is solved. He says a further flood will
follow as firms buy other system upgrades that had to be postponed
because of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Among software companies, he particularly likes Keane Inc.,
which provides applications software and services to companies,
government agencies and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman also figures that data-storage companies, such as
disk-drive-maker Seagate Technology, ``are a place you want to be
for the future. As more and more things go digital, there will be
the need to store more and more data.''
</P>
<P>
   In line with that reasoning, he also likes Documentum, which
provides data-management products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, market strategist with Salomon Smith Barney in
New York, observes that most tech companies have brought their
inventories down from the swollen levels of a year ago _ a big
plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech is in the sweet spot right now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he warns: ``There's the potential that between now and late
spring, there might be some profit-taking _ people taking some of
the money they've made off the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
