<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASCEND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Ascend Rises on Takeover Rumor  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shares of Ascend Communications Corp. jumped 8 percent yesterday as
rumors of a potential acquisition by Lucent Technologies began a
fresh wave of takeover speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda's Ascend, which makes computer-networking gear, and New
Jersey's Lucent, the nation's largest telecommunications equipment
provider, have long been mentioned as potential partners, but
industry watchers said the two companies may be days away from
announcing a $17 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   A pairing of the two, first reported Sunday in London's
Financial Times, would create a data networking powerhouse capable
of challenging Cisco Systems and 3Com Corp. in the market for
computer gear sold to phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said the two companies are expected to meet
today. Lucent chief executive Rich McGinn will be in town to give a
speech at the Churchill Club in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Lucent and Ascend have been trying to partner for
some time but have been unable to agree on a price. Now that
Lucent's stock has more than doubled since October, the two may
finally have agreed on an $80 per share price for Ascend, sources
said. That figure is a 12 percent premium over's Ascend's Friday
close of $71.44 and just slightly above yesterday's close of $76.75
a share.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Christin Armacost, a telecom analyst with Everen Securities
in Chicago, said the two companies have been in discussions for
``an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a question of whether Lucent is willing to pay the
price for Ascend. I don't think they had been able in the past to
agree on a fair valuation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Donovan, a spokesman for Ascend, said the rumors are ``all
speculation'' and that reports of a merger between the two have
been percolating for months. ``There's nothing new to report,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is imminent, it appears to have evolved rather
quickly, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   In November, 11 top executives at Ascend filed to sell 685,000
shares of stock at a share price significantly lower than where
Ascend's price has been the past week. Ascend President and CEO
Mory Ejabat sold 100,000 shares at prices that ranged from $47.50
to $51.
</P>
<P>
   Since October 1, Ascend stock has risen about 46 percent. Ascend
was up $5.31 yesterday. Even on Friday, days before the rumor began
circulating, Ascend was above $71. Lucent ended yesterday down
$2.31 at $112.94.
</P>
<P>
   Since mergers tend to boost the stock price of an acquired
company, some industry watchers said it was unusual for Ejabat and
other executives to sell shares if a deal with Lucent was on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not logical,'' said Bob Gabele, director of research for
Investnet, a Baltimore company that tracks insider selling. ``There
probably is not that much chance of a merger.''
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is imminent, Gabele said, there may be two
explanations: ``Either something materialized recently or,
possibly, the insiders at that time didn't feel the deal with
Lucent would carry out much of a premium,'' Gabele said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the merger happens this week, analysts
expect Lucent and Ascend to join hands at some point.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Ascend, which develops switches that transmit
data over networks, is an attractive takeover target for Lucent,
which has a very weak networking presence, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend's most valuable asset is its asynchronous transfer mode
switch, or ATM, which can seamlessly carry voice, video and data
traffic over the same network.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications providers, such as phone companies, are
looking toward ATM as a way to converge all phone calls, Internet
traffic and other data onto the same network. Using ATM is cheaper
and more efficient than the fractured network phone companies use
today and also allows companies to do a better job of managing the
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big conversion taking place in telecommunications
and the major purchasers are spending a significantly greater
portion on data equipment,'' said Gregory S. Geiling, an analyst at
J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   While Lucent has great name recognition and strong customer
relations with the biggest names in telecommunications _ AT&AMP;T, SBC
Communications and AirTouch Communications, to name a few _ it
doesn't have the new technology these companies are demanding for
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   That weakness has given new competitors, such as Cisco, Bay
Networks and 3Com, a chance to snatch market share away from the
AT&AMP;T spin-off.
</P>
<P>
   In order to compete in the 21st century, Geiling said, Lucent
needs to offer ATM to its customers, and the easiest way to achieve
that would be to buy Ascend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only hole Lucent has is that they don't have great data
technology, such as ATM,'' Geiling said. ``Ascend has a very strong
standpoint in ATM and if you put Lucent's customer relations with
Ascend's customer base, it makes all the sense in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A merger would give Ascend access to a broader base of customers
and the backing of a financially solid company. Lucent has
experienced tremendous growth since it was spun off from AT&AMP;T a
little more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Lucent's revenue has soared from $23.3 billion in
1996 to $30 billion in 1998. Ascend's 1997 revenue was $1.16
billion. Lucent, whose market value is $148 billion, has been so
successful because its products run everything from traditional
phone systems to wireless phones to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of Lucent and Ascend is advantageous because
it broadens the market potential that Ascend can reach,'' said
Armacost, with Everen Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said Ascend should go for a merger with Lucent
because it would help Ascend avoid being squeezed out by the
inevitable pricing pressure that will evolve in the ATM market over
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The ATM market is valued at about $2 billion and as competitors
flood the marketplace, companies will be forced to lower their
prices. That will be easier for a combined Ascend/Lucent to handle
than it would be for Ascend on its own, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   If Lucent does buy Ascend, it won't be the first time the New
Jersey company has snapped up a Silicon Valley firm. In 1997,
Lucent bought Livingston of Pleasanton, a data-networking company,
and Octel Communications Corp., a voice mail and messaging company
in Milpitas.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation for months that Lucent would buy
Ascend or some other networking company. In October, Lucent was
finally able to make large acquisitions without being penalized by
certain accounting rules that apply to spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Just yesterday, Lucent announced a deal to pay $1.5 billion in
stock for Kenan Systems Corp., a Cambridge, Mass., company which
makes software for billing and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend also made news yesterday. The company agreed to sell
assets it acquired as part of its October 19 purchase of Stratus
Computer Inc. to an investor group led by Investcorp, an
international investment bank based in Bahrain. Ascend said it
would divest other nontelecommunications businesses later this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
