<SLUG> BC-DDN-WEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odds are weather about to change
 &HT;    By Brandon Peterson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For a meteorologist, predicting an accurate
weather forecast is sometimes equivalent to hitting the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most difficult part of our job here,'' said John
Franks, meteorologist for the National Weather Service in
Wilmington. ``During the winter, we try to forecast a day or two in
advance, and after we find out how much water is expected to fall,
we have to determine whether it's going to be rain, sleet, or snow.
. .along with what kind of temperatures and accumulation goes with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Miami Valley residents _ especially school administrators
and road crews _ hope this weeks' premature weather predictions
proves to be a jackpot. Forecasters predict only a chance of snow
this week with warmer temperatures on the way by the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   But don't break out the suntan lotion and tank tops yet. It's
still going to be cold.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures are expected to be around 30 degrees this morning
and remaining steady most of the day, according to the NWS.
Forecasters expect a 50 percent chance of rain changing to light
snow tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Though the weather can be as surprising as a snow-covered
potholes, one thing is for sure _ many Miami Valley schools will be
closed again today and snow and ice covered roads will continue to
cause major accidents and headaches for police.
</P>
<P>
   Wet pavement and blowing snow was the cause of a wreck involving
nearly 20 vehicles on southbound Interstate 75 near Needmore Road
on Monday afternoon, according to Sgt. Greg Menke with the
Montgomery County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Menke said the accident left one car pinned between two semi
trucks. Other vehicles then spun out of control and landed in
ditches and medians. There were a few minor injuries in the pileup,
Menke said.
</P>
<P>
   Various agencies around the Miami Valley are hoping for a
reprieve after trying to cope with a ferocious winter.
</P>
<P>
   Already this winter, nearly 17 inches of snow have been dumped
on the Miami Valley. Though the snow has come in dramatic waves,
it's way off the record-setting snowfall of 67 inches the area got
in 1977-78, meteorologists say. The average snowfall for the winter
season is 30 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The area is above the mark for January though. Nearly 14 inches
of snow has fallen already this month, with the average being close
to 9 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Peterson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
