<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Levi's President, COO Peter Jacobi Resigns  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Peter Jacobi resigned as Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s president and chief
operating officer yesterday, saying a fresh perspective is needed
to turn around the ailing jeans-maker.
</P>
<P>
   The exit by Jacobi, who started his Levi's career in 1970 as a
low-level production assistant, signifies the struggle that engulfs
the 146-year-old company as it tries to overcome its entrenched
corporate culture and become more responsive to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, what really made me think seriously (about
leaving) was watching Bill Chiasson, our new chief financial
officer'' who joined the company in August, Jacobi said yesterday.
``He started asking questions about why we do certain things, and
as we went through the discussion I realized that things that
seemed so logical in our own inbred mentality'' didn't necessarily
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `There really are new ways to be looking at
things,' '' said Jacobi, 54, who will remain until a replacement is
found from outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's chief executive Robert Haas, the great-great-grandnephew
of company founder Levi Strauss, credited Jacobi with instituting
painful measures such as factory closings and a $200 million
cost-cutting effort that should have been implemented years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Jacobi was promoted to president, he saw a company
that, while growing, faced ''falling market share among young
consumers, a cost structure that was getting out of line,
overcapacity in our sewing facilities in the U.S. and abroad, a
lack of product relevance and marketing that had become a little
too predictable,'' said Haas.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi responded by closing plants, laying off thousands of
workers, hiring a new advertising agency, moving toward trendier
fashions and restructuring management to focus more on branding.
The company is only one year into its two-year project of slashing
20 percent of its overhead costs, and more layoffs are expected in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's sales, meanwhile, declined 4 percent in 1997 and are
expected to have dropped even more when the company reports its
1998 sales next month. Although the company's Slates and Dockers
lines are growing rapidly, its Levi's jeans market share has
declined to about half the 30 percent level it enjoyed in 1990,
according to Tactical Retail Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the company's overhaul is well under way, ``there need
to be changes, and I think the good news here is that they're
finally recognizing it and saying `We must grow our sales,' '' said
Helen Bulwik, director of global retailing for Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to their future is bringing in a president and chief
operating officer who has the background to understand who their
customer is,'' said Bulwik. ``There's still room left for Levi's,
because of the strength of its brand, to see some significant
revenue increases.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the concrete changes he instituted, Jacobi pushed
for an overhaul of the company's debilitatingly democratic
corporate culture, which has been guided since 1987 by a document
called ``the Aspiration Statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi's employees were thoroughly trained to cultivate the values
of the Aspiration Statement, which encouraged mutual respect and a
diversity of opinions. Workers' compliance with the document was an
important benchmark in performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement had a devastating impact on company
effectiveness, according to people close to Levi's. Staff were
afraid to debate company strategy because arguing violated the
Aspiration Statement. On issues in which no consensus could be
reached, all too often, no action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, a former Peace Corps volunteer whose goal for the
Aspiration Statement was to create a more humanitarian company,
admits now that it spawned a ``dysfunctional'' culture. While
Levi's remains a values-driven concern, the document is undergoing
some ``fine tuning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One offshoot is that Levi's has stopped trying to reach
consensus on all issues among its nine senior level executives.
Now, issues are debated at meetings, the decisions are made by the
chief executive and chief operating officers, ``and we move on,''
Haas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
