<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCENT-KENAN-BOS &LR;      01-11 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-KENAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TO PAY $1.4 BILLION FOR SMALL BAY STATE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Kenan Sahin has always been unusual in the world of
high technology. For 16 years, the Turkish-born entrepreneur
quietly built his software company in an industry that craves the
limelight. He didn't hire outside publicists and rarely issued
press releases to tout his business. After starting his business in
1982 with just $1,000, he never took on outside investors,
remaining its sole owner.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed Monday when the 57-year-old former
professor became the nation's newest billionaire. In a deal that
catapulted him out of anonymity, Sahin agreed to sell his
750-employee software firm, Kenan Systems Corp. of Cambridge, to
giant Lucent Technologies Inc. for $1.45 billion in Lucent stock _
all of which will go to Sahin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have maintained a deep privacy _ in a company setting and
personally,'' said Sahin, acknowledging trepidation about being in
he spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Sahin's instant fortune reflects the rich opportunities possible
in the fast-moving field of telecommunications, where companies
like Lucent will pay huge amounts to buy technology and products
that let them get ahead of other global competitors. Indeed, huge
megabillion dollar deals are becoming commonplace these days in
telecommunicatoins as companies like Lucent prowl for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent saw a gem in Kenan Systems' arcane but sophisticated
software, used by leading phone carriers for tracking all kinds of
communications services and putting them on one customer bill.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sahin said part of his megafortune will go into an
educational foundation that he expects to launch in 2000. He said
it will focus on adapting classroom instructional material for the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to work with many people in education and other areas
before I begin the foundation next year,'' said Sahin, who spent
almost 16 years teaching at the MIT's Sloan School of Management,
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst and Harvard University's
School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Sahin, who clearly is uncomfortable with his sudden fame and
fortune, preferred to play down his windfall. ``I try not to think
about these things. The exciting thing is not so much the
price...but our success in the marketplace, our employees and our
contribution to the software industry in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahin came to the United States in 1963 to study at MIT. Two
years after graduating, he earned a business degree from Sloan. He
taught information systems and management science at the university
level from the late 1960s to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before leaving Sloan, he plunked down $1,000 to form
his company, then called Consultants for Management Decisions. He
later left Sloan to focus on his business, which had 20 employees
and was soon doing management consulting for the US Postal Service
before getting into communications software. In 1990, he changed
the company's name to Kenan Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software is a tricky area, it's not science, it's an art. One
of the biggest challenges is being able to have large groups of
companies work with the same software for billing and customer
care,'' said Sahin.
</P>
<P>
   Sahin saw his big opportunity in 1992 when fancy new
telecommunications services, such as cellular, Internet and other
technologies, started to become popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public reads newspaper ads for cellular phones, that don't
talk about the quality of the reception but about pricing like
getting 100 minutes and weekends free and discounts for this and
that. Telecommunications carriers today want to put all these
different offerings...together in a single bill.'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Systems began developing software that was snapped up by
the leading telecommunications players. In the past three years
revenues have skyrocketed from about $40 million to $175 million
and the company's work force has grown from 100 employees to 750 _
half in Cambridge and half elsewhere in the United States and in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Sahin, who employs two of his three sons in the
business, shunned the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenan treasures his company's autonomy and he turned down
offers to become a publicly traded company because he did not want
to be distracted by shareholder interactions or annual meetings,''
said Robert M. Kiburz , Kenan Systems senior vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He never accepted venture capital or Wall Street financing
offers, and he turned down numerous buyout offers.
</P>
<P>
   Sahin said decided to sell his business after realizing, during
a ``long walk'' during a London business trip, that remaining an
independent software firm has its limitations amid the
telecommunications revolution of the 1990s. He concluded that
Lucent, an AT&AMP;T Corp. spinoff that is a longtime Kenan Systems'
customer, would be a good partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the conclusion that we had done very well, but if
were to jump to the next level, we could not do it alone and if I
did not affiliate with Lucent I would expose the company to
subsequent stagnation and possible dangers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lucent, which had tried last year to acquire Kenan Systems
but was rebuffed by Sahin, buying the Cambridge company helps it
broaden beyond telecommunications equipment and become a major
software player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't a player in this (telecommunicaitons billing and
customer care) space, so we decided to jump to the head of the pack
by acquiring the hottest player in the business,'' said Dan
Stanzione, Lucent executive vice president who is chief operating
and president of Bell Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Sahin, who will address his employees Tuesday morning, will
continue to run Kenan Systems, which is expected to remain in
Cambridge as a Lucent subidiary. He will gain the additional title
of vice president of software technology at Bell Labs. Lucent said
it will give employees bonuses and Lucent stock to remain with
Kenan Systems.
</P>
<P>
   While announcing its deal to buy Kenan Systems, Lucent Monday
appeared to be on the verge of making an even bigger acquisition.
The New Jersey-based telecommunications giant reportedly is in
talks to buy Ascend Communications Inc. of Alameda, Calif., a big
data switch maker, for $15 billion to $16 billion. Some analysts
expect a merger announcement as early as Wednesday. In reaction to
the merger reports, Ascend stock Monday jumped 5 1/4 to close at 76
11/16, while Lucent fell 2 5/16 to $112 15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
