<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Vacationers Can't Cash in on Euro  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Castles, statues and mountain vistas may be on your agenda this
year if you're taking a vacation in Europe. One thing you won't
see, however, is the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Although 11 European countries began converting to the new joint
currency on January 1, actual cash and coin won't be available
until Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   You still can make purchases in euros, which are worth about
$1.16 _ but only with traveler's checks and credit cards. Any
change you receive will be in the currency of the ``Euroland''
country you are visiting _ Austria, Belgium, Finland, France,
Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal or
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Three other members of the European Union, &UR;  &LR; Denmark, Sweden and
the United Kingdom, as well as non-EU members such as Switzerland
and Poland, are keeping their national currencies. Greece, an EU
member, wants to convert to euros but is having trouble meeting
financial requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Major credit and charge card companies, such as Visa and
American Express, have made the conversion to the euro, as have
traveler's check issuers like Thomas Cooke. If you buy an item in
euros with your credit card, it will appear on your monthly
statement with a dollar conversion at that day's exchange rate, the
same system used for other foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
   By July 2002, you will be able to use the euro for all
transactions in the Euroland countries, which will make it easier
to compare prices between countries and also calculate how much you
are spending in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, you can't use euros everywhere. While euro
charges are accepted by some tourist-oriented enterprises such as
Marks &AMP; Spencer and EuroDisney, most have not made the change.
</P>
<P>
   American Express spokeswoman Victoria Handwerk recommends that
Europe-bound travelers continue to take with them a mix of local
currencies, travelers checks and credit or charge cards.
</P>
<P>
   The more transactions you make in euros, the more you will save
in money-changing fees. If you wind up with too many euro checks,
most exchange bureaus and banks in Euroland countries will convert
them into national currencies without charging a fee. However, if
you change them into dollars or other non-Euroland currencies, you
may be charged for the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   What to do if you have the option of making a payment in either
the euro or a traditional currency like the French franc or the
Dutch guilder?
</P>
<P>
   Nick Colannino, a spokesman for the European Commission, the
governing body for the EU, says it doesn't make any difference. As
soon as the euro became active, all 11 Euroland currencies were
pegged to it and are moving collectively relative to other
currencies such as the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
