<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRAVOLTA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN OF `ACTION': TRAVOLTA, SERIOUS IN LATEST FILM, IS AT HEART
A  CLOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEVA CHONIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``I should like,'' John Travolta declares in a
tony British accent, ``to perform an interpretive dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopting an expression of the most sublime suffering, the actor
flails across the length of his palatial hotel suite, where he's
ensconced to talk about his new movie ``A Civil Action.'' But film
is the last thing on his mind as he wails a lyric from the musical
``Rent'' like an existential mantra: ``Won't you light my (set
ital)caaaandle(end ital) / Light my (set ital)caaaandle(end ital)
...'' He doubles over, giggling.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta is just getting warmed up. Settling back into his
straight-backed Edwardian chair, he adopts a Viennese accent and
leans conspiratorially across a glass table. ``Do not think of me
as your psychoanalyst but as your well-qualified friend,'' he
whispers to an interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10 a.m., the sun is shining, the suite is white and
Travolta is dressed entirely in black. ``Muhammad Ali once told me,
`Always wear black, 'cause it slims ya down.''' He pats his round
belly. ``Even then I knew of my proclivity for ... what's that word
again? Corpulence.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta's suit boasts casually clean lines that hint at wealth
and languid chic. The famous Travolta looks are intact, if packing
a little more padding since their '70s salad days.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old actor still knows how to shake his booty. In ``A
Civil Action,'' on the other hand, Travolta offers a study in
understatement as Jan Schlichtmann, a snaky personal-injury
attorney who sacrifices his career to champion the cause of a town
that claims its children are dying from water laced with toxic
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta, who met the real Schlichtmann while filming in Boston,
acknowledges that at first he had a hard time getting his head
around playing an ambulance-chasing attorney _ albeit one who
experienced a life-changing epiphany and turned environmental
crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept reminding myself that I didn't have to like him,
because I don't know if I could really like a guy who chooses that
kind of a life, even if in the end he evolves into a pretty soulful
guy,'' Travolta confesses, staring thoughtfully _ perhaps
suspiciously _ at his water glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think Schlichtmann as a character is necessarily
unlikable, though his tactics are. I think that `A Civil Action'
will let audiences see for the first time some of the realities of
the practice of law. Now (set ital)those(end ital) are unlikable.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta does share his character's love of fast machines _ in a
pivotal scene in the film, Schlichtmann gets a ticket for speeding
in his Porsche _ and Travolta flies, expertly, his own fleet of
four jets. He piloted a 707 to San Francisco the night before his
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally nocturnal,'' he explains. ``My average sleep time
is 5 or 6 a.m. I've been this way my entire life. Even in school I
would go to bed at 1 a.m. if my mom would let me stay up. I have a
theory, and it's pretty obvious, so it's not a great one, but here
it is: If your perceptions are acute, you're perceiving everybody's
s_ in the daytime and it's acting as an antagonism. Then suddenly
everybody goes to bed, and you can just be who you are. I think I'm
more who I am from midnight to 5.''
</P>
<P>
   The wee hours of the morning weren't always times for serene
reflection. During his days as a stage actor touring with musicals
such as ``Grease,'' Travolta suffered from insomnia. ``I was so
lonely. I wasn't really friends with anybody, and I just wanted to
be coddled, maybe because I come from a sheltered background. And
there's no one interested in coddling you when you're 18 or 19. I
was very naive about what life should be.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses to gaze out the window. ``Awww, now you're making me
cry. But that's really what I wanted. That's what I still want, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta grew up in a dramatic household. His parents were
involved in theater and encouraged their youngest son (out of six
children) to perform musical numbers in their living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I forced (set ital)them,(end ital)'' he chuckles. ``I
wanted to be one of those kids in `Gypsy' who held a balloon. I was
worse than a stage mother. I was a bratty stage kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Travolta is on his feet again, laughing, swirling
across an imaginary stage. For the next five minutes, movie star
and interviewer proceed to dance, execute heinous interpretations
of flowering trees and recite random passages from Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you love this?'' Travolta says, pausing for breath and
still giggling. ``There's this unfortunate James Dean thing that
some actors get into, where they think pain and death is art.
Uh-uh, baby. The pleasures in life are harder to find. That's the
real challenge in acting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
