<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TOUR-SPI &LR;      01-11 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC SUDDENLY APPRECIATES (GASP) QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It's too late for ``Maximum Bob'' and other
good shows that died too soon, but ABC's programming pooh-bahs seem
to have heard what viewers and TV columnists have been screaming
about for several years. Jamie Tarses and Stu Bloomberg said Monday
they are convinced that good new shows like ``Sports Night'' and
``Cupid'' need time to build an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Well, duh!
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give shows more time for people to find them,''
said Tarses, president of ABC Entertainment. ``If you've got a good
show, you want to have the luxury of letting it fail by virtue of
the fact that people are rejecting it, not that they simply were
unaware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to photocopy this for use as ammunition the next time
ABC yanks a promising new show.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is ...
</P>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   The losers are other shows that have created a mini-industry on
Oscar night by airing pre-Oscar programs rooted in the red-carpet
romp of the glitterati.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy's contract with ABC prohibits anyone other than ABC
from airing live footage during the half hour before the March 21
ceremony _ when many of Hollywood's big-name celebrities will
emerge from their limos to greet the vernal equinox. That's because
the Academy and ABC will do their own pre-gala show for the first
time, hosted by Oscar winner Geena Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Academy president Robert Rehme said no one has griped to him
yet, but Gil Cates, producer of the Oscar telecast, said, ``I'm
sure over the next six to eight weeks we'll have complaints, and
we'll deal with them as we get them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar telecast this year moves to Sunday, the only day on
which the Academy Awards have never been presented. The preliminary
show airs at 5 p.m. Pacific time, the actual ceremony at 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   A few words from producer David E. Kelley on Marla Sokoloff, who
plays Lucy Hatcher, the bratty office manager who pushes everyone's
buttons on ``The Practice'':
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were looking for in the character, more than anything
else, is someone who could come in and, with one line, make an
impression, either good or bad, with our characters. ... She just
captivated us from the very beginning. She's funny. She's able to
punch lines easily and quickly. You believe her intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers hoping to see loose-lipped Lucy get a pink slip will be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure you,'' Kelley said, ``she's not finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' ends its run on Fox, possibly
this season or maybe next, producers Aaron Spelling and E. Duke
Vincent are ready with ``90210: The New Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time to do it again,'' Spelling said, `` ... with
different characters, with a mixed ethnic group _ a mistake we made
with the first `90210' _ and we're looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And now for the real truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good franchise,'' Spelling confessed, ``and easy to
sell overseas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
