<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JANUARY 12
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SAFRICA-BIKO-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 10,
about a former South African police officer who was denied amnesty
in connection with the death of the anti-apartheid campaigner Steve
Biko in 1977 misspelled the officer's surname. He is Gideon
Nieuwoudt, not Niewhoudt.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ITALY-VATICAN-NYT (moved on Friday, Jan. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Jan. 8,
about a meeting between Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy and
Pope John Paul II misidentified the archdiocese of Michele Cardinal
Giordano, whose investigation by Italian law enforcement officials
is a source of friction between the Vatican and the Italian
Government. Cardinal Giordano is the Archbishop of Naples, not
Milan. A picture caption with the article referred incorrectly to
Mr. D'Alema's two children. He has a son and a daughter, not two
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IMPEACH-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 10,
about the issue of calling witnesses in President Clinton's Senate
trial misstated the party of Senator John B. Breaux of Louisiana.
He is a Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
