<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-INAUG-COX     01-11 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-INAUG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft tackles literacy in inaugural address
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper and Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft used his inaugural speech Monday
to call for 20,000 Ohioans to volunteer to teach children to read,
and said that under his leadership, Ohio will become the ``Reading
State of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft, 57, was officially sworn in as Ohio's 67th governor in a
private ceremony just after midnight Sunday. Twelve hours later, he
ceremonially took the oath of office before an audience of about
4,000 in the elegant Ohio Theatre in downtown Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Anna, 19, administered the oath while his wife,
Hope, held his family Bible. It was the same Bible Taft's
great-grandfather, U.S. President William Howard Taft, bought in a
Cincinnati bookstore and used for his swearing-in as president in
1909.
</P>
<P>
   Also taking oaths of office Monday were Lt. Gov. Maureen
O'Connor; Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell, who has been
Ohio treasurer; incumbent Attorney General Betty Montgomery;
incumbent Auditor Jim Petro; and new Treasurer Joseph Deters,
former Hamilton County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the governor and his wife attended three balls:
the $1,000 per ticket Governor's Ball, the $250 per person Capitol
Ball and the $25 Buckeye Bash. The proceeds are to pay for the
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Taft said he has the opportunity to do what only
one other person has done: ``Be at the helm when our state closes
the door on one century and opens the door to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 20th century, he said, Ohio was a giant
on the industrial frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, the frontier is not the western edge of America or
the cutting edge of industry. Our frontier is knowledge and
technology _ a place where Ohio must be a leader among states and
nations.''
</P>
<P>
   To become that leader, he said, Ohio must make sure schools are
``adequately funded, safely built, well-maintained, and
laser-focused on academic achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the court order to overhaul Ohio's school funding
system, Taft said no other issue has triggered so many harsh words.
Now, he said, barricades must be replaced with bridges.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that fewer than half of Ohio's fourth graders passed
the ``reading'' portion of the state proficiency test, and he said,
``There is no single educational challenge of greater urgency than
the need to make sure every Ohioan learns how to read because no
matter how advanced our technology is in the next frontier, reading
is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, he had pledged to create a volunteer force
of 10,000 reading tutors for students in the kindergarten through
fourth grade. On Monday, he said he would double the program, and
called for 20,000 tutors.
</P>
<P>
   He said next week he will begin tutoring a student at Kent
Elementary School in Columbus, and he called on his ``partners in
state government'' to become reading tutors for children in need.
</P>
<P>
   Taft praised his wife for devoting herself to a crusade against
drug and alcohol abuse and said she will personally lead a new
campaign to engage parents, neighborhoods and others in abuse
prevention and education.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks and months ahead, Taft said he will present details
of his ``opportunity agenda'' to Ohioans and the legislature. On
Monday, he said he favors changing the tax code to recognize that
``lifelong learning leads to lifelong earning'' by making college
tuition and job training costs more affordable. He also said
patients must have access to the medical care they need and judges
should be given the tools to prevent juvenile delinquents from
becoming juvenile criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The address was well received by both Democratic and Republican
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, said the emphasis on reading
is better and more focused than former Gov. George Voinovich's
pledge to be the education governor.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jim Buchy, R-Greenville, said Taft's promise to run
an ethical administration may have been the most important part of
the speech. ``If that occurs over the next eight years, no matter
what else happens, he will have been successful as governor,''
Buchy said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. J. Donald Mottley, R-West Carrollton, was pleased
with Taft's emphasis on technology, and said, ``Our region has some
unique things to bring to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He touched all the right notes,'' said state Rep. Jeff
Jacobson, R-Phillisburg. ``He is obviously very enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Richard Finan, who, like Taft, is also a
Republican from Cincinnati, said he has fielded many questions
about the fact key state posts are now held by Cincinnatians,
including Blackwell and Deters. Finan said Hamilton County ``has
been known for good government'' and he expects that tradition to
continue under Taft.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Elsie Snider, a 73-year-old retiree from
Elmore in northwest Ohio, said she'd like to volunteer as a reading
tutor. ``I was glad to hear him talk about education. It's such a
big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Snider and others stood in a two- to three-hour receiving line
to get a chance to greet the governor and his wife at a reception
inside the theatre's Galbreath Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Taft succeeds Gov. Nancy Hollister, the state's first woman
governor, who completed the last 11 days Gov. George Voinovich's
term, after he left for a seat in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's first executive order, signed Monday afternoon, froze
hiring in all state agencies under the governor's office. For six
months all vacant positions will be reviewed by the department of
budget and management and filled only if they are essential to
running state government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state, even though our economy is good today, faces
serious budgetary challenges,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Montgomery on Monday identified several broad
areas of concern for her second term, including health care,
juvenile crime and protecting the elderly from fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Jasper and Jim Bebbington write for the Dayton Daily News,
Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
