<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SPEAKER-COX     01-11 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SPEAKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas house expected to support Laney
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas House Speaker James ``Pete'' Laney has
heard the partisan horror stories from his counterparts in the
other 49 states: Massive staff layoffs after one party grabs
control of a chamber from the other. Laptops distributed to the
majority party, but withheld from the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the best job there is in state government anywhere in
the United States,'' said the 55-year-old cotton farmer from Hale
Center, a town of 2,000 near Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an extraordinary turn of events, the Democrat will be
holding on to his dream job, which he has held since 1993, for at
least the next two years. The 150 members of the traditionally
nonpartisan Texas House will elect a speaker shortly after the
session begins at noonon Tuesday _ as part of a political play that
began almost two years ago. In fact, the real election for speaker
occurred between sessions, when a majority of representatives
signed written pledges of support for Laney. Laney's fourth term
was virtually confirmed on election night, when Democrats retained
control of the House and quashed the possibility of a Republican
challenge to his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As speaker, Laney has tremendous influence over the day-to-day
workings of the House _ and the fate of individual bills.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several weeks, Laney will choose the chairmen and
vice-chairmen of House committees and assign members to fill many
of the slots. When the House and Senate pass different versions of
bills, the speaker assigns representatives to meet with senators to
hammer out a final version.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker also assigns bills to committees, meaning that Laney
can send legislation he supports to panels where they are likely to
get a favorable hearing. Members can't speak on the floor without
his permission, so he can prevent them from offering certain
amendments or expressing unwanted views.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the powers of the speaker's office enable
Laney to make the House focus on his priorities. But because Laney
is famously reticent _ and deferential, at least publicly, to the
will of his colleagues _ it's hard to say what those priorities
are.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview in his Capitol office, Laney mentioned
education and utility deregulation, and suggested that there may be
action to curb the high cost of campaigns, which he believes is
dampening political participation.
</P>
<P>
   But his response to a question on how the multi-billion dollar
state budget surplus should be spent was typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been bashful about saying that I would like to see
us look at the big picture and a long-term investment of this money
so it's not just a dividing up of the pie type deal,'' Laney said
rather cryptically. ``(We should) just make sure that the money
goes where it produces positive results.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   But Laney's low-key approach has produced positive results,
according to many of his colleagues. He's earned accolades from
nearly everyone, for example, for his efforts to let the sun shine
on previously secret House proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Laney took the House helm at a time of mounting concern over
backroom dealing and ethical lapses by lawmakers. His predecessor,
Gib Lewis, had been indicted on an ethics charge accusing him of
accepting an illegal gift from a San Antonio law firm, and
legislators were under fire for lobbyist-paid vacations and other
perks. Lewis pleaded no contest to a lesser charge and did not seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Laney had been one of Lewis' lieutenants, but he promised
reforms to open the House's legislative sausage-making to the
public. The House Calendars Committee, which schedules bills for
floor debate _ or doesn't, effectively killing them _ would
deliberate openly for the first time, he said. Lawmakers no longer
would have to vote on bills or amendments before they had a chance
to read them, and there would be fewer late-night decisions after
marathon floor sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Many legislators and good government advocates say Laney has
largely fulfilled his promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's done an excellent job in reforming the rules of
the House and restoring credibility to the House,'' said Suzy
Woodford of Common Cause. ``In terms of the legislative process,
it's clearly become more open.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kent Grusendorf, R-Arlington, who was a vocal critic of the
secret powers of the Calendars Committee, said opening the doors of
that panel is ``the number one improvement'' of Laney's tenure.
Rep. Elliott Naishtat, D-Austin, contrasted the committee's
operations during his first term, when Lewis was speaker, to the
current rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several bills that I sponsored my first term which never made
it out of the Calendars Committee, for reasons unknown to me, in
subsequent sessions became laws,'' Naishtat said.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant change, according to both Grusendorf and
Woodford, is that under Laney the House has reformed its rules so
that a speaker no longer can punish rebellious chairs by replacing
them during a session.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Smith of Public Citizen praised Laney for having ``a steady
and true gavel in terms of generally siding with long-held
precedents'' on procedural rulings, rather than ruling according to
his whims.
</P>
<P>
   But Laney hasn't kept another promise he made when he was first
elected _ to remain in the speaker's post for only two terms.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1970s, speakers customarily served for two terms. Bill
Clayton broke with that tradition by remaining speaker for four
sessions between 1975 and 1982. Clayton was succeeded by Lewis, who
served a record five terms. When Lewis was indicted, many observers
said that too much power had become concentrated in the speaker's
office during his long tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But Laney now says his 1993 pledge was ``to stay as long as the
membership desires me to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not foresee leaving before redistricting,'' he said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith of Public Citizen said he isn't bothered by that
broken promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Laney is a classic example of why we don't believe in
term limits,'' Smith said. ``When you have good leader, there's no
point in replacing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
