<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMANSACHS-SHAKEUP-     01-11 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMANSACHS-SHAKEUP-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS SHAKES UP TOP MANAGEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. shook up senior management Monday
after suffering steep losses in bond trading and delaying its plan
to go public last year, with Jon Corzine, the co-chairman and chief
executive, withdrawing from day-to-day management.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 52, ceded management responsibilities to Henry Paulson
Jr., 52, his co-chairman and chief executive. Corzine will continue
at the firm as a senior partner and non-executive chairman. Goldman
also named John Thain, 43, and John Thornton, 45, co-chief
operating officers reporting to Paulson, a move that formally
establishes the duo as the heirs apparent of Wall Street's last big
private partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman called the changes a natural evolution toward a more
corporate-style management structure in line with plans to revive
the public stock offering sometime this year. As part of the
overhaul, Goldman named a 15-member management team consisting of
division heads to replace the five partners who now make most big
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But some Goldman bankers said privately that the moves amounted
to a power play by Paulson, Thain and Thornton, who seized on weak
results in last year's fourth quarter to speed up a leadership
transition.
</P>
<P>
   The management shift was made final last week in a meeting of
Goldman's executive committee over the objections of Corzine,
people at the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who has led Goldman since 1994 and who served as sole
chairman and chief executive until he promoted Paulson to join him
in May, had long envisioned promoting a team of new managers to
take over some of his duties. But Corzine was described as opposed
to a proposal to make such changes now and agreed to it only under
pressure, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a native of Illinois noted for his laid-back demeanor
and professorial speaking style, rose through the firm's cutthroat
bond business and was the top executive most closely associated
with its risky trading operations. Goldman suffered heavy trading
losses estimated at half a billion dollars last fall. The losses
caused Goldman to record an 80 percent decline in fourth quarter
earnings and pushed annual profits below the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's image also suffered when Goldman delayed its
much-anticipated initial public offering in September. He had
shepherded the plan to go public for years, overcoming substantial
opposition within the firm, but had to retreat when market
conditions soured. Goldman executives stressed that the public
offering was still on track and that Corzine would continue to
focus on preparing to sell stock in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, in an interview Monday, described the suggestion that
his accession amounted to a palace coup as ``inaccurate in every
respect.'' He said the management changes had nothing to do with
Goldman's trading losses or the delay in the public offering,
adding that he would continue to work closely with Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an evolutionary transition in management and
governance, something that made long-term sense for the firm,''
said Paulson, a Chicago native who earned his Goldman stripes
advising companies and arranging big banking deals. ``The firm is
doing very well, and we thought it made sense to put it in place
these changes in place before the public offering.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Corzine said he has every intention of remaining active at
Goldman. He said that the firm's performance in 1998 was good given
the poor market conditions. ``This was a volatile period in the
business, not something that's unique to Goldman Sachs or Jon
Corzine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quick shifts in leadership are not unusual on Wall Street during
tough times. Corzine himself took control of Goldman in 1994,
during one of the toughest years in its recent history. Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. fired or demoted executives in its bond and risk
management division after suffering a loss in last year's third
quarter. James Dimon, the president of Citigroup, resigned under
pressure after the bank's Salomon Smith Barney investment banking
unit suffered steep trading losses and the newly merged firm had
difficulty integrating its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said they were surprised by the changes at
Goldman. But some said there were logical reasons that the firm
would want to de-emphasize trading as it prepared to go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corzine came up from the trading side, and the trading side
has not done so well,'' said Hal Schroeder, an investment banking
analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods. ``As you go public, the risk
profile of the organization has the change. To the extent you are
making this change you need new leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman relies much more on trading than many of its peers,
including Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Merrill Lynch. Those firms
have larger fee-generating money-management divisions and retail
brokerage operations. In the first half of this year, which was
highly profitable for Goldman, the firm earned 43 percent of its
profits from trading on behalf of customers and for its own
account.
</P>
<P>
   Weak earnings during the downturn in stock and bond markets were
not unique to Goldman. Merrill suffered an outright loss in this
year's third quarter. But Morgan Stanley powered ahead to record
earnings both for the fourth quarter and for the year. Lehman
Brothers, which like Goldman derives the largest slice of its
earnings from trading, had a smaller fourth-quarter decline than
Goldman and posted record earnings for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare them to Lehman and Morgan, Goldman got the
worst of it,'' said Raphael Soifer, brokerage analyst at Brown
Brothers Harriman. ``I'm not sure that calls for major strategic
rethinking, but it has to be of some concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes at Goldman indicate that Thain and Thornton are in
line to take over leadership of the firm. The two have been viewed
as a close team since they jointly managed Goldman's European
operations in the mid-1990s. Before their promotions to chief
operation officers, Thain, considered a protege of Corzine, served
as chief financial officer. Thornton, who is based in London,
manages Goldman's extensive international banking business.
</P>
<P>
   The two are seen as complementary. Thain, like Corzine, comes
from Goldman's fixed-income division and succeeded Corzine as chief
financial officer. Thornton, like Paulson, specializes in advising
major companies and led the firm's highly successful push to become
a major player in European and Asian investment banking. Thornton's
client list includes Ford Motor, Laura Ashley and Richard Branson,
the British entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a logical step for two strong young leaders,'' said
Paulson, adding that he fully expects them to succeed him down the
road. ``We like to do things in an orderly manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman insiders said that in the debate over whether to go
public, Thain was seen as lukewarm to the idea and Thornton was
known to be strongly opposed. But Paulson said that has changed. He
emphasized that the entire management team now stood solidly behind
the plan to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if we do not go public in 1999,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
