<HEADLINE>
BRUINS STRUGGLE TO PICK UP SLACK LEFT BY INJURED BOURQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With Ray Bourque sidelined by a hip flexor strain, he
knew he was going to have to work harder, much harder. He knew he
was going to have to play more, much more. But Kyle McLaren said he
had no inkling that he was going to be in the lineup for 36 minutes
and 38 seconds of Saturday's game against the Maple Leafs in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 37 minutes of torture, too, as the Bruins were
shellacked by Toronto, 6-3, after the Leafs had taken a 4-0 lead
only 14 minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The only player who was on the ice more than McLaren was
goaltender Rob Tallas, who relieved Byron Dafoe at 4-0 and played
45:46.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns went with four defensemen for the most part,
with Brandon Smith, in his NHL debut, playing just 1:37. Don
Sweeney, who played 28:46, was one of four Bruins and the only
defenseman to finish with a plus.Darren Van Impe, suffering from
the flu, logged one second shy of 30 minutes and Hal Gill was on
for 21:38. But it was up to McLaren to pull yeoman's duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I played that much,'' said the 21-year-old
McLaren, who is emerging in his fourth season as one of the best
blue liners. ``I knew I played a lot because I felt like it, but
almost 37 minutes, that's a lot of ice time
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired, not really mentally but physically. I had nothing
in my legs. I got a little tired and you try to slow your game down
a little bit, and with that team, you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The first clue he had that he was logging a heavy load was when
someone told him he had played 26 minutes in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're in the game, you're going and going,'' said
McLaren. ``Even when I play 20 minutes, I'm tired some shifts out
there. With four defensemen, I knew I was going to get a lot of ice
time, everybody was. Five is OK. Six is good but four is tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even feel like I came off in the second period.
You're there for a couple of seconds, you catch your breath, get
some water, take a deep breath, and you're right back out there.
You don't really have time to think about being tired. You're just
going and going and doing your job. You try to get breaks during
whistles and stops in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's absence was sorely felt, literally and figuratively,
as the undermanned Bruins tried to fill their captain's
considerable shoes. It didn't help that, of the available players,
two were fighting the flu, two others had a total of two games of
NHL experience, and another had played just eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is truly our heart and soul and has been for many years,
even before I got here,'' said McLaren, who was mentored by Bourque
during his rookie year. ``I think this team can play without him if
he's hurt. I don't think it's a sign of anything to come with him
missing one game. You look at what he brings to the team and it's
everything. It's not just offense or defense, it's the whole game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're missing your key guy, I can't pick up his slack.
Donny can't pick up his slack. It has to be the 20 guys on the ice
who are playing that night. They have to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said that if Saturday's disaster taught the young
defensemen anything, it was to appreciate the workload Bourque
carries. That message wasn't lost on McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 38 years old playing 30 minutes _ I don't know how he
does it,'' said McLaren. ``I'm 21 and I'm barely getting over 25
and I'm very tired after games. He's a machine. Look at his legs,
they're tree trunks. He's in the best shape I've seen a guy in.
When I miss the net, you can see I'm upset. When he misses the net
or something, it's the same face as always. I'm still astonished by
him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bourque is the steady, strong two-way player, McLaren's
trademark is his mean streak. When he first broke in, he would have
the jump on opposing players who tried to challenge him physically
because he's lefthanded. He figured if he could get the first shot
in, he'd have a good chance. After 3 1/2 years, he still has an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still don't know I'm lefthanded,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Burns thinks McLaren is at his best when he's nasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I've seen of him this year,'' said the coach. ``He
gets lackadaisical sometimes. He's getting close to that point
where he could become a great player in this league. I love when
he's dirty, and he can be dirty, too. He can be a mean SOB. I
wouldn't want to play against him when he's in that mood, and we
try to get him in that mood.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren gets frustrated when he doesn't play that way. When he
goes home after games, he watches the replay on TV and cringes when
he sees himself not playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm hitting and being the meanest guy out there, I help
this team out,'' he said. ``When I'm quiet or timid on hitting
guys, that's when I feel myself being an average player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be 6-4 and go out there and play like I'm 5-2. I know
sometimes I do that, I play like I'm small, and that's not good.
When I go out and hit guys, the crowd gets into it. That's the best
feeling I get, when the crowd goes nuts after a big hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
