<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HIGHERED-COX     01-11 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HIGHERED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmaker urges one overseer for schools, colleges
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's public education system, from
kindergarten through college, should be governed by a single
commissioner and a super-board, the head of the House Higher
Education Committee said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you have one commissioner, that commissioner
would be equally concerned about public education and higher
education,'' said Chairwoman Irma Rangel, D-Kingsville, speaking to
participants at a higher education symposium in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Public schools have dragged their feet in developing curricula
that adequately prepare students to make a smooth transition from
high school to college, Rangel said. And colleges and universities
have been slow in focusing their resources on public schools to
help them prepare students for the rigors of college, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between what subjects students need to earn their
diplomas and what academic requirements they need to be admitted to
college could best be closed by a single commissioner and
super-board focused on both sectors of education, Rangel said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said she intends to capture her thoughts in legislation.
Her comments came at the first Higher Education Issues and the 76th
Texas Legislature forum at the University of Texas. The symposium
brought together college admissions officials, lending institutions
and policymakers to examine bills and proposals lawmakers will
consider to increase financial aid, improve college graduation
rates and increase enrollment of Hispanic and black students
without using affirmative action criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, nine states _ mostly small ones _ and Washington,
D.C., and Puerto Rico have one commissioner and a super-board. The
states include Hawaii, Rhode Island, Utah, Nevada, North Dakota and
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   But larger states, such as Georgia, Maryland and Ohio, are
examining the concept of administering education from kindergarten
through college _ called ``K-16'' _ instead of the traditional
kindergarten through grade 12 model. Such a model aims to create
seamless transitions between public school and college, improve
teacher preparation and balance spending among public schools, said
Amy Cook, a research assistant for the Education Commission of the
States in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the separation of powers, that transition is not as
seamless as some would like it,'' Cook said. ``High school
graduation requirements don't necessarily match up with college
admissions requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia in 1995 created a prekindergarten through 16 council to
deal with those issues as well as governance issues affecting
public schools and state colleges and universities, she said. The
state still has two commissioners, however, one for public
education and another for higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said her proposal likely ``won't go anywhere'' this
session but at least it will call attention to educational
disparities between high schools and colleges and urge stronger
partnerships between colleges and universities and their pipeline _
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like public schools and colleges and universities would
have a better partnership by having one commissioner instead of
two,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
