<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DETROIT-CLEANUP-ART-6     01-11 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-CLEANUP-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOR CITY: WHERE THE ROADS OUTSIDE ARE FRIGHTFUL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill., Ohio, N.Y., Ga., D.C.)   (jw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Every city reacts in its own way to snow. Atlantans
panic and drive badly. Washington closes government offices early
and sends everyone home. Chicagoans expect their politicians to
have the streets plowed immediately _ or face the consequences at
the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has another, more surprising approach to snow: Ignore
it.
</P>
<P>
   For as far back as this city has been able to check its records,
close to half a century, it has had a policy of not plowing
residential streets. As a result, it has just 59 snowplows,
compared with 750 in Chicago, whose area is just slightly larger.
Only large avenues, highways and the streets in front of schools
are plowed here, and even those are done slowly.
</P>
<P>
   But with many Detroit neighborhoods still impassable from the
foot of snow that fell on Jan. 2, and with three more snowfalls
since then having added a half-foot, a lot of people here are
suddenly angry about the policy. To make matters worse, the
temperature has seldom climbed even into the 20s since the first of
the year, and never above the freezing mark, while nighttime
temperatures have dropped as low as 10 below zero, unusually cold
for southeastern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there is no thaw in sight, and the snow is turning to
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have had trouble reaching their jobs. Schools were
closed for most of last week, and few children have been able to
reach them since they reopened on Friday. Food distributors' trucks
have had trouble supplying corner grocery stores, which remain
common here because the city's poverty and crime have scared off
most supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy snowfall nine days ago caused particular trouble at
Detroit's airport, where dozens of arriving Northwest Airlines
flights waited for hours before unloading passengers because the
airline did not have ground crews available. The airline, the city
and Wayne County have been trading accusations ever since over
whether Northwest should have diverted the flights to other cities
or whether Detroit's snow removal policies prevented the airline's
workers from reaching the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Johnson, 23, has been unable to walk her 6-year-old
son, Demar, to school because the snow is too deep for his short
legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to walk in the streets,'' Ms. Johnson said angrily,
``and the streets are no better.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her neighbors, James E. Barksdale, 75, has lived at his
home for 50 years, and in all that time the street in front of it
has never been plowed, he said as he stood in 3-degree weather late
Monday morning. He was digging a path down his driveway to the
road, where the snow had been tamped down by the repeated passing
of sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Dennis Archer has taken the brunt of the criticism. He
waited five days to start paying suburban governments to send 17
snowplows here to help clear the streets. Then the suburbs, most of
which try to plow all their streets, quickly recalled their trucks
when more snow began falling last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has asked for a citywide volunteer effort to shovel
streets and sidewalks. But that has had limited effect in a
sprawling city that is six times the size of Manhattan and has less
than half the population.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, the city had been planning to improve its snow
removal efforts this winter, having ordered 42 new trucks with
snowplows for delivery last autumn. But the trucks have not
arrived, because, Archer said in an interview, the manufacturer of
the trucks' transmissions is behind schedule.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The policy of letting residential neighborhoods fend for
themselves is rooted in the city's peculiar combination of climate
and history.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Great Lakes ports like Cleveland and Buffalo,
Detroit gets little ``lake effect'' snow, because it is situated on
the Detroit River, 20 miles upwind of Lake Erie and across the
state from Lake Michigan. So the city usually gets its snow three
or four inches at a time; in a city of self-reliant auto workers,
driving over a little snow is not viewed as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's population has also plummeted, from a peak of 2.2
million in the mid-1950s to some 950,000 now. Four-fifths of the
city's white population moved to the suburbs, mainly after the
riots of 1967. While there have been recent hints of an economic
recovery, the city remains among the poorest in the nation, with
thousands of abandoned houses on which no taxes are paid. What tax
revenue there is brings many demands other than snow removal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all that is the fact that Detroit, though largely a city
of single-family homes, has a scarcity of home garages. Few
residents have anywhere to park their cars except on the street,
which would make snow removal a headache in any case.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as five years ago, when 10 inches of snow
immobilized Detroit just as Archer was being inaugurated for his
first term, the snow removal policy did not create controversy. But
the mayor seems to have raised expectations since then by promising
to improve services.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Michael Bilandic of Chicago lost an election in 1979
because of his city's difficulties in cleaning up after a blizzard
that year, and Mayor John Lindsay of New York had trouble winning
re-election in 1969 after streets in Queens were not cleared
quickly following a snowstorm. But Archer, a Democrat, said he
believed that Detroit voters would not hold the current problems
against him. In any event, he is only one year into his second
four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that even as several more inches of
snow fell Monday night, the mayor's reputation was suffering but
might yet recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically he's damaged,'' said Mario Morrow, a political
analyst here. ``I wouldn't say he's buried at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
