<SLUG> BC-DOOMSDAY-CULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES STILL CUT OFF FROM CULT MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Family and friends of members of an apocalyptic cult
who were deported from Jerusalem kept vigil Monday in hopes of
seeing grandchildren they had never met or sons and daughters who
had disappeared months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Eight adults and six children were deported on Saturday by the
Israeli authorities, who cited fears of violence by the parents,
who are members of Concerned Christians, a group led by Monte Kim
Miller, a former resident of Denver. The Denver police, citing
security concerns, moved the deportees from the airport before the
families could get in touch with them, taking them to a Holiday Inn
downtown, where some of the relatives still waited Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like a yo-yo of emotions,'' said Sherry Clark of
Carbondale, Colo., who spoke for the waiting families. ``It's been
great disappointment, despair for parents, anger, crushing our hope
beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Dyck, the father of James Dyck, 20, who joined the group
with his wife and their infant son, hoped for a moment of contact.
``I just wanted to say, `I love you, we miss you,' and maybe that
was all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday a police officer escorted at least four of the adults to
a state motor vehicle office, as their driver's licenses were left
behind in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the families have tried sending notes. Most said they
had not heard a word, but one family member apparently received a
four-word note. A local television station said the note read,
``Mom, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
