<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-DEATH-CO     01-11 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carnival death going back to grand jury
 &HT;    By Leah Quin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The case of carnival owners and workers charged
with murder in the death of a Wells Branch teen-ager killed on a
ride will head back to the grand jury this spring, prosecutors said
Monday. The announcement prompted cautious optimism from defense
attorneys and industry officials who said the original charges are
ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors handling the case declined to say exactly why
they're presenting the case again. However, they referred to first
assistant district attorney Rosemary Lehmberg's statement in
September that the indictments might be fine-tuned and the charges
might be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   No new evidence has surfaced since a Travis County grand jury
returned nine charges of murder this fall against the owners,
operators, maintenance workers and inspectors for B&AMP;B Amusements,
said prosecutor Brian Kingston. All nine were charged in the death
of 15-year-old Leslie Lane, who was killed March 19 while riding
the Himalaya, a circular coaster, at the Austin-Travis County
Livestock Show &AMP; Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to look at the charges and see if they're
supportive of the evidence,'' Kingston said. ``That's all we're
going to do. There's been no new light shed on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand juries often re-indict cases, sometimes just changing the
wording of the original charges. But the panel would also have the
opportunity to reduce or drop charges against all or some of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we're hopeful,'' said David Wahlberg, an attorney
who represents maintenance worker Ottis Frasure of Yuma, Ariz. ``A
second grand jury may take a more critical look at the state's
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   When the charges first became known, legal experts and industry
officials were taken aback. Cases involving ride accidents are
rarely _ if ever _ tried in criminal court, and the charge of
murder, which implies intent to kill, is unprecedented in the
carnival ride business, said Bob Johnson, director of the Outdoor
Amusement Business Association, based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to minimize the tragedy,'' Johnson said Monday.
``But as an industry, we can't believe the case belongs in criminal
court.''
</P>
<P>
   All nine defendants, all of whom live out of state, appeared in
court Monday, though attorneys did little more than confer behind
closed doors for an hour and then agree what information would be
shared between prosecutors and defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would present the case to the grand jury
within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Quin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
