<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINER-WIRING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF FIRE LEADS TO REQUEST FOR WIRING CHECKS ON PLANES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Canadian investigators have found extensive wiring
problems on several MD-11 airplanes, and United States safety
experts say more inspections are needed to avert the threat of
in-flight fires.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators began checking planes after the September crash of
a New York-to-Geneva Swissair flight, which killed all 229 people
aboard. Wires pulled from the wreckage, near Halifax, Nova Scotia,
showed signs of a potentially dangerous escape of electricity, or
arcing, and the Canadian authorities found other problems in MD-11s
they inspected that were still in service.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what the Canadian examinations found, the United States
agency in charge of investigating air crashes, the National
Transportation Safety Board, Monday asked the Federal Aviation
Administration to order checks of more wiring on MD-11s registered
in this country. The aviation agency said it was likely to order
such checks ``very shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Canadian crash, suspicion has centered on the
entertainment system, which used large amounts of electricity and
was unique to Swissair. Although investigators found wiring
problems with the entertainment system and other components, they
have not identified the cause of the crash. The areas of the
Swissair plane that showed arcing are common to all MD-11s, near
the circuit-breaker panel in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   In arcing, an electric current jumps from the copper wires to
the outside of the insulation, where it forms sparks. In a letter
dated Dec. 22 to Bernard Loeb, the director of aviation safety at
the National Transportation Safety Board in Washington, the
director of air investigations at the Canadian Transportation
Safety Board, J.L. Maxwell, said that the wires recovered from the
wreckage that showed arcing were two heavy-duty wires on the left
side of the plane, one carrying alternating current and the other
direct current. The wires carry power necessary to fly the plane in
an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few other wires that are identified as original aircraft
wiring show evidence of arcing, but could not be further identified
or physically located within the aircraft because the identifying
insulation covers are missing,'' Maxwell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter pointed out that it was well known that arcing could
be caused by a breakdown of insulation. Insulation, the letter
said, can be damaged by, among other things, vibration, moisture,
temperature extremes, strain and contact with rough surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation experts say the damaged wires may be an effect of the
crash, not the cause. The wires could have arced in the last
minutes of flight because of problems elsewhere on the plane, the
experts say, or might have been arcing for months.
</P>
<P>
   Other MD-11s, however, showed a variety of flaws, like wire with
insulation that was chafed, or bent tighter than manufacturers
allow, or not properly tightened. Electrical conduits that should
have been sealed were not, and ``various examples of damaged,
cracked, or chafed wires were found,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   It added that the investigating team ``has not established a
direct relationship between the wiring discrepancies discovered in
the in-service MD-11s that were recently inspected and the damaged
wire from the Swissair 111 wreckage.'' But because of the
inspections, Maxwell said in his letter, ``questions arise about
how widespread these phenomena might be within the MD-11 fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 65 MD-11s registered in the United States and 174
worldwide. McDonnell Douglas built the MD-11 as an improved version
of the DC-10, but after Boeing bought the company in 1997, it said
it would stop making the MD-11 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and a consultant to Swissair are helping by laying out
what should be inspected, Maxwell's letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, a copy of which was obtained by The New York Times,
is a summation of findings that Canadian investigators have shared
over time with American participants in the inquiry into the
Swissair crash. As the letter noted, in December the Federal
Aviation Agency ordered a one-time inspection of wiring above the
front doors of MD-11s, and Boeing also told its customers to check
some of the wiring.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed into the Atlantic a few minutes after the
pilots radioed that they had smoke in the cockpit. For months,
Canadian investigators have stopped short of saying there was a
fire on board, but the letter says that ceiling panels forward and
aft of the wall that divided the cockpit from the passenger cabin
showed damage ``consistent with the effects of a fire in those
areas; the initiating source of the fire is not known.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
