<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ABELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA P. ABELSON, 72, BOOKSTORE OWNER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa)  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virginia Eloise Peterson Abelson, a former bookstore owner and
past Democratic Party district leader who also worked in publishing
and created crossword puzzles, died on Sunday at her home in
Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y. She was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Abelson, a native of Red Oak, Iowa, graduated in 1948 &UR;  &LR; from
the University of Iowa, where she majored in English.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, she worked as an advertising director for
Cambridge University Press of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, she owned a store called Books Unltd. in Croton.
For about 15 years, into the 1980s, she also contributed crossword
puzzles that were published in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and 70s, Mrs. Abelson was a party district leader
in Croton. She was also a member of the board of the Croton
Community Nursery School.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Abelson is survived by her husband, Alan, a columnist for
Barron's magazine; a daughter, Reed Abelson of Manhattan, a
business reporter at The Times; a son, Justin, of Greenfield,
Mass., and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-660&AMP;     01-11 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MANAGERS OFFER A LEGAL BRIEF OF THEIR CASE AGAINST THE
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-CENSURE) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Henry Hyde and the 12 other impeachment
managers on Monday presented a road map of the case for removing
President Clinton that they plan to make to the Senate beginning on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 105-page document, with 250 pages of supporting evidence,
offers a highly circumstantial case that relies on persuading
senators that a chain of events, read in its entirety, demonstrates
a compelling argument for the president's ouster. Each senator will
receive a loose-leaf binder containing the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence contained in the record, when viewed as a unified
whole, overwhelmingly supports both charges,'' the document states.
The president is accused of perjury before a grand jury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The filing tracks the closing arguments made last month by David
P. Schippers, the chief House investigative counsel, and the House
Judiciary Committee's final report. Those presentations led the
Judiciary Committee and then the full House to approve along party
lines the two articles of impeachment against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, the House managers adopted a tone that was
alternately derisive and unyielding as they restated much of the
voluminous record that Hyde and the Judiciary Committee compiled in
their inquiry. Although they were restricted in their filing to the
House record, the managers' outline goes beyond bolstering the two
articles of impeachment. Even as it lists the number of sexual
encounters the president had with Monica S. Lewinsky, it asserts
that the sexual details of their affair need not be detailed either
in the brief or through witnesses' testimony at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is not about sex or private conduct,'' the brief
states. ``It is about multiple obstructions of justice, perjury,
false and misleading statements, and witness tampering _ all
committed or orchestrated by the President of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the managers' case is the charge that Clinton,
in his deposition in the sexual harassment suit brought by Paula
Jones, offered a cleverly worded lie about his relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky and then schemed to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the House managers argued, Clinton ``deliberately
and willfully testified falsely under oath'' before a federal grand
jury on Aug. 17. Clinton engaged in the scheme, the managers
asserted, to obstruct both the grand jury and the Jones civil case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the House managers said, obstructed justice in these
ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ Trying to influence the testimony of his secretary, Betty
Currie;
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing several of his top aides with ``elaborate lies''
about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky;
</P>
<P>
   _ Orchestrating a campaign to discredit Ms. Lewinsky to undercut
her credibility, and
</P>
<P>
   _ Using the power of the presidency to help get Ms. Lewinsky a
job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing a frequent defense raised by the White House that
Ms. Lewinsky testified that no one told her to lie or bought her
silence, the House managers argue that her words are not
exculpatory if they are viewed in context along with a skein of
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course no one said, `Now Monica, you go in there and
lie,''' the document read. ``They didn't have to. Ms. Lewinsky knew
what was expected of her. Similary, nobody promised her a job, but
once she signed the false affidavit she got one.''
</P>
<P>
   And the managers stressed what they consider the gravity of the
president's offenses, saying they ``have the effect of seriously
compromising the integrity of the entire judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's misconduct has had ``devastating'' consequences,
they state. ``Make no mistake, the conduct of the President is
inextricably bound to the welfare of the people of the United
States,'' the managers said. ``Not only does it affect economic and
national defense, but even more directly, it affects the moral and
law-abiding fiber of the commonwealth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Monday's filing marked the first step in a carefully scripted,
but still fragile, schedule the Senate unanimously adopted on
Friday, which postpones a decision on the polarizing issue of
whether to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to comment on the Senate's plan, Hyde told reporters:
``I'm in a difficult position. Now is not the time to get angry at
the Senate. At the same time, this is a strange process, one we're
not familiar with in terms of making a case. When we reach the
point of asking for witnesses, we feel that senators will be in
more generous mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the House managers and the White House have a total of 24
hours to present their cases. Rep. Charles T. Canady, R-Fla., said
the managers faced a ``strategic decision'' on whether to use all
of their time, because the Republicans don't want to ``test the
patience of those listening.'' House aides said on Monday night,
though, it appeared likely that the managers' presentation would
spill over to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the managers' current plan, subject to changes, Hyde would
open their presentation with brief introductory remarks. Rep. F.
James Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin would then give a 40-to-50
minute overview of the House's case.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the managers' case would be divided into three
parts. One team of managers, which includes several former federal
prosecutors, would present the factual record of the case, drawing
heavily on material from the independent counsel's report.
</P>
<P>
   This presentation, which would include Reps. Ed Bryant of
Tennessee, Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, James E. Rogan of California
and Bob Barr of Georgia, would last several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Following that, Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida would lead a team
laying out the legal basis for the two articles of impeachment,
perjury before a grand jury and obstruction of justice.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the managers linked the factual record to a legal
framework, Canady and a group of managers would make the
Constitutional arguments as to why the charges against the
President rise to impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these parts, but especially in the factual
presentation, the managers will highlight conflicting testimony
that requires the calling of witnesses to clarify the disputed
points.
</P>
<P>
   The managers last week spoke of summoning as many as 18
witnesses, but lawmakers say they have narrowed that list about six
witnesses. At the top of the list, managers say, are Ms. Lewinsky,
Mrs. Curry, and Vernon Jordan, one of the president's confidants
who helped Ms. Lewinsky get a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate's trial plan, senators would vote up or down on
a list of witnesses requested by the House managers and the White
House. After taking depositions from the witnesses, the Senate
would vote on which, if any, of them would actually testify in the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Rogan, Hyde and Rep. George W. Gekas of Pennsylvania,
will deliver the managers' closing arguments, with Hyde wrapping
up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
