<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8762 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     01-11 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL TEAMS INDEED SPECIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For five seasons, the Mighty Ducks' power play
was somewhat less than powerful. Anaheim's penalty killing unit
wasn't much to speak of, either.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Ducks' special teams were hardly anything
special. When the Ducks won, they usually won in spite of their
special teams, not because of them.
</P>
<P>
   But this season has been a special one for the Ducks' special
teams. Anaheim has the third-ranked power play in the NHL and the
penalty killing is ranked 10th.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers reflect a dramatic change for a team whose power
play had finished in the bottom three of the league four times in
five years. Moreover, the Ducks' penalty killing unit hasn't been
ranked higher than 17th since Anaheim's first season, when it was
the sixth best in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know how to explain it,'' said center Steve
Rucchin, a key contributor on both units, of this year's success.
``Obviously, it was something we stressed in the past, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understood it. Being part of the special teams, it was
pretty frustrating. It seemed like every year we would end up with
low numbers and you wouldn't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the Ducks are putting up special numbers, a big part
of the reason they've been able to hang around the .500 mark
despite being outscored 54-52 at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim has scored 39 power play goals, while allowing only 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can win games for you,'' said Paul Kariya of special teams
play. ``Keep their power play off the board and score one or two of
your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play has won us some games, and in the past that
really hasn't been the case. We have more confidence in it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially at the Pond. Anaheim has the NHL's top-ranked power
play at home (26.3 percent). The Ducks have scored at least one
power play goal in 18 of 20 games at home. Sunday night they stole
a game from Edmonton by scoring three times with a two-man
advantage. Earlier in the year, Anaheim scored four power play
goals in a victory over Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see guys out there who are very determined to make the power
play work,'' said defenseman Fredrik Olausson. ``Guys who want to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Ducks had the 25th-ranked power play last year,
Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg insists ``the power play isn't a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get surprised very much,'' he said, ``because with the
people we can put out there, we should have a good power play.''
</P>
<P>
   A move Hartsburg made in early November turned the power on for
Anaheim after the unit had stumbled out of the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were 4 for 45 with a man advantage when the Anaheim
coach moved Kariya back to the point -- a position just inside the
blue line where most plays are set up in such situations. The power
play has scored 35 goals in 31 games since the change and Kariya
leads the NHL with 26 power play points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a quarterback,'' said Hartsburg of the Ducks, who
hadn't had an effective one since Dmitri Mironov played the point
position on the '96-97 Anaheim power play, which finished ninth in
the league. ``Most good power plays have a guy back there who can
score and make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have three good players down low and if you have no
threat up top, I think you are easy to defend. It gives us more
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya did not play the point in college and only sporadically
during his first four NHL seasons, but the winger has made himself
right at home on the blue line this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is one of the few guys who can step in, play the point
and look natural at it,'' said Olausson, who often plays the other
point opposite Kariya and has contributed 17 power play points of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his intelligence and skills. Like getting shots through
to the net; that's the difference between a good player and a great
player.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Kariya tries to deflect the attention and praise,
preferring to credit the power play's overall chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a group that has played together for a while now,'' he
said, refering to Teemu Selanne, Olausson, Rucchin, and Marty
McInnis or Tomas Sandstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the coaches) have stuck with us and that has helped. In
the past we were always switching around. Now, you get to know
where somebody is and when somebody is going to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, who leads the team with nine power play goals, said
shooting is the key to power play success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how well you move the puck, if you don't
shoot,'' he said. ``You have to make the right decision when to
pass and when to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The room the Ducks are getting on their power play is exactly
what they are trying to take away when they kill penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin says the Ducks are trying to do that by pressuring the
puck more and taking some of the pressure off goalie Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, they'd want us to pressure, but when the other
team got the puck, we'd kind of sit back in our box,'' he
explained. ``Now we want guys to be jumping players at all times
and it seems to be working. Obviously, the less time you have, the
less time you have to make a play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2140EST &QL; 
