<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 1/11/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- IMPEACH-3, 1-11 -- Sen.
Mike DeWine (D-Ohio), third from left, discusses the Senate
impeachment proceedings with members of his staff on Monday. Two
days after the Senate struck an unexpected note of harmony with an
agreement on how to conduct the impeachment trial, Republicans and
Democrats clashed anew on Monday over whether to call witnesses.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- FBN-JETS-PARCELLS,
1-11 -- Bill Parcels, head coach of the New York Jets, speaks to
reporters on Monday. His team put on a powerful offensive show on
Sunday, and didn't allow several mental and physical blips to halt
them from defeating the Jaguars by 34-24 in what was the first
playoff game for more than half the Jets. It was also their seventh
straight victory. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) DETROIT -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- DETROIT-CLEANUP, 1-11 -- For
close to half a century, Detroit has had a policy of not plowing
residential streets. ``Out of my 50 years, it has never been
plowed,'' says James E. Barksdale, a 75-year-old retired auto parts
worker, of the street in front of his home on the city's east side.
When ice mixes with the snow, he cautions that ``you'd better use a
pick to get into it.'' (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- FAR-THEATER-REVIEW, 1-11 --
Michael Hayden and Lisa Emery in ``Far East,'' A.R. Gurney's uneven
but poignant new play at Lincoln Center. Throughout his career, the
author has been criticized for working on too small a canvas, but
here he tries hard to extend his thematic reach. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- NY-PORN-APPEAL, 1-11 -- A
shop which only sold sexually explicit material gets rid of some of
its goods in order to make room for non-pornographic products
during a sale in June. The United States Supreme Court on Monday
refused to hear a challange to New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's administration in curbing sex shops in the city.
(William Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LUBBOCK, Texas -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- PRAIRIE-DOG-DEBATE-2,
1-11 -- The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is set to announce soon
whether it sees sufficient cause for a nine-month study of whether
black-tailed prairie dogs, seen recently in a field, should be
listed as a threatened species. The notion of declaring the animals
threatened is greeted by most private ranchers and farmers in the
area with contempt. (David Bowser/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) AMARILLO, Texas -- Jan. 11, 1999 --
PRAIRIE-DOG-DEBATE-1, 1-11 -- George Carlile, an exterminator who's
been fumigating grain and poisoning prairie dogs for more than 40
years, holds a pellet of aluminum phosphide used to kill the
animal. The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is set to announce soon
whether it sees sufficient cause for a nine-month study of whether
black-tailed prairie dogs should be listed as a threatened species.
(David Bowser /New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- Jan. 11, 1999 --
SAFRICA-MURAL, 1-11 -- Reshada Crouse opposite her mural recently.
In a country with lots of memorials to British and Boer victories,
the South African artist has created an unusual post-apartheid
mural. (Lori Waselchuk/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- STOPPARD-BARD-B&AMP;W, 1-11 --
Tom Stoppard on the set of ``The Real Inspector Hound,'' in New
York in 1992. With ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Stoppard completes an
arc that began in 1967 with ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are
Dead,'' his first produced stage play. Taken in the context of the
playwright's other work, the two are primary instances of Stoppard
in love - with Shakespeare. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KINSHASA, CONGO -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- CONGO-CONFLICT, 1-11
-- A billboard in the capital emphasizes national unity near the
residence of Congo President Laurent Kabila. This huge and unsteady
country has become a battlefield of soldiers from no fewer than six
foreign nations. It is experiencing a war that has as much to do
with problems outside of Congo as inside it. (Nori Onishi/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MILAN, Italy -- Jan. 11, 1998 -- MILAN-MEN-FASHION-3,
01-11 -- An evolution of one trend-setting Gucci look from last
season, velvet jackets, were given the patina of garnets, rubies or
sapphires. Acting as a counterweight to the collection's whimsy
were militaristic jackets, coats and trousers with red piping. At
left is Ford's sport-military combination with white T-shirt and ,
at right, is a goatskin and fur topper over beaded and embroidered
jeans both by Tom Ford for Gucci. (Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MILAN, Italy -- Jan. 11, 1998 -- MILAN-MEN-FASHION-2,
01-11 -- Naoki Takizawa, designer of the Issey Miyake men's
collection, the elements of old and new were represented in
wonderful suits and coats to which he had applied a series of
creases resembling the folds in origami. At right is his more
pedestrian white ski parka and sleek sport pant. At left, is Dolce
&AMP; Gabbana's leather top stitched jacket and lean side zip pant.
(Corina Lecca/New York Times Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MILAN, Italy -- Jan. 11, 1998 -- MILAN-MEN-FASHION-1,
01-11 -- From Donatella Versace for Gianni Versace, right, a color
blocked leather coat with fur collar over zip-leg suit. Monster
coats of leather trimmed with huge collars of fox or wolf were
thrown over slim suits in Ms. Versace collection. At left, from Jil
Sander, is a sweatshirt-style pullover and unstructured trousers
from her this casual collection. (Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- IMPEACH-2, 1-11 -- Senator
Tom Harkin (D-Iowa), left, speaks with his colleague Sen. Paul
Wellstone (D. Minn.) in the Senate Waiting Room prior to a joint
news conference in the Capitol on Monday. Senate waiting room prior
to a joint press conference Monday afternoon. Two days after the
Senate struck an unexpected note of harmony with an agreement on
how to conduct the impeachment trial, Republicans and Democrats
clashed anew on Monday over whether to call witnesses. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SANTA FE, N.M. -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- SCI-SCALING, 1-11 --
From left, Dr. Brian Enquist, Dr. Geoffrey West and Dr. Jim Brown
of the Santa Fe Institute. In their collaborative theory, scaling
emerges from the geometrical and statistical properties of the
internal networks animals and plants use to distribute nutrients.
(Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- SCI-PSYCH-B&AMP;W, 1-11 -- Dr.
Robert Pyles, president of the American Psychoanalytic Association.
Unlike his predecessors of a few decades ago, who prided themselves
on a scholarly detachment and made no attempt to promote their
profession's image, Dr. Pyles is a political activist. ``This
attitude of psychoanalysis having to exist in some isolated
hothouse has driven me nuts,'' he says. ``I think it damn near
killed us.'' (Dr. Robert L. Pyles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Jan. 11, 1999 --
SCI-PACZYNSKI-PROFILE, 1-11 -- Princeton University's Dr. Bohdan
Paczynski is an aficionado of stars, be they binary, pulsating or
exploding. ``The point is that we just do not know what unexpected
things may be there,'' he says of the cosmos. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- SCI-SENIORS-BALANCE, 1-11 --
Experts are urging the elderly to adopt a balance-aiding regimen,
already popular among younger adults. John Blievernicht, left,
recently supervising balancing exercises; Joanna Chodorowska sits
on a Swiss Ball and Paul Odell stands on a low balance beam. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- BARYSHNIKOV-KABUKI, 1-11 --
Mikhail Barishnikov in rehearsal for a dance he will perform at an
AIDS benefit on Tuesday. Baryshnikov, 51, will perform choreography
drawn from traditional Japanese forms in ``Dance With Three Drums
and Flute,'' a new solo created for him by the Kabuki star
Tamasaburo Bando. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- STAGE-BRUSTEIN-BOS,
1-11 -- Robert Brustein outside the American Repertory Theatre at
Harvard. ``I think my whole career as an artistic director, and as
a critic, has been devoted to try to persuade people that theater
can be something more than entertaining,'' explains Brustein, 71.
``That the theater is worthy of the same kind of serious attention
as classical music and the novel and dance, ballet, the opera.''
(Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- HILLARY-CLINTON-FLOATER,
1-11 -- First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton holds up a new
commemorative coin honoring Dolly Madison at the White House on
Monday. Mrs. Clinton has not announce running for any political
office. But that has not dampened a persistent buzz in New York
political circles that she might dive into the Democratic race to
succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- IMPEACH, 1-11 -- President
Clinton hosts Argentine President Carlos Menem, left, in the Oval
Office on Monday. At right is Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. Looking on in the background is an unidentified
interpreter. Two days after the Senate struck an unexpected note of
harmony with an agreement on how to conduct the impeachment trial,
Republicans and Democrats clashed anew on Monday over whether to
call witnesses. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
