internal networks animals and plants use to distribute nutrients.
(Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- SCI-PSYCH-B&AMP;W, 1-11 -- Dr.
Robert Pyles, president of the American Psychoanalytic Association.
Unlike his predecessors of a few decades ago, who prided themselves
on a scholarly detachment and made no attempt to promote their
profession's image, Dr. Pyles is a political activist. ``This
attitude of psychoanalysis having to exist in some isolated
hothouse has driven me nuts,'' he says. ``I think it damn near
killed us.'' (Dr. Robert L. Pyles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Jan. 11, 1999 --
SCI-PACZYNSKI-PROFILE, 1-11 -- Princeton University's Dr. Bohdan
Paczynski is an aficionado of stars, be they binary, pulsating or
exploding. ``The point is that we just do not know what unexpected
things may be there,'' he says of the cosmos. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- Jan. 11, 1999 -- SCI-SENIORS-BALANCE, 1-11 --
Experts are urging the elderly to adopt a balance-aiding regimen,
