<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-RELIGION-COX     01-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RELIGION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Bush endorses bill for religious freedom
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush gave a pre-session
endorsement Monday to legislation that would prohibit government
from interfering with the free exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country was founded on the rock of religious freedom,''
Bush said in a press conference. ``Yet recent court decisions have
begun chipping away at that rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas intends to restore it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Religious Freedom Restoration Act, which would replace
a national version struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1997,
would require government to have a ``compelling interest'' before
it could limit the free exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has bi-partisan support in the Texas House and Senate
and from a broad base of religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's enforcement strength, according to University of
Texas law professor Doug Laycock, is the right to ``sue for an
injunction to require the state agency to comply with the statute.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would waive the state's sovereign immunity,
clearing the way for anyone to sue the state for damages if the act
is violated. The act will apply to state and local governments and
any government-related entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill . . . puts the burden on government to have such a
compelling public interest before it in any way limits religious
expression,'' Bush said. ``Court decisions have made it easier for
government to encroach on people's religious rights, one small
action at at time: one bureaucratic rule; one regulatory decision;
one threatened lawsuit. That is unacceptable in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill parallels a national one that was passed by Congress,
signed by President Clinton in 1993, and struck down by the Supreme
Court in 1997. The court heard a case involving a Roman Catholic
church in Boerne _ about 80 miles southwest of Austin in the Hill
Country _ that wanted to expand its sanctuary but was refused a
building permit by local officials because the building was in a
historic district.
</P>
<P>
   The church countered that government was interfering with its
exercise of religion under the federal Religious Freedom
Restoration Act. Laycock, an expert on church-state issues, argued
the case before the Supreme Court on behalf of the church. The
court ruled in a 6-3 decision that Congress did not have the
authority to impose the law on the states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, states are enacting their own laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the most narrow and compelling of circumstances should
government interfere with a citizen's right to free exercise of
religion,'' said Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``When enforcement of regulation interferes with someone's
religious practice, it should be up to the government to prove that
enforcing the law in this particular case protects a vital public
need,'' added Rep. Scott Hochberg, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley and Hochberg are two of the bill's primary sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Religious Freedom Restoration Act was in response to
a 1990 Supreme Court decision that removed the longstanding
``strict scrutiny'' test, which said religions could not be unduly
burdened unless there was a ``compelling state interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal groups worried that the federal act might cause
discrimination, for example by offering rights to landlords who
refused to rent to non-married couples for religious reasons. That
concern does not apply to the Texas bill, Laycock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue can't arise in Texas because we don't prohibit
non-marital discrimination anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the law could offer prisoners some rights, Laycock
said. Under the act, any Texas prison that doesn't already
accommodate prisoners' religious dietary requirements probably
would have to, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the law won't protect everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the act will not shield gang members, who can be
prohibited from wearing religious symbols in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a compelling public reason why you don't let gang
members wear religious icons,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is supported by mainline religious leaders throughout
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rare indeed when the religious community speaks with one
voice,'' said Phil Strickland of the Baptist General Convention of
Texas, who helped to build the religious community coalition
supporting the measure. Every religious leader that was asked to
support the bill has signed on, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
