<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-UTAH-IMAGE-1STLDW     01-11 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-UTAH-IMAGE-1STLDWRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC SCANDAL TARNISHES SALT LAKE CITY'S MODERN IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, A member ..., to CORRECT date of upcoming
election to November, sted 2000; ADDS quote 4th graph; minor
changes, tightening throughout.)  (pr) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ For the past decade, Salt Lake City has been on
a roll. It has boomed as a Western high-tech center, one of the
nation's fastest-growing cities, and shed its image as a backwater
whose only claim was that it was the capital of the Mormon
religion. The 2002 Winter Olympics Games were supposed to be the
city's chance to show the world just how far it has come.
</P>
<P>
   But a scandal involving bribery allegations against top Olympic
officials has tarnished this city's effort to project a new a more
cosmopolitan image to the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the evolving scandal apparently claimed its latest
victim, one who has not been publicly linked with any corruption
allegations, Salt Lake City's mayor. The mayor, Deedee Corradini,
announced she would not run for a third term, crushing her dream of
presiding over the Olympics here. Only a year ago, the mayor,
smiling radiantly and dressed in a flame orange jumpsuit, accepted
the Olympic flag at the end of the Winter Olympics in Nagano,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, the 54-year mayor, with tears in her eyes,
alluded to the growing scandal only in passing, ``Despite all the
controversy swirling around Salt Lake City these days, I want you
to know this is a purely personal decision.'' She added, ``You
don't make a four-year decision based on a two- week event.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Salt Lake Olympic Committee board since she took
office seven years ago, Ms. Corradini maintained warm relations
with the International Olympic Committee, telling reporters on
several occasions in recent months that committee members were
urging her to run in November for a third term. But now four
official inquiries into the two Olympic committees are under way.
On Friday, she sat stolidly as the resignations were announced of
the top leadership of the Salt Lake Olympic Committee: Frank
Joklik, the president, and Dave Johnson, the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Utah's governor, Michael O. Leavitt, called for
``quick and complete'' disclosure of any wrongdoing in the bidding
process by Salt Lake City for the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This did not start in Salt Lake City, but it needs to stop
here,'' the Governor, a Republican, said in an interview. Referring
to the president of the International Olympic Committee, Juan
Antonio Samaranch, he said, ``President Samaranch has given me his
personal assurance that those involved will be expelled.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that a state panel could produce its report as early as
next week, the governor continued: ``This needs to be a turning
point for the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   The games are expected to cost $1.45 billion, and organizers are
worried that corporate sponsors may shy away if scandal taints the
selection process. Last week, U S West Inc., the official
telecommunications sponsor, announced it was delaying a $5 million
payment, pending answers to a series of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assurance I have had with the corporate sponsors I have
talked with has been that they will see this through,'' the
governor said, noting that he had talked to two companies.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Utahans had started pursuing the Winter
Olympics as an opportunity to show the world their state's modern
face.
</P>
<P>
   Greater Salt Lake now boasts of having more high-tech companies
_ 2,120 _ than fast food restaurants. And Salt Lake has the
nation's highest proportion of households with personal computers,
about 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive over its national image as a square city, dominated by
Mormons who shun coffee and alcohol, city promoters once gave
visiting sports reporters bottles of local beer and pointedly noted
that the city's first Starbucks coffee shop had just opened.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the Olympics, Salt Lake has become a vast
pre-Olympic construction site. Crews are building projects worth
more than $2 billion: a new runway and a refurbished terminal for
the international airport, a European-style light-rail system, new
hotels, an athlete's village, a winter sports park and an expansion
of the local football stadium to 50,000 seats. Commuters have
endured epic traffic jams as the north-south Interstate here, I-15,
is widened from six lanes to 10 lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Forty minutes to the east, in the snow-covered mountains of the
Wasatch Front, workers are putting the finishing touches on the
Olympic venues: ski jumps, luge runs, bobsled runs and Nordic
trails. Utah's 14 ski resorts are investing heavily, hoping to use
favorable Olympics publicity to catch up with Colorado, their
winter sports rival on the other side of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   On a state level, Utahans were so eager to get the Olympics that
they voted a sales tax to build Olympic facilities in 1989, six
years before the International Olympic Committee gave the state the
nod in the summer of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent airing of the Olympics selection
committee's dirty laundry, the Winter Games were backed by 62
percent of 423 Utah voters interviewed last weekend for a
KASL/Deseret News poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are demanding the right to review the books, but I
don't think they will lose the Olympics,'' said Dan Jones, whose
polling company conducted the survey. Noting that popular support
was in the midrange for polls conducted in the last five years, he
predicted that ``Governor Leavitt will turn over every stone'' to
clarify the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Utah's sometimes squeaky clean image, the state has been
plagued in past years by white collar crime.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, only weeks after her election, Ms. Corradini, a
Democrat, was embroiled in the collapse of the Bonneville Pacific
Corporation, an alternative energy company. Several company
principals went to jail in the case. Ms. Corradini, who was an
officer of a related corporate entity, agreed to an $800,000
settlement with Bonneville's bankrupcy trustee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a few months after the mayor was narrowly re-elected,
it became known that to pay the bankrupcy settlement she had
solicited and received $231,000 in gifts and loans from prominent
residents. A report on to the City Council about the gifts found
that half of the 24 individuals who gave or loaned money to the
mayor had business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Gunnarson, the Salt Lake County District Attorney and a
friend of the mayor, decided not to file charges in the affair,
citing the city's vaguely worded laws on conflicts of interest.
When she was not indicted, Ms. Corradini claimed vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics scandal really was what has ended her political
career,'' Deeda Seed, a Democratic member of the City Council, said
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-COKE-OLYMPICS-COX     01-11 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-COKE-OLYMPICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympics could lose Coke deal
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola, the longest-running and biggest-spending
Olympic sponsor, said Monday the escalating bribery scandal
surrounding the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City could threaten
the corporation's future Olympic funding if not cleared up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not handled properly, this could have significant negative
impact on our involvement with the Games as well as that of other
sponsors,'' Coca-Cola Olympic marketing spokesman Ben Deutch said.
</P>
<P>
   Because corporate and public support is the lifeblood of the
Olympics, the International Olympic Committee is marshaling a
public relations campaign to preserve both as the scandal continued
to puncture the integrity of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Payne, the IOC's marketing director in Lausanne,
Switzerland, is scheduled to meet with Coca-Cola officials today
and Wednesday in Atlanta to update them on the IOC's investigation
of the Salt Lake situation and to shore up support. Payne met with
officials of public relations powerhouse Hill &AMP; Knowlton in New
York on Monday. He will traverse the country to meet with other
worldwide sponsors, including Atlanta-based United Parcel Service,
Xerox and Visa, which pay upward of $40 million for a four-year
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate support remains an issue in Salt Lake, where $350
million of the $1.45 billion budget has yet to be raised.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Hodler, the IOC executive board member from Switzerland who
sparked the Olympic corruption investigation last month, said
Monday he believed the Salt Lake Games could be moved elsewhere or
canceled if organizers fall short of their budget in the event of
eroding corporate backing.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler ignited the biggest scandal in IOC history by alleging
that Salt Lake's efforts to secure the 2002 Games amounted to
bribery and by citing widespread corruption in other campaigns for
host cities, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, IOC Vice President Anita DeFrantz indicated as many
as 12 committee members might be ousted in the ensuing
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee Corradini, who helped win the
Winter Games for her city, said she has decided not to run for
re-election, but that it has nothing to do with the Olympic bribery
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to Olympic funding, Australia's Sydney Morning
Herald reported Monday that Caltex, a joint venture of the U.S. oil
companies Texaco and Chevron, had written to the organizing
committee for the Summer Games in 2000 that it was withdrawing from
an arrangement that would have set up a $6.3 million sponsorship
deal. A company spokesman cited a downturn in the oil industry, not
the Salt Lake scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola is already committed to sponsoring the Summer and
Winter Games through 2008. Only one other corporate sponsor,
Time/Sports Illustrated, is locked into such a lengthy contract.
Many of the current worldwide sponsors, including UPS, have yet to
commit to Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic brand is everything to us,'' said Susan Rosenberg,
Olympic marketing spokeswoman for UPS. ``But it is now premature
for us to go into a tailspin and determine if there's been a
serious damage to the brand. They need to fix it in a way not only
addressing the specifics of what happened in Salt Lake City, but
(that) also establishes a standard so there can be nothing
misconstrued moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's worldwide marketing agency, Atlanta-based Meridian
Management, also is working to soothe sponsors' concerns. ``We are
communicating with our partners on a daily basis and making them
comfortable that the IOC is taking the steps they need to take,''
said Terrence Burns, who managed Delta Air Lines' Olympic marketing
program in 1996 before joining Meridian as a senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these folks have long-term relationships with the IOC.
They are interested in this thing being solved quickly and
correctly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has been a sponsor since 1928 and, as a result, wields
considerable influence. The company spent more than $200 million on
its sponsorship and marketing of the Atlanta Games and the Olympic
torch relay.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola executives have expressed their concerns to Payne and
to Dick Pound, the IOC executive board member overseeing the
investigation. They've also talked to officials with the U.S.
Olympic Committee and the Salt Lake committee, and are concerned
about the results of ongoing investigations by the U.S. Justice
Department as well as a USOC ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a problem here that has to get fixed,'' Deutch said.
``It's not only a public relations issue, it is an operational
issue if the allegations are true. There is a process here that has
been violated. If those things occurred, then there needs to be a
change in the process or an enforcement of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Joklik, president of Salt Lake's organizing committee,
resigned last week after detailing a pattern of giving
scholarships, free medical treatment, lavish gifts and cash
payments of up to $70,000 to IOC members and their families during
the city's bid for the 2002 games.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg of UPS said, ``It's not enough to just point fingers.
The mere fact that people stand up and say mea culpa, the mere act
of an individual resigning, is not enough for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see what decisive action is taken to prevent this
from happening in the future, what action taken will mitigate
damage to the brand,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS will decide later this year if it will sign up for another
four-year Olympic sponsorship, Rosenberg noted. ``What happens will
factor into that decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns of Meridian Management said he believes the Olympics will
emerge unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are able to differentiate between the movement itself
and individuals in it,'' he said. ``The brand is 2,500 years old
and has been through a lot. And it has endured. It has, and will
continue to have, great attraction for sponsors and the public in
general, as long as it does things to maintain their confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch is scheduled to be in New
York City this month for the world premiere of a large-format,
IMAX-type film titled ``Olympic Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
