<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-1STLD     01-11 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ISSUES HIS FIRST DEFENSE DOCUMENTS; HOUSE PROSECUTORS
RESPOND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf for change of wording, making it read ``an illegal
presidential coverup,'' etc.) (See also IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-RULES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton formally defended himself on
Monday for the first time against removal from office by the
Senate, arguing that he had committed no crimes and that the
charges against him are so vague and muddled that they are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, prosecutors drawn from the House of Representatives
released a scorching memorandum mapping out the case for an illegal
presidential coverup that they will begin to present on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling documents, filed in response to deadlines imposed by
the Senate, drew on the same body of evidence to provide
night-and-day versions of whether Clinton lied under oath and
obstructed justice to hide his affair with Monica Lewinsky _ and
whether the charges against him could warrant ejecting a president
from office for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   None of the wrongdoing of which the president is accused, his
lawyers argued, reaches the level of ``high crimes or
misdemeanors,'' the constitutional standard for removal from
office. ``The charges in the two articles of impeachment do not
permit the conviction and removal from office of a duly elected
president,'' they wrote in their 13-page brief.
</P>
<P>
   But the House prosecutors took a far different view of the
charges and the stakes. ``If the president is not convicted as a
consequence of the conduct that has been portrayed,'' they wrote,
reprising arguments made before the House Judiciary Committee,
``then no House of Representatives will ever be able to impeach
again and no Senate will ever convict. The bar will be so high that
only a convicted felon or a traitor will need to be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In an intensifying flurry of paper, the filings came as each
side refined its legal and political arguments in preparation for
Thursday. The defense filing on Monday was in response to a summons
from the Senate last Friday. On Wednesday, the president's team is
expected to provide the Senate with a fuller brief rebutting
Monday's prosecutorial document, which at 105 pages contained much
more detail.
</P>
<P>
   Although he met briefly with his lawyers and political team this
morning, Clinton did not comment in public on his filing. Instead,
he presided over the state visit by President Carlos Menem of
Argentina, greeting him in the Grand Foyer on Monday morning,
meeting with him at length and holding a state dinner for him this
evening. In an unusual move, the White House did not schedule a
joint press conference for the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton sat down with Menem at the White House, nine of
the 13 House prosecutors toured the floor of the Senate, where new
tables were installed over the weekend for the prosecution and
defense tea
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spent two hours Monday afternoon in the Oval Office
with his senior advisers to discuss his State of the Union Message.
The White House said that despite the objections even of some
Democrats, Clinton still planned to give the speech to both houses
of Congress on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   To contest charges that Clinton lied under oath and obstructed
justice, his lawyers boiled down their previous lengthy factual
arguments into a tightly focused summary. They attacked what they
called myths about his sworn testimony before the grand jury
investigating his relationship with Lewinsky. He simply did not
tell lies that the House accused him of telling, they said.
</P>
<P>
   They said, for example, that it was a myth ``that the president
failed to admit his improper intimate relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they noted, Clinton read a prepared statement at the
beginning of his testimony acknowledging ``inappropriate intimate
contact.'' The statement's intent, the lawyers wrote, was to permit
prosecutors to ``obtain necessary information without unduly
dwelling on the salacious details of the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But the House prosecutors tried to turn that same statement
against the president, saying that it ``contained totally false
assertions and other clearly misleading information.''
</P>
<P>
   On the charges of obstruction of justice, the president's
lawyers saw sweeping vindication where the prosecutors saw an
absurdly narrow interpretation of the facts. Clinton's defense, as
presented on Monday, relies heavily on Lewinsky statement to the
grand jury _ unprompted by prosecutors _ that ``no one every asked
me to lie and I was never promised a job for my silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Expecting that argument, the prosecutors had prepared a salvo of
derision, turning against Clinton a favorite White House term for
describing his ability to divide his attention. The evidence, they
wrote, ``cannot be compartmentalized.'' Events and words that seem
innocent, they added, ``may well take on a sinister, or even
criminal, connotation when observed in the context of the whole
plot.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The White House brief was delivered to the Secretary of the
Senate at 11:48 a.m. by G. Timothy Saunders, Clinton's executive
clerk, who routinely ferries White House documents to the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While it responded on Monday as mandated to the Senate summons,
the White House passed up an opportunity to file motions
challenging the charges or the conduct of the trial by 5 p.m. Such
motions, White House aides said, could have delayed the trial for
weeks, and they are eager to move it along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the judgment that the Senate should go forward in the
way they're going forward, and we shouldn't try to pre-empt this
process before both sides have had a chance to make their case,''
said Joseph Lockhart, the White House press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican senators voted unanimously on Friday
to approve the procedure for conducting the trial, and if the White
House had objected, it may have appeared to be playing the spoiler.
The move might have alienated some of the jurors Clinton needs.
Filing motions, said one senior Clinton adviser, ``didn't seem like
something that would be welcomed or effective.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House signaled that if the Senate chooses to
extend the trial beyond prosecution and defense presentations to
the calling of witnesses, it will probably file motions challenging
the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Those motions could include one arguing that the charges against
Clinton should be dropped because they are woefully imprecise. For
the first time on Monday, Clinton's lawyers advanced that line of
reasoning in their brief, using it to assault each of the two
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the article accusing Clinton of perjury
identifies no specific perjurious statements. ``One of the
fundamental principles of our law and the Constitution is that a
person has a right to know what specific charges he or she is
facing,'' the lawyers wrote, warning that otherwise a trial
``becomes a moving target for the accused.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, they argued, the first article is ``fatally flawed''
because it bundles together multiple accusations of perjury by
Clinton in his grand jury testimony, without listing individual
statements. As a result, they wrote, Clinton could be convicted by
senators who disagreed widely about his wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if 34 senators agreed that Clinton perjured himself in
Answer X, and a different 34 senators agreed that he perjured
himself in Answer Y, the Senate would have the requisite 68 votes
to convict him _ even though the 68 senators did not all agree
about what he had done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also argued that the second article of impeachment,
accusing the president of obstruction of justice ``provides little
or no concrete information about the specific acts in which the
president is alleged to have engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   In the brief the lawyers drew heavily on Lewinsky's testimony in
attacking the charge of obstruction of justice, but not in
attacking the charge of perjury. The reason is that Lewinsky's
testimony conflicts with the president's on some issues central to
the perjury charges.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are seizing on the portions of Lewinsky's testimony
that they find helpful while downplaying those that hurt.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Lockhart was pressed to say whether, in
including Lewinsky's testimony in their filing, Clinton's lawyers
were endorsing her truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that they were not. ``The inclusion of her
testimony is an acknowledgment of her testimony,'' he said. He
called the quotations in the brief ``a useful piece of information
for the senators as they move forward to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart repeated a previous assertion that the White House
would not attack Lewinsky's credibility. ``For a year now, people
in this building have not atacked her, and I don't expect that to
change,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
