<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8788 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-H&AMP;Q-SFCHRON &LR;      01-11 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-H&AMP;Q-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gene Stalkers Draw Potential Investors  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The money-making potential of mapping disease-causing genes drew
overflow crowds of investors to two sessions at yesterday's
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist health care conference.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day H&AMP;Q conference in San Francisco offers 240 public
and private biotech firms a chance to explain their companies to
venture capitalists, financial analysts and stock fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees lined up to hear presentations from Incyte
Pharmaceuticals of Palo Alto and Genset SA of Paris, two of several
rivals in the ``genomics'' race to identify _ and patent _ the
genes that cause heart disease, cancer and other maladies. Armed
with this data, biotech firms can then develop ``designer drugs''
to attack or prevent these diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte portrayed the race as a new gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capability here to discover every disease
pathway,'' Incyte chief executive Roy Whitfield promised the crowd
that spilled out of the Grand Ballroom at the Westin St. Francis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Whitfield's 30-minute presentation followed a similar talk by
Pascal Brandys, chief executive of Genset.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a race here, very clearly,'' Brandys said. ``As soon
as the gene is associated with a disease,'' a firm can file for a
patent.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte's Whitfield spent much of his presentation discussing the
fact that his firm, unlike many competitors, is already generating
a profit by selling some of the genetic information it has
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be several years before clear winners emerge in the
genomics sweepstakes, making investments now highly speculative,
according to Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock
Letter in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte gained $1.25 yesterday to close at $37.75. Genset, which
is traded on the Munich exchange, was unchanged at 69 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Lance, chief executive of Chiron Corp., used his 30-minute
talk to tell investors how he plans to refocus his Emeryville firm,
a biotech pioneer whose stock has stalled in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Lance, who took over Chiron last March, has sold off some
business units to push a handful of promising new cancer and
AIDS-fighting drugs though the Food and Drug Administration's
approval process.
</P>
<P>
   Now sitting on more than $1 billion in cash, Chiron is in the
enviable position of being able to buy up  &LR; young cash-starved
companies with promising technologies that have not been able to
stage initial public offerings because Wall Street has shied away
from small ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock
Letter, said Chiron's size, cash hoard and new leadership ``make it
one of the most interesting companies around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last of the big biotech firms that hasn't had a stock
run-up,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Lance's solid but dull presentation failed to ignite much
interest yesterday as Chiron slipped 31 cents to close at $29.56.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
