<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA's Investment Banking Arm Seems to Be Backing Off Biotech  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Is NationsBanc Montgomery Securities _ the investment banking arm
of the new BankAmerica _ pulling a Kevorkian with its biotech
business?
</P>
<P>
   Word in the hallways and salons of the annual Hambrecht &AMP; Quist
health care stock conference at the Westin St. Francis here is that
Montgomery is pulling the plug on its life sciences and medical
technology underwriting practices.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the move was news to BankAmerica Chairman and CEO Hugh
McColl, who launched his West Coast goodwill tour yesterday when he
met with a group of editors and reporters at The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that our company was one of the risk takers,''
McColl retorted, adding that he was unaware of such a decision by
his investment banking unit.
</P>
<P>
   A NationsBanc Montgomery Securities (yes, the legal name for the
underwriter is still NationsBanc Montgomery) was unable to confirm
the information before deadline. Investment bankers have long
speculated that NationsBanc Montgomery will shift its underwriting
emphasis away from risky, entrepreneurial sectors, such as high
tech and biotech, and concentrate on raising money for the parent
bank's existing commercial banking customers.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the silver-haired Southern dealmaker took the
opportunity to underscore why what is now BankAmerica bought
Montgomery in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery was an important acquisition to us because it would
enhance our underwriting ability,'' McColl said.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that he managed to build a significant investment
banking presence in bonds and other financial instruments prior to
the Montgomery buyout, but that the acquisition gave the new
BankAmerica the machinery necessary to underwrite initial public
offerings and other stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has it been easy'' building an investment bank from the ground
up? McColl asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not. (And) we've had some of the same pain in (our
new) equity business, too,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McColl acknowledged that the second half of 1998 was
pretty rough for biotech. What's more, he underscored his bank's
fundamental strengths in underwriting energy and forest-related
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, with the prospects of a top competitor leaving the
biotech sector, H&AMP;Q Chairman Dan Case seized the opportunity to
remind potential clients that his firm is committed to the health
care and life sciences sector.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q is the last of four so-called technology banks that is still
independent (Robertson Stephens, Alex. Brown and Montgomery were
each acquired), and Case is banking that his firm will increase
this year the volume of biotech deals that it lead-manages.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, if Montgomery is de-emphasizing biotech, then its
research department will likely reduce coverage on many of the
companies that Montgomery helped take public. Sell-side analyst
coverage of young public companies is critical to the future growth
of their stock, and it is often one of the things investment
bankers pledge to provide after the IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview yesterday, Case couldn't help but fire a shot at
his Bay Area rivals. ``We've always believed in doing what we
promised our clients,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PULLING THE TRIGGER &LR; : From the better late than never file. ...
As reported last summer by Street Smarts, San Francisco's
MarketWatch.com (parent company of the financial Web site CBS
MarketWatch) is going forward with its plans for an initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company's underwriters are expected to price its shares as
early as this Thursday. About 2.75 million shares will go on the
market at a price estimated between $10 and $12 a share. The deal
is being lead-managed by BT Alex. Brown assisted by Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, MarketWatch management was shooting for a mid-August
IPO after several hot offerings had ignited the new issue market
last summer, especially those by Broadcast.com and Inktomi. But of
course, August's market meltdown placed most offerings on the back
burner for the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-CAPITAL &LR; : Critical Path, a San Francisco outsourcer of
electronic-mail services, is expected to announce today that it has
raised about $33 million in private equity financing, sources
familiar with the situation say.
</P>
<P>
   In what would be the company's second round of funding,
2-year-old Critical Path managed to tap some high-profile clients,
including E-Trade and US West. During the past 12 months, the
start-up has attracted about $42 million in funding.
</P>
<P>
   Other major investors included Verio, Network Solutions, CMG
Venture, Benchmark Capital, Mohr, Davidow Ventures, Attractor
Investment Management and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. E-Trade chief
executive Christos M. Cotsakos sits on Critical Path's board, which
is eyeing a possible IPO down the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
