<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YEAR 2000, UTILITIES EXPECT NO BIG PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A succession of electric industry officials and the
secretary of energy said Monday that the utilities had made
substantial progress toward eradicating the threat of
computer-induced blackout on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to build public confidence in the industry on which so
much activity depends, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said at a
briefing for reporters, ``We can be cautiously optimistic about the
prospects for the industry meeting its Y2K challenge.'' Tests and
repairs are now more than half done, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Electric Reliability Council, an umbrella
group that in the past has mostly concerned itself with whether
enough generating stations and transmission lines were in operation
to meet demand, released a report that forecast only minor
problems. These ``do not appear to affect the ability to keep
generators and power delivery facilities in service and electricity
supplied to customers,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   North America's four major electric grids run from moment to
moment with the aid of complex digital computer systems, but
experts said that even if parts of those failed, the system was
mostly reliant on heavy equipment that would keep plodding along,
much of it controlled by old-fashioned nondigital components that
do not have software.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials said they were still a little anxious
about the telephone system, without which they cannot operate. They
plan two major Year 2000 tests in the coming months but got started
too late to involve the phone companies in the tests, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that if the telecommunications and electric systems
hold together, all else will work or can at least be fixed. But
those two systems require each other, and if either fails,
disruptions will be more widespread and persistent, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 problem is an artifact of computer programmers'
decisions in years past to enter years as two-digit numbers; when
the clock rolls over from 99 to 00, some computers will shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities could be especially vulnerable because of their
interconnections, with hundreds of generators belonging to hundreds
of utilities mostly run by computers in 136 separate control
centers, which themselves are linked by computer and telephone
lines, swapping power among utilities and among centers minute by
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Michehl R. Gent, president of the reliability council, said,
``The networks are so tightly tied together that if we have some
kind of upset in Minneapolis, we can tell by frequency variations
in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Interconnection is generally considered to improve reliability,
because when all the generators pull together, the failure of a
single one is like a decision by a single rower on a big scull to
stop pulling; the boat continues almost unaffected. But unsure
about their neighbors, some utilities have lately speculated about
cutting themselves loose. Gent said Monday that this would be a
last-ditch tactic.
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, appointed by President Clinton to coordinate the
federal government's Year 2000 efforts, said, ``In this industry,
our worst-case scenarios appear not to involve anything that looks
like a national failure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
