<SLUG> BC-NY-BANANA-SCAM-220&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANANA REPUBLIC CLERK CHARGED WITH FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sales clerk at a Banana Republic store on
Manhattan's Upper East Side has been arrested and accused of
defrauding the store out of more than $50,000 during the busy
pre-Christmas rush, police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk, Carolyn Peters, 47, was arrested Sunday evening as
she left the store at 59th Street and Lexington Avenue and faces
charges of grand larceny and criminal possession of stolen
property, said Lt. Richard Ference of the Police Department's grand
larceny task force.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplice who did not work at the store, identified as Peter
Jamwant, 31, was arrested on the same charges, Ference said.
</P>
<P>
   Ference declined to explain how the scheme worked, except to say
that it involved ``the fraudulent use of a credit card.'' But a law
enforcement official who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
that Ms. Peters was accused of taking merchandise from the shelves,
entering it into the store's computers as returned goods and then
having refunds added to the credit card accounts of friends and
accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Ms. Peters was also charged with stealing
clothes from the store and giving them to Jamwant, who is accused
of selling the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Both were being held Monday night awaiting arraignments on
charges of larceny and possession of stolen property, officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ference said Ms. Peters and Jamwant, who met while working
together at another store, were accused of stealing more than
$50,000. The law enforcement official said that detectives were
investigating the extent of the scheme and that the final tally
could reach as much as $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ference said that Banana Republic officials discovered the
problem after doing an audit and conducting their own
investigation. The main thefts took place on Dec. 23 and 24, he
said. The police were called in last week, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Banana Republic, Cindy Capobianco, declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
