<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-TRANSPLANT-COX     01-11 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-TRANSPLANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Infant undergoes skin transplant operation
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a procedure that scientists say heralds a new era of
factory-harvested body parts, doctors here are replacing most of
the skin of a 2-month-old Broward County girl using a product grown
from human skin nurtured in a bed of cow collagen.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-minute operation performed Monday at the Jackson Children's
Hospital _ one of dozens Tori Cameron will undergo in the next few
months _ appeared virtually painless to the infant. Though the
product, called Apligraf, has been used to treat skin ulcers in
hundreds of patients, Tori is the youngest person to receive such a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   She also is the first Apligraf patient with epidermolysis
bullosa, a rare disease that causes her skin to rub off at the
slightest friction and has left her covered in purple and black
blisters.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure performed Monday was the 15th graft Cameron has
received since she was 11 days old.
</P>
<P>
   University of Miami doctors gently placed a circular piece of
the pink-hued Apligraf over a raw, red sore on Tori's tiny right
calf. Then they covered it in anti-bacterial ointment and wrapped
it in gauze.
</P>
<P>
   In six days the area will be indistinguishable from healthy
patches of her natural skin, said Dr. William Eaglstein, the
chairman of dermatology at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is potentially, a very exciting therapeutic
breakthrough,'' said Dr. Lawrence Schachner, a professor of
pediatrics and dermatology at the University of Miami. ``There is
really no other treatment for this disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Bio-engineered skin begins to realize medicine's potential to
grow custom body organs and nerves, Eaglstein said. Apligraf is the
first mass-produced substance containing living human cells to be
approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, according to
Organogenesis, the Canton, Mass.-based company that makes it.
</P>
<P>
   Science is less than 20 years away from growing livers, hearts,
kidneys and even spinal cords, Eaglstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Apligraf is made by sterilizing the foreskin of circumcised
infants and nourishing it with protein of cow collagen. Kept at
body temperature in a company factory, the skin cells divide at a
phenomenal rate. One postal stamp-sized piece of foreskin can
multiply enough times in 21 days to cover six football fields.
</P>
<P>
   And because the nearly-transparent skin has no pigments or
immune-system cells, it will not be rejected by the recipient. In a
process scientists do not completely understand, Apligraf blends in
and actually stimulates the patient's own skin to rebuild itself.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, Lorraine and Randy Cameron hope the Apligraf will
eventually teach their daughter's skin to grow normally.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of epidermolysis bullosa do not have the normal
anchoring mechanisms that attach skin to flesh. As a result, the
slightest rubbing or friction causes sores and blisters as the skin
rubs off. About one in three babies born with this disease _ which
affects 100,000 people in the United States _ die before their
first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   It takes the Camerons up to 45 minutes to change Tori's diapers.
Her arms and legs are wrapped in gauze from previous grafts. The
dressing must be changed once a day, which can take an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go at her pace,'' said Lorraine Cameron. ``Whatever she can
handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her parents' precautions, Tori is covered in blisters.
But on the 40 percent of her body where Apligraf has been applied,
almost no new blisters have appeared. Doctors plan to cover about
80 percent of her skin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anna Falabella, an assistant professor of dermatology,
perforates the Apligraf four times with a scalpel before placing it
on the baby. The holes allow the pusfrom Tori's blisters to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Just like real skin, Apligraf can heal itself. Because it is a
living organism, it is packed it a pinkish nutrient for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   It will stay alive only for five days between the laboratory and
the patient, and must be heated to body temperature before it is
applied. Each piece costs $975. Most insurers have paid for the
procedure when used to treat leg ulcers, Eaglstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
