<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-ADCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING AGENCIES STILL HAVE URGE TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo, Ill., Iowa, Ohio, Mass., Pa., Texas, Belgium,
Canada, England)  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mergers and acquisitions on Madison Avenue continue
to be alive and well in the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Any lingering doubts that 1999 would be another year of frenetic
deal-making along Madison Avenue are being dispelled with a spate
of agreements involving agencies specializing in assignments as
disparate as retail advertising, entertainment marketing, employee
communications and direct marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The urge to merge is proving strong enough to stimulate renewed
speculation that some giant agency companies are poised to bid for
competitors. One subject of rumors over the weekend, Cordiant
Communications Group PLC in London, issued a statement Monday
denying reports that it was in negotiations to be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the realm of the real deal, the Integer Group in
Lakewood, Colo., said Monday that it had acquired Stern Advertising
in Cleveland. Terms of the transaction were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has 80 employees in Cleveland and field offices in
Buffalo, N.Y.; Dayton, Ohio; Pittsburgh, and Syracuse, N.Y.,
handling accounts with capitalized billings estimated at $96
million for retailers like Homeplace Stores Inc., McDonald's Corp.
and Sterling Jewelers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Stern will operate autonomously as Stern Advertising, a member
of the Integer Group. William Stern, 52, president of Stern, will
stay in that job. Integer has 581 employees at three units _
Integer Denver, Integer Dallas and Kragie/Newell in Des Moines _
handling accounts with capitalized billings estimated at almost
$400 million for clients like the Blockbuster Entertainment unit of
Viacom Inc., McDonald's and the 7-Eleven unit of the Southland
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of entertainment marketing, five top employees of
Russek Advertising, a New York agency known for work for accounts
like Lincoln Center Theater, the Joyce Theater, the show ``Stomp''
and Columbia Artists Management, are joining Berenter Greenhouse &AMP;
Webster in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts represent about three-quarters of the clients of
Russek, said Jim Russek, president of Russek, which closed on Dec.
31 after grappling with what he described as debts incurred from
unsuccessful theatrical productions. Russek, 52, becomes a vice
president at Berenter Greenhouse, which has billings estimated at
$140 million from clients such as Bed Bath and Beyond, Noodle
Kidoodle and Starbucks Coffee Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's experience could bring a lot to our retail accounts,''
said Bill Berenter, chairman and co-creative director at Berenter
Greenhouse, ``because entertainment plays a large part in the
success of retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   In employee communications, Ketchum in New York, the public
relations agency owned by Omnicom Group, acquired Sheppard
Associates in Glendale, Calif., for undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard, with 85 employees in Glendale and seven other cities
like Boston, Chicago and Houston, will become the foundation for
what Ketchum describes as a new worldwide unit, the Workplace
Communication Practice, which will specialize in tasks like
internal communications, human resources and labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies have been saying for years that employees are
important,'' said David Drobis, senior partner and chief executive
at Ketchum. ``Now they're starting to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fleischer, 45, partner and director of the Ketchum Chicago
office, was named to the additional position of heading the
workplace practice as partner there. Don Sheppard, 52, will remain
chief executive of Sheppard, which has $14 million in income from
clients like Media One and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to direct marketing, Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in Chicago
acquired CM Partners, a direct marketing agency in Rolling Meadows,
Ill., with billings estimated at $100 million from clients like
American Medical Association and Progressive Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Wells, a spokeswoman at Foote, Cone, a unit of True North
Communications, said that CM Partners and its 70 employees would be
integrated into Impact Direct, the agency's marketing-services arm.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Land, 36, president of CM Partners, was named to the new
position of executive vice president and integrated communications
director at Foote, Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Clive MacLean, 39, who had been executive vice president and
managing director at CM Partners, will become an executive vice
president at Foote, Cone, and a co-director of Impact Direct. Scott
Grafft, 47, senior vice president and direct marketing director at
Foote, Cone, is being promoted to executive vice president as he
becomes the other co-director at Impact Direct.
</P>
<P>
   Another agency, Draft Worldwide, a unit of the Interpublic Group
of Cos. that offers direct marketing and integrated-marketing
services, acquired three integrated-marketing shops in Belgium,
Britain and Canada and a data base management company in France.
Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition in Canada, Gingko Group Ltd. of Toronto, marks
Draft's entry into that country.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, turning to the deal that apparently is not, the
statement issued by Cordiant came in response to reports in the
trade publication Adweek and a London newspaper that Cordiant was
in serious discussions to be acquired by True North.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday Telegraph of London reported that True North planned
a cash bid of more than $574 million for Cordiant, which owns
agencies like Bates Worldwide. Adweek reported that the two agency
companies had exchanged financial data.
</P>
<P>
   The Cordiant statement acknowledged ``indications of interest in
the company'' since Cordiant was formed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' the statement continued, ``no discussions are
taking place which may lead to an offer being made for the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Harbour, a spokeswoman in Chicago for True North, which
acquired Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon &AMP; Eckhardt at the end of 1997,
said: ``At this time, there are no discussions going on. There will
be no further comment because it is our policy not to comment on
acquisitions or mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordiant's American depository receipts rose sharply on the New
York Stock Exchange Monday on heavy trading volume, closing at
$11.8125, up $1.625. Shares of True North also rose, up $1.9375, to
$29.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
