<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DENIES APPEAL BY SEX SHOPS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Capping a string of unbroken legal victories for the
administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the U.S. Supreme Court
refused to hear an appeal Monday from sex shop owners and the New
York Civil Liberties Union that a new antipornography zoning law is
an unconstitutional infringement on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the city's success in carrying out the new law remains
checkered, with strip clubs and adult video stores continuing to
find legal loopholes, ranging from admitting minors to selling
enough nonadult products to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Since the city began enforcing the law in July, only 26 of the
61 sex shops that the city had sought to close have been shut down,
while 18 others have closed voluntarily, city officials said.
Scores more have yet to become the targets of the city's
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expected everyone to pack up and go out of business,''
said Herald Price Fahringer, a lawyer representing more than 100
sex shops. ``But they're standing their ground, and they're
succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the sex shops have repeatedly failed in their
effort to block the new zoning law, as shown by Monday's court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called the development proof of the fairness of the new
zoning law, which limits adult establishments to manufacturing
areas and forbids them near schools, churches or other sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the court decision today is terrific,'' he said
Monday. ``It shows that you can have a sense of balance in all of
the ways that we deal with the Constitution, including the free
speech clause.''
</P>
<P>
   But Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, lamented the decision. ``I think it's fair to say
that history will look back at the period and note that it was an
extremely repressive climate.''
</P>
<P>
   With the sex shops largely failing in their effort to defeat the
law, what has taken place instead has been a grinding war of legal
attrition, with the city battling to close each business one by
one, as the sex shops devise ways to skirt the law.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most highly publicized cases involves a Manhattan
strip club that avoids shutdown by allowing minors to enter,
thereby losing its label as an ``adult'' establishment. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Many more sex shops, particularly video stores, are avoiding
the impact of the law by building back rooms for pornographic
products, making the majority of their stock ``nonadult'' and
declaring themselves no longer adult entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains to be seen whether the owners of the sex shops
can outlast the campaign against them by city lawyers. Legal bills
are rising as the owners defend themselves through lengthy court
proceedings, and Fahringer said that profit margins have decreased
as the owners have cut the portion of their businesses devoted to
adult fare.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the two sides are locked in a seesaw battle. Each time
the sex shops appear to find a loophole in the law, the city
appeals to a higher court, and no clear standard has emerged that
would allow strip clubs to remain open.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ten's, a strip club on East 21st Street, was allowed to remain
open because it admitted minors. In a decision that Giuliani
assailed as ``nuts,'' Judge Stephen Crane ruled in November that
the club could remain open because the new law specifies that an
adult establishment is one that does not allow minors to enter.
</P>
<P>
   When a second strip club, the VIP club, on East 20th Street,
tried the same strategy, Crane rejected it. In a Nov. 19 ruling, he
said that because the VIP club had only recently started granting
admission to minors, the exemption did not apply. Ten's, by
contrast, had been allowing minors in for more than a year and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   One week after VIP was padlocked, lawyers for the club presented
new arguments to Crane that persuaded him to reopen it. He has not
issued a written ruling explaining why he allowed the VIP Club to
reopen, but lawyers for sex shops are eagerly awaiting the reason
in the hope that they can emulate it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawyers for the city asked the Appellate Division of
the State Supreme Court to reverse Crane's ruling and throw out the
minors issue entirely. On Monday, Giuliani said the city was
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to win all of them because, like anything
else, judges interpret it differently,'' he said. ``But we've won
the vast majority of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
