<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-ARCH-COX     01-11 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-ARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tyson proves that biting pays
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ He trained in front of the cameras and crowd wearing
nothing but a black T-shirt that proclaimed ``Be Real,'' sockless
black boxing boots and fluorescent lime green bikini underwear.
</P>
<P>
   No trunks. No apologies. And certainly no humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arrogance is an ingredient of greatness,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   This was Mike Tyson's return to Las Vegas and boxing, Monday,
and if you didn't understand where he was coming from, all you had
to do was sit back later in a secluded MGM Grand Garden dressing
room and listen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I lost to Holyfield. I bit his (expletive) ears. He's a
good fighter, but he's not Mike Tyson. He and Lennox Lewis are
going to fight and they can't sell out the Garden. I could sell out
Madison Square Garden, masturbating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I fight on the same night as these guys, they're out of a
job. I'm making $35 million fighting a 10 rounder this weekend. I'm
the champion even when I'm not the champ. I'm the king. Muhammad
Ali set the stage, but there's never been a fighter as big as Mike
Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   You might blanche at his imagery or argue his sense of history.
You can curse his brashness or condemn his petty-hood nastiness and
rap sheet atrocities. But one thing is true.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you consider him a hero or a villain _ whether you
define him as savage knock-out artist, self-tortured soul or
irredeemable thug _ Mike Tyson has an undeniable mystique. It's not
only made him boxing's most lucrative draw, but for one night's
work, he can command more money than any athlete in any sport in
the history of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson will prove that Saturday night at the MGM Grand Garden,
when he returns to the ring for the first time since his banishment
after twice biting Evander Holyfield's ears in their title fight at
this same Las Vegas arena in June of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Though out of the game 19 months, Tyson is guaranteed $33
million for his 10-round bout with Frans Botha, the South African
born plodder who has lost once in 40 fights.
</P>
<P>
   In the six previous fights he's had since being released from an
Indiana prison where he served three years for rape, Tyson has been
paid close to $140 million. That last fight against Holyfield broke
all pay-per-view records when it was bought by 1.8 million
households and brought in over $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday night, plenty people will tune in again even though
Botha shouldn't last more than a few rounds. But with Tyson these
days, who knows what he has left or what he might do? And that's
the allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still incredibly exciting and you never know what's going
to happen,'' said veteran promoter Don Elbaum. ``When you watch
Tyson, you're seeing an animal. That's something you're not going
to get with a Roy Jones or Lennox Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Larkin, the executive producer of Showtime Championship
Boxing, recently said: ``Boxing fans traditionally care about more
than the fight. They care about the conflict behind the conflict.
And in terms of drama, few can compare to Tyson. Tyson the story
has eclipsed Tyson the boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true, not only because the fistic side of Tyson has
diminished dramatically _ the last world class fighter he has
beaten was Razor Ruddock almost eight years ago _ but because the
myth of Tyson gets more incredible as each day goes by.
</P>
<P>
   He's gone from juvenile delinquent to slaughterhouse superstar,
from troubled husband to convicted rapist, from rehabilitated
headliner to crazed ear biter. This is his last shot at redemption
and yet as he's prepares for Botha, one irony stands out.
</P>
<P>
   As reprehensible as it was, his ear-biting disqualification may
have helped his boxing career. Sure there was a 15-month ban
administered by the Nevada Athletic Commission, the whopping $3
million fine and the pillorying from every corner of the globe, but
his image of dark destroyer stayed in tact. In fact, it was
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   And were it not for the biting, he almost certainly would have
been beaten by Holyfield for the second time in seven months. With
that tarnish, Tyson would no longer be able to command $33 million
paydays.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the cannibalism fed the jumbled mystery that surrounds
the 32-year-old ex champ. And so Monday. the freak show began in
earnest once more.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a palpable sense of menace when Tyson enters the
room, but there's a noticeable difference to his entourage. He's
gotten rid of bombastic promoter Don King _ whom he is suing for
$100 million _ and has bounced former co-managers John Horne and
Rory Holloway, both of whom he also accuses of skimming his funds
and helping cause him to end up with a $13 million IRS bill.
Trainer Richie Giachetti has been replaced too, by Tommy Brooks,
who co-trained Evander Holyfield before this.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson looked fit, almost small during Monday's workout.
Afterward, came a free-wheeling, often bizarre session that
reminded you, as one backer has said, of the stream of conscience
rants of Robin Williams _ without the humor.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he said he might fight four more times and quit the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks he could really give up the one thing he's
been so successful at, he shrugged: ``Look, I'm not even supposed
to be here now. I'm supposed to be finished. I've been in prison.
Thorazined (sic), or what's that stuff they gave me? Lithium. Most
guys I fought are fighting crack problems or are in oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me I been on the bottom, hit the top, fell again and now am
coming back up. The difference with me is that I know how to get
back again. I was really screwed up before... and that was just a
couple of days ago. But now, now I'm the king.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, five days before his return to the ring and two days
past crazy, one thing was certain. Mike Tyson wore his arrogance
like his lime-green underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
