<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TREASURIES ARE IN THE DOLDRUMS 
(ATTN: N.J.)
</HEADLINE>
  ( ms ) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Treasury market, an unexpectedly fine performer last year,
is not looking so attractive right now. And it may take another
rush of panic about the world's economy and global financial
stability to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   Despite low _ and possibly declining _ inflation and the
forecast by many economists that the American economy is slowing
down, Treasury interest rates, from short-term notes to long-term
bonds, have shot sharply higher the last month. The yield on the
30-year bond is now 5.30 percent, well above the 4.96 percent of
just a month ago. In trading Monday, the yield rose as high as 5.36
percent before prices, which move in the opposite direction,
rallied to wipe out most of the day's losses.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the fact that Brazil has yet to complete its fiscal
reform program, that Latin America faces a severe economic slowdown
and there is no concrete sign that Japan has been able to turn its
economy around, Treasury yields could go higher.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's wrong? A lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the U.S. economy is not showing any signs of slowing
down, a fact made clear by the November and December jobs reports,
both of which were surprisingly strong. The November numbers were
reported on Dec. 4, just days before the bond rally peaked and the
30-year bond yield hit 4.96 percent. And December's 378,000 job
increase, announced on Friday, was even more surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs on Friday raised its growth forecast for the
fourth quarter to 4.2 percent from 3.5 percent, left the first
quarter at 2.7 percent but lifted the second quarter to 2.2 percent
from 1.9 percent. Upward revisions in growth don't help bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in the stock market to new highs is also likely to
keep consumer spending stronger in the months ahead, which should
help keep growth robust, though other crucial sectors, like capital
spending, are slowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This long-awaited slowdown just doesn't come,'' said Ward
McCarthy, managing director of Stone &AMP; McCarthy Research Associates
in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He also said ``the bond market has just had a tough time
competing with this stock market for attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the perception that the threat of a full-blown
world financial crisis has eased. And this, in turn, has reversed
the rush to the bond market for safety, known on Wall Street as a
flight to quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to think you should have a flight to quality with
the stock market at new highs,'' said Lewis Crandall, chief
economist at R.H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, which has cut its interest rate target
three times since the end of September, and European central banks,
which made one rate cut at the end of last year, were major
contributors to this change in psychology. Rallies in emerging
stock and bond markets have also helped, though by any reasonable
measure the world economy still faces a lot of uncertainties, with
Brazil No. 1 on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed easing and the stronger-than-expected U.S. economy lead
to another problem for bonds. ``It is not likely that the Fed is
going to ease anytime soon,'' said Robert J. Barbera, chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. in Rye Brook, N.Y. So that hope for
bonds, which sparked the big fall rally in the first place, is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's weakness, especially against the Japanese yen, and
a move by some investors into the euro, the new European currency,
have also contributed to bond market weakness, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   What is not happening, both Barbera and Crandall argue, is an
inflation scare. ``It is not that inflation is going to come
back,'' Barbera said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald A. Guild, senior vice president for the taxable
fixed-income division of Advest Inc., disagrees a little. ``We have
a classic inflation scare rasing its head again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the same breath, he argues that there should be no such
fear because ``companies cannot pass on price increases.'' But
although he thinks inflation concerns are unfounded, he said the
psychology had ``dynamically changed'' in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean for bonds? Guild thinks that because the
inflation scare is phony, the bond selloff should be near its end.
He said he would be surprised if the yield on the 30-year bond
exceeded 5.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall said that right now ``bonds are not perceived to have
as much upside'' as analysts thought just a month ago. This means
selling could push yields higher.
</P>
<P>
   But he is counting on two factors to turn the tide. One is that
the economy will slow, though maybe not as soon as he thought. The
other is that investors will have new reasons to worry about the
stability of world financial markets again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to have events in the first half of 1999 that
will give Treasuries a flight-to-quality boost,'' he said. ``Global
financial markets are going to remain accident prone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
