<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMPBELL SOUP WARNS OF LOWER EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Blaming the weather for sluggish sales of its biggest brand,
Campbell Soup warned that its earnings in the current quarter and
fiscal year would be off by 18 to 23 cents a share, significantly
lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, the company said its sales
of condensed soup, those familiar red-and-white cans that make up
two-thirds of Campbell's sales and earnings, had been depressed by
warm weather in November and December and would not meaningfully
improve before its second quarter ends on Jan. 31. Dale Morrison,
Campbell's chief executive, said soup sales would grow by only 1
percent to 2 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT IN DEAL FOR KENAN SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said it would buy Kenan Systems, a leader in
billing software, but declined to talk about the far bigger deal on
Wall Street's mind, a possible acquisition of Ascend
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   SEC FINES 28 WALL STREET FIRMS
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission fined 28 Wall Street
firms more than $26 million and suspended 51 traders for reputed
abuses on the Nasdaq stock market, ending an investigation that
began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   KEATING TO GO ON TRIAL AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Charles Keating Jr., the former savings and loan executive, will
be tried again on charges that he defrauded customers by selling
them millions of dollars in worthless bonds.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA RISKS WRATH OF BANKERS
</P>
<P>
   China's relations with the banking world may go into a deep
freeze after its decision not to bail out foreign creditors of a
debt-ridden provincial investment company.
</P>
<P>
   BERGEN BRUNSWIG IN EXPANSION
</P>
<P>
   Bergen Brunswig, a supplier of pharmaceutical and other health
products, said it was entering the long-term health care business
by buying Pharmerica for $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BOND MARKET LOSES ATTRACTION
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury market, an unexpectedly fine performer last year,
is not looking so attractive right now. And it may take another
rush of panic about the world's economy to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AS NASDAQ RISES
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed with many issues pulling back after the rally
to records last week raised concern among investors that the market
is getting too expensive. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
23.43 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 9,619.89. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 11.21 points, or nine-tenths of a
percent, to 1,263.88. Nasdaq reached a seventh consecutive record,
climbing 40.18 points, or 1.7 percent, to 2,384.59.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Internet companies surged, led by Broadcast.com, which
rose 44.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
