<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      01-11 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-TOBACCO HERO RETHINKS A 2000 RACE 
PLAYING A POLITICAL NAME GAME 
THE HIGH PRICE OF THE PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ill.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the first state attorney general to win a health-costs
settlement from the nation's tobacco companies _ it was worth a
whopping $4 billion _ Michael Moore is a hero to many
Mississippians and something of a legal icon in the anti-tobacco
movement.
</P>
<P>
   So when Moore announced in October that he would try to parlay
his popularity into higher office by running for governor in 1999,
political handicappers made him the favorite to succeed the current
governor, Kirk Fordice, who cannot seek a third term under state
law.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore, a Democrat, has had second thoughts. He says now he
will not run for governor but will instead go after a fourth term
as attorney general so he can ``finish some of the work that we've
started,'' not the least of which will be wrapping up the details
of how the state will spend its tobacco money windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that my heart is not in that
race,'' Moore confessed in pulling out of the governor's contest
last week. ``I feel like a ton of bricks has been lifted off my
back. Being attorney general is a job that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Close students of Mississippi politics say Moore's change of
mind may have been as pragmatic as heartfelt. They note that
Mississippi is known as a ``weak governor state,'' one whose laws
and organizational chart give top legislative leaders, the
lieutenant governor and, yes, the attorney general almost as much
clout as the governor.
</P>
<P>
   So with Moore no longer interested, Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove is
left as the only big-name contender for the Democratic nomination
at this point.
</P>
<P>
   What's in a Name? Ask Moseley-Braun
</P>
<P>
   In politics, name recognition can often be, well, the name of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years in Chicago, for example, more than a few
candidates for alderman have adopted an ethnic middle name or a
catchy nickname in hopes of snaring a few extra votes. Thus, in
that city's ward elections next month, voters will find such middle
monikers on their ballots as Pookie, Junebug, Cosmos, Gator, Curly
and Butch.
</P>
<P>
   They may also find the name Carol Moseley-Braun.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Carol Moseley-Braun, the former Lauryn Kaye
Valentine _ no relation to Carol Moseley-Braun, the former U.S.
senator from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The former Ms. Valentine (henceforth, Ms. Moseley-Braun II) went
to court in September and asked permission to change her name to
Carol Moseley-Braun, telling the judge that the senator
(henceforth, Ms. Moseley-Braun I) was one of her heroes. The judge
required that Ms. Moseley-Braun II send word of the change to Ms.
Moseley-Braun I, who was then mired in a losing re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun II, a 21-year-old market researcher, sent a
letter to Ms. Moseley-Braun I that concluded: ``I'm not trying to
be you and I would never dishonor your name in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun I sent back word that there were probably
better ways to honor someone than a name change. Nevertheless, she
said, she was honored.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-December, Ms. Moseley-Braun II filed to run for alderman
in the 37th Ward, challenging the veteran incumbent, Percy Giles.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun I cried ``identity theft'' and ``fraud.'' She
has since asked her lawyers to look into the possibility of
obtaining a court order to rescind the name change.
</P>
<P>
   Giles, asserting that ``someone is trying to trick voters'' with
``a name that outpowers mine,'' also put his lawyers to work. They
are trying to have Ms. Moseley-Braun II disqualified on the ground
that when she filed to run _ they say she started gathering the
required petition signatures within a month of her name change _
she was not re-registered to vote under her new name.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moseley-Braun II says she is ``incensed'' at the accusations
leveled by Ms. Moseley-Braun I and Giles.
</P>
<P>
   Next step: A hearing on Friday by the Chicago Board of Elections
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Presidency in 2000: $2,893 an Hour
</P>
<P>
   The cost of running for president spirals ever higher. With the
primary and caucus season more front-loaded now than ever,
candidates with any hope of being contenders must not only be able
to raise staggering amounts of money but must also be able to raise
it in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional political wisdom holds that in the 2000 election,
any candidate who on Jan. 1, the beginning of the primary and
caucus season, does not have $25 million in hand, may well be out
of the running.
</P>
<P>
   What does raising $25 million involve, keeping in mind that the
main source of money for most candidates early on is gifts from
individuals and that federal law limits each gift to $1,000?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the way The Hotline, a widely distributed political tip
service, calculated it on Jan. 5, with 360 days to go, give or take
a few ticks of the clock:
</P>
<P>
   ``If to run for president in 2000 will take raising $25 million
in 1999 from at least 25,000 different people giving up to $1,000
each, that's $69,444 every day for the rest of the year, every
Saturday and every Sunday included _ $2,893 an hour, 24 hours of
every single day. Just by taking the time to read this, you have
fallen another $34.73 behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
