<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NORTH-KOREA-NYT &LR;      01-11 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NORTH-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRAYED DEAL WITH NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 12: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new and potentially volatile crisis is brewing between the
United States and North Korea. Pyongyang's reckless behavior
threatens to unravel a 1994 nuclear agreement with Washington. That
would effectively end diplomatic dialogue between the two countries
and could lead to heightened military tensions on the Korean
Peninsula. Late last year the Clinton administration appointed
William Perry, the former defense secretary, to review American
policy toward the North. He is now trying to learn more about what
Pyongyang is up to and to see if the growing tensions can be
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot succeed if North Korea continues new construction
that would break its pledge to freeze nuclear weapons development
or if it alarms its neighbors with further missile tests. At best,
North Korea's actions are an attempt to extort new money and
concessions from the West. At worst they signal an intention to
break the nuclear agreement or even to threaten South Korea and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 agreement committed North Korea to freeze nuclear
programs that were producing bomb-grade materials. In return, a
group of Western countries led by the United States agreed to build
new civilian power reactors for the North and supply it with
imported fuel oil. Until now, both sides have formally complied
with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, American intelligence agencies spotted the
apparent beginnings of a new underground North Korean nuclear
complex. Pyongyang refuses to let Americans inspect this site
unless Washington makes large additional payments. Then last
August, North Korea launched a three-stage rocket over Japan. There
are signs that it may be readying another test. The missiles do not
violate the nuclear agreement, but they may drive Japan to stop
financing the nuclear deal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if North Korea is only advertising its rocket and missile
prowess to get the West to pay for freezing these programs as well,
it is a troubling development. Paying for a missile freeze might
lead to further demands as North Korea looks for ways to keep its
bankrupt dictatorship afloat.
</P>
<P>
   America should help North Korea deal with its devastating famine
and should offer support if the North begins to move away from its
disastrous command economy. But Perry must make clear to Pyongyang
that there are limits to American generosity and that Washington
expects the 1994 nuclear agreement to be honored in full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990111.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      01-11 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LET CLINTON SPEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 12:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, understandably eager to change the subject,
wants to deliver his State of the Union address on schedule next
week. Senators who have sworn an oath to do ``impartial justice''
will no doubt feel awkward listening to Clinton proclaim his
achievements as if they were not sitting as jurors in his
impeachment trial. House Republicans may feel the same way. As a
result, many lawmakers are suggesting that Clinton put off the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the comfort level of the lawmakers should not be the
determining factor. The State of the Union address is too important
a part of the governmental calendar to put on hold indefinitely.
The fact that he has been impeached has not stripped Clinton of the
right to speak at a time of his choosing, even if his primary goal
is to strengthen his own hand. If he wants, at long last, to
address more fully his lies under oath and other misdeeds, so much
the better. If, on the other hand, he has nothing useful to add
about his signal failure to protect the rule of law, the public has
a right to know that too.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the Constitution requires any president to deliver a
State of the Union message at this time of year, or in person. But
Americans have come to expect a speech in January laying out a
president's priorities, and Clinton's appearances before a Congress
controlled by the opposition since 1995 have been among his most
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Congress can escape the political shadow of
the impeachment process. No doubt many in Congress are sincere in
wanting to finish that process before the State of the Union
address. Since it seems unlikely Clinton will be thrown out of
office, there is something to be said for waiting until the end of
the trial. Then the speech could be given as a kind of final
catharsis, calling for a return to work on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   But impeachment itself is inherently political. It feels
artificial to deprive Clinton of the opportunity to rally his
support and claim credit for the nation's extraordinary prosperity
at this critical moment. Just as the House has the right to put out
its best evidence, Clinton has a right to demonstrate that the
public does not want him removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of political calculation, the president, for his own
reasons, may decide to wait a few days and speak to Congress just
after the House impeachment managers and the White House defense
team have finished laying out their case in opening presentations.
That would be all right, too. A speech of confession just before
the Senate decides on whether to proceed to a full-blown trial,
with witnesses and cross-examination, might well tilt the balance
toward censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cannot ignore the Senate trial. Neither can Congress put
all national business on hold while it focuses on finding the
appropriate punishment for his behavior. The best course is for the
legislators to accept graciously the larger rhythm of democracy,
listen to the State of the Union and demonstrate to Americans that
pressing foreign and domestic issues of the day are still getting
some thought and attention. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
