<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-EXCL-BKN-JORDAN-RET     01-11 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EXCL-BKN-JORDAN-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN WILL RETIRE, 3 OFFICIALS WITH NBA SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (EXCLUSIVE: 12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story is also being
transmitted with an n ``s'' category code.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, basketball's pre-eminent player and the world's
best known athlete, will retire from the National Basketball
Association for the second time in five years, according to three
officials in the NBA with knowledge of Jordan's plans. They said
Monday night that they expected Jordan to make an announcement this
week, possibly as early as Wednesday, at a news conference in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's future has been the biggest issue in basketball in the
wake of the bitter labor dispute that ended last week after an
impasse that lasted six months and wiped out the early part of the
season. Aside from his athletic and entertainment value to the
league, he was viewed as &UR;  &LR; a cultural icon and ambassador for the
sport who would help bridge the gap to disenchanted fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls' star has not made a public statement
regarding his plans since the lockout ended, and his agent, David
Falk, declined Monday night to comment on the possibility of
Jordan's retirement. But the three officials said the decision had
been made.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, more and more signs had pointed to the game's most
prominent star re-retiring at the age of 35. Falk had not held any
contract discussions with the Bulls, and Jordan had not been
working out regularly. In addition, an editor of a new book by
Jordan, ``For the Love of the Game: My Own Story,'' acknowledged
that the publisher was counting on Jordan's retirement when it
decided to publish the book last fall, and had received positive
signals from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   His failure to announce a decision publicly put things on hold
for the Bulls, who won six league titles with Jordan as their
leader and top performer. While the franchise awaited his decision
on whether or not to re-sign, his free-agent teammates were in
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   His decision would give the go-ahead for Bulls Chairman Jerry
Reinsdorf and General Manager Jerry Krause to rebuild and give his
teammates a chance to sign with other teams, should the Bulls not
re-sign them. The Bulls currently have only four players under
contract. Among the players whose futures are hinging on Jordan's
decision are all-star forward Scottie Pippen, whom Jordan has
called his ``little brother,'' and the league's leading rebounder,
Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's teammates acknowledged that the star has not been
consistently working out and getting in prime physical shape for a
shortened season _ a requisite for Jordan every year during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been preparing, that's the biggest reason I think
he's not coming back,'' said Steve Kerr, a Bulls guard. ``Michael
hasn't told me anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was on vacation last week in the Bahamas, and it was
unclear whether he had returned home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 objective we have here as a franchise is to bring
Michael Jordan back, to bring the championship team back,'' Krause
said Monday. ``When Michael lets us know what he's going to do,
certainly, if he comes back, we intend to make a very concerted and
very serious effort to bring the rest of the championship team
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's history of changing direction in his professional life
left open the possibility that he may return _ if not this season,
than possibly the following year. He last retired in 1994. But he
ended a floundering career as a baseball player _ he never advanced
past the minor leagues _ in the spring of 1995 to return to the
game in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan would be leaving the game on the highest note possible.
The five-time most valuable player led the Bulls to their third
championship in three seasons last June 16, carrying Chicago to its
sixth title in eight seasons with a dramatic 40-second sequence in
the clinching Game 6 victory over the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   He hit the game-winning shot with 5.3 seconds left, an 18-foot
jump shot that left a stunned gathering at the Delta Center in Salt
Lake City paralyzed. It was the final blow as the Bulls beat the
Jazz for the second season in a row in six games to the win the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's retirement would be the linchpin decision in the
disassembling of the Bulls, basketball's modern-day dynasty whose
six titles in eight seasons drew comparisons to the Bill
Russell-led Boston Celtics of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The first departure was the coach, Phil Jackson, who left the
franchise after the Bulls won the title in June, saying he would
take an extended sabbatical from the game before returning. Krause
hired former Iowa State coach Tim Floyd to replace Jackson under
the stipulation that if Jackson wanted to return, Floyd would
become an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had said all last season he would not play for another
coach, but seemed to be backing off that stance in the off season.
Falk said last week if the situation were right _ meaning that
Pippen, Rodman and most of the supporting cast were re-signed _
Jordan would consider playing again.
</P>
<P>
   But with the league recovering from the most damaging period in
its 52-year history _ a six-month labor dispute that cost players
and owners hundreds of millions of dollars and turned once-loyal
fans apathetic _ the thinking is that perhaps Jordan did not want
to be associated with a tainted image of the NBA. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
