<HEADLINE>
DODGERS KNOW EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park, meet Kevin Brown. Devon White, say
hello to Mark Grudzielanek. Todd Hundley, this is Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Devon. Over there is Gary Sheffield. Ummmm, wait . . . you
already know each other, right? Not from the Los Angeles Dodgers
but with the Florida Marlins. Before they were a minor-league
club.Right?
</P>
<P>
   That's what the well-attended first day of winter workouts were
like at Dodger Stadium on Monday. It was the first day of school
with a bunch of new transfer students and a new teacher. And the
principal is new, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around and saw these players, and that's something,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I was ready to start playing
some ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary winter workouts are an annual prelude to spring
training in Dodgerland, but this was different than others. Star
power was prevalent and even most of those who didn't attend had
reasons that general manager Kevin Malone found acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything is different about the Dodgers. Much of the
roster, the manager, the general manager. And, most importantly,
the expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Much like a month ago when the Dodgers and Brown agreed to a
seven-year, $105 million contract, the talk was mostly about the
World Series. And how the Dodgers are stocked to make a run at
their first title in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been around so many young veterans in my life,''
Hundley said. ``Half the team is in the prime of their careers and
the other half is coming into the prime of their careers. That's
why back on Memorial Day I went back to the Mets and had a limited
no-trade clause put in my contract, so that this type of situation
would come up and I wouldn't end up somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, the former Mets catcher who was, in essence, traded for
Mike Piazza, talked about handling a starting rotation of Brown,
Park, Darren Dreifort, Carlos Perez and Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   There's the anticipation of an outfield comprised of Sheffield
in left, White in center and Raul Mondesi in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers certainly showed they want to win, and I like
that,'' said Brown, who's played in the World Series with the
Marlins and Padres the last two seasons. ``You know most of these
guys, but this is just a time to meet a few people and shake their
hands. I saw (Sheffield) and (White), guys I played with in
Florida, and there's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in attitude, which brings an aura of arrogance to the
Dodgers, was orchestrated by the megabucks the Fox Media Corp.
shelled out. But enveloping the whole situation is Johnson's
reputation, which says the days of a blase, lackadaisical,
noncompetitive atmosphere have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been here there's been a lot of patience, and
that's good and that's bad,'' Karros said. ``There's some
stability. I like our chances going into this season as far as
being in this organization. This is probably as excited as I've
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those not at Dodger Stadium were Mondesi, third baseman
Adrian Beltre, Perez, catcher Angel Pena and pitcher Mel Rojas.
Malone said Rojas is working out in the Dominican Republic and the
others are playing in the Dominican Republic. All of which is
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are playing, so it makes no sense for them to quit
playing and come up here,'' Malone said. ``Beltre's got a chance to
be the MVP of the league, so it's better they keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The exuberance was bursting, yet it will fade away when most of
the prominent players return to other warm-weather retreats and
private training sessions at week's end and await the start of
spring training. But with overwhelming anticipation for a season
that will hold many expectations, it was enough to wet the baseball
appetite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 38 days away from pitchers and catcher reporting, so
it's kind of a springboard for getting into the '99 year,'' Malone
said. ``I just can't wait, and I think you see a lot of that on
this team with how many big-league guys showed up
here.'' &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
