<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-DEFENDANTS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA BARGAINS FOR THREE GOTTI CO-DEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a surprise move, federal prosecutors Monday
reached plea &UR; - &LR;  bargain deals with three co-defendants of John A.
Gotti, the reputed acting boss of the Gambino crime family, in a
broad racketeering case.
</P>
<P>
   The deals were made after the government reversed its own trial
strategy, in which it vowed to accept individual pleas in return
for reduced sentences only if Gotti, the top target in a three-year
mafia investigation, also admitted his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Plea negotiations for Gotti and seven other defendants in the
case seemed to break down two weeks ago when Gotti rejected a deal
that could have sent him to prison for up to eight years. At that
time, defense lawyers said that federal prosecutors were demanding
a global settlement in which all eight defendants facing trial on
organized-crime charges would have to plead guilty. Otherwise, the
lawyers said, no separate plea bargains would be accepted by
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But James J. DiPietro, a lawyer on the defense team, said that
prosecutors made new offers late last week and the three defendants
accepted the terms Monday morning at hearings in federal District
Court in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Two other defendants are expected to plead guilty Tuesday in
White Plains, whittling down Gotti's remaining co-defendants on
organized-crime charges to two when he goes on trial later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, 34, who is sometimes called Junior, is the son of John J.
Gotti, 58, who law enforcement officials say is the Gambino family
boss and still influences the Mafia faction while serving a life
term in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cutler, the younger Gotti's lawyer, said that Monday's
pleas might benefit his client at a trial scheduled for later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly doesn't hurt him,'' Cutler said. ``If anything,
it might help him by avoiding confusion among jurors over the
charges and the number of defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers in the case said that in reversing course and
agreeing to individual pleas, the government demanded longer prison
sentences than previously offered each defendant for a global
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   At hearings Monday, John J. D'Amico, 64, pleaded guilty to a
single count of illegal gambling, and Louis Ricco, 68, to one count
of loan sharking. Both men have been identified by prosecutors as
Gambino capos, or heads of crews.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, according to the FBI, was appointed by the elder Gotti
to a three-man committee that helped run the Gambino family after
he was sentenced in 1992 to life in prison without the possibility
of parole.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico faces a prison sentence of one year and nine months to
two years and three months. Ricco, faces a minimum sentence of
three years and 10 months and a fine of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Antonicelli, 67, who prosecutors said was a Gambino
soldier, pleaded guilty Monday to a loan-sharking charge. His
minimum sentence, according to the deal, will be three years and
five months in prison and a fine of $26,000.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants who agreed to plea deals did obtain some
concessions. They will not be required to testify against Gotti or
have to admit to being members of the Gambino family.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Organized-crime investigators, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that prosecutors reversed themselves on holding out
for a global settlement for two main reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas, they said, assured prison terms and convictions of
two senior Gambino family capos and will allow prosecutors to focus
on the principal accusations against Gotti _ that he was part of
the extortion of about $1 million from the former owners and
employees of Scores, a Manhattan strip club.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and lawyers say that the prosecution plans to call
two former associates, or workers, in the Gambino family as
witnesses against Gotti on the Scores extortion accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, however, insisted that the deals reflected the
weakness of the government's overall case and that prosecutors were
willing to accept pleas to reduced charges from Gotti's
co-defendants rather than risk acquittals in a mass trial on the
more serious racketeering counts against them.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for Mary Jo White, the U.S. Attorney
for the Southern District of New York, whose office is prosecuting
Gotti, declined to comment Monday on the reasons for the plea deals
and the strategy shift.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that two other co-defendants,
Gregory DePalma, 66, who was identified as an acting Gambino capo,
and his son Craig, 32, a suspected Gambino soldier, had agreed to
plead guilty Tuesday to reduced racketeering charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
