<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGAY-NAVAJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADER OF NAVAJOS TRIUMPHED OVER `DARK WATERS' OF ALCOHOLISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BETTY REID AND BILL DONOVAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1975, Kelsey Begay was drowning in ``dark waters'' _ the
Navajo phrase for being swamped in the evils of alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from the jungles of Vietnam, the former soldier was living
on the streets of Los Angeles, a world away from his home in this
remote community on the Navajo Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Navajos, he'd fallen prey to the lure of alcohol. And
like many American soldiers, he used it to help him cope with
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to be crazy to go out into the jungle sober,'' Begay
said.
</P>
<P>
   With each drink, during the war and after, memories of Kaibito,
Ariz., slipped away. But Begay's destiny was not to end in the
alleys beneath the looming skyscrapers of urban America.
</P>
<P>
   Today, (TUESDAY) sober for more than two decades, Begay, 48,
will be sworn in as president of the Navajo Nation, becoming
caretaker of the largest tribe in America.
</P>
<P>
   After escaping from the trap of alcohol and drugs himself, Begay
gave others hope by counseling them about the dangers of addiction.
Now, he intends to give tribal members hope through a style of
leadership that emphasizes family values.
</P>
<P>
   Educated in public and federal reservation schools, Begay
aspired to be an evangelist, not a politician. Friends say one of
his favorite hobbies is strumming an electric guitar and belting
out songs ranging from Christian and blues to country music.
</P>
<P>
   To some, his personality doesn't seem very presidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people out there still don't believe I am president,''
said Begay, former speaker of the Navajo council.
</P>
<P>
   But Begay says he intends to draw on his background growing up
here to do an effective job.
</P>
<P>
   Kaibito, named after the willows that once flourished in a giant
wash, gave Begay the comforts of family and the beauty of nature,
minus basics like running water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs were rare. Kaibito was no different than other Navajo
communities whose youngsters must migrate to nearby bordertowns or
larger cities to find work.
</P>
<P>
   For Kaibito residents, that usually meant Page, Flagstaff,
Phoenix or Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Kaibito had in common with larger places was the
problem of alcohol. Alcohol had taken a toll, not on just the
Kaibito community, but the tribe in general. Alcohol ranks as the
number one cause of death on the Navajo reservation, according to
Navajo Area Indian Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   Page, which is nestled on an upsweep of sandstone just east of
the Glen Canyon Dam, also has had a history of scrimmages with
inebriated tribal members.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Begay turned his life around and started helping
others do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Grayeyes, residential director of Rainbow Bridge
Residential Treatment Center in Page, has heard Begay describe his
ordeal with alcohol. Grayeyes is director of what once was called
the Local Alcohol Reception Center, which Begay previously headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess after he came out of the Army, Kelsey returned here,
and was a frequent visitor to the water holes in Page,'' Grayeyes
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ended up at LARC, and through that connection, he was
counseled by an individual who changed his life. Begay became a
counselor himself.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1976. Begay sobered up with the help of the 12-step
program and found God in a Pentecostal Church. But he said his
Christian faith does not erase who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Navajo first, Christian second.''
</P>
<P>
   And, following Navajo tradition, he identifies himself through
his maternal clan _ ``todichiinii,'' or ``bitter water''_ and his
paternal clan, ``tabaha,'' ``edgewater.''
</P>
<P>
   James Bilagody, a Tuba City leader who is Begay's friend, met
the tribal leader in the 1980s when Begay was head of the western
portion of the tribe's behavorial-health services.
</P>
<P>
   Bilagody, now on the Navajo council, believes that Begay relates
well with tribal members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Kelsey) is very dependable,'' Biligody said. ``He has
an administrative experience background. He is in tune with the
everyday problems of Navajo people - meaning a lot of
inconsistencies that are part of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Begay says there are several issues he intends to deal with as
president.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of his victory, Begay told supporters he would
investigate the tribe's scholarship program because many people
complained about it while he was campaigning. He also encourages
more Navajo youth to join tribal government.
</P>
<P>
   If Begay is to be successful, some Navajos say, he will do on
the strength of character rather than charisma. He's not known for
displaying the presence or passion of gifted English and Navajo
orators such as past tribal leaders Peter MacDonald and Albert
Hale.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, said former tribal president Peterson Zah. Zah said
the voters were not seeking charisma so much as a stable, older and
committed leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not the flashy, shoot-from-the-hip type person,'' Zah
said. ``He is very deliberate and thinks about what he is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanda MacDonald, wife of Peter MacDonald, said Begay is
dependable and believes in family values. Peter MacDonald is the
former tribal president serving a prison term for inciting a riot
at Window Rock following his removal from office for conspiracy and
taking bribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Begay was more of a work horse than a race horse,`` she said.
``A race horse may look good but it is the work horse that will
accomplish the most.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kaibito, the people say Begay is compassionate and generous.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Kathleen Bennett, 52,a foster mother who lives in
a tiny ramshackle house in Kaibito. Though the three-room home has
electricity and running water, it's not large enough to accommodate
Bennett and the nine youngsters, including grandchildren, who live
with her.
</P>
<P>
   She says Begay helped one of her daughters to get a college
scholarship and in the late 1980s, when he was Kaibito chapter
president, he tried to get public assistance for her.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she contacted attorneys but was told that
emergency housing funds had run out. Her hope is that now that a
Kaibito man is president, some help will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like Begay to think of his people out here,'' Bennett
said. ``Too many people, once they become politicians, they move
east past White Mesa, past Black Mesa, dash to Window Rock and
forget their community.''
</P>
<P>
   In late December, two weeks before the inaugural ceremonies,
three Navajo ladies selling frybread, coffee and hamburger from the
back of their pickup across from the Kaibito supermarket also
expressed hope that Begay's presidency would bring good things to
their community.
</P>
<P>
   They stood, chattering about politics, as Navajo Mountain
shimmered in the background against spacious blue skies. Warmth
wafted from a steak grill.
</P>
<P>
   Etta Jackson, 33, worried that Begay might fall victim to brutal
politics in Window Rock, a five hour drive away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope people don't buck him,'' Jackson said. ``I hope people
treat him well in Window Rock. We worry about Kelsey and we say a
lot of prayers for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Reid can be reached at 271-8885 or at
betty.reid(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
