<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMERS SING HOUSING LAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some of the new Dodgers are learning about the
health of the Los Angeles real estate market, and it has taken them
by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the recent high-priced acquisitions arranged their
trip to Monday's opening day of winter workouts at Dodger Stadium
to coincide with afternoon meetings with real estate agents. But
it's such a sellers' market some of the players are having trouble
finding a viable living location.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found lots of houses I like, I'm just not sure,'' said
pitcher Kevin Brown, owner of a seven-year, $105 million contract.
``I'm a little sticker-shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not much better for center fielder Devon White, who signed
a three-year free-agent contract worth $12.4 million but can't find
a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to find a place to stay within my budget,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Contract talks: Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone is
hoping to speak with pitcher Chan Ho Park about a contract
extension within the next week. Park, who was 15-9 with a 3.71 ERA
last season, is in the last year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started here and I feel very comfortable with the Dodgers,
and even living in Los Angeles, it's like my second hometown, so
it's something I'd like to do,'' Park said. ``When I come here I
feel like I'm coming home. If it's a pretty good deal, I wouldn't
have to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who returned from Korea over the weekend, said he hasn't
thought about contract terms he's seeking.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hansen returns: The Dodgers announced Monday that infielder
Dave Hansen signed a one-year contract. He'll most likely be used
in a utility/pinch-hitter role.
</P>
<P>
   It's Hansen's second stint with the Dodgers. He was a
second-round pick by the Dodgers in the 1986 draft and hit .259
with 12 homers and 83 RBI in seven years with the team. The
30-year-old Hansen, who graduated from Rowland High in Walnut,
played for the Cubs in 1997 before spending 1998 in Japan with the
Hanshin Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Brown endowment: Brown announced he will give a $1 million
endowment to the Los Angeles chapter of the Reviving Baseball in
Innercities (RBI) program to establish the Kevin Brown RBI Academy
of Excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The academy will combine baseball instruction and academics,
which will help kids with SAT prep classes, time-management
seminars, human-development courses, retreats, college tours and
college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them the opportunity to get some instruction but also
a chance to prove themselves academically,'' Brown said. ``It's a
chance for the youth of the inner cities to be involved in
baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
