<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      01-11 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: A Compromise Is Proposed
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Northern Ireland secretary proposed a compromise on
the crucial issue of the disarmament of the Irish Republican Army.
The secretary, Mo Mowlam, agreed in effect with the position held
by Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, that the language of
the Belfast peace agreement did not require the IRA to disarm
before May 2000. But Ms. Mowlam said she hoped the IRA would make
some gesture toward disarmament sooner than that.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Warning to Separatists
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar warned Basque separatists that
there was ``absolutely no acceptable level of violence,'' as
concerns grew about recent firebombings in the northern Basque
region, despite a cease-fire observed since September by the Basque
guerrilla group ETA. The government said the rebels sent a fresh
round of extortion letters to businesses threatening attack if they
did not make substantial payments.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Police to Be Reinforced
</P>
<P>
   ROME _ Responding to a crime wave in Milan, where nine people
were killed in the past 10 days, the Italian government announced
that it was sending 800 more police officers to help combat a rise
in organized crime among gangs of illegal aliens from Albania and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan: President Re-Elected With 81 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Nursultan Nazarbayev was re-elected president of Kazakhstan with
81 percent of the vote, according to preliminary results, relying
on a powerful security and political machine that disqualified his
main rival and harassed his critics. Nazarbayev thanked voters and
declared that democratization had begun in the former Soviet
republic.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Soldiers Face Trial
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian soldiers are facing a court-martial after the
military admitted that they tortured and killed four suspected
separatist rebels Saturday night in the north Sumatran province of
Aceh. The suspects were captured during a military operation
against the village of Kandang, the suspected hideout of Ahmad
Kandang, leader of the Free Aceh movement.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Unofficial Start to Campaign
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY: Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas has not officially
announced that he is running for president in the July 2000
elections, but over the weekend his backers appeared unofficially
to set off his campaign. One hundred legislators from Cardenas'
leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution and many senior party
officials published a letter backing his candidacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
