r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KANSAS-MANHUNT-2Takes     01-11 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-MANHUNT-2Takes-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHUNT LEADS TO OVERLAND PARK, THEN WICHITA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and RASHEEDA CRAYTON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Two suspects in a multistate series of
crimes took brief respite at an Overland Park hotel Saturday before
catching a cab ride that ended in Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, whose identities are unknown, remained at large
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents and police on Sunday searched the Overland Park
Marriott hotel and the neighborhoods near Interstate 435 and
Metcalf Avenue before learning the men had left the area. They also
impounded and searched a stolen truck that had been abandoned in
the hotel parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The two are wanted in the killing of a Louisiana car salesman on
Thursday and a bank robbery and the wounding of an Iowa police
chief on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The men were last seen in Wichita, where an Overland Park
cabdriver dropped them off after a sometimes nerve-racking ride.
Although the driver did not know the men were wanted in a killing,
he became concerned for his safety during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat the cell phone in his lap and dialed 911, so all he'd
have to do is press `send' in a jam,'' said John Harsh, the
driver's supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The ride ended safely for the driver, however, and he did not
have to call for help before dropping the men off at the Mark 8
motel in eastern Wichita, Harsh said.
</P>
<P>
   The men are thought to have a large-caliber handgun and a rifle
or shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Police first learned the men had been in Overland Park when
hotel security officers noticed a pickup truck in the hotel parking
lot about 2:30 a.m. Sunday. The truck matched a description the
officers had heard on news reports about the Louisiana and Iowa
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The security officers called police, who in turn contacted the
FBI's fugitive unit. Agents soon determined the men were no longer
in the hotel. Police found bank money wrappers when they searched
the men's hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   A review of hotel records found the two men checked into a room
about 4 a.m. Saturday, just hours after the Iowa bank robbery, a
shootout and a massive manhunt in northern Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   FBI special agent Jeff Lanza said the men used the name Tim
Taylor in registering for the room. Lanza said the name is an
alias. Hotel employees told police they last saw the men about 7:15
a.m. Saturday in the hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   A Marriott official declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The men paid cash, checked out of the room Saturday afternoon
and called for a cab.
</P>
<P>
   A driver for Southland Cab Co. picked the men up and took them
to Oak Park Mall in Overland Park, said Harsh, the driver's
supervisor. The driver declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As the driver dropped off the men at the mall about 4:30 p.m.,
they changed their mind and asked to go to Topeka, Harsh said. The
driver offered to take them there after handling another fare
first. The men agreed, declining an offer to leave their suitcases
in the trunk of the cab.
</P>
<P>
   When the driver returned, the men had traded their suitcases for
newly purchased, large duffel bags and said they were still willing
to pay $98 to go to Topeka, Harsh said.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway to Topeka, the driver radioed Harsh, saying his
riders wanted to go to Wichita instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabdrivers, if their wheels aren't turning, they're not making
money,'' said Harsh. ``So I told him it was up to him. He's from
Wichita and figured he could hook up with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The men paid the extra $162 in fare to Wichita up-front. Shortly
after, the men began to whisper back and forth in the back seat,
and the driver became concerned, Harsh said.
</P>
<P>
   When the driver sped up, the men seemed agitated, constantly
asking him to slow down, as if they were worried he would get
pulled over by police, Harsh said. The driver stopped at a
fast-food restaurant at the men's request, but they refused to get
out and would only use the drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the driver grabbed his cell phone. He kept it on his
lap until dropping the men off around 8:30 p.m. at an east Wichita
motel, where they spent Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Southland Cab said it was not unusual for older
businessmen to take taxi rides to Wichita or Topeka, but it was
quite unusual for men who were in their late teens or 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Police and federal agents arrived at the Wichita motel about
11:30 a.m. Sunday. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed them by a little more than an hour,'' Lanza said.
``They're on the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men were described as white and in their late teens or
early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   One was described as 5 feet 10 or 11 inches tall and weighing
165 pounds. He has a blond goatee and an acne-scarred face. He was
last seen wearing a black cap, a white long-underwear T-shirt
beneath a black T-shirt, blue jean overalls and black boots.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspect was described as 5 feet 11 inches tall and
weighing 135 pounds. He has black hair and a mustache. His eyebrow
is pierced with two silver loops, and he has a silver tongue stud.
He was wearing a white T-shirt, blue jeans and sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   The series of crimes began Thursday afternoon in Shreveport,
La., where the men are suspected of killing a car salesman while
test-driving a 1989 Pontiac Firebird. Police discovered the body of
Chester Howell, 56, on Thursday afternoon at a bridge on a gravel
road about 30 miles south of Shreveport. He had been shot twice in
the chest and once in the back, said Judson Rives, chief
investigator of the De Soto Parish Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Howell had worked less than two months at Morgan
Pontiac-GMC-Buick. He accompanied two men on a test drive about an
hour before his body was found.
</P>
<P>
   Howell did not make a copy of either man's driver's license
before the test drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is for the salespeople to use extreme caution and,
if they feel uncomfortable with the customer, to copy the
license,'' general manager Keith Marcotte said.
</P>
<P>
   Rives said the two men closely resembled two persons who visited
at least two other dealerships in southeast Shreveport. At Elkins
Nissan, salesman Rocky Yates did not give them a test drive because
they appeared too young.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appeared nervous and were driving what looked like a $100
set of wheels,'' Yates said. ``They said they were headed to
Daytona Beach, Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, two men carrying a pump shotgun and a
large-caliber revolver held up the Lamoni Commercial Federal Bank
in southwest Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoni Police Chief Dale Killpack chased the men into Missouri.
A fragment from a bullet fired from the Firebird hit Killpack in
the eye, and he was in fair condition Sunday at University
Hospitals in Iowa City, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   As the robbers fled south on Interstate 35 with Killpack in
pursuit, a Missouri Highway Patrol trooper overheard radio traffic
about the chase. Troopers positioned themselves on the highway in
Harrison County, but the two robbers turned onto a county road
about a mile north of the roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   The Firebird was found abandoned in a snowbank about one mile
east of the interstate near Bethany, Mo., in Harrison County.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Highway Patrol troopers searched for the men in
Harrison County. Footprints led investigators Saturday to a
roadside service business in north-central Harrison County, said
Linda Cottrell, a Highway Patrol telecommunicator in St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   There, the two men were thought to have stolen the 1981 white
Chevrolet service truck that was later recovered at the Marriott.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
