<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 PODESTA &AMP; RICCHETTI  
 KING FIGHTS BACK ONLINE  
 BIG RECYCLING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where there is a Podesta in Washington, it seems, there is also
a Ricchetti.
</P>
<P>
   When John Podesta became the White House chief of staff on Nov.
1, he named Steve Ricchetti to be his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went to the White House, Podesta, 50, was a partner
with his older brother, Anthony Podesta, 53, in a lobbying firm
called Podesta Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it changed its name to podesta.com and bought
Ricchetti &AMP; Associates, the lobbying firm that Ricchetti, 41,
opened in 1996 after his last tour of duty at the White House. (He
had been deputy assistant to the president for legislative
affairs.)
</P>
<P>
   Ricchetti's younger brother, Jeff Ricchetti, a 38-year-old
lawyer who has specialized in health-care law, worked for Ricchetti
&AMP; Associates and now works for podesta.com.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently by coincidence, the Podesta and Ricchetti firms had
some of the same clients: MCI paid the Podesta firm $100,000 and
the Ricchetti firm $83,000 in the first half of 1998, for example.
But that was before MCI merged with Worldcom. Officials of
podesta.com said they did not know whether Worldcom would continue
with podesta.com.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of podesta.com also say they do not depend on White
House connections to draw clients. ``We are an extremely bipartisan
firm,'' said Missi Tessier, a principal at podesta.com. ``Several
of us, myself included, have at least 20 years apiece in Republican
politics. I don't want to leave the impression that this is purely
a Democrat firm.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fear on Line &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If this had been a Stephen King page turner, a chronicle of
murderous modems and haunted floppy disks, the title might well
have been ``Nightmare on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is about real life. Specifically, King's life. He was
fed up with the misinformation being spread about him online. No,
he is not planning to retire, and no, he does not give tours of his
house on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   So he set up an official site, www.stephenking.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were more than 30-odd sites,'' said Marsha De Filippo,
an assistant to King. ``You can imagine with that many, there could
be a lot of rumors going around. I have not gone to every single
site, and some of them, it's hard to tell whether they are serious
or not.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Season's End &UR;  &LR;   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Guy Torsilieri is ready to perform the final ritual of the
holiday season: the disposing of the Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any tree, but the 74-foot Norway spruce that stood in
Rockefeller Center from late November until last week. The one that
was topped by a 12-foot star unveiled by John Glenn after his trip
on the space shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk is now in three pieces at Torsilieri's landscaping
company in Gladstone, N.J., 38 miles from Manhattan. The branches
are on another trailer on his lot. Torsilieri is preparing to strip
off the wires and bulbs and chop what is left into smaller pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it for 15 years now,'' he said, ``so I'm kind of
used to that negative feeling, that Christmas is over and it's time
to start getting ready for the next holiday. I don't get any pangs
of pain anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Rockefeller Center trees were recycled into sailboat
masts or family room floors. But since 1983, the trees have gone
through Torsilieri and have ended up at the headquarters of the
U.S. Equestrian Team, also in Gladstone. Pieces of the trunk will
be used to make the wooden jumps for training sessions for the Pan
American and Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always people up there talking about how whatever
they use it for used to be the tree at Rockefeller Center, so the
tree lives on,'' Torsilieri said. ``They're still talking about the
one we took from the nuns in the Bernardsville mountains. The nuns
came over as the horses jumped over it, and they blessed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
