<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-11 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEATING-AZR &LR;      01-11 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEATING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIER KEATING AND SON WILL BE RETRIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles H Keating Jr., the central figure of the 1980s savings
and loan scandal, will be retried on charges that he looted Lincoln
Savings.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors made the announcement at a hearing Monday in Los
Angeles before U.S. District Judge Mariana Pfaelzer. The case was
returned to Pfaelzer after an appellate court overturned the 1993
convictions of Keating and his son, Charles H Keating III, who also
faces retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, a former federal prosecutor in Los Angeles,
said the decision to retry Keating reflects his high-profile in a
scandal that provoked widespread outrage against Keating and
politicians who supported him. Lincoln's failure cost taxpayers a
record $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at the heart of that whole mess,'' said Levenson, dean
of Loy ola University law school in Los Angeles. ``So from the law
enforcement point of view, this is about a man they believe
perpetrated one of the largest frauds in American history and
continues to walk away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Neal, Keating's attorney, said it is an abuse of federal
power to retry a 75-year-old man who has already served 4{ years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would think that at some point, given the age of the
issues here and Charlie's age, they would see that fundamental
fairness would lead reasonable people to say enough is enough,''
Neal said. ``The government should give this case up.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal said Keating, who recently underwent two hip operations, is
trying to re-establish himself as a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would love to get all these issues fully behind him so he
could fully reintroduce himself to the business world,'' Neal said.
He said Keating, who last year was selling telecommunications
equipment, ``is still exploring a variety of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Attorney General Janet Napolitano, a former U.S.
attorney, said the decision to retry Keating indicates that
prosecutors are confident they can still present a strong case
against the Keatings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witnesses can disappear or die, documents can become
disorganized and assistant U.S. attorneys leave the office,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two prosecutors who took the Keatings to trial have left
federal employment. One is a law professor at UCLA and the other is
a municipal judge in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is on Keating's side,'' said Levenson. She said Keating
may benefit from a dissipation of public outrage of the early 1990s
in the wake of the savings and loan debacle.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Rep. Jim Leach, Republican of Iowa, condemned
Keating as ``a financiopath of obscene proportions.'' Leach was a
member of the House Banking Committee that held televised hearings
into Lincoln's failure.
</P>
<P>
   When Pfaelzer sentenced Keating to 12 years and 7 months, she
called his crime ``staggering in its proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   But the conviction was reversed after it was discovered that
jurors knew of his conviction in a California state court and had
discussed it during his federal trial.
</P>
<P>
   The state conviction, on charges that Keating had swindled bond
investors in American Continental, Lincoln's Phoenix-based parent
company, was thrown out because of a flawed instruction to the jury
by the judge, Lance Ito.
</P>
<P>
   Ito later achieved his own national notoriety in the O.J.
Simpson murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Keating's new federal trial could be short-circuited by a plea
agreement with prosecutors. Such an agreement could take into
account the time he has already served in prison. But it would also
require Keating to do something he has always scorned: acknowledge
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and prickly as a saguaro, Keating has staunchly asserted
his innocence. He contended he was tagged as scapegoat for the
national thrift disaster by a ``vicious and vindictive group of
bureaucrats and sinister politicians hoping to cover their perfidy
and ignorance by pillorying Charlie Keating.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating, who gained national notoriety in the 1970s as a
crusader against pornography, scorned regulators as ``scum.'' He
mocked their rules to protect Lincoln's federally insured deposits
as bureaucratic meddling by the small-minded and meek.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's hearing, Pfaelzer asked prosecutors to consider
paring down the 77-count indictment that spawned a nine-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll certainly review it and see if that's possible,'' said
Jim Whalen of the Phoenix office of the FBI. Whalen led the
investigation into Keating's empire, one of the largest
white-collar probes in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged that the Keatings fabricated an illusion of
prosperity by rigging phony land deals, many of them on the
outskirts of Lincoln's master-planned Estrella community west of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Keating said he made legitimate, arm's-length sales of
undeveloped land to a group of ``prime customers'' who saw the raw
land as a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said the customers were really ``straw buyers''
who bought the land at inflated prices in return for huge loans
from Lincoln that were never repaid.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the bogus sales, the indictment charged, Lincoln
recorded $82 million in bogus profits. Then its directors used a
tax-allocation plan to ``upstream'' much of the money to American
Continental and to insiders in the form of lavish salaries and
bonuses. Many of the insiders were Keating relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1987, when federal regulators were uncovering what they
said were massive abuses at Lincoln, Mr. Keating asked five U.S.
senators to take up his cause.
</P>
<P>
   He had collected $1.3 million for the campaigns of the senators
_ Dennis DeConcini and John McCain, both of Arizona, Alan Cranston
of California, John Glenn of Ohio and Don Riegle of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, who became known as the Keating Five, suffered
varying consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Cranston, who said he and Keating had formed ``a mutual aide
society,'' was censured in the Senate. DeConcini and Riegle were
criticized sharply, while McCain and Glenn received mild rebukes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
