<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONELY DAY FOR FISHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Informal workouts began Monday around the NBA, but
if the Los Angeles Lakers wanted to run fullcourt, they would have
had to challenge reporters to a game of five-on-five.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of 12 Lakers showed at L.A. Southwest College and the
poor attendance was cause for consternation among the dedicated
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the guys that are here, we do feel a letdown,'' said guard
Derek Fisher, joined by Lakers veterans Shaquille O'Neal, Eddie
Jones and Sean Rooks, rookie Tyronn Lue and free agent Rick
Brunson.
</P>
<P>
   The no-shows were Kobe Bryant and Elden Campbell, who both live
in L.A., Corie Blount, Tony Battie, Robert Horry and rookies Sam
Jacobson and Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   No one begrudged Horry's absence _ he's home in Houston
attending to his ill daughter and his wife, Keva, who is eight
months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple other guys that knew about it and should be
here,'' Fisher said. ``Shaq feels that way and we all feel that
way. Nobody's making us be here, but we're here because we're
committed to this team and we're committed to winning. That's the
way everybody should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson and Blount are arriving today from Cincinnati, where
they were working out at their alma mater. Same goes for Jacobson,
arriving today from Minnesota. Battie, acquired from Denver in
June, couldn't be reached by team officials. Both he and Bryant are
expected at practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executive Jerry West downplayed the absences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see most of them there (today),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who said he called most of his teammates personally,
sounded perturbed but declined to criticize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today wasn't really mandatory. . . . As long as guys are ready
on the 18th (for training camp), I don't have a problem,'' O'Neal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps another round of calls?
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke once. I don't need to speak twice,'' he said. ``From
now on, I'm speaking once and the second time I'm swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Shape of things: Fisher, Lue and Jones, all regulars at UCLA
pickup games during the lockout, all figured to be in good shape.
But O'Neal was a concern for the team.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up Monday weighing, according to O'Neal, about 335
pounds. That's 17 pounds over his lowest playing weight last season
but only five to 10 pounds above his typical playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``I'm good enough to get 26-27 (points) and
10-11 (rebounds). But nothing is going to get me in shape like
playing and running and bumping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille obviously is someone we're always concerned about,
and he looks a lot better than I thought he would,'' said trainer
Gary Vitti, who along with strength coach Jim Cotta was the only
team official allowed at the workout. ``It's hard for a big guy to
stay in shape . . . because he doesn't have anybody big enough to
play against.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Dribbles: Training camps might not open until Jan. 19, a day
later than projected, while NBA and union attorneys complete the
new labor agreement. The Lakers are considering sites in Santa
Barbara, Irvine and San Diego. . . . The Lakers will play both of
their exhibition games against the Clippers, one at the Forum and
the other at the Sports Arena. Dates have not been set. . . .
Disgruntled Charles Oakley, traded from New York to Toronto in
June, opened practice saying, ``Tell the Lakers I'm ready.'' The
Lakers are in the market for a power forward, but sources say a
deal for Oakley is highly unlikely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-11-99 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
